<HEADLINE>
BRITISH CABLE TELEVISION CONCERN EXPECTED TO DISCLOSE ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Telewest Communications PLC, Britain's second-largest
cable television company, is expected to announce as early as
Thursday that it will acquire Flextech PLC, a British TV production
concern, for about 1.9 billion pounds, or $3 billion, executives
close to the talks said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   If the acquisition proceeds, Telewest, whose biggest
shareholders include Microsoft and AT&AMP;T's Liberty Media Group,
would be able to create a $14.4 billion company that both produces
and distributes programming over one cable system. The move is
expected to make Telewest more competitive with British Sky
Broadcasting Group, the satellite television company that is 40
percent owned by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. and NTL Inc., the
acquisition-hungry British cable company that bought the Swiss
company Cablecom this week.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from both companies spent the evening working out
terms of the deal, though a final agreement will not be reached
until sometime in January when due diligence is completed, the
executives said. The executives stressed that there was still a
chance that the talks could break down and that the deal could be
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that the all-stock offer was below
Flextech's closing price on Wednesday, though the offer constituted
a premium of almost 10 percent over Flextech's share price when
speculation about a possible combination began earlier this month.
Both companies acknowledged they were in talks on Dec. 6.
Executives from both companies are expected to maintain roles at
the company. Spokesmen from the companies could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Telewest's ambition to own programming
operations mimics the success of B Sky B, which has pursued a
similar strategy. It produces and distributes its own branded
premium programming like sports and film channels over its
satellite system. Owning Flextech would give Telewest ownership of
premium television channels like Bravo and Living in Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
