<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG HIGH COURT RULES THAT DEFACING CHINA'S FLAG IS CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 11th graf to correct name of judge issuing concurring
opinion. His name is Kemal Bohary, not Sir Anthony Mason.)  (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Steering clear of another legal confrontation with
the Chinese government, the top court in Hong Kong on Wednesday
ruled that defacing the Chinese flag is a crime. The decision was a
victory for the local government and reversed a lower court's
ruling that defacing the flag was a form of expression guaranteed
by the constitution of this former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Striking down a Hong Kong law that protects the flag, legal
experts said, could have led to a showdown with China. The law was
adopted by the new legislature here hours after the colony reverted
to Chinese rule in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The flag decision was released a week after the court had said
that Beijing had the right to overturn its landmark decision that
granted residency to more than a million people from mainland
China. Taken together, the rulings prompted some critics here to
contend that the Hong Kong judiciary had lost its independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid people will see this as a trend,'' said Hong Kong
Democratic Party leader Martin Lee. ``It won't be long before Hong
Kong goes down the same route as Singapore or mainland China, where
the courts never rule against the government on sensitive cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a lawyer, refused to comment on the case itself. Other
legal experts noted that unlike the immigration case, where the
court made a well-reasoned decision that Beijing overturned,
Wednesday's decision involved a thorny issue that has bedeviled
courts in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure people will say the court is collapsing,'' said
former Hong Kong Solicitor General Daniel Fung. ``But this ruling
is not a knee-jerk response to executive pressure. On the contrary,
the judges are looking at how other mature jurisdictions have
approached this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The case stemmed from a pro-democracy rally in January 1998 in
which two men, Ng Kung-siu and Lee Kin-yun, carried heavily defaced
Chinese and Hong Kong flags. Both flags were torn, smeared with
black ink and had the Chinese word for ``shame'' scrawled on them.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the two argued that they had the right to express
themselves, even by destroying the flags, under the International
Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which is enshrined in the
Hong Kong constitution. The government countered that the men had
violated laws that protect national and regional flags. The
defendants won their case on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the 51-page ruling, Chief Justice Andrew Li acknowledged that
the flag ordinance restricted civil liberties. But Li said it did
not stifle other forms of political expression, and he said it was
justified because the Chinese flag symbolized Hong Kong's effort to
integrate itself into the Chinese motherland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protection of the national flag and the regional flag from
desecration, having regard for their unique symbolism, will play an
important part in the attaining these goals,'' the judge declared.
</P>
<P>
   In a concurring opinion, another justice, Kemal Bokhary, seemed
eager to show that Hong Kong was squarely in the mainstream of
international legal opinion. He noted that defacing the flag was a
crime in Germany and Italy. The Portuguese colony of Macau, which
returns to Chinese rule Sunday, also recently banned the practice.
Even in the United States, where the Supreme Court has struck down
state laws that would make flag burning a crime, Bokhary noted that
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy had expressed distaste in voting to keep
it legal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the judge acknowledged that the ban was ``just within the
outer limits of constitutionality.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Chen, the dean of the law faculty at the University of
Hong Kong, said, ``The case could have gone either way.'' But he
noted that the Chinese flag played a more sensitive role here than
national flags in other countries because it is ``one of the few
manifestations of Chinese sovereignty in Hong Kong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
