<HEADLINE>
BACK TO CHALKBOARD FOR ODOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the education of a basketball prodigy begins surrendering
to the new math, the student may be obliged to stay after school.
</P>
<P>
   We now can expect to find Clippers rookie Lamar Odom camped at
the chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to get back in the gym, get in the weight room,''
Odom said after Tuesday's 2-point performance in his team's barking
loss to the Lakers. ``I have to be more of a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   Good idea _ while the Clippers were getting spanked by their
down-the-hall rivals, the Golden State Warriors were knocking off
the Miami Heat. And the Warriors will show up at Staples Center
Friday to see if the Clippers have enough pride to put their latest
catastrophe behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here has pride or they wouldn't be in the NBA,'' said
Odom, whose 5-17 team's recent 1-10 moonwalk may have more than a
coincidental relationship with the forward's personal, on-court
funk. ``I have to keep being a good teammate and not worry about my
own stats ... which I never do anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, this is a wonderful strategy that seems even better
when viewed beneath the reading lamp of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Since scoring 24 points in a victory over the New York Knicks,
Odom has made 54 of his next 144 field-goal attempts, a success
rate of 37 percent. Astute NBA film scholars noticed that Odom
prefers taking the ball to the hoop; in recent weeks, opposing
defenses have begun daring Odom to fire from distance.
</P>
<P>
   An even more important welcome wagon has left the tour, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clippers' first 11 games, hospitable NBA referees
escorted the kid to the line for 94 free throws. In the last 11
games _ despite frequent drives to the hoop that yield little aside
from various aches and pains _ Odom has be rewarded with only 41
free-throw attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blaming nobody else but Lamar Odom,'' said Lamar Odom,
whose rising celebrity has inspired reporters from ESPN The
Magazine and the Boston Globe to track his progress this week. ``I
know it's going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) Ankles away
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not getting much better in the wheels department.
</P>
<P>
   One night after shooting guard Derek Anderson parlayed a
second-degree ankle sprain into two weeks of rehab, forward Brian
Skinner responded with a copycat injury.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who also is expected to miss two weeks, was on crutches
Wednesday, but still rolled out in a sharp suit and power tie to
attend the team's charitable event at the AMC Theatres complex at
Norwalk. Clippers players, coaches and staff spent about 90 minutes
with children from the United Rescue Mission.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chris Ford gave the players a day off from practice to
recuperate (mentally as well as physically), autograph T-shirts and
hand out toys in an effort coordinated by Denise Booth of the
team's community relations department.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) SOS not out yet
</P>
<P>
   With his options reduced, Ford said he and Elgin Baylor, the
team's vice president of basketball operations, would discuss
possible acquisitions to produce a near-depth experience.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, who attended Wednesday's event at Norwalk, said no
roster moves were imminent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
