<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS DEFEAT CAVALIERS, 111-101 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Nets were so charmed on
Wednesday night that at one point Jamie Feick, their undersized yet
somewhat lumbering center, was swishing long jump shots. At other
times, Kendall Gill, who has spent much of the season in search of
his touch, was on target from the perimeter. And once, Stephon
Marbury scrambled for a loose ball, penetrated desperately and sank
a contested 12-footer that barely beat the 24-second shot clock
while he lost a shoe.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of night for the Nets. One on which, except for
brief periods and a late-game tantrum that earned Gill two
technical fouls and an automatic ejection, the Nets could do no
wrong against Cleveland. They shot well, had active, flicking hands
on defense and executed proficiently in defeating the Cavaliers,
111-101, before an announced crowd of 12,767 at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Nets' fourth in their last five games and
pushed their record to 6-16. Those four victories have all been by
double-digit margins, and three of them have come against teams
with winning records. The Nets snapped a six-game losing streak to
the Cavaliers dating to Nov. 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seems unfathomable, the success may be going to the
Nets' heads. Coach Don Casey was flippant after being told that the
Nets had moved ahead of the Washington Wizards (6-17) and out of
the bottom spot in the Atlantic Division. When reminded that the
order could change when the Nets play at Washington on Thursday,
Casey said: ``Yes, it could. I doubt it, but it could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets say such brashness is good. They believe cockiness and
toughness are what they were missing earlier in the season. For
that reason, those associated with the club, from the coaching
staff to the bench players, were glad to see Gill shove Cleveland
center Andrew DeClercq in the fourth quarter. ``It's good to be
frisky,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   Gill said DeClercq had been throwing cheap shots all night, and
when he saw DeClercq muscling up Keith Van Horn with five minutes
left in the game, he pushed his shoulder into DeClercq's back.
DeClercq got in Gill's face, and then Gill pushed him before the
officials slapped them both with technical fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who led the Nets with 27 points and 8 rebounds,
insisted that he had nothing to do with the exchange, but Gill, who
was ejected for the first time in his 10-year career, and the Nets
thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to let people know that your teammates and you
aren't going to be shoved around, and that's part of the reason I
did it too,'' said Gill, who had 16 points and 6 rebounds. ``We
hadn't had that much success against the Cavaliers for a long time,
and sometimes we may have to establish that we're not going to take
anything. We have to establish some type of toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight seconds after jawing with DeClercq, Gill was
ejected. DeClercq gave Gill a hip check, and Gill faked throwing an
elbow, provoking an official, Rashan Michel, to give Gill a second
technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great how Kendall stuck up for his
teammate,'' Feick said. ``The team chemistry is definitely a lot
better now than what it was at the start of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything is better. Whereas the Nets' offense was all Marbury
when the Cavaliers beat them by 97-90 on Nov. 3, they had great
balance on Wednesday night. Nine Nets had scored, including four in
double figures, by the time they took a 57-47 halftime lead. They
opened the second half with a 16-8 run that put them ahead by 73-55
midway through the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury followed Van Horn with 23 points, 7 assists and 5
rebounds, while Kerry Kittles added 17 points and 5 assists. The
balanced scoring outweighed Cleveland's two-headed offense of Shawn
Kemp (36 points) and Wesley Person (22 points, 6 of 6 on 3-point
attempts). The Cavaliers fell to 11-10 despite shooting 56.2
percent from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're slowly returning to form,'' Gill said.
</P>
</TEXT>
