<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SUFFER SECOND STRAIGHT ROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kings coach Andy Murray has said all season there is
nothing to be learned from losing. He better hope he is really
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Murray better hope that the team he watched get crushed on
back-to-back nights is not the one he was hoping to take to the
playoffs for just the second time in the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   He better hope that all the Kings lost in Wednesday's 8-3 rout
by the New York Rangers was their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens on one night, you just say it was a fluke and
you move on,'' captain Rob Blake said. ``When it happens in two
straight games you have to wonder what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Kings were blown out 7-1 by New Jersey on Tuesday and
then again by the Rangers on Wednesday, it was hard to believe they
came in with the best road record in the National Hockey League.
Most of the season, they have been among the elite in the NHL's
Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Now that seems trivial. Not so is the Kings' four-point lead
over the Mighty Ducks in the Pacific Division. A week ago that
number was 10.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was anything more absurd than the final score it
was that the Kings outshot New York 48-31 and even scored two
power-play goals.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was such a disaster that Murray, whose coaching style
usually is scripted to the minute, wasn't sure whether he would
call a practice today. The team, which plays lowly Chicago on
Saturday, was scheduled to arrive back in Los Angeles at 3 a.m.
That is unless he made the players walk home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you saw was a team that didn't play desperate,'' Luc
Robitaille said. ``We are a team that is not good enough not to
play desperate every time we hit the ice. When we don't play like
this is our last game, teams will blow right by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just plain losses might have been understandable. The Devils
were coming off their worst loss of the season, 3-1 to the very
beatable Edmonton Oilers. The Rangers came in 3-0-1 after a
miserable start.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils might have played extra hard for assistant Larry
Robinson, who was fired by the Kings after last season. Many Kings
players have said their problems last year stemmed from Robinson's
lack of structure.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's loss, the Kings stayed overnight at their hotel
in New Jersey. They met after the game for a team meal and meeting.
Murray said Wednesday he thought the team had moved on. But before
leaving for the 45-minute bus ride to Madison Square Garden,
third-line left winger Craig Johnson was asked if the team had put
New Jersey in its rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer numbers don't even explain Wednesday's mess. The Rangers
scored six goals in the first period, including five in a
five-minute stretch. For the second straight night, starting
goaltender Jamie Storr was pulled after one period.
</P>
<P>
   And on New York's first three goals _ two by Todd Harvey and one
by Tim Taylor _ came after the Rangers blew by Kings' Ian
Laperriere, Ziggy Palffy and Garry Galley.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and John MacLean had two goals after entering the game
with just one apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, whose responsibility as team captain stems far beyond
scoring and defense, said any problems the team is having will
remain in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk, but this will not get blown out of proportion,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say when it was 8-0 at the beginning of the third
period. That's when Blake finally scored the Kings' first goal.
Palffy and Marko Tuomainen added two more, but that was not what
the players were talking about after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very successful this season and now we have to
regroup,'' Storr said. ``We didn't get here by accident, we got
here with hard work. We haven't had that the last two games, but we
know it is the key to our success. It is hard to know why it comes
and goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
