<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS HAVE BEEN DEEP-SIXED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you want USC coach Henry Bibby to grimace, just
ask him about his bench. Or more specifically, why he hasn't used
it much.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's face tightens, followed by a usually sharp response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, everyone said there was too many guys playing,'' he
said. ``Now, it's `We're not playing enough guys.' Everyone is a
Monday morning quarterback. People say, `Why didn't you
substitute?' Well, you didn't see them play in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why four USC starters have averaged at least 32
minutes through the first nine games, and no starter has averaged
less than 29 minutes this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby might feel undue attention has been paid to his aversion
to substitute at the start of the season, but slowly, things appear
to be changing for the Trojans' bench.
</P>
<P>
   It actually seems to be contributing, and improving, even if it
is taking baby steps in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman center Kostas Charissis earned his first start last
week against Hawaii and played 23 minutes and had six rebounds.
Freshman shooting guard Nate Hair scored nine points and grabbed
five rebounds against Loyola Marymount.
</P>
<P>
   Junior point guard Rashad Jones played 22 minutes and had four
assists against Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly earth-shattering statistics, but Charissis and Hair
each played only seven minutes in USC's first five games. If USC
wants to escape the bottom echelon of the Pacific-10 Conference
beginning next month, it figures the reserves will have to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I found a little niche that makes me valuable out
there,'' Hair said. ``I can give a boost. There's a lot of things
we've heard, like the Trojans have no depth or play only six guys.
But I don't think I've been written off.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not for now. However, Bibby was reluctant to offer too
many compliments following Hair's recent three-game span when he
hit 4 of 8 3-point attempts and grabbed eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get encouraged, then I get discouraged with him in
practice,'' Bibby said. ``Some guys are gamers. He's not a practice
guy, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's true, but I do come to play,'' Hair
retorted.
</P>
<P>
   As for Charissis, Bibby preferred to redshirt him, but USC's
lack of depth has forced him to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like things he does. He just doesn't know how to play,''
Bibby said. ``He's made great progress. He used to travel the first
three or four times he touched the ball. Now, he's playing like an
American player.''
</P>
<P>
   Charissis, a 6-foot-11 center who grew up Greece, said it has
been difficult adjusting to American rules. While he could hook
players with his arms in Europe, it's not allowed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the rules in the States are different than Europe. I
don't know how to protect myself from early fouls,'' Charissis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Comments like those could make Bibby cringe, along with the fact
Charissis has fouled out twice in less than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It's one reason that Bibby is trying to seek a balance between
getting young players experience without sacrificing quality of
play. Or, as he bluntly puts it, ``Who would you rather have with a
game on a line? A tired Brian Scalabrine or a fresh Kostas
Charissis?''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine, USC's best all-around player, is averaging 16.7
points and 33.2 minutes this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tired Brian is better than a fresh Kostas,'' Bibby added.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby has even begun to tell USC's players that they shouldn't
get tired so much, because they never play more than four minutes
at a time between TV timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get to rest every two-to-three minutes because you get a
break,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Scalabrine is open to the concept of trying to tough out
the rest of the season playing iron-man minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with six guys you can win,'' he said. ``If you can get
guys to play for 10 minutes, that's pretty good. But people can't
accept being on the bench. You've got to have attitude. That's what
gets you off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bibby's defense, the one reserve he was counting on _ forward
Jarvis Turner _ sprained his ankle early and is expected to return
to practice next week. He could be playing again when USC opens
Pac-10 play on Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   USC also expects help soon from football player Sandy Fletcher,
who joined the team this week, and is envisioned to be a backup
point guard by next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can go with eight guys or even nine,'' an
optimistic Hair said. ``I think more guys are gaining confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
