<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0592 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-SEAHAWKS-WHITSITT-SPI     12-16 2647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAHAWKS-WHITSITT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITSITT A ONE-MAN ARMY RUNNING ALLEN'S SPORTS SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Five-year-old Richard Ramsey waits wide-eyed for his
Christmas gifts that have arrived courtesy of the Portland Trail
Blazers front-office staff, who have come to his neighborhood
day-care center as part of an annual community tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Richard's Santa Claus is none other than the head man himself,
Blazers president and general manager Bob Whitsitt, and Richard
rips into a package containing a team sweatshirt as soon as
Whitsitt hands him the gift.
</P>
<P>
   Performing a task Whitsitt has done dozens of times before, the
man known throughout the NBA as ``Trader Bob'' helps little Richard
pull the new shirt over his shoulders and straighten it out for the
waiting cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Blazer!'' Richard proclaims, doing a dance of delight
and high-fiving Whitsitt.
</P>
<P>
   Another fan for life has been brought into the fold, just like
the many players Whitsitt has brought to the Pacific Northwest over
the past 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after he was summarily moved out of his Seattle office
and dismissed from the organization he helped rebuild over eight
years as the Sonics' president and general manager, Whitsitt is up
to his old tricks _ with a few new wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has he retooled a Blazers franchise that has been to
the playoffs 17 times in a row and 22 times since 1970 (second only
to the Los Angeles Lakers' 26 post-season appearances), he's also
taken on the dual job of president of the Seattle Seahawks,
Football Northwest and First &AMP; Goal Inc. Just another rebuilding
project that includes a new $455 million football/soccer stadium
and exhibition center. He's also putting together Portland's new
WNBA expansion franchise and entering into talks to bring an NHL
team to Portland's Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Since Blazers and Seahawks owner Paul Allen chose Whitsitt to
run the sports end of the billionaire's diverse business interests,
Trader Bob has been remade into Tireless Bob, the man who never
stops working.
</P>
<P>
   The trades are still there: 14 trades and 14 lottery players for
the Blazers, including Scottie Pippen, Steve Smith, Rasheed
Wallace, Damon Stoudamire and Stacey Augmon on the 1999-2000
roster. Free-agent signings also abound: Detlef Schrempf, Brian
Grant, Joe Kleine.
</P>
<P>
   But basketball is no longer the only game in town for the man
who became the youngest president in the NBA with the Sonics at the
age of 30.
</P>
<P>
   He's 43 now and somehow manages to find the time to run two
sports organizations, live in two cities _ Portland and Bellevue _
show up for his daughter's high school basketball game, take his
wife to a Bette Middler concert and play Santa to the
underprivileged, all in a 48-hour span.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he's at the Blazers' offices to lunch with the
team's Community Builders volunteers and be filmed by KING-TV's
Paul Silvi. Then it's off to the Blazers game against Minnesota in
the Rose Garden, where he sits under the Blazers basket with owner
Allen, who is on the edge of his seat throughout the close win.
</P>
<P>
   By 12:30 that night, he's home in Bellevue, courtesy of a ride
in Allen's jet, but then he's up by 7 a.m. to head to Seahawks
headquarters for another media interview, a round of paperwork and
a meeting with general manager/coach Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys in pro sports salivate at the chance not to do work.
I don't do that,'' Whitsitt says emphatically, recalling how he
came to leave Sonics owner Barry Ackerley and go to work for Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt had an agreement with the Sonics that he would not do
any work for another NBA team until the 1994 draft was complete,
even though he had been replaced by Wally Walker earlier in the
year. The man who had brought Shawn Kemp, George Karl, Detlef
Schrempf, Sam Perkins and Gary Payton to the Sonics, and who had
been the 1994 NBA Executive of the Year in Seattle, found himself
looking for a new job but not wanting to move his family from
Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, the Microsoft co-founder who bought the Blazers in 1988,
made it all possible, allowing Whitsitt to keep his home life
intact as long as he also maintained a residence in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, Allen wanted Whitsitt to maintain the Trader
Bob reputation for rebuilding aging basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best owner in pro sports,'' Whitsitt says of Allen.
``Whatever you're going to do, it starts at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's associates speak just as well of Whitsitt, particularly
his ability to handle several jobs in two different but intertwined
sports markets. They remark glowlingly about his ability to
``multi-task'' in Paul Allen's network.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good at juggling a lot of balls at the same time,''
said Bert Kolde, who represents Allen in a variety of business
interests, including serving as the vice chair of the Seahawks and
the Blazers. ``He embraces technology to stay in touch and
communicate with a lot of people on a lot of things on an ongoing
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But what caught Allen and Kolde's eye most about Whitsitt was
his boldness as a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is willing to take the bold step and make the bold move. If
you ask me to compare him with other people in the business, there
are some people in some franchises who are afraid to take those
bold steps,'' Kolde said. ``To me, that his biggest difference.''
</P>
<P>
   MOST HATED MAN IN PORTLAND
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt wasn't the Santa Claus that Blazer fans were expecting
when he first arrived in his new position and new city.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a Willamette Week article had fans ripping Whitsitt for
getting rid of popular players such as Clyde Drexler, Jerome Kersey
and Buck Williams. He replaced coaches, Rick Adelman for P.J.
Carlesimo, and then Mike Dunleavy two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the team went from being the NBA's oldest in
terms of average age to the seventh youngest at the end of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the fans came around as the Blazers continued to make
the postseason, culminating in last season's Pacific Conference
banner in the lockout-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Sparked by a rare cut in ticket prices going into the season,
the franchise last year averaged 19,462 fans in the Rose Garden,
which is 97 percent of the building's capacity and the fifth-best
attendance in the NBA _ all for a market that ranks 24th in size.
</P>
<P>
   ``With sports, if you're winning, they love you. If you're
losing, they won't invite you over for dinner,'' Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   During all of the changes and through all of the criticism that
met his early years in Portland, Whitsitt was never second-guessed
by his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk with him, I lay out short-term and long-term. He
has never told me what to do and, carte blanche, what not to do,''
Whitsitt said of Allen's influence. ``He'll be involved all the way
down, but he'll never force you to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the short- and long-term goals are the same: Capture
another championship to match the storybook 1976-77 team led by
Bill Walton and coach Jack Ramsay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Championship teams have to be built. It takes time and it
takes planning. It takes thought,'' Whitsitt says as if it is his
personal mantra.
</P>
<P>
   As an organization, the Blazers have all the ingredients in
place. The team is ranked in the top five in the NBA for revenue,
has one of the league's best practice facilities, draws from one of
the most loyal fan bases in one of the league's most fan-friendly
arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Whitsitt's main responsibility to put the product on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a championship window, and that takes a lot of time
just to get in this position,'' he said. ``But whatever we're
working on, the biggest single asset is our basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   BOB KNOWS FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt played three sports in college at the University of
Wisconsin-Stevens Point, and was the football team's starting tight
end.
</P>
<P>
   So when Allen was approached in 1997 by government and business
officials about buying the Seahawks to stop ex-owner Ken Behring
from moving the franchise to Southern California, Whitsitt helped
push the ball forward while Allen, a basketball fan at heart, was
somewhat hesitant at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put together something that Paul was willing to buy into,''
Whitsitt said. ``He takes owning a team very seriously. It's more
than just a business. It's a public trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Paul Allen: If he says he's going to do X, it
means he's going to do 2X. He always goes above and beyond. He is a
Renaissance man.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt first had to convince Allen that he could build that
trust back with Seahawks fans. When he first came to work for the
Sonics, Seattle was a football town that heavily supported the
Huskies and the Seahawks, which had a yearly waiting list for
season tickets, Whitsitt said. But that all changed when Behring
tried to relocate the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times change, but it usually goes back to building a good
product and doing things right,'' Whitsitt said when he looked at
the plight of the Seahawks as a business. ``We didn't have to do a
lot of market research and wonder if Seattle and the whole
Northwest would support an NFL team. We knew they would if the team
did things like they were supposed to do. They didn't burn all the
bridges up there with the previous ownership, they blew all the
bridges up. I think people wanted them to be rebuilt, but just
because Paul bought the team didn't mean that people were
automatically coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   What brought the fans back ultimately was another key move by
Whitsitt: The hiring of Holmgren, someone who is as shrewd and as
driven as the president in the art of the deal and the devotion to
organization. As Holmgren has changed the product on the field, the
fortunes at the gate have changed as well under Whitsitt's
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people now are talking Seahawks, they're wearing
Seahawks, they are believing Seahawks,'' Whitsitt said. ``Every
game is sold out this year for the first time in like a decade,
it's on TV every Sunday and there's a buzz. I'm not telling you
where we are on that mountain yet, I don't know, but I know we're
climbing that mountain and we want to plant the flag on top. We're
not satisfied yet, but we're definitely going the direction we want
to go. To me, that's a huge starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ART OF THE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt was 24 when he made his first deal for the Pacers as
the team's assistant general manager, a position he'd obtained just
a couple of years after completing his internship for his master's
degree in sports administration at Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers had chosen Clark Kellogg as their first-round draft
pick and Whitsitt was pushed into having to negotiate a rookie
contract with a rookie's background in dealing with such
high-stakes situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really have a general manager. We had a lawyer who
was acting as our general manager,'' Whitsitt recalled. ``The
couple things I can remember is that he got a five-year deal for $1
million, when the market was a five-year deal for $2 million. ...
But the fact that we got him under market had nothing to do with
me. That was all the money we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt learned most of the tricks of his trade in Indiana,
where the team was always having financial troubles and struggling
to put fans in the seats and players on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to start with other things and leave money alone,''
Whitsitt said about his philosophy of negotiating with a player.
``You have to start with the human elements _ family, the
organization _ then you layer in money.''
</P>
<P>
   In signing Schrempf away from Seattle as a free agent or
bringing in Pippen after the trade, Whitsitt said he pointed out
that the Blazers have ``the best airplane in the world, the best
practice facility, community, fans, quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all stuff I believe in and it's true. I talk about our
owner. That's the way I deal with athletes, and I always tell them
the truth. They can feel if you're lying to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's come to accept the ``Trader Bob'' label that is
mentioned prominently in the Blazers media guide, Whitsitt can
envision a day when he sits back and enjoys not working his network
of scouts or flipping endlessly through the channels for another
game in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like making deals,'' he confesses after talking
about his most recent moves. ``When you make deals, you are making
changes, and we have some marquee changes this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Will they work this time and will they be enough to return a
championship to Portland?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really count W's,'' Whitsitt said as the Blazers, at
17-5 and tied with the Lakers in first place, come into Seattle
Thursday night to face the Sonics in KeyArena. ``I don't feel real
good where we are right now, but I feel the W's will take care of
themselves. ... We're early in the tour and the show's going to get
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   A FAN FOR LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt sees his role as the head of a service company that
answers to the fans, who deserve a quality experience for their
money.
</P>
<P>
   What he can't completely control, he says, is what happens in
``the live theater'' on game days. So even if the home team doesn't
win, Whitsitt believes he has a responsibility to make sure that
the fan doesn't feel cheated by the service or the performance.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he began tinkering with the Portland roster, even
though the team was successful on the court last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's the only game in town, but this organization has put
together a standard of excellence that is a high mark. ... We
recycled the whole team, retooled it, and now we're back in the
window,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking toward a new century, Whitsitt believes sports in the
future will have to become more globalized, which will mean
marketing and distributing the product to world-wide audiences. He
noted that in 1978, when he got into the business, the NBA didn't
even have a marketing department, and every team now has its own
marketing arm, in addition to an entire licensing and products
division at the league level.
</P>
<P>
   But with all those layers of research and personnel, Whitsitt
believes that a successful sports executive should never get too
far removed from what's happening in the crowd that shows up night
after night or in the locker room both before and after the games.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he often works out at the Blazers facility with the
players before games and sits in the crowd to keep his feel for his
audience and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to stay young,'' Whitsitt said, a back-handed way of
admitting that the NBA's youngest president is feeling a little
older these days. ``You need to know what the young people are
doing and what the fans are all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with both teams appearing to be doing well and the new
stadium due in 2002, Whitsitt is starting to plan a few years in
advance to take his first real vacation since starting the job in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is the thing I feel the worst about,'' Whitsitt
says of the difficulties of living between two cities. ``Even when
I was in one market, it was tough on the family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, family vacations in the past have had wife, Jan,
daughter, Lily, and son, Sean, enjoying some major attraction such
as Disney World, while Whitsitt spends his time in business
meetings or with scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Where will they go on their next vacation to avoid a similar
fate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa to look at elephants,'' Whitsitt said without
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere where there's not a phone or a deal to be made. Where
there's not a player to be signed.
</P>
<P>
   But don't believe Whitsitt won't be looking.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Angelo Bruscas can be reached at 206-448-8010
</P>
<P>
   or angelobruscas &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
