<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0593 &Cx1f; tth-z
r S BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      12-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' WOES FRUSTRATE HOLMGREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Mike Holmgren's biological clock has gone
haywire.
</P>
<P>
   That will happen when you're coaching a team that three weeks
ago appeared to be in total control of the AFC West, but is now
tied for the division lead after dropping its past three games.
</P>
<P>
   That will happen when your remaining three games are against the
Broncos in Denver, where the Seahawks have lost nine of their past
10 games; at home against the Kansas City Chiefs, who have won
three in a row to pull into a tie with the Seahawks; and against
the New York Jets, a game that will follow a coast-to-coast trip on
New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   That will happen when you're coaching a team that never has been
in this situation before, and you're not really sure what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to sleep and, bang, I wake up at 2:30 in the morning,''
Holmgren said Wednesday of a rude, but not unusual, awakening for a
football coach. ``I'm thinking about the end of the San Diego
Chargers game. You know, the plays we called, what we did, seeing
the ball hit the upright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm mad because I can't go back to sleep,'' he said.
``That's kind of how it is at this part of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is, off the scale doses of sleep deprivation and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   It's called pressure. And in the Seahawks' case it's a
combination of the pressure to perform in these next three games as
they did during their five-game winning streak that has been
followed by the three-game skid; and the ability to generate
pressure on the opposing quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren is attempting to keep things light and upbeat. You
know, the old the glass is half full, not half empty analogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I spoke to the team today, it's not real deep,'' Holmgren
said. ``Really. This is not rocket science. It's football.''
</P>
<P>
   But too many of the players he was speaking to don't know the
formula to succeeding in this type of situation and at this point
in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all new,'' said defensive end Cortez Kennedy, who has
been with the club since 1990 and never come close to sniffing a
playoff berth. ``We've got a lot of guys on this team who have
never been in a position to win it all like this. It's a matter of
knowing how to react and how to respond. Not everyone knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   More pressure. The kind that comes from being the division
leader and having every team you face elevate its game.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan knows the feeling. His Broncos won the Super Bowl
the past two years after going 12-4 and 14-2, and were 13-3 the
season before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really challenging and you look forward to it because you
know you're getting everyone's best shot,'' the Broncos' coach said
during a telephone interview from Denver. ``But you better play
accordingly, because if you don't have 46 guys playing at the same
level, you can lose very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: In the past two games, the Seahawks' defenders
too often have looked more like they're playing the accordion,
rather than accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it's pressure. But in this case, it's a lack of it. The
Seahawks have sacked the opposing quarterback once in the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation that has Holmgren already looking to the
offseason, when he plans to determine if the Seahawks presently
have the personnel to play the style of defense he brought with him
from Green Bay, or if the scheme needs to be tweaked to match the
players who were here to play another style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we like to do, and we believe it's a very sound
way to go,'' Holmgren said. ``But in fact, are the players capable
of doing it and, two, are they willing? We have to look at that and
see how much of this season was that and how much was, well, we
needed some help in this area or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   But then that's consternation for some other sleepless night.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Holmgren has to find a way to get it done with what
he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to come out with a sense of urgency,'' running back
Ricky Watters said. ``We have to jump on these teams. We're the
same team that won five in a row. We've just got to get back to
that. We were very confident back then and there were a lot of
games we could have lost. But we won those games in the same
fashion that we've lost some of these games. We didn't make the
mistakes in the early part of the season that we've been making. We
have to get back to feeling like we can win any game.''
</P>
<P>
   And then perhaps Holmgren can get back to sleeping through the
night.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
