<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S WNBA TEAM GAINS AN IDENTIY IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MEREDITH BAGLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle's WNBA team may not yet have a name, but head
coach Lin Dunn introduced her first six players Wednesday after the
league held its 2000 Expansion Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Like a wise player, Dunn took care of the ball first, choosing
experienced guards Edna Campbell and Sonja Henning with her first
two picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get my backcourt first,'' Dunn said. ``It was
tough to do with four teams picking, but I got who I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who will play shooting guard, played three seasons
with the Colorado Xplosion in the ABL before joining the Phoenix
Mercury last year in the WNBA. The 5-foot-8 Campbell started 24
games for the Mercury, averaging 9.6 points per game and shooting
.376 from three-point land.
</P>
<P>
   Henning won a league title last season with the Houston Comets,
starting all 32 games for the two-time champions and averaging 4.0
points per game. A four-year starter for Stanford and graduate of
Duke Law School, the 5-6 Henning had a .444 field goal percentage
last year. Before joining the Coments, Henning played under Dunn
with the Portland Power in the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonja is an elite athlete,'' Dunn said. ``She is a tremendous
defender and led the league in turnover ratio. I was holding my
breath that she'd be available for us, and was surprised that she
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell ,29, and Henning, 30, bring valuable maturity and
leadership to the Seattle team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a blend of young and veteran players was a priority of
ours,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   With her other picks, Dunn chose guard Angela Aycock from the
Minnesota Lynx, Yugoslavian center Nina Bjedov from the Los Angeles
Sparks, Phoenix forward Toni Foster, and guard Charmin Smith from
the Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   Aycock, a 6-2 guard or small forward, played for the Seattle
Reign from 1996-98. A familiar face for local fans, the versatile
Aycock averaged 8.7 points per game for the Reign.
</P>
<P>
   Another former Reign player, Kate Starbird, was drafted by Miami
in the first round, and subsequently traded to the Utah Starzz for
a player and a future draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kate Starbird was absolutely in our mix,'' Dunn said. ``She
was gone by our second pick, but I wish her the best of luck. We
will continue to have interest in anyone connected to Seattle, the
Reign or the University of Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   A reserve center behind Lisa Leslie for the Sparks, the 6-6
Bjedov gives Seattle an inside presence. Bjedov averaged 16 minutes
per game in Los Angeles, shooting 52 percent from the floor and 42
percent behind the arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know many players her size that can post up and hit
threes,'' Dunn said. ``But I know I'm going to start taking lessons
in Yugoslavian.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1 Foster, a teammate of Campbell's in Phoenix, brings
mobility and range to the small-forward position. Foster was a
Kodak All-American at Iowa and earned Big Ten Player of the Year in
1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   Charmin Smith is another ex-Portland Power player who spent last
season in Minnesota with Aycock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the core,'' Dunn said. ``We want an athletic team that
can run and press, and be versatile all over the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased to have a face for our new team.''
</P>
<P>
   All 16 teams will participate in the WNBA Draft on April 25, and
Seattle will pick ninth in each round. In addition, more ex-ABL
players will be available to teams through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look for college players that will fit into our
up-tempo aggressive style of play,'' Dunn said. ``And we will also
focus on the free agents who are older and more veteran players.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking over her draft-day efforts, Dunn was exhausted but
excited for the team's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do we have great players on this team, but we have
some great role models for the community.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Seattle will open its inaugural season at KeyArena in
mid-May. The team will play a 32-game schedule, which should be
finalized by the first of the year. ... Seattle leads expansion
teams with 7,100 season ticket pledges, and Dunn hopes to have
10,000 season ticketholders by the team's opening tip-off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
