<HEADLINE>
RUSH, BRUINS HAD BEEN WARNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like all UCLA athletes, suspended forward JaRon
Rush has been warned repeatedly that taking money or gifts from
sports agents could jeopardize his college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with his letter of intent 20 months ago, Rush has read
and/or signed at least nine documents acknowledging NCAA rules
governing agents and the potential penalties, which range from
suspension to loss of amateur status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to take preventative steps with education, but there
are no guarantees,'' said Bruins coach Steve Lavin, who declined to
discuss the Rush situation.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, a sophomore from Kansas City, has been suspended
indefinitely by UCLA for possible violation of NCAA rules. Sources
close to Rush said he accepted between $200-300 in cash or cash
equivalent (meals, shoes, etc.) from Los Angeles-based sports agent
Jerome Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley has denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Teams using players who violate NCAA rules face a plethora of
penalties: forfeiture of victories; loss of revenue; and reduction
of TV appearances. In extreme cases, teams are barred from playing
in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA suspended Rush before concluding its investigation because
it didn't want to risk using an ineligible player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agents are the biggest problem facing college athletics
today,'' Pac-10 commissioner Tom Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's education process reflects that concern.
</P>
<P>
   It begins when recruits sign letters of intent and financial aid
agreements, which outline the terms of their eligibility and
amateur status.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA also sends the ``Guide for the College-Bound
Student-Athlete'' to high schools throughout the country. It
states: ``NCAA rules don't prohibit meetings or discussions with an
agent. However, you jeopardize your college eligibility if you
agree (orally or in writing) to be represented by an agent while in
high school or college.... Also, receiving any benefits or gifts by
you, your family or friends from a player-agent would jeopardize
your college eligibility.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA requires all athletes to read and sign a statement each
year that explains NCAA regulations. Its athletes also sign a
code-of-conduct form and write their initials next to 13 points,
including agent-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Men's and women's basketball players are required to sign
affidavits before the NCAA Tournament stating they have no
agreements with, and have not accepted money from, agents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, UCLA compliance director Rich Herczog outlines
pertinent NCAA rules for each team before its season begins, and
NCAA rules are posted on UCLA's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try our due diligence to deliver (the information) in a
manner they can hear,'' associate athletic director Betsy
Stephenson said. ``It's an ongoing process that exists in the
normal course of a student-athlete's career.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the documents and affidavits, Lavin uses
real-world methods to warn his players about agents. Last year,
when Rush was a freshman, a spokesman from the Drug Enforcement
Agency lectured the Bruins on drinking, gambling, gangs and agents
_ the fringe elements that pervade big-time college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin also brought Ronnie Lott, Jerry West, Rafer Johnson and
two former Bruins, Mitchell Butler and Darrick Martin, to Pauley
Pavilion last year to speak to the players about proper conduct.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA and USC are in unique positions among major colleges: They
feature dozens of potential pros in a city teeming with agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so much time in the day,'' Lavin said. ``But I
think UCLA's on par with the top programs in terms of education and
compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is also examining Rush's relationship with former AAU coach
Myron Piggie, who is under FBI and Internal Revenue Service
investigation for tax evasion and fraud, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Rush testified about Piggie last month before a Kansas City
grand jury; he did not have legal representation. His testimony
prompted the FBI and a U.S. attorney to inform UCLA of possible
NCAA violations involving Rush, Piggie and Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Rush won't play Saturday against DePaul or accompany the team to
Hawaii next week for a three-game tournament. A source said the
investigation could last at least a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
