<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CLOSE TO DEALS WITH SASAKI, MCLEMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Having failed to land a closer in trade talks with the
Cincinnati Reds and New York Mets, the Mariners are close to
signing Japanese free agent closer Kazuhiro Sasaki. The club also
is finalizing details on a contract for leadoff hitter Mark
McLemore, formerly of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki, 32, the all-time saves leader in Japan, was in Seattle
Wednesday to complete a physical. His agent, Tony Attanasio, said
the sides were ``very close'' to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners tried to acquire Scott Williamson from the Reds and
Armando Benitez from the Mets in potential deals for center fielder
Ken Griffey Jr. Now they apparently will sign right-hander Sasaki,
who had bone chips removed from his pitching elbow last summer, to
be their closer. Jose Mesa, who saved 33 games last year but was
erratic while doing so, has been mentioned in trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   Attanasio also represents McLemore, who met with Mariners
officials at the winter meetings in Anaheim, Calif., on Monday.
McLemore flew to Anaheim _ to his agent's and the Mariners'
surprise _ after learning the club had raised questions about his
weight.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, whose primary position would be left field, agreed to
include a weight clause in his contract. The sides have agreed on
terms of a deal, and the only thing to be worked out, Attanasio
said, is the language of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' pursuit of former Anaheim starter Chuck Finley,
however, has ended. The club will make no further contract offers
to Finley, who is strongly considering Cleveland, but the M's are
still hopeful he will accept their last proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we understand it, he's contemplating,'' said Lee
Pelekoudas, Mariners vice president for baseball administration.
``I know we've worked very, very diligently for the better part of
three weeks and we've done everything we can.''
</P>
<P>
   If Finley does not sign with Seattle, the M's may accelerate
their pursuit of free agent Texas starter Aaron Sele, a Poulsbo
native.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
