<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     12-16 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMAR FOUND PIECES IN PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the fall of 1996, when rookie coach Lorenzo
Romar walked into the Pepperdine locker room for the first time,
seven players were waiting for him _ just over half a normal
roster.
</P>
<P>
   They barely knew how to practice, much less win. They had no
passion. Romar knew it wouldn't be easy; the Waves had won 10 games
the previous year. It was quantum physics.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Romar's the rookie coach at St. Louis.
Compared to Pepperdine, it's basic multiplication.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a building situation,'' he said. ``Pepperdine was
rebuilding. There wasn't anything there. We had to teach those guys
to work hard and care about winning. They were pretty much just
going to school. That's not the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Billikens were in the NCAA Tournament two years ago.
They have talent, although it's not NBA talent. They have solid
fundamentals, courtesy of former coach Charlie Spoonhour. They have
a huge fan base (15,000 per game) and, as of Sunday, they have a
huge victory over in-state rival Missouri for Romar's resume.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a botched rebound against Kansas State, Romar
couldn't have imagined a better start to his St. Louis tenure. His
family likes the area. The weather's been tolerable. The
administrative support is solid, and the Billikens are 5-2 with one
eye on the NCAA Tournament and one eye on a brutal upcoming
schedule that includes Cincinnati (tonight), Dayton and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that sold me on the program, I'm still sensing,''
Romar said. ``I liked the conference (USA), the opportunity to win
on a national level, and the support in the community. That hasn't
changed. We'll have 21,000 (in the Kiel Center) for Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were 15-16 last year under Charlie. They've been
taught how to play sound defense. They're unselfish. They have high
character. We don't have any lottery picks, but they're all
Division I players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Billikens beat Air Force in Romar's debut. They've handled
UNC Asheville, Southwest Texas State and Alabama, which is coached
by Mark Gottfried, Romar's former cohort on Jim Harrick's staff at
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Billikens would have beaten Kansas State but for a
mishandled rebound in the final seconds. They lost to Louisiana
Tech, then, before 25,000 in the Trans World Dome, they outlasted
Missouri in the teams' first meeting in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game, we wanted to win,'' said Missouri's first-year
coach, Quin Snyder. ``The rivalry. The city. It meant a lot to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much it means for Romar, he can't say.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps, ever humble, he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked that a lot around here this week,'' he said.
``I think (recruits) are more concerned if you go to the NCAA
Tournament. When you go recruiting in July, they won't remember
this. But, in that Missouri is the more accomplished program, it
does help us get established.''
</P>
<P>
   Big week: Romar wasn't the only former UCLA coach to record a
major victory last week. Georgia's Jim Harrick had two: A few days
after defeating Georgia Tech, the Bulldogs rallied from a 13-point
deficit with nine minutes left to beat then-No. 18 Wake Forest at
the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs have won five in a row, the last three by a total
of seven points, and they've shown more heart than Harrick's former
team did against Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an unbelievable week,'' Harrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Singing the bluegrass: Kentucky is out of the top-25 for the
first time since the week of Dec. 4, 1990 _ a streak of 164 polls,
and that's the fourth-longest span in history. (UCLA holds the
record, 221 weeks, from 1966-80.) The Wildcats have lost three of
their last four entering Saturday's showdown against Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little confused right now,'' reserve guard J.P.
Blevins told reporters. ``We're looking for answers, and we're not
getting them.''
</P>
<P>
   No answers, but plenty of problems. The Wildcats play one of the
toughest schedules in the nation; center Jamal Magloire, expected
to be their best player, is shooting 38 percent; point guard Saul
Smith (six turnovers at Maryland) hasn't become an elite player;
talented youngsters Jules Camara, Tayshaun Prince, Desmond Allison
and Keith Bogans aren't ready to carry the load.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents better take their best shot this season because the
Wildcats will be awesome in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   In and out: The two best players in the West, Utah forward Hanno
Mottola and Fresno State guard Courtney Alexander, started the
season with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Mottola suffered a partial tear of the medial collateral
ligament in his knee Nov. 16 and hopes to return next week against
Texas. Without him, the Utes have relied on the 3-point shooting of
Jeremy Killion and Alex Jensen. That's good enough against
Washington State and Stony Brook, but it won't suffice against
Texas (Dec. 22) or Louisville (Jan. 6).
</P>
<P>
   Alexander missed six games because of a stress fracture in his
left foot, and the Bulldogs were 3-3 without him. He's played the
last three games (one win) and didn't take long to regain his
touch, scoring 43 points at Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: Stanford had plenty of reasons to lose to
Georgia Tech last weekend. The Cardinal had just finished final
exams. It was playing on the road, at 9 a.m. body time, without its
best player (injured forward Mark Madsen). In addition, the
Cardinal shot 30.8 percent from the field. How did it survive?
Character, and suffocating defense: Georgia Tech shot 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga guard Matt Santangelo's description of UCLA's zone
offense _ ``They just kind of stood around'' _ speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for leadership? Oregon State guard Deaundra Tanner
has been disciplined twice in seven games, once for missing the
bus, once for breaking an undisclosed team rule.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona freshman point guard Jason Gardner played 40 minutes
against Michigan State and should get ready for more of the same.
For the second consecutive year, the Wildcats don't have a backup
point guard. Last season, Jason Terry played at least 40 minutes 18
times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, after a 6-21 season, Oregon removed coach Don Monson
and reassigned him to the golf team. Monson was totally unqualified
and never reported, giving Oregon justification for terminating his
contract. Saturday, Monson's son, Dan, leads Minnesota against the
Ducks. Dan just might have that episode on his mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 0207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
