r s BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN     12-16 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORR HAS OPEN-GOAL POLICY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goaltender Jamie Storr got the Kings through more
than a month without many of their top players. Now that they're
coming back, he's falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive night, Storr was pulled after just
one period. Wednesday, it came after allowing six goals in an 8-3
loss to the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never felt comfortable,'' Storr said. ``I don't know
why. You'd think that after Tuesday's game (7-1 loss at New Jersey)
that we would shake it off and move on. That just wasn't the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings Coach Andy Murray didn't blame Storr for the loss to the
Devils, where he was benched after allowing three goals in the
first period. The Kings played poorly on defense and never gave him
a chance.
</P>
<P>
   This time Murray wasn't so kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to make some stops,'' Murray said. ``We didn't give
him much help tonight, especially the first three goals when the
Rangers just walked in. But we needed more. We made a decision that
he was going to play the whole period regardless of what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr, who had allowed two or fewer goals in eight of his first
14 games was NHL Player of the Week in early November after taking
over for injured Stephane Fiset. Even with the lopsided loss at New
Jersey, Storr was 8-4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that I stayed in after the first three
goals,'' he said. ``But there were a lot of guys suffering out
there and I should be one of them. We're still a team, you know,
even if we have been playing terribly the past two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray would not speculate whether Storr would be back in goal
Saturday when the Kings host the Chicago Blackhawks. Fiset has
played four periods the past two games and looks ready to take back
the job he had for the first 14 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset's right hand, which was injured Nov. 6 and forced him to
miss six weeks, is not 100 percent. But he allowed just two goals
after taking over for Storr to start the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Lappy's lament: Even with their injured stars trickling back
into action, the Kings know the work ethic they bring to the ice
every night will decide their season. That means third-line center
Ian Laperriere is more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Laperriere was beaten on the Rangers' first goal of the night,
allowing Todd Harvey to walk in on Storr untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take responsibility for this game,'' Laperriere said. ``Our
line sets the tone and this shouldn't happen. The New Jersey game
should have been one of a kind and we should have moved on. The
only way you make that happen is start hitting guys. They just beat
us up the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Kings defenseman Garry Galley entered the game
with the team's best plus-minus rating (+11). He was on the ice for
four of the Rangers' eight goals. . . . Rangers coach John Muckler
was supposed to be fired last month when his team got off to a
terrible start and had the league's worst power play. Now the team
is 4-0-1 in their last five. ``We seem to be going up the ladder
now,'' he said. ``This is a reward for all the hard work we've
done. That was the best first period we've played all year.''
Actually it is the best first period the Rangers have played since
Oct. 30, 1988, when they scored six goals in a 9-2 victory over
Pittsburgh. . . . Former Dodger Mike Piazza was at the game. He's a
blond now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
