<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARY LAKERS BRACE FOR ROAD TESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They're sick, they're sore, and they're just now
getting to the tough part of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have embarked on their first significant road trip of
the season _ four games in five days, starting with tonight's game
against the Atlanta Hawks at Phillips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   They're not exactly in prime shape to meet their biggest
challenge of the season to date.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper is still suffering from a bruised left quadriceps but
might be needed for big minutes. Glen Rice is still recovering from
an upper-respiratory infection that sidelined him for two days this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else is just nursing the usual bumps and bruises. Coach
Phil Jackson gave his team the day off Wednesday to rest them for
the arduous trip that also includes stops in Minneapolis, Toronto
and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher figures everyone will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys will get some good rest, get a chance to sleep in
(Wednesday morning), which we don't get a chance to do very often,
and be ready to go on Thursday,'' he said. ``As far as Glen being
sick, he'll get himself back going. Harp's going to drag that leg
all year, so there's nothing new. He'll still be able to go out
there and compete and give us what he can give us.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said playing four road games in five days, on an injured
leg, ``ain't anything I haven't seen in the past 10 years in this
league. . . . Whatever Phil asks me to do, I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice might not be such a concern. Though knocked out for two
days by a 102-degree fever, he played one of his better games of
the season Tuesday against the Clippers _ 8 for 11 from the field,
17 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the times in the past when I've been sick I've been
able to go out there and play pretty good basketball,'' said Rice,
his voice hoarse. ``I'm going out there realizing that I'm sick, so
I'm a little more focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Moment of truth: The Lakers are sporting an NBA-best 18-5 record
but Jackson has insisted that no assessment can truly be made of
this team until they've gone through an extended road trip. This
one's been circled on the calendar since opening night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with that,'' Fisher said. ``I mean, we know (how good
the team is), but we haven't been on the road, down 10 (points) in
the third quarter and had to fight back. Sacramento was our first
opportunity to be in that situation, and we didn't win. So these
four games will be on the road, we'll be down and everybody will be
against us, so we'll have to figure out a way to stay together,
stay strong and come out with four wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The season is more than a quarter over, but the Lakers have
played just nine road games, and until now, they've only had one
trip that's lasted longer than a day (a two-day trip in early
November).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I agree with Phil, as far as this trip being a very
nice test for us, to kind of see where we are at at this point, as
far as our ability to execute, play together,'' Fisher said. ``You
know, it's tougher on the road. One night you can put it together,
maybe two nights you can put it together. But now we have four
games on the road, and we have to be able to put it together all
four nights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
