<SLUG> BC-OSTLER16-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER NOT WAIT FOR MUNI AT AMMIANO'S BUS STOP  

</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Great, now Muni will never get fixed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why would Willie Brown want to fix Muni when it's what brings
Tom Ammiano to work?
</P>
<P>
   Willie, despite his wide margin of victory, has to be steamed.
He's one of the most powerful politicians of our times, and he had
to campaign like a madman to beat a guy who should have been a bug
on the mayor's windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if Ammiano hadn't been so scarily liberal, and hadn't
made most of his pre-mayoral-campaign headlines by standing up for
the zinging nuns and against ATM fees.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Supes, Ammiano has been the patron saint of
fringe causes, and still he was able to play Rocky Balboa to
Willie's Apollo Creed.
</P>
<P>
   Now Brown says he's planning to hang onto his grudge against
Ammiano over the Cookie Jar Statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign debate, referring to the FBI investigation of the
city's Housing Authority, Tom said Willie got caught with his hand
in the cookie jar. Brown interprets that as an accusation that he
was on the take.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Ammiano was accusing Brown of getting caught doing the
worst thing a mayor can do when whiffs of scandal filter up to his
office from below: Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Ammiano should have said Brown got caught with his  &LR; head
 &LR; in the cookie jar.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Tom, thanks for the excitement, and good luck catching
your bus this morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BITTERLY COLD  &LR; out, it was last Friday night. At the Anchor Brewery
on Potrero Hill, brewer Bill Kiebala was alone, finishing his work,
when he heard a rapping on the rear gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're cold and we're locked out of the church,'' someone said.
``Can we come in and warm up until someone brings the key?''
</P>
<P>
   Bill said sorry, but he was busy and he was working alone.
Brewers are notoriously softhearted, though, and he changed his
mind, opened the door and ushered 20 members of the S.F. Choral
Artists Group into the taproom.
</P>
<P>
   The person with the key to St. Gregory Episcopal across the
street never showed, so the group held choir practice for several
hours in the taproom, using Anchor's well-tuned piano, with
refreshments supplied by good old Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bill even gave 'em a brewery tour, and the singers serenaded the
burbling vats of Anchor Steam.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a church key when you've got a tap?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE MARRIAGE  &LR; of Albertson's and Lucky has already lost some of its
electricity, notes Cammy Blackstone, wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   She reports: ``On the market sign at the Lakeshore Plaza, some
letters are burned out and it reads `AL E SO S.'''
</P>
<P>
   One rumor is that Albertson caught Lucky getting lucky with
Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ANOTHER  &LR; sighting by Cammy the signfreak: The marquee at the
McDonald's at 16th and Potrero, ``TOY CANDY DISPENSERS NOW
HIRING.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of OSTLER16 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Just wondering: Will the fast-food kids of today become adults
who will reject any meal that's not accompanied by a new cheap toy?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DEPT. OF VITAL  &LR; information: Since Watergate, people don't name
their kids Richard.
</P>
<P>
   So observes Richard (I Am Not A Kook) Glasson, who says,
``Richard is like Benedict, Adolf or Lee Harvey. No longer P.C.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HEY, NASA,  &LR; asks Doug Biggs, are you offering a reward for the
return of your two lost Mars-exploration thingies?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I've found them,'' Biggs says, ``on two pedestals in
front of the Ferry Building.''
</P>
<P>
   City art czar Stanlee Gatti would probably like to post a sign:
``Welcome, artists, to San Francisco _ 750,000 art critics, no
waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TWO WELL- &LR; dressed little old ladies distributing copies of ``The
Watchtower'' ride the up escalator from the Powell St. Bart station
to the cable-car turntable.
</P>
<P>
   At the top, notices Scott McKellar, the ladies bump into two
homeless men selling the ``Street Sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiles are exchanged and without a word, two Watchtowers are
traded for two Street Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE GREATEST  &LR; thing since sliced bread? Cuffs Corbett has found it,
in the little sewing kit in his guest room at the Hilton:
prethreaded needles.
</P>
<P>
   A great labor-saving device, probably assembled in Third World
sweatshops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MIDNIGHT WILL COME  &LR; early on New Year's Eve for the revelers at the
Gold Coast, on California. At 8 a.m. on the 31st, they'll toast the
stroke of midnight in Fiji with appropriate Fijian libations and
incantations, and whatever cable TV feed they can suck in from that
time zone.
</P>
<P>
   And so on, a new New Millennium celebrated every hour, circling
the globe until 2 a.m., when whoever's left will attempt to
pronounce ``Aloha'' and demand that the globe stop spinning so
fast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STRANGE DAY,  &LR; Tuesday was, notes Lotta Dotz. ``Willie Brown talked
the talk and Charlie Brown took a walk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNCLEAR ON CONCEPT:  &LR; Don't worry, there will be no shortage of
Pokemon trading cards between now and the time they're all gone.
</P>
<P>
   In a newspaper ad ``letter to the fans of Pokemon,'' the Pokemon
people say, ``please be assured that there are enough Trading Card
Game Cards for every (Pokemon movie) ticket purchased.''
</P>
<P>
   Just mail them your ticket and they'll send you a card.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny print at bottom of ad: ``Offer good while supplies last.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
