<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0610 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE--COLUMN-LA     12-16 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE--COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE MAKES IMPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge was at the center of another
stunning, numbing jolt last Saturday. Did you feel it?
</P>
<P>
   It shook college basketball pretty forcibly, the shockwaves
spreading out from the west like a shiver down Dick Vitale's spine.
</P>
<P>
   They've been talking about it as far away as Tennessee. And in
Eugene they're still sifting through the rubble, looking for
answers as to how the Matadors managed to beat Oregon on its home
court.
</P>
<P>
   The result was jarring, if only because these weren't sitting
Ducks that CSUN toppled 79-77. Oregon has returned three starters
from the squad that graced last season's NIT Final Four and is
widely regarded as an upper echelon team in one of the country's
toughest, tightest conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, McArthur Court is easily one of the toughest
places to play in the Pacific-10. Winning streaks tend to go there
to die. Just ask UCLA, which has lost two of its last three games
on that court.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Matadors haven't cornered the market on upsets.
The college basketball season hasn't even reached the time line and
already we've seen Samford beat St. John's, Northern Illinois
defeat Wisconsin and Kentucky fall out of the Associated Press Top
25.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN, though, is one up on the Bulldogs and Badgers, both of
whom participated in last season's NCAA Tournament. Twice now, the
Matadors have chanted the magic word _ ``teamwork'' _ shaken their
capes and, presto!, a huge win has materialized out of air thick
with hostility.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would appear the Oregon win was an aftershock to the
temblor of Nov. 30, when CSUN stunned Fresno State 69-66 in front
of a sellout crowd of 10,200 at Selland Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Understand: Fresno State isn't simply Jerry Tarkanian's team; it
was No. 20 on basketball virtuoso Vitale's preseason top-40. The
Ducks graced his list, too, at No. 35.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Matadors, they haven't been this high since the 1996
Big Sky Conference championships when they came within one win of
qualifying for the NCAA Tournament after upsetting Northern Arizona
in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fresno State was the one I was praying for,'' said the
Matadors' fourth-year coach Bobby Braswell. ``Just so the guys
could taste what a hugger is.''
</P>
<P>
   A hugger, for the uninitiated, is the next best thing to hitting
the lottery jackpot and having Ashley Judd present you with the
check.
</P>
<P>
   It's when your heart is racing and time is standing still.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sensation not unlike stumbling out of the dark into
brilliant sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   It's the celebration that ensues when Andre Larry banks in a
jumper over three defenders with the clock ticking down at Oregon
or when the your team opens up an 18-point lead at Fresno State and
hangs on to win.
</P>
<P>
   The hugs and hurrahs are coming fast and furious now, as quickly
as former players can click ``send'' on a congratulatory e-mail or
dial the telephone. There's so much Matador pride it has Braswell a
little misty-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day,'' he remembered preaching to his players as recently
as their 73-59 loss to USC on Nov. 19, ``we're going to get to the
point where you're not embarrassed to wear the Northridge shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Braswell didn't know how right he was. The only red his players
are wearing these days is on their shoes or jerseys, not their
faces. Heck, they aren't even ashamed of clashing.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Jeff Parris, junior guard Carl Holmes and
sophomore point guard Markus Carr are the team's designated
leaders. Their responsibilities include leading the Matadors in
stretching and establishing the game-day fashion.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the trio risked the wrath of Mr. Blackwell by
eschewing the black sneakers the team traditionally wears with its
black road jerseys in favor of the red and white sneakers they
usually save for home games.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that helps explain why the Matadors felt right at home in
the roiling sea of green. They kept their composure when the Ducks
held a three-point lead with just over three minutes to play. There
was a timeout and before Braswell could speak, Carr cleared his
throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are NOT going to lose this game,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Carr said of his bravado, ``I felt if I showed
some leadership, it would (resonate) through the team.''
</P>
<P>
   If you saw the movie ``Hoosiers'' you have a pretty good idea
what happened after that.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, a senior who started his career at Oregon, banked in his
improbable shot to put the Matadors ahead by one with 10 seconds
left. Five seconds later, an Oregon player missed a layup and Carr
was fouled.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who had goaded his teammates into believing stepped to
the line and, to his disbelief, missed his first free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, who said he ``was definitely nervous,'' regrouped and
swished his second attempt. In the time it took his second shot to
fall and the remaining seconds to tick off the clock, Carr learned
more about himself and this team than could be crammed into seven
semesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so satisfying, just showing myself I can play with the
big boys and showing people our team can play with the big boys,''
said Carr, who finished with 13 points and eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   The players now believe. But what about CSUN's sixth man? Are
the fans open to being converted?
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest fear is that what the players achieved will go
unnoticed and they'll get discouraged,'' Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors play two games on the road next week, at Oral
Roberts and Texas El-Paso, before returning home to the 1,600-seat
Matador Gym on Dec. 28 to play St. Francis of New York. The law of
supply and demand will be in effect: If the students demand seats
to the game, Braswell will supply the pizzas for those cueing to
get tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to stand at the mall and hand out flyers
(advertising) the game, I will,'' Braswell vowed.
</P>
<P>
   You should know, Braswell's value is climbing faster than area
real estate. If players like Carr keep improving and the Matadors
continue winning, Braswell is going to be harder to keep at CSUN
than a secret.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors long in the shadows of Pepperdine and UCLA and USC,
are dropping their cloak and developing a swagger. When the next
win of significant magnitude comes, don't say you weren't warned. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
