<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV19-C     12-16 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: NEW LEGAL MEDICINE FOR DOCTORS ONLY
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are some 700,000 self-employed doctors in the
United States. They earn, on average, $200,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such typically cushy incomes, many doctors are griping.
It's not about money, they say. It's about health care plans that
jilt their patients to satisfy stockholders. By working in concert,
some doctors say, they would stand a better chance of putting
things back in sync.
</P>
<P>
   But that would break the antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians agree it's time to right the balance. Earlier
this year, the House Judiciary Committee held hearings on a
bipartisan bill that would permit health care professionals to
negotiate collectively with health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsors say that would bring about an equilibrium in
negotiating power, foster competition and enhance the quality of
patient care, without impacting doctors' duties to offer medically
necessary care.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill, seeks to strike a balance
of his own in the struggle. Says Hyde: ``The doctor-patient
relationship must be preserved, and I am concerned that it may be
diminishing.'' He adds, however, that ``almost everyone's life
would be easier if they were exempt from the antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joel Klein, the government's top cop, says it's all about
greed. The legislation, he maintains, ``would hurt consumers and
taxpayers by raising the costs of both private health insurance and
governmental programs with no assurance that quality of care would
be improved.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Eric Holder, the deputy attorney general, who is
married to a doctor, went to the annual meeting of the local
medical society. He heard some horror stories caused by insurers'
bureaucratic bungling. (I know this because I'm married to a doctor
too.)
</P>
<P>
   But Holder didn't budge a stitch. So with a presidential veto in
the offing, the American Medical Association has gone to Plan B: it
has formed a union.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers signed up the first members earlier this month at the
AMA's winter meetings in San Diego. They call themselves Physicians
for Responsible Negotiations, or PRN for short, the Latin
abbreviation for ``pro re nata,'' which is what doctors write on
prescription pads to show that the medicine should be used only as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a funny kind of union. It won't strike or honor picket
lines or link up with other labor groups. Only doctors can join,
but of course you can practice medicine without joining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't intended to be focused on the almighty buck,'' says
Susan Hershberg Adelman, a Southfield, Mich., pediatric surgeon who
has been named PRN's president. ``So far,'' she adds, ``doctors are
coming to us with stories about their working conditions and how
that impacts their ability to take care of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton turns a deaf ear, the National Labor
Relations Board is listening. Earlier this month, the agency
overturned its own 1976 decision by ruling, 3-2, that interns and
residents who work in private hospitals can join labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
