<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0683 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-$AD     12-16 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMING UP: MUCH MORE OF THE SAME
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As anyone who once bought an eight-track tape
player can attest, predicting the future of technology is not for
those who embarrass easily.
</P>
<P>
   Still, forecasters keep looking down the road, doing their best
to guess where the new century will take us. While they differ
about what specific tools and toys will shape our tomorrows,
prognosticators do seem certain about one thing: Whatever we have,
we'll have more of it.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have more computers, more televisions, more phones, more
types of food, more kinds of fabric. Because of computer-controlled
manufacturing systems and expanding global trade, the price of
goods will be falling while our affluence will be rising. That
means more of us will have more of everything.
</P>
<P>
   So far, our response to affluence has been to build bigger
houses. Last week, the U.S. Census Bureau released its latest
Statistical Abstract, providing fresh data about how we are
handling our prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the size of the average new home shot to 2,190 square
feet, up dramatically from the 1970 figure of 1,500 square feet. In
1998, about half of all new homes had at least two and a half
bathrooms, up from just 16 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   These bigger houses have allowed us to stack up our shoes,
sheets, shampoos and other possessions. Landfills have absorbed the
rest. Peering into the typical American closet, one might conclude
that we have about all we need.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to material wealth, we ain't seen nothin' yet.
</P>
<P>
   The typical household of the 21st century will have far more
goods, if for no other reason than shifting demographics. As the
World War II generation dwindles in the early years of the new
century, baby boomers will inherit trillions of dollars worth of
cash and goods. Boomers will be bringing into their already crammed
houses their deceased parents' furniture, dishes, pictures, jewelry
and heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   Then in another 20 years, the oldest of the boomers will start
dying off in large numbers. The peak of this inter-generational
wealth transfer will come in about 2035. Because they gave birth to
fewer children than their parents, boomers will have fewer heirs to
absorb the cascade of accumulated goods that will come tumbling
down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, younger generations already will be piling up their
own mountains of cheaply produced goods. When the compounded wealth
of the World War II generation and the boomers finally comes to
rest in the chock-full homes of their children and grandchildren, a
nationwide cry may go up: Where are we going to put all this stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this immense wealth of goods will provide Americans with
a chance to help poorer people around the world. Charitable
organizations that can find ways to bundle up our bounty and ship
it overseas might help reduce the wealth gap between First and
Third World nations.
</P>
<P>
   At this time, few organizations are interested in cleaning,
sorting and sending clothes and other goods to poor countries. That
means our castoffs generally bounce from one yard sale to the next
until the landfill claims them.
</P>
<P>
   In the 21st century, our ability to manage mountains of
merchandise may determine whether we will improve the world, or
simply bury ourselves. The ``more millennium'' will be ours to
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
