<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-CO     12-16 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: An unanticipated Y2K glitch
 &HT;    (For release Dec. 19, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With guarded anticipation, perhaps a slight sense of foreboding,
I await the arrival of the next thousand years _ give or take a
year. As a good little soldier, I have read everything I could
understand about Y2K, which is not a lot but an effort
nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   But just when I thought I was fully compliant, I found out I
wasn't. Oh, my computer is ready (even though my venerable word
program still thinks it is 1982); the airlines say they're ready to
serve me, the medical records departments indicate full compliance,
the government claims it's prepared, but I suddenly realized that I
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   It was while writing a check to the cable company that I noticed
that the space for the date concluded with 19; as in 1999 or 1901.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I order checks by the bale, printed
with my name, address and part of the date on it. They're ordered
about 350 at a time. And now they seemingly are out of date _ by a
whole millenary!
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as I favor overreaction to most things, I began to
wonder if any checks I write beginning Jan. 1 will be good. Do you
simply cross out the 19 and scratch in 2000? Or is this all a
gambit to have us discard our inventory and buy new checks that
begin the year date with 20?
</P>
<P>
   Obsessed with this nominal glitch in Y2K compliance, I sought
out two banking executives from different banks.
</P>
<P>
   What do I do about the 19?, I asked seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The answers, not in these exact words, were, ``What are you,
nuts?''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the explanations that rattled me. One banker said
that no human being at her bank actually looks at any checks for
less than $3,000; it's one of those computer-driven processes. So
an imprecise date wouldn't mean anything. The second banker told me
his bank doesn't look at any check that is written for less than
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean I can write a check and date it Oct. 12, 1492, or
Dec. 7, 1941 and if it's less than $1,000, it will just sail
through unnoticed?'' I asked the second banking executive.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, pretty much, he responded. Then he cautioned me, while
functioning from his humorist/banker mode: ``But just in case the
check has to be examined for something, say a claim of forgery, you
should know that checks written in 1492 are not honored. In Florida
(where the banker operates) there is a limit of one year on checks
being deposited or cashed.''
</P>
<P>
   All this simply leads to more questions, far too heady for me to
approach at this time of holiday-spirit and spirits. Such as
wondering how banks spot forged checks that are written for amounts
below the guidelines of human scrutiny. Or if I could write a check
now for, say, $387, date it Dec. 19, 2056, and have it accepted by
the seemingly Y2K compliant computer?
</P>
<P>
   As for the known quandary about existing pre-printed 19 checks,
until such time as I get an ominous call from the bank telling me
otherwise, I simply will cross out the 19 and write in 20. It's all
so logical, I don't know why it ever concerned me.
</P>
<P>
   When Y2K flips over in a couple of weeks, and the planet remains
in its orbit, we'll likely wonder why we ever were concerned with a
lot of the stuff that they've been telling us to be concerned over.
</P>
<P>
   You want to panic over something? I'll tell you what to panic
about. Microsoft announced last week that its Windows 2000
operating system for businesses will be shipped to corporate
customers Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be the millennial bug we have been anticipating,
but think of all those businesses that have computers to which we
owe payments. The people who program and operate them will have to
orient themselves to Windows 2000, and if you ever tried to learn
Windows 95 or Windows 98 from scratch, you can imagine what Windows
2000 will be like.
</P>
<P>
   And when things don't happen smoothly _ such as you made a
payment but ``their'' computer didn't record it _ the businesses
usually defend themselves, saying that ``a few bugs need to be
worked out'' in the new system. This could be the situation
beginning Feb. 17, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Those, then, will be the true millennium bugs!
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
