<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX     12-16 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Yes, Internet, there is a tax collector
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to what Karl Marx expected and Ronald Reagan hoped, no,
the state is not _ repeat: not _ going to wither away. Which brings
us to taxes. Which brings us to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is much urgent mulling going on at high levels and low
over the prospect of applying state and local sales taxes to
``remote'' retail trade _ that is, to catalog and Internet commerce
_ just as they are applied to store sales.
</P>
<P>
   Most state and local governments, it will not surprise you to
learn, are for it. The opponents are more animated and more varied.
</P>
<P>
   They include the usual right-wing foundations, think tanks and
activists formed up ad hoc as the ``e-Freedom Coalition,'' which
really does want to defund government away. The aginners include,
too, of course, many of the businesses that would have to charge,
collect and distribute the taxes and would rather not. And the
la-de-da Internet romantics, who, in a fantasy of perpetual
adolescence, imagine an Internet life forever cut off from the real
world, gravity free, where the only responsibility is to the
gratification of the cruiser's impulse of the moment. Taxes offend
that notion.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, this is a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   State and local governments already are losing about $5 billion
in taxes annually to catalog sales, and with Internet commerce
booming they could be losing $15 billion in another three years.
Remote sales hit $2.7 trillion last year, 3.5 percent of total
retail sales, and the Direct Marketing Association figures their
share will double by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   There is simply no good reason not to charge routine sales
taxes. The Supreme Court worried about an undue management burden
30 years ago when it limited catalog sales tax charges to buyers in
states where the seller has a fixed facility, but computer
technology makes broad collection feasible.
</P>
<P>
   The current tax-free status of remote sellers gives them an
unfair, government-sanctioned competitive edge over other
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   And there's an issue of social fairness, though to say so these
days is to be accused of fomenting class warfare. Sales taxes are
inherently regressive, sopping up a bigger part of low incomes than
of high ones. Tax-free remote sales worsen that imbalance,
benefiting shoppers, especially on the Internet, who are on average
far better off than most customers.
</P>
<P>
   A high-level commission is to recommend to Congress next spring
whether the current, legislated moratorium on Internet and catalog
sales taxes should be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The 46 states with sales taxes collect, on average, more than 40
percent of their revenue from that source. The revenue funds
schools, law enforcement, park systems and more. If state and local
governments are aced out of an increasing proportion of potential
sales taxes, they will simply have to raise other taxes _ the
property tax, payroll or income taxes _ to make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, there still ain't no free lunch, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
