<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0731 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FBI-Y2K17-COX     12-16 0206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-Y2K17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI is getting ready for any millennium bugs
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The FBI will maintain 56 24-hour Y2K command
posts across the nation to address any potential federal criminal
violations or national security incidents during the millennium
rollover.
</P>
<P>
   ``While no specific threats have been received to indicate an
increased level of criminal activity, general information has been
disseminated at the national level which suggests the potential for
increased malicious cyber activity as well as potential physical
attacks on the nation's infrastructures from millennial or
terrorist groups,'' said Sheri A. Farrar, special agent in charge
of the Cincinnati FBI division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information concerning such threats or an actual incident
occurring in the southern half of Ohio should be promptly reported
to the Cincinnati FBI,'' Farrar said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that ``while some malicious cyber activity may occur,
the main concern with the Y2K rollover is the possibility of
isolated service outages affecting public utilities caused by the
Y2K date problem in older computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
