<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX     12-16 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To many of certitude, complexity is evil in and of itself
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The numbers say newspaper readership is declining.
Take a Page 1 story Tuesday in most metro papers in the country and
get a hint as to why.
</P>
<P>
   Slapped down on the nation's doorsteps that morning: complexity,
raw human complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Top story: Surgeon General David Satcher challenges the way we
look at the mentally ill. He estimates that nearly one in five
Americans has suffered from mental illness, ranging from clinical
depression to bipolar disorder, but two-thirds of those stricken
never seek treatment. Either they are paralyzed by stigma, or they
just don't know they're sick.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard about missile gaps, learning gaps, earning gaps.
Satcher's important report demonstrates a perception gap.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans will take this information and become better
informed, better able to deal with a world of complexity. Some will
just cancel their subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   They will crawl into their bunkers to protect themselves from
the commie threat of our age, ``com'' as in com-plexity.
</P>
<P>
   Having someone in Washington point out that clinical mental
illness is far more pervasive than assumed rubs against
assumptions, particularly among the ever-thriving fundamentalist
persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   It is neat and tidy to think that there are good people and
there are bad people.
</P>
<P>
   Don't give us the thesis that many bad people are good people
with an illness that makes them act badly.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go informing us that new-generation drugs can make
miraculous strides with schizophrenics. You're talking about lots
of money in curbing these mumbling street persons (we know they're
simply slothful), more government trying to help people. We say,
each to his own bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly we don't want to get too deeply into this mental illness
stuff because it removes the certainty we take with us in asserting
right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the death penalty. Few people would bemoan the fate of
a sound-minded individual who killed and, knowing what he bargained
for, gets death in return. But what if he were mentally ill?
Insanity is a defense, we say. It also is as uneven as a dart toss.
Certainly the odds of making such a defense stick are far greater
than one in five, which are the odds of mental illness among even
the peaceable.
</P>
<P>
   Move away from crime. That complexity stuff finds other ways to
make life difficult for the devoutly certain. That is why they
often are given to cursing science.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of man is one such area. Is evolution as origin
anti-God? Hardly. It is simply not something that can be elaborated
in one chapter, 31 verses and six days.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution as origin can be as good as the Good Book describes.
It just can't be as concise.
</P>
<P>
   Complexity be gone. And take science with you.
</P>
<P>
   Be gone, these people will say, with scientists studying to see
if homosexuals carry a genetic trait or some other determinant that
makes their sexuality not a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you go equating homosexuality to right-handedness or
brunetteness, the certain will say. That makes things far too
complex and almost impossible to condemn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that would make homosexuals among the creatures placed
on this earth as is, as was when the creator, to paraphrase Genesis
1, said, ``Behold _ very good.''
</P>
<P>
   I know what the rejoinder to this is: This complexity stuff is
simply a dodge for relativists who won't acknowledge evil, won't
acknowledge sin.
</P>
<P>
   My only question as a newspaper man: Is inquisitiveness among
God's gifts to man, or is it original sin?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
