<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Far-right group attacking Republicans
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Tommy Merritt, a Republican state representative
from Longview, was intrigued recently by a letter asking him and
wife Janet to ``change the future of Texas. We need your help in
finding a qualified conservative candidate for state
representative.''
</P>
<P>
   Merritt read on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This letter is sent to you because you are a proven civic
leader who has voted in several recent primaries. You live in a
district that has strong Texas values and votes for conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet your State Representative, Tommy Merritt, has received
only a 58 percent rating on conservative issues according to our
respected analysis of critical votes,'' the letter continued.
``This is a failing grade. Rep. Merritt does not vote for the
values of your district.''
</P>
<P>
   Merritt and several other incumbent Republican state
representatives have been complaining to their Democratic
colleagues that the far-right groups that once campaigned against
the Democrats are now campaigning against some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The letter to Merritt was written on the stationery of Free PAC,
the political arm of the Free Market Committee. It was signed by
Richard Ford, founder and operator of both groups, who says he is
paid benefits but no salary. Ford's letter asked Merritt to help
find a candidate to run against Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is your district represented by someone who does not vote
according to the wishes of the folks back home?'' Ford wrote. ``We
think it's because the one expert who knows your district hasn't
been asked _ you! We are asking, pleading, begging for your help.''
</P>
<P>
   And money.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ford should not count on receiving help or money from
Rep. Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was chagrined about the letter, too: ``That was a mistake _
meaning he should not have received a letter from our mailing
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he'd specifically told the direct-mail operation to
take Merritt's name off the GOP voter mailing list. But he had no
apology for opposing Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   Merritt charged that Ford's group styles itself as a
free-market, free-enterprise outfit, but ``predominantly used
social issues as a scoring mechanism.'' Merritt was marked down by
Ford's group for votes on parental notification on abortion _ he
voted to allow a pregnant girl to tell a member of the clergy
rather than a parent before getting an abortion _ and for a
hate-crimes bill championed primarily by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Bonnen (R-Angleton) says the same ultraconservative
opponent he beat in a runoff in the 1996 GOP primary, Diane Hensley
of Alvin, is readying to run against him again. In her first race,
she received backing from far-right groups such as Free PAC and
another political action committee associated with San Antonio
multimillionaire James Leininger, Bonnen noted. Leininger
co-chaired Free PAC's dinner in October.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Eppstein, a Fort Worth-based political consultant, advises
more than three dozen Republican legislators, including Merritt and
Bonnen. He said many contributors to special interest groups such
as Free PAC or the Eagle Forum and the Christian Coalition, which
make abortion their main issues, are well-meaning. But some of the
positions the groups' leaders devise are out of step with
mainstream Republicans, from Gov. George W. Bush on down, Eppstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hue and cry of Republican voters and officials all over
the state of Texas is `We want a broader, more inclusive Republican
party. We do not want litmus tests,''' Eppstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Merritt, a businessman who belongs to groups such as the Texas
Association of Business and Chambers of Commerce, was alerting some
people and organizations who have sent money to either the Free
Market Committee or its PAC, saying they ``should examine very
closely the members and what their true agendas are.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ford's ham-handed effort against Merritt may already be
backfiring. For instance, Vaughn Aldredge, AT&AMP;T's governmental
affairs vice president, wrote Ford to complain _ and pledged
continued political support for Merritt from the ``AT&AMP;T PAC and
hundreds of AT&AMP;T managers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Aldredge said AT&AMP;T would no longer
contribute to the Free Market Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Land Commissioner David Dewhurst is a financial supporter of
Free PAC who was listed as vice chair of the group's biennial
banquet honoring its ``Top Ten'' percent conservative Texas
legislators. Dewhurst ducked when asked his feeling about Ford's
group opposing Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to have been a sponsor of the dinner for
conservative legislators held each year by Free PAC, but I'm not
consulted in PAC activities or decisions,'' Dewhurst said through
spokesman Richard McBride.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
