<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0736 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CHRISTMAS17-COX     12-16 2852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CHRISTMAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's an appropriate tome for every type on your list
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're still searching for a holiday gift for your
significant other, distant cousin, persnickety mother-in-law or
weird uncle, perhaps you should consider a book. They're easy to
wrap, returnable and, best of all, you don't have to worry about
getting the right size. You do, however, need to match the
recipient with the right book.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have an aunt who has saved every issue of The Saturday
Evening Post? Give her ``Norman Rockwell: Pictures for the American
People'' (Abrams, $45) or the three-dimensional ``Norman Rockwell:
A Pop-Up Art Experience'' (Rizzoli, $18).
</P>
<P>
   Got an armchair adventurer in the house? ``Last Climb: The
Legendary Everest Expeditions of George Mallory'' (National
Geographic, $35) by David Breashears and Audrey Salkeld is
realistic enough to give him frostbite.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer heft, you can't go wrong with ``Century: 100 Years of
Human Progress, Regression, Suffering and Hope 1899-1999''
(Phaidon, $49.95). This 13-pound volume is the best-selling gift
tome of the season, says Katie Parker of the Atlanta-based Chapter
11 Discount Bookstore chain. The 1,120-page book by Bruce Bernard
has more than 1,000 photographs, including rare images of the
Beatles performing in Liverpool's Cavern Club and Teddy Roosevelt
visiting Booker T. Washington in 1901.
</P>
<P>
   Other brisk sellers are ``The Greatest Generation Speaks''
(Random House, $19.95), Tom Brokaw's follow-up to his best seller
``The Greatest Generation,'' and ``LIFE: Our Century in Pictures''
(Bulfinch, $60), a collection of images from the fabled magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Books that have won awards or been featured on television are
always in demand, Parker says. ``Ha Jin's `Waiting' took off after
he won the National Book Award. Oprah's books still do OK, but a
lot of readers say they're getting a little tired of this
emotional, redemptive fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no ``Cold Mountain'' this year, but Kent Haruf's
``Plainsong'' (Knopf, $24) is an excellent substitute. Set in a
small Colorado town, the novel is the story of how two teachers,
two young boys, a couple of quirky ranchers and a pregnant high
school teenager converge to form an extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations by category:
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY FICTION
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ahab's Wife'' by Sena Jeter Naslund (William Morrow, $28),
an entertaining tale told from the viewpoint of the captain's wife
from ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Long Home'' by William Gay (Macmurray &AMP; Beck, $24.95),
a story of a young Tennessee carpenter and a beautiful young woman
who are forced to confront one of the most evil villains in recent
literature.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Welding With Children'' by Tim Gautreaux (Picador, $22).
Eleven stories featuring eccentric characters such as a camera
repairman who uncovers a young woman's secret in a roll of
decades-old undeveloped film.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``For the Relief of Unbearable Urges'' by Nathan Englander
(Knopf, $22). These brilliant short stories deal with the clash of
Jewish law and tradition with the reality of secular life.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Book Borrower'' by Alice Mattison (Morrow, $24). This
poignant novel follows a 20-year friendship between two women in
New York and the life of an anarchist from the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Night Inspector'' by Frederick Busch (Harmony, $23). An
atmospheric novel about a Union sniper who makes friends in New
York with author Herman Melville.
</P>
<P>
   PAGE TURNERS
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Timeline'' by Michael Crichton (Knopf, $26.95). From the
writer who gave us ``Jurassic Park,'' a sci-fi tale of 20th-century
scientists who are able to enter life in 14th-century France.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Personal Injuries'' by Scott Turow (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $27). Legal intrigue about the feds' efforts to use a dirty
lawyer as an informant against bribe-taking judges.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Be Cool'' by Elmore Leonard (Delacorte, $24.95).
Mobster-turned-movie-producer Chili Palmer is now in the record
business.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Hannibal'' by Thomas Harris (Delacorte, $27.95). This
follow-up to ``The Silence of the Lambs'' is entertaining but way
over the top. Not for the queasy.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Heartwood'' by James Lee Burke (Doubleday, $24.95). Texas
lawyer Billy Bob Holland struggles with corruption, powerful
enemies and the sins of the past.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   -- ``And the Crowd Goes Wild'' by Bob Costas and Joe Warner
(Sourcebooks, $49.95). Read about the greatest moments in sports
with this detailed retrospective and listen to the actual events on
two audio CDs.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``ESPN SportsCentury,'' edited by Michael MacCambridge.
Introduction by David Halberstam (Hyperion, $40). This companion to
ESPN's series about the century's greatest athletes celebrates the
heroes and great moments in sports with photographs and essays by
Joyce Carol Oates, Roy Blount Jr. and others.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``NASCAR: A Celebration'' by Bob Latford (Carlton, $24.95). A
former publicist for NASCAR provides an inside-track look at the
growth of stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Guinness World Records 2000'' (Guinness World Records,
$25.95). A century's worth of new records, accompanied by 700
full-color photographs. A trivia lover's delight.
</P>
<P>
   ART AND PHOTOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Deep Blues: Bill Traylor 1854-1949,'' edited by Josef
Helfenstein and Roman Kurzmeyer (Yale University Press, $29.95). A
fascinating study of the works of the former Alabama
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see BOOKS, E2
</P>
<P>
   slave who became a renowned folk artist. Also included are
photographs that reveal the daily life of blacks in Alabama during
the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``American Characters: Selections From the National Portrait
Gallery'' by R.W.B. Lewis (Yale University Press, $45). This
fascinating collection includes 160 portraits of Americans ranging
from Pocahontas to Louis Armstrong. Each portrait is accompanied by
lively commentary.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Diego Rivera'' by Pete Hamill (Abrams, $40.50). The
journalist-author blends his narrative gifts with a lifelong love
of Mexico and an early education in art to write about the
outspoken Mexican muralist who made his politics known through his
frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Women.'' Photographs by Annie Leibovitz, essay by Susan
Sontag (Random House, $75). The women in this stunning book run the
gamut from models to Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``New York: An Illustrated History'' by Ric Burns and James
Sanders (Knopf, $60). In case you missed the PBS series, this
beautifully illustrated book captures the essence of the Big Apple
and many of its characters, from Peter Stuyvesant to F. Scott
Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   AWARD WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Waiting'' by Ha Jin (Pantheon, $24). This National Book
Award winner follows the ordeal of a married Chinese doctor who
falls in love with a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Disgrace'' by J.M. Coetzee (Viking, $23.95). Winner of the
Booker Prize, this novel is the story of a South African professor
whose affair with a student leaves him jobless and friendless
except for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Bone by Bone'' by Peter Matthiessen (Random House, $26.95).
The winner of the Southern Book Critics Award, this final novel in
a trilogy set in turn-of-the-century Florida concludes the story of
Edgar Watson, a pioneer entrepreneur and murderer.
</P>
<P>
   THE OPRAH CLUB
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Map of the World'' by Jane Hamilton (Anchor, $12.95
paperback). A school nurse attempting to deal with a personal
tragedy is charged with sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Vinegar Hill'' by A. Manette Ansay (Avon, $13 paperback). A
young wife and her jobless husband are forced to move in with his
unpleasant parents in this Midwestern Gothic novel.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Tara Road'' by Maeve Binchy (Delacorte, $24.95). An Irish
wife swaps houses for the summer with a New England woman after her
husband leaves her for his pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHIES
</P>
<P>
   AND NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Walker Evans'' by James R. Mellow (Basic Books, $40). A
gracefully written biography of the famous photographer who
captured the images of the Depression-era South in ``Let Us Now
Praise Famous Men.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mandela: The Authorized Biography'' by Anthony Sampson
(Knopf, $30). A comprehensive study of the political prisoner who
became president of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Hungry Years: A Narrative History of the Great
Depression in America'' by T.H. Watkins (Henry Holt, $32.50). The
acclaimed historian looks at the Depression from the viewpoint of
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Toy Story: The Essential Guide'' (Dorling Kindersley,
$14.95). Illustrated profiles of the major characters in Disney's
new film, including little-known facts about Woody and Buzz
Lightyear.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The World of Ripley's Believe It or Not,'' edited by Julie
Mooney (Black Dog &AMP; Leventhal Publishers, $24.95). And, finally,
for that weird uncle who has a collection of shrunken heads and
other oddities, a coffee-table book with some of the world's
greatest curiosities. Read about ``Three Ball Charlie,'' the
Nebraskan who could put a tennis ball, billiards ball and golf ball
in his mouth and still whistle, or follow the exploits of Angelo
Corsaro of Catania, Italy, who walked 558 miles to the Vatican on
10-foot stilts.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Pop-Up Book of Phobias'' by Gary Greenberg (Rob
Weisbach Books, $24.95). A three-dimensional book with pop-ups of
spiders, snakes, plane crashes and other scary stuff.
</P>
<P>
   eaa
</P>
<P>
   Books: Page-turners to nonfiction dazzlers
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Continued from E1
</P>
<P>
   slave who became a renowned folk artist. Also included are
photographs that reveal the daily life of blacks in Alabama during
the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``American Characters: Selections From the National Portrait
Gallery'' by R.W.B. Lewis (Yale University Press, $45). This
fascinating collection includes 160 portraits of Americans ranging
from Pocahontas to Louis Armstrong. Each portrait is accompanied by
lively commentary.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Diego Rivera'' by Pete Hamill (Abrams, $40.50). The
journalist-author blends his narrative gifts with a lifelong love
of Mexico and an early education in art to write about the
outspoken Mexican muralist who made his politics known through his
frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Women.'' Photographs by Annie Leibovitz, essay by Susan
Sontag (Random House, $75). The women in this stunning book run the
gamut from models to Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``New York: An Illustrated History'' by Ric Burns and James
Sanders (Knopf, $60). In case you missed the PBS series, this
beautifully illustrated book captures the essence of the Big Apple
and many of its characters, from Peter Stuyvesant to F. Scott
Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   AWARD WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Waiting'' by Ha Jin (Pantheon, $24). This National Book
Award winner follows the ordeal of a married Chinese doctor who
falls in love with a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Disgrace'' by J.M. Coetzee (Viking, $23.95). Winner of the
Booker Prize, this novel is the story of a South African professor
whose affair with a student leaves him jobless and friendless
except for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Bone by Bone'' by Peter Matthiessen (Random House, $26.95).
The winner of the Southern Book Critics Award, this final novel in
a trilogy set in turn-of-the-century Florida concludes the story of
Edgar Watson, a pioneer entrepreneur and a murderer.
</P>
<P>
   THE OPRAH CLUB
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Map of the World'' by Jane Hamilton (Anchor, $12.95
paperback). A school nurse attempting to deal with a personal
tragedy is charged with sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Vinegar Hill'' by A. Manette Ansay (Avon, $13 paperback). A
young wife and her jobless husband are forced to move in with his
unpleasant parents in this Midwestern Gothic novel.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Tara Road'' by Maeve Binchy (Delacorte, $24.95). An Irish
wife swaps houses for the summer with a New England woman after her
husband leaves her for his pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHIES
</P>
<P>
   AND NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Walker Evans'' by James R. Mellow (Basic Books, $40). A
gracefully written biography of the famous photographer who
captured the images of the Depression-era South in ``Let Us Now
Praise Famous Men.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mandela: The Authorized Biography'' by Anthony Sampson
(Knopf, $30). A comprehensive study of the political prisoner who
became president of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Hungry Years: A Narrative History of the Great
Depression in America'' by T.H. Watkins (Henry Holt, $32.50). The
acclaimed historian looks at the Depression from the viewpoint of
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Toy Story: The Essential Guide'' (Dorling Kindersley,
$14.95). Illustrated profiles of the major characters in Disney's
new film, including little-known facts about Woody and Buzz
Lightyear.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The World of Ripley's Believe It or Not,'' edited by Julie
Mooney (Black Dog &AMP; Leventhal Publishers, $24.95). And, finally,
for that weird uncle who has a collection of shrunken heads and
