<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0737 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS17-COX     12-16 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Cameraman's memoir: Lens on the best
</P>
<P>
   By the time he died earlier this year at the age of 96, Freddie
Young was universally regarded as the greatest living
cinematographer, if only for his three collaborations with David
Lean (Lawrence of Arabia, Doctor Zhivago and Ryan's Daughter).
</P>
<P>
   Seventy Light Years (Faber and Faber) is a delightful memoir by
Young, whose greatness as a cameraman was equaled by his decency as
a man. Although reputedly difficult with his crews, Young was
renowned for his kindness when dealing with young cinephiles and
writers. I found this out when I contacted Young a few years ago
for a biography. Although in a wheelchair, he was still painting,
enjoying his life, and was immensely helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy Light Years is an urbane Cook's Tour that details
Freddie's beginnings in silent movies (lots of spectacular detail
about the methods of developing and tinting film that made the
silent movie experiencee such a sensual delight) through a long
lifetime of doing what he loved.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon ...
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa is talking his memoirs for Warner Books in a project
that is expected to be on the stands before the 2000 baseball
season.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King and Peter Straub, who last teamed for The Talisman
long ago in 1984, are re-teaming for a sequel that will be
published by Random House in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   And Neil Nyren, who is to Putnam what Michael Korda is to Simon
&AMP; Schuster, has bought a spy thriller he says is the most exciting
he's read since Eye of the Needle, a book he edited.
</P>
<P>
   A Gathering of Spies concerns itself with a female Nazi spy
trying to smuggle the secrets of Los Alamos out to the Germans in
the last days of the war. OK, it may not sound like much, but then
most thrillers don't, when reduced to their bare, usually
implausible bones.
</P>
<P>
   New and worthwhile ...
</P>
<P>
   The Library of America has issued Henry James: Complete Stories
1864-1874, the first 24 published stories.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as turgid is William Faulkner: Novels 1957-1962, the last
group of books that culminates in The Reivers. The volumes are $35
apiece and continue the Library's high standards of presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Pound (that rat) says somewhere that it is incredible to him
that so many 'poets' simply pick up a pen and start writing verse
and call it poetry, while a would-be pianist knows full well how
necessary it is to master scales and thousands of exercises before
making music worthy of the name. Playing scales, for a writer,
means reading. Is there any real writing that has no reading behind
it? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   _ David Remnick
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
