<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-EAST17-COX     12-16 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EAST17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Scott Eyman
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Books Editor
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Eyman
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Books Editor
</P>
<P>
   Tarlton
</P>
<P>
   A WINDOW FACING EAST, by John S. Tarlton. Bridge Works; 176
pages; $22.95
</P>
<P>
   MARGRIM
</P>
<P>
   View of affair from `Window' lacks complications
</P>
<P>
   The dangerous age used to be 30, or, if you were being generous,
40. But we're living longer now, and boredom is rampant, so all
ages are dangerous, especially the late 40s, as Gatlin is finding
out.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin is a financial planner in Baton Rouge, and he is 47 going
on 16. He can't understand why his beautiful wife Sarah is no
longer interested in reenacting the Kama Sutra with him. She wants
to take long trips, he wants to work; she wants to have kids, or
adopt, or something, and he just doesn't see the point. Basically,
all he wants to do is have sex, and all she wants to do is
something other than have sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere along the line, we allowed the incidence of our sex
life to become a strategem in the ongoing repartee. We punish each
other with fussy abstinence.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is bad enough. What makes it well-nigh unbearable is
that Gatlin's best friend is engaged in strenuous extramarital
exercises that can lead to cardiac arrest, divorce court or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we grow older,'' Gatlin tells a friend, ``we learn that sex
is only a minor figment in the grand scheme of things. Like the
notion of a good night's sleep, the idea of ever getting filthy
rich, sex is something we leave behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like you're not getting any,'' says a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's having fun but Gatlin, so he begins thinking about
having an affair of his very own. A client, perhaps. A perfect
stranger, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   A Window Facing East is not a bad novel, but it's not exactly a
good novel, either. The premise has a certain residual interest _
last time I checked, male menopause was still a growth industry _
but John Tarlton's novel lacks narrative energy, as well as
spiraling complications.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain amiable charm on view, and some hard-won
wisdom about divorce. ``Bitter is only a word,'' says Gatlin's
friend Cliff about his ex-wife, who found him entwined with his
secretary and didn't believe his explanation that he was
demonstrating Roman wrestling. ``What Marian really wants is to run
a large vehicle over my dead ass. Then back up and run over my ass
again.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a sense that this novel is an interlocking series of
skits that don't quite coalesce into a compelling narrative whole.
Take, for instance, an unlikely episode where Gatlin and a friend
present a theatrical performance in a prison that nearly provokes a
riot.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that Philip Roth has written this novel
out of rage, John Updike has written this novel out of confusion
and Richard Ford has written this novel out of sorrow. Tarlton's
particular contribution is to combine a good old boy's sexual angst
with some unappetizing whining.
</P>
<P>
   To tread on such familiar territory, more needs to be tucked
into the baggage than Tarlton has provided. This is a twice-told
tale that needs more energy, or surprises, than Tarlton seems
willing to give it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
