<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0739 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-LAWRENCE17-COX     12-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LAWRENCE17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Tom Blackburn
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   LAWRENCE: The Uncrowned King of Arabia, by Michael Asher.
Overlook Press; 418 pages; $35.
</P>
<P>
   Photo by Mariantonietta Peru
</P>
<P>
   Michael Asher (right) admits up front he still finds his subject
elusive after following him all over Arabia, on camelback when
there was a camel to be rented.
</P>
<P>
   T.E. Lawrence cut a dashing figure in 1916-18, but the reasons
have misted over with time.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's biographer delves deep, even reenacting his desert
trek.
</P>
<P>
   Across the sands of time
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Blackburn
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   LAWRENCE: The Uncrowned King of Arabia, by Michael Asher.
Overlook Press; 418 pages; $35.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Asher fits a description of the ideal biographer of
Lawrence of Arabia. A British Arabist who lived with a Bedouin
tribe for three years, he followed T.E. Lawrence's trail with a
dog-eared copy of The Seven Pillars of Wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   The sort of thing that irks him is having to approach one
battlefield anachronistically in a Land Rover because there isn't a
camel for rent in that part of Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Asher sees beauty where others see rocks. But he doesn't share
Lawrence's Victorian romanticism. Lawrence formed a mental image of
the noble Arab _ beautiful, manly, untamed by effete civilization _
long before he met his first Arab. Then he went out and found some
who fit his image.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's current reputation rests on Peter O'Toole's portrayal
in the 1962 David Lean epic Lawrence of Arabia and on Seven
Pillars, which at one time was displayed in literate homes even if
the owner never quite read it all the fustian way to its end.
</P>
<P>
   The film, even at an extreme length, compressed a lot. It began
with Lawrence in British intelligence in Cairo, omitting his time
as an archaeologist in Syria. That's where he employed the Arab boy
who was the love of his life (platonic but highly charged, Asher
believes). And the film left out his odd childhood with a
self-effacing father who was a big landowner before running off
with Lawrence's strong mother, a governess.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Pillars is part fact, part fiction. Lawrence wrote of some
adventures that never happened. His mystique rests partly on the
oddity that the parts that reflect credit on the author generally
are true, and he invented the parts that tend to discredit or
embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence cut a dashing figure in 1916-18, but the reasons have
misted over with time. It was World War I, but he didn't fight
Germans in the trenches of France. Rather, he fought Germany's
allies, the Ottoman Turks, in what is now Syria, Israel, Jordan and
Saudi Arabia, all under Turkish rule at the time. His mission was
to organize the desert tribes against their overlords to aid the
British war effort.
</P>
<P>
   He went beyond his mission by trying to make his mental images
come alive in an Arab nation. The Turks were run out of the area,
but Arab nationhood is still a sometime thing. Lawrence organized
it around the Hashemites, who were protectors of Mecca. The Saudis,
another tribe, protect Mecca now, and the Hashemites rule way up
north in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Lawrence history of the area is at least as amazing as
his three-year run to fame. But it lacks the compelling figure of
Lawrence himself.
</P>
<P>
   Asher excels on this background. He is the rare Lawrence
biographer who gives the Arabs in the Arab Revolt the attention
they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   On Lawrence himself, Asher is of many minds. He admits up front
that he still finds his subject elusive after following him all
over Arabia, on camelback when there was a camel to be rented.
</P>
<P>
   One feat he attempted to copy was crossing the Sinai Desert in
49 hours, as Lawrence had done to report his victory at Aqaba. The
Howyatat, who live there, told Asher it couldn't be done. He gave
them the old ``What? Are you not the men your fathers were?''
argument and got two guides to go with him and his wife (!) on the
trek.
</P>
<P>
   After a day, they were 10 hours behind Lawrence's pace, and one
of the guides was panting and groaning. Asher called it off. Later,
at the British Museum, he discovered the pocket diary Lawrence kept
at the time. Lawrence had given himself a 24-hour head start before
counting the 49 hours.
</P>
<P>
   As George Bernard Shaw said, Lawrence was ``no monster of
veracity.'' Asher also doubts the story about the first man
Lawrence shot, supposedly to avoid a tribal feud. There is diary
evidence that the victim was alive afterward. Even worse for the
myth, Asher raises doubts about whether Lawrence was ever captured
and sodomized by the Turks.
</P>
<P>
   So what's left? A very strange Englishman who, with the
unlikeliest of armies, waged one of the most magnificent campaigns
in military history. The story gets along perfectly well without
the part Lawrence made up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
