<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-MAYAN-RUINS17-COX     12-16 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYAN-RUINS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mayan ruin, Chichen Itza, attracts thousands of tourists each
year
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULUM, Mexico _ A convoy of tour buses lumbers down the dirt
road and sends plumes of dust and diesel swirling in the fresh sea
wind.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting at the curb as the air brakes groan is a battalion of
government guides who promise the new arrivals that soon the
mysteries of the ancient ruins will be theirs for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   Newlyweds on snorkeling honeymoons and vacationers from Iowa
exit the air-conditioned buses, video cams churning. Large patches
of white flesh turned red from the beach and the cruise ship decks
are herded together, assembled into exploratory groups.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient ruins are still a mile away, with dozens of souvenir
stands selling $5 blankets and $20 sculptures lining the route. For
$1, you can ride a well-weathered tram that in another life might
have worked the Disney World parking lot, Goofy maybe. For free you
can walk the rest of the way up the dirt road.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 centuries ago, the great Maya civilization built a
stone fortress on the Yucatan cliffs overlooking what would become
known as Mexico's Caribbean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Mayas envisioned their walled city of Tulum as a spiritual
and commercial center. For their gods, they made temples and altars
of sacrifice. For seafaring merchants, they made pyramid
lighthouses.
</P>
<P>
   Today half the Mayan dream is enduring: Tulum remains a booming
commercial attraction.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely epicenter for an explosive expansion of new tourism,
Tulum has become the day trip of choice for the cruise ships that
anchor daily in Cancun, 80 miles to the north, the gateway to what
is being called the Maya Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   A new four-lane highway completed by the Mexican government
makes the Maya city easily accessible by bus or rental car. On the
information highway, the government uses a glitzy Internet Web site
to tout its Cancun convention center with meeting rooms for 7,500
and a fine Robert Trent Jones golf course. A New York marketing
firm is succeeding in linking two words most American usually
haven't: Mexico and Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   This year, tourism to the Yucatan is up 11 percent over last,
with nearly 2.8 million people visiting the Cancun-Quintana Roo
coast through September. That could reach 4 million by year's end,
double what the area drew six years ago. Most of them (1.3 million)
were Americans. About 35 percent of all Mexico tourists go to the
Cancun coast, according to the National Trust for Tourism
Development.
</P>
<P>
   On a good day, as many as 5,000 tourists will be ushered in and
out of Tulum, filling the 10 acres of stone ruins so completely
that finding a clear sight line for photography is next to
impossible. Environmentalists and preservationists worry that
development has come too far too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ''On one hand, we understand the need for pulling in the tourist
dollars, but on the other is the fear that we may be destroying the
very thing that makes people want to come,'' said Kate Robinhawk of
Centro Ecologico Akumal, a Yucatan environmental group. ''We'd like
the rate of growth to slow down here. But we know that's not going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo has defended the growth of tourism,
saying that environmentalists are overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a good plan in place,'' Zedillo said recently. ''We
believe it is possible to have economic benefits and preserve our
heritage at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultural collisions have always been ruthless, reckless and
given to misunderstanding here on the peninsula. When the Spanish
conquistadors came 500 years ago, they asked the Mayas what their
land was called. The Indian people answered with something that
sounded like ''Yucatan,'' so that's what the Spaniards called it.
Really, what the Mayas were saying was ''I don't know what you
mean'' which was perfectly understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Tulum is the only Maya city known to be circled by a wall and
the most impressive built on a sea coast. The most striking
structure is known as El Castillo , ``the castle,'' a pyramid
topped by a small temple sitting on a 40-foot cliff above the white
beach and cobalt blue water. Rare works of Mayan art were
discovered in what is called the Temple of the Frescoes during
excavations by the Carnegie Institution that began in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous and mysterious of the 60 structures is The
Temple of the Descending God, where over the main entrance a winged
deity, flying head first toward the ocean, is carved. The meaning
of the descending god has been debated for decades. Some
archeologists believe it to be a rain god, others think it depicts
an ocean diver or a baby being born. The most radical
interpretation is that the Mayas were memorializing a visitor from
outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists routinely trample atop the stone platform that once was
used for dances, funerals and, yes, human sacrifices. The Mayas
also would bring their babies here when they were five days old and
bind the sides of the heads with two boards; flat, elongated heads
were considered desirable. Today families of iguanas still scamper
as they have for centuries through the gaps between the stone work.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning around 1520, the Spaniards launched a systematic
campaign to destroy the Mayan culture, burning some 2,000 books
that had been written on bark paper. Three books survived: one
contained the Mayas' calendar and remarkably accurate astronomical
calculations; another held a system of mathematics that introduced
the concept of zero and foreshadowed modern computer language; the
third was about religion.
</P>
<P>
   What revelations were lost in the other 1,997 books will never
be known _ a sad reminder, environmentalists say, of the
irreversible nature of rash action.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing we can do about the tourism and the
development,'' said Robinhawk. ''We can educate people how to deal
with it, though. Future generations probably will look back at this
as a tragic period unless we are successful teaching how to
conserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
