<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-XMASDINNER _ In Latin homes across South Florida, there's
no waiting for the big Christmas dinner _ it's on Christmas Eve, or
Nochebuena. With many variations, Cubans, Spaniards, Puerto Ricans
and Mexicans celebrate the birth of Christ on Dec. 24 with a lavish
feast of symbolic and traditional regional dishes, games and music,
and Midnight Mass _ Misa del Gallo. (Norris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-COED _ LONDON _ Travel brings an uncle and neice into
each other's worlds, in London: We were at Tiger-Tiger, a
ridiculously popular disco just a few steps from Leicester Square,
the most bewildering tourist hole in all of London. My niece Renee,
a freshman from South Georgia College in Douglas, Ga., who spent
the fall semester at the University of London, was yukking it up
with two of her classmates. Imagine three 18-year-old Georgia
peaches done up in their best Felicity Shagwell outfits. Fresh off
the plane, I was jet-lagged, wobbly, just trying to keep a grip.
And I was about to discover that family resemblances are sometimes
more than skin deep. . . (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-48HOURS _ PARIS _ Paris can be explored in less than 48
hours and without spending a lot of money, but you have to have a
sense of adventure. Planning is necessary, of course, but so is
flexibility. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ CHARLESTON, S.C. _ It's not Fifth Avenue, but King
Street is Charleston's great shopping street. And never is it
busier than during the holidays when Christmas in Charleston is
under way. We go for a stroll down the street and offer a list of
holiday happenings throughout Charleston. (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NAPLES _ What I love about Naples is how people there
appreciate a good sunset. A half hour before the sun goes down the
march to the sea commences. (Thurwachter, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   MAYAN-RUINS _ TULUM, Mexico _ The great Mayan ruins, Chichen
Itza and Uxmal, are the reason most visitors travel to Merida,
capital of the State of the Yucatan. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post)
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1214 -- Sophisticated dining and chic hotels are
turning a backwater Bahamas island into a South Beach sibling.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) Art includes2-column art headline
treatment, a 2-column color photo of a vacationing couple sitting
on a couch and a 4-column color photo of a hotel resort's pool
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHOPPING IN FREEPORT -- Check out the shopping deals in
Freeport; it's too bad all of life's duties can't be so easy.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 1-column color photo
Lenox china.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOAT RIDE TO FREEPORT -- JetFoil service to the Bahamas
puts you on a thrilling vessel that literally flies across the
seas. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 2-column color
photo a JetFoil.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Disney is soon to launch a new smoking
policy for its U.S. parks. (N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   MCEVOY-MAKEUP _ Tips from makeup artist extraordinaire Trish
McEvoy. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 20. WITH PHOTOS. COSMETICS _
The wide range of cosmetic brands offers different strokes for
different folks. A makeup artist rates three brands she hasn't used
before. (AHill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and
LAYOUTS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SINGING-MONK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Giorgio Cebrian, the
singing monk, tours the world, impersonating homicidal fathers
(Rigoletto), mad monarchs (Nabucco), crowned assassins (Macbeth)
and, now in West Palm Beach, a slippery, serpentine diplomat in
this weekend's production of Andrea Giordano's Fedora. He worships
Verdi when he is not worshiping God. He carries a photograph of
Giuseppe Verdi with him in his travels, along with his breviary of
prayers. He speaks sincerely of leading ``a consecrated life'' in a
little hermitage in Siena, Italy, where he will return to live in
quiet contemplation after his magnificent baritone voice deserts
him, as it must someday. Ashes to ashes, dust to dust. (Browning,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 1216 _ former bodyguard Michael clarke
Duncan goes the distance for his party in the critically acclaimed
``The Green Mile.'' (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 4-column color photo of Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS --``Drop Dead Gorgeous'' is a cheerfully
mean-spirited spoof of beauty pageants. This movie bombed at the
box office, but it's a guilty-pleasure rental. Also reviews of
``The General's Daughter,'' The Red Violin'' and ``Teaching Ms.
Tingle.''' (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes an 18-pica color
photo from ``Drop Dead Gorgeous''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ The Doobie Brothers' new boxed set from Rhino is
the essence of what rock 'n' roll is (or was) supposed to be _ an
emotional celebration of life from the gut. Also reviews of the
latest from Third Eye Blind and Archer Prewitt. (Staff, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   STAR FILE_ MGM's songbird Jane Powell is ready to take flight
again in a movie and television shows. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post)
Art includes one 6-pica color photo of Jane Powell.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN MUSIC _ Diverse artists reflect popular chulture with
their spiritual message. (Lloyd, Dayton Daily News) Art includes
1-column color photo of gospel singer Kirk Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ In the December cold, midnight Mass was more
than a gathering of the faithful. It was always the quietest
service of the year, despite the hushed excitement that accompanied
congregants into a vestibule fragrant with the smell of
frankincense and candle wax. It was what Roman Catholics call a
High Mass, longer and more formal in its liturgy, but on Christmas
it was without the usual Sunday sermon. The Latin liturgy was
audible, but for the most part it was a ceremony conducted in
silence. You could commune with your maker, uninterrupted by human
voices. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 23.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-STORYVILLE _ Review of Dale Peterson's nonfiction
``Storyville, USA.'' (McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Like other mystery writers, Roswell theater
director Phillip DePoy read Raymond Chandler when he began writing
crime novels. His biggest influence, however, has been Argentine
author Jorge Luis Borges. DePoy will do a theatrical reading of his
newest Atlanta mystery Sunday at the Horizon theater. In other book
news, five Georgians' favorite poems are included in Poet Laureate
Robert Pinksy's new collection of Americans' Favorite Poems. . .
Home Hickham, the Alabama author of ``Rocket Boys,'' has signed a
million-dollar-plus deal with Bantam for two more books based on
his West Virginia childhood. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CHRISTMAS _ If you're still searching for a holiday gift
for your significant other, distant cousin, persnickety
mother-in-law or weird uncle, perhaps you should consider a book.
They're easy to wrap, returnable and, best of all, you don't have
to worry about getting the right size. You do, however, need to
match the recipient with the right book. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ By the time he died this year at the age of 96,
Freddie Young was universally regarded as the greatest living
cinematographer; ``Seventy Light Years'' (Faber and Faber) is
Young's delightful posthumous memoir. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EAST _ Review of the book ``A Window Facing East,'' by
John S. Tarlton. This is a twice-told tale that needs more energy,
or surprises, than Tarlton seems willing to give it. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LAWRENCE _ Review of ``Lawrence: The Uncrowned King of
Arabia,'' by Michael Asher. (Blackburn, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-GIFTS _ Which book is the right book to give to that
special, or not so special, person? No one can make that choice for
you, but the following are a few books discussed here during the
year just past that might give you a little help in making this
important choice. (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
