<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, December
17, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-XMASDINNER _ In Latin homes across South Florida, there's
no waiting for the big Christmas dinner _ it's on Christmas Eve, or
Nochebuena. With many variations, Cubans, Spaniards, Puerto Ricans
and Mexicans celebrate the birth of Christ on Dec. 24 with a lavish
feast of symbolic and traditional regional dishes, games and music,
and Midnight Mass _ Misa del Gallo. (Norris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-COED _ LONDON _ Travel brings an uncle and neice into
each other's worlds, in London: We were at Tiger-Tiger, a
ridiculously popular disco just a few steps from Leicester Square,
the most bewildering tourist hole in all of London. My niece Renee,
a freshman from South Georgia College in Douglas, Ga., who spent
the fall semester at the University of London, was yukking it up
with two of her classmates. Imagine three 18-year-old Georgia
peaches done up in their best Felicity Shagwell outfits. Fresh off
the plane, I was jet-lagged, wobbly, just trying to keep a grip.
And I was about to discover that family resemblances are sometimes
more than skin deep. . . (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-48HOURS _ PARIS _ Paris can be explored in less than 48
hours and without spending a lot of money, but you have to have a
sense of adventure. Planning is necessary, of course, but so is
flexibility. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ CHARLESTON, S.C. _ It's not Fifth Avenue, but King
Street is Charleston's great shopping street. And never is it
busier than during the holidays when Christmas in Charleston is
under way. We go for a stroll down the street and offer a list of
holiday happenings throughout Charleston. (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NAPLES _ What I love about Naples is how people there
appreciate a good sunset. A half hour before the sun goes down the
march to the sea commences. (Thurwachter, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   MAYAN-RUINS _ TULUM, Mexico _ The great Mayan ruins, Chichen
Itza and Uxmal, are the reason most visitors travel to Merida,
capital of the State of the Yucatan. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post)
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
