   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320,
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all keyword lines.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e''category)
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-FAN (Rotterdam, N.Y.) _ In 1994, 3-year-old Louis Lohraseb
and his mother were watching World Cup soccer on television when
the announcer said the next program would be a concert by the Three
Tenors. Kim Lohraseb assumed her son would rather hear from the
Three Stooges than the Three Tenors. She was wrong. Louis gave the
classical music singers a listen and fell under the spell of
Luciano Pavarotti. By CHRIS STURGIS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MEGADETH (Undated) _ Don't look now metal fans, but
Megadeth lead singer Dave Mustaine _ the man who professes to have
at one time ``smoked, snorted or shot just about everything'' _ is
becoming quite the model citizen. ``The most important thing that
happened in 1997 was the
</P>
<P>
   birth of my daughter,'' says Mustaine, 38, during a tour stop.
By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEWS (Undated) _ Reviews of movies ``Dick,'' ``Drop
Dead Gorgeous,'' ``The General's Daughter'' and ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle,'' which
</P>
<P>
   are being released on videotape. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-JEWEL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Yeah, but can she act? As a pop
singer, Jewel is a success. At acting, however, Jewel is a novice.
``Ride With
</P>
<P>
   the Devil,'' opening Friday, is her feature-film debut. Jewel
has the female lead in this Civil War drama directed by Ang Lee
(``Sense and Sensibility,'' ``The Ice Storm''). By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GAME-SHOWS (Undated) _ We're waiting for the return of ``The
Gong Show`` to prime time. That's how dispirited and jaded we are
about stupid game shows sucking up time and space on the schedule.
If everyone is so fired up about game shows, get the damned Game
Show Network and let us have our sitcoms back. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-TAXMAN (Undated) _ The cast of ``The Taxman,'' like
the title character himself, seems out to prove something, and in
this winsome little independent film made by Hollywood insiders,
they do. Co-written and directed by someone who has had success in
Hollywood (Avi Nesher), starring people who have had success in
Hollywood (veteran actor Joe Pantoliano, Elizabeth Berkley and
Robert Townsend), ``The Taxman`` shows how Tinseltown sensibilities
can be well thought out even on a low budget. By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CRUISES (San Antonio) _ The women in the Tunkis family left
husbands, kids, jobs and ringing phones for massages, afternoon
teas, shore excursions and an all-female gabfest aboard the
luxurious Crystal Cruise 's Harmony. ``Sisters of the Sea,`` they
called themselves, as they sailed through the
</P>
<P>
   Panama Canal to ports in Mexico, Central America and the United
States. They're repeat cruise passengers. By KARAN HARAM.
</P>
<P>
   With BC-CRYSTAL-CRUISES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEWS-COLUMN (Washington) _ My dictionary defines a
``Catch-22`` situation as one in which ``the only solution is
denied by a circumstance inherent in the solution.`` Joseph Heller,
who invented the phrase in his 1961 novel of that name, died last
Sunday. But as we saw in the next night's debate from Des Moines,
the spirit of his anti-hero, the World War II bombardier Yossarian,
lives on. By CHRIS MATTHEWS.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-SCAPEGOAT (San Francisco) _ Americans across the country
regard the indictment of Dr. Wen Ho Lee on charges of mishandling
nuclear secrets as a travesty of justice, one which affects the
future of all Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is it that sticks in our craw about this case?
Consider the following. By GEORGE KOO.
</P>
</TEXT>
