<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0772 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CHRISTMAS-EVE-PERSON-     12-16 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-EVE-PERSON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO BE A `CHRISTMAS EVE PERSON' ALL YEAR LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Every year it was the same: the congregation sang ``Silent
Night, Holy Night'' as candlelight filled the darkened sanctuary.
Church bells sounded midnight. It was Christmas.
 &HT;    Even when my parents did not attend services regularly, my
family celebrated Christmas by going to church. On Christmas Eve,
we'd have guests, serve a late supper and attend the midnight
service at the local Methodist church.
 &HT;    Guilt, sentimentality, tradition? I never knew why mother and
dad wanted to go. They just did.
 &HT;    I looked to the family Christmas Eve with great anticipation. I
love Christmas carols and hymns. Singing them in an
evergreen-draped church set the mood for the busy days to follow.
Many of my favorite family memories are of that holiday service.
 &HT;    This year, however, I considerd not attending the midnight
service on Christmas Eve. Despite its nostalgic beauty, Christmas
Eve church troubles me.
 &HT;    Finding a seat at a midnight service is like finding a parking
place at the local mall. The church is full of people you've never
seen. Inevitably, someone is sitting in your favorite pew. Folks
know the traditional carols but the liturgy and regular music
confuses them. They don't know how to take communion.
 &HT;    And the minister preaches some predictable sermon about peace
and goodwill, not wanting to offend the ``Christmas and Easter''
crowd. As a regular churchgoer myself, I find the ``big'' Christian
holidays spiritually tedious.
 &HT;    But it's really not even this Christmas religious rush that
troubles me. Rather, Christmas Eve itself troubles me -- it reminds
me of how hard it is to live as a Christmas person all year.
 &HT;    In a way, I envy my ``Christmas and Easter'' brothers and
sisters. Perhaps they can hear about ``peace and goodwill'' on
December 24 and count it only a charming story, a utopian pipe
dream.
 &HT;    Christmas Eve is not a once-a-year proposition. Like marriage,
like churchgoing, it is a tough-minded commitment to bring forth
God's love in the world.
 &HT;    In the Gospel of Luke, Mary announces the coming of God's
kingdom through her child: ``He has shown strength with his arm; he
has scattered the proud. He has brought down the powerful from
their thrones, and lifted up the lowly; he has filled the hungry
with good things, and sent the rich away empty.''
 &HT;    She's not ``Mother Mary, meek and mild.'' She's a biblical
prophet thundering away at the wealthy and indifferent.
 &HT;    Jesus is not just her sweet baby. For Christians, Jesus is the
embodiment of God's vision for humanity -- perfect justice and joy
forever. The prophet Isaiah describes this vision as a New
Jerusalem in which God's people find dignity, prosperity and peace.
There, ``the wolf and the lamb shall feed together, the lion shall
eat straw like an ox.''
 &HT;    When the angels announced Jesus' birth, they proclaimed that
God's New Jerusalem had come. The long-expected Kingdom could now
be found among humankind. This child was its prophet, priest and
king.
 &HT;    Every Christmas Eve, we sing that proclamation: ``Hark, the
herald angels sing! Glory to the newborn King! Peace on earth and
mercy mild, God and sinners reconciled.'' It is here! It is here!
The Kingdom of God has come!
 &HT;    But where?
 &HT;    As we step over the homeless on the way to the parking lot? As
we lament wars and rumors of wars? As children starve on this
Christmas Eve? As people die? The divorced and widowed cry at home
alone? Just where is the Kingdom of God?
 &HT;    It is, of course, a mystery how that Kingdom could be here and
not be here at the same time. Some people say, rather
disingenuously, that God's' kingdom is in our hearts. But the
Hebrew and Christian prophets proclaim a real kingdom, a physical
place of union and harmony with God, one another, and all creation.
 &HT;    Living into that reality is the stuff of church (and synagogue,
temple and mosque as well). God's reign is being brought forth and
worked out by God's people. It is commitment to make a more just
world in Gods image, to serve others, to love our neighbors as
ourselves.
 &HT;    We cry, yes. But not out of nostalgia. We cry because it is hard
to live as Christmas Eve people -- believing the truth of the
angelic proclamation and acting on it every single day.
 &HT;    And I will be there on Christmas Eve just as I have always been.
Singing my heart out, teary-eyed, and praying for the grace to do
it better this coming year.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
