<HEADLINE>
`RISK' FACTORS GROW FOR MEGADETH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent marks needed over both e's in resume.) 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proud father. Active Christian. College graduate. Political
activist.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like the resume of a presidential candidate? What if I
tell you that this person also can summon the hounds of hell as he
manhandles a guitar?
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now metal fans, but Megadeth lead singer Dave
Mustaine _ the man who professes to have at one time ``smoked,
snorted or shot just about everything'' _ is becoming quite the
model citizen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Megadeth was celebrating a Grammy nomination (the band's
seventh), platinum status for its last album, ``Cryptic Writings,''
and an invitation to play at Howard Stern's birthday party. None of
them rank as the prime event of the year for Mustaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that happened in 1997 was the birth
of my daughter,'' says Mustaine, 38, from a hotel on a tour stop.
``I never thought I'd voluntarily wipe another person's nose or
(bottom), but being a father comes first with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He needs a little spin-doctoring on the heartfelt sentiments,
but get him fitted for a suit-and-tie and out on the campaign
trail, pronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never hold office. I've done everything a man should
and shouldn't do,'' Mustaine says in rehashing his younger days.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the podium, Mustaine and Megadeth, the band he
founded in 1983 after being kicked out of Metallica, have always
provided a forum for politics as much they have for music. The
group's earliest songs were steeped in anger about Cold War
tensions, Reaganomics and economic disparity in America. Sixteen
years later the Cold War has thawed and cutthroat capitalism has
leveled off. But with its ninth album, ``Risk,'' Megadeth is still
lobbying for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not neglect the fact that Boris Yeltsin still has his
fingers on a nuclear warpile,'' Mustaine says. ``The man very
smugly likes to remind the U.S. about that periodically.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dave Mustaine most mosh pit fans know is a heavy-metal elder
and professional hellraiser. He and James Hetfield of Metallica
stylized many of the gnashing chords that filled the gap between
Black Sabbath and Rage Against the Machine. Bands like Limp Bizkit
and Korn are currently tweaking those riffs, adding bass lines and
rhymes and making a mint on the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   The private Mustaine is a much more cerebral beast. Sober for
the last four years _ ``I won't even allow my dentist to use
nitrous oxide in my mouth'' _ Mustaine left Los Angeles not long
after quitting drugs and resettled in Arizona. In down time from
the band he earned two blackbelts in karate and became an advocate
for the motor-voter bill that allows people to register to vote
when they renew a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   When the Megadeth members are in the studio or on the road,
Mustaine still plays with a fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guitarists consider themselves artists stroking the
guitar with a gentle paintbrush,'' Mustaine laughs. ``I consider it
a chainsaw that I whip out to carve a tree stump into a bear. It's
a weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   The anger of a young punk looking for an outlet that propelled
his early days has now evolved into the frustration of a pro-active
adult who still gets pigeonholed as a punk.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at me and say, `Hey, he has long hair so he must
be stupid,''' Mustaine says. ``They would never suspect that I was
a spokesman for the Youth of America for the National Democratic
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Mustaine will have the last laugh. Besides almost guaranteed
platinum sales (1 million albums sold) from a die-hard
international cult of fans, he holds a business degree from the
University of Phoenix. Apparently, biz classes inspired him to
expand his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years he has collaborated with Chaos Comics! to
produce a comic book series, The Cryptic Writings of Megadeth,
which adapts lyrics from the band's songs into the animation. It is
now a coveted collectors' item. ``Crush 'Em,'' the first single
from ``Risk,'' was featured in the movie ``Universal Soldier: The
Return.'' The movie's stars, WCW wrestling star Goldberg and
Jean-Claude Van Damme, even joined Mustaine to film a video for the
song.
</P>
<P>
   As professional wrestling rules prime time and its muscle-bound
heavies are America's favorite soap stars, hitching Megadeth's
wagon to Goldberg might prove to be the equivalent of a can't-miss
stock tip. The band appeared on ``WCW's Monday Nitro'' to play
``Crush 'Em'' as Goldberg stalked the ring. Usually, only Shania
Twain and Ricky Martin can get that kind of prime-time network
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Some die-hard fans might grumble about the group selling out
with such a commercial move. Mustaine has no apologies to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, professional wrestling is more rock 'n' roll than
rock 'n' roll is,'' Mustaine says. ``If someone doesn't want to buy
our albums because of it, that's fine. There are plenty of others
that will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Risk'' as a whole album is also a little bit of a departure.
After ``Cryptic Writings'' was released, Metallica drummer Lars
Ulrich said in an interview that Mustaine needed to mix things up a
bit. Mustaine took him at his word. Instead of a constant guitar
assault, songs like ``Insomnia'' open with docile violins attaching
Zeppelin-inspired Middle Eastern chords and techno-beats to the
chord layers.
</P>
<P>
   And if you missed ``Crush 'Em'' on ``WCW Monday Nitro,'' it
shouldn't be long before you hear it at pro hockey and football
games. Licensed to both the NFL and NHL, the song is giving Gary
Glitter's ``Rock 'n' Roll Part Two'' a run for crowd anthem of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Glitter?'' Mustaine says of the comparison. ``Now that
wasn't very nice to say.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
