<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEEP THROAT' GOES SOPRANO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `DICK'
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``Dick'' is a ``what if'' film.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Watergate scandal bean-spiller known as ``Deep
Throat'' had been two silly teen girls in the wrong place at the
right time?
</P>
<P>
   That frothy premise propels a delightful comedy in which Kirsten
Dunst and Michelle Williams play 1972 gal pals with little on their
minds beyond boys, fashion and innocent idealism.
</P>
<P>
   They live in the Watergate complex, and they take a White House
tour. You take it from there.
</P>
<P>
   The girls not only stumble onto the breakin of Democratic Party
offices, but they also bump into cover-up higher-ups during their
tour _ even the president.
</P>
<P>
   Oblivious to politics, they happily accept the offer of
President Nixon (Dan Hedaya) to be ``official White House dog
walkers'' (so he can keep an eye on them).
</P>
<P>
   Dunst and Williams are lovable, clueless and a hoot, piercing a
monstrous scandal with adorable naivete while chastising the
president for his ``potty mouth.'' Hedaya nails Nixon's shifty,
twitchy deceptiveness and paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   But his enemies don't fare much better. Washington Post
reporters Bob Woodward (Will Ferrell) and Carl Bernstein (Bruce
McCulloch) are shown as petty, vain, lucky opportunists.
</P>
<P>
   They might even have stayed unknowns if two teens hadn't
accidentally learned the truth. To think _ what if?
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Columbia TriStar, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD
$24.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `DROP DEAD GORGEOUS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least Kirsten Dunst has one good new flick on video. ``Drop
Dead'' should be buried in the back of the bins.
</P>
<P>
   It's fertile ground for satire: the studied wholesomeness and
cloaked ambition of beauty-pageant contestants. But the writing and
performances aren't just bad _ they're grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   At least this is a suitable vehicle for Denise Richards, unlike
her scientist role in ``The World Is Not Enough.'' Here she plays
the heinous heir apparent to a small town's beauty throne, with
Dunst as her nice-girl rival from across the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Presented as a documentary (which worked far better in the
comparable ``Waiting for Guffman''), the film heaps big, sloppy
helpings of eccentricity and nutty spitefulness on its plate.
</P>
<P>
   The cast's worst offenders are Kirstie Alley and Ellen Barkin as
the maniacal moms behind the prima donnas. To call them cartoonish
is to insult cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Such sledgehammer subtlety isn't needed to debunk low-rent
beauty pageants. A real documentary would have worked well enough.`
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 star.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, New Line, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98 &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This glossy Hollywood product poses as a sobering look at
violent sexism in the military (a female officer is savagely raped
and later murdered) and its tendency to close ranks in the name of
solidarity but at the expense of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the film's dominant mission is to provide a star vehicle for
John Travolta, who plays a tough military investigator on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta is good, and he has some terrific scenes opposite James
Woods as an Army psychologist. Madeleine Stowe as his partner and
James Cromwell as the title's general also lend strong support.
</P>
<P>
   But rules of billing make the murderer's identity too easy to
guess, and flashbacks of the rape are hideous and overstated for a
film professing sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Paramount, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TEACHING MRS. TINGLE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're only as good as your last film, Kevin Williamson _ the
It screenwriter after ``Scream'' _ is very bad indeed.
</P>
<P>
   This, his directorial debut, which he also wrote, is amoral and
witless, lacking a single character we can sympathize with or at
least understand.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Holmes is an honors student who needs an ``A'' to win a
scholarship. Unfairly thwarting her is Helen Mirren's Mrs. Tingle,
a baldly antagonistic teacher who, for reasons never fully
explained, wants her students to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes and vapid classmates Barry Watson and Marissa Coughlan
invade Tingle's home to press their case and wind up as her
captors.
</P>
<P>
   Things get mindlessly messy, yet Holmes flits back to school to
accompaniment of soulful music that's supposed to make her somewhat
endearing.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   These teens are deluded idiots, and their crime plays like a
high school spin on ``A Simple Plan'' _ you know, ``Dumb and
Dumber'' without the laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Mirren, at least, has moments. She's superbly haughty and
hateful as the teacher. But she belongs in a better movie _ with a
script that provides some motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Williamson shows hints of his previous sharp dialogue,
his teen characters are still stupid, even if they do use terms
such as ``passive-aggressive'' in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can't be the only way to get into college,'' Holmes
laments. Duh.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 star.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Miramax, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD _ due
Tuesday _ $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COLLECTOR'S EDITION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' gains a collector's edition on DVD this
week, which means you can pay $10 more to see a few trailers and
unused footage and hear its creators gush in self-praise.
</P>
<P>
   Adding ``documentaries'' to DVDs sounds good, but too often they
heap on the hype while ploddingly recounting a plot we know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare's'' disc is guilty of both. Its filmmakers extol
each other's ``brilliance.'' Didn't they get enough Oscars and
raves without wallowing in back-slapping?
</P>
<P>
   But the deleted scenes are intriguing, including an expanded
ending.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Gwyneth Paltrow and Joseph Fiennes have their tearful
parting in a different part of the theater, and her imagined
shipwreck scene is expanded.
</P>
<P>
   But best of all is a deliberate blooper from Geoffrey Rush, as a
drunken producer, exhorting his playwright in a tavern scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us have pirates, clowns and a happy ending,'' he insists,
``and you will make Harvey Weinstein a happy man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut!'' shouts director John Madden, hurriedly entering the
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein, of course, is co-founder of Miramax and this film's
executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
