<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JEWEL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE `DEVIL' IS JEWEL UP TO? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yeah, but can she act?
</P>
<P>
   As a pop singer, Jewel is a success. Her combination of vocal
and writing talent, healthy good looks and sexy, independent
attitude have sold more than 15 million copies total of her two
albums, ``Pieces of You and Spirit.'' (She also has a new album of
Christmas standards, ``Joy: A Holiday Celebration'').
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Alaskan has been performing all her life, with
years of experience to hone her stage and vocal skills before
anyone really knew who she was, or cared.
</P>
<P>
   At acting, however, Jewel is a novice. ``Ride With the Devil,''
opening Friday nationwide, is her feature-film debut. Jewel has the
female lead in this Civil War drama directed by Ang Lee (``Sense
and Sensibility,'' ``The Ice Storm'').
</P>
<P>
   This time, everyone knows who Jewel is and will be analyzing
just how well she does at her new job.
</P>
<P>
   Her co-star, Tobey Maguire, had only praise for her performance
and for her courage in tackling a new field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough situation,'' Maguire said. ``She was the only
girl (among the main characters), the only one who hadn't done
anything _ and the big celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really eager. I thought it was courageous that she
chose the thing in the first place, especially with her high
profile. People would be watching her and having expectations of
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make it easy on her. She was there to work, and she
was serious, so she earned her stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting, which Jewel says she was always planning to pursue as
soon as she established her singing career, is not her first
attempt to expand her creative horizons. In 1998 she published a
book of poetry, ``A Night Without Armor,'' which took a critical
beating but made the best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   The young woman sitting scrunched down in her chair with a worn
jean jacket over her lap has a strong presence and a healthy,
outdoorish aura. Her nails are plain, her long tresses uncombed,
and she wears a T-shirt. Her only jewelry is a ring with small
diamonds and rubies.
</P>
<P>
   Jewel Kilcher has a reputation for being difficult in
interviews. That is not the case on this fall day in a Toronto
hotel. She's reserved but polite and pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is mostly serious during the conversation, when she
laughs, her chuckles are hearty, not dainty. She peppers her
conversation with occasional profanity that's used unconsciously
and without emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   Jewel appears at ease, confident. But she admits some of that
confidence deserted her when it came to acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' she says, her voice suddenly soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only because I was famous. Fame, you know, is an odd creature.
It's like its own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own person has always been most concerned with growing.
Above anything else. With no fear of failure. You're gonna fail,
you're gonna look bad sometimes if you're pushing beyond what
you're comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have that kind of courage pre-fame is real easy, because if
you fall, who cares? When you're famous, it's in front of the whole
world, and the world does not value growth over perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   When a singer, athlete or model takes a shot at acting, many
people delight in shredding the performance. More often than not,
the criticism is justified. But there also seems to be a prejudice
against famous people trying to move into new fields.
</P>
<P>
   Already an old pro at how the fame game is played, Jewel is
ready for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be just and unjust,'' she says. ``To say I am
good at music _ much less acting at age 25 _ would be absurd. I
don't think you're really great at a craft until you're probably
50, and I plan to take a lot of hits in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ride With the Devil,'' Jewel plays Sue Lee Shelley, a young
Southerner already widowed by the war when she meets and helps hide
three guerrilla fighters played by Maguire, Skeet Ulrich and
Jeffrey Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Caught up in the urgency of the war, Sue Lee puts aside
convention and falls quickly into a passionate romance with one of
the soldiers. Pregnancy and the fortunes of war tie her first to
one man, then another.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenging and fairly large role, not the ideal first
job for an untrained actor. Jewel's performance is less than
powerful, but under the guidance of Lee, who is considered an
actor's director, she holds her own.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell is the first to admit she is not going to blow anyone off
the screen. She expects a long process of learning her new craft.
</P>
<P>
   She says she was nervous when she saw her ``Ride With the
Devil'' performance for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make myself throw up,'' she says. ``I mean, that's
good, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were a lot of places where I looked at the movie and
thought, `I wish I'd done more there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If I heard tapes of some of the gigs I did when I was a kid, I
would want to kill whoever owns them,'' she says, laughing loudly.
``But luckily I got to be pretty good by the time I recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this (movie) will follow me for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As a singer, Jewel is a public performer. No hiding in a
recording studio for her. She likes to get onstage, where she feels
totally in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my humor and spontaneity really come from a live
interaction, from having a new audience to impress every night and
having to be fresh every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pure energy thing _ a reciprocity. If people are tired,
they just got off work, they don't want to hear all your
intellectual, wordy music; they just want to have fun. They want to
hear a love song; they want to have comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not paying attention to their mood, (if) you go
right into heady stuff, you lose a whole crowd. That's a terrible
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who likes television because I know I'm going out
(on the air) live, and millions are seeing me. It raises the
stakes, and I turn on.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a film, with no audience _ except actors and
technicians who all knew a lot more about it than she did _ was
intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real hard psychological thing for me. I had to
psych myself out for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Lee is a director who inspires confidence in
actors. He worked with Jewel for months, she says, before giving
her the part. Then he continued to give her special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ang helped me in so many areas _ like you can't move your
hands a lot on screen. I had to learn to be still, not to move my
eyes a lot, keep my chin down ... things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee taught her tai chi to ``get me grounded.'' He taught her to
pace herself so she wouldn't tire out before noon. He made her take
her lunch away from the other actors so she could focus, since it
took her longer to get back into character than the trained actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could talk to somebody right up to going onstage (to sing)
and be perfect onstage,'' she says. ``I couldn't do it with this.
It took all of my focus, all of my time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lee didn't teach her everything. Jewel came up with one
acting technique herself _ singing her lines while she learned
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a trained actress, I didn't have any skills at
getting into character, so I had to work with what I have,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to get to an emotional place in yourself, and
you want the quickest road to it. My most established path is
music. When I sing, I immediately feel the emotion I'm singing
about. It immediately overwhelms me.''
</P>
<P>
   She even wrote a couple of songs _ for herself, not for the film
_ from Sue Lee's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just put me in that mood immediately,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever critics and the public think of Jewel's work in the
film, they can expect her to do more acting. And more writing. And
anything else she finds to expand her creative side. And if she
fails, she plans to keep doing it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to (fail) at some point. I'm not kidding myself
about that. If you go beyond what you're comfortable with, you're
going to fall on your face at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather take the risk than not take the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
