<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     12-16 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR BOOKS SHOW THE READER AROUND THE 21ST CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adding to the Best of '99 theme from last week, here are some
more recommendations for holiday shoppers staring blindly at the
shelves of their local bookstores. These books would also make
great New Year gifts since they give fascinating accounts of where
we're heading in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Times foreign affairs columnist Thomas L. Friedman
artfully writes his observations on everything from Japanese
factories to the Wailing Wall in Jerusalem in ``The Lexus and the
Olive Tree'' (Farrar, Straus, Giroux, 394 pages, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   ``The slow, stable, chopped-up Cold War system that had
dominated international affairs since 1945 has been firmly replaced
by a new, very greased, interconnected system called
globalization,'' Friedman observes. ``We are all one river.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects of that global river are felt in every corner of the
world, as technology enhances or clashes with nations, religions,
communities and families.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman says that in the Cold War, the question most asked was
``How big is your missile?'' In today's global world, the question
is ``How fast if your modem?''
</P>
<P>
   The book was on the bestseller list for weeks, and rightly so.
It presents a fascinating picture of how once far-reaching parts of
the world are being woven together, as well as insightful
commentary on what it all means.
</P>
<P>
   _ No one is making the transition into the third industrial
revolution _ the knowledge-based economy _ better than the United
States, argues esteemed MIT economist Lester Thurow in his latest
book, ``Building Wealth: The New Rules for Individuals, Companies
and Nations in a Knowledge-Based Economy'' (HarperCollins, 301
pages, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 10 largest companies in the world are American,
compared with just two in 1990. Nine of the top 15 banks are also
based in the United States. In 1990, none of them were American.
</P>
<P>
   But now the big shift is from national to global for business _
and no world government organization with any real power exists,
Thurow warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a global economy with no enforceable, agreed-upon
set of rules and regulations, no sheriff to enforce codes of
acceptable behavior, and no judges and juries to appeal to if one
feels that justice is not being done,'' Thurow writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continental Europeans often refer to what is now happening as
`cowboy capitalism.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thurow also suggests that one of the biggest changes in the
economy in the next century will be in retailing.
</P>
<P>
   _ How Alan Greenspan made the Fed chairmanship such a pinnacle
of power and how he influences the world markets is explored in
``The Greenspan Effect: Words That Move the World's Markets''
(McGraw Hill, 273 pages, $18.95).
</P>
<P>
   The book is written by best-selling business authors and
consultants David B. Sicilia and Jeffrey L. Cruikshank, who have
done their homework. Sicilia and Cruikshank take a different
approach by staying away from technical jargon and charts and
discuss the issues often in Greenspan's own words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our subject has become a megacelebrity _ known, respected,
feared, scrutinized, consulted, and quoted throughout the world,''
they write. ``Alan Greenspan has emerged as one of the most
influential actors on the world economic stage.''
</P>
<P>
   How has he done this and helped the U.S. economy enjoy its
longest period of uninterrupted growth in history? Sicilia and
Cruikshank explain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Global aging is going to be a serious issue in the next
century, and economist and author Peter G. Peterson explores its
monumental impact in ``Gray Dawn: How the Coming Age Wave Will
Transform America _ and the World'' (Times Books, 280 pages, $23).
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that global aging will become the transcendent
political and economic issue of the twenty-first century,''
Peterson writes.
</P>
<P>
   Among his observations: By 2030, 25 percent of the total world
population will be seniors. By 2030, the benefits of Social
Security, Medicare, Medicaid and federal and military pensions will
exceed total revenues in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson offers a number of ideas to address these problems,
including raising the retirement age, encouraging larger families
with government benefits tied to the number of children and
applying benefits only to seniors who need financial help, not to
those with other incomes and savings.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Cover blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding and Changing Your Management Style''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert C. Benfari
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $25
</P>
<P>
   This book was developed from the curriculum that Robert Benfari
assembled for his course at Harvard University School of Public
Health called ``Understanding Your Management Style.'' While
teaching this course and hundreds of workshops and seminars
throughout the country, Benfari developed what he calls an
Integrated Management Style Model, which is designed to help
managers analyze how they react to many aspects of management.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Defying the Market: Profiting in the Turbulent Post-Technology
Market Boom''
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen and Donna Leeb
</P>
<P>
   McGraw Hill, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Has the technological world slowed down? That is one of the
burning issues in market analysts Stephen and Donna Leeb's latest
book. They say that technological advances are slowing and that,
combined with a mandate for economic growth, will lead to that
awful ``I'' word _ inflation. The Leebs, who write one of the
largest investment newsletters in the country, Personal Finance,
provide a strategy on dealing with this major influence over the
markets.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``In The Worlds of Great Business Leaders''
</P>
<P>
   By Julie M. Fenster
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $18.95
</P>
<P>
   The 19 business people chosen for this book have spent most of
their lives in the trenches. From Sam Walton and Henry Ford ll to
Herb Kelleher and David Packard, these business icons have done
more than pontificate on how business should be run; they've run
it. Each is featured in anecdotes and with quotes and interesting
stories of who they are and how they got where they did. Julie
Fenster is a business historian who writes for The New York Times
and other publications.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
