born into the world.
 &HT;    When the baby grew to a man, he said yes, too. Saying yes to
God, Jesus submitted to humiliation, pain and death _ all for the
love of his brothers and sisters.
 &HT;    If not for Mary's yes, God's yes would have been silenced. No
wonder generations have blessed her.
 &HT;    This holiday season, I suggest we change ``just say no'' to
``just say yes.'' When we say yes to God, yes to love, and yes to
each other, healing and reconciliation come.
 &HT;    The Christmas story proclaims God's yes: Love and peace are born
into the world. Truly, good news of great joy for all people!
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
