<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-BICENTENNIAL-REV     12-16 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BICENTENNIAL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVER `BICENTENNIAL MAN' MISSES THE BIG PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine Sam Neill as a rather open-minded 19th-century
Southerner, one who treats a slave as nicely as anyone who ever
kept another human being as property.
</P>
<P>
   Picture Robin Williams as his butler, a subservient,
gentle-natured fellow who, as he often says, ``is glad tobe of
service.'' Inside, he never stops yearning to be free, if only in
the legal sense, while keeping his post with ``Sir'' and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward that scenario 150 years and then some, and you have
``Bicentennial Man,'' director Chris Columbus' adaptation of a
short story by sci-fi author Isaac Asimov. It is a story worth
telling, especially to young audiences who seek out Williams'
movies, if only it didn't feel as though it took 200 years to tell
it.
</P>
<P>
   Williams plays a robot dubbed Andrew by the San Francisco family
who acquires him fresh from the factory sometime ``in the near
future.'' It is apparent early on that Andrew is no ordinary
NorthAm Robotics model NDR-114. He seems to feel some emotions, at
least on a primitive level.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to suppress Andrew's ambitions to understand
the human condition, Sir decides his family will treat Andrew as a
person _ albeit one who probably has been purchased on a payment
plan _ and he encourages the machine's curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Andrew evolves in both emotional and
intellectual development, and undergoes physical advancements that
enable him to smile, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no denying he's still a robot, an ageless piece of
machinery that outlives Sir, Ma'am and their daughter, Little Miss,
and still doesn't know how to mourn their loss.
</P>
<P>
   While wealthy Americans spend time and money trying to postpone
the inevitable, Andrew never ceases his quest to be mortal, to feel
the extreme highs and lows and aches and pains humans go through on
their way to death. It takes him 200 years to realize that goal.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Williams lets his personality shine through the
most inhuman of his costumes; somehow he transcends the glassy
eyes, the hinged mouth and the stiff joints to give Andrew the
unique quality apparent to his master. But often there is too much
of Williams in the role _ either the actor himself or one of his
past characters. It's almost as if Andrew were channeling Mrs.
Doubtfire and Mork at a seance.
</P>
<P>
   Embeth Davidtz holds her own in a dual role as the adult Little
Miss and, later, her granddaughter Portia. She has risen to the
challenge of aging as two different women, both of them dear to
Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Williams' role turns serious, Oliver Platt and
Kiersten Warren lighten up the movie as a late 21st century
inventor and his overly perky robot assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Johnson's robotic effects (and yes, Andrew is most often
Williams in a suit) are quite good. Norman Reynolds' fanciful
impressions of futuristic San Francisco are appealing in a
``Tomorrowland'' sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   It's not often that Columbus (``Home Alone'' and ``Jingle All
the Way'') is associated with food-for-thought movies.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bicentennial Man'' he has an important fable about the
values of freedom and human life. Unfortunately, with the pace set
by Columbus and screenwriter Nicholas Kazan, their most important
audience may lose interest before they get the message. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Bicentennial Man'' (PG; some profanity and adult
themes). &QL; 
The stars: Robin Williams, Sam Neill, Hallie Kate Eisenberg, Embeth
Davidtz, Oliver Platt. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Chris Columbus. Written by Nicholas
Kazan. Released by Touchstone Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 12 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
