<SLUG> BC-TV-GAME-SHOWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GAME SHOW MANIA TURNS VIEWERS INTO LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Television Notes  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are waiting for the return of ``The Gong Show'' to prime
time. That is how dispirited and jaded we are about stupid game
shows sucking up time and space on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   If everyone is so fired up about game shows, start the Game Show
Network and let us have our sitcoms back. And as much as we have
mocked Regis, we would take it all back if only someone would say
that the hiring of Maury Povich to host ``Twenty One'' were a cruel
joke.
</P>
<P>
   What next _ Jenny Jones doing ``Card Sharks'' or Ricki Lake
hosting ``The Joker's Wild''?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &LR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Let's face the hard truth, those Gap Christmas ads are great.
Very catchy, visually stimulating, addictive.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, after countless great campaigns, ESPN is
mired in two lousy ones. The dogs-playing-poker idea was never ever
funny and just continues to get old. And its latest, the ``Hoops
Malone'' sitcom concept with Dick Vitale, is just lame and
embarrassing for all involved. Get back to basics, the kind of
subtle humor that drove the promos for ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &LR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's always an eye-opener to find out what USA Network is
planning. No other channel loves the patently cheap and sexy like
USA. It has Sam Raimi lined up for a ``psychological thriller in
the tradition of `Rosemary's Baby,''' a drama about the United
States entering the fray of a Mexican civil war; and ``Desert
High,'' described as a drama of ``two rival groups of teen-agers
ensconced in an epic turf war, where the weapons of choice are
fuel-injected muscle cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, those are the dramas.
</P>
<P>
   And where does USA get off using the word ``ensconced''? That
has to stop.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &LR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The White House is expected to step up efforts to better educate
the country about the V-chip, which is installed in every new
television. This ought to make it easy _ just press the ``let the
government raise your kid'' button on the new remote. Pretty
simple.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
