<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-TAXMAN-HN     12-16 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TAXMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THOUGH FRESH AND FUN, `TAXMAN' CAN BE TAXING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cast of ``The Taxman,'' like the title character himself,
seems out to prove something, and in this winsome little
independent film made by Hollywood insiders, they do.
</P>
<P>
   Co-written and directed by someone who has had success in
Hollywood (Avi Nesher), starring people who have had success in
Hollywood (veteran actor Joe Pantoliano, Elizabeth Berkley and
Robert Townsend), ``The Taxman'' shows how Tinseltown sensibilities
can be well thought out even on a low budget.
</P>
<P>
   Pantoliano, last seen in ``The Matrix,'' recaptures the feel of
perhaps his best role, as the bail bondsman in ``Midnight Run''
(1988). This time he's high-strung, overzealous tax investigator Al
Benjamin, who makes it his mission to bring down a complicated
scheme by the Russian mob in New York to siphon off the federal
excise tax imposed on gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Teaming with an earnest young cop, Romero (Wade Dominguez), Al
goes after a Russian gas station owner (Michael Chiklis), whose
engaged daughter Nadia (Elizabeth Berkley _ that's right, the star
of the much-maligned ``Saved by the Bell'' television series and
the motion picture disaster known as ``Showgirls'') catches his
eye.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who are trying to drag themselves into a higher
standing by cracking their first Big Case, get a federal prosecutor
(Robert Townsend) to sign off on the investigation, and go right
after the top man. That takes them into the Russian immigrant
community centered in the Brighton Beach section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Nesher, who has directed several forgettable action movies
(Remember Drew Barrymore in ``Doppelganger'' or Michael Biehn in
``Timebomb''?), reportedly saw the original script by former tax
investigator Roger Berger, which was full of mindless action, and
worked with Berger to craft a more realistic story.
</P>
<P>
   While fresh and fun _ it appears to have been a real treat for
the actors to work on _ ``The Taxman'' isn't the character-driven
indie they would like us to believe it is.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's plot-driven to the point of distraction. Al
constantly complains about the pressures of supporting a wife and
child, but we never meet them. Instead, he seems fixated on a
woman, Nadia, whom he cannot have and with whom there is not even
the pretense of a romantic relationship, or any kind of
relationship, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Berkley, who is called on to deliver lines in Russian, seems
only to be out to prove that she really can act (she can).
Townsend, with ``Hollywood Shuffle'' a dozen years behind him now,
is convincingly low key as the idealistic prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Pantoliano's movie. Al is a man who has to learn that
the relentless pursuit of truth has rules, too. He's an Everyman
hero, who can't dance and is proud of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
