<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW LIGHTS VISIONS OF GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What felt like a full gale on our salty coast turned into the
white gold upcountry, and the cold weather that followed made for a
real ski weekend. This weekend should repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The report from Bretton Woods was that the skiing was pretty
darn good on half a dozen trails, especially considering winter's
slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday, we had the place to ourselves,'' said Kenny, who
skied with his family for a few days there over the weekend and
into this week. ``The snow was decent, and when my son took a group
boarding lesson he was the only one in the class. A private
lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Bretton Woods was always one of the best snowmakers/groomers in
the business, and a really nice place to begin the season, since
the cruising is on the low-stress side.
</P>
<P>
   My own favorite run at Bretton Woods when I find it relatively
uncrowded and no one is over on the right-side trails is to take
the Granny's Grit top to bottom without a turn. I imagine I am
Peter Mueller gliding down the upper flats of the Aspen downhill
run, then plunging down the face of Aztec.
</P>
<P>
   And now I am flying at heroic speeds, blasting through tight,
tough turns, probably hitting record speeds as I whiz past the TV
towers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the rolls I go, prejumping the lips and keeping my hands
low and well out in front until I come through the finish to the
delight of thousands of ski fans, many of them my teenage
satellites who traveled here from Zurmat to see Pirmin and me strut
our stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the crowd steps the beautiful and talented Edie Thys of
Ski magazine (best writer at any of the major ski magazines) who
sticks her microcassette recorder in my face and asks the
inevitable:
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, Peter. Tell me about your run today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vell, eet vas lack thees,'' I say between deep gulping breaths
after my two-mile flight. But then there is another voice cutting
through this haze of fantastic self-absorbtion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You idiot! You're going to kill yourself one of these days!
What do you think, you're still a college kid?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, my wife is right. A high-speed fall at this age is an
event the body is likely to remember. The bones are more brittle,
less cartilage to elasticize those moving parts.
</P>
<P>
   So why doesn't Nature, with her many designs to protect her
living creatures, curtail the hunger for speed in the soul of every
skier and boarder I know? After all, the beauty and grace in the
sport is at its peak when a body is moving fast enough to feel
almost airborne.
</P>
<P>
   Racers descending those steep icy tracks at 80 miles an hour,
flowing so smoothly with the undulations of mountain terrain,
leaping through the air in hundred-foot bites, create the most
beautiful dance on earth. And great racers like Mueller always
brought to mind the W.B. Yeats line, written about a ballet he
watched: ``I couldn't tell the dancers from the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, when I once did find myself on the Aspen downhill
course, I did not ski it exactly as I did on Granny's Grit or Coos
Caper at Bretton Woods. Former US Ski Team racer Andy Mill led a
``press inspection'' of the run the morning before a World Cup
downhill race. All was fine out of the starting shack and down the
flats until Mill stopped us on the lip of Aztec, the steep face
that starts the real acceleration into the turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side slip this part,'' Mill said.
</P>
<P>
   Gleep! See Andy, it's like this, I think looking down this
elevator shaft of a drop: This is pure ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out, it's icy,'' says Mill, adding with a chuckle,
``just the way the racers like it.''
</P>
<P>
   No description needed here, but suffice it to say the only
reason anyone would have interviewed me after that run was to get
the perspective of the Aspen Winternational snow clown.
</P>
<P>
   But speed is addictive, and the addiction doesn't diminish with
age. Long after we lose our taste for driving fast in cars,
motorboats, motorcycles, snowmobiles and the like, that speed
monster stays alive, well, and ageless in the skier's soul.
Hopefully, at least we learn when and where to indulge it.
</P>
<P>
   Once and only once, in my early twenties, I got my lift ticket
pulled by the ski patrol. It was at Saddleback Mountain in
Rangeley, Maine. I had been racing with fellow University of Maine
student Scott Kauffman, and we had taken White Stallion (then Gray
Ghost) top to bottom. As we braked to a stop at the bottom, some
really mad guy (it could have been Jon Christi himself) gave us a
dressing down and demanded our tickets on grounds of reckless and
dangerous skiing.
</P>
<P>
   He was right, of course. Anyone on the trail in front of us that
day could have . . . well you know. Losing the $3 ticket didn't
hurt. It was near the end of the day anyway. But the guy really
knew how to cut down a couple of young bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you try that again,'' he said, ``at least learn how to
ski.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed. You never get over it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
