<HEADER>
A0841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-ART-B     12-16 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASONED VET MALONE HASN'T MISSED HIS SHOT AT CHAMPIONSHIP YET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Here's an easy one. Which member of the Utah Jazz do
you suppose was lying on his back an hour before the game, tossing
a medicine ball _ some kind of round, oversized object, anyway _
higher and higher as he watched a videotape of the Celtics playing
the Miami Heat?
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the man who was suiting up for the 1,127th time in
1,132 regular-season opportunities over a NBA career that is now in
its 15th season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I have to do to get ready for a game,'' said Karl
Malone, who would go on to score 27 points as the Utah Jazz beat
the Celtics by a 96-86 score Wednesday night at the Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for the off-days, when he might be in the weight room,
or stretching, or meditating, or whatever it is that he does
longer, harder, and with more zeal than just about anyone who has
ever played this game. In case you're wondering, that body was
made, not bequeathed.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has been coming to Boston a long time, and not always in
the same circumstance. In his early days, trips to Boston were
ritualistic embarrassments. The Jazz just didn't win in Boston.
They got one in Hartford when Pete Maravich hit them with a
triple-double before we even knew what a triple-double was, but
Boston? Uh-uh. The years rolled on, and the Jazz would get their
annual spanking in the Boston Garden. After one such trashing,
coach Frank Layden responded to the first postgame inquiry by
saying, ``What? Were we supposed to win?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. It didn't matter who joined the team. Adrian
Dantley joined the team in 1979 and they lost. John Stockton joined
the team in 1984 and they lost. Malone joined the team in 1985 and
they lost. And lost. And lost. And lost. And lost. And lost. And,
yes, lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you came in here (i.e. the Garden),'' Malone reminisced,
``you couldn't afford to have any off quarters. We'd have to
execute our plays perfectly every time downcourt in order to have
any chance at all of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Garden losing streak stretched to 20. Finally, on
Nov. 18, 1992, Malone, Stockton, Jeff Malone, and the rest of the
Jazz did what their hoop-loving ancestors had never been able to
do. It was Utah 92, Boston 91, and the team loved the taste of it
so much they have not lost another game in any building to the
Celtics. That's right. The winning streak is now 14.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Karl Malone has cemented his place on the
all-time roster. He is now a two-time MVP. He has been a first-team
All-NBA member a record 11 times. He's got two gold medals. And
with a 19-foot first-quarter jumper against Golden State Nov. 29 he
moved into third place on the all-time scoring list, trailing only
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Wilt Chamberlain. The only meaningful thing
he doesn't have is a championship ring, and he hasn't given up on
that, either.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many, it's all over for the Utah Jazz. People
say, ``They had their chance,'' alluding to defeats in the NBA
Finals in 1997 and '98. They couldn't get out of the second round
last season, losing to the Portland Trail Blazers in six games. Now
all the talk centers on the Pacific Division, where powerhouses Los
Angeles (18-5) and Portland (17-5) are off to great starts, with
Seattle (16-6), Sacramento (13-6), and Phoenix (14-7) in hot
pursuit. It's as if the Jazz (15-7), who trail San Antonio (17-7)
in the Central by just one game, don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' acknowledged Malone. ``It's not even like we're
lying in the weeds. People have forgotten all about us.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Jazz now have a seven-game winning streak,
and they've been doing it the same old way. ``If you were them,''
inquired Celtics assistant coach John Carroll, ``would you change
anything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old, same old,'' added Boston assistant Lester
Connor. ``They're still slicing and dicing you. Pick-and-rolls with
Stockton and Malone. A thousand post-ups for Malone.''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't post Malone? He seems to be the same player he was
five or 10 years ago, landing in Boston as the league's No. 3
scorer (25.8) and No. 9 rebounder (10.2). No one is in better
shape, and no one intends to be in better shape. The man has just
re-upped for another four years, which will make him 40 years old
and an 18-year NBA veteran when that deal is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to keep playing this way my whole career,'' he vowed.
``And when I do retire, I'll know I left it all out there, on the
floor. I think I can do it, as long as I keep preparing to play the
way I know how.''
</P>
<P>
   And know-how is a pretty good way of describing the manner in
which he scored his just-showing-up superstar's 27, since he did it
by making just one jump shot and by simply willing himself to the
foul line, where he was 13 for 17. But, hey, he does lead the
league in free throw attempts for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   He never even fantasized about such a career. ``Who could do
such a thing?'' he said. ``I never expected anything like this.
Thinking back from high school, the college, and all this time in
the NBA, it feels like the whole thing is storybook. When it's
over, I'll look back and say, `It's been a hell of a ride, you
know?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Want to talk storybook? How about the Celtics beating him here
one more time before he heads to the ranch, the hills, or wherever
he'll go when it's over?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
