<HEADER>
A0843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DEPRESSION-BOS &LR;      12-16 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DEPRESSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPRESSION AS A STATE OF MIND, A WAY OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WHERE THE ROOTS REACH FOR WATER 
A Personal and Natural History of Melancholia 
By Jeffery(cq)  Smith 
North Point Press, 304 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antidepressants didn't work for Jeffery Smith. None alleviated
his depression for more than a few months. Not long after one
cocktail of medications induced a paralytic seizure, Smith stopped
taking the things altogether. ``Where the Roots Reach for Water: A
Personal and Natural History of Melancholia'' is Smith's account of
his life in the months that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible for a writer to convey the texture and contour of
depression to readers who have never experienced it? It may be that
depression is a foreign country, a place you can try to imagine but
can never really know until you've been there. To someone who has
more than once pitched her tent in that rough terrain, Smith's
account is authentic, sometimes depressingly so. And it is more
than a story about one man's struggle with his dark side: It's also
a fascinating and highly idiosyncratic exploration of the illness,
its history, and its place in the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   Smith begins with a haunting description of a sudden descent
into depression. Zoloft had granted him a ``glorious reprieve'' for
several months. One day it no longer worked. His psychiatrist
instructed him to double the dosage, but his depression refused to
budge.
</P>
<P>
   Smith neglected his job as a caseworker in a Missoula, Mont.,
mental-health center. His girlfriend broke up with him. He
retreated to his dark basement room, subsisted on watery lentil
soup and burned cheese sandwiches, and tried to shut out the world.
But he couldn't hide from the inner critic he calls Mr. Shoulder,
who whispered into his ear a merciless inventory of his
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Smith plotted suicide. He'd walk into a remote stretch of river,
thinking that ``like Virginia Woolf, I would surrender my weight to
the current.'' Instead, standing alone one night by the same river,
he decided once and for all to quit taking antidepressants. He
tried nonpharmaceutical approaches to his illness _ first
homeopathy, then traditional therapy. When he felt a little better,
he began delving into the history of depression, which he prefers
to call by one of its ancient names, melancholia.
</P>
<P>
   He read up on astrology, and learned that for centuries saying
that someone was born under the sign of Saturn (his own birth sign)
was a shorthand way of saying the person was prone to melancholy.
He learned about the Roman physician Galen's ``humoral'' theory of
medicine, his theory that ``black bile'' (a purely hypothetical
substance) ``darkens the seat of reason.'' He read Hildegard of
Bingen, Dante, Thomas Merton, William James, T. S. Eliot, Susan
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered that in some cultures there is no word for
depression. In others, the condition is viewed not as an illness
but as ``a more or less `natural' result of the vicissitudes of
life.'' In other times _ ``Ages of Melancholy,'' in Renaissance
Europe and in Elizabethan England, and the reign of the
19th-century Romantics in Germany and Great Britain _ depression
was seen as ``a great gift; painful and trying, yes, but on the
whole a worthwhile experience _ desirable, even.''
</P>
<P>
   Premillennial America is hard on the depressed. ``In spite of
all evidence,'' Smith writes, ``modern-day Americans keep trying to
convince ourselves that happiness is the natural state of our
species.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular notion that all depression can be cured with a pill
is far from true, as Smith testifies. He calls this the Age of
Anti-Depression, a time of a single, reductionist, biochemical
approach to a condition that nevertheless feels unique to each
person who suffers with it.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn back to his family home in the hills of West Virginia,
Smith recognizes one source of his depression: the longing for a
familiar landscape. He also learns that both sides of his family
tree are full of depressed people. It's in his blood, an elderly
aunt tells him. He wonders: Why has depression remained in the
human gene pool? What function does it serve?
</P>
<P>
   As his book closes, 18 months after he quit taking medications,
Smith is learning to live with his depression. He has made a home
with a woman he loves. He has found religion, and a ``sustaining
kinship'' with animals, plants, the landscape, his family, the
past. He has come to see his depression as an excess of self,
something that comes between him and God. He reads Merton still. He
struggles to annihilate will, desire, ego, to avoid ``the cheap,
cowardly out of cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's destination may not be where every traveler in the
landscape of depression would wish to find himself. But his account
of his journey there is fascinating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
