<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALVE WILL PREVENT `SHOWER SHOCK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When others use water in my house, the temperature changes
drastically in my shower, either too cold or too hot. How can that
be fixed?
</P>
<P>
   LILLIAN SHULMAN, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Install a one-handle valve, which prevents this sudden change
in temperature that has plagued shower users for years. They used
to be called antiscald valves, but now are called pressure-control
valves. They work by adjusting the pressure in the lines when
someone other than the person showering draws water. Such valves
are required in many states in new construction and when replacing
an old valve.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I get a whiff of gas when the shower goes on. What is it, and
what causes it? How can I prevent it from happening?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with a simple answer and possible solution,
especially since you get no whiff from other sinks or faucets. And,
by whiff I assume you mean it is temporary. If it were sewer gas
coming up from an empty trap, the odor would be continuous. It may
be a dirty drain, full of grease, oil, hair, and other gross
things. When water goes down that drain, its movement causes odor
from this greasy buildup to rise to your unsuspecting nose. The
cure is to clean the drain with bleach and water. Then pour a cup
of bleach down the drain and leave it overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is hydrogen sulfide gas in the water, caused
by bacteria. A dirty aerator (the shower head) could be the cause.
Cleaning it will help.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, hydrogen sulfide is in the water naturally. In that
case, letting the water run a few minutes usually helps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am bulding a small, one-story house on the Cape. The
specifications call for floor registers for hot-air heat. I was
told that floor registers allow extremes of heat and cold, but
nothing in between. Is that so? If so, how should the registers go?
</P>
<P>
   CONFUSED, on the Cape
</P>
<P>
   A. I think that is an old wives' tale. However, floor registers
do little to distribute the heat properly. You would be better off
with baseboard registers for your hot-air system. These units, 18
inches long, 5 inches high, and 4 inches deep, fit over floor
openings and butt against the wood baseboard. Their fronts are
louvered to distribute air as evenly as a hot-air system can
manage. If I were you, I would insist on baseboard registers. They
are a shade more expensive than floor registers, but are worth it.
And, they will be as easy as the floor ones to install.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever tried to drill a hole in ceramic tile or glass,
and had a devil of a time getting the hole started without the
drill bit walking all over the place? It happens no matter how hard
you try to keep that spinning drill steady.
</P>
<P>
   One way to curb the wayward bit is to apply a piece of duct tape
to the tile or glass. This will hold the drill as you begin. Other
handymen have suggested drilling a small hole in a piece of wood,
laying the wood on the glass or tile, and using the hole to reduce
the drill wobble.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things will work, and Joe Horner of Belmont, Mass., who
has helped the handyman on occasion, suggested this: Rotate the bit
each way without power, to chip out a tiny bit of glass or tile.
The bit will fit into that tiny chip and stay put as you apply
power. Or, take a nail and tap it ever so slightly to make that
chip.
</P>
<P>
   With the latter approach, you stand a chance of breaking the
glass or tile if you are not careful or just get unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   Another trick: Try drilling and chipping on a scrap. If it works
on a scrap, you can go ahead on the real thing with renewed
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A concrete panel was replaced in my sidewalk, but the new
panel is the wrong color. The panels are 3 feet square, so the new
one really stands out. How can I make them match? What kind of
paint should I use?
</P>
<P>
   WALLY GIANNONE, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Wait a few years; the panels will match, eventually. Do not
paint; you won't get a match anyway, and with paint, you will have
a perennial chore of scraping and repainting.
</P>
<P>
   If the difference in color really bugs you, try this: Stain the
entire sidewalk with a concrete stain. It won't peel, and the color
will be consistent. You can get any number of colors in the stain
that Muralo makes, sold at paint stores. And, by the time the stain
starts to wear off, the color on all panels will probably be
consistent enough for you to tolerate without restaining.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COMPOST-BOS &LR;      12-16 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COMPOST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCKING IN THE GARDEN FOR A LONG WINTER'S COMPOSTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As with the rest of life, gardening is a series of transitions
interspersed with occasional lulls of contentment.
</P>
<P>
   Winter to spring, spring to summer, summer to fall, fall to
winter. The drudgery of these busy times tends to be tempered by
excitement over what is to come. Thus, when my back and shoulders
and arms ache from early spring digging and raking and pruning
following a too-sedentary winter, I am nonetheless ebullient at
being back in touch with the earth. I fairly glow at the promise of
the coming season. I dose myself liberally with ibuprofen.
</P>
<P>
   So it is now. As autumn starts to nod off into winter's chill,
it is a last chance to finish closing the garden shop. Leaves must
be raked out of bushes (drooping forsythias embrace oak leaves,
spreading euonymus clutch at the detritus; all must be removed).
</P>
<P>
   The lawn gets a last mowing, with the blade lowered from its
highest setting, where I normally keep it, for a close trim that
must last until spring. There will be warm spells between now and
then, and grass being grass, the lawn will grow. (Fertilizing and
liming was done two months ago.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't rake leaves from the lawn. Instead, I mow them with the
grass and deposit the grounds on various beds where they can rot
down and improve the soil. The backyard mowings go on perennial
beds, not in the vegetable garden, because the dogs have free rein
in the back, and their particular fertilizer is not wanted where we
grow lettuce and such.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby town reside a pair of horses and three donkeys whose
fertilizer is very much wanted. On my annual pilgrimage, I back my
pickup truck up to the manure bin, grab my shovel, chat with the
animals' owner, and begin heaving that heady mix of straw, wood
chips, and poop into the truck bed.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoy this. I break a sweat, take a break, exchange bestial
glances with the horses and donkeys, who have gathered by the
adjacent fence to watch. As I dig into the pile, steam rises from
the heat of composting. The manure smell to me is delicious. It is
a farm smell, a garden smell, the stuff of life. I think I'll make
two trips this year.
</P>
<P>
   The stench is not appreciated by everybody. My wife is never
pleased at the spillage in the driveway when I unload and cart the
manure around in the wheelbarrow. (The dogs, on the other hand,
know just what barn sweepings are for, and I have to make sure they
don't break into the manured beds for a good roll.)
</P>
<P>
   The manure is raked atop the vegetable beds. It will rot down
nicely over the winter. I do not till the beds, but I don't walk on
them either, so they are not compacted. Tilth, soil structure, is
important.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment needs attention now. I clean the lawn mower, give
exposed parts a spritz with an oil spray, remove and sharpen the
blade with a file. The snow blower comes out, is gassed, and starts
on the umpteenth pull (which it won't during a storm a month from
now).
</P>
<P>
   Garden tools are dulled from a season of use. Hoes, shovels,
edgers, trowels need sharpening. I wipe steel parts with
lubricating oil and wood handles with linseed oil cut with paint
thinner. Good tools should last a lifetime. Many of my tools came
from my grandfather's cellar. Others came from my mom's garage
(I'll return them soon; sure I will). Gardening is a matter of
connections.
</P>
<P>
   The first catalogs have arrived (that 2000 on the covers looks
funny). I toss them in a pile. They are for January reading _ and
dreaming. But a warm day now is perfect for a walkabout, notebook
in hand, casting a critical eye on the garden and jotting down
observations.
</P>
<P>
   The dead ornamental plum would support a clematis or two. If I
cover the lawn around it with newspapers under mulch, I can create
a nice, big bed, a home for the lacecap hydrangea I have wanted for
years. Next to the dead tree could go a small ornamental tree,
perhaps a Franklinia alatamaha (white flowers in September and
October, gorgeous orange and red autumn foliage) or a stewartia
(mottled bark, white flowers in July, purple and reddish orange
autumn foliage). When the new tree had some size to it, the
clematis could be retrained to grow up it and the adjacent dead
trunk removed.
</P>
<P>
   Plants have thrived, and plants have died. I take note. I bend
and pull things out, pat things down. Here a quick raking, there a
pruning of a damaged branch.
</P>
<P>
   The pace quickens in these final weeks, and while there is a
sense of satisfaction, it takes a toll on the gardener.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I grin and bear it. Pass the ibuprofen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
