<SLUG> BC-SKI-GIFTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORES REALLY HAVE THE GOODS FOR SKIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While few gifts could be more welcome than one huge honking
blizzard about now, along with a stretch of seasonably cold
weather, the next best thing is slope stuff _ to slide on, to wear,
to play with on the chairlift.
</P>
<P>
   --One of the biggest trends the last five years has been a
takeoff in showshoes. Ever since lightweight plastic and aluminum
arrived on the scene, developed by Tubbs and Atlas, the growth of
snowshoeing is one of those skyrocket success stories.
</P>
<P>
   More and more skiers are picking up snowshoes for walking around
the resort after ski hours or on non-ski days, and every year there
are more choices.
</P>
<P>
   Weight, of course, is a big factor, and retailers have charts to
figure out the right snowshoe for the wearer. But these days,
buyers have to know how their snowshoes will be used _ whether it's
bushwhacking through the deep wilderness with lots of rough terrain
and icy crust, or perhaps fitness walking, or even jogging on
groomed trails or moderately deep snow.
</P>
<P>
   For every specialty there is a snowshoe and a price range. For
kids, the BearCub or new Tubbscout snowshoes run $40 to $80. Tubbs
lower end ``Discovery'' snowshoe costs about $120, while upper end
wilderness and backpacking snowshoes sell for $220 to $250.
</P>
<P>
   For snow joggers, a pair of Premiere Running snowshoes sells for
about $200.
</P>
<P>
   --Cross-country skis and boots offer about the same kind of
variety and price range. Binding systems have evolved from the old
three-pin free-heelers to the extremely lightweight Solomon
boot/binding system common in modern equipment. In any case,
gift-givers should be aware that boots and bindings must be the
same system, and they should not buy skis with bindings unless they
know what boots will be worn with it.
</P>
<P>
   Again, will the skis be used in wilderness touring through
untracked backcountry or skating on groomed tracks? The equipment
differences are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   On one end is the long traditional waxless skis narrow enough to
ski in groomed tracks but long and wide enough to remain stable on
ungroomed snow. With this style ski, there is a range of boot from
leather to Gore-Tex, most of them offering support and stability
for the backcounty. A typical package runs $250 to $400 for
lightweight carbon-fiber skis.
</P>
<P>
   The other extreme in cross-country is the high-tech skating
ski/boot/binding combination used on skating tracks and fast
kick-glide double-trackset skiing. The boots are as light as
running shoes, and a typical combination might feature Rossignol
high-performance waxable-carbon skis with Solomon Active SC binding
and boot combination. A package of this sort runs $350 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a pair of the easier-turning skis designed
primarily for groomed tracks, packed fields, snowmobile tracks.
These skis are shorter and wider, and turn much easier than long
ones, snowplow, and herringbone up hills easier than traditional
skis. Adult ski/boot/binding packages run $200 to 250.
</P>
<P>
   --For parents who never quite know what to buy for small
children, former ski racer Steve Lathrop has designed a whole line
of innovative gear.
</P>
<P>
   There is the T-bar for towing kids as young as a year old, the
tip connecters for older kids, and a Kidder Lift _ a device that
helps small children ride the chairlift. The gear starts at around
$25 and is available at Ski Market.
</P>
<P>
   --Still very hot are snowblades, which appeared about five years
ago and are popular among younger skiers, but anyone can use them.
These shorty devices are great for scooting around smaller hills
with a minimum of gear, and they sell for around $170 for a top
Solomon blade.
</P>
<P>
   --Needless to say, before buying skis or a snowboard for
someone, take into account the recipient's abilities and physical
traits. A general recommendation is for skiers and riders to select
their own skis and boards after trying out a few demo models.
</P>
<P>
   But these gifts do look festive under the tree Christmas
mornings, so the next best thing is to have a clear return
agreement at a store with a wide variety of brands and models.
</P>
<P>
   Shaped skis are the norm these days, but there is a wide variety
of shapes, from the extreme for beginners to the moderate and
slight shapes for more advanced skiers.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers should be mindful that eager learners just getting
started may outgrow a pair of extreme sidecut skis in less than a
season; so they are not recommended here. Extreme shapes do allow
faster turning, but after a few days of beginner turns, new skiers
want to add some speed, at which point these extremes become
unstable because they don't track very well.
</P>
<P>
   And one tip for a buyer of shaped skis for an experienced skier
who has always been on traditional skis: Spend the extra $60 for a
one-hour private lesson on the technique nuances that get the most
out of the shaped skis. Usually, it takes no more instruction than
this, but leave it to a pro.
</P>
<P>
   --If the person you are buying for wants ski boots, buy a gift
certificate at a ski store with a wide inventory and trained boot
fitters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ski accessories come in all sizes, shapes, and prices. Here's a
smattering:
</P>
<P>
   --Walkie-talkies allow families and groups to stay in touch
especially at large resorts. These easily fit in the pocket and are
great for groups of mixed abilities who spread out on a mountain
but want to meet for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Bell has walkie-talkies for less than $100 per radio. Kenwood
has a good waterproof unit for $125. Look for external
speaker/microphone features.
</P>
<P>
   --For real gadgeteers, the wrist computer with altimeter is a
must. Suunto makes a good one for around $200, but there are many
on the market. This lets skiers/boarders keep track of how many
miles they have skied in a year, at what elevation they're skiing,
and provides infinite fiddling opportunity on the chairlift.
</P>
<P>
   --Almost every retail shop has a zipper thermometer for less
than $10. It's a very useful stocking stuffer.
</P>
<P>
   --A weather radio is great to have in the hotel room to know
what to expect next day. Many manufacturers offer these. Radio
Shack has one for under $20.
</P>
<P>
   --For night cross-country or snowshoe forays in the woods (these
are fun parties, incidentally), a headlamp is handy. This is a
flashlight that straps onto the head. Made by Lightsource, the
battery-pack model sells for around $50.
</P>
<P>
   --There also are goggles ($20-$50), thermal socks ($15),
polypropelyne long underwear ($30), the Leatherman knife/scissors
tool ($50), and a stainless steel vacuum bottle ($30) to keep
drinks hot while you ski or board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
