<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' GOAL: FIND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's no one thing that has tripped up the Bruins during
their 1-4-3 slide. Off the ice, there have been all sorts of
meetings, but they haven't kept the Bruins from falling to sixth
place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a different aspect the last two weeks,'' said
assistant coach Ken Baumgartner. ``Some nights its goal scoring,
some nights it's point coverage, and other nights it's 2-on-2 and
3-on-3. We have to pick our game up in all aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been this way since a 2-2 tie with the Vancouver Canucks
Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have as many meetings as you want and if it's not being
done on the ice, it doesn't mean anything,'' Sergei Samsonov said.
``I'm sure the guys aren't happy with the way the team is playing
right now. Everybody's trying to chip in and do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will try again twice this weekend, at Atlanta Friday
followed by a visit to St. Louis Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that means that there's no time to think about it,''
Samsonov said. ``Especially on the road. You go out and get 2
points and you try not to give up a lot of chances by not giving up
any goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is the Bruins have never been the type of team
to score a bundle of goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win, 1-0, 2-1, games like that,'' Samsonov said.
``If we score two or three goals a game, we have a real good chance
to win because that's our defensive style. We're sticking to our
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze has been asked about the Bruins' plight before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent question, and if we had the answer, of
course, we'd fix it as soon as we could,'' he said. ``It's basic,
simple hockey we have to play. That's the good equation. We just
have to stick to it. It's the whole package, it's never one thing.
It's 20 guys all sticking to a system and playing well together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have known what the opposition is going to try to do
even before the game gets underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that we're not executing right now,'' Joe Thornton
said. ``We just have to score one more than the other team. That's
the bottom line. Like against Phoenix (a 2-0 Boston win), we were
shooting the puck, we had a lot of chances while driving hard to
the net, and we did a nice job of keeping the opposition out of the
middle of the ice. We have to get back to that sort of game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just a matter of the players believing they are going to do
it in that particular game. It usually has to do with simple
hockey, playing the game with plenty of intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple stuff won for us before,'' said P.J. Axelsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do our job in the team system and play with some
urgency,'' Joe Murphy said. ``We have to play with some
desperation. Every game you've got to look at like it's a must-win.
We have to go out and have fun. Right now we do it in spurts. One
line does well, the next line does fine, and then we miss the next
two shifts. We don't seem to put it together for the 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some games it's a matter of some guys trying to do too much,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not any different than other teams that go through the
highs and lows in a year,'' Rob DiMaio said. ``The key for us is to
play within our system and maybe simplify our game in some ways. We
usually play very solid together. We know exactly what we're
supposed to so. Maybe we're searching for something now to get out
of this and be more effective defensively. We need to find the
happy medium. We have a solid group of guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all of us finding what gives you confidence, with
everybody on top of their game, everybody playing good, solid, high
at a consistent level when we're effective as a team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
