<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-CRASHES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE FRUSTRATING TO SOME, BOON TO OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Resending with graphic)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Genest, a public relations executive, is upset. On
crutches with a foot injury, she decided to do her holiday shopping
on line rather than go to the malls.
</P>
<P>
   But when she tried to buy a car racetrack set for her 6-year-old
son, she wound up with a large toy airplane instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total nightmare,'' she said of shopping on line.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston University, e-commerce professor Bruce D. Weinberg has
had a different experience. As of September, he stopped shopping in
brick-and-mortar stores altogether, buying everything from holiday
gifts to tires and light bulbs on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a ton of fun,'' said Weinberg, who added, ``I'm straining
to think of something terrible that happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With holiday shoppers expected to spend $6 billion to $10
billion this season, anecdotal evidence abounds about retail Web
sites crashing or fouling up orders, but e-commerce analysts claim
on-line shopping is not all that different from shopping in the
real world.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are on-line hassles, analyst said, but there are
hassles at malls and department stores as well.
</P>
<P>
   On-line horror stories have been ``well publicized,'' said Seema
Williams, an analyst at Forrester Research. ``But there have been
no wholesale disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, on-line holiday shopping went mainstream last
year when consumers spent a total of about $3 billion on
holiday-related purchases, according to Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of problems in 1998. Many Web sites couldn't
handle the crush of business. Consumers found some sites hard to
navigate, and other sites couldn't manage to get the right orders
to the right consumers at the right times.
</P>
<P>
   This year, traffic is far heavier. According to Jupiter, 28.8
million consumers will shop on line this year, 10 million more than
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers are seeing exponential jumps. In Waltham, Mass.,
toysmart.com equaled the number of orders it received for all of
December 1998 in the first 30 hours of December 1999, spokesman
Patrick Rafter said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several big retailers have seen traffic to their Web
sites double since October, said Christopher Vroom, an analyst with
Thomas Weisel Partners.
</P>
<P>
   One reason some consumers have problems with retail Web sites
may be that their expectations are too high, said analyst Alan
Alper with Gomez Advisors in Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce technology is still ``immature,'' he said, yet some
people expect it to function as smoothly as ``clockwork.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jupiter, the most experienced on-line shoppers know
better than to place too much faith in Web retailers just yet. In a
recent survey, shoppers told Jupiter that they plan to spend less
than 10 percent of their holiday budgets at retail Web sites
because they expect to encounter on-line snafus.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to take a chance that their holiday orders won't
arrive on time _ or that they'll get the wrong stuff _ these
consumers said they plan to do the bulk of their shopping at
old-fashioned stores and malls, Jupiter found.
</P>
<P>
   Given the novelty of on-line shopping, some consumers might
think a mysterious new technology is to blame for most problems.
But the real challenge may be more mundane, and more humbling.
</P>
<P>
   After a consumer hits the ``buy'' button at a Web site, a
retailer must perform a sequence of steps that can add up to a
logistical headache: first, the order must be picked from warehouse
shelves, then it must be properly packed, and finally it must be
turned over to a delivery service such as UPS to get the package to
a consumer's home.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound all that difficult, but multiply it many
times over, compress the crunch time into a six-week window, and
order fulfillment can become a daunting task indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Wal-Mart Stores Inc. In the brick-and-mortar world, the
huge retailer is known for its mastery of technology, yet its
retail Web site is not working as smoothly as hoped. Last week,
Wal-Mart posted a note on its Web site saying it can't guarantee
orders will be delivered by Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Many so-called ``pure-play'' e-commerce retailers _ retailers
that have no stores and sell products only over the Internet _ hire
third parties to handle many order-fulfillment tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as Amazon.com, have invested heavily in building a
network of automated warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Because e-commerce companies employ different strategies and
because some of them execute those strategies much better than
others, a consumer's experience can vary widely from Web site to
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Web is chock-a-block with e-commerce upstarts,
and a post-holiday period of shakeout and consolidation is almost
inevitable, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Vroom believes the survivors will be the Web sites with
which consumers have the fewest hassles, and those probably will be
the ones that have focused the most on the logistics of fulfilling
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Genest, from Stoneham, Mass., had her order fulfilled all right.
It was just that eToys.com, the Web site at which she made her
purchases, sent her a toy airplane instead of toy cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplane is taking up the better part of my living room,''
she said of the six-foot-long package.
</P>
<P>
   Genest said she has contacted eToys twice by phone. Once she was
put on hold for 30 minutes. If things aren't straightened out by
the weekend, she'll brave the mall, bad foot and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really need a heavy incentive to do this again,'' she said
of on-line shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some customers are experiencing frustrations, and we're
genuinely sorry about that,'' said eToys spokesman Ken Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Coping with a ``significant uptick'' in the number of orders it
has received, eToys is working ``24 hours a day seven days a week''
on service and delivery and is dedicated to improving all aspects
of its shopping experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts consider eToys to be one of the best e-commerce
retailers and they agreed with Ross's claim that bad experiences at
the eToys Web site is the exception and not the rule.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, BU professor Weinberg said he's had mostly good
shopping experiences on line. Amazon.com and Landsend.com are among
the sites that have impressed him.
</P>
<P>
   For many e-commerce retailers, a bigger challenge may come after
Christmas, when many consumers attempt to return and exchange
gifts, said Alper, the Gomez analyst.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, many Web sites suffer from growing pains, but
eventually the best ones will get it right, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Alper, ``The time savings and convenience'' that on-line
shopping offers to consumers ``are too much to give up on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
