<HEADER>
A0851 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CROWDED-VALLEY-BOS &LR;      12-16 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROWDED-VALLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY A HIGH-TECH PARADISE LOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ When HotDispatch, a young Internet
company founded in Cambridge, was asked by its investors to move to
Silicon Valley, it was confirmation of the West Coast region's role
as the epicenter of high tech.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   All of HotDispatch's technical talent refused to go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction was: Are you joking?'' Scott McKay, senior
engineer at HotDispatch, said of the proposal to move his entire
company westward. ``Ten years ago, people were touting Silicon
Valley as a new earthly paradise. Now, it's more than filled up,
and the quality of life is substantially lower because so many
people got on the bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   The result: HotDispatch ended up with a split existence _ sales,
marketing and headquarters in Mountain View and engineering in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise at HotDispatch reflects an increasing uneasiness
among technology companies and their employees to move to Silicon
Valley, where the cost of housing is among the highest on the
planet and a 30-minute commute can easily grind into a three-hour
gridlocked ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Congestion and the high cost of living and doing business are
nothing new to this region, but the price of Silicon Valley's
success has become acutely evident the last few years amid the
Internet boom fuelling the region's economy. As a result, high-tech
companies and their workers increasingly are shunning the Valley
for places ranging from Montana to Texas _ and even Massachusetts,
which is near the top of cost charts.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Bay Area continues to be the undisputed mecca
for technology start-ups, on course to attract $10 billion in
venture capital this year, or one-third of the nation's start-up
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the bravo, however, many business and civic leaders here
are quietly worried that, unless dramatic improvements are made in
the area's quality of life, Silicon Valley may become a victim of
its own success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, part of convincing workers to relocate here is
to get them to agree to getting half the home they had at twice the
price. The people you want don't fall for that very long,'' said
Carl Guardino, president of the Silicon Valley Manufacturing Group,
an organization that represents 150 of the largest high-tech
employers in the Valley, including Hewlett-Packard Co., Apple
Computer Inc., Intel Corp., and Cisco Systems Inc. ``It is an issue
we have to tackle in order to maintain the economic miracle of the
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many companies, the lack of employee loyalty _ compounded by
today's hot job market _ in the Valley is the biggest turnoff, said
David Orfao, who has worked on both coasts and is now chief
executive of Allaire Corp. in Cambridge. In two years, Allaire's
turnover rate among its 300 employees is less than one percent,
compared to the double-digit attrition rates often experienced by
high-tech companies in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Allaire was a start-up in Minneapolis, its
founders were debating whether to relocate to the Boston area or
Silicon Valley. The company even signed a lease for office space in
Mountain View, but backed out because it found more ready access to
executive talent in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in the Valley have a 24- to 36-month time horizon
when they're working for a company,'' Orfao said from Cambridge.
``Out here, people are far more open to committing to a five-year
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maeder, managing partner of Highland Capital, a venture
capital firm with offices on both coasts, put it this way:
``Silicon Valley has twice the talent as anywhere else, hands down.
But the talent is almost impossible to keep. They cost twice as
much to hire, and you can only keep them for half as long.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a torrid employment market in the Valley has
meant that workers can hop from job to job ``without changing car
pools,'' as one executive told University of California at Berkeley
professor AnnaLee Saxenian in her book, ``Regional Advantage:
Culture and Competition in Silicon Valley and Route 128.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the challenges he would face to pay and retain
employees, Greg Gianforte, founder and chief executive of RightNow
Technologies Inc., skipped the Valley altogether. In March 1998,
Gianforte started RightNow, a profitable Internet software company,
in Bozeman, Montana, a place he fell in love with while on a field
trip to the city in junior high school.
</P>
<P>
   For the vast majority of customers, RightNow is able to market,
install and support its products _ almost entirely over the
Internet. ``The Internet removes geography from the whole business
equation,'' Gianforte said.
</P>
<P>
   Gianforte delights in spurning Silicon Valley. ``I really
believe Silicon Valley is the wrong place to do a start-up,'' he
said. ``There is a shortage of people in the Bay Area. When demand
outstrips supply, that creates chaos. Salaries are out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists that his company's location hasn't hindered his
ability to recruit employees, many of whom are drawn to the outdoor
activities available in rural Montana. His company's Web site
beckons workers with a large photo of Bozeman at the foot of
snowcapped mountain ranges. ``You could live here!'' blares a
caption.
</P>
<P>
   For companies outside ofn Valley, the call of the wild _
or at least a more balanced life _ has succeeded in snagging
technology employees yearning for less stressful careers, shorter
commutes, or more buying power than is possible in the Bay Area,
where the average sales price of a single family home in Palo Alto
in November hit $899,255, up nearly 30 percent over last year's
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It discourages people from coming to work here, and eventually
it will cause a problem in bringing good people to work in the
high-tech industry,'' said Douglas Tobin, president of the Santa
Clara County Association of Realtors in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin recalls spending a day last year ferrying an engineer from
Dallas who had just gotten a substantial job offer from a Silicon
Valley semiconductor company. The engineer brought pictures of his
Dallas home, a two-year-old, 4,000-square-foot house on a half acre
of land that was valued at about $225,000. To get a comparable
house in Los Altos, an enclave for Valley executives, the engineer
would have had to spend $1.5 million. ``He just said `no way' and
went back to Texas,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The high cost of housing has led to another problem _ the
displacement of teachers, artists, firefighters, public servants
and others not employed in technology. The average tenure of a
teacher in Silicon Valley is a mere four years. The main reason
teachers cite for leaving the Valley: the high cost of homes,
according to Guardino. His organization is lobbying for a
regionwide program to subsidize closing and down payment costs _ up
to $10,000 _ for each teacher who remains in the area for at least
5 years. The fledgling program, funded with city money, was adopted
in San Jose in February and so far has attracted 350 applicants.
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't just housing. In Silicon Valley, rush hour begins
at 6 a.m. on some major freeways. Orfao, who lived in Los Altos,
said he saw his commute to San Jose double from 20 minutes to 40
minutes over a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many companies still go to great lengths to establish some
presence in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where it's happening,'' said William Davidow, general
partner of Mohr, Davidow Ventures in Menlo Park, Calif. ``By not
being here, you're going to have to work harder to have access to a
whole infrastructure for building your business.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the Valley's critical mass of high-tech companies that has
allowed the area to excel, according to Saxenian's book, ``Regional
Advantage.'' The proximity of so many companies, from chipmakers to
software vendors, gives Silicon Valley firms easy access to both
customers and business partners.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Silicon Valley business leaders realize that
the area's future preeminence will be determined by how it
addresses the increasingly prohibitive cost of living and doing
business here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger for Silicon Valley is internal, not external,''
said Stephen Levy, director of the Center for Continuing Study of
the California Economy in Palo Alto. ``The things that human
resources managers are most worried about are housing, education
and transportation. The growth here has raced ahead of the region's
ability to build infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenges we face are due to our own success,'' said
Guardino. ``As long as we focus on solving these problems, we'll
continue to be a success. If we get cocky, we'll fail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
