<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD'S SAHLMAN SAYS BAH-HUMBUG TO RISING PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The inflation numbers continue to look good, but that hasn't
stopped investors and the Federal Reserve from worrying that the
strong economy will soon trigger rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   William Sahlman thinks such fears are overblown. ``The US
economy is just fine, thank you,'' he writes in the latest issue of
the Harvard Business Review. ``In fact, it's never been better _
sturdy, resilient, and raring to grow. And it will remain that way
for years to come if the government just manages to stay out of its
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The source of Sahlman's optimism is the new economy and the way
it is transforming companies, new and old. As a professor of
entrepreneurial finance at the Harvard Business School, Sahlman is
in a good spot to watch the new economy in action. Many of the men
and women running today's start-ups are his former students.
</P>
<P>
   We sat down with Sahlman earlier this week to get his take on
the economy, the Internet, and stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You seem pretty convinced inflation is not as big a problem
as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   A. My assertion is that it is very hard for companies to raise
prices when confronted with the massive levels of entry into new
businesses and the massives degree of reengineering we are seeing.
And I am not just talking about the Internet. I have been involved
with a 120-year-old company in Marlborough that makes industrial
sanitary supplies: basic stuff. Is it possible for them to raise
prices? The answer is no. The competition they face is vicious. So
what do they do? They figure out how to become more efficient and
effective than they would otherwise be. You pick your sector, the
revolution is present.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does the Internet accelerate this process?
</P>
<P>
   A. When I talk about the Internet I compare it to Jurassic Park
when the force field comes down and the raptors run loose. Imagine
that companies for 100 years have tried to build a brand identity
and physical barriers to entry: the best locations in the mall or
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Then along comes the Internet and switches off the force field
that has been protecting all these companies. The raptors attack
the inefficiencies and reorganize the economy. I cannot overstate
the impact of the Internet. I believe it is as important as
electricity or the railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are the changes you talk about strictly American ones?
</P>
<P>
   A. The last e-mail I got was from Chile. They wanted to know if
they could translate an article of mine about writing business
plans. Just as television and music have revolutionized culture in
other countries, so will the Internet. In fact, outside the United
States, where the inefficiencies are far greater than here, you
will see these tools have a bigger impact. Take Japan, where partly
by political choice, consumer goods are relatively expensive. You
can't protect that inefficient system in the world of the Internet
and Federal Express. It goes away. If you look at our international
students, they used to want to stay in the US. Now many want to go
back to their home country and apply what they have seen here.
</P>
<P>
   Q. There have been some pretty radical changes in the past few
years at Harvard Business School. A big percentage of your students
are creating dot.com firms, right?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think cultures ever change. If you go back 50 years,
about half our students always wound up in entrepreneurial settings
10 or 15 years after they graduated. What is so amazing with our
current generation of students is that everything is happening so
much more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Today people are able to get access to critical resources _
customers, money, employees, suppliers _ when they are 27
years-old, not 40 years-old. They are skipping a lot of the
intermediate steps our graduates used to take.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Won't that cause problems?
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course it will. We will see lots of mistakes being made.
Lots of companies will fail. When you are young and moving quickly,
sometimes you haven't been there before or seen how things play
out. No doubt many people, including some of our graduates, will be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You are not suggesting that these students should be moving
slowly?
</P>
<P>
   A. It turns out you cannot go slowly today. There are few slow
paths to success. In fact, the slow path is a quick path to
failure. That happens to be a characteristic of an economy that so
many smart people are trying to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In your article you suggest that our willingness to tolerate
failure in the US is one of our competitive advantages.
</P>
<P>
   A. In Japan if you fail you can become a bank guard _ in the
United States. Throughout the world, failure is disastrous, social,
politically, economically. Here we reward people for working hard
and trying things. We don't penalize them unless they cheat.
Failure is an opportunity to have learned on someone else's nickel.
I am perfectly happy, and the venture capital community is
perfectly happy, to take someone from a company that hasn't worked
out and use that experience to advantage next time around. It is
one of the fundamental characteristics of this economy.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Presumably investors in some of these new companies will wind
up with failed investments.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you go back in the history of markets, there have always
been times when people were convinced every company would succeed.
It might have been computer retailers, or the makers of computer
workstations or disk drives. The fact is, with the benefit of
hindsight, some companies did well and many failed. We have not
suspended those laws this time around. They always hold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
