<HEADLINE>
TEBUCKY JONES FINALLY GETS HIS CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Based on the grief he gets from the media
know-it-alls and fans, Tebucky Jones probably had every right to
tell Patriots director of public relations Stacey James to stuff
his request for a press conference in some hurtful place.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones were a vengeful man, he wouldn't have stood at the
podium at Foxboro Stadium Wednesday before the vast majority of his
accusers who think he's not an NFL cornerback, never mind share his
feelings and opinions about replacing the injured Ty Law for the
remainder of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones is not vengeful. He has always been impervious to
criticism about why he can't play the position. Those judgments are
based on a small sample size of opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jones will have ample opportunity to show what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   Law will be lost for 2-4 weeks after undergoing a surgical
procedure on his broken right hand Wednesday at Massachusetts
General Hospital to stabilize the three pins that were dislodged in
Sunday's loss to the Indianapolis Colts. Law will not be placed on
injured reserve in the hope that he can return if the Patriots make
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why be nervous?'' said Jones, the Patriots' second first-round
pick (No. 22 overall) in 1998. ``It's my opportunity to go out
there and put it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones played most of three quarters Sunday at Steve Israel's
left corner spot after Israel sprained his left ankle. Jones was
called for a pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   At times during the season, the 6-foot-2-inch, 215-pound native
of New Britain, Conn., has played in nickel packages. On tight
coverage, he has the tendency to hold onto a receiver for too long.
Some question his recovery speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish . . . like a lot of guys . . . if they had thrown me in
there before this, I'd be way ahead of where I am now,'' said
Jones, a man of few words. ``With Steve and Ty playing ahead of me,
it's been tough getting that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell called
Jones's play ``disappointing.'' But a week after making those
comments, Jones had returned to the spot in the nickel package that
he had lost to Kato Serwanga.
</P>
<P>
   Jones makes no apologies for what some perceive as his slow
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a running back all of my life and then I played safety
one year (at Syracuse) because I didn't want to split time with
three running backs in my senior year,'' he said. ``I don't pay
attention to what other people say about me. I was drafted for the
second-hardest position on the field, a position I'd never played
before. I didn't care where I played as long as I played
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll has defended drafting Jones out of Syracuse
all along and even now says, ``Buck has been a productive player
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true Jones has been one of the team's top special teams
cover men. He has, and will again Sunday against Philadelphia, be
back on kickoffs along with Tony Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones will be measured against how he performs against Eagle
receivers Torrance Small and Na Brown. Fans can expect a more
physical approach from Jones than Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot from Ty, but my style and his style are
different,'' said Jones. ``I'm going to be right there on the line
with their receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Any time there's an inexperienced cornerback on the field, the
opposition usually goes after him on the game's first play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should come after me,'' Jones said. ``I'm hoping to get a
couple of picks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
