</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACISM-CHALLENGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE ACTIVISTS FIGHT RACISM WITH COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KERA RITTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Horace Seldon has witnessed it all. The race riots. The
violence over court-ordered busing. The March on Washington. So it
is with a twinge of skepticism that he views the relatively placid
state of race relations in America today.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Seldon's experience with the civil rights movement
that has fostered an unusual union with a wide-eyed young man named
Ian White Maher.
</P>
<P>
   Maher represents a new generation of civil rights activists _ he
grew up after the death of Jim Crow laws and came of age after the
convulsions of the busing era. He has always mingled with
minorities, and, like some in his generation, finds it difficult to
accept that racism remains an issue in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Seldon, 76, and Maher, 27, have bridged the generational gap to
devise a plan to fight institutional racism, which is defined by
them as a system where policy decisions of institutions negatively
affect minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Their weapon in this war: the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   The two are using their whiteness to challenge other white
people to see the privileges that come with being white. They have
chosen to do so through speeches and in classrooms, and through a
quarterly newsletter Maher founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they not only don't understand it, but don't want to
understand it,'' said Seldon, who in 1968 founded Community Change,
a nonprofit group working to eradicate racism. ``There's a kind of
built-in resistance because if they understand, it will demand
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The message of racial equality is not new, but Maher and Seldon
want to reach those who have misunderstood or rejected the same
lessons preached by black activists for years. Maybe with a
different messenger, they say, more white people, particularly the
next generation of decision makers, may be willing to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Gill, an associate history professor at Tufts University,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Some audiences are more sympathetic to a person who looks like
them with a similar background, he said. For example, a white
person from South Boston talking about race relations might be
better accepted than a person of color, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can ignore what doesn't touch upon their daily life,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``white privilege'' Maher and Seldon speak of will continue
to cause racial divisiveness in this country, they say, unless
white people acknowledge it and make personal changes. ``Black
people have been saying this for a long time and now a young
27-year-old steps in and suddenly it's, `One of us is stepping up.
Maybe I should listen,' '' Maher said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Maher launched Birth Rights, a quarterly newsletter
distributed to subscribers and coffee shops in the Boston area.
Each issue features a first-person account of local civil rights
activists describing how racism affected their lives, and directs
readers to discussions, classes, conferences, and other
opportunities to talk about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Seldon, who has taught the course ``History of Racism'' at
Boston College for years, serves as a mentor and guide on racial
issues for Maher. Both also work for the state parks department as
tour guides on the Black Heritage Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to their work has been mixed. Seldon has overheard
derogatory comments and some of his students, black and white,
refuse to accept a white person teaching about racism. Maher and
Seldon have received hate mail.
</P>
<P>
   They understand the difficulty people have accepting their
message. Both vividly recall the moment when they finally grasped
the concept of institutional racism and white privilege.
</P>
<P>
   For Maher, it was two years ago while working with a nonprofit
health care organization in the Dominican Republic. He said he was
compartmentalizing the blacks into categories, but was not doing
the same to whites.
</P>
<P>
   Seldon learned about racism while working with black high school
students through a United Church of Christ outreach program in the
1960s. ``I'm forever greatful to them,'' Seldon said. ``I began to
see what institutional racism was _ although at the time I didn't
use that term _ and institutional sexism. I watched desegregation
unfold in Boston and it just taught me an immense lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher knows history is the best teacher and feeds from Seldon's
extensive experience, but is quick to note this generation's
challenges are unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents had to go through this thing where they had to make
themselves believe that blacks and Latinos and Natives were equal
to them,'' he said. ``That fight isn't my fight; it was my parents.
What I have to do is attack the underbelly of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, history plays a significant role in current affairs,
Maher and Seldon say. Unwillingness to acknowledge it, they say,
could hinder the learning process or slow progression regarding the
understanding of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many people willing to dismiss the historical
perspective and too many saying if `I wasn't involved, therefore I
shouldn't be held accountable,' '' Gill said. ``But you need to
have it brought up to show the continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldon added that inaccurate information is just as damaging.
Some students in his classes have shaped their ideas and values
around incorrect or incomplete accounts that, in many ways, suggest
whites are superior to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history books are full of misinformation so they've gotten
that all through high school, and before that, and even college,''
said Seldon. ``It just escalates and keeps accumulating, and you
get people who don't know history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another illustration of the institutional racism issue,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
