<HEADLINE>
BEST WINTER DRIVING EQUIPMENT IS COMMON SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winter driving should be a carefully thought out, cautiously
executed, top-to-bottom exercise.
</P>
<P>
   That's top to bottom as in, first, use your head, understand
that the mistakes you make driving in summer are mistakes you won't
get away with in winter; and, second, put the right tires on your
car.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, far too many folks will neglect the first, the
second, or both. When that happens, and you get into trouble _
can't stop quickly when you have to, or go into a skid on a
slippery turn _ you have to know how to get out of the mess you've
put yourself in.
</P>
<P>
   The head part involves common sense, says Tim O'Neil of the Team
O'Neil Rally School in Franconia, N.H. O'Neil, winner of multiple
rally championships in the United States and Canada, did most of
his racing on gravel, snow, and ice courses, so he knows something
about dancing on the edge of control.
</P>
<P>
   His first advice: Don't get to that edge. That means paying
attention to road conditions, knowing you can't stop or turn the
way you can on the good-gripping roads of summer. Watch the outside
temperature reading gauge that is offered in so many cars now. When
it drops from a warm day to 32 degrees and below, slow down.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to tires, snow tires on all four wheels is best,
especially if you're on the road a lot or your weekends take you
north for winter recreation. Snow tires are soft, so the rubber
moves around. They are ``stiped'' _ covered with thousands of tiny
sliced grooves that open to form thousands of little edges that
help them grip. And their treads are designed to ``work'' the snow
by packing it into strong Vs that give the tires bite.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by mud-snow tires. Tires that do well in mud do
not do well in snow. Their clunky treads are made to spit out mud,
not work snow. Picture snow tires as boat shoes with all their tiny
slits giving grip on slippery surfaces. Picture mud tires like
clunky-treaded hiking boots.
</P>
<P>
   If you want all-weather tires, O'Neil advises, get soft ones _
sometimes the cheaper tires. Don't go for high-mileage all-weathers
because they are built harder to last longer. When it's slippery,
harder is bad. Check tires with your thumb. See if you can get the
rubber to move. These are best for winter.
</P>
<P>
   Now think about what kind of car you drive: all-wheel drive,
rear-wheel drive, front-wheel drive, four-wheel drive. For the most
part, says O'Neil, consider them all the same.
</P>
<P>
   At their base, he says, cars with all four wheels driving are
``incredibly helpful'' and driven properly, he says, ``are much
safer.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, their performance breeds overconfidence and
people think they can drive them faster. But many of these vehicles
are heavier (SUVs, pickup trucks, vans), less stable in turns, and
harder to stop in an emergency. And when they do get into skids, it
is nearly impossible to drive out of that skid as you might do with
a front-wheel- or rear-wheel-drive vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   So know they perform better, but drive them as carefully as you
would any other auto.
</P>
<P>
   But since we won't all ``be careful out there,'' as the Sarge
used to say on ``Hill Street Blues,'' here's what to do when the
two most likely emergency situations _ emergency stop, loss of
control in a slippery turn _ happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   --You're driving down a straightaway, are distracted a moment,
and see a car stalled ahead of you when you look back at the road.
Get ready to let go of your instincts.
</P>
<P>
   If your vehicle does not have ABS, use the pumping technique.
Touch your brakes until you feel the wheels are about to lock up,
release, pump again _ hopefully with a bit lighter touch on the
pedal. Release, and continue this diminishing pressure of pumping
until you either have to, or now safely can, attempt to steer
around the object ahead of you.
</P>
<P>
   When you're steering, don't hold the brakes on. This is where
you are going against instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to release when your brain says, `I want to stop,'
'' says O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   If you do have ABS, slam the brakes on hard. The ABS system will
do the pumping for you. With the brakes on, steer around the
danger.
</P>
<P>
   --This time, you're in a corner, wheels turned, when you realize
the car is not going where you want it to. Instinct tells you to
let off on the gas or maybe hit the brakes. Either action transfers
weight from the rear to the front of your vehicle. Now you are
skidding. One of two things is likely happening.
</P>
<P>
   Say you are making a left-hand turn. Your rear end glides out
toward the right and is trying to pass your front (oversteer).
</P>
<P>
   Turn your wheels smoothly back to the right. Let off the brakes
_ and against instinct again, you may want to give it a bit of gas.
Gain control by turning into the turn. In bad skids, you may find
yourself going back and forth, right-left-right to fully halt the
alternating skids. But it works. Try it in a slippery abandoned
parking lot sometime.
</P>
<P>
   Now say you are making that left-hand turn but the nose keeps
going to the right (understeer). Don't think that by turning the
wheels more to the left that the car will suddenly catch on and go
that way. What you must do is let off the gas and turn to the right
until the car begins to go where you point it. You'll know this is
happening because you will feel the front wheels begin to grip
again. Now you can gently steer the car back to your intended line
_ or at least away from looming trouble.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil says understeer is more common in front-wheel-drive cars
while oversteer is more common in rear-wheel drive. All-wheel drive
has what he calls ``flat spin,'' in which the car will most likely
go immediately off the road. It's rare, but if you're not careful,
it can happen.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil describes his technique of teaching winter driving as
showing people ``how to avoid getting in the goo and what to do
when you are in the goo.''
</P>
<P>
   American drivers, he says, need to develop a better feel for
their cars and the skills needed in driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people die because they don't have the ability to get
out of a skid,'' he says. ``We should approach driving the way
pilots approach flying.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best advice _ though it will go unheeded by far too many
_ is this: Folks, be careful out there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
