<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RACE-CRITERIA-BOS &LR;      12-16 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-CRITERIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE RULING FURTHER ERODES RACE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It started 21 years ago with the Bakke case, a 1978
Supreme Court decision that startled universities nationwide by
ruling that a white student, Allan Bakke, was improperly denied a
spot in a California medical school set aside for a black
applicant.
</P>
<P>
   Bakke was the first in a line of court cases that struck down
minority preferences in hiring, firing, school admissions, and
government contracting, leading to a gradual erosion of
affirmative-action programs around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Boston remained a proud holdout. It boldly
practiced policies that promoted blacks into the previously
all-white upper ranks of the Police Department, skipping over
higher-scoring whites in the process, and set aside seats for
minorities at the city's prestigious Boston Latin School.
</P>
<P>
   So when a Superior Court judge ruled Tuesday that the Boston
Police Department was wrong to rely on race, rather than test
scores, in promoting officers, the initial assumption was that the
decision would be quickly appealed. It was not.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Police Commissioner Paul Evans, while insisting he
wants a racially diverse command staff, said he would abide by the
ruling and immediately promote about two dozen white officers who
were passed over for promotion in 1996 in favor of lower-scoring
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels this year of a decision by the Boston School
Commmittee not to appeal a federal appeals court ruling striking
down its race-sensitive admissions plans for the city's exam
schools, affirmative-action programs are under siege here, as
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that from the Supreme Court on down, the
trend has clearly been to erode affirmative action as an acceptable
policy,'' said Christopher Muse, a lawyer for the Boston Police
Detectives' Benevolent Society, the union which challenged the
department's promotion policy.
</P>
<P>
   While Bakke was the opening salvo in the war against minority
preferences, the campaign against affirmative action gained
momentum during the Reagan era, as conservative federal courts
chipped away at programs granting minority preferences and
set-asides.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a federal appeals court ordered the University of Texas
to stop giving preference to minority law school applicants. In the
same year, California's Proposition 209 banned racial preferences
statewide. Washington state's Initiative 200 did the same last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Using that legal backdrop to their advantage, such local lawyers
as Chester Darling and Michael McLaughlin successfuly challenged
raced-based policies in the Boston public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the nation's courts have ruled that affirmative
action programs may exist, but that they must be narrowly tailored
to address specific instances of past discrimination and must not
establish rigid quotas. Such rulings have resulted in a weakening
of affirmative action programs that Northeastern Law School Dean
Roger I. Abrams calls ``a very sorrowful trend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing tactics used by the civil rights movement, like
litigation and threats of litigation, as a way to turn back the
clock based on the assertion that everything is fine now,'' Abrams
said. ``But of course everything isn't fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   But for opponents of affirmative action, the legal climate that
underpinned Tuesday's ruling was long in coming _ and welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general feeling both in greater society and within
the courts that we've drifted too far away from the original
principles of the civil rights movement,'' which promised equal
protection, not preferences, said Kevin Nguyen of the American
Civil Rights Institute, a Sacramento research and education
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get back on track toward a colorblind society and
not continue seeing people through a color-coded lens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Jonathan Albano, an attorney for the Massachusetts
Minority Law Enforcement Organization, caution against the
conclusion that all affirmative action programs are doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It overstates where the law has gone to say that affirmative
action is now unlawful,'' Albano said. ``To make that blanket
statement, in my opinion, overstates what the Supreme Court has
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, faced with legal precedents tilting away from
broadly-tailored affirmative-action programs, supporters often are
reluctant to appeal to a higher court, for fear of risking a ruling
that could affect cases nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you appeal and you lose, you're going to be stuck with what
is a firm, universal precedent,'' Muse said. ``So sometimes you
have to be very careful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
