<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BINDING-GIFTS-2TAKES-     12-16 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINDING-GIFTS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL TOWN REVEALS A BIG HEART 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; JAFFREY, N.H. _ Sitting by the wood-pellet stove that warms
much of the 200-year-old farmhouse once owned by his grandparents,
David Coll hesitates when his wife, Kelly, says she awaits
Christmas feeling blessed. A moment later, he agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Look around the newly renovated house, and the reasons for both
assertion and pause are clear.
</P>
<P>
   David Coll, 31, is in a wheelchair, his mobility the casualty of
an errant crosswind and a falling maple in a logging accident deep
in the New Hampshire woods last June. That he is alive after
breaking his back, puncturing both lungs, and having his vital
signs yo-yo from the shock of it all is one blessing. That his
family and friends volunteered evenings and weekends to make his
home wheelchair-accessible while he was far away in a
rehabilitation hospital in Colorado is another.
</P>
<P>
   From the edge of his new porch, Coll can see Peter Sawyer's
silos. Bad luck also visited Sawyer this year. A fire in August
claimed the barn at his dairy farm and killed 120 cows. Good will
knocked last month when Sawyer's neighbors and friends rebuilt his
barn, as they did when a silo fell on it in 1983. That's why the
new silo bears a ``Thank you'' sign.
</P>
<P>
   Between Coll's place and Sawyer's is the raised ranch where
Robin Mazejka lives with her two children. On June 14, a Chevrolet
crossed the center line of the Milford bypass on Route 101 and hit
Mazejka's Toyota head-on at 55 miles per hour. The driver of that
car, Melinda Aldrich, was killed. Mazejka and her children were
seriously injured. When doctors said the children would come home
in wheelchairs and her daughter, Tina, might not walk again,
Mazejka's friends made her home accessible, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable town. When we were in Colorado, people
said my neighbor wouldn't do this,'' says Kelly Coll, who is 32.
``In the midst of a hard struggle we've been really blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   In a season when the big question seems to be whether to park
'n' shop for presents or click 'n' shop, what happened in Jaffrey
in 1999 reminds us of the true spirit of giving and of receiving.
These are the greater gifts, the lasting gifts that soothe and
bind.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the generosity witnessed here is a small-town thing. As
contractor Norman Shepard, volunteer foreman at the Colls' house,
sees it, ``When you can wave to almost anybody, it's going to be
like that.'' Or maybe, as town economic development officer Peter
Davis suggests, ``It's just human nature to want to help your
neighbor when they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, there are isolated people in a small town, people whose
misfortune would not propel an outpouring of precious time. Surely,
there are people in the most crowded big-city neighborhoods who
contribute casseroles and baby-sitting and scrub brushes in times
of hardship. Surely, in Worcester, 30 times the population of
Jaffrey, there are people giving from their hearts to six families
whose husbands, sons, and fathers sacrificed their lives on the
whiff of a chance that they could save someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffrey, indeed, is so small (population 5,400) that people pass
along telephone numbers in four digits and so rural that Kelly Coll
can't tell a visitor how to get here from Boston. It's home to
Mount Monadnock and the sprawling green plant of D.D. Bean &AMP; Sons
Co., the matchbook maker that is one of the town's largest
employers, with 170 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown is a stretch of yellow brick buildings with shops like
Good N' Baked and the Thrifty Bean. A Rite Aid is going up across
the street and McDonald's is down the road. The Jaffrey Women's
Club offers scholarships and maintains a historic meeting hall. A
task force wants to open a drop-in center for the teenagers who
hang in front of the library. The ambulance squad is volunteer, and
firefighters get paid by the call.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer's farm, which has been in his family for five
generations, was the last dairy farm in a town that once had 15.
Coll's father, Archie, who supplies organic eggs to natural-food
stores, is the second generation of Colls to run a farm here. So
when David Coll and Peter Sawyer suffered this year, the people who
helped were mending the very fabric of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never left Jaffrey,'' says David Coll. ``Never wanted to. I
never had that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robin Mazejka, on the other hand, is a relative newcomer, a city
lover who moved from Shrewsbury, Mass., in 1986. She was so upset
about her husband's career bringing them to such a small,
out-of-the-way place that she continued working in Worcester for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Mazejka, now divorced, consider Jaffrey home is the
connection nurtured through volunteer work she undertook only
because her former job as local bank branch manager required it.
She laughs at the memory, because these days she's active in the
Chamber of Commerce, sits on the planning board, and coordinates
volunteers for the annual Atlas Fireworks show. The hand she
learned to extend is now extended back to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to my first planning board meeting after the
accident, they stood up and clapped for me,'' says Mazejka, 41.
``How can you not want to live in a town like this?''
</P>
<P>
   The list of what people did to help these families is long.
</P>
<P>
   Coll's parents bought most of the materials to redo his house,
while family and friends provided free labor. They regraded the
driveway and repaved it to make it less steep and less bumpy. They
added a porch, a ramp, and an interior foyer. They knocked down
walls, widened doorways, and renovated the kitchen and bathroom.
When the work was done and the house a mess, 20 women scrubbed it
clean by the time David and Kelly and their two children returned
from Colorado. When rain left Coll soaked before he could hoist
himself from wheelchair to truck, a crew built a garage for him.
The other day an electrician, more a friend of Coll's brother than
of Coll, wired the garage. Then there's the $30,000 raised to help
defray the family's expenses.
</P>
<P>
   For Mazejka, contractor William Harper juggled a hectic summer
workload so he could get the house ready for the family's
homecoming. That meant adding a wheelchair ramp out back,
converting the rear porch to a room, and redoing the bathroom, all
for about half what he normally charges. When Mazejka was
unconscious for two weeks and couldn't see her injured son and
daughter, restaurateur Michael Barlick, 34, and businessman Steven
Walker, 32, were at the hospital almost daily visiting the
children.
</P>
<P>
   At Sawyer's farm, help came in the form of a barn-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it's pulled the town together,'' says Women's
Club president Joanne Buck, 63. ``So many people came out of the
woodwork. The people that have been involved in these things, you
don't see them in the town office, out front on committees, and
getting their names in the paper. They're the silent people that
just do things when they need to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   They're Jaffrey natives and newcomers, cousins and friends and
friends of friends, people who bought cordwood from Coll or shopped
at his parents' farm stand or found comfort in the lone remaining
dairy farm.
</P>
<P>
   Norm and Beth Shepard helped because David Coll and Beth are
cousins, even though they weren't very close. ``I can't explain why
we were so hellbent on doing this. Maybe it was divine
intervention. We needed to give and they needed to receive,'' says
Beth Shepard, 38, who manages Coll's Garden Center. ``I miss the
closeness of working so hard. It was unbelievable what it did for
your heart and your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Visentin, 45, a service technician for a cable television
company who's lived in town only two years, was at Coll's house
many evenings and weekends because his neighbor, Norm Shepard, was
there and he likes Shepard. ``When somebody has misfortune,''
Visentin says, ``you thank God it didn't happen to you and look for
a way to help.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BINDING-GIFTS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-16 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINDING-GIFTS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 JAFFREY, N.H.: ... to help.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people who pitched in are busy people for whom time is hard
to come by, just as it is for any harried city dweller. Coll's
brother Mark, 39, and his wife, Lori, 35, are building a sugaring
business in addition to working the family farm.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Shepard, 41, not only works weekends at his contracting
business but he and his wife also cut their own wood and slaughter
their own meat. Walker was building a new plant for his company,
New England Wood Pellet, Inc., when he redid Mazejka's driveway and
visited the hospital. ``It was a little bit of a wild time,'' he
says. ``It was just necessary. What are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The people who received the help are busy people, too,
self-reliant New Englanders averse to asking for help and reluctant
to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want people to put themselves out again for me,''
says Sawyer, 61, who cut down the trees used to rebuild his barn.
``People kept saying we're having fun doing this. That made it
easier for an old Yankee to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning to take the help has been a big learning lesson,''
says Kelly Coll, office manager for her parents' trucking business.
``Not running myself ragged trying to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   You could probably ask and ask but never know if the generosity
seen here could only happen in a small town. But the interlocking
strands of Jaffrey's rough year are purely small town. Where else
would Norm Shepard see Sawyer's barn burning and spend the day
helping clear debris, then work on Coll's house at night? Where
else would Bruce Coll, 35, haul fill for Mazejka's yard and donate
trucks to carry rubble from Sawyer's farm and pitch in at his
cousin's house? Where else would David Coll, who years ago shoveled
silage when Sawyer's silo fell, stop by the farm the day of the
barn-raising and know, from the volunteers' faces, ``that it's as
good for them as for the people receiving?''
</P>
<P>
   Life is settling down now for those in Jaffrey who gave and for
those who received. Sawyer is limiting his farming to crops and
won't rebuild his dairy operation. Instead of working 70 hours a
week, David Coll spends a few hours a day at an outdoor wood
processor adapted for him and manages his logging business from
home, with help, sometimes, from the inspirational sayings
(``Choose to be happy,'' ``You can if you think you can'') on old
calendar pages his wife has tacked to his office wall. When he runs
into people in town, he's apt to take time to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel more connected,'' he says. ``People downtown, if they
have something to say, you'll spend the extra minute. Before, I had
to get going, trying to get as much done as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazejka is back at work part time as manager of commercial
lending at Fleet Bank in Keene, and both her children _ Zachary,
12, and Tina, 16 _ are walking unaided. She carries a poem her son
wrote with the line ``I feel filled with friends,'' and she is
making plans to give her wheelchair ramp to a relative of David
Coll's so one more house will be accessible to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have to drive by the mountains and the beach to say
this is why we live in New Hampshire,'' she says. ``I don't do that
any more. I just look at the people who live here.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Beth Shepard ran into Helen Coll, David's mother.
I miss those hugs we had every day, the niece told the aunt, and
the aunt, 61, said she did, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had giving fill me up as much as this did,'' says
Shepard. ``I was so full of love. It brought me a lot closer to the
Lord. It was a gift to be able to give in a way that was needed so
badly. Maybe that's what it is. I never was needed so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas,'' says Helen Coll, ``does bring thoughts of how
much we have received from other people and how can we give back.
It makes me think about the less fortunate who don't have money or
family or friends to fall back on. What happens to those people?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
