<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURIFIED BY OUR TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend I'll call Karen recently told me that she's been crying
a lot. I've known Karen my whole life and believe me, this is a
good thing. Karen's the nicest person you could ever hope to meet,
slow to anger, not bothered by the little things that usually upset
other people, but her demeanor is flat and controlled, as if she's
locked her deepest emotions in a box and buried them.
</P>
<P>
   Since she started therapy at the ripe old age of 51, her tears
have been brimming over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to work at learning to cry again,'' she confided.
``When I started therapy, the only way I could cry was to create a
group of imaginary friends in my head. It was like weeping at a
movie. I started crying about things I imagined happening to them,
but then I started letting myself cry about my own hurts, like a
friend forgetting my birthday. I even burst into tears in a
restaurant because my husband of 20 years wasn't holding my hand. I
knew it was foolish, but it's so hard for me to show neediness, so
hard to cry while I'm confused about what I feel, that I decided
not to hold back my emotions, whether they seemed justified or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this would upset people, but surprisingly it didn't.
I made clear to everyone that `something was taking its course'
inside me, and people accepted that. I thought my sadness would be
a burden to others, but my husband especially saw it as an
opportunity to grow emotionally himself. I've always taken care of
other people's needs. Now I'm working to let the people who love me
take care of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And something is taking its course,'' she explained. ``The
more I let my body do the crying _ weeping out loud instead of
holding back, letting the tears flow instead of just trickle down
my cheeks _ the more I've come to accept the validity of my pain.
I'm not a hypersensitive woman overreacting to trivial slights. It
isn't even the adult I am now who's crying as if her heart would
break. I'm expressing the grief I felt as a child, shedding
9-year-old tears about afternoons home alone and childhood
betrayals I never mourned. That grief intensified every year I kept
it pent up inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. I know it sounds like I should be miserable, but
crying my heart out is much less painful than scrunching the tears
down into the pit of my stomach. Strange as it sounds, the more I
cry, the less it hurts. It's like I've spent my life struggling
over a piano lesson, memorizing the music, and painfully banging
out the notes. Now I've just given myself over to the spirit of the
piece, and it's flowing out so effortlessly and so copiously that
I'm hardly aware of feeling pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen's words made perfect sense to me. I could remember a
period about 20 years ago when I'd been deep in therapy myself. I'd
followed the sun around our living room like a cat, finding a
comfortable spot to drink wine and listen to folk singer Don McLean
sing about a friend's suicide on the stereo while tears streamed
out of my eyes, day after day. I'd ignored my own lifelong sadness
for years myself, afraid it would overwhelm me, only to discover
what a great relief it was to finally let it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was satisfied just to be able to express my feelings,''
Karen said with a note of pride in her voice. ``You can't imagine
how much better it is to feel sad than to feel nothing. But now a
new feeling has come back. In between the cries, I'm happy, and
that resonates with the past, too. I'm childishly happy, like a
little girl skipping down a sidewalk. I haven't felt this buoyant
since I was 9 years old. I'm working on expressing that part of me,
too. Last night I burst into song at the kitchen table.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it make sense to reenter the closet where painful memories
are stored and reclaim the unbearable feelings that accompanied
them? This is what Karen has discovered to be true: The adult she
has become can bear feelings that were overwhelming to her as a
child.
</P>
<P>
   When you think of gifts of the spirit, what could be more
generous than to no longer hold innocent people and unintended
slights responsible for pain whose source extends far into the
past? In this season of joy to the world, what casts a brighter
light than your own spontaneous happiness set free from years of
emotional anesthesia?
</P>
<P>
   This is what drives many of us to confront the past: the hope
that courageously facing the truth will enable us at last to
experience great pain and great pleasure with awareness,
acceptance, intensity, and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
