<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2TAKES-     12-16 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS CAN TURN OVER SOME NEW LEAVES WITH GARDENING BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas gift books are the best read of the year because they
help gardeners get through the excruciating indoor months of
winter. All the obvious garden books have already been written, so
this has been a year for bold sorts that expand the genre with
fierce rage and gentle whimsy. There are also books that take
readers back in time to ancient China or the American Revolution,
as the new field of garden history continues to blossom. And, as
always, there are paeans to plants, plants, and more plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Essays &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My Garden (Book),'' by Jamaica Kincaid (Farrar, Straus and
Giroux, $23). Kincaid's collection of essays is self-indulgent and
doesn't tell you much about plants, but instead dives into the
feelings gardening evokes in Kincaid (and many of the rest of us),
especially the obsession, envy, and discontent that mark this as a
passion, not a hobby. Kincaid's fierce writing style, powered by
incantational rhythms and repetitions, challenges the conventions
of garden literature the way gospel rocked the Protestant hymnal.
With undercurrents of rage and revolt, Kincaid, a descendant of
Antiguan slaves, lobs hand grenades at a genre long modeled on the
wit and understatement of ruling-class snobbery. Of one trip to a
famous English garden, Kincaid writes: ``when I saw Gravetye, it
was an Eden I loved so much, one from which I could not wait to
escape. Gravetye is now an ideal luxurious inn; I had a delicious
lunch in the dining room, and while eating I was struck with the
desire to behead all of my fellow diners.'' Kincaid's a major
writer, and her appearance in the garden book section adds an
astonishing voice to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Style &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Garden Whimsy,'' by Tovah Martin and Richard W. Brown
(Houghton Mifflin/Francis Tennenbaum, $30). Most garden art that
reaches for humor is really so dumb and ugly that it scares
gardeners into playing it straight. So when the team that brought
us the best-selling ``Tasha Tudor's Garden'' went on the hunt for
horticultural levity, its challenge was to find garden features
that could, like actress Cameron Diaz, make us laugh while still
looking enchanting. Here whimsy is presented as the more comely and
well-heeled sister of funkiness. Sculpture groups, such as a band
of patinaed frogs playing jazz or a trio of stone figures as round
as the Pillsbury Doughboy, look like expensive commissions. Martin
does a deft job of laying out the book's simple premise (gardeners
need to lighten up) and then holding it all together with
mischievous anecdotes and essays. A few of the photos lack punch,
but sometimes Brown just nails it, as with the shot of
choreographer Moses Pendleton's creepy crone scarecrow commanding
obeisance from a ring of bowing sunflowers, or the cover picture of
a prom-queen scarecrow, armless and white as the Venus de Milo,
wearing an old strapless chiffon  &UR; evening &LR;  gown in flamingo pink,
seemingly the signature color of garden whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designing With Plants,'' by Piet Oudolf (Timber Press, $35).
This visionary Dutch nurseryman is a founder of the ``New Wave''
planting style for perennials that has inspired a whole school of
northern European designers. Whereas the still-dominant English
perennial border that Gertrude Jekyll pioneered almost a century
ago is based largely on color, Oudolf's revolutionary perennial
plantings dismiss color as a ``secondary consideration'' and focus
instead on the structure of plants, whether in or out of bloom. The
result is gardens of architectural foliage and seedheads, well
illustrated here, that create moods rather than images, and that
change with the seasons but maintain their fascination for most of
the year. This important book could be a revelation to serious
perennial aficionados who despair of trying to maintain constant
color in their gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish Gardens,'' by Olda FitzGerald (Hearst Books, $40). This
beautifully photographed tour of 20 Irish gardens, conducted by one
of the owners, wife of the knight of Glin, introduces the oxymoron
of the wild estate garden. These once formal landscapes started out
on the English model. But thanks to a climate that encourages more
rampant growth, access to generally more limited funds, and an
embrace of passionate disorder as a form of beauty, they evolved
into something quite different. This is a book to whet the appetite
for travel. Details are given for visiting each of the gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of the Kitchen Garden,'' by Jan and Michael Gertley
(Taunton Books, $30). Ornamental vegetable gardens are in vogue
these days, and for perfectionists who adore Martha Stewart, this
book offers the last word in garden craft projects. Just make sure
your giftee is an experienced vegetable gardener who grows plants
from seed and has an itch to show off. The patterns in this book
range from intricate rosettes to stars and Celtic ornaments, all
rendered in cabbages, beets, lettuces, parsley, colored Swiss
chards, and other edibles springing from the earth. Each
``potager'' can be adjusted to any size plot, but you must have a
vantage point such as a deck or terrace that will allow you and
your very impressed friends to look down on the garden. Each garden
here was photographed from a camera hoisted 40 feet above it to
reveal its symmetrical patterns, but you can hardly do that to
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garden history &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Traditional Garden: A Practical Guide to Creating and
Restoring Authentic American Gardens for Homes of All Ages,'' by
Michael Weishan (Ballantine Books, $35). They've lovingly restored
every doorknob in their old house. Now bringing the land around
their antique home back into period is only common sense _ and the
year's hottest gardening trend. Editor of the successful niche
newsletter Traditional Gardener, local author Weishan will continue
to win converts with this book. He's an opinionated pragmatist who
shares hints on how to add an appropriate old-time flavor to a yard
without being a slave to period accuracy or archival research. This
is a user-friendly and extremely enthusiastic once-over-lightly
introduction to garden history on a personal scale, full of
anecdotes and breezy sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gardens of William Morris,'' by Jill, duchess of Hamilton,
Penny Hart, and John Simmons (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $35). This
book is more about Morris, the best-known British founder of the
Arts &AMP; Crafts movement, than about his philosophy of garden design,
which was prescient but hardly a major focus in his prodigious
life. Like all the Pre-Raphaelites, he was smitten by idealized
images of the Middle Ages. Medieval gardens were the template for
his resurrection in the 1860s of the concept of formal ``garden
rooms'' outlined in woven wattle. He was also a champion of cottage
gardening with native plants. This is a pretty book for those who
love the interplay between romantic decorating and gardening,
especially when it contrasts Morris's famous wallpaper designs with
photos of the plants that inspired them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... inspired them.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Washington's Gardens at Mount Vernon: Landscape of the Inner
Man,'' by Mac Griswold, photographed by Roger Foley (Houghton
Mifflin/Francis Tennenbaum, $40). This is a double portrait of
Mount Vernon and the man who created it. The gardens are, of
course, beautifully preserved, but more intriguing is the bold way
historian Griswold uses them and historical sources to examine the
real George Washington behind the icon, through his unguarded
devotion to his land. She shows us a landscape with flourishes
designed by a surprisingly theatrical leader, with views created to
be quickly glimpsed since the owner himself was always in motion.
During the Revolution we find a general who is cheered by planning
future garden improvements to Mount Vernon when news from the
battlefield is grim. And in the end we have met a man who never
quit until he reached his goals and who left at Mount Vernon a
completed vision. This is American garden history at its best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plants &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Garden Plants of China,'' by Peter Valder (Timber Press, $50).
Since China opened to visitors, the focus of gardeners has been the
stream of wild plants from remote areas being introduced into the
nursery trade. But this noted Australian horticulturalist runs
counter to the trend by cataloging known Chinese ornamental garden
plants, and in the process creating a reference work unique in the
English language. Most fascinating are Valder's introductory
essays, which tell us, for instance, that the Chinese traditionally
restricted ornamentals to the relative few that had acquired
symbolism through their appearance in philosophy, poetry, and art,
while more beautiful plants often went uncultivated for lack of
cultural associations. (This is one reason for the current wave of
plant explorers.) Valder gives us a window on a sophisticated
garden ethic very different from Europe's, and an encyclopedia of
more than 400 Chinese garden plants. Many will inevitably become
more widely seen here because of their natural resistance to pests
and diseases now arriving from Asia via global trade. Valder uses
English names, Latin names, and Chinese names, both in characters
and romanized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rare Orchids,'' by Bela Kalman, text by Rodalie Davis and
Mariko Kawaguchi (Little, Brown/Bulfinch Press, $45). This hypnotic
page-turner will cast a spell over anyone susceptible to the beauty
of living things, even nongardeners. Some flowers can compare with
orchids for loveliness, but none can for diversity. The mesmerizing
thing about the 140 orchids captured in color-saturated intimacy by
Boston photographer Kalman is that they find so many different ways
to be beautiful. In addition to moth orchids that look like moths
and lady's slippers that look like slippers, there are translucent
yellow-green stars, orange macaroni, and Holy Ghost orchids that
look like tiny doves. Each plant is loaded with attitude, and no
matter how different they are, each has a fleshy mystique that
identifies it as an orchid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treasured Perennials,'' by Graham Stuart Thomas (Sagapress,
$40). At age 90, Thomas is himself treasured as one of the most
knowledgeable and erudite garden writers in England. His legacy
includes increased popular interest in antique roses, ground
covers, and foliage plants. In this rather slight volume he picks
about 200 of his favorite perennials, ferns, and ornamental
grasses, obviously a fraction of what he's grown over a long
lifetime. Most of these plants are pretty obscure, though it's
illuminating to hear the master laud common wildflowers like false
Solomon's seal (Smilacina racemosa) and sweet rocket (Hesperis
matronalis) that we take for granted. The index gives hardiness
zones, but you're on your own for locating sources. This book will
be welcomed by plant connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perennial Combinations,'' by C. Colston Burrell (Rodale Press,
$30). The art of gardening is in composing attractive combinations
of plants. This is the year's most helpful book on the subject,
which is trickier than it sounds because plants that would
theoretically look good together can require different growing
conditions or bloom at different times. Most of Burrell's photos
are keyed so you really know which plant is which, and are
accompanied by growing tips. A Virginia garden designer, Burrell
has put together many useful categories of combinations. This book
is a safe gift for beginners because it covers the basics and will
not frustrate them with impossible visions, as will English garden
books on the same subject that feature plants lacking hardiness or
availability here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discovering Annuals,'' by Graham Rice (Timber Press, $35).
Annual flowers have long been tainted by association with gaudy
bedding schemes. Besides, most American gardeners don't like to
grow plants from seed. So perennials have gripped our attention,
while the wide world of annuals has gone largely unexamined. This
handsome, well-written book is a first-rate introduction to both
annuals and biennials (which bloom the second year from seed). It's
also discriminating enough to interest people who have been growing
them all their lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Landscape Architecture &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Guide to the Landscape Architecture of Boston,'' by Jack
Ahern (Hubbard Educational Trust, $20). This book is an unusual mix
of past, present, and future. Pocket-size but richly illustrated,
it contains locations and very brief descriptions of 193 selected
landscape projects in metropolitan Boston and the North Shore. Some
sites, such as the Olmsted-designed Moraine Farm in Beverly, are
the kind of hidden historic gems you expect in a guidebook. But
many, like the New Charles River Basin, haven't been built yet.
This is either a visionary book or one with a short shelf life,
depending on how many of these projects are realized according to
plan. Meanwhile, a flip through these pages will convince you that
there is a lot of open space on the table right now, making this
the most active era in the sculpting of Boston's landscape in 100
years. We hope it goes well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
