<SLUG> BC-HOME-BOOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN BOOKS OFFER WORLDS TO EXPLORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's design books cover topics from historical furniture
to Indian interiors to how to marry light and color in your rooms.
They range from the scholarly to the silly. Terence Riley's ``The
Un-Private House'' (Abrams, $29.95) may strike some people as both.
Museum of Modern Art curator Riley documents 26 houses, worldwide,
that are Brave New World: glass walls; no walls; no walls even in
the bathroom; a computer in every room. It's the most provocative
design tome this year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Patricia Bayer's ``Art Deco Architecture: Design,
Decoration and Detail From the Twenties and Thirties'' (Thames &AMP;
Hudson, $29.95) is downright nostalgic. Here are homes with
luxury-liner lines and Mayan Revival details; urban facades adorned
with friezes of noble agricultural workers; cocktail shakers that
look like skyscrapers and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   For a dive deeper into history, consider ``A Renaissance
Treasury: The Flagg Collection of European Decorative Arts and
Sculpture'' (Hudson Hills, $50) by Laurie Winters. The collection,
which is housed at the Milwaukee Art Museum, includes such delights
as clocks in the form of a camel and a tabernacle, a door knocker
shaped like a lion, and a lock depicting St. Michael slaying the
dragon, hinting that death would likewise be the fate of an
intruder.
</P>
<P>
   For a record of a decorative arts collection of more recent
vintage, see ``The Art of Craft: Contemporary Works From the Saxe
Collection'' (Bulfinch, $50), by Timothy Anglin Burgard, an
imaginative curator who used to work at Harvard and is now at the
Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco, future home of the crafts that
Dorothy and George Saxe have amassed over the past two decades.
Burgard's essay is as entertaining as it is enlightening; he
gracefully connects contemporary American artists with those of
long ago and far away. And because the Saxes don't distinguish
between high art and low, ``fine'' artists like Kiki Smith and
Christopher Wilmarth are also included in their collection and
Burgard's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   For a book where ideas, not pretty pictures, are the point,
there's Richard Hill's ``Designs and Their Consequences:
Architecture and Aesthetics'' (Yale, $30), a scholarly examination
of the relationship between theory and real buildings, concluding
with an evaluation of modernism's aim of tying form to function.
</P>
<P>
   The season's most unusual design book is Elizabeth Smith
Brownstein's ``If This House Could Talk: Historic Homes,
Extraordinary Americans'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35), which weaves
together the stories of notable Americans and their houses, from
Abraham Lincoln to Frank Lloyd Wright. The New Englanders
represented include the predictable _ Robert Frost, John Quincy
Adams _ and the unexpected. In the latter category are Rebecca
Nurse, 17th-century victim of Salem's witchcraft hysteria, and
writer Edward Gorey, whose expanded Cape in Yarmouth Port, Mass.
Brownstein cheerfully describes as ``decaying, peeling and
dilapidated.'' Explains its owner, with equal cheer, ``Life is
basically ghastly.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very beginning of the 20th century, Gustav Stickley
started making furniture that is still prized at century's end.
Victorian fuss was on the wane when Stickley stepped in, becoming a
leader of the Arts &AMP; Crafts movement that advocated simplicity of
line and truth to materials. He built a lifestyle around those
beliefs and published books and magazines to disseminate them. In
``Stickley Style'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $40), writer David Cathers
ably chronicles his career. But it's Alexander Vertikoff's
masterful color photographs of interiors filled with rectilinear
oak furniture and jewel-toned tiles that are the book's chief lure.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that a good number of the makers featured in
``Furniture Studio: The Heart of the Functional Arts'' (the
Furniture Society, $30) hail from New England. This region is a
leader in the American studio furniture movement _ a leader even on
a global scale. (British furniture maker David Linley gets more
international press than anyone in the United States, though: It
helps to have an aunt who's the queen.) The book, intended as the
first in a series, includes essays both philosophical and
practical, gorgeous photographs of adventurous work, and chapters
on where to find it and how to commission it.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent _ and puckish _ New England furniture artist has a
book all to himself this year. In ``Two Looks to Home: The Art of
Tommy Simpson'' (Bulfinch, $50), Connecticut-based Simpson writes
about the influence that growing up in a small Midwestern town had
on his fantasy furniture, where columns and caryatids can serve as
spindles on a Windsor chair that also sprouts wings. And mittens.
And a flower and a snake.
</P>
<P>
   What New England is to one-of-a-kind handmade furniture the
Pacific Northwest is to glass. And, say what you want about him _
that he hasn't tackled the tough technical stuff himself for years,
that his workers turn out endless clones of his most popular pieces
_ Dale Chihuly is king of the field. In a newly expanded edition of
``Chihuly'' (Abrams, $75), the distinguished critic Donald Kuspit
analyzes the artist's explosive, fluid glass forms, and recent
gargantuan glass installations.
</P>
<P>
   In their sumptuous and surprising ``Indian Interiors'' (Taschen,
$39.99), writer Sunil Sethi and photographer Deidi von Schaewen go
from mud huts to maharajas' palaces. The constants are vivid, even
clashing, colors and the impulse, no matter what the rank or
resources of the homeowner, to adorn every last inch of every last
wall. A posh lakeside houseboat is one of the showstoppers, filled
with carved wooden walls and ceilings and softened by acres of
crewel embroidery. Abundant use of lacy, pierced wood keeps the
boat's rooms light and airy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color is light made visible,'' writes Donald Kaufman, who,
with fellow color consultant Taffy Dahl, authored ``Color and
Light: Luminous Atmospheres for Painted Rooms'' (Crown, $50). The
book is the result of their travels across the country to advise
people on what hues to paint their walls, recommendations based on
the time of day the room will get the most use and the differences,
say, between the clear, warm light of Santa Fe and the gray murk of
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   People passionate about their art also tend to be picky about
its setting, whether it be a minimalist interior, where what's on
the walls is the only focus, or surroundings of baroque exuberance,
where the art has to compete. The range is explored in ``At Home
With Art: How Art Lovers Live With and Care for Their Treasures''
(Potter, $50), by Estelle Ellis, Caroline Seebohm, and Christopher
Simon Sykes. The authors allow you to play the voyeur, peeking into
the homes of major collector couples including Agnes Gund and
Daniel Shapiro, and creative types like playwright Edward Albee,
who, in the entrance of his Manhattan loft, mixes part of a
Philippine pygmy hut with a Biedermeier chest and Lipchitz
painting. Boston is represented in the book by John Axelrod, whose
Back Bay condo is filled with art from California funk ceramics to
the South American painting he champions.
</P>
<P>
   The antique Oriental carpet is a subject that mystifies many
Westerners. Enza Milanesi's ``The Carpet: Origins, Art and
History'' (Firefly, $50) offers an in-depth study of the origins of
this ever-popular form of textile that seems to harmonize with
almost any decor. Milanesi, a Rome-based art historian, explains
the making of carpets, the meanings of their symbolic designs, and
the milieus in which they were created. Best of all, the book
boasts a wealth of color photographs that show exactly what she's
talking about, as well as a list of museums in the United States
and abroad with stellar examples of carpets in their collections.
</P>
<P>
   John Morley's ``The History of Furniture'' (Bulfinch, $75) is
almost as all-encompassing as the title suggests. The former Keeper
of Furniture and Interior Design at the Victoria and Albert Museum
in London, Morley has produced an engrossing study of the
development of style, starting with King Tutankhamen's surprisingly
modern-looking ceremonial chair, a design dating from circa 1320
BC. He traces Asian and African influences on Western furniture,
and tracks enduring idioms like the Gothic, which has reappeared
periodically since its 12th-century debut. The framework for his
nimble arguments is contrasts: classical vs. romantic; order vs.
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms have always been decorated, of course. But the profession
of interior designer _ as distinct from, say, architect, fresco
painter, or ebeniste _ is largely a phenomenon of the 1900s. In
``Influential Interiors: Shaping 20th Century Style Through Key
Interior Designers'' (Potter, $45), Suzanne Trocme looks at key
figures in the field, from Elsie de Wolfe to Philippe Starck, and
examines major ``looks'' from English country house to
son-of-Art-Nouveau to the all-purpose ``eclectic.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child of the '60s, I'm not sure I want to relive them. Op
Art still gives me a hangover. Nonetheless, Cara Greenberg's ``Op
to Pop: Furniture of the 1960s'' (Bulfinch, $40) is fun. Chairs
made of molded plastic, tubular steel, or giant bean bags, shaped
like Marilyn's lips or toadstools, filling rooms with undulating
walls: These were staples of a decade when the revolutionary home
looked like either a spaceship or a cave. Greenberg discusses
experiments of the era including Bloomingdale's adventurous model
rooms, and designers from the somber Scandinavians to the impish
Frank Gehry. Turns out she's a Flower Child herself: There's a
photo of her taking a dip in the reflecting pool of the Washington
Monument during a '60s protest march. She rightly notes that few
Americans of the time actually came into contact with radical
furniture. ``Most of it was simply too avant-garde to have found
its way into American homes,'' she writes. Should you want it to
find its way into yours belatedly, she's included a handy list of
sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
