<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 1853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTHING STEPFAMILY GATHERINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When two adults with children from previous marriages try to
make Christmaswork under one roof, expect the worst.
</P>
<P>
   As pessimistic as that may sound, it can actually be a positive
coping skill. Professionals who work with stepfamilies say any
holiday, but especially a big one like Christmas, can be so
stressful that it's better to keep expectations low, lest hurt and
resentment build.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often what works best is not at all what you had in mind,''
says psychologist Patricia Papernow, a stepfamily researcher in
Cambridge, Mass. and author of ``Becoming a Stepfamily''
(Analytic).
</P>
<P>
   No new couple imagines separating on Christmas, for instance,
with you heading off to your parents with your child and your
spouse to hers with her children. That feels bad, as if you're
coming apart rather than together. But that just may be what you
need to do first, says Papernow.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the matter is that it's not just adults who have
memories and fantasies. ``The holidays are full of moments that
hold loss, even for young children,'' says family therapist Judy
Osborne, director of Stepfamily Associates in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, children typically can't or don't label or talk
about feelings. Their sadness comes out as resentment and anger and
translates to behaviors that make holidays messy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pent-up anxiety &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michele Rogers, for instance, who is 12 and lives in Framingham,
Mass. with her father and stepmother, is normally cheerful and
cooperative. But her mother and sister, Kim, live in Colorado, and
she's been hoping since the summer that Kim will come east for
Christmas. She doesn't talk about it, says her father, Bob Rogers,
but he can tell it's on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's cranky and frustrated. Quick to talk back,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Whether hurts are big or small, spoken or not, children need to
get issues out in the open and know that any feelings are OK to
have, says Osborne. Rogers and his wife, Ann-Marie, try to do that
with Michele, but they walk a fine line: They want to offer empathy
but not foster false hope. Says Ann-Marie, ``I told her the other
day, `It's gonna stink for you, isn't it, if she doesn't come?' I
know that's how she feels and I want her to know we know how
important it is to her.''
</P>
<P>
   As tough as it can be, at least the Rogerses know exactly what's
bothering Michele. Many parents and stepparents field moodiness and
angry outbursts without a clue as to what's fueling them. When in
doubt, says Osborne, assume it's feelings of disloyalty. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   --It's time to go to church and your 5-year-old son won't get
into the car with his stepsiblings. ``Maybe he's remembering the
years when it was just the two of you and he sat in front,'' says
Osborne. Translate his behavior to: ``I feel betrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   --It's your first Christmas with your 7-year-old stepdaughter
and you're cooking up a storm when she becomes mean and pouty.
Translation: ``She's trying to outdo my mom!''
</P>
<P>
   --Although you've gone to your husband's sister's family for
three years since you married, your 9-year-old suddenly is refusing
to go. Translation: ``I really like it there.'' In other words,
says Osborne, the more comfortable she feels with extended
stepfamily, the more disloyal she feels to her other parent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cutting to the nub &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As irrational as some of these thoughts may seem, they are real
to a child. Ignoring them makes things worse, not better. Cutting
to the nub _ ``Does your mom make holiday cookies, too?'' _ may or
may not get her talking. But dealing with the surface issue _ ``It
hurts my feelings when you talk to me like that'' _ will only fuel
her resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when a child experiences disappointment, don't brush
it off. ``Acknowledge it,'' says stepfamily researcher and lecturer
Margorie Engel, president of the Stepfamily Association of America.
Better to say ``I'm sorry your dad didn't send a gift; I know that
hurts'' than to make excuses _ ``He probably didn't know what size
you are now'' _ or pretend it's not a big deal: ``Look at all the
other great gifts you got!'' Whatever you do, she says, don't
bad-mouth the other parent or family.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointments or eruptions in the middle of your celebration
are dreadful; there's nothing like a miserable child to cast a pall
over the day for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Papernow remembers her own first Christmas with her now-adult
stepdaughter, Pam, who was 9 at the time. ``We'd spent lots of time
negotiating in advance about her traditions and mine, and I thought
everything was worked out,'' she says. ``Halfway through opening
presents, she burst into tears and ran upstairs. Turns out,'' says
Papernow, ``I'm a person who likes to open one gift at a time, get
a cup of coffee, open another gift. She's a person who likes
everyone to open presents until they're all done. By my third cup,
she was over the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you've expressed empathy and offered an ear, Papernow
advises, give a child permission to take some time alone, and
suggest she rejoin you after she regroups. If she returns and
continues to be miserable, it's OK to set a limit: ``This is still
Christmas for us. If you can't be pleasant, it's better for you to
stay in your room.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Typical letdowns &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most common sources of disappointment are also two of
the trickiest for parents to deal with:
</P>
<P>
   --Unequal treatment from steprelatives. It's not unusual for
grandparents to lavish gifts on their biological grandchild and
ignore their new stepgrandchild. What's worse is if they indulge a
baby who is the half sibling of the stepgrandchild. For a child who
already feels left out, inferior, and/or abandoned, this is an
awful blow, says Papernow. She urges relatives to give equally to
all children even if you don't feel equally about them, even if you
haven't met them. She also tells parents to work to eliminate
disparate treatment, including defraying costs for grandparents. If
unequal treatment occurs anyway, talk about it, even with
preschoolers: ``Grandma and Grandpa are having trouble
understanding how our new family works. We need to help them.''
Unequal treatment that continues into a second or third year is
significant enough to allow you to temporarily disassociate
yourselves from a family celebration, says Papernow.
</P>
<P>
   --Time spent with one family is time away from the other. For a
child with two families, there is sadness at having to leave one to
be with the other, no matter how much she loves those people, too,
says marriage and family therapist Taube Kaufman of Chapel Hill,
N.C. There's also a scary thought as she leaves each home _ ``What
am I missing?'' _ and another one when she returns: ``Will I still
fit in?'' The more frequently she makes the transition, the less
worry there is, but at holidays it increases for any child going to
either home. If there are issues at one house, from a new baby he
loves to a stepsibling he hates, expect transitions to be off the
scale in difficulty. Then you can be that much more pleased if they
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman tells parents to build in half an hour to a day of
transition time, depending on familiarity. ``Don't schedule them so
tightly they have to rush off to an event 15 minutes later,'' she
says. Also don't expect them to be warm and loving or even social
when they first arrive; many kids need time to decompress by
themselves in the new space. Kaufman is author of ``The Combined
Family: A Guide to Creating Successful Step Relationships''
(Plenum). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Common concerns &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume, either, that the huge, overarching issue for you _
understanding how this new family works _ isn't also a big issue
for your child. It is for Nathaniel Richman, but his mother, Robin
Hanley, found out only inadvertently.
</P>
<P>
   It happened just after their first Christmas, four years ago.
Because Nathaniel and Robin are Jewish and her husband Dean and his
daughter, Felicity, also 12, are Catholic, this was Nathaniel's
first tree. The buildup was immense. But on Christmas, Felicity was
with her mom and Nathaniel was sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me, `Do you want to know my idea of a perfect
Christmas?' '' Robin says. ``He told me it would be to spend it
with everyone he loves: his dad and stepmom, Felicity and her mom,
and me and Dean.''
</P>
<P>
   For Robin, it was a poignant moment. ``He realized how
complicated the concept of family had become,'' says his mom. ``All
the people he loved couldn't be together on a holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Suggestions for stepparents &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Before a stepfamily's first holiday together, ask each child,
regardless of age, the best thing about previous celebrations. Get
specific: favorite food to favorite song. Then help them narrow the
list down to the top three or four priorities they'd like to see
included in this year's get-together. Be clear that your
celebration will be respectful of their wishes but that final
decisions belong to the adults.
</P>
<P>
   --Remember that familiar food can be critical to a child's
comfort level.
</P>
<P>
   --Rather than re-create old rituals, create new ones together.
</P>
<P>
   --A good answer when they're unhappy about something: ``This is
how we're making this new family work right now, for this holiday.
Next year, we can rethink it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Hold a review afterward: What should we do again next year?
Take copious notes, including ones about who liked what, so that
when you make changes, they aren't only the ones Nancy asked for.
Repeat this process every year; it can become a ritual in itself.
</P>
<P>
   --Before your child leaves for his other parent's, give him
permission to enjoy himself: ``I hope you will have a good time.
I'm going to, too. Afterward, we'll share our stories.''
</P>
<P>
   --Keep in mind that it can take four years for a stepfamily's
holiday celebration to feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   --Be flexible with teens who do not want to be part of an
extended stepfamily meal: ``Being part of this family means you
show up and you're civil. But you only have to stay an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   --Help children choose or make gifts for stepgrandparents.
</P>
<P>
   --If you're a father who has remarried, sign the card on your
child's gift even if your wife buys and wraps it. Otherwise, he
feels abandoned: ``Dad didn't even do my gift this year.''
</P>
<P>
   --If a child is spending part of a holiday with steprelatives
she doesn't know, details help her cope, including knowing the menu
and seeing photos of people ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   --Stepfamily Associates has a Web site with holiday tips:
www.stepfamilyboston.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ For advice about choosing toys for children with
disabilities, call the Lekotek Toy Resource Hotline at
800-366-7529. Also, the American Foundation for the Blind offers a
free ``Guide to Toys for Children Who Are Blind or Visually
Impaired.'' Write the American Toy Institute, 1115 Broadway, Suite
400, New York, NY 10010.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
