<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TRAVEL-$ADV18     12-16 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TRAVEL-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM ARMAGEDDON TO CABLE CARS, MILLENNIUM SITES READIED
 &HT;    (Contains optional trim.)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-AGENTS-$ADV18.
 &HT;    EDs: With box information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International, (l) Lifestyle and (t) Travel
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Dec. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEGIDDO, Israel _ The world might be coming to an end, but at
least you'll have a place to park.
</P>
<P>
   At the archeological site of Megiddo, known in the New Testament
as Armageddon, Israeli park authorities are adding a reserve
parking lot for the influx of visitors expected in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the hill-top dig overlooks a wide valley where,
according to the Book of Revelations, the final battle before
Judgement Day will be fought. Many believe that comes shortly after
the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Megiddo's ruin-with-a-view already hosts 250,000 people annually
and officials expect that to double next year.
</P>
<P>
   With similar projections for other biblical locations,
especially along the path of Jesus Christ, improvements are being
made throughout the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   At many sites, jack-hammers still pound away. Both Palestinian
and Israeli officials acknowledge, and are criticized for, their
late start. Many attractions and hotels and new roads will not be
ready until mid-year.
</P>
<P>
   But, once pilgrims fight through the traffic jams and long
lines, they will see enhancements at the places where biblical
beliefs meet the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Near Jericho, there are new cable cars scaling the mountain
believed to be the Mount of Temptation. In Bethlehem, there is a
massive overhaul of Manger Square. On the Sea of Galilee, Israel is
adding new boat piers. In Nazareth, there will be new roads,
tourist routes and plazas.
</P>
<P>
   Here, at Megiddo (pronounced, 'mi-GEE-doh'), a national park in
central Israel, the new parking compliments two new platforms for
prayer among the excavations. The park already had a small museum,
restaurant and souvenir shop _ with guidebooks, videos and Megiddo
ball caps.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Cathers, an evangelical pastor from near Lexington, Ky.,
visited with parishioners recently for his fourth time. He said he
believes the biblical prophecy will play out in the battle in the
valley in ``a matter of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Visits to Megiddo and other sites, he said, bring the scriptures
to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have video to go with the audio,'' Cathers said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the best video will not come until the end of the
year. Park officials plan a wide-screen show that will super-impose
images from different ages on a view of the actual ruins.
</P>
<P>
   For now, according to planning director Ze'ev Margalit, the
parks authority is making sure it can handle the crowds. Margalit
said they can handle a half-million visitors a year for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' he said. ``We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, the largest renovations are taking place at the
key site of the millennium, Christ's birthplace of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   About five miles south of Jerusalem, Bethlehem was transferred
from Israeli to Palestinian control in 1995. It had become a
chaotic city of 150,000, overcome by refugee camps, and lacking
suitable roads and sewage.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors long chafed at the noisy bus parking lot in front of
the massive stone Church of the Nativity, which stands over the
traditional site of Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   In an $8.5 million project paid for with Swedish aid money, the
parking lot has been removed and replaced with a tidy stone,
tree-lined piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Near the church on Manger Square, an ugly prison left over from
British and Israeli rule was destroyed and replaced with a ``Peace
Center.'' It will offer a nativity museum, displays on the history
of Bethlehem and a tourist information center.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials have used the millennium to launch an
overall renewal of the biblical city. The rutted streets of the old
quarters near the church have new stones and sewage systems. A
Christmas Market, offering crafts and souvenirs opened this week.
</P>
<P>
   The new sites now offer a full day's activities for pilgrims,
who frequently come just to visit the church and leave.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has several new hotels, including a five-star
Inter-Continental Hotel built around a restored palace.
</P>
<P>
   The work is being done through foreign donations and loans of
$86 million and private, mostly Palestinian investment, of another
$110 million.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The second-most striking new construction in the Palestinian
territories is a new, $10 million cable car, shopping and hotel
complex in Jericho.
</P>
<P>
   A private venture, the cable cars soar at over 210 feet above
date palm orchards and an excavation site of the 8,000-year-old Tel
es-Sultan tower.
</P>
<P>
   They climb midway up the Mount of Temptation, where the Devil
tried to tempt Christ. Nearby is a Greek Orthodox monastery.
</P>
<P>
   At the cable cars' mountainside perch is a French restaurant and
small caves. At the ground level take-off point is another
restaurant, a mini-mall with 16 souvenir stores and a soon-to-open
55-room hotel.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, the city of Nazareth is getting the biggest makeover,
which has been going on for about three years at a cost of $55
million. Roads and plazas are being upgraded and an illuminated
nighttime walk is being made for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sea of Galilee, a new promenade is being paved along the
seashore and piers are being added for the ancient-style wooden
boats that give pilgrims a trip on the water.
</P>
<P>
   But, the government may not be able to make one important
alteration that initially seemed easy.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Israeli officials have wanted to install
an emergency exit in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, which most
Christians believe is the site of Christ's crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   But, the six denominations that control parts of the cavernous
church cannot agree on a location.
</P>
<P>
   BOX: Cable Cars, Piers and Nativity Museums on Millennium Trail
</P>
<P>
   With 3.2 million visitors expected for the year 2000, Israeli
and Palestinian officials are remaking many of the Holy Land's
sites. Here are some of the new attractions completed or coming:
</P>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM:
</P>
<P>
   Peace Center with Nativity Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Stone piazza at the Church of the Nativity.
</P>
<P>
   Remodeled old city.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Market for crafts.
</P>
<P>
   NAZARETH:
</P>
<P>
   Illuminated tourist routes.
</P>
<P>
   New piazza and old city renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooks on biblical Mount of Precipice
</P>
<P>
   JERICHO:
</P>
<P>
   Cable car and shopping complex at Mount of Temptation
</P>
<P>
   SEA OF GALILEE:
</P>
<P>
   New pier for ancient-styled wooden boats.
</P>
<P>
   Display of restored 2,000-year-old boat, Kibbutz Genosar.
</P>
<P>
   Seashore promenade at Capernaum.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Bethlehem 2000, Telepherique and Sultan Tourist Center,
Jericho and Israeli Ministry of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
