<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MIDEAST-AGENTS-$ADV18     12-16 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-AGENTS-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEACE AT MILLENNIUM A CHANCE FOR TOURIST COOPERATION
 &HT;    (With optional trim.)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-TRAVEL-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International, (l) Lifestyle and (t) Travel
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Dec. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ It took peace talks and expectations of a million
extra visitors in 2000 for the first joint Israeli-Palestinian tour
agency to be born.
</P>
<P>
   IPP Tours formed out of the age-old motive for profit and market
maximization.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, American tourists have booked heavily with
Israeli firms, Europeans more likely to go with a Palestinian
company.
</P>
<P>
   IPP officials, who ran other travel firms on their own sides of
the cultural divide, said the recent re-opening of peace talks
between Israel and the Palestinians made the climate right to merge
talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the millennium will give us the advantage of sharing
the world market; that Israelis and Palestinians can work
together,'' said Palestinian co-founder Hana Siniora.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government projects 3.2 million tourists coming to
Israel and the Palestinian areas this year, topping the previous
high of 2.5 million in 1995. Travel executives are looking to break
down old barriers of politics and competition.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Holy Land might not be ready for the influx. The
private agencies have been cooperating more than the Israeli and
Palestinian governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very bad,'' said Yoel Mansfeld, director of
the Center for Tourism, Pilgrimage and Recreation Research at
Israel's Haifa University. ``This is a hallmark event, one of the
biggest I have ever heard of. Planning should have started 10 or 12
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, it began about four years ago. He worries
about bottlenecks or dangerous crowding at holy sites. Already, the
narrow streets of Jerusalem's Old City are sometimes so jammed that
people are shoved against the shop walls, knocking merchandise to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd control gets trickier when two governments are involved.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks, Israeli military and police officials have been
meeting weekly with Palestinian officials to discuss security,
traffic flow, and emergency services during the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Shlomo Dror, spokesman for the Israeli
administration in Palestinian areas, said 20,000 tourists are
expected to travel the five-mile route from Jerusalem to Bethlehem
each day during 2000. They will have to pass a one-lane Israeli
army checkpoint where Palestinian cars are often searched.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are setting up a room to monitor which areas of
Bethlehem, Jericho and other popular cities are overcrowded so
buses can be diverted, if necessary. Finally, they are sharing
names of religious fanatics who may be working their way to the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Dror said the coordination should probably have started a year
ago. But tense relations between Israel and the Palestinians, at
the time made it impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the problems between us, the year 2000 is not going to
wait,'' Dror said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   For the private travel industry, the motive is money and the
cooperation has been better.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli and Palestinian tourists industries have long worked
together, despite Palestinian complaints of short shrift. Israel
controls the airports and border points into the region, so most
visitors spend their nights in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Palestinian-controlled Bethlehem allege that,
although 40 percent of the region's visitors come to their city,
they only get 5 percent of the region's tourist spending.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli-guided tour buses often lead pilgrims to the Church of
the Nativity then whisk them back with no time for shopping or
eating.
</P>
<P>
   But, an overhaul of Bethlehem has created new sites and will
likely generate tourists for a longer stay.
</P>
<P>
   There, and elsewhere, huge opportunities will be created this
year because of the convergence of the millennium, a possible visit
from Pope John Paul II and peace talks _ which always improve
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that we are together in this, Israelis,
Palestinians and even Jordanians,'' said Avi Rosenthal, director
general of the Israeli Hotel Association. ``Everybody has a vested
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal hopes the millennium will build a foundation for
``regional tourism'' that would commonly take tours through
Palestinian areas, Egypt, Jordan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It's normal in other regions, but still under-developed here
because of regional tensions. For example, Arabs usually refuse to
come to Israel because of the political conflicts between their
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
