   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Undated) _ The U.S. trade deficit widened to
another record of $25.9 billion in October as rising crude oil
prices pushed the petroleum deficit to an all-time high. The
deficits with Japan and China were also at record levels. The trade
gap hit $25.94 billion in the month, higher than expected and a 7.4
percent increase from the revised $24.15 billion September figure.
The numbers provide more evidence that consumer spending
domestically is more than offsetting a recovery in demand for
American goods from overseas. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-WALMART (Undated) _ Wal-Mart Stores and America Online Inc.
announce that they are joining up to provide online access to
Wal-Mart customers. Microsoft, meanwhile, buys a $200 million stake
in Best Buy, which will promote and sell MSN Internet access and
connectivity software under the agreement. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-PHONE (Tokyo) _ KDD, Japan's largest international
telephone service company, announces plans to merge with two
smaller phone companies, IDO and DDI, in an effort to challenge the
dominance of NTT. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TRADE (New Delhi) _ A closer look at why emerging-market
nations, led by India, are so united in opposing American efforts
to make improved working conditions a requirement for joining the
World Trade Organization, a dispute that contributed to the group's
unsuccessful meeting in Seattle this month. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The column, by Floyd Norris.
</P>
