<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Dec. 16, 1999   Editors  
    The Hearst News Service will file the following for Friday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-Y2K (Washington) _ Pentagon officials say they are
confident that Russian nuclear weapons won't be launched
accidentally because of Y2K glitches. But they base that judgment
mainly on Moscow's verbal assurances rather than independent
verification. ``A lot of our confidence is based on what they tell
us,'' Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre admits. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BINGE-DRINKING (Washington) _ While one of every three
teen-agers admits to going on drunken binges, only 3 percent of
parents are aware of such behavior, according to a new survey. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PARODY (Washington) _ Poking fun at Democratic presidential
hopefuls Al Gore and Bill Bradley, the Republican Party opens a
``Gore Store and Bradley Boutique'' here with gifts for harried
last-minute shoppers. The store offers such items as ``I invented
the Internet'' mouse pads, ``alpha male'' baseball caps and coffee
mugs for those who want to stay awake during Bill Bradley speeches.
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-FOREIGN (Washington) _ Conservative Republican
presidential candidates Gary Bauer and Patrick Buchanan attack
President Clinton and some moderate Republicans, saying they should
stop putting trade above human rights and national security in
dealing with China. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Everyone knew six years ago that the
don't-ask-don't-tell rule for gays in the military was a temporary
cop-out because President Clinton couldn't get the change in policy
he wanted. Now the rule is back as a campaign issue, and nobody is
surprised. It was never going to work. By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CZAR (Washington) _ People watching television news on New
Year's weekend will likely see a lot of John Koskinen, the White
House's Y2K czar. But Koskinen hopes that once the weekend is over,
few Americans will remember his name. To him that would mean the
United States experienced relatively few Y2K-related problems. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
</TEXT>
