   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ Spot coverage of the talks between
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: A 5 p.m. EST briefing is scheduled after the talks. The
story is expected to move by 8:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE _ JERUSALEM _ With the first round of new peace
negotiations between longtime enemies Israel and Syria now in
motion, whither the Mideast peace process? Israel is now on track
to be at peace with its internal Arab enemy and its most
influential external Arab enemy by October. Can overall peace in
this long-troubled region be that far behind? Developing. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 7 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BRADLEY _ CLAREMONT, N.H. _ In an historic encounter,
Sen. John McCain and former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley, both
vying for their party's nomination, will meet at a public forum to
discuss campaign finance reform. The forum will take place in
Claremont, N.H., where President Clinton and Newt Gingrich pledged
to enact campaign finance reform in 1995. The former colleagues
will also hold a joint news conference following the event.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HISPANICS _ (Developing) Months after he garnered criticism
for saying no to speaking invitations from some of the nation's
most prominent Hispanic groups, Gov. George W. Bush continues his
assiduous courting of Latino supporters in his own way, employing a
pro-business style designed to win votes _ and money. (Heath,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-RIGHTS _ WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno and
Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth make a 1 p.m. EST
announcement about a civil rights enforcement case that will
involve Florida and some other states. (Schultz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 5 pm. EST.
</P>
<P>
   ADHD _ WASHINGTON _ A new brain imaging technique promises to
provide a new way to diagnose attention deficit/hyperactivty
disorder, according to a research paper released Thursday.
Diagnosis of the disorder, for which millions of American children
take daily medication, is now based on doctors' observations.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SCAMS _ WASHINGTON - Consumer Products Safety
Commission officials said Thursday they plan to crack down on
Internet crooks victimizing kids in Yuletide scams. (Glass, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-AIRLINES _ WASHINGTON _ The head of the Federal Aviation
Administration's Y2K office holds a 3 p.m. EST briefing on Y2K and
the air traffic control system. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NEWT-MARIANNE _ Newt and Marianne Gingrich go face-to-face in
court-ordered mediation over their divorce. (Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FBI-Y2K _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The FBI will maintain 56 24-hour Y2K
command posts across the nation to address any potential federal
criminal violations or national security incidents during the
millennium rollover. (Hills, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
