A0909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-OPERA-FAN-HNS &LR;      12-16 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-FAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUNG OPERA FAN WANTS TO EMULATE THE TENOR OF MENTOR'S TONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRIS STURGIS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROTTERDAM, N.Y. _ In 1994, 3-year-old Louis Lohraseb and his
mother were watching World Cup soccer on television when the
announcer said the next program would be a concert by the Three
Tenors.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Lohraseb assumed her son would rather hear from the Three
Stooges than the Three Tenors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go in your room? You won't like this,'' Kim
recalled telling the boy. She was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Louis gave the classical music singers a listen and fell under
the spell of Luciano Pavarotti, who, along with Placido Domingo and
Jose Carreras, form the Three Tenors.
</P>
<P>
   ``His voice is beautiful,'' said Louis, now a poised and
enthusiastic 8-year-old who attends Jefferson Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 5 years old, Louis went to New York City with his
grandfather, Louis Miranda, to see Pavarotti sing at the
Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   At first, security personnel wouldn't let the pair go backstage,
but they changed their tune after the youngster demonstrated his
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last guard said, `I heard that you like to sing. Sing a
little,''' the boy recalled, his dark eyes shining. ``There were
2,000 people in the room, waiting in line. So I started singing `O
Sole Mio' and everybody started clapping.''
</P>
<P>
   A security guard produced a backstage pass. After the concert,
the youngster felt a mixture of excitement and nervousness. ``I was
shaking in my boots,'' Louis said. ``I couldn't stand still.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis sang, and his idol put two fingers to his lips and let out
a whistle. ``That's a singer,'' Pavarotti said, looking around for
a handkerchief to autograph. He was out of hankies, so his manager
suggested using a napkin from a fruit basket.
</P>
<P>
   Pavarotti rejected that substitution, saying in Italian, ``What
are you doing with that dish cloth?'' the boy's grandfather
recalled. Both Louis Miranda and his wife, Mary, were born in Italy
and emigrated to the United States as teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Young Louis also saw Pavarotti in May when he performed in
Albany. This time he got a signed handkerchief. In July, he held
that souvenir as he sang for an audience of 1,500 at the inaugural
performance of the amphitheater in Schenectady's Central Park.
While he looked calm and poised on stage, his family could read his
nervousness in the twisting of the hankie.
</P>
<P>
   He also has appeared on the ``Rosie O'Donnell Show'' and
Nickelodeon's, ``Figure it Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis has never taken a voice lesson, picking up the mechanics
and expression of opera from videotapes and recordings. He learned
``like you study science. You look,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken piano lessons for three years, building on his
prodigious ability to play opera accompaniments by ear.
</P>
<P>
   He is writing an opera that his grandfather is helping translate
it into Italian. In August, Louis will travel with his grandparents
to Italy for a week, a trip paid for by the ``Rosie O'Donnell
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be able to show him things we wouldn't be able to,''
his mother said of her parents. ``Plus, they speak the language.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole family is a bit perplexed by Louis' love for opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us have any musical talent,'' his mother said. ``I
don't know where this came from.''
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather said: ``I like opera, but I really began to like
it when he began to sing. It's very, very unusual. It's a blessing
and gift.''
</P>
</TEXT>
