<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0932 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMPAIGN-GERALDINE-FE     12-16 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GERALDINE-FERRARO-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING FOR THE HOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from The New York Times Syndicate. See below for
sales information.) 
 By GERALDINE FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    On Monday night, I sat down for the fourth time in less then a
month to watch the Republican presidential candidates debate. And
the thought that cheered me most was the realization that this was
the last debate either party would be having this year, this
century, indeed this millennium.
 &HT;    It couldn't have come soon enough for me!
 &HT;    In all fairness, I must admit that I feel this way partly
because I'm a Democrat and, if Fox News weren't paying me to
politically analyze the event, I probably would have been out
Christmas shopping.
 &HT;    But there is a part of me that's very interested in getting to
know the men who have the potential to be the Republican nominee,
the men who might even _ heaven forbid! _ move into the White House
in January 2001.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, that interest was left unsatisfied. The debate
failed me _ but, far more important, it failed the Republicans
across the country who will be voting in the upcoming primaries and
caucuses.
 &HT;    Like me, those voters didn't have a chance to get to know the
men who might be president, because there were four other guys
standing up there, getting in the way.
 &HT;    Not that the problem is as simple as too many debaters. By their
very nature and because so much is at stake, presidential debates
shed little light on the political process and tell us very little
about the candidates. That's as true today as it was in 1984, when
George Bush and I were alone on the stage, standing across from
each other as our parties' vice-presidential nominees.
 &HT;    We were the ones up on the stage, but our staffs had done all of
the tough work _ in the process making it virtually impossible for
anything spontaneous or informative to emerge from the debate. They
had negotiated the height of the podium and of the box I'd stand
on, the color of the curtain behind us, the reporters who would ask
the questions and the time allowed for each answer and for each
followup.
 &HT;    We ourselves were even more painstakingly prepared. During
rehearsals our staff directed us on how to stand, how to move, how
to acknowledge the reporters, the audience and the other candidate.
They peppered us with every possible question, and provided
carefully packaged answers for each. My friend Bob Barnett played
George Bush in rehearsal, while my House colleague Lynn Martin was
playing Geraldine Ferraro for Bush.
 &HT;    Even after the debate, nothing was left to chance. Well before
the final handshake, our staffers had kicked into overdrive,
frantically spinning the story for the press, ensuring that
anything spontaneous or human that might have slipped out was
nudged back into ``the message.''
 &HT;    It's hardly comforting, watching these debates 16 years later,
to see that nothing has changed.
 &HT;    There is one difference, though: In 1984, the country at least
knew that one of us was going to be the vice president. These 1999
debates are tedious displays of poor theater, featuring a large
cast of characters, four of whom have in common that there's no way
they'll ever be president.
 &HT;    On Monday night, vote.com went online to ask for viewers'
opinions as to who had ``won'' the debate. It was interactive play
time, and the big winner was judged to be ... Alan Keyes.
 &HT;    Alan Keyes?
 &HT;    That many people thought he won is absolute proof that this
whole debate thing needs rethinking. He didn't advance a single
idea that we'd want to govern this country by, but he said whatever
it was he said with emotion, with commitment, with flair.
 &HT;    He was sharp, he was articulate, he was smooth. He showed the
theatrical skills he honed in college, on talk radio, on the
lecture circuit and, yes, on the campaign trail. With such an
accomplished presentation, does it matter that he didn't say a word
that made him seem like a plausible future president?
 &HT;    Well, no, probably it doesn't matter. Because, of course, he
will never be president. And neither will Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes
or Orrin Hatch.
 &HT;    So spare us.
 &HT;    It's time either to stop these silly, so-called ``debates'' or
to get serious about them. And if we want to get serious, a good
way to start is by clearing the stage.
 &HT;    Either Gov. George W. Bush or Sen. John McCain will be the
Republican nominee for president _ you know it, I know it and so do
all six men up on that platform.
 &HT;    Maybe it's time they did something about it.
 &HT;    Maybe for the good of their party and their country, they should
emulate Elizabeth Dole's leadership, exhibit Dan Quayle's
intelligence and get out. Take a quick bow and sit down.
 &HT;    And if they won't, perhaps it's time they were decorously pushed
into the wings, leaving enough time for us to get to know the two
men who have a measurable chance of becoming our next president ...
and to finish our Christmas shopping.
 c.1999 Geraldine A. Ferraro  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Geraldine Ferraro was the Democratic candidate for vice
president in 1984. A former member of Congress, she is a political
analyst for Fox News and president of G&AMP;L Strategies in New York
and Arlington, Va., a corporate consultancy on workplace and
diversity issues.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MS-NBC host Laura Ingraham.)
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _ _  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
