<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0961 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     12-16 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap22-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: STRANGERS IN THE NIGHT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. The series is a wonderful way to celebrate the millennium
with your readers. FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, please contact New
York Times Syndicate Sales Executive Bob Farnell by phone, (800)
535-4425, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   THE STORY SO FAR: Reporter Max Timlin is hired by editor Kate
Banks to investigate a doomsday cult called The Watchers and
succeeds at penetrating their inner sanctum. Max confronts The
Watcher leader, Raoul Glaber. Max suspects that is not his real
name. He then learns that Glaber's protege, the beautiful Angela
Powers, is really the daughter of Kate Banks. Two Watchers are
found floating in the sea, suspected suicides. Violet helps Max
track down Glaber's real identity and earns his affection. Max
overcomes his fear of heights to spy on The Watcher's convention at
the domed stadium.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   The crow's nest behind the speakers turned out to be the perfect
vantage point to view The Watchers' so-called ``New Awakening.'' A
work crew had erected makeshift bleachers across the outfield. The
doors had opened at noon, and Max watched as a sea of white
streamed in noisily, trying to get as close as possible to a
central stage, erected near home plate.
</P>
<P>
   White banners were hung everywhere with slogans such as WATCH
THIS! and WATCH WITH US and AWAKE AND AWARE.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers pumped stadium music. Rocky told Max to wear
earplugs, but all the sound was directed out from where he was
sitting. Whoever picked the music and big screen videos had a sense
of humor because all the songs had ``white'' in the title _ from
``White Christmas'' to ``A Whiter Shade of Pale'' to, amazingly,
Billy Idol's ``White Wedding.'' Max curled his lip reflexively.
</P>
<P>
   The lights went out, and the crowd hushed and then became more
excited, like a rock concert, anticipating the featured act. Then
more music, the familiar throbbing of that great rock anthem of
paranoia and stalking, the rhythm like a heartbeat over Sting's
persistent voice: ``Every step you take, every move you make ...
I'll be watching you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a blast of crisscross laser beams, as bright white lights
shone on Glaber and his minions _ all dressed in blood-red tuxedos
_ almost 30 of them _ all blond or bald, except Glaber whose hair
was dark _ and one woman in a red, skintight, formal dress. Angela
Powers.
</P>
<P>
   Glaber raised his hand for silence. ``You know,'' he began,
``I've been following the stock market recently ...'' He paused,
and the crowd laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So here we are less than a month before a new millennium, and
the market is down. Now where is Wall Street's confidence? My
children, the economies of the world are about to crumble. Those
who put their stock in gold, now have rust. Those who put their
stock in lust, now have AIDS. Those who put their stock in the
religions of your fathers, are left with empty promises. Pie in the
sky when you die.'' More laughter and applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what about all of you who have put your stock in me? What
do you all have?''
</P>
<P>
   The Watchers rose as one in prolonged waves of cheers and whoops
and cries, morphing finally into a chant of their leader's name:
``Ra-ool, Ra-ool.'' It shook the stadium, and Glaber put his hands
on his hips, nodded up toward the cheap seats, and smiled, looking
every bit the presidential candidate about to give an acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   They showered him with love, dancing and jumping up and down the
aisles, waving placards that pronounced their place of origin: New
York, California, Montreal, Brazil, Denmark, even Japan.
</P>
<P>
   From Max's watchtower it looked like he was staring into a
microscope at some strange organism, vibrating with energy,
changing shape, a source of fascination and mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you have been through the rite of initiation _ you have
shed the garments of darkness for robes of white. And let me say
that some of you look better without your clothes than others.'' He
glanced toward Angela. Waves of laughter. ``We on this stage wear
red, as you all will wear red in a new dawn, blazing with blood and
fire.'' That quieted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you will experience a New Awakening. If there are any
among you who still slumber _ if your right eye is closed _ it will
be opened. With opened eyes we will watch together. For it is
ordained that we shall not watch alone. And so today, before you, I
will take unto me a bride.''
</P>
<P>
   The news caught the crowd by surprise, until people started to
point and call out, and before long they were cheering and chanting
her name: ``An-gel-a, An-gel-a.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber reached out her hand for her. She stood slowly, holding
her hands over her face, but Max could not tell the nature of the
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let that poor girl go! Let her go, I say. Give her her
freedom. Freedom, I say, freedom!'' The new voice was loud and
strong, coming clearly through the sound system. The voice was
familiar to Max, but it was not Glaber's.
</P>
<P>
   The group on stage stood and looked at each other and around the
stadium in search of the phantom voice. People in the crowd were
pointing. ``Up here, Glaber. Up here, on the catwalk.''
</P>
<P>
   Max turned to see a solitary little man, dressed in an orange
jump suit, wearing a halo of silver hair. He was looking down, like
Moses descending from Sinai, and was holding a wireless mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' said Max aloud, ``it's Rocky, the sound engineer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Glaber,'' the voice boomed again. ``This is the day of a Great
Awakening, all right. And it's time for all these people to wake up
and see you for what you really are. A no-good stinker. A coward. A
bum.''
</P>
<P>
   Max stood up straight in his crow's nest, this interloper's
words ringing in his ears, vibrating from the speakers through his
body. It was not Rocky Como after all, he realized. ``It's Father
Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE GREAT DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
