<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     12-16 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap26-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: FALL DOWN AND GO BOOM  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. The series is a wonderful way to celebrate the millennium
with your readers. FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, please contact New
York Times Syndicate Sales Executive Bob Farnell by phone, (800)
535-4425, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Violet comes to Max's rescue, and they spend
days working with police on finding the kidnapped Angela. A
Christmas Eve gathering is interrupted by a shocking phone call.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Sam Lockhart and Max raced from the beach to the Dome in
separate cars. The chief of police even loaned Max a portable
rotating police light he could stick on the dashboard of the
Mustang. He felt like a kid with a new Christmas toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if somebody had given Glaber his own police light,'' Max
mused, ``it would have satisfied his thirst for power.''
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived, they found the Dome lit up like a movie set.
Max counted seven police cars _ the police station was right across
the street _ three news trucks, two news helicopters, a police
helicopter, three fire trucks, one with a long ladder extended to
the lip of the Dome roof, and maybe 200 onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Two rescue workers had succeeded in hooking a harness to the
young man, and were beginning to lower him to the ground. Max was
close enough to recognize him, the hairless Watcher he had first
seen on the shore of Cosmos Key during the initiation ceremony.
From Max's vantage point, the kid looked limp and lifeless, a rag
doll.
</P>
<P>
   They unhooked him on the ground, placed him on a stretcher and
rolled him into an ambulance. A detective approached Sam and Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is conscious, but incoherent. He looks OK from the
outside, but they'll be checking him for internal injuries. We
can't tell if he fell, jumped, or was pushed out. These people saw
the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   An older couple approached now and described how they had been
on the patio of a sports bar, drinking merrily and singing
Christmas songs with their friends, but their Yuletide gaiety was
interrupted by the drone of a small plane: ``The kind that flies
over the beach dragging commercial signs,'' said the woman.
</P>
<P>
   The plane flew a tight circle over the Dome, when a figure,
clearly visible in white against the night sky, dropped straight
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked for a chute to open, or a bungee cord,'' said the
man, ``like it was a publicity stunt, but he just landed near the
top of the Dome, bounced once, and then slid out of sight. I
expected to find him on the ground, dead. We screamed for the
bartender to call 911, rushed over here, and saw he was hooked on
the ledge of the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam thanked the couple and turned to the detective. ``Any word
about the plane? Anyone call saying they lost a passenger?''
Negative.
</P>
<P>
   Max and Sam drove to the hospital and waited for more than two
hours before a doctor came out to see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That roof is made of a tough fiberglass. It was no kiddie ride
down that thing. He's got what amounts to second degree burns down
his back from the slide. He's cracked his pelvis. Maybe busted some
ribs. But he's very much alive. The roof had enough give to cushion
his fall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we talk with him?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given him something for the pain, but you can try. Take
it easy, though. He's in Room 211.''
</P>
<P>
   Max stood back and let Sam conduct the interview. The young man
was lying on his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, son, you've had quite a fall. What's your name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas. Thomas Day.'' Max took a step closer to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. Thomas. Tell us how you fell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't fall, man. I jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You jumped out of the plane? Why did you do that, Thomas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were going to push me out. Like the others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The four Watchers who were found in the Bay?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew those people, man. They were good people.'' He winced.
``I didn't think they would kill themselves, so I started asking
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Glaber?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not that high up. But to his buds. They didn't like that I
was nosin' around. So they said, `Come on, man, we know where your
friends jumped from. We can show it to you from the plane. We can
say a prayer for them.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you went with them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, what an idiot, huh? Man, the pain's goin' away, but I'm
feelin' pretty sleepy. Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on, Thomas. Why did you jump?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot was next to me and this big guy behind me. When we
got up there, everything changed. Said I wasn't worthy to follow
Glaber into a new world. Said I wasn't strong enough to do what had
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had to be done?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. On New Year's Eve. These people are wacked, man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What had to be done, Thomas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out what it was, and that they probably killed
those people because they didn't want to do it. They were scarin'
me, man. So when I looked down and saw the Dome. I can't believe I
jumped, man. Oh man, when they told me what they were going to do
... I've got to sleep man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``On New Year's Eve....'' He was breathing heavy now, about to
fall off into a painless sleep induced by his medications.
</P>
<P>
   Sam leaned over and shouted. ``What are they going to do,
Thomas? Tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   The police chief turned his head and placed his ear closed to
the young man's lips. Max could hear nothing, but it appeared as if
the man's lips moved.
</P>
<P>
   Sam stood straight and turned to Max, a look of disbelief on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you get it? What are they going to do, Sam. Did he tell
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he told me. He said they're going to blow up the Skyway
Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE DEAD OF NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
