<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     12-16 2237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap29-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: SAVE THE LAST DANCE FOR ME  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. The series is a wonderful way to celebrate the millennium
with your readers. FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, please contact New
York Times Syndicate Sales Executive Bob Farnell by phone, (800)
535-4425, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   THE STORY SO FAR: Reporter Max Timlin is hired by editor Kate
Banks to investigate a doomsday cult called The Watchers. He learns
that the leader of The Watchers, Raoul Glaber, has a false
identity. He also learns that Glaber's bride-to-be, Angela Powers,
is the daughter of Kate Banks. With the help of Father Ralph, Max
rescues Angela, until she is kidnapped by Glaber's henchmen. A plot
is uncovered to blow up the Skyway Bridge on New Year's Day. Violet
closes in on Glaber's real identity, just as a hurricane bears down
on West Florida.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max had a half-hour, he figured, to reach the top of the Skyway
Bridge, driving his old Mustang through wind and rain of hurricane
force.
</P>
<P>
   Two things worked in his favor: the eerie emptiness of the roads
and the portable rotating police light he had never returned to Sam
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   He stuck the cop light on his dashboard and cruised forward as
fast as the conditions would allow, through water that rose to his
fenders, over downed power lines and around tree limbs and other
detritus of the high winds.
</P>
<P>
   He waved himself past two clueless toll-booth attendants, but
was stopped at a small roadblock on the stretch of highway leading
to the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry, sir, the bridge is closed to all traffic. The
winds are way too dangerous. And the lightning. You'd best be
getting home.'' The officer was young and by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a reporter working on a story. The police chief gave me
this light. Call him if you want. My name is Max. Max Timlin.'' The
officer checked his ID.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anyone driven up there in the last hour?'' asked Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a Highway Patrol trooper. About 15 minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you talk to the driver?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Just waved him through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you call the roadblock on the other side, please, it's an
emergency, to see if he made it across?''
</P>
<P>
   The officer, thoroughly perplexed, went to his car to use his
radio. Max stepped on the gas.
</P>
<P>
   He drove as fast as he could, but winds from the south seemed to
be pushing against his grille like a fleet of trucks. Gusts knocked
the car sideways, blowing water and wind through the tiny spaces of
the ragtop. He fought the steering wheel for control.
</P>
<P>
   As he climbed the bridge, he realized he was flying blind. The
old wipers seemed to make things worse, and he had no time to
fiddle with the defogger. He tried wiping the window clear with his
hand. As the incline took him higher, more than 100 feet above the
sea, closer to 200, the winds strengthened. Blasts of lightning
crashed around him.
</P>
<P>
   Max feared only two things: lightning and high places. This ride
up the roller coaster was as irrational as anything he had ever
done. He hoped _ he prayed _ hands glued to the wheel, that the
Mustang would cruise over the apex of the bridge, safely to the
other side. That he would find nothing.
</P>
<P>
   More lightning, illuminating the top of the bridge and, too
late, the red reflector lights of a black and gold Highway Patrol
car.
</P>
<P>
   Max slammed the brakes, but the Mustang slid at an angle and
crashed into the bigger, heavier vehicle. He climbed out dazed and
unsteady, and the wind knocked him over. He stumbled up but a
lightning bolt hit one of the bridge towers, and the fear of it
drove Max to his belly. He waited a moment, trying to regain his
breath. He tasted blood.
</P>
<P>
   Max looked up. Another flash. And there, maybe 30 yards ahead,
in the middle of the bridge, at the highest point above the water,
stood a man against the edge, his two arms around the figure of a
woman, appearing limp and unconscious. It was Michael Miller _ aka
Raoul Glaber _ prepared now to die for the sins of his father, and
to take Cassie Powers with him.
</P>
<P>
   Max got to his feet and pressed forward, like a man dragging a
300-pound weight. His nemesis stood perfectly still, immune to the
elements, gazing toward the sky as if in prayer. The man looked at
his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not time to die, Michael. Stop. Stop.'' Max shouted at
the top of his voice, like King Lear railing against the storm.
``Your life isn't done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller turned in complete bewilderment, and then leaned the
young woman in his arms over the edge of the bridge, 200 feet above
the roiling sea. ``You're too late, Max. Unless you want to join
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Miller. Your suffering is over. You are NOT your
father. Please put her down. Put the girl down. Please. Come with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Max moved closer. Only three steps separated them. Max leapt for
Miller's feet, but missed, knocking the wind out of him. Miller
aimed a vicious kick with a heavy boot to Max's head and landed a
glancing blow. Max couldn't tell if he was seeing more lightning,
or just the electricity in his brain.
</P>
<P>
   Max looked up, helpless. The King of The Watchers had his angel
_ his Angela Powers _ in his hands now and, almost without effort,
pressed her over his head like an Olympic weight lifter hoisting a
broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   Through the storm in his brain, prone and helpless, Max could
hear Miller, repeating over and over: ``Father, forgive me, for I
know not what I do. Father, forgive me. Father, forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   Max squeezed his eyes shut, so he would not have to see the girl
fly to her death.
</P>
<P>
   Miller screamed, and Max's eyes snapped open to see him fall
backward in pain and confusion, the girl dropping to the pavement
with a sickening thud. Max was dreaming. Or else a dog, a dog like
Daisy, was standing over Miller, growling like a mother protecting
her babies, her jaws locked on his arm. Someone was helping Max to
his feet. ``Violet _ help Cassie.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Max a good minute, and all his strength, to pull Daisy
off the fallen prophet, who rolled in pain on the pavement. Max
looked up to see Violet's white Jeep behind his crumpled Mustang,
and, down the incline, three police cars, their lights barely
visible, their sirens barely audible in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' he thought. ``It's finally over.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller made a wild dash for the side of the bridge, emitting a
scream of pain and despair that shot Max into action. Just before
Miller went over the edge, Max tackled him from behind, his arms
locked around the Watcher's shoulders. But Miller's momentum and
the demons inside him carried him over _ carried them both over _
the ledge.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Max heard was Violet's scream. And then silence.
And the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max was dead. He had to be. But could you be dead and dreaming
at the same time? Because this was the strangest dream. Even for a
dead man. He dreamed he was lying in a coffin, a pretty comfortable
one, actually. That surprised him.
</P>
<P>
   And Father Ralph was in the room, saying a prayer over him, and
performing the last rites. Behind him, against the wall of the room
_ quite bright for a mortuary _ stood a row of women. One by one,
they filed by, bent over to kiss him, leaving their hot tears on
his cold face.
</P>
<P>
   First was his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have been a lawyer,'' she whispered in his dead
ear. Then Kate Banks, ``Thanks for saving my daughter.'' Then,
Sherry Darling, who snapped a photograph of him in the coffin and
then hugged his lifeless body until it hurt. Then Violet Rose, the
beautiful flower, who kissed him on the lips, with more passion
than anyone had ever kissed him, but, too bad, cause he was dead
now, but if he was really dead how come he was having this certain
feeling that he associated with being very much alive?
</P>
<P>
   It was all over, he thought now in his dream, I can drift off to
a big, big sleep. Just then he heard a scratching, and looked up to
see two brown and black paws, and then the large head of Daisy the
dog, who whimpered, then drooled on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Max was in a coma for two days, and in the hospital for a month.
He broke his wrist, his collarbone and three ribs. His left lung
collapsed. They removed his spleen. While they were at it, a
plastic surgeon came in and lasered the Watcher tattoo off Max's
behind.
</P>
<P>
   There were dozens of strange theories as to how Max survived the
fall from the bridge. The most common was that Miller absorbed most
of the impact, breaking Max's fall. There was science talk about
terminal velocity and the softening effects of water in motion.
Some people spoke of miracles, but Father Ralph discouraged it.
``Good people make their own miracles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not forget the Coast Guard,'' said Samson Lockhart.
``They risked their lives to fish his sorry butt out of the
water.'' The stormy sea had washed up Max's body onto one of the
bumpers designed to protect the bridge from another collision.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of rehab, Max asked Violet to pick him up at St.
Anthony's Hospital on the day of his release. She rolled his
wheelchair to the front entrance, helped him into the Jeep and
drove at twice the speed limit for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a surprise for you,'' she said, her face fighting to
contain the width of her smile. A lovely ride on a crisp, sunny
February day brought them to the condo, where Kate was waiting to
greet them. She hugged Max, and then wiped the kisses from his face
with her thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the surprise?'' he said goofily.
</P>
<P>
   From around the corner came an amazing site. His Mustang,
looking in mint condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gift from the newspaper. We had it repaired, rebuilt
the engine, top of the line paint job, and magnificently
detailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving the car, with the top down, was Cassie Powers, wearing
reflector sunglasses and a black bikini. It looked like something
out of an old hot-rod magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In the back, proud and pretty, her head tilted back, enjoying
the breeze, was Daisy the dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to drive, Max?'' Cassie got out and embraced him.
Violet hopped in the passenger side, and Max took the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   He looked down at the dashboard and laughed until it hurt. The
odometer had finally crawled over the 100,000-mile mark _ in fact,
seven miles over, to 007.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like the ending of `Goldfinger,''' he said, cruising down
Gulf Boulevard, feeling the joy of a new day.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
 &UR; EPILOGUE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The body of Michael Miller, aka Raoul Glaber, was never
recovered. He is presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Father Ralph Rizzo and James ``Choirboy'' Jones started a
program for former Watchers, and succeeded in directing many
towards community service and productive social action.
</P>
<P>
   Samson Lockhart retired from police work, received many awards
for his contributions, and opened a chain of New Orleans-style
restaurants called Daisy's.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy the Dog appeared with Max Timlin on the cover of Time
magazine, and visited Max at the beach every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Banks became Max's good friend, drinking buddy and dance
partner. She hired him and teamed him with Sherry Darling to head
up a special investigative team for the Florida Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Cassie Powers was never called ``Angela'' again. Max took a
fatherly interest in her and coached her on the writing of her
memoir, ``Inside the Watchers,'' which became a best seller.
</P>
<P>
   Max wrote a 29-part blockbuster series about The Watchers. It
was titled ``Ain't Done Yet.'' The Pulitzer Prize Board, an
unusually conservative group, granted him a special award by
acclamation, although one editor thought the series was ``a little
long.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm that hit West Florida on New Year's Eve didn't have an
official name, but Max dubbed it Hurricane Millie, short for
millennium, and the nickname stuck forevermore.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether Max ever hooked up with Violet Rose, well, you're
going to have to check in some time down the road with the new
adventures of Max Timlin, because Max and Violet ... well, let's
just say they ain't done yet, either.
</P>
<P>
   THE END
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
