<SLUG> BC-MCCONAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SHOP RESTORING HEARSE THAT CARRIED JFK'S BODY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON MCCONAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALVARADO, Texas _ Trinidad De La Cruz is one of eight people in
the world who can make a Rolls Royce grill.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is what a television commercial said about him a
few years ago. That does make him special when it comes to auto
body work.
</P>
<P>
   And right now, he's engaged in a special job. He is restoring
the Cadillac hearse that carried the casket and body of President
John F. Kennedy from Parkland Hospital in Dallas to Love Field to
be flown to Washington after his assassination in Dallas in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I feel honored to work on this hearse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So does Luis Guerrero, the detail man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to look good. I promise you that. It is going to
look good,'' Guerrero said.
</P>
<P>
   The hearses and limousines the men refinish for sale at Vaughan
Special Automobiles do look good.
</P>
<P>
   Several were parked around the 1903 2-story house where owner
Arrdeen Vaughan lives.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in a white Cadillac hearse that looked like a new
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a dandy, isn't it,'' said Vaughan. ``We are taking
it to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   He's friendly, and on this day he wore a leather jacket for
protection against a stiff north wind. He's been in this business
since 1961 and sells about 200 hearses and limos a year.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll trade or buy anything. Proof is in his office and
shop, which are full of antique gasoline pumps, cars, clocks and
Cushman Eagle motor scooters.
</P>
<P>
   There sat an old juke box packed with old records. He punched
the button and Boogie Woogie by Tommy Dorsey's band played.
</P>
<P>
   He told about being reared in Hillsboro. His father owned a
garage and sold buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I don't care what you do when you grow up,
whether it's selling popcorn or car parts. But I want you to make
sure every sack that comes out of your place has `Vaughan' written
on it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   We drank coffee, and then he issued an invitation. ``Well, come
on, let's look at what may be the most famous hearse in the world _
the last one that carried President Kennedy's casket and body,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the hearse along with 50 other cars from a leasing
company about 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in good shape when I got it,'' he said. ``But I didn't
take care of it and let it sit out in the weather, and it got in
pretty bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   He decided to have his crew rebuild it a few months ago after
his son Michael Vaughan became owner of funeral homes in Donna and
Mercedes in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That country is 98 percent Catholic, and Michael buries many
of them,'' he said. ``And many of those people loved Kennedy. So I
thought, why not give them the chance to make that last ride to the
cemetery in the hearse that carried JFK.''
</P>
<P>
   We had reached the hearse. The headliner, floor and many other
parts are being replaced. De La Cruz has already built new tail
fins.
</P>
<P>
   We looked at the work and smelled the odor of paints and glass
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we really got on it, we could probably finish it in a
month,'' said Vaughan.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to call me when the work is completed.
</P>
<P>
   (Jon McConal writes a column about Texas. You can e-mail him at:
mcconal(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
