<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOW WHAT FOR GAYS IN THE MILITARY? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ We all knew six years ago, liberals and
conservatives alike, that President Clinton's mushy compromise over
gays in the military was a temporary cop-out to get the subject out
of the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was having trouble getting the armed services to accept
him, let alone openly gay soldiers. He had ducked Vietnam under
fishy circumstances, and veterans were resisting his authority as
commander-in-chief. So he did what politicians always do in a bind
_ he punted.
</P>
<P>
   The president had promised during his 1992 campaign to allow
gays and lesbians to serve their country without discrimination,
whether in the civil service or the military sector. But dire
predictions of disaster from Congress and the Joint Chiefs of Staff
sent him scurrying for cover.
</P>
<P>
   After long negotiations, the result in 1993 was a policy of
``don't ask, don't tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping secrets was to solve the problem, although even children
in grade school quickly learn that denying reality is never a
permanent answer.
</P>
<P>
   So the don't-ask-don't-tell policy is back now as a campaign
issue. It was never going to work, and it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   One immediate political trigger for the current debate was the
conviction last week of an Army private for bludgeoning to death a
fellow soldier who had been taunted for months with anti-gay slurs.
The other was the clear division now evident between the Democratic
and Republican presidential candidates on the subject as the
election contest heats up.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it was Hillary Clinton who was out in front first.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning for the New York Senate seat before a gay group, she
said the policy wasn't working and that fitness for military
service should not be based on sexual orientation. Later, in
Washington, her husband added that he also thought his own policy
was ``out of whack'' and needed to be ``reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Defense Secretary William Cohen weighed in, ordering a
review but not committing the Pentagon to any major reform. A
Pentagon spokesman said an investigation will be launched to
evaluate how the services are carrying out the policy, and if they
are bothering at all to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's goal is to assess ``what the climate is'' at bases where
straight soldiers and gays, undetected or suspected, interact.
</P>
<P>
   Under the present policy, recruits are no longer asked their
sexual orientation at induction. Superiors are forbidden to
question their troops about their sex lives or investigate their
private activities. But the services, which have official
guidelines about dealing with gays, have not established formal
training programs to assure that suspected homosexuals are left
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore was quick to jump on the bandwagon too.
He has long supported allowing gays to serve openly in the
military, but in a new
</P>
<P>
   statement he called forcefully for eliminating the
don't-ask-don't-tell policy. It was a tougher public stand than he
had taken before.
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic presidential rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, had
earlier called for a policy change to allow gays to serve openly.
``I won't settle for a policy that discriminates against gays in
the military,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats are in direct disagreement with the two
leading Republican presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a traditionalist opposed to
single-sex marriages and women and men training together in the
military, has refused to appear before a gay Republican group. It
is thus no surprise that he supports the present policy and says
that any change is ``for the military to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, a Naval Academy graduate and Vietnam
prisoner of war who has the staunchest military credentials of the
presidential field, is firmly opposed to reform in this area as
well. He said he ``absolutely'' supports the don't-ask-don't-tell
rule.
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``it might be appropriate'' to review the policy.
But he criticized the president's timing, suggesting that he
proposed it now only to help his wife's candidacy for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the president should have called in the Joint Chiefs
and proposed a review in an orderly way rather than dropping the
bombshell in a media interview. ``This is the most volatile,
emotional issue probably that we face,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that the military is going to have to bite the
bullet here. If gays volunteer to defend our country and even die
for it, more power to them. The military brass cannot forever
resist cultural change that has been accepted in many parts of the
civilian society.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials initially resisted allowing women serious
roles in the military, and their increasing participation still
rankles some hardliners. But after some horrible examples of
discrimination, the Department of Defense eventually set down firm
rules to give women opportunities similar to those offered men and
to punish mistreatment based on gender. And gradually women are
proving they can fit in and do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Pentagon similarly resisted opportunities for
racial minorities, and they too have proved they can carry military
responsibility well.
</P>
<P>
   It is finally the turn of gays to be treated fairly and given
the chance to prove themselves without harassment. It is time for
the Joint Chiefs and the rest of the military hierarchy to
establish no-nonsense rules that assure the safety and equality of
all those whose service is meritorious and in accord with routine
military discipline.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
