<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CIDERHOUSE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CIDER HOUSE' IS PACKED WITH OSCAR-WORTHY PERFORMANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his American films, Swedish director Lasse Hallstrom (``My
Life as a Dog'') has had a marvelous way of finding nobility in
characters who seem, on the surface, unsympathetic or distasteful _
think of the massively obese mother of ``What's Eating Gilbert
Grape'' or the obnoxious salesman hero of ``Once Around.''
</P>
<P>
   In this adaptation of John Irving's best-selling novel, ``The
Cider House Rules,'' Hallstrom finds it with two abortionists and
an incestuous father. It's quite a feat, and quite a movie. Many
will find the subject matter disturbing (and worth more than a
PG-13 rating), but it's clearly one of the holiday season's richest
and most daring movie entries.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Irving himself and set in the World War II homefront
in 1943, it's the story of the irascible but dedicated Dr. Wilbur
Larch (Michael Caine, with a coarse American accent) and his
protege, Homer Wells (Tobey Maguire), an orphan who has grown up in
the orphanage the good doctor runs in rural Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The orphanage is like something off the cover of the Saturday
Evening Post except for one thing: Dr. Larch freely conducts
abortions on the desperate young women who come to him in trouble;
and he's also not only taught Homer how to conduct abortions, but
how to deliver babies with the skill of a seasoned midwife.
</P>
<P>
   From this situation, the film develops into a coming-of-age
drama as the innocent, sheltered Homer _ loving his mentor and his
orphanage but never comfortable with his side duties _ decides to
see the world and goes to live and work on a nearby apple farm,
where he becomes involved in a love affair and several moral
dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   What the dilemmas teach Homer _ and what the movie is ``about''
_ is the veracity behind Larch's admonition that right and wrong
are often relative, and sometimes life's rules (like the inane
rules Homer finds posted in the migrant apple-pickers quarters, or
cider house) have to be broken in order to ``make things right.''
</P>
<P>
   But what gives the film its complexity and bite, and makes it
considerably more than a single-minded parable, is its cautionary
subplot involving another of Homer's noble father figures: the
leader (Delroy Lindo) of a group of black migrant workers who also
breaks the rules of life but has much less happy results.
</P>
<P>
   As in his three earlier Hollywood films, Hallstrom has wrapped
this all up in an irresistible package that includes a sweepingly
bittersweet Rachel Portman score, gorgeous photography (shot at
several Norman Rockwellish New England locations) and his own
distinctive directorial touch, which that tends to agreeably
alternate blatant sentimentality with hard-edge realism.
</P>
<P>
   The film is packed with impressive performances: Caine, Maguire,
Lindo and Charlize Theron (achingly perfect as Homer's earthy,
confused love interest) should all be Oscar contenders; and Paul
Rudd, Kathy Baker, Jane Alexander, Kate Nelligan, Kiernan Culkin
and Erykah Badu are equally effective in smaller but memorable
parts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cider House Rules. Directed by Lasse Hallstrom. Screenplay
by John Irving. Cast: Tobey Maguire, Michael Caine, Charlize
Theron, Delroy Lindo, Paul Rudd. Miramax. 129 minutes. Rated PG-13
for abortion and incest themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1530EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0134 </DOCNO>
