</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STUART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STUART LITTLE' A WELCOME ADDITION TO FAMILY-ORIENTED HOLIDAY FILM
FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not be the unqualified crowd-pleaser that the already
phenomenally successful ``Toy Story 2'' has turned out to be, but
``Stuart Little'' _ the second of the holiday movie season's
``family'' affairs _ makes a more than worthy companion piece.
</P>
<P>
   It goes the distance in trying to be a completely faithful movie
equivalent of a classic children's book (by E.B. White, a best
seller for more than 50 years), its computer-generated special
effects are amusing and effective, and its overall charm translates
well to adults.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about the Littles (Geena Davis and Hugh Laurie), a
New York couple who decide to adopt a brother for their only son
(Jonathan Lipnicki), but somehow return from the orphanage with a
child from another species. In fact, a mouse _ Stuart (voice of
Michael J. Fox).
</P>
<P>
   The movie deals with the problems that arise as Stuart's new
brother refuses to accept him, the family cat (voice of Nathan
Lane) wants to have him for lunch, and Stuart himself begins to
feel an ``empty space'' in his heart and longs for his real
parents.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Rob Minkoff (a Disney veteran who co-directed
``The Lion King''), the wonder of the movie is that, like so many
of the great children's stories, it takes a single fantasy
absurdity (a humanoid mouse) and plops it right down into an
otherwise real world, and makes it more or less work.
</P>
<P>
   If the film has a drawback, it is that we never quite fully
accept this improbability on the screen in the same way we can on
paper or even within the total fantasy environment of a cartoon, so
its story can never quite grab the audience on an emotional level.
It's enormously cute, but it doesn't allow us to ever completely
suspend our disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the character of Stuart is endearing, the production
design is splendidly stylized to reflect the illustrations of a
children's book, the script (co-written by M. Night Shyamalan, the
director of ``The Sixth Sense'') has some clever twists, and the
effects _ by John Dykstra (the original ``Star Wars'') are quite
arresting.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the best of these effects are the ones that humanize the
numerous cat characters _ the villains of the piece _ by taking
real cats and computer-generating lip movements and human facial
expressions. This technology has been used a lot recently (in
commercials and films such as ``Dr. Doolittle''), but here it seems
to have reached a pinnacle of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Little. Directed by Rob Minkoff. Screenplay by M. Night
Shyamalan and Greg Brooker. Cast: Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie,
Jonathan Lipnicki, with the voices of Michael J. Fox, Nathan Lane
and Steve Zahn. Columbia. 92 minutes. Rated PG for a few flatulence
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1533EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
