<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANNA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      12-16 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANNA AND THE KING': WHAT? NO SINGING? IS A PUZZLEMENT! 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If any movie could be said to be haunted (maybe cursed is a
better word) by another movie, it is Andy Tennant's picturesque but
stodgy ``Anna and the King.'' The film that does the haunting (and
the cursing) is the 1956 film adaptation of Rodgers and
Hammerstein's classic Broadway musical ``The King and I,'' based on
the same material.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Tennant's film, which stars Jodie Foster and Chow
Yun-Fat in roles played in the earlier movie by Deborah Kerr and
Yul Brynner, you keep expecting the characters to burst into song,
but they never do. And because the mostly solemn dramatic tone of
``Anna and the King'' is so similar to that of ``The King and I,''
the absence of songs comes as a letdown. Especially missed when
their moments arrive are ``Getting to Know You,'' ``A Puzzlement''
and above all ``Shall We Dance?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's unfair to ask ``Anna and the King'' to be
anything but what it is. But ``The King and I'' has become so
deeply embedded in our culture that its version of the true story
that inspired Margaret Landon's book ``Anna and the King of Siam''
supersedes all others in much the same way that ``My Fair Lady''
now looms over Shaw's ``Pygmalion.'' (Before ``The King and I,''
Langdon's work had been adapted into a popular nonmusical 1946
movie starring Irene Dunne and Rex Harrison.)
</P>
<P>
   What the new film offers in place of songs is lush local color
(the film was shot in Malaysia), grand palaces, dazzling pageantry,
one heated battle scene, and a much more enlightened,
multiculturally sensitive perspective on world affairs than the
view offered by the musical. Here the British (with the exception
of Anna) are painted as greedy double-dealing industrial merchants
deviously promoting a 19th-century version of globalization. Anna
ultimately finds herself pulled between her loyalty to Britain and
her pained awareness of her countrymen's racism and deceitfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' is also a misstep for the gifted Ms.
Foster, an actress who seems more interested these days in
sanctifying herself as an old-fashioned heroine than in taking on
dramatically risky roles. Adopting a tentative British accent, she
plays the title character as a virtuous, nobler-than-thou ice queen
and seems even chillier here than she did in ``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Foster's late-'90s screen personality often suggests that
she is aspiring to fill the shoes of the '60s Julie Andrews in
spreading high-minded sweetness and light. But she lacks Ms.
Andrews' vigor and down-to-earth sense of fun, and even when being
playful she emits a certain guardedness, her sharp blue eyes
scrutinizing the surroundings for signs of trouble. Three decades
ago Ms. Andrews may have been mocked as embodying a reactionary
ickiness, but no one accused her of being thin-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Foster's character, Anna Leonowens, a British widow who
traveled to Bangkok in 1862 with her young son to be schoolteacher
to the 58 children of King Mongkut, was among other things a
spirited pioneer taking enormous chances. But Ms. Foster's Anna
hardly seems to have a body. Whatever lust for adventure drove the
character to make that journey is barely apparent in Ms. Foster's
demure, wary performance.
</P>
<P>
   Chow's imperious, polygamous King inevitably begs comparison
with Brynner's. Although this Hong Kong superstar lends the king an
imposing authority (mitigated by moments of softness), his
performance lacks Brynner's terrifying thunder. His carefully
shaded performance may be many things, but it is never truly scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' has the rambling pace of an episodic 1950s
costume drama. As Anna and her cheeky young son, Louis (Tom
Felton), adjust to their new life in Southeast Asia, there are the
inevitable collisions between Siamese and British ways of thinking.
Among the many little dramas that unfold, the most significant
involves Tuptim (Bai Ling), the king's newest wife, who refuses to
be parted from her lover and flees the palace to join him in a
Buddhist monastery.
</P>
<P>
   Later the focus shifts to regional politics and an attempted
coup by the rebellious General Alak (Randall Duk Kim). Siamese
politics and military strategy might be described in these scenes
as the art of the high-stakes bluff.
</P>
<P>
   In evoking the undeclared, unconsummated love between Anna and
the king, the movie is as prim and tight-lipped as its 
lady. And although Chow can be charming, even charismatic, he lacks
Brynner's swashbuckling sensual magnetism. Without any real sparks
between the main characters, ``Anna and the King'' unfolds like an
exotic historical diorama with dramatic vignettes thrown in for
spice.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Anna and the King'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It has scenes of people who have been tortured and one
execution.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANNA AND THE KING'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Andy Tennant; written by Steve Meerson and Peter
Krikes, based on the diaries of Anna Leonowens; director of
photography, Caleb Deschanel; edited by Roger Bondelli; music by
George Fenton; production designer, Luciana Arrighi; produced by
Lawrence Bender and Ed Elbert; released by Fox 2000 Pictures.
Running time: 140 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jodie Foster (Anna), Chow Yun-Fat (King Mongkut), Bai Ling
(Tuptim), Tom Felton (Louis), Syed Alwi (the Kralahome) and Randall
Duk Kim (General Alak).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
