<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUART-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STUART LITTLE': EXTRA! SLY CAT UPSTAGES STUART LITTLE! 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The plucky title character of ``Stuart Little'' may be an
adorable three-inch-tall digital mouse, but the scene stealer in
this delightful screen adaptation of E.B. White's classic
children's book is Stuart's feline nemesis, Snowbell. A white
Chinchilla Persian cat played by five nearly identical felines and
voiced by Nathan Lane in a sly, streetwise New York accent tinged
with hauteur, Snowbell is one of the most fully rounded nonhuman
characters to appear in a family film in quite some time. Every
imperious toss of Snowbell's head and twitch of his petulantly
bowed mouth synchronizes so smoothly with Lane's dialogue that at
times he seems remarkably close to being like a real-life talking
cat.
</P>
<P>
   When Stuart (Michael J. Fox, sounding indefatigably perky and
upbeat) is adopted by the Little family and goes to live with them
in their cozy Manhattan brownstone, Snowbell is outraged that a
mouse should have the status of a family member. Jealous and
resentful, he longs to pounce on the new arrival and devour him.
And because he is a pampered house cat, he is also mortified at the
prospect of becoming a laughing stock among his neighborhood
cronies should they discover he is ``a cat owned by a mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the devious scheme Snowbell contrives to get rid of Stuart, a
pair of mice posing as Stuart's biological parents call on the
Littles to claim their son and take him off to their dingy home in
faraway Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart Little'' sustains a lovely balance between enchantment
and playfulness as it follows Stuart's travels from orphanage, to
Manhattan brownstone, to Brooklyn and back to the Littles. It is
especially witty in portraying the difficult adjustments Stuart
must make in settling comfortably into a human-scale world. One
morning, Stuart nearly drowns when he is accidentally tossed into a
washing machine. He also has problems bonding with his new parents'
human son, George (Jonathan Lipnicki), who was hoping for a
playmate of his own species and size. The two eventually find
common ground when Stuart enters the miniature mouse-size world of
George's electric train set.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's most euphoric moment, the boy and the mouse
collaborate in a toy boat race in Central Park that begins as a
disaster but turns into an unlikely triumph as Stuart pilots the
vessel to victory, navigating the alarmingly choppy waters and
resisting the aggressive collisions of competing boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart Little,'' directed by Rob Minkoff from a screenplay by
M. Night Shyamalan and Greg Brooker, blends images of the real New
York City with an impressionistic storybook version that captures
some of the original book's enchanted mid-1940s ambiance. That
period feeling is enhanced by the look and demeanor of Mr. and Mrs.
Little. As played by Hugh Laurie and Geena Davis, they embody a
young child's-eye view of parents as benign but mysterious figures
who inhabit another world.
</P>
<P>
   In the last third of the movie, the conscience-stricken
impostors confess their hoax to Stuart and send him back to
Manhattan in the toy roadster George gave him. But will Stuart make
it home safely or will Snowbell and his alley cat co-conspirators
intercept him? When Stuart gets lost in Central Park and is stalked
by several hungry cats who plan to divide him up into portions, the
magical city becomes a shadowy nightmarish jungle that is spooky
but not too frightening for young children.
</P>
<P>
   The only element that doesn't completely harmonize with the rest
of the film is the visually unremarkable digital figure of Stuart.
In a movie where everything else is a surreal storybook version of
the commonplace, the character often appears too cartoonish for his
environment. Of course, for many children, who will be charmed by
this fable about learning how to fit in while standing up for
yourself, Stuart's very otherness will be taken as proof that he,
like every child who identifies with him, is special.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Stuart Little'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). Some young children might be frightened by scenes in
which Stuart's life is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STUART LITTLE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Minkoff; written by M. Night Shyamalan and Greg
Brooker, based on the book by E.B. White; director of photography,
Guillermo Navarro; edited by Tom Finan; music by Alan Silvestri;
production designer, Bill Brzeski; senior visual effects
supervisor, John Dykstra; produced by Douglas Wick; released by
Columbia Pictures. Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Geena Davis (Mrs. Little), Hugh Laurie ( Little) and
Jonathan Lipnicki (George Little).
</P>
<P>
   And the voices of: Michael J. Fox (Stuart Little), Nathan Lane
(Snowbell), Chazz Palminteri (Smokey), Steve Zahn (Monty), Jim
Doughan (Lucky), David Alan Grier (Red), Bruno Kirby ( Stout),
Jennifer Tilly (Mrs. Stout) and Stan Freberg (Race Announcer).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
