<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BICENTENNIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BICENTENNIAL MAN' PLAYS LIKE FAITHFUL TESTIMONIAL TO SCI-FI'S
GOLDEN AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Columbus seems an unlikely candidate for the honor, but
his new movie, ``Bicentennial Man,'' represents one of Hollywood's
rare excursions into the realm of ``classic'' science fiction _ so
unsullied by the normal sci-fi movie conventions that it might have
been lifted from the pages of ``Galaxy'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It's far from completely successful, and is sure to disappoint
much of its audience _ both sci-fi purists who will object to Robin
Williams' shtick, and mainstream movie fans who will go in
expecting another riotous masquerade comedy on the order of
Columbus' earlier collaboration with Williams, ``Mrs. Doubtfire.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has an interesting and rather outrageous premise, which
it follows faithfully to a logical end. It's a movie centered on an
idea, and since the sci-fi movie genre has tended to avoid ideas
whenever possible in favor of formula, shoot-em-up action and
monster pieces, it's definitely something different.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a short story (which was later expanded into a novel)
by Isaac Asimov, it's the parable of Andrew (Robin Williams, in a
kind of streamlined-moderne, ``Wizard of Oz'' tin-man outfit), an
android designed to be a domestic servant who enters the service of
a wealthy San Francisco family in the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly turns out that Andrew is not just a machine but a
mutant machine _ the one robot in his line that has curiosity,
judgment and a creative flair that soon has him bonding with
several of the family members (Sam Neill and Embeth Davidtz),
carving models out of wood and making elaborate clocks that become
a flourishing business.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie rapidly jumps through the succeeding years
and decades and centuries as Andrew stays close to the family and
their descendants, continually upgrades himself with each new
generation of advances in computer and artificial intelligence
technology, and becomes more and more human.
</P>
<P>
   The idea it follows is the theory that artificially created
intelligence will, by design or mutation, inevitably take on
increasingly human traits (while humans increasingly repair
themselves with bionic parts) until, at some point, it will be
increasingly hard to tell the difference between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with Columbus (``Home Alone'') at the helm, this idea
is explored with plenty of scenes of both cute and nasty children,
much family bickering and flatulence jokes (his specialty). And
it's structured to contain a string of sight gags and showcase what
appear to be the usual extemporaneous Williams one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bicentennial Man'' increasingly loses even these
commercial considerations and gets bolder and more interesting as
it sweeps through time, and finally becomes a somber, sentimental
and rather profound romantic fantasy that is more true to the
spirit of the Golden Age of science-fiction writing than possibly
any other movie of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Bicentennial Man. Directed by Chris Columbus. Screenplay by
Nicholas Kazan. Cast: Robin Williams, Embeth Davidtz, Sam Neill,
Oliver Platt. Disney/Touchstone. 130 minutes. Rated PG for language
and some sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1610EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
