u e BC-EMPEROR-FILM-REVIEW-N     12-16 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMPEROR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE EMPEROR AND THE ASSASSIN': A BLOODTHIRSTY UNIFICATION OF
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a measure of Hollywood's global reach that Chen Kaige's
historical epic ``The Emperor and the Assassin,'' reputed to be the
most expensive Asian film ever produced, should closely resemble
one of Cecil B. DeMille's grandiose cinematic circuses.
</P>
<P>
   In its blend of pomp, suds, swashbuckling action and moralizing
(about the price of power and imperial ambition), the movie conveys
the sweep of history with a capital H.
</P>
<P>
   The story revolves around Ying Zheng (Li Xuejian), the ruthless
third-century B.C. ruler who became China's first emperor after
conquering and forcibly unifying the country's seven kingdoms. That
conquest, achieved only through a staggering loss of life, proved
tenuous. An epilogue informs us that Ying Zheng's dream of a united
China lasted only 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to draw your own conclusions about whether the story
is a disguised parable about the failed ambitions of Mao Zedong's
Cultural Revolution. Even if it isn't, the movie addresses issues
that haunt Chinese history to this day, about the value of the
individual in the world's most populous country, not to mention the
age-old question of ends justifying means.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Chen's last two films, the modern historical epic
``Farewell, My Concubine'' and the gorgeously chilly, opium-hazed
``Temptress Moon,'' ``The Emperor and the Assassin'' clanks along
in a relatively conventional way.
</P>
<P>
   As its blood-soaked narrative skein of back-stabbing imperial
politics, murderous betrayals and mass slaughter marches forward,
the characters are somewhat dwarfed by the scenery and by stunning
battle sequences that are awesome even by Hollywood's blockbuster
standards.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene of mass slaughter, a large rebel army is caught by
surprise in front of the emperor's palace, surrounded and
methodically mowed down by an opposing army of royal archers who
leave behind a staggering pile of carnage. In another, scores of
children from a city under siege leap off the battlements of the
castle in which they've been imprisoned. Those who survive the jump
are later discovered to have been buried alive.
</P>
<P>
   As for the accuracy of historical events depicted, it is
probably not much greater than in one of Shakespeare's history
plays. Another recent movie, Zhou Xiaowen's ``The Emperor's
Shadow,'' released here last year, surrounded the same emperor with
an entirely different set of schemers, power brokers and
hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   In this version, the two principal characters are the ruthless
emperor and his lover (and childhood playmate and brilliant
strategic ally), Lady Zhao (the great Chinese actress Gong Li). By
the end of the movie, the emperor has betrayed her so completely
that he is left standing alone and friendless in the mess he has
made, rather like a third-century B.C. Michael Corleone.
</P>
<P>
   It is Lady Zhao who concocts a devious plan to unite the
populace behind the emperor by arranging a bogus assassination
attempt that will justify his invasion of the neighboring kingdom
of Yan.
</P>
<P>
   The climactic showdown with Jing Ke (Zhang Fengyi), the fearless
professional killer she recruits for the job (and with whom she
falls deeply in love) takes place at an ambassadorial ceremony
where he appears in disguise and presents Ying Zheng with a box
containing the severed head of an enemy general and a map with a
concealed sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Emperor and the Assassin'' story is crammed with enough
melodrama to fill several soap operas. What sends Ying Zheng
tumbling down a slippery moral slope from imperial idealist to
bloodthirsty despot is his discovery about his parentage, which
drives him to murder anyone with knowledge of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   His mounting desperation eventually drives him to break his vow
to Lady Zhao that he will not invade her homeland. That broken
promise is the ultimate betrayal to the only person he can trust.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the film's treacherous characters, the most vivid is
Changxin (Wang Zhiwen), a wily, androgynous-looking marquis who
plays the clown to Ying Zheng and is the queen mother's lover as
well as her servant. His glittering false smiles and air of
frivolity conceal the heart of a traitor and go-for-broke rebel
leader. In the high-stakes imperial politics of ``The Emperor and
the Assassin,'' every appearance is a deception. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE EMPEROR AND THE ASSASSIN'
</P>
<P>
   `The Emperor and the Assassin' is rated R. (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian.) It has a lot of violence
and gore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Chen Kaige; written (in Mandarin, with English
subtitles) by Wang Peigong and Kaige; director of photography, Zhao
Fei; edited by Zhao Xinxia; music by Zhao Jiping; production
designer, Tu Juhua; produced by Han Sanping, Shirley Kao and Satoru
Iseki; released by Sony Pictures Classics. Running time: 161
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Gong Li (Lady Zhao), Zhang Fengyi (Jing Ke), Li Xuejian
(Ying Zheng, King of Qin), Sun Zhou (Dan, Prince of Yan), Lu Xiaohe
(Gen. Fan Yuqi) and Wang Zhiwen (Marquis Changxin). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-MILLENNIUM-$AD     12-16 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MILLENNIUM-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICANS TO PRAY, PARTY, EVEN COMMUNE WITH ANCESTORS TO MARK NEW
MILLENNIUM
 &HT;    With MEXICO-Y2K-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington and (L) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Dec. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico, one of Latin America's most influential
countries, is welcoming the new millennium with the same clash of
cultures its lived with for 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church is inviting its faithful to attend Mass for
a night of prayer and devotion to Jesus Christ, born 2000 years ago
in a land the original Mexicans didn't know existed until the
1500s.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City is holding a daylong party to celebrate Mexico's
``diversity,'' with a parade, dancing and music along its main
Paseo de la Reforma boulevard and in the city's gigantic main
square. Acapulco, Puerto Vallarta and other resort cities that are
selling inflated hotel packages for New Year's Eve are also
promising public entertainment and big fireworks shows.
</P>
<P>
   For those who wish to commune with their indigenous ancestors,
rock promoters here are putting on a New Age musical and dance
extravaganza next to Mexico's ancient Teotihuacan pyramids north of
the capital city. The pyramids, which rival those of Egypt in bulk,
were begun in 100 A.D., making them almost as old as Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The civilization in the area stretches back to 400 years before
Christ _ a reminder that ancient Mexico was home to cities that
were more sophisticated than most European urban centers during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   With the pyramids of the Sun and the Moon looming behind them,
Mexico's folklore ballet is scheduled to perform on New Year's Eve
at Teotihuacan along with Indian dancers, mariachi bands and
marimba groups.
</P>
<P>
   The rock line-up is ambitious. In addition to several famous
Mexican bands that are confirmed to perform, promoters are still
trying to get at least two of the following acts: rocker Peter
Gabriel, the Pretenders, and English early 70's bands like Jethro
Tull, King Crimson, Yes or the Moody Blues.
</P>
<P>
   None of the big international acts is confirmed yet, but
promoters are putting a positive spin on the event, which is called
the ``Last Night of the Millennium'' and is expensive by Mexican
standards. Tickets are the equivalent of more than US$40 tickets in
advance or US$75 at the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people care if they see Peter Gabriel or the
Moody Blues,'' said Carlos Barba, an assistant to the directors of
Rockotitlan, the Mexican company putting on the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is this is going to be at Teotihuacan,''
Barba said. ``We're the first to have obtained permits to put on a
show there.''
</P>
<P>
   Teotihuacan, which means ``the place of Gods,'' had already been
abandoned for more than 700 years by the time the Spanish
conquistadors marched into Mexico in the early 1500s. At its peak,
the complex of ceremonial pyramids and other structures was home to
between 100,000 and 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The sound system for the ``Last Night of the Millennium'' will
be designed for an audience of 200,000, according to the promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's bash is going to be a ``party of citizenship
participation,'' said Alejandro Aura, director of the city's
Culture Institute. Residents of all the city's boroughs have been
invited to make floats for a parade, and disposable cameras will be
handed out around the city so people can record their version of
the last night of this century, Aura said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is different than just offering entertainment to a
passive public,'' Aura added.
</P>
<P>
   But along the city's Paseo de la Reforma, dancers and musicians
will play into the dawn of Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment will be diverse and will celebrate Mexicans'
various European and indigenous roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a show by conchero dancers (Indian dancers who wear
walnut shells on their ankles) is as valid as a show by a string
quartet,'' Aura said.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's main square, four giant screens will transmit
celebrations from around the world as the new millennium begins to
gradually dawn. A huge fireworks display is planned, along with a
mariachi band singing the traditional Mexican birthday song, ``Las
Mananitas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific coast city of Puerto Vallarta, the city is
inviting celebrants to wear white to mark a peaceful change of the
century. Hotels and restaurants are also trying to sell inflated
hotel packages demanding four- or five-day stays at double or
triple normal room rates.
</P>
<P>
   Air fares to resorts have soared, too. Even flights to
industrial towns that are near resorts are double the price now. A
short flight from Mexico City to the Pacific coast city of Lazaro
Cardenas, for example, costs about $400 instead of less than $200.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent feature of Lazaro Cardenas is its oil
refinery. But it is also less than two hours away from Ixtapa, one
of Mexico's prime beach resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents are reporting that air fares and hotel rates may
start to drop as Dec. 31 draws closer and many hotels still have
vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Sanchez, a 32-year-old Mexico City computer programmer,
said he's bucking all the hype over the new millennium and planning
to go the traditional route. He'll toast the New Year with his
family and attend Mass at his church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a special Mass with a message of hope
for renewing our faith,'' Sanchez said. ``The beginning of the new
millennium doesn't mean much change for us. I think that all the
publicity on the part of different organizations and businesses is
contaminating us and forcing us to think we have to do something
different at this year's end.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe Zamora, a 20-year-old college student said he'll be
going to church, too, if just to please his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great. I'm witnessing the change of one
millennium to another,'' Zamora said. ``But the reality is the
situation in our country isn't going to change simply because of
the magical change of a clock.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
