<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON ALBUM OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q-TIP: ``Amplified'' (Arista).
</P>
<P>
   Tribe Called Quest disbanded last year, but its great insight
lingers on with Q-Tip's ``Amplified,'' the first solo album by a
Tribe member. Where hip-hop is saturated with booming bass lines
and larger-than-life voices, Q-Tip defies both mandates to breeze
through the din.
</P>
<P>
   The tracks on ``Amplified,'' produced by Q-Tip and Jay Dee, pare
bass lines to clipped syncopations, and Q-Tip raps without rushing
or raising his voice. Although Busta Rhymes and a self-parodying
Korn show up at the end of the album, most of ``Amplified'' is
Q-Tip on his own or with the women he's sweet-talking.
</P>
<P>
   He's secure in his boasts and playful in his seductions, and the
syncopations of his monotone are as much percussion as speech. With
electronic blips, tersely swinging drumbeats, two-chord vamps and
tightly rationed doses of melody, ``Amplified'' turns weightless,
transparent rhythms into hypnosis. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
