<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANNA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANNA' DOESN'T COMPARE AS WELL TO OLDER VERSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood just can't seem to get enough of the story of Anna
Leonowens and her friendship with the King of Siam. It's given us
the 1946 ``Anna and the King of Siam,'' the 1956 version of Rogers
and Hammerstein's immortal Broadway musical, ``The King and I''
(both multi-Oscar-winners), and a short-lived 1972 TV series.
</P>
<P>
   This year, we've had a watered-down, animated version of ``The
King and I'' aimed at children (with half the R&AMP;H songs missing);
and now, only a few months later, ``Anna and the King,'' a splashy
new, non-musical version (ostensibly based on a ``new'' source,
Leonowens' journal) starring Jodie Foster as Anna and Chow Yun-Fat
as the King.
</P>
<P>
   This latest _ and at 140 minutes, longest _ version of the tale
definitely has its moments, and looks so stunning that it works on
the level of an historical epic. In most other ways, however, it
pales in comparison to its two classic predecessors, and also just
generally feels like one too many trips to the well.
</P>
<P>
   The script follows the basic story beats of '46 and '56
versions: Anna, a spunky British widow comes to Bangkok in 1862 to
tutor the numerous children of King Rama IV, they butt heads but
gradually come to appreciate and learn valuable lessons from one
another, and she helps him keep Siam free from European domination.
</P>
<P>
   But in this take, the conflict between the pair is toned way
down (Chow's King is a much kinder, gentler fellow than the
swaggering bully created by Rex Harrison and Yul Brynner), they
seem to adore each other from first sight, and much of the inherent
comedy _ and charm _ generated by all the sparks is lost.
</P>
<P>
   By far the best thing about this new production is its visuals,
with gorgeous cinematography (by Caleb Deschanel), convincing
computer-generated backgrounds of 19th century Bangkok, and the
movie year's most impressive set _ a sumptuously detailed
recreation of Bangkok's Grand Palace, built in Malaysia after the
Thais refused permission to film in the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Director Andy Tennant (``Fools Rush In,'' ``Ever After'') and
his writers, Steve Meerson and Peter Krikes (``Star Trek IV''),
also aim rather high, spending much screen time on the intricate
politics of the story, and refusing to dumb-down the King's complex
situation and threats both internal (from Siamese rebels) and
external (from the European powers).
</P>
<P>
   But by writing in so many conspiracy and battle scenes, it
almost ceases to be a character-driven romantic comedy, to become
more of an action spectacular. Surprisingly, given Tennant's thirst
for authenticity, the film also works to a strangely bogus climax
that seems clumsily designed to give Jodie Foster a big moment as
an action heroine.
</P>
<P>
   As the King, Hong Kong's Chow Yun-Fat makes a powerful and
stately presence, and _ if not quite the star turn of Yul Brynner
in his prime _ he at least does his own elegant and enjoyable
interpretation. Be warned, however, that due either to his accent
or poor sound recording, about half of his dialogue is
unintelligible.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Foster also does her best, and gives her usual intense and
heart-felt performance, but the part requires the movie-star
sparkle of an Irene Dunne or the aristocratic charm of a Deborah
Kerr. In comparison to either of these two earlier Annas, her
performance here seems self-conscious and rather dull.
</P>
<P>
   Anna and the King. Directed by Andy Tennant. Screenplay by Steve
Meerson and Peter Krikes. Cast: Jodie Foster, Chow Yun-Fat, Bai
Ling. 20th Century-Fox. 140 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1615EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
