<HEADLINE>
`RIDE' IS ANG LEE'S THRILLING TAKE ON THE AMERICAN CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it about the myth of the West that so appeals to
overseas film directors?
</P>
<P>
   While American moviemakers like John Ford once embraced its
loner heroism, contemporary filmmakers (and audiences) have tended
to shy away from the wildness of the old West _ save for Clint
Eastwood's revisionist ``Unforgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   But recently the British director Stephen Frears (``The Hi-lo
Country'') and Taiwanese Ang Lee have gotten back in the saddle and
made an effort to reinterpret this movie staple from the point of
view of the outsider.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ride With the Devil,'' Lee's Civil War drama, he's mixed
zen with a Larry McMurtry sensibility, utilizing a cross-cultural
troupe of characters with a cause. In this case, men of the South
are mobilized to form a guerrilla warfare unit of Bushwhackers
wreaking havoc on the invading Union army and its sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Two childhood friends, the poor German immigrant Jake Roedel
(Tobey Maguire) and wealthy plantation son Jack Bull Chiles (Skeet
Ulrich), enlist alongside leader Black John (James Caviezel), loose
cannon Pitt Mackeson (Jonathan Rhys Meyer), George Custer lookalike
George Clyde (Simon Baker) and his former slave, the quiet but
observant Daniel Holt (Jeffrey Wright).
</P>
<P>
   The men diligently and violently attempt to beat back a
formidable foe and face horrific deaths, destruction and decimation
not only to their own hides, but to a Deep South that they deeply
love.
</P>
<P>
   Lee cuts loose in the action sequences and certainly knows how
to stage a battle. The sight of Southern desperados holding off an
advancing Yankee unit in rather gentlemanly form is both thrilling
and anguishing. It adds another feather to the cap of a director
who has never shied away from experimenting with every genre,
including gay romantic comedy (``The Wedding Banquet''), Jane
Austen period piece (``Sense and Sensibility'') and the breakdown
of a family torn apart by the confusing '60s (``The Ice Storm'').
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Lonesome Dove,'' which ``Ride With the Devil'' often
resembles, these weathered-but-traditional men face the end of an
era as well as a way of life as they've known it and an air of
sadness and change permeates the film. But unlike McMurtry's epic
novel about two old friends and Texas Rangers who embark on a
cattle drive north to renew their lives, ``Ride With the Devil''
doesn't offer much texture or depth of character.
</P>
<P>
   One principal is killed off before the halfway mark and much of
the rest of the film serves as a memorial to him that sparks a
tenuous attraction between Jake and a widow named Sue Lee (Jewel),
who was in love with the dead character. While Tobey Maguire and
the singer verbally spar (a sure sign they're meant for each
other), the deeper love affair in ``Ride With the Devil'' lies
between its two outcasts _ Holt and Jake _ who, being black and an
immigrant, find they have only each other for true and equal
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has cast his film with the cream of rising actors. While
they all contribute as much as they can in such a large ensemble
enterprise, it's Wright, who played the painter Jean-Michel
Basquiat in Julian Schnabel's ``Basquiat,'' who steals the show as
an insular man with a unique wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   As the war ends, the film fumbles for an appropriate resolution,
but doesn't find one with any dramatic tension. After such a
thrilling ride through a compelling war story, with its alliances
and losses, that old standby, love, feels anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   Ride With the Devil. Directed by Ang Lee. Written by James
Schamus. Cast: Tobey Maguire, Skeet Ulrich, Jeffrey Wright, Jewel.
USA Films. 138 minutes. Rated R for violence, brief nudity,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
