<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rembrandts, Anyone?
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any seasoned collector of old masters will remember
the two auctions of extraordinary drawings from Chatsworth, the
Derbyshire home of the Duke of Devonshire, at Christie's in London
in 1984 and 1987. Both were landmark sales at which institutions
like the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles and collectors like
Ian Woodner snapped up drawings by artists including Rembrandt,
Barocci, Poussin and Rubens at record prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sale contained drawings you were just not going to see on
the market again,'' said Noel Annesley, deputy chairman of
Christie's. ``It broke all the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in what is considered something of an event, Christie's in
New York will be selling two Rembrandts from the Chatsworth sales
on Jan. 28. The drawings come from the estate of Michael S.
Currier, a rancher and philanthropist who was a great-grandson of
Andrew W. Mellon, the financier who was a founder of the National
Gallery of Art in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Currier also collected Asian art. ``The penwork in both drawings
is surprisingly similar to the Chinese,'' Annesley said.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings are both landscapes showing different views of
Amsterdam. ``The Ramparts Near the Bulwark Beside the City Gate at
St. Anthonispoort, Amsterdam'' was drawn on the northeast side of
the city, a few minutes from Rembrandt's house.
</P>
<P>
   His technique suggests it was drawn between 1648 and 1652,
Christie's experts say. Currier bought the drawing in the 1987 sale
for $2.2 million. Christie's now expects it to bring $1.8 million
to $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The other drawing, ``The Bulwark de Rose and the Windmill de
Smeerpot,'' depicts a group of houses near the artist's home. The
bulwark, on the west side of Amsterdam, was the last of three
bastions that ran from the sea in a straight line.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow cast on the ground by the row of houses on the left
indicates that the scene was sketched on a summer morning and
presented as if the viewer were standing in the landscape. Currier
bought it at the 1984 sale for $686,782. Christie's now expects it
to sell for $1.8 million to $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Annesley said he thought the drawings would appeal not only to
old master devotees but also to buyers in other collecting
categories. ``In today's market you can still buy superb examples
of old master drawings by great artists, which is quite impossible
to do with paintings,'' he said. ``There's enough out there that it
is still possible to form a great old master drawings collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital Diversity
</P>
<P>
   As more and more artists explore film, video and Internet art,
institutions like the Brooklyn Academy of Music are expanding their
programs to include the best multimedia work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new artist's horizon that we want to work toward
developing,'' said Joseph V. Melillo, the academy's executive
producer. ``For the next Whitney Biennial to have Internet art,
well, that's the shot heard round the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This week the academy announced plans to create an in-house
digital media lab in its main building in Fort Greene. The academy
has also established ``Arts in Multimedia,'' a two-year initiative
with Lucent Technologies in which artists work with scientists in a
virtual studio to create projects using new media.
</P>
<P>
   The academy is also introducing a series of Web documentaries on
the academy's Web site, www.bam.org. The new digital media lab is
scheduled to be up and running by February.
</P>
<P>
   Just who will be allowed to use the lab will depend on those
selected for its ``Multimedia'' program. An advisory panel of art
and media experts will review proposals from artists who have been
invited by the academy and Lucent to apply to the program. Three
artists will be chosen and will become partners with researchers
from Bell Labs, the research and development arm of Lucent, on
their project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a conference last month in Manhattan at Lucent's
headquarters to introduce the work of the invited artists and the
researchers who were interested in the program,'' Melillo said.
``We will get 19 proposals to review in January and from there will
choose the three artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning artists will start work in February and have three
months to create a project, to be exhibited in May. Although the
commitment from Lucent is for only two years, Melillo said the
academy was committed to multimedia art and would continue
developing more such projects.
</P>
<P>
   Cube Squared
</P>
<P>
   Jay Jopling, one of London's most influential contemporary-art
dealers, has gained a reputation for showing the work of many young
British artists _ like Damien Hirst and Marc Quinn, who were
included in ``Sensation,'' the exhibition at the Royal Academy in
London and the Brooklyn Museum of Art _ before they were famous.
</P>
<P>
   While Jopling's shows have had huge reverberations in the art
world, they were conceived out of White Cube, his tiny gallery on
Duke Street, St. James'. ``I think it's the smallest art gallery in
Europe,'' Jopling said. ``But I've never shown an artist twice in
that space.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jopling will have an alternative space. In April he plans to
open a considerably larger second gallery in Hoxton Square, in
London's East End, just north of the financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Mike Rundell, the architect who designed Hirst's
restaurant Pharmacy in Notting Hill, the new space will be called
White Cube2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The location is crucial,'' Jopling said. ``This is a vital
cultural neighborhood at the moment, a place where the local
council allows artists to live and work.''
</P>
<P>
   The gallery is to open with an exhibition of work by many of
Britain's top contemporary artists, including Hirst, Jake and Dinos
Chapman, Tracey Emin, Antony Gormley, Mona Hatoum, Sam Taylor-Wood
(who is married to Jopling) and Gavin Turk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
