<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-16 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG A FORCE IN LIGHTING AND CRAFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)  (af) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How's this for a quintessential New York client list:
the New York Stock Exchange, City Hall, Waldorf-Astoria, Morgan
Bank, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Ronald McDonald House and
Trinity Church, on Wall Street?
</P>
<P>
   These institutions have all been clients of Rambusch, a small
101-year-old family business that makes high-quality custom light
fixtures, stained-glass windows, mosaic murals and wrought-iron
gates for projects all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition tracing a century of Rambusch commissions in
perhaps every conceivable style can be seen at the National Arts
Club through Jan. 1. The show, and an accompanying booklet with a
self-guided walking tour of selected Rambusch commissions in New
York, resembles a history of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been involved in the initial construction of
dozens of buildings, as well as scores of major historic
restoration projects, including the Shubert Theater, the Moorish
interior of the Central Synagogue and St. Bartholomew's Episcopal
Church, on Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting-edge projects include lights commissioned by the
architect Michael Gabellini for the clothing designer Jil Sander's
headquarters in Hamburg and boutiques in America.
</P>
<P>
   Now a fourth-generation family enterprise, Rambusch was founded
in 1898 by Frode C.V. Rambusch, 29, a Danish immigrant, who decided
to seek his fortune in New York after attending the Royal Art
Academy in Copenhagen and schools of applied art in Berlin and
Munich. An accomplished painter, he opened a company specializing
in decorative murals, ecclesiastical ornaments and wrought-iron
metalwork.
</P>
<P>
   He was bankrolled by a partner, William F. Hencken, a New Yorker
and Princeton graduate whose family was seeking business experience
for their son. The family advanced $2,500 to establish the Rambusch
Glass and Decorating Co., at 160 Fifth Avenue, where McKim, Mead &AMP;
White had its architectural offices.
</P>
<P>
   Frode Rambusch was quick to see the potential of Thomas Edison's
tungsten filament lamp, the light bulb. In the show are drawings,
from 1908, of Rambusch's ``light shield,'' a hammered copper
fixture that covered the light socket and irritatingly bright bare
bulb. His ever-evolving light fixtures were adopted by churches,
opera houses, vaudeville theaters and movie palaces.
</P>
<P>
   His sons, in turn, invented the famous Downlite, a ceiling
fixture patented in 1936. The company's art-metal workshop did the
lighting for the Daily News building of 1930, the interiors and
exteriors of the many Horn &AMP; Hardart Automats and about 1,000 movie
theaters, including the Fulton in Brooklyn and long-gone Roxy in
Manhattan. (There are now 1,082 variations on the Downlite.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, the company added a stained-glass studio. The show has
a stained-glass window, with accompanying drawings and mock-ups,
made for the McCormick Spice Co. headquarters in Sparks, Md.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Rambush fabricated the abstract stained-glass facade of
the American Airlines terminal at Kennedy International Airport for
the architects Kahn &AMP; Jacobs. The wall, which is 23 feet high and
330 feet long, is thought to be the largest stained-glass window in
the world. Mosaic projects in the show include a sanctuary wall
that is 64 feet high and sheathed in gold mosaic.
</P>
<P>
   Rambusch made metal decorations for ocean liners and sculptures
for public buildings, including one for the 1939 World's Fair, a
metal sculpture for the Science and Education Building, which is in
the show.
</P>
<P>
   During the Depression, the company was saved by its many
commissions for houses of worship, including marble lecterns, metal
candlesticks, hammered-silver communion cups, tabernacles and
crosses. The company did the Fifth Avenue lobby for the Empire
State Building, the interiors for the Stork Club and Century
Association and the original ceiling of Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, its metal shops created a prototype for
radar antenna. The company also applied stained-glass techniques to
the art of camouflage: before-and-after aerial photos of the Glen
L. Martin aircraft plant in Baltimore show how three million square
feet of plant and runways were painted so they could not be
detected from the air.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Rambusch makes architectural decorations and lighting
fixtures for such household names as the architects Frank Gehry,
Robert A.M. Stern and Charles Gwathmey. The company is now run by
two fourth-generation Rambusches: the twins Edwin and Martin
Rambusch, age 33.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin is in charge of the lighting division and Martin the
crafts (art metal, stained glass, mosaics, tapestries and
liturgical designs and furnishings). Their father, Viggo Bech
Ansgar Rambusch, continues to work on ecclesiastical commissions.
The company employs more than 40 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one Rambusch style,'' said Catha Grace Rambusch,
the guest curator of the show, company archivist and mother of the
twins. ``Everything is custom-designed and resolved in coordination
with the design of the job. We have a guild system. The client
works with our designers, engineers and craftsmen, who tell them
when a design will or will not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambusch did the complicated light fixtures for the decorative
arts rooms at the Getty Museum in California; they were hired by
Howard Brandstom, a New York lighting consultant, who worked with
the designer Thierry Despont on the Getty project. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The Rambusches had to develop a brand new piece of equipment
for the Getty,'' Brandstom said. ``They came up with a suggested
solution, a fixture that is a wall washer, a downlight and accent
light, all coming out of one small aperture in the ceiling _
instead of having 60 or 70 fixtures hanging like dead bats from
tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's prototype of the chrome-plated copper fixture that
Gehry designed for the Conde Nast lunchroom at 4 Times Square, to
open this winter, looks as soft as a handkerchief floating in
midair. In fact, it houses both an uplight and a downlight. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The cafeteria commission is the second with Gehry: Edwin
Rambusch spent three years creating the optics for his Bilbao
Museum in Spain. Rambusch craftsmen also fabricated the new
8-foot-tall bracket lanterns outside Baruch College, which were
inspired by the Strozzi Palace in Milan. Edwin Rambusch worked with
Davis, Brody architects, who transformed a former IRT subway
headquarters for Baruch.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shannon of Moed de Armas &AMP; Shannon, architects in New York,
commissioned light fixtures for the lobby of the Bear Stearns
building at 245 Park Avenue. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The company is as modern now as it was in 1900,'' he said.
``They understand the architect's ideas and goals. They get into
all the details and have the highest levels of engineering, finish
and craftsmanship. The bronze fixtures at 245 Park look like Swiss
watches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
