<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Range of cosmetic brands offers different strokes for different
folks
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All cosmetics are not created equal.
</P>
<P>
   So we asked Tina Russell, makeup artist at the Don and Sylvia
Shaw Salon at Park Place near Perimeter Mall, to sample and rate
three brands she had never used before. Russell also offered tips
on how to apply the makeup.
</P>
<P>
   She experimented with Versace, a high-end line created by the
late designer three years ago; Stila, a moderately priced product
from Estee Lauder, which has a line of new fall colors; and Sonia
Kashuk, an inexpensive brand made exclusively for Target, which hit
stores in September. Our models were three students from Bauder
College in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Russell found:
</P>
<P>
   VERSACE
</P>
<P>
   (modeled by Dorscheiia Jackson)
</P>
<P>
   THE BASICS: Long Lasting Hydrating Cream Concealer (V2004, $30)
blends well, especially on darker skin tones, and goes on smoothly.
Extra Creamy Compact Foundation (V2008, $40) provides excellent
coverage for people with flawed or unevenly colored skin, but it
still gives a natural appearance without a heavy feel.
</P>
<P>
   CHEEKS: Compact blush (V2062, $36) has built-in shimmer and is
easy to apply without blotching.
</P>
<P>
   EYES: Comfort eye pencil (V2000, $23) lines the lid and rim of
the eye. Glides on easily without smearing. Rich colors have good
holding power. Eyeshadow Trio (V2052, V2053, $30), applied to lid
and crease, blends well, goes on smoothly and is true to its color.
White highlighter ($23), used under the brow, is a true white color
with shimmer that helps open up the eye for a more youthful
appearance. Ideal for women who like to wear diamond, silver or
clear crystal earrings.
</P>
<P>
   LIPS: Lipliner (V2011, $23) is applied to the rim of the mouth
and over the entire lip to make lipstick last longer. The liner has
a satiny finish and goes on smoothly. Lipstick (V2054, $23) is
creamy and shiny, with a rich, smooth finish.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: A high-quality brand that contains everything a
professional makeup artist looks for in a cosmetic. Great for
people who want a polished look with a rich color and lightweight
texture. Might be a bit pricey for someone who doesn't wear makeup
often.
</P>
<P>
   STILA
</P>
<P>
   (modeled by Linda Mom)
</P>
<P>
   THE BASICS: Liquid foundation (Shade b, $30) is extremely
lightweight and translucent. Blends quickly into skin and
disappears. The look is natural, but it doesn't cover flaws well,
even when used with Stick Concealer (Shade b, $17). Pressed powder
($32), applied over foundation, does a good job of eliminating
shine.
</P>
<P>
   CHEEKS: Brava cheek powder ($15), lightly applied, is a soft hue
that looks natural and stays on well.
</P>
<P>
   EYES: Pewter eye shadow ($15) on the lid has a nice shimmer,
goes on well and can double as an eyeliner. Viola shadow ($15),
applied to the crease, goes on well and blends easily. Color turns
out rosy with a slight shimmer. Twilight shadow ($15), applied
under the brow, gives definition and depth to the eye.
</P>
<P>
   LIPS: Lipstick (Joan, $16) is creamy, easy to apply and holds
color. Has a shimmery, wet look.
</P>
<P>
   ADDED TOUCH: All Over Shimmer ($28) comes in a tube and can be
gently dabbed over the entire face, after makeup is applied. Also
blends well on neck and shoulders for a subtle shimmer when wearing
low-cut dresses or tops.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: Eye shadow colors are trendy and great for
evening. But the foundation needs to be boosted with a dual
powder/foundation to provide better coverage for someone with
flawed skin or discolorations.
</P>
<P>
   SONIA KASHUK
</P>
<P>
   (modeled by Jessica Hanna)
</P>
<P>
   THE BASICS: Perfecting liquid foundation (Creme No. 6, $9.99)
comes in a pump for easy control. Good for complexions with golden
tones. Dual coverage powder foundation (Sand, $9.99) helps liquid
foundation stay on longer and provides added coverage.
</P>
<P>
   CHEEKS: Beautifying blush (Dawn, $7.99), dusted on the cheeks,
goes on smoothly and has a nice color that holds well after being
applied.
</P>
<P>
   EYES: Enhance Eye Color (Plum, $4.99) for lids blends well and
goes on subtly. A good complement for people with light brown or
hazel eyes. Enhance Eye Color (Sable, $4.99) works well in the
crease for definition and under the rim of the eye to keep other
makup from smudging. Enhance Eye Color (Bronze, $4.99) gives a nice
shimmer to the eye when used under the brow.
</P>
<P>
   LIPS: Lip definer (Wine, $4.99), used on the rim of the mouth
and over the entire lip, looks more like fuchsia when applied.
Luxury Lip Color (Rosewood, $5.99) looks moist and shiny when
applied to the lip and topped with lip gloss (Flirt, $5.99).
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: Good quality for the price, but the foundation
and concealer don't provide enough coverage for flawed skin. A good
set of brushes is a must to apply and blend this makeup properly.
</P>
<P>
   AND WHAT ABOUT NEW YEAR'S EVE?
</P>
<P>
   The glam face for the big night will have shimmer and shine,
Russell says.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes will be adorned in silver or gold shadows to make a
dramatic statement, or as an accent to smoky shades of plum, mauve
or pewter.
</P>
<P>
   Lips will glisten in tones of wine and roses, with a dab of
metallic shadow or gloss in the center of the lip for added
sparkle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't be too glitzy. You don't want to overdo it,''
advises Russell, noting that subtle beauty is still the look of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
