<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-WINONA-RYDER-IN-GIRL-INTERRUPTED-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINONA, INTERRUPTED: REAL-LIFE MENTAL ILLNESS SHAPES RYDER'S
ON-SCREEN PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Winona Ryder in
a scene from ``Girl, Interrupted.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In her powerful new film ``Girl, Interrupted,'' Winona Ryder
plays a young woman who, after her first visit to a psychiatrist,
is heavily drugged and locked up for two years in a mental
institution.
 &HT;    It's a sad, shocking story _ all the more so for being based on
fact _ but it would seem to be a million miles from anything the
popular, 28-year-old actress could know anything about.
 &HT;    But appearances can be deceiving. Ryder, star of films such as
``Beetlejuice (1988), ``Mermaids'' (l990), ``Little Women'' (1994)
and ``Alien Resurrection'' (1997), has known some of those same
experiences firsthand.
 &HT;    ``I could have been that woman,'' Ryder says, ``and so I
strongly identified with what she went through. I too have been a
patient in a mental hospital and have suffered from depression,
panic and anxiety attacks.''
 &HT;    At one point, she adds, she felt ``too sensitive to be living in
the world.''
 &HT;    The slender actress, who has specialized in playing troubled
teen-agers, talked frankly about her own emotional problems on the
eve of the film's Los Angeles opening on Dec. 21 _ it will open
nationwide on Jan. 14 _ because, she says, she wants to help other
young women who may find themselves in the same boat.
 &HT;    ``Girl, Interrupted'' is based on Susanna Kaysen's best-selling
1993 memoir about a group of teen-age girls in a New England mental
hospital. Ryder plays the author, who in the late 1960s was
diagnosed as suffering from borderline-personality disorder.
 &HT;    Ryder read Kaysen's work after her own breakdown, and was
shocked and then delighted to discover that she wasn't unique and,
in fact, that her own life had a great deal in common with the
author's nightmarish experiences.
 &HT;    ``Susanna saw a psychiatrist for 20 minutes,'' the actress says,
``and then she was locked up for two years.''
 &HT;    One of the most successful stars of her generation, Ryder would
seem to have the world in her hands. She keeps company with
Oscar-winning writer/actor Matt Damon, best known for ``Good Will
Hunting'' (l997). She lives in a $2.5 million, four-bedroom Beverly
Hills estate, and is a fixture on lists of the most beautiful women
in the world.
 &HT;    But the waifish actress admits that, by the time she was l9, she
was having horrible anxiety attacks which eventually culminated in
a full-fledged breakdown.
 &HT;    The pressure was unrelenting, she recalls. She was working
nonstop while trying to cope with the breakup of her first serious
romance, with Johnny Depp, her co-star in ``Edward Scissorhands''
(1990). And their shattered relationship was being played out on
front pages around the world.
 &HT;    ``I grew up in front of everybody,'' the actress says. ``I got
my first pimples on film, I went through puberty on film and even
had my first period, literally, on film. At the time my boyfriend
was an actor, and everything we did together was photographed and
endlessly written about. My whole life was amplified for public
consumption.
 &HT;    ``And every time I complained about it,'' she adds, ``I was
called a brat. So I learned I wasn't supposed to complain about
anything _ the message was that we were perfect people who led
perfect lives.
 &HT;    ``Of course that's not true.''
 &HT;    Gradually her anxiety attacks, fueled by her bottled-up
frustrations, became more severe.
 &HT;    ``My heart would be thumping at 90 miles an hour and I'd be
sweating,'' she recalls. ``I was l9, felt totally alone and felt I
couldn't tell anybody in the world how I was feeling. It's horrible
and scary not to be able to describe that terror. You're on a plane
and you want desperately to get off. So you turn to the stranger in
the next seat and you want to say something, but you don't know
what you want to say.''
 &HT;    Ryder says she had no idea what was happening to her. Finally,
desperate, she checked herself into a mental hospital for a week.
 &HT;    ``It was scary,'' she recalls, ``and a lot like the hospital
wing in `Girl Interrupted.'''
 &HT;    Eventually, Ryder says, she learned that she had to help
herself.
 &HT;    ``No matter how rich you are,'' she says, ``no matter how much
you pay some hospital or doctor, they can't fix you. They can't
give you a secret answer to anything that's going to make you all
better. You have to figure it out for yourself.''
 &HT;    When she learned to talk about her attacks to friends, she adds,
she discovered many of them had experienced similar symptoms,
including her ``Girl, Interrupted'' co-star Brittany Murphy. Only
then did she begin to be able to control her episodes of panic.
 &HT;    ``Over the years I got a response from other women who were also
grateful to know that they were not alone,'' she says. ``For me,
reading Susanna's book when I was 21 showed me that what happened
to me wasn't so unusual. I discovered that these are feelings that
we all have _ it's not just an isolated incident that happens to
one girl.
 &HT;    ``In America,'' she adds, ``I know it's something that's
sweeping the country. It's about the loneliness that we all go
through.''
 &HT;    Like her, Ryder says, many women keep their problems hidden for
as long as they can.
 &HT;    ``You get scared you're not going to be able to control it,''
she explains. ``I have now made a conscious choice to talk about
it, although as actors we have a rough time if we mention we're
going through a depression. We get slammed and called utter brats.
 &HT;    ``We're told we should be grateful for everything,'' Ryder says.
``And it's true, I live a very privileged life. We're sickeningly
well paid, get these amazing bonuses and have these very charmed
lives.
 &HT;    ``But I also have the same pressures that any other human being
has, only amplified because of the work I've chosen to do and
because our lives are a lot more public.''
 &HT;    Reading ``Girl, Interrupted'' convinced Rider to produce a movie
version, and to star in it as well.
 &HT;    ``I was so drawn to this character,'' she says. ``She was so
brutally honest about herself without being self-indulgent _ that's
pretty rare in literature, especially for a female character. She
also kept a journal, and so do I.''
 &HT;    But it wasn't an easy movie to get made. Hollywood was hardly
enraptured over the prospect of what some called ``an all-girl
`Cuckoo's Nest.''' It took six years for the cameras to roll _ long
enough that Ryder was beginning to feel that she might be too old
to play a teen-ager.
 &HT;    Aided by her slight frame and youthful face, she pulls it off _
no surprise, since she admits that she'd have done almost anything
to play the role. Long at her best in moody, troubled roles, Ryder
complains that, when it thinks of movies for female audiences or
meaty roles for actresses, Hollywood is more inclined to make
softer, romantic ``popcorn movies'' such as ``Runaway Bride''
(1999).
 &HT;    ``I'm not out to badmouth that film,'' she says, ``but most of
what is offered to young women in film is terrible _ it's really an
insult. Most films don't raise issues or bring good conversation to
the table.
 &HT;    ``We need to start offering women something they can relate
to.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Girl, Interrupted,'' consult
the official Website at www.girlinterrupted.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
