<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1033 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-LONDON-COED19-COX     12-16 1787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-COED19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In London, tea for two with Uncle Cheap
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Nearly all her life, she had been promised a trip to
Europe. We had planned on Paris for her 16th birthday, but we ended
up at Barnsley Gardens in northwest Georgia. Now we were at
Tiger-Tiger, a ridiculously popular disco just a few steps from
Leicester Square, the most frenzied tourist magnet in all of
London.
</P>
<P>
   My niece Renee, a freshman from South Georgia College in
Douglas, Ga., who spent the fall semester at the University of
London, was yukking it up with two of her classmates. Imagine three
18-year-old Georgia peaches done up in their best Felicity Shagwell
outfits. Fresh off the plane, I was jet-lagged, wobbly, just trying
to keep a grip. And I was about to discover that family
resemblances are sometimes more than skin deep.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   First, an audacious young blade sidled up to our table to
inquire as to whom exactly I might be. ``No, I'm not her father,''
I sniffed. ``I'm her uncle!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, trying to make small talk with one of Renee's friends,
Jennifer, I mentioned that I'd changed planes in Newark to get a
cheap fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheap? Is this where you get that from, Renee?'' said
Jennifer, a wholly sweet, wholly innocent young lady who plans to
be a veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   How rich.
</P>
<P>
   You see, I'm the sort of guy who'll share a hotel bathroom so as
to have pocket money for cocktails, theater tickets, tea at the
Dorchester Hotel _ and $200 Chinese dinners for two. I operate on a
student's mentality, a journalist's salary and a diet that's high
in calories.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Renee paid for her five-week, $3,500 ``semester''
by waiting tables at Ruby Tuesday's in Douglas, baby-sitting and
lobbying hard for cash graduation gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Her credo was ``London or Bust.'' Mine was: ``Bust a Gut in
London.''
</P>
<P>
   By hook or by crook, on little more than our common genes and a
prayer, we made it. And if we can make it in London _ one of the
world's most expensive cities _ we can make it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   So while Renee studied art, psychology and Brit lit, I slept
late, went to galleries, sought out weird places to eat and checked
out Soho's pubs and coffee bars. While she went to hear the
Counting Crows, I went to see Vanessa Redgrave in Noel Coward's
``Song at Twilight'' at the Gielgud Theatre. While she took exams,
I went to Evensong at Westminster Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   We were so independent, yet so in touch, that we virtually
bumped into each other one day as we rounded a corner near the
British Museum. ``Wanna go get some fish and chips?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   We never ventured to Jane Austen's cottage at Chawton or the
Lake District. But I found a Bloomsbury room with a view _ and got
to see the likenesses of some of my favorite writers (Iris Murdoch,
the Brontes, A.S. Byatt) at the National Portrait Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   And at night, we splurged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wendell and I are having fun,'' Renee wrote her grandmother on
a postcard cutout of Queen Elizabeth II's bespectacled visage.
``Maybe I'll take him out dancing _ if I can get him out of the
restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   We penned the note at the North Sea Fish Restaurant as we
polished off those fish and chips, which we both thought were the
best we found in London.
</P>
<P>
   Always an England
</P>
<P>
   How can three young women sleep when all London beckons?
</P>
<P>
   Devon Jackson, Jennifer Deen, Renee Brock: It's your night of
nights! These girls had just one week left _ and they were
determined to make the most of it. And after a few pitchers of
various hues at Tiger-Tiger, it was Three Sheets to the Wendell
(you'll pardon the pun).
</P>
<P>
   We drank, we laughed, we danced.
</P>
<P>
   I heard about their side trips to Paris, Ireland and Scotland,
about the meningitis scare. ``We paid some stupid doctor (British
pound)36 to tell us we had bedbugs,'' said Jennifer, in that
wonderful way she has of getting right to the heart of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The girls told me they refused to talk to any guy who couldn't
do a shagadelic Austin Powers imitation. And over a pitcher of ...
Seabreezes, I believe ... we even saw a birthday soiree for which
the young honoree had donned a tiara and a tiny purse, as if to
remind us that there'll always be an England.
</P>
<P>
   Late that night, I took the tube back to the frumpy St.
Margaret's Hotel near Russell Square in Bloomsbury, where I'd
checked in earlier that day. Even with its weird plumbing and
toasty smell, I liked the dowdy old walk-up, just a short stroll
from the British Museum. My room had a view of the Duke of
Bedford's back yard, and downstairs there were pictures of the day
the queen took tea in the garden. At $75 a night, it was a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon, I met the girls in Camden Town, a maze of
outdoor markets, storefronts and cheap restaurants. ``Very Little
Five Points,'' Devon said. When she stopped to buy a slice of pizza
($1.70), the sidewalk vendor stretched out to press his
sauce-covered hands around her Botticelli-like hair.
</P>
<P>
   Renee had wanted to take me to tea at Harrod's, but it was
closed on the Sunday afternoon we dropped by. So we went to Harvey
Nichols, the somewhat fancier Knightsbridge department store next
door, where Patsy and Edina often had lunch in ``Absolutely
Fabulous.'' Upstairs at Yo! Sushi, we sat at the bar and grabbed a
few bites off the conveyor belt and ordered a few more off the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   Then we hiked up to the Dorchester to take afternoon tea in the
lobby of the magnificent hotel built in 1931 across from Hyde Park.
But first, we had champagne at the bar _ a splendid room of
mirrored ceilings and polished wood the color of pistachio shells.
While we were perched there, a woman returned to look for a diamond
bracelet she'd lost. This, after all, is a place where Alfred
Hitchcock and Elizabeth Taylor once stayed.
</P>
<P>
   We read in our guidebook that the Sultan of Brunei owns the
place, so when a sheik walked past in full regalia, we let our
imaginations run wild. We spent $135 for champagne, tea, sandwiches
and pastries. As Renee and her group would say, we were ``sconed''
_ that's the word they coined to mean ``full.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared with our dinner at Fung Shing, a
Cantonese restaurant in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   Hands down, it was one of the best Chinese meals of my life _ so
good that I made a return visit before leaving London. Talk about a
banquet. Over two visits, we tried _ and loved _ slices of tender
suckling pig sauced with just a hint of star anise; pan-sauteed
oysters with ginger and scallions; whole fried sea bass in a pool
of sweet-hot chili sauce; tubes of squid stuffed with seafood on a
pile of fried garlic slivers. But our favorite dish was the whole
lobster whacked into pieces and tossed with garlicky buttered
noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Was this worth changing planes in Newark? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   Renee's dining pick was Wagamama, an Asian noodle bar near the
British Museum that opened in 1992 and had a major role in the
noodle craze that ate the Western world. At about $10 for a big
steaming bowl of ramen with miso broth and chicken, it was a
bargain. I went for the spiky bowl of chili beef noodles with lime
(about $12). Renee became a regular, and even bought the cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness by the pound
</P>
<P>
   The real question wasn't how many pounds I spent, but how many I
gained. Even Renee _ who normally wears a size 2 _ put on a few
ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Before she left, she bought my brother, Wade, a T-shirt that
said: ``My daughter went to London, and all I got was this stupid
T-shirt.'' She bought her grandmother a CD of the Westminster Abbey
choir. When I went to visit my mom recently, she couldn't get the
CD to work in her car, so I went out to help her. And as she drove
slowly out of the driveway, I heard the music: ``Hark the Herald
Angels Sing.''
</P>
<P>
   It took me right back to London, somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Renee and I always knew we were boon companions, but this trip
sealed the friendship. When she makes good on her dream to become a
medical doctor, I hope she'll remember poor Uncle Wen.
</P>
<P>
   And Jennifer, hon, don't worry about it now. But when you've
become a veterinarian, and paid off your college loans, remember
that (British pound)5 ($8.50) I loaned you in London.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. With interest, that will be . ...
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   Airfares are competitive, so it pays to check around. Delta _
and several other airlines _ currently offer a $439 round-trip fare
for Jan. 3-March 31 travel. Sale ends Jan. 6. 1-800-241-4141.
</P>
<P>
   RECOMMENDED HOTELS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Margaret's Hotel. An excellent location, equidistant from
Russell and Bloomsbury squares. Short walk to central theater
district. As the bellhop said with a wink, ``an English breakfast''
is included: toast, eggs, choice of meat, sliced tomatoes and
mushrooms. Shared or private baths. 26 Bedford Place, Russell
Square. 011-44-171-636-4277.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thanet Hotel. Also in Bloomsbury, this small hotel has a
pretty facade and nicely remodeled rooms with private baths. Single
room, $105. Breakfast included. 8 Bedford Place, Russell Square.
011-44-171-636-2869.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Portobello Hotel. With a reputation for catering to the likes
of Mick Jagger, it is quiet, discreet and near the sprawling market
of the same name. If you want a romantic tryst on trendy Notting
Hill, this is the place. A bit of a splurge for the budget traveler
($166 for a single room), but well worth it. 22 Stanley Gardens.
011-44-171-727-2777.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANTS, TEAS, WINE BARS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Sea Fish Restaurant. Delightful and authentic, with
supremely fresh fish of your choice. 7-8 Leigh St., near Russell
Square. 011-44-171-387-5892.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fung Shing. 15 Lisle St., Chinatown. 011-44-171-
</P>
<P>
   437-1539.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wagamama. 4 Streatham St. 011-44-171-323-9223.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chutney Mary. Not your typical curry house, this restaurant
offers regional Indian specialties in an upscale, overdecorated
series of rooms in Chelsea. Worth the trip from central London.
Loved the rosewater sorbet and the mango-martini ice cream. 535
Kings Road. 011-44-171-351-3113.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Promenade, the Dorchester. For a classic afternoon tea _
with champagne, piano music and waiters in tails. Park Lane.
011-44-171-629-8888.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grape Street Wine Bar. This downstairs Bloomsbury nook is
perfect for a glass of wine, a cheese plate or a wedge of pate
before the theater. 224-A Shaftsbury Ave. 011-44-171-240-0686.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   British Tourist Authority. 1-800-462-2748, fax 212-986-1188,
online at www.usagateway
</P>
<P>
   .visitbritain.com.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
