<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-PARIS-48HOURS19-COX     12-16 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-48HOURS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paris in 48-hours
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The three-hour trip from London to Paris on a 186-mph
bullet train set the tone for the next two days in the City of
Light.
</P>
<P>
   We had to be fast, direct and efficient if we were to see
everything we wanted to see.
</P>
<P>
   Paris can be explored in less than 48 hours and without spending
a lot of money, but you have to have a sense of adventure. Planning
is necessary, of course, but so is flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Planning the trip
</P>
<P>
   For our first trip to France _ or anywhere requiring a passport
_ my friend and I armed ourselves with a very limited understanding
of French, our ATM cards, two guidebooks and maps of the Paris
streets and subway. We were two rookies in a country where we
barely understood the language, but we could ask about prices,
understand directions and order from a menu.
</P>
<P>
   We booked a cheap flight to London _ $198 plus taxes _ where we
stayed with a friend before boarding the Eurostar, bound for Paris,
long before daybreak.
</P>
<P>
   We had reserved our seats on the high-speed train,
affectionately known as ``the Chunnel,'' by going online to
www.eurostar
</P>
<P>
   .com. Before leaving the United States, we'd also checked Web
sites that provide restaurant and hotel prices and amenities
(conveniences should never be assumed in France).
</P>
<P>
   Nice surprises
</P>
<P>
   Once in Paris, we reminded ourselves to be flexible and open to
any opportunity. As a result, we found friends everywhere: the
elderly woman who tried to help us find our way even though she
spoke no English; the French security officer who spent a few hours
interpreting for us and showing us around a street market of art,
flowers, fresh cheeses and produce; the Georgia couple we met at a
wine store who greeted us with, ``Where y'all from?''
</P>
<P>
   Our only requirement was finding a clean bed in which to sleep.
Anything more would be considered a luxury. We landed at the
Residence les Gobelins, a tiny place on a side street in the Latin
Quarter, in a quaint $65-a-night hotel room that had a private
bath, a telephone and a television.
</P>
<P>
   Once settled in our almost luxurious lodgings, we began plotting
our route on the street and subway (the Metro) maps, numbering our
destinations in the order we wanted to see them. Mindful of how
much time it took to get from one place to another, we tried to
organize our routes so there would be minimal, if any,
backtracking. Our goal was to use straight lines, but eventually
circle back to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Though we wanted at least a few Paris taxi experiences, for the
most part we walked. Walking gave us better, longer looks at places
we did not plan to enter, such as the Eiffel Tower and Shakespeare
&AMP; Co. Bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   When time was short, we lined up at marked taxi stands _ the
only place to get cabs _ or pulled out our stash of Metro passes.
</P>
<P>
   We were armed with change for the pay toilets located along
sidewalks, which also are dotted with artists, flower stands and
fruit vendors. We also had credit and ATM cards to draw on as
needed, which gave us a better exchange rate than we would have
found had we swapped dollars for francs before leaving the States.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite places
</P>
<P>
   We started our Paris adventure on the roof of the Samaritaine, a
department store near Pont Neuf, which translates as ``new
bridge,'' even though it is the oldest in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   From the ninth-floor roof, we were treated to a 360-degree
unobstructed view of Paris _ one best seen at night but still
beautiful in the sunlight. There was no charge to go to the roof.
Store personnel politely directed the steady stream of tourists to
elevators that go to the base of a narrow, twisting staircase to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Next was Notre Dame. There is no charge to get inside, though
there are boxes for donations if visitors decide to light candles
in remembrance of loved ones. Taking pictures is allowed, and
there's plenty to photograph. The outside _ with carvings of the
Apostles, the Last Supper and depictions of Paradise and hell _ is
just as breathtaking as the inside. Under a ceiling 115 feet high,
light seeps in through stained glass windows of scenes from the Old
and New Testaments and of madonna and child. Long hallways are
lined with arched doorways that lead to shrines with candlelight
illuminating the statues. There are choir lofts and private areas
for prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame also is a repository for religious artifacts and
sacred silver and for fragments believed to have come from Jesus'
cross, as well as the crown of thorns and the nails that held
Christ to the cross.
</P>
<P>
   Another stop that invoked reverence was the Orsay Museum. Even
with a relatively small entrance fee _ $6 to $7, depending on
exchange rate _ there was no wait to get inside and no crowds to
see Renoir's ``Dance Garden on the Butte Montmartre'' or Degas'
``Ladies Bathing.'' ``Whistler's Mother'' also was here, along with
the works of Monet, van Gogh and Cezanne. The Orsay was easy to
tour and understand, with recorded self-tours and written
explanations _ in various languages, including English _ beside
each work.
</P>
<P>
   The Louvre Museum, another famous destination, is huge and could
be an all-day commitment. But we had specific pieces in mind _ the
Venus de Milo, the Winged Victory of Samothrace and the Mona Lisa _
so we were in at 4:30 p.m. and out before the 5:30 closing. The
charge is $6 to $7, depending on exchange rate, after 3 p.m. and on
Sundays, which is almost half the regular price.
</P>
<P>
   I had seen these works of art in books, but to view them in
person was a completely different experience _ inspiring an awe
that reduced every conversation to a whisper. Visitors can get
close enough to feel the texture of paint or the smoothness of the
sculptures, but the magnificence of these masterworks made even the
urge to touch unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   It was sunny and warm when we left the Louvre and walked past
the Place de la Concorde, where dozens of children encircled a
large fountain, using sticks to guide their miniature sailboats. A
place once known for death _ Marie Antoinette, King Louis XVI and
Robespierre lost their heads here _ the Place de la Concorde is
marked with a 75-foot Egyptian obelisk, covered with hieroglyphics,
between two ornate fountains.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to meet a boat that would take us up and down the
River Seine, we saw a bridge and small sculpture, ``The Flame of
Liberty,'' that recently have become unofficial monuments to
Princess Diana. Standing in somber silence despite the traffic
noise, people leave notes and flowers marking the spot where the
princess' life was cut short.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons to return
</P>
<P>
   At sunset, as the city lights were coming on, we began a
70-minute ride on the Seine (several companies offer such boat
tours) on a Bateaux-Mouches _ at a cost of about $10 _ that took us
under ornate bridges and past government buildings, a smaller
version of the Statue of Liberty and an illuminated Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   No trip would be complete without a walk up the Champs-Elysees,
the street that Allied troops took to the Arc de Triomphe to
celebrate their World War II victory. The sidewalks lining the
boulevard _ one of the most famous in the world _ were crowded with
tourists and Parisians out for a stroll, tempted by the seemingly
endless open cafes and ice cream shops.
</P>
<P>
   In our two days, we sampled plenty of wine and bread and butter
and cheese _ all the things for which Paris is famous. But soft
drinks are expensive _ at $5, pricier than a glass of wine or the
chocolate souffle we ordered _ and they don't come with ice.
</P>
<P>
   Even though time was short, we saw everything we wanted to see
and still had some leisure moments to eat eclairs and drink coffee
at a sidewalk table.
</P>
<P>
   If given a second chance, we'd do it all over again _ with a
whole new game plan befitting seasoned Paris visitors like us.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Midweek winter round-trip fares to Paris are
$418 on American, British Airways, Delta, KLM, Northwest, Sabena,
Air France, Air Canada, United, Lufthansa and USAirways. Purchase
by Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging and attractions: Residence Les Gobelins; fax (33)
01-43-31-44-05, phone (33) 01-47-07-26-90. Other hotel suggestions
can be found online at
www.europe-france.com/France/Paris/index.shtml and
www.travel-in-paris.com. Both sites also provide information on
events, attractions, the weather and getting around. For restaurant
listings, check www.restau.com. For more information on the Orsay
Museum, visit www.musee-orsay.fr.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Call the French Government Tourist Office,
410-286-8310. Or go online at www.francetourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
