<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS19-COX     12-16 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oases of silence becoming harder to come across
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the December cold, midnight Mass was more than a gathering of
the faithful. It was always the quietest service of the year,
despite the hushed excitement that accompanied congregants into a
vestibule fragrant with the smell of frankincense and candle wax.
It was what Roman Catholics call a High Mass, longer and more
formal in its liturgy, but on Christmas it was without the usual
Sunday sermon.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin liturgy was audible, but for the most part it was a
ceremony conducted in silence. You could commune with your maker,
uninterrupted by human voices.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the altar, Fraser firs 10 foot tall were strung with
blue lights, nothing more, and the simplicity was eloquent in its
own way. In recent years I've been trying to sell my children on
the idea of a Christmas tree with just blue lights _ no silver
bells, no gingerbread men, no drummer boys or peppermint canes _
but no one's buying it. They want blinking lights of every color
(except pink), and a tree hung heavy with ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   And they want a lot of noise and chatter, as children should.
They want the sounds of the season, as most of us do.
</P>
<P>
   They are not yet into reverence or reflection, and would not
think to associate either of those with Christmas or with prayer. I
am not in the best position to be instructing others on prayer, not
having said enough of my own. But it was from the midnight Masses
of my childhood that I came to identify devotion with silence.
</P>
<P>
   And not just devotion. Call it what you wish _ relief or
respite, sanctuary or sanity _ quietude is the undervalued state in
a world that likes noise for the sake of noise. The sounds of
silence, to paraphrase Simon and Garfunkel, are the sounds we try
to quell because they remind us of loneliness, emptiness,
purposelessness. Driving to work, we replace them with Neal Boortz
jabbering on about anything and nothing; in the evening, we are no
sooner in the door than we turn on the TV, proof that we are not
alone when, deep down, we know we are.
</P>
<P>
   A little solitude goes a long way
</P>
<P>
   Even those of us who at the end of the day want nothing more
than to be alone _ to soak in a tub, sip a drink or just sit back _
do not want it for long. An hour is divine; a day and it brings on
a certain dread. We are sociable creatures, most of us, and we want
company.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is perfectly understandable, but Barbara Brown
Taylor, who teaches philosophy and religion at Piedmont College in
Demorest, believes God speaks through his silence. It is in the
interstitial space in our lives that we come to a sense of
something not just beyond ourselves but beyond the words that wash
over us every waking minute.
</P>
<P>
   In lectures at the Yale Divinity School two years ago, Taylor
spoke _ the irony is understood _ on God's reticence. Her lectures,
reprinted in a slim volume titled ``When God Is Silent,'' are as
poetic as Anne Morrow Lindbergh's ``Gift From the Sea'' and as wise
as Ben Franklin's autobiography in their everyday common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fewer and fewer oases of silence in our noisy
world,'' Taylor writes. ``Communication has higher value for us
than contemplation. Information is in greater demand than
reflection. There was a time when only doctors wore pagers and the
only person who carried a telephone around with him was the
president of the United States, in case of nuclear attack. Now we
are all that important. We can be found anywhere, at anytime, by
anyone who needs us. When a pager goes off in a room full of
people, a banner unfurls above the wearer's head: I am necessary. I
am involved in something so urgent it cannot wait.''
</P>
<P>
   An eternal tussle with silence
</P>
<P>
   I was reading this the other morning at Starbucks, a kind of
chapel in my irregular religious life. Beside me a guy had both
elbows propped on the table and his cell phone jammed to his ear. I
don't eavesdrop, but it was no emergency. Maybe it was his honey,
maybe it was his bookie. Whoever it was, sitting quietly with his
coffee was more than the man could bear.
</P>
<P>
   We are as ambivalent about silence as we are about solitude.
Speech, Carlyle wrote in ``Sartor Resartus,'' is of time; silence
is of eternity. Even the night sounds _ a refrigerator's hum, a
furnace's recurrent shutting off and coming back on _ assure us
that everything is working. With machines, as Taylor writes,
silence means malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   It is different with people, for whom silence is a void to be
feared, to be filled at all cost. Do preachers preach because the
faithful would otherwise be in the dark? Better, sometimes, that we
let silence speak, in church and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Taylor writes, ``I think we do all the talking
because we are afraid that God won't. Or, conversely, that God
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
