<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-CRUISES-HNS &LR;      12-16 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VETERAN CRUISERS ENJOY WATER, WATER EVERYWHERE  
 &HT;     (WITH: CRYSTAL-CRUISES.) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KARAN HARAM  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year for the holidays, the Tunkis family flew to Texas from
California and the Midwest for its annual get-together at the
family ranch in Bandera.
</P>
<P>
   The native Texans had a great reunion, but this fall the women
of the family decided to do it one better. They left husbands,
children, jobs and ringing phones for massages, afternoon teas,
shore excursions and an all-female gabfest aboard the luxurious
Crystal Cruise's Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sisters of the Sea,'' they called themselves, as they sailed
through the Panama Canal to ports in Mexico, Central America and
the United States. ``This is our second cruise together. We had
such a good time on our first cruise , we couldn't wait to do it
again. We're cruising into the next phase of our lives,'' says
Peggy Tunkis of Sonoma, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The women, including Tunkis' aunt, Quita Mathis of Corpus
Christi, Texas, are eager to cruise yet another time, but with only
two cruises under their belts, the Tunkises will have to work hard
to catch up with some other repeat cruisers on the Crystal Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Take Viola Chien of Houston, who, on the same ship, was on her
20th Crystal Cruise . If you add it all up, she says, she and her
husband, a retired doctor, have ``spent 1,000 days on cruise ships.
We took our first cruise _ a short one _ years ago. We loved it. So
as soon as my husband retired, we started cruising whenever we
could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiens normally cruise on Crystal two to three months a
year. ``Our favorite way is to take one long cruise in the winter.
You pack for a cruise, then put in two more dresses and three more
blouses and you can stay as long as you want,'' the experienced
cruiser says.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is you clean out the refrigerator and stop the
newspaper. You might as well stay away as long as you want.''
</P>
<P>
   When they were younger, the Chiens enjoyed ``late buffets and
then a few dances after that,'' as well as exploring ports of call
when the cruise ship docked. These days, they enjoy the relaxing
aspects of cruising, including the ability of Chien's husband to
nap when he wants. ``And now we go to bed after dinner,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think the Chiens are ready to return home after their
cruises, one of which lasted 70 days, nothing could be further from
the truth. ``We don't care if we ever get off,'' she says. ``Often
times we don't. We like sea days and all the activities.''
</P>
<P>
   For Harriet Cole of Lakewood, Colo., the October cruise on the
Crystal Harmony was her 54th. Although she loves ``Crystal's food
and service,'' she saves most of her praise for its dance program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only cruise where they have host programs because I love to
dance,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The world traveler, who has been to 50 states and Nepal, China
and the Mediterranean, among numerous other countries, says she
sticks with Crystal because ``it's the best line that I have been
on. It's like old-home week. I run into all these people I know,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   According to Crystal Cruise Lines, as of mid-October, 174,759 of
their passengers were repeat cruisers, all of whom become members
of the Crystal Society. A Crystal Society black-tie cocktail party
on the Harmony honored the 200 Crystal Society members on the ship,
including one mother-daughter team from Southern California who had
come on board Sept. 8 on their 26th Crystal sailing, as well as
others who were on anywhere from their second cruise to their 20th.
</P>
<P>
   But none compare to Thorne Corse , who earlier this month left
his San Francisco home for Singapore to join the Harmony's sister
ship, the Symphony, for his 84th Crystal cruise. He planned to sail
from Singapore to Los Angeles, then to Mexico back to Los Angeles,
then around the world.
</P>
<P>
   As he was packing his four suitcases for his trip, scheduled to
end on May 4, he was hard pressed to recall how many cruises he'd
been on. ``God save us. The problem is I really don't know. We're
talking something over at least 100,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His first ``honest-to-goodness cruise'' was in the late '50s to
the Caribbean. Although he enjoyed the cruise, his work as a lawyer
kept him busy and he didn't cruise again until 1980, when, in
Europe on business, he had two weeks free.
</P>
<P>
   A Mediterranean cruise he booked to fill up the time ``pretty
much hooked me,'' he says. ``Then my wife and I cruised on Royal
Viking for many years until Crystal came along.''
</P>
<P>
   A widower today, Corse enjoys the food and entertainment aboard
the ship, but ``it's not the most important thing to me. I play
backgammon quite a lot and have a regular group with whom I play,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   And while he doesn't plan his trips to coincide with any other
repeat cruisers, he enjoys being on board with ``good friend''
Reidulf Maalen, captain of the Crystal Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I know best and am most comfortable with are the
officers and crew. Always there are other repeat passengers whom I
know and many of whom I rather like. It's my home away from home,''
Corse says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike home, however, where you have to make your own bed, scrub
your own shower and often share table space with others, Corse has
more options. In the dining room, for example, he has a table to
himself. ``That's somewhat unusual, but 83 cruises count for
something,'' he says. And, yes, even with all those cruises under
his belt, Corse still goes through the mandatory lifeboat drill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sometimes I don't go and they don't throw me overboard,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   At the Crystal Society cocktail party where frequent cruisers
were honored, the Crystal Society hostess told the group that after
75 Crystal cruises, they were entitled to a free two-week cruise in
a penthouse with a private veranda.
</P>
<P>
   At the milestone 100-cruise level, guests get a free 14-day
cruise with a stay in the 950-square foot Crystal Penthouse,
complete with dual bathrooms, a Jacuzzi with an ocean view,
spacious living room and private butler.
</P>
<P>
   If Corse keeps going at his present rate, the cruise line better
start getting it ready.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &LR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises has two ships, the Crystal Harmony and Crystal
Symphony. Itineraries range from the Panama Canal, Mexico and the
Caribbean to Asia, Europe, West Africa, Australia and the South
Pacific, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Published prices begin at $2,190. For more information, call
your travel agent, visit the Web site at www.crystalcruises.com or
call 310-785-9300.
</P>
<P>
   The Crystal Harmony navigates the locks of the Panama Canal.
Crystal Cruises was named the ``Best of the Best'' large cruise
line by the Robb Report earlier this year, and Travel and Leisure
readers rated the cruise line the ``world's No. 1 luxury travel
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   A penthouse with veranda (above) features 375 square feet of
living space for Harmony passengers. Two private restaurants,
including Kyoto and Prego offer fine-dining experiences for those
who want an intimate dinner prepared to order. Special theme
cruises, including holidays, are popular with Crystal's repeat
cruisers. The Crystal Harmony offers gala lunch buffets with
themes, such as the American Classics on the 12-day Panama Canal
cruise.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Haram can be reached by electronic mail at
kharam &LR; express-news.net.)
</P>
