<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-CRYSTAL-CRUISES-HNS &LR;      12-16 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRYSTAL-CRUISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CRUISE LINE FOCUSES ON SERVICE, INTIMACY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KARAN HARAM  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what is there about Crystal Cruises that makes repeat
cruisers out of so many of its passengers?
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the 10-year-old cruise line has earned an
unprecedented number of industry awards, including three
consecutive designations as ``World's Best Cruise Line'' and ``Best
Large Ship Cruise Line'' from the readers of Travel and Leisure and
Conde Nast Traveller magazine, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Crystal Cruises was named the ``Best of the Best'' large
cruise line by the Robb Report earlier this year, and Travel and
Leisure readers rated the cruise line the ``world's No. 1 luxury
travel experience,'' surpassing every other cruise line as well as
every luxury hotel and resort and worldwide destination.
</P>
<P>
   Besides themed voyages, such as the October Wine and Food
Festival from Acapulco, Mexico, to New Orleans, Health/Fitness and
Big Band/Jazz extravaganzas, the cruise line is known for its
service, gourmet dining and elegant, classic decor.
</P>
<P>
   Luxuries such as plump, oversized robes and towels, down
pillows, linens and lavish table settings, including Riedel wine
glasses are commonplace, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Like other cruise ships, the Crystal Harmony offers a dining
room where passengers take most of their meals. But two private
restaurants, Kyoto, with a Japanese menu, and Prego, with Italian,
offer fine-dining experiences for those who want an intimate dinner
prepared to order.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the 940 guests on board visit the restaurants at
least once.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, we wanted the cruise line to offer an
alternative type of cuisine. It wasn't so well received at first,
but now it's very popular,'' says Toni Neumeister, director of
culinary operations.
</P>
<P>
   Executive chef Markus Nufer says beyond the private restaurants,
there's another big difference in the food on the Crystal line.
``While other large cruise ships may have only two or three chefs _
an executive chef, a sous-chef and sometimes a pastry chef _ we
have 33-35 trained European chefs on board, and all our waiters are
European,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Although food is readily available in a variety of settings
whenever guests desire, rather than midnight buffets, the Crystal
harmony focuses on gala lunch buffets, including Cuisines of the
Sun featuring foods from Spain, France and Sicily, as well as
Morocco, Israel and Turkey. An American Classics buffet takes
passengers back to the roots of American dining, while the Asian
Cafe features the cuisines of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guests love to have the regional influences we offer them,
especially where they feel it's not safe to eat ashore,''
Neumeister says.
</P>
<P>
   On Australian cruises , for example, that means adding to the
dining room menu an offering of seared kangaroo loin with bush
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put it on the first time, I thought we wouldn't sell
it. We had 300 side orders. One guest ordered it three times
afterward,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The broad travel experiences of the typical Crystal passenger
translate to a more sophisticated cuisine than you would normally
find on a cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe food is not about food only. It's the service, the
wine you drink with the food, the friends you sit around the table
with,'' Neumeister says.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment is upscale as well, focusing more on Broadway-type
productions than Las Vegas-style shows. Guest lecturers also offer
special insight into topics as varied as handwriting analysis and
jazz to a history of the politics of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ships with passengers numbering in the thousands, the
Harmony and Symphony, with guest capacities of 940 each, feel
tranquil and spacious, yet intimate. There's no struggling to find
a seat in the theater or long lines to get your formal photos
taken.
</P>
<P>
   And therein may lie one of the secrets of the cruise line's
success. ``We don't try to be everything to everybody,'' Neumeister
says. ``We concentrate on doing what we do well. We know what our
guests prefer and act accordingly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
