<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, Dec. 17, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israel and Syria swapped ideas
about building confidence after a half-century of hostility
Thursday as White House-directed peace talks moved into the
dynamics of a projected Israeli pullback on the Golan Heights. The
bilateral negotiations ended about 3:15 this afternoon, and the
Israelis and Syrians moved to the White House to meet with
President Clinton. (Summary from wires) By John M. Broder. (1200
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Washington) _ Facing a phalanx of cameras during
a ceremony meant to herald the resumption of Israeli-Syrian peace
talks, Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa sounded every bit
the unreconstructed foe of the Jewish homeland. Apparently, though,
al-Sharaa did not display the same muscular posture privately.
Afterward, ensconced in the Blair House, the negotiations took on a
professional tone. Each side did indeed mean business, or they
wouldn't have bothered to break a 45-month freeze in talks.
Although there may seem a puzzling inconsistency in al-Sharaa's
behavior, it actually fits a pattern in Israeli-Arab peace
negotiations. On every track, there is a private and public face to
the relationship. For each side, making peace involves juggling two
campaigns: one at the negotiating table and one on the homefront.
In actual negotiations, concessions are inevitable. But publicly,
some leaders choose to present an implacable facade as defender of
his own people's needs and rights. A news analysis by Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-REPORT (United Nations) _ A strongly worded report issued
Thursday by an international panel of experts holds both U.N.
officials and leading member countries, primarily the United
States, responsible for failing to stop the genocide in Rwanda. The
report says that about 800,000 people were killed in 100 days
between April and July 1994, in a Hutu-led campaign of genocide
against Tutsi and moderate Hutu. The report portrays an
organization weak on analysis and slow to respond to accumulating
warnings in the months that preceded the attacks. The United
States, which provided minimal help and no documents to the
investigators, effectively blocked the Security Council in 1993 and
1994 from authorizing any significant action in Rwanda. On a trip
to Africa last year, President Clinton apologized for this American
inaction. By Barbara Crossette. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Pervomaiskoye, Russia) _ Scores of desperate
civilians came under fire Thursday as they tried to escape the
fighting in Grozny through a newly established humanitarian
corridor. Russian troops have begun to mount reconnaissance raids
and probes into Grozny, signaling that the battle for the city is
finally underway. Russian commanders do not plan a frontal assault
on the capital, but want instead to take Grozny back, neighborhood
by neighborhood, depending heavily on their overwhelming advantage
in firepower. By Michael R. Gordon. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-U.S. (Paris) _ Among allies, France has had for 50 years
a unique capacity to annoy Americans who may love French fries,
French wine, and sometimes even the French themselves, at least in
those rare moments when they stop their constant hammering.
Irritation at the French is running high now in Washington,
American officials there say, so President Jacques Chirac and other
high French officials here are now putting out the word that it's
time to apply a little Gallic charm to their hypersensitive
American friends. By Craig R. Whitney. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CHILD-MURDER (London) _ The European Court of Human
Rights ruled Thursday that two 10-year-old boys who kidnapped and
killed 2-year-old James Bulger in a suburban Liverpool shopping
center in 1993 had not received a fair trial in Britain. The judges
said that the two boys, Jon Venables and Robert Thompson, had been
were too young to take part effectively in a procedure designed for
adults and that the home secretary, at the time, Michael Howard,
had erred in increasing their 8-year jail sentence to 15 years. The
boys have already served six years, and, while the European
decision does not affect their convictions, it could be the basis
for a move by their lawyers in British courts to seek their
release. By Warren Hoge. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BRADLEY (Claremont, N.H.) _ Senator John McCain and
former Senator Bill, both insurgent candidates for president,
joined forces across a partisan and ideological divide today to
pledge their support for revamping the nation's campaign finance
system and to take some sharp shots at each other's front-running
opponent. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-TRIAL (Ellicott City, Md.) _ Alternating between deep
concern and lightheartedness, Monica S. Lewinsky testified in a
Maryland court Thursday for more than an hour in an effort to help
state prosecutors put Linda R. Tripp in jail for secretly
tape-recording their conversations. Ms. Lewinsky, a poised and
practiced witness by now, told the prosecutors that she had not
given Ms. Tripp permission to record their telephone conversations
as she discussed her relationship with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ENGLAND-DRUGS (Montpelier, Vt.) _ In the first such meeting
of its kind, legislative leaders from the four northern New England
states gathered here Thursday to plot possible joint strategies for
lowering the price of prescription drugs, from imposing local price
controls to demanding a regional discount. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBANS-DETAIN (St. Martinville, La.) _ The hostage situation in
Louisiana involving Cuban detainees has underscored once more the
fate of hundreds of Cubans locked in legal limbo in U.S. prisons.
By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (New York) _ An appellate court ruled Thursday
that the trial of four officers accused of killing Amadou Diallo
last February should be held in Albany County, because a ``tidal
wave of pretrial publicity'' would make it impossible to hold a
fair trial in the Bronx. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK (New York) _ A man who apparently wanted to
``clean'' a controversial picture of the Virgin Mary at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art has defaced the work with white paint. The
suspect in the afternoon attack got the paint past metal detectors
by concealing it in a plastic container, then feined a heart attack
to get past a guard and slip under a plexiglass shield. By Robert
D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOND-PENSIONS (New York) _ New York pension fund manager Alan B.
Bond was charged by U.S. authorities with taking almost $7 million
in kickbacks from brokerage firms in connection with his management
of retirement accounts belonging to National Basketball Association
players and other clients. (Summary from wires) By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
</TEXT>
