<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-MILLENNIUM-FOOD-LADN &LR;      12-16 3520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN THE KITCHEN GETS EASIER, TASTIER VIA DECADES OF INNOVATION 
RESEND FOR SUSAN AT THE TRENTON, N.J., TIMES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Carol Bidwell and Natalie Haughton, Staff Writers
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th century began, cooking was hard work. There were few
things to make a housewife's life easier, and virtually everything
had to be made from scratch. Even families with modest incomes had
paid ``help'' in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Many housewives counted themselves lucky if they had running
water (yes, a pump counted) inside the house. If not, water had to
be drawn from a well. Wood had to be carried, and a fire had to be
made in the stove.
</P>
<P>
   The cow had to be milked. Coffee was ``boiled up'' in a pot on
the stove, often with a eggshell thrown in for clarity. Biscuits
had to be baked, meat and eggs fried, gravy made, jars of homemade
jam brought from the pantry.
</P>
<P>
   All this and it was only 6 a.m. And there were two more meals to
prepare that same day.
</P>
<P>
   Women's work in the early 1900s was generally in the home, and
much of it was spent growing and preparing food _ and, of course,
cleaning up afterward. Housewives were ready for new advances that
made their lives easier.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, times were prosperous despite _ or perhaps in part
because of _ Prohibition, which drove evn the law-abiding to drink
as sweet cocktails masked the taste of bathtub gin. Chinese
restaurants provided a bit of exotica. For ladies, tearooms became
popular, as did gelatin salads, the fruit-filled Lady Baltimore
cake, devil's food cake and pineapple upside-down cake. At the end
of the decade, with the stock market crash, financial havoc was
created on many fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rough financial times in the '30s, Americans loved to
socialize and found affordable ways to do it. Sunday night suppers,
tea parties and one-dish meals made entertaining inexpensive.
Gadgets such as the new electric toaster, waffle iron, percolator
and electric mixer made it fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   There were new things to cook, too: It was in this era that
zucchini and broccoli first became widely available in the United
States. Ruth Wakefield changed American snacking forever when she
chopped up chocolate and mixed it into cookie batter, creating the
first chocolate-chip cookies, which she named Toll House Cookies
after the New England inn she and her husband ran.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking methods became standardized, and assorted cookbooks
began to appear. With the opening of Route 66 between Chicago and
Los Angeles, highway eateries thrived. So did food companies, which
introduced a wealth of new products.
</P>
<P>
   In the '40s _ with the best of American food sent overseas to
soldiers and sailors doing the fighting _ those left at home had to
make do with what was left. Meat, coffee, sugar, butter, cheese and
canned goods were rationed _ if they were available at all. So
housewives _ who might have spent their days working in a defense
plant _ planted victory gardens to provide for their families.
</P>
<P>
   Basic American home cooking was the food of the day. Onl the
very rich still had servants. Patriotic housewives saved bacon fat
to use in cakes and made their own jams, jellies and pickles. With
commodities scarce, entertaining was often coffee and dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Housewives also benefited from some foods produced for GIs _
dehydrated soups, dried potatoes, canned biscuits, pudding mixes,
margarine and vegetable oils. After the war, GIs brought home a new
taste for exotic food, especially pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed in the food realm. Frozen and pre-made foods
became available _ and supermarkets made shopping easier. A
prosperous future with an abundance of food _ including gourmet and
convenience foods, plus new and more exotic restaurants _ was on
the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, with World War II and the Korean War over, GI Joe
was home, his wife was back in the kitchen, and that kitchen was
often in the suburbs, where new houses were being built with
fabulous kitchens, patios and barbecues. Beef _ long before any of
us knew about cholesterol _ went on those barbecues. Add a baked
potato, a salad and garlic bread, and you had a meal as American as
apple pie. That's not to say suburbia wasn't a breeding ground for
gourmet cooks, though: Beef Stroganoff and baked Alaska were tops
on any gourmet's list of dishes to perfect.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Swanson was marketing TV dinners, complete
frozen meals the family could eat while watching television. Other
convenience and frozen foods also came into their own. Fast-food
chains got their start and boomed.
</P>
<P>
   The psychedelic '60s were a mishmash of food trends, from fast
food to spa food, from blender gazpacho to fondue, from soul food
to luaus. To really put on the dog, cooks dished up veal Orloff,
beef Wellington, rumaki andmore. With the affluence, prosperity and
jet travel of the era, foreign foods became more familiar and
accessible. Ethnic restaurants appeared in ever-increasing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s, known by many as the ``me'' decade, was a time of
singles bars, mood rings, pet rocks, Earth shoes and disco, a time
when even the food had strange names, like Screaming Yellow
Zonkers, Fluffernutters and Harvey Wallbangers. Eventually, though,
dinner parties, cooking classes, nouvelle cuisine, regional
cuisine, the food processor and such trendy foods as goat cheese,
farm-fresh greens, chocolate truffles and specialty produce became
all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Crock-Pots (electric slow cookers) had moved into the kitchen,
along with bundt pans and granola. And cooks were turning out
zucchini and carrot cakes slathered with cream cheese frosting
along with crepes and quiche. Restaurant favorites were fettuccini
Alfredo, main dish salads, salad bars, ranch dressing and Kahlua.
</P>
<P>
   Americans had had enough of spa food and itty-bitty portions in
the '80s. They wanted comfort food like Mom used to make. Meatloaf
was king again, along with fried chicken, mashed potatoes (although
cooks added garlic) and pizza.
</P>
<P>
   America's power elite and baby boomers had become foodies,
wheeling and dealing over power lunches at high-priced restaurants
and becoming awed by star chefs who became celebrities at a time
when status and style were all-important.
</P>
<P>
   Grazing _ eating a bit of this and a bit of that throughout the
day _ was the ``in'' thing, and so were Cajun and Southwest
cuisine. Salsa replaced ketchup as the favorite condiment. Cooks
could find kiwi, mangoes, mesclun, free-range chickens, goat cheese
and creme fraiche in markets. Pesto was a new favorite, along with
risotto, croissants and muffins. Cholesterol-lowering oat bran made
up for all that comfort. In the home kitchen, heat-and-eat
convenience foods _ with no cooking required _ were popular.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe as a backlash to all that comfort food, in the '90s
Americans became obsessed with fat _ how much in food items and
dishes and how to reduce intake _ along with nutrition, health and
fitness. Supermarkets began devoting more shelf space to nonfat and
low-fat cookies, sour cream, cream cheese, ice cream and products
containing a new low-fat fat named Olestra as manufacturers rushed
to get in on the fat-free, reduced-fat product craze. Some were
good and found a permanent place on the shelves; others were so
poor and disappointing that they disappeared quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, obesity rates soared. Other consumers were into luxury
and quality (super-premium ice creams, fine wines and cheeses, for
instance). Biscotti in an array of flavors became popular. And
bread machines, turning out custom loaves with little effort,
became the rage for home cooks. Foods that were once only available
at ethnic markets were now available in supermarkets. And now it
was possible to order groceries, talk with other cooks and find
recipes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As you look back over the last century in food, reminisce with
this sampling of some of the most popular recipes. Depending on
your age, you may recall having eaten _ or cooked _ some of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson
(Clarkson Potter; $35); ``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren
(Macmillan; $25); ``Better Homes &AMP; Gardens' 75 Years of All-Time
Favorites'' (Better Homes &AMP; Gardens Books; $29.95); ``America Eats
Out'' (Wiliam Morrow &AMP; Co.; $25); ``Back of the Box Gourmet''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster; $12.95); Bon Appetit magazine, September 1999;
and ``On the Town in New York'' (Routledge; $30).
</P>
<P>
   PORCUPINE MEAT BALLS
</P>
<P>
   The sort of easy, novelty recipe that appealed to cooks in the
'30s appears to have been developed during World War I as a way to
stretch meat. In ``Conservation Recipes'' (1918), compiled by the
Mobilized Women's Organizations of Berkeley and published by the
Berkeley Unit, Council of Defense Women's Committee, there is
something called Rice Meat Balls, a clear forerunner of the recipe
here, which is adapted from ``My Better Homes and Gardens Cook
Book'' (1939). The 1918 version plumps up a pound of round steak
with 1 cup crumbs and 3/4 cup rice. The Better Homes recipe
specifies beef neck, shank or plate ground to order - not readily
available today. Ground chuck has been substituted.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground beef chuck
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup uncooked converted rice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 (10 1/2-ounce) can condensed tomato soup
</P>
<P>
   1 soup can water
</P>
<P>
   Using hands, mix beef, rice, salt, pepper and onion well and
shape into 1-inch balls.
</P>
<P>
   Mix tomato soup and water in a medium heavy skillet and bring to
simmering over moderate heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add meatballs, adjust heat so mixture bubbles very gently, cover
and simmer 1 hour. Serve accompanied by a crisp green salad. Makes
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson
(Clarkson Potter).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RIVER ROAD BAKED SWEET POTATOES WITH MARSHMALLOWS
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe is from ``River Road Recipes'' (1959) by
The Junior League of Baton Rouge Inc. It is more typical of the
sweet potato csseroles popular in the '50s and '60s. Often crushed
pineapple substitutes for milk, and sometimes the potatoes are
spiked with sherry.
</P>
<P>
   8 medium-size sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Few dashes nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Bake sweet potatoes in preheated 350-degree oven until done.
Peel hot potatoes and put through a ricer until mashed. Scald milk
and add vanilla, sugar and butter.
</P>
<P>
   To potatoes, add cinnamon, nutmeg and orange juice. Stir. Add
milk mixture to potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Layer 1/2 of potato mixture in a buttered casserole; add a layer
of marshmallows and remaining potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees F until very hot. Add a top layer of
marshmallows and brown. Makes 8 to 10 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPAGHETTI SAUCE WITH MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning (around the turn of the century),
Italian-American restaurants did not serve meatballs with their
spaghetti. These were added to satisfy America's hunger for red
meat. Of course, there are dozens of variations on the theme. But,
the best, to my mind, is this make-ahead spaghetti sauce with
meatballs, cooked up by Sharon Bates, a recipe I featured in a 1992
Family Circle article.
</P>
<P>
   MEATBALLS:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Italian-seasoned dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound hot Italian sausage, thickly sliced
</P>
<P>
   5 (14 1/2-ounce) cans stewed tomatoes, with their juice
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) can tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mushrooms, wiped clean and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large ribs celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons Italian herb seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For Meatballs, coat a 15 1/2x10 1/2x1-inch jelly-roll pan with
nonstick cooking spray; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Using hands, mix all meatball ingredients thoroughly. Shape into
1-inch balls; arrange on pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 12 to 15 minutes until
uniformly browned.
</P>
<P>
   For Sauce, brown sausages in a large heavy kettle, over
moderately high hea3t until most of drippings cook out, 8 to 10
minutes. Pour off drippings. Reduce heat to moderate, add meatballs
and all sauce ingredients and bring to a boil. Adjust heat so
mixture bubbles generously, cover and simmer very slowly for 3
hours, stirring, as needed, to prevent sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Cool mixture, ladle into food freezer containers, date, label
and store in 0 degrees F freezer. Makes 1 gallon.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The American Century Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson
(Clarkson Potter).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WARTIME CAKE &QL; 
(World War II)
</P>
<P>
   This recipe was created by the nutrition committee at General
Mills and printed in a 1942 Betty Crocker booklet titled ``Your
Share: How to Prepare Appetizing, Healthy Meals With Foods
Available Today.'' In this little booklet are 52 wartime menus, 226
recipes and 369 hints, including tips for using the government's
newly created Basic 7 Food Groups. This cake is eggless, milkless
and butterless.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup lard OR other shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 cups seedless raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda dissolved in 2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour mixed with 1 teaspoon bking powder
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour an 8x8x2-inch baking pan; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Mix brown sugar, water, lard, raisins, nutmeg, cinnamon and
cloves in a large saucepan. Bring to a boil over moderate heat,
then boil 3 minutes; cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Add salt and baking soda solution to saucepan and mix. Then
blend in flour mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into baking pan, spreading to corners.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven about 50 minutes, until cake
begins to pull from sides of pan and is springy-firm to touch.
</P>
<P>
   Cool in pan on a wire rack before cutting into squares. Makes 1
cake, about 16 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAMIE EISENHOWER'S MILLION-DOLLAR FUDGE
</P>
<P>
   The talk of the '50s - the recipe everyone had to have - was
this fabulous fudge3, made from Mamie Eisenhower's own recipe. It
appeared in ``Who Says We Can't Cook,'' a spiral-bound collection
of recipes published in 1955 by the Women's National Press Club of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tall can evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces semisweet chocolate pieces
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces German sweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1 pint marshmallow cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, combine sugar, salt, butter and evaporated
milk. Boil 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place chocolates, marshmallow cream and nuts in a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Pour boiling syrup over ingredients in bowl; beat until
chocolate is all melted and pour in a pan.
</P>
<P>
   Let stand a few hours before cutting. Store in a food tin box. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRENCH SILK PIE
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate pies began showing up in early 1900s cookbooks. This
rich and silky smooth recipe is adapted from one that first
appeared in ``Better Homes and Gardens All-Time Favorite Pies''
(1978), then reappeared in a salmonella-proof vesion in the 1996
edition of the ``Better Homes and Gardens New Cook Book.''
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (1 1/2 sticks) butter (do not substitute)
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) package semisweet chocolate chips, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup frozen, thawed egg product
</P>
<P>
   1 (9-inch) baked pie shell
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy whipping cream, stiffly whipped
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate curls for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Cream sugar and butter in an electric mixer bowl at medium
speed, 4 minutes, until fluffy. Stir in cooled chocolate and
vanilla, then gradually add egg product and beat at high speed,
scraping sides of bowl constantly until light and fluffy.
</P>
<P>
   Turn filling into pie shell, cover and chill overnight or until
set.
</P>
<P>
   Swirl whipped cream over top and sprinkle with chocolate curls.
Keep any leftovers refrigerated.Makes 1 (9-inch) pie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPOSSIBLE COCONUT PIE
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Bisquick published a recipe for its first ``impossible
pie'' - Impossible Coconut Pie - so named because the mixture
3formed its own crust as it baked. About 100 more ``impossible''
pie recipes were later developed.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup buttermilk baking mix (Bisquick)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup margarine OR butter
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flaked OR shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   Grease a 9x1 1/4-inch or 10x1 1/2-inch pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in a blender. Cover and blend 15 seconds
on high speed. Pour into pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 50 to 55 minutes or until
golden brown and a knife inserted in center comes out clean. Makes
8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOCK APPLE PIE
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine, even during the depths of the Depression,
having crackers around, but no apples. Still, that's the period
when his recipe was developed by Ritz crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Pastry for 2-crust 9-inch pie
</P>
<P>
   36 Ritz crackers, coarsely broken (about 1 3/4 cups crumbs)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Grated peel of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Roll out 1/2 of the pastry and line a 9-inch pie plate. Place
cracker crumbs in prepared crust.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, over high heat, heat water, sugar and cream of
tartar to a boil; simmer 15 minutes. Add lemon juice and peel;
cool. Pour syrup over cracker crumbs. Dot with margarine; sprinkle
with cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out remaining pastry; place over pie. Trim, seal and flute
edges. Slit top crust to let steam vent.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 425-degree oven 30 to 35 minutes or until
crust is crisp and golden. Serve warm. Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIVE-CUP AMBROSIA SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Once marshmallows and sour cream were marketed commercially,
Southern cooks dished up this easy-to-put-together salad. Here's a
Kraft version.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange sections
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grapes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix together all ingredients. Chill. Makes 4 to
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATION: Substitute 1 (11-ounce) can mandarin orange segments,
drained, for orange sections. Add 1 (8-ounce) can pineapple chunks,
drained. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OUR BEST BRAN MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to a bowl of cereal, this bran muffin recipe
appeared on the Kellogg's box for years
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-bran cereal
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Stir together flour,baking powder, salt and sugar; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, stir together cereal and milk. Let stand 5
minutes. Add egg and oil; beat well.
</P>
<P>
   Add flour mixture, stirring only until combined.
</P>
<P>
   Portion batter evenly into 12 greased 2 1/2-inch muffin-pan
cups.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 400-degree oven 18 to 20 minutes. Makes 12
muffins.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATION: Add 3/4 cup raisins to batter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DILLY CASSEROLE BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Few Bake-Off Contest Grand Prize winners are more popular than
this one, which has become an American classic. It was the creation
of a Nebraska cook named Leona P. Schnuelle, who entered it in the
1960 Bake-Off Contest
</P>
<P>
   2 to 2 2/3 cups all-purpose flour OR unbleached flour, lightly
spooned into a measure and leveled off
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons instant minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dill seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup very warm water (110 degrees to 115 degrees F)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 2 teaspoons margarine OR butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cream-style cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon coarse salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Mix 1 cup flour well with sugar, onion, dill seeds, 1 teaspoon
salt, baking soda and yeast in a large electric mixer bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Heat water, 1 tablespoon margarine and cottage cheese in a small
saucepan, over moderately low heat, until very warm (120 degrees to
130 degrees F).
</P>
<P>
   Add warm liquid and egg to mixer bowl and beat at low speed
until mixture is moistened. Increase mixer speed to 3medium and
beat 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By hand, stir in remaining 1 to 1 2/3 cups flour to form a stiff
batter.
</P>
<P>
   Cover with a cloth and let rise in warm, dry spot, away from
drafts, 45 to 60 minutes, until doubled in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Toward end o rising, grease a 1 1/2- to 2-quart casserole well;
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Stir batter down to release air bubbles. Turn into casserole,
cover and let rise, until light and doubled in bulk, 30 to 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Toward end of rising, preheat oven to 350 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover casseorole and bake bread 30 to 40 minutes until richly
golden brown and hollow-sounding when tapped.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately remove bread from casserole and set on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   While loaf is still warm, brush with remaining 2 teaspoons
margarine, melted and sprinkle with coarse salt. Makes 1 (8- to
9-inch) round loaf. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
END &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
