<P>
   CHIP-IMPLANT _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here's a high-tech tracking
device not even George Orwell envisioned: a gizmo slightly smaller
than a dime inserted under a person's skin. Palm Beach-based
Applied Digital Solutions said this week that it bought the patent
for the implant, which it calls the Digital Angel. People who use
the transmitter _ powered by the carrier's muscle _ could be
tracked by global positioning satellite, the same technology used
in some luxury cars and boats. (Ostrowski, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NET-FUTURE _ As we close out one century and enter the next few
things will become as pervasive in our lives as the Internet, some
folks say. We take a look at what the future looks like from the
World Wide Web perspective. (Cocks, Austin American-Statesman). 40.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-OLYMPICS _ ATLANTA _ Coke unveils a Super Bowl promotion
with the Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. This is the first
joint promotion Coke has had with a convention bureau in the U.S.
Beginning Dec. 26, Coke will begin selling 12-pack pacakages of
Coke with the ACVB logo on the box and a booklet inside that will
offer discounts to attractions and Super Bowl events around
Atlanta. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   COX-MINORITIES _ Cox has hired Images, an African-American
marketing company, to pitch its cable and high-speed Internet
services to minority markets. It may be the first high-tech company
to do this sort of thing in an industry that is so new it has yet
to begin segmenting its marketing. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   QWEST-BELLSOUTH _ Q: This announcement about Qwest comes a week
after BellSouth's somewhat parallel deal with KPN. So just how well
is the Qwest deal working out? Qwest Communications and BellSouth
Corp. said they have won 27 multiyear contracts valued at $250
million since BellSouth purchased 10 percent of Qwest for $3.5
billion in May. Qwest, the No. 4 U.S. long-distance carrier, and
BellSouth, which sells local telephone service in nine southeastern
states, agreed to coordinate their marketing efforts when they
announced the transaction in April. They said they now have more
than 250 proposals pending with governments and retail, financial
and health-care companies, in addition to the new contracts.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TRADEX _ ATLANTA _ Tradex, a company that allows business to
business bulk buying over the web, is being bought by Ariba, a
California company, for almost $1.7 billion in stock. (Clothier,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   SOCOMPANY-SUIT _ Southern Co. has reached a $9.2 million
settlement with the municipal-owned utility of Springfield, Ill.,
in a lawsuit over the summer 1998 electricity trading fiasco when
Springfield was unable to deliver electricity to Southern at an
agreed-upon price. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   TIMBER _ Timber Co., the forest unit of Georgia-Pacific, has
completed the its California timberlands, which marks the last step
in a strategy to streamline its business and boost profit. Timber
Co. has sold land in Maine, West Virginia and Canada to weed out
wood such as redwood that doesn't fit the company's product mix.
(Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   WORK-PAJAMAS _ Tips for working from home. (Lohr, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-AIR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ An anti-air pollution plan that Gov.
George W. Bush says Texas could consider would likely limit the
number of trucks, sports utility vehicles and large cars that
automakers would sell in the state, according to a group of auto
manufacturers. The proposal is one of more than a dozen aimed at
getting nearly all of Texas in line with federal pollution
standards by 2007. (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
