<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CIVIL-RIGHTS17-COX     12-16 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-RIGHTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADAM'S MARK HOTELS NAMED IN FEDERAL RACE BIAS SUIT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department filed a federal
discrimination Thursday lawsuit against Adam's Mark Hotels and
Resorts, alleging that it violated the rights of black patrons in
its 21 hotels across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of behavior is simply unacceptable,'' Attorney
General Janet Reno said at a news conference. ``It is hard to
believe that 35 years after the Civil Rights Act was passed by
Congress, this type of discrimination still exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation of the hotel chain, which is owned by
HBE Corp. of St. Louis, found that minorities _ especially large
groups of blacks _ were given less desirable accommodations than
white guests, were charged more for rooms, in-room movies and hotel
bars, and had to adhere to stricter security requirements such as
wearing orange wrist bands for identification.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the actions were a clear violation of the Civil Rights
Act, which prohibits discrimination on the basis of race, color, or
religion in public accommodations. The lawsuit against the hotel
chain would mandate changes in its alleged discriminatory
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint of inferior treatment of blacks was not isolated
to a few hotels within the chain, but was part of a corporate
policy to discourage minority patrons, said Bill Lann Lee, acting
assistant attorney general for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Kummer, president of HBE Corp., said ``we believe the facts
will prove that our conduct has reflected no bias with regard to
race or ethnicity, and that our actions were consistent with those
employed by other leading lodging companies across the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Minorities make up nearly 55 percent of HBE's employees
nationwide and about 21 percent of its supervisory and management
positions, according to Kummer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state of Florida announced it is joining in a
private lawsuit filed by disgruntled black patrons who stayed at
the Daytona Beach Adam's Mark Hotel during the ``Black College
Reunion'' in April.
</P>
<P>
   The patrons suing the Daytona Beach hotel allege that it removed
furnishings from the lobby and their rooms when they checked in,
denied them access to the main driveway in front of the hotel, and
refused to provide them with valet parking.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth, who joined Reno at the
news conference, said that in addition to the the state's
intervention in the private lawsuit, he was also filing a state
civil rights complaint against the hotel on behalf of nearly 1,200
black patrons who alleged discrimination in April.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Daytona Beach hotel, there are Adam's Mark
resorts in Orlando and Clearwater.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels across the country that were investigated included
locations in Grand Junction, Denver, and Colorado Springs, Colo.;
Dallas, Houston, and San Antonio, Texas; Winston-Salem and
Charlotte, N.C.; Columbia, S.C.; and Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark hotels are also scheduled to open in Atlanta and
Jacksonville next year.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that although a lawsuit has been filed, the
investigation will continue. The Justice Department urged
individuals who believe they were victims of discrimination or have
information on discrimination at any of the 21 Adam's Mark Hotels
to call the Housing and Civil Enforcement Section of the Civil
Rights Division at 1-800-896-7743.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
