<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-TITANS17-COX     12-16 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TITANS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Washington's `Titans' recalls racial strife on gridiron
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Denzel Washington, clad in black shorts, maroon golf
shirt and cleated shoes, is anything but the stylish leading man
strutting around the football practice field at Clarkston High
School in DeKalb County, Ga. And he's barking like somebody had
better step up to win one for the Gipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. Let's go, let's go,'' the Oscar-winning actor shouts.
``Show me that option. Left again!''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two white-suited extras portraying football players, a
roughly equal number of whites and African-Americans, leap into a
fierce crash of shoulder pads. They do it again. And again. And
again.
</P>
<P>
   For just over two months, Washington's loud snarls and the
menacing crack of shoulder pads have been heard all across metro
Atlanta and North Georgia _ from Berry College in Rome and Druid
Hills High School in DeKalb County to the city of Covington and
Grady High School in Midtown Atlanta _ as a Disney movie crew has
been completing the big-screen football drama ``Remember the
Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   Budgeted at more than $10 million, the film, expected to be
rated PG and debut next fall, stars Washington and Will Patton
(``Armageddon'') as two real-life coaches _ one African-American
and one white _ who teamed in 1971 to lead a racially plagued high
school football team against great odds to an undefeated season and
the Virginia AAA state championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an emotional piece with very emotional characters,''
producer Jerry Bruckheimer (``Armageddon,'' ``The Rock,'' ``Top
Gun'') says while surveying filming at Clarkston High on a day when
``Titan's'' strict closed set policy was relaxed for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and ``60 Minutes,'' which filmed a profile of
Washington expected to air next month. ``I love scenes where people
make a difference and these two coaches definitely made a
difference. They changed a community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan's'' real-life coaches are Herman Boone, a former North
Carolina coach, who rocked Alexandria, Va., by being named head
coach at T.C. Williams High in 1971 after three schools were
combined into one under forced desegregation, and Bill Yoast, a
former coach at Roswell High School here who had been expected to
be named T.C.'s leader. Both are serving as consultants on
``Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Herman had been in the city as an assistant but I didn't know
him,'' Yoast says. ``The people in my area _ I had a lot of
followers _ were really outraged when Herman was named head coach
over me. I had nine starters who said if you're not going to coach
at T.C. we're not going to play. You look back, we had a hard time
because you can imagine that here are all these kids battling at
the schools (over desegregation) and all of a sudden we're all on
the same team.''
</P>
<P>
   The script includes a few scenes of angry townspeople hurling
bricks into Boone's home, death threats and confrontations at a
restaurant that refuses to serve African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, the racial attacks were non-stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something happened to my house every ballgame,'' Boone says.
``Not just bricks. They left toilet bowls on my lawn, painted slurs
on my house and covered it in eggs. That strengthened me. I wasn't
going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the turmoil, the two coaches supported each other with
Boone taking the offense and Yoast leading the defense. Their
coaching styles were also attractive opposites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herman is so aggressive _ a Woody Hayes type,'' Yoast says.
``I'm more like Tom Landry.'' Boone describes it this way: Yoast is
``the calm before the storm. I'm the storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who repeatedly declined to be interviewed in Atlanta
for ``Titans,'' and Patton spent time with both coaches for
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denzel came to my house in Alexandria the night of a
hurricane,'' Boone recalls. ``He wanted especially to know things I
said, how I talked and like my family's word for cursing. We use
John Brown. If you're mad, you say 'John Brown it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really trying to play me,'' Boone says. ``It becomes
frightening. After all this, I may not be able to go to the
drugstore ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
