<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIRST SEVEN YEARS': PITY THE COBBLER WITH A SCUFFED SOUL
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
By WALTER GOODMAN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernard Malamud's ``First Seven Years'' is a love story in which
the lovers are never caught meeting, neither on the page nor in
Sunday's quiet screen adaption. Emotions are subdued in Feld's shoe
repair shop on the Lower East Side of Manhattan, but passion for
Feld's pretty 19-year-old daughter, Miriam, bubbles in the bosom of
Sobel, 35, a concentration-camp survivor who has been Feld's sole
employee for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's feelings are confined to books; Sobel lends Miriam
``The Brothers Karamazov,'' not your typical love story. Feld
discerns that something is up and wants a more promising match for
his daughter than an over-the-hill cobbler. ``Don't you want to
meet a college boy?'' he pleads. He tries to fix her up with young
Max, who is studying to be an accountant when he is not reading the
sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   The taciturn Sobel puts down his tools, takes off his apron and
quits. In what must be the first real talk about the most important
thing in both men's lives, he protests to Feld: ``Why do you look
for boys on the street to go out with Miriam? Why don't you think
of me?''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much the tale, distinctively Malamudian in its
sureness of characterization, if not one of his most imposing
works. These are little people with big hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Seven Years'' benefits Friday night from the
30-minute production's faithfulness to place and to period
(although the shop is too tidy) and to Israel Horovitz's nuanced
portrayal of Feld. Although he is no philistine, it takes Sobel's
outburst to awaken him to both Sobel's love for Miriam and her own
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Feld knows that his quick reaction _ ``My Miriam will never
marry a man as old and as ugly as you'' _ is cruel, and he is too
decent not to appreciate what he owes to a loyal worker and a camp
survivor to boot. But not to worry: Max the aspiring accountant is
not for a girl who goes for Dostoyevsky.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are all low-key; neither Sobel (Ned Eisenberg)
nor Miriam (Annette Arnold) is given to romantic effusions, and
dramatic impact is determinedly understated or avoided. That seems
right for 1949, when Feld and Sobel are still absorbing the
imponderables of the Holocaust while scrabbling to make a living
and a life.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a somewhat bland dish: say, gefilte fish with not
enough bite. But the flavor is sweet, and it goes down easily. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE FIRST SEVEN YEARS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On PBS, Channel 13, New York, Sunday night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   at 11:45.
</P>
<P>
   Presented by KTEH, San Jose, Calif. Based on the story by
Bernard Malamud. Brian Devine and Jason Orans, producers; Jen
Small, associate producer; Rachel Saltz and Kryssa Schemmerling,
writers and directors. Danny L. McGuire, executive producer for
KTEH; Molly Bernstein, editor; Rolf Grimsted, production design;
Ben Wolf, director of photography.
</P>
<P>
   With: Israel Horovitz (Feld), Carol Kane (Mrs. Feld), Annette
Arnold (Miriam), Daniel London (Max) and Ned Eisenberg (Sobel). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
