<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RFK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      12-16 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RFK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IN LOVE WITH NIGHT': DECONSTRUCTING ANOTHER KENNEDY MYTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The enigmatic title of Ronald Steel's new book, ``In Love With
Night,'' comes from the Shakespeare lines that Robert F. Kennedy
quoted, in a tribute to his assassinated brother, at the 1964
Democratic National Convention. The lines, spoken by Juliet about
Romeo, read:
</P>
<P>
   When he shall die,
</P>
<P>
   Take him and cut him out in little stars,
</P>
<P>
   And he will make the face of heaven so fine
</P>
<P>
   That all the world will be in love with night,
</P>
<P>
   And pay no worship to the garish sun.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion with both Kennedy brothers, of course, is that
they have become posthumous members of a dazzling celestial
pantheon, mythic figures more powerful in death than in life.
</P>
<P>
   There is a second, darker meaning, however, to the book's title.
Throughout this volume Steel speaks of the two Bobbys: the ``bad
Bobby'' (the vicious campaign manager, the merciless congressional
investigator) and the ``good Bobby'' (the empathetic advocate of
civil rights, the impassioned champion of the poor and the
oppressed).
</P>
<P>
   The ``bad Bobby,'' Steel asserts, committed ``dark deeds'' that
made him, in the words of Robert Frost, well ``acquainted with the
night.'' He defended, even applauded, the Red-baiting of his former
boss, Sen. Joseph McCarthy. As his brother's attorney general, he
demonstrated what Steel calls ``a disturbing tendency to justify
whatever behavior he found useful'' in his pursuit of adversaries
like Jimmy Hoffa. And in his zeal to get Fidel Castro, Steel
writes, he ``was drawn excitedly into the shadowy world of
counterinsurgency,'' proposing what amounted to ``a U.S.-financed
and -directed terrorist operation.''
</P>
<P>
   In this volume Steel, the author of such critically acclaimed
books as ``Pax Americana'' and ``Walter Lippmann and the American
Century,'' tries to deconstruct the myths that have grown up around
Robert Kennedy, most notably the myths that ``had he lived and
become president, he would have quickly ended the Vietnam War,
brought black and white Americans together, alleviated poverty and
discrimination and achieved a more just and humane society.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel concludes that ``there is little, beyond hope and need, to
lead us to believe'' that Kennedy could _ or would _ have
accomplished such dreams. He reminds us that RFK ``is not
remembered for any single great achievement'' in his thousand days
as attorney general or his equally brief tenure as a U.S. senator,
and he adds that ``much of Kennedy's allure lies in the future
conditional: in what he would have been, what he would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Such observations are not exactly earthshaking, especially in
light of all the revisionist portraits of the Kennedys in recent
years. In fact, ``In Love With Night,'' which Steel describes as
``a study of character and circumstance'' in the style of
Plutarch's ``Lives,'' is essentially a long essay that pulls
together a lot of familiar material while glossing it with
speculative analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The chapters about President John F. Kennedy's administration
are indebted to books by Michael R. Beschloss and Richard Reeves,
while Steel's examination of RFK's contentious relationship with
Lyndon B. Johnson owes a serious debt to Jeff Shesol's compelling
1997 book ``Mutual Contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of RFK's involvement in CIA plots against Castro
and his possible role in catalyzing events that would lead to his
brother's assassination, Steel goes further than Shesol. Whereas
Shesol suggested that Robert Kennedy might have experienced ``guilt
_ or fear that his own adventurism had cost his brother's life,''
Steel contends that ``his sense of guilt was overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Bobby who had hounded the Mafia; who had goaded the CIA
to get rid of Castro; who knew of his brother's connection to the
very Mafia don the CIA had hired to kill the Cuban leader,'' Steel
writes in one particularly melodramatic passage. ``The psychic
weight of such a burden of knowledge and responsibility must have
been enormous _ the fear that in his single-minded zeal to destroy
those whom he considered to be evil, he had set in motion actions
that resulted in the murder of his brother. This is the horrible
irony he carried with him and kept secret until the day he died. He
had trafficked in the darkest realms of conspiracy and murder, and
he had brought this fate upon himself. It was the classic
definition of Greek tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is popularly believed that the grief Robert Kennedy
experienced over his brother's death ``helped humanize him,'' that
in the months after the assassination a sensitive, caring ``new
Bobby'' emerged ``from the chrysalis of the old.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Steel seems to believe that RFK tried, near the end of
his life, ``to compensate for his failings by identifying himself
with the deprived,'' he remains skeptical about the depth of this
transformation. He credits Robert Kennedy with having ``learned to
talk the talk,'' giving speeches that underscored his empathy with
the disfranchised, but argues that his new concern for civil rights
``could have been simple political calculation: he needed the votes
of black Americans if he was to stand a chance of being elected
senator or president.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel argues that RFK's antipoverty plan was insignificant as
``a national program to attack the causes of poverty, or as a means
of breaking down segregation.'' As for his stand on Vietnam, Steel
not only points out that Robert Kennedy had been an ardent hawk
(``we will remain here until we do win,'' he said in Saigon in
February 1962) but also adds that his eventual criticism of the war
was considerably less radical than Eugene McCarthy's.
</P>
<P>
   Had he lived and been elected president, Steel speculates,
Robert Kennedy ``would probably have worked out some means of
extrication from Vietnam earlier than Nixon did,'' but ``his
opposition to unilateral withdrawal and his vague formulas for a
negotiated settlement hardly differed from Nixon's `peace with
honor' formula.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, then, the portrait of RFK that Steel draws in this
slender book is that of a man in thrall to his brother's memory, a
man both imprisoned and empowered by his family's mythology, a man
who is ``remembered to this day as an idealist,'' but who was in
fact ``an agile and unsentimental realist in the pursuit and the
wielding of political power.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IN LOVE WITH NIGHT: The American Romance With Robert Kennedy'
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Steel
</P>
<P>
   220 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
