<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writer-director DePoy sets his latest mystery in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many beginning mystery writers read Raymond Chandler or Dashiell
Hammett for inspiration. Phillip DePoy turned to Argentine author
Jorge Luis Borges for the magical realism in his Flap Tucker
mystery novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stories are like little metaphysical mysteries,'' says
DePoy, whose latest novel, ``Dancing Made Easy'' (Dell, $5.99),
features his detective on the trail of a serial killer in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker is not like other private eyes. A Zen master with psychic
gifts, he uses patterns and meditation instead of a gun to solve
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The new novel opens with the discovery of a young woman hanging
by an apron string from a lamppost in Piedmont Park. Pinned to her
clothing is a note: ``Number One: The Tarantella.'' When a second
body is found with a second note that reads ``Number Two: The
Tango,'' Flap Tucker turns to the city's rival crime czars to help
stop the killer.
</P>
<P>
   DePoy, who juggles his writing career with a job as a theater
director, says he finds both stimulating. ``One informs the other.
One thing that helped sell the novel, my editor said, was the
dialogue that I get from theater.''
</P>
<P>
   DePoy's next directing project is ``The Complete History of
America, Abridged,'' which will be performed at Marietta's Theatre
in the Square in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his previous novel, ``Two Easy,'' has been nominated
for a Shamus Award. ``If you compare the Edgar Award to the
Oscar,'' he says with a laugh, ``then I guess the Shamus is the
equivalent to the Golden Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   DePoy will be onstage at 8 p.m. Sunday at the Horizon Theatre,
1083 Austin Ave. N.E., with three other performers for an ensemble
reading of ``Dancing Made Easy.'' Information: 404-584-7450.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Poetry of the people: Several years ago, poet laureate Robert
Pinsky set out to ask the American people what their favorite poems
were. After holding a series of open readings and sifting through
thousands of letters, Pinsky has compiled 200 of these in a new
anthology, ``America's Favorite Poems'' (Norton, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Included are five metro Atlantans' favorite poems with their
remarks. Nancy Nersessian, 51, relates the influence ``The
Sentence'' by Russian poet Anna Akhmatova had on her in
understanding her brother's experience in Vietnam. ``It struck me
very forcefully as capturing the struggle that my brother faced
with all the other traumatized vets.... He shipped out for Vietnam
in January 1970 and after a year in continuous combat he returned
home a decorated war hero and a broken man of 21.'' Part of the
poem reads: ``Today I have so much to do/ I must kill memory once
and for all, / I must turn my soul to stone, / I must learn to live
again ....''
</P>
<P>
   Yina Liang, 15, an Atlanta student, chose Emily Dickinson's
``I'm Nobody! Who Are You?'' because ``it tells me I can be by
myself, and it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Hartley, 36, an Atlanta furniture builder, said the first
verse of ``The Waking'' by Theodore Roethke _ ``I wake to sleep,
and take my waking slow'' _ helped him deal with his leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta student Lee Samuel, 11, chose Ernest Lawrence Thayer's
``Casey at the Bat'' because ``I am a complete baseball fanatic.''
Elizabeth Kendall, 13, a Conyers student, selected Sir Henry
Wotton's ``On a Bank as I Sat Fishing'' because of her love of the
outdoors. Nature seems so peaceful on the surface, she writes,
``but by lifting a rock, I can find a whole new world, full of
lizards and bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A career like a rocket: Huntsville, Ala., writer Homer H.
Hickam Jr., author of ``Rocket Boys,'' has signed a $1 million-plus
deal for two more books about his West Virginia childhood. The
inspiring autobiographical ``Rocket Boys,'' which was made into the
film ``October Sky,'' was the story of small-town boys who built a
rocket and won a national science competition. The first book in
the new contract is ``A Coalwood Christmas,'' a tale of the Hickham
family's last Christmas together in their mining town. The second
will continue the story of the boys to the summer after high school
graduation. Meanwhile, the movie rights to Hickham's novel, ``Back
to the Moon,'' have been sold to Beacon Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
