 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Black Mountain, N.C. _ Holiday events include Circle of Lights
featuring luminarias and caroling at Lake Tomahawk on Saturday and
Holiday Tour of Inns on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-669-2301.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winston-Salem, N.C. _ The 34th annual Salem Christmas on
Saturday is the highlight of the holiday season at Old Salem, which
runs through December. A Moravian backcountry Christmas celebration
of the late 1700s and early 1800s will be re-created. Historic
buildings dating to 1769 are open for candlelight tours. Also, ``A
Neoclassical Southern Christmas'' at the Museum of Early Southern
Decorative Arts and traditional music by Puddingstone.
1-800-653-7253 or www.oldsalem.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, Ga. _ Candlelight Christmas Evenings at Biltmore
House continue through Jan. 1. Hundreds of luminarias light the
front lawn, and fireplaces inside glow as guests enjoy the music
and opulent decor of another age. 1-800-543-2961 or
www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Huntsville, Ala. _ Huntsville Botanical Gardens' ``Galaxy of
Lights'' Friday through Dec. 31 takes visitors into a fantasy world
with shooting stars for lampposts, Santa and his reindeer and an
icicle forest with snowflakes. 256-830-4447.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anniston, Ala. _ The Anniston Museum of Natural History Museum
Store hosts its annual fine arts and crafts show, ``A Winter
Market,'' featuring the works of more than 60 Southeastern artists.
Through Dec. 26. 256-237-6766 or www.anniston.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ The Tennessee Aquarium Imax 3D Theater presents
``The Imax Nutcracker,'' a 37-minute, nonballet adaptation of the
classic E.T.A. Hoffmann fairy tale, through Jan. 3. 1-800-262-0695
or www.tnaqua.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. _ The Colonial village will be gift-wrapped
in 18th-century Christmas decorations through Jan. 2. Events
include ``Felicity in Williamsburg: An American Girls Living
History Program'' and the exhibit ``Holiday Magic: Antique Toys and
Playthings.''
</P>
<P>
   1-800-447-8679.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ The sixth annual Nights of Lights,
illuminating the houses and buildings of historic downtown with
millions of tiny white lights, continues through January. On
Saturday: Las Posadas, a traditional Spanish candlelight procession
led by Mary and Joseph up San Marco Avenue, ending at a live
Nativity at the Mission of Nombre de Dios, live music and family
activities. Also Saturday: 18th Century Open House at Castillo de
San Marcos and candlelight caroling from the Downtown Plaza to the
fort.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-653-2489.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pine Mountain, Ga. _ Fantasy in Lights, the annual
light-and-sound holiday celebration, continues through Dec. 26. See
larger-than-life displays nestled in the woodlands, a Nativity and
``The Night Before Christmas'' displays on Robin Lake Beach and the
Christmas Village, featuring food, entertainment and shopping in
the Beach Dome. 1-800-225-5292 or www.callawaygardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Lanier Islands, Ga. _ Magical Nights of Lights
illuminates Lake Lanier Islands Resort through Dec. 30 with
animated light displays along a 6.5-mile drive, plus Santa's
Village and Holiday Village with live music, holiday fare and a
bonfire for roasting marshmallows. 770-945-8787 or
www.lakelanierislands
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ Dollywood's ``Smoky Mountain Christmas''
continues through Dec. 30 with yuletide entertainment, including a
live Nativity, gospel music and shows such as ``Hometown
Holidays,'' ``Christmas in the Smokies'' and ``Christmas on the
Porch.''
</P>
<P>
   1-800-365-5996 or www.dollywood.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
