<HEADER>
A1097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HOMELESS17-COX     12-16 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOMELESSNESS, HUNGER PERSIST AMIDST PLENTY, MAYORS REPORT
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Problems of homelessness and hunger are growing
despite the nation's economic prosperity, according to a study
released Thursday by the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From sea to shining sea, great pockets of homelessness exist
and persist,'' said Mayor Vincent Cianci of Providence, R.I., a
member of the task force.
</P>
<P>
   The 15th annual survey of 26 cities indicated that demands for
emergency food and shelter assistance are at their highest levels
in years. The numbers show no sign of leveling off, said Mayor
Peter Clavelle of Burlington, Vt., chair of the survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this task force still exists is a statement in
itself,'' Clavelle said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Low-paying jobs and high housing costs are to blame for much of
the problems. The task force found the ``working poor'' had the
greatest need for emergency assistance programs, which in some
cases have had to turn away people seeking help because of excess
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homelessness is a symptom of larger problems,'' said Fred
Karnas, a deputy assistant secretary for economic development in
the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment, mental illness and substance abuse contribute to
the homeless problem as well, Clavelle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what to do to fix these problems. We just need to do
more of it,'' Karnas said.
</P>
<P>
   The task force called for increased local control over services
and resources and more efforts by community-based organizations to
address low job skills and job placement.
</P>
<P>
   Education about benefit programs can also be expanded. Some
people may not be aware of their eligibility for federal
assistance, said Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman. One-third of
people eligible for food stamps don't take advantage of them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MEXICO-Y2K-$ADV18-COX     12-16 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-Y2K-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO STEPPING UP TO THE PLATE ON Y2K READINESS
 &HT;    With MEXICO-MILLENNIUM-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington, (i) International and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Dec. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX and SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While computer experts question whether many Latin
American countries will be prepared to fend off millennium computer
bugs on Jan. 1, Mexico stands as a model of ``Y2K'' readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is an interesting success story,'' said John Koskinen,
head of the U.S. President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``Mexico is very well prepared'' for facing the
so-called Y2K bug, a widespread software flaw that could cause some
older computers to read only the last two digits of the date. That
seemingly small programming error could cause many computers to
malfunction or shut down on or after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen and other Y2K experts say that in terms of crushing
computer bugs, Mexico appears on par with its North American free
trade partners, the United States and Canada. Mexican industries
already have completed complex Y2K tests and demonstrated back-up
systems before international observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee nothing will happen, but we can say that
Mexico is prepared,'' said Victor Guerrero, technical director for
Mexico's Commission for Information Conversion in 2000 in Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts attribute Mexico's vigorous attack on the bug
to several factors, starting with President Ernesto Zedillo's
commitment to modernizing the nation's software. Rather than
procrastinate, as did many political and business leaders in other
Latin American countries, Zedillo assigned thousands of government
computer programmers, engineers and auditors to fix Y2K problems,
starting more than two years ago and committing $236 million to the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zedillo made Y2K a high priority issue,'' also meeting several
times with his counterparts from the United States and Canada to
coordinate bug-battling efforts, Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico also had some advantages over the U.S. and Canada. In
Mexico, state monopolies control huge industries, which makes it
easier for the government to order nationwide repairs. For example,
Mexico's Federal Electricity Commission generates about 98 percent
of the country's power. In the United States, thousands of private
power companies had to manage the Y2K problem without direct
government oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico also has a state oil monopoly in Petroleos Mexicanos
(Pemex).
</P>
<P>
   Telefonos de Mexico (Telmex) is privately owned, but it is a
monopoly that also went through the motions to correct potential
problems.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans have to count on the Y2K-readiness of thousands
of lending institutions, Mexicans have only 16 banks. This October,
those banks collectively performed a large-scale test to see how
check cashing, deposits and ATM withdrawals would be affected by
the date change. ``We discovered only small flaws,'' Guerrero said.
</P>
<P>
   By having far fewer companies to manage and far greater
government control over them, Zedillo was able to push
Y2K-remediation plans at a surprisingly quick pace, Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mexico benefitted from its close business ties with
U.S. and European companies. For example, global automakers'
assembly plants in Mexico used the same software fixes there that
they used in domestic plants.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico only has about 5 million computers, most of which are
concentrated in the financial sector, government, airline services
and in large manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   In July, six of Mexico's main airlines participated in a test
that required them to fly to various cities and land during and
after simulated clock changes.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, Mexican airports are planning to suspend
take-offs between 11:45 p.m. (CST) on Dec. 31 and 12:30 a.m. (CST)
on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But international observers, Guerrero said, have agreed that
Mexico's airports appear to be prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been intense international activity here,'' he
added. Mexico belongs to a United Nations group that was directing
Y2K preparations. Mexico has also served as a coordinator helping
Central American and Caribbean countries.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's national electrical supply will be supervised on the
night of Dec. 31 through Jan. 4 with an extra 1,500 technicians,
according to Jorge Hernandez Aguilar, manager of Information and
Telecommunications for the Federal Electrical Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happens, we'll be the first thing society
notices,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the electrical commission invested $45 million in
overhauling its equipment. If computers fail, however, the system
can be run manually, Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready just as we would be ready for a natural
disaster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity commission also has an early-warning system that
will alert technicians if other countries begin to experience
problems as the clock changes. It also has an independent satellite
telephone system for communications.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's only nuclear power plant, Laguna Verde on the Gulf
Coast, has also been prepared for the new millennium. Accusations
of mismanagement and corruption have dogged the plant in the past,
but Hernandez said Laguna Verde's Y2K readiness meets international
standards, including those set by the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said more than 130 private businesses were concerned
enough to petition the electricity commission to check its system
to ensure preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's huge Volkswagen car manufacturer, for example, asked to
audit the commission.
</P>
<P>
   We opened our doors because it was beneficial for us to know if
there was a problem,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Where Mexico may have problems is with its small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the United States, many small entrepreneurs have not
had the time or money to focus on Y2K the way big businesses have.
But some computer experts say Mexico's small businesses may
actually have an advantage in terms of Y2K because they still
operate with manual systems that do not depend on computers.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers correspondents Marilyn Geewax and Susan Ferriss
reported from Washington and Mexico City, respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-1217-CO     12-16 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-1217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SYRIA-ISRAELI PEACE WOULD SETTLE MOST REGIONAL CONFLICT, BUT
PALESTINIANS IN WINGS
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-TALKS-1217.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Just before then-Egyptian President Anwar Sadat made
his historic journey of peace to Jerusalem in 1979, he asked Syrian
President Hafez Assad to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Assad refused. Moreover, when Sadat made his journey, an
embittered Assad declared a Syrian national day of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, Syria has lead the block of ``rejectionist'' Arab
countries, saying no to peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   That's why an agreement to continue peace talks in Washington in
January matters. Peace between Israel and Syria could lead to the
end of the Israeli-Arab conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a conviction that Syria is really in control of the
whole process of peacemaking,'' said Jordanian political analyst
Radwan Abdullah. ``If Syria joins the peace process, that's it. All
doors will be open.''
</P>
<P>
   A peace with Syria would likely bring along its neighbors _ from
Lebanon to Saudi Arabia. The largest question would be its affect
on peace between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A success with Syria could relieve pressure on Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, who promised voters he would make peace, to
deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Barak's trip to Washington has extended delays in two
peace process deadlines _ the next transfer of land to the
Palestinians and the next release of Palestinians from Israeli
jails.
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli newspaper reported Thursday that U.S. President Bill
Clinton urged Barak not to play the Syrians off against the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Palestinian officials say there can't be a
peaceful Middle East if they are left forgotten and stateless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the core of the problem,'' Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat told Cox Newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Though Syria could attack with tanks over a border, it has not
for nearly 20 years. The Israelis and Palestinians, meanwhile,
clash frequently in close quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the daily strategic threat to them and they are the
daily life strategic threat to us,'' Erekat said. ``We cannot
escape each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials say security in Syria will make it easier to
make deals all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The developments with Syria aren't going to have any negative
impact on talks with Palestinians. Rather, it's the other way
around,'' Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said last week.
</P>
<P>
   American University in Cairo political scientist Walid Kazziha
said, however, that Palestinian President Yasser Arafat's influence
over Israel is already slipping and will drop more if Syria leads
the other Arab states into peace.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, meanwhile, could fulfill Israel's dream of being accepted
throughout the Middle East. Egypt signed a treaty with Israel in
1982. The PLO officially ended its hostilities in 1993 and Jordan
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis, and American mediators, see Syria as the key to the
rest of the ``rejectionists'' in the region.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Syria controls Lebanon, maintaining 40,000 troops
there. In any agreement, Israel will insist that Syria reign in the
Hezbollah guerillas fighting against Israel in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   That would end the 18-year war Israel has fought there and lead
to its withdrawal from Lebanese land its has occupied for 18 years.
Lebanon would then likely sign a treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Syria could also bring Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and other Persian
Gulf Arab states to open relations with Israel. Some of them
explored diplomatic ties with Israel during the intense 1994-96
round of Syria-Israel talks.
</P>
<P>
   The oil-rich Gulf states and technology-savvy Israel are eager
to begin trade with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Syria is the Arab country with the best relations with
Iran, and could act as an intermediary between the two enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
