<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1114 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-AIRLINES17-COX     12-16 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-AIRLINES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JAN. 4 MAY BRING BIGGEST Y2K HEADACHE FOR AIR TRAVELERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Air travelers who hoped to avoid Y2K hassles on New
Year's Day by booking flights three days later may face other
troubles. Airlines expect Tuesday, Jan. 4 to be the busiest day of
the holiday travel season, with some 2 million people packing the
nation's airports.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, many travelers delayed their homeward-bound trips to
avoid possible service disruptions involving the Y2K bug, a
computer software flaw that could cause some computers to
malfunction when the date rolls over to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than rush back after New Year's, ``people are stretching
out their vacations,'' Delta Air Lines spokesman Kip Smith said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association (ATA), an industry trade group
based in Washington, forecast this week that 34.2 million people
will board planes during the two and a half weeks encompassing the
holidays. That would be about 700,000 passengers more than last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Before Christmas, the busiest travel days will stretch from
Friday, Dec. 17 to Monday, Dec. 20, with daily load factors _ the
proportion of seats offered that were sold _ hitting 83 percent. A
normal load factor is 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The least busy day will be New Year's Day, with just 1.3 million
passengers boarding planes.
</P>
<P>
   While Jan. 1 is always a relatively quiet travel day, concerns
about the Y2K bug will likely make the first day of 2000
particularly low-key, ATA spokesman David Fuscus said. He noted
that while overall planned holiday travel is up from last year,
travel on New Year's Day is down significantly from last year's
figure of 1.6 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the big drop in passengers Jan. 1, major airlines
have been cutting the number of scheduled flights. For example,
Delta is scheduling 18 percent fewer _ significantly more than last
year's 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At a Thursday press briefing about the air traffic control
system, the Federal Aviation Administration's top Y2K expert, Mary
Powers-King, said flight reductions would not cause any FAA
staffing cutbacks. ``We plan business as usual,'' she said. In
fact, the FAA will have extra staff on duty to make sure all
systems operate well during the date rollover.
</P>
<P>
   She said the FAA completed its software fixes in June, and since
that time has ``tested and retested'' all systems. ``We believe we
are in excellent shape,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
