<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLE'S-DALLAS-ART-3T     12-16 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-DALLAS-ART-3TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 10-GALLON PLACE WITH DREAMS TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The words and music have stuck in my mind for 40-odd
years, because they seemed so apt. Frank Loesser wrote them for a
musical called ``The Most Happy Fella,'' and they stopped the show
every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're from Big D I can guess,'' a brassy dame sang, ``by the
way you drawl and the way you dress. You're from Big D, my, oh yes.
I mean Big D, little a, double l, a, s. And that spells Dallas, my
darlin', darlin' Dallas ... where every home's a palace, 'cause the
settlers settle for no less.''
</P>
<P>
   Big money, big hair, big talk. Such is the lingering stereotype
of this city. It occupies a sizable spot in the national
consciousness as the home of the big, bad Dallas Cowboys, of J.R.
Ewing and Miss Ellie and all the gang at Southfork, and of the
little guy with the big ears and bigger ambition, H. Ross Perot,
who was a billionaire before he turned 40.
</P>
<P>
   And for those old enough to recall the events of November 1963,
it occupies an especially dark corner of memory, as the cursed
place where John F. Kennedy was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Dallas and its smaller sibling, Fort Worth, an unmatched
pair if ever there was one, amount to much more than that. Together
with the little cities that cluster around them like pilot fish,
they constitute the largest metropolitan area in the nation's
second largest state. (Houston is bigger, but its metropolitan area
is slightly smaller.) They boast the largest collection of major
corporate headquarters outside of New York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Identified with all that is brash, Dallas is also the home of
Neiman Marcus, an emblem of all that is stylish, and of its
impresario, Stanley Marcus, an emblem of all that is civilized and
sophisticated, who still travels alone at age 95. ( Marcus brought
the designer Coco Chanel to Dallas in 1957 for one of his store's
fabulous Foreign Fortnights and reported later that he had found
her a dull luncheon companion.)
</P>
<P>
   Once known as Cowtown, Fort Worth is the home of the Kimbell Art
Museum, the masterwork of the great modernist Louis I. Kahn, with
an exquisite collection of Old Masters in its top-lit galleries. At
the risk of offending fans of the Frick in New York, the Gardner in
Boston and the Phillips in Washington, I would choose it as the
nation's best small museum.
</P>
<P>
   Enormously wealthy, often eccentric men populate the histories
of the two cities: Columbus Marion (Dad) Joiner, who discovered the
largest oil field in the world on Daisy Bradford's farm in Rusk
County; H.L. Hunt, who bought the leases from him for $30,000,
built an empire and spent his old age as a megarich loony, selling
Gastro-Majic indigestion pills at the state fair; and Sid
Richardson, a legendary wildcatter whose great-nephews, the Bass
brothers, have invested it well, amassing a huge fortune and
rebuilding downtown Fort Worth in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is incredibly inventive, endlessly entrepreneurial. Here
Herb Kelleher dreamed up Southwest Airlines, with its low prices
and jokey style (``Austin Auften,'' say the billboards). His planes
have become the Greyhounds of the 1990s. Here a Texas Instruments
engineer named Jack Kilby, who had been with the company too short
a time to earn a vacation, spent July 1958 in the lab and hit upon
the idea of the silicon chip, or integrated circuit, ushering in
what has been called the Second Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed since Harry McPherson was growing up in Tyler,
100 miles east of Dallas. McPherson went to Washington in the
Johnson years and stayed on, writing what is widely considered one
of the best books ever written on the capital, ``A Political
Education'' (1972). And there is much that still rings true about
the description of Dallas that he wrote 20 years ago for The
Atlantic, including this passage:
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as you passed the Buckner Orphans' Home _ I imagined it
full of city kids like Mickey Rooney, presided over by Spencer
Tracy _ you could see the metropolitan skyline. It floated in the
cold autumn sunlight, or trembled in the waves of summer heat.
Dallas. Mysterious. Rich. Full of merchants, criminals and
transplanted country boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas took a pasting in the second half of the 1980s. ``They're
going to go broke, making all of these crazy loans,'' Theodore H.
Strauss, the businessman-brother of Robert S. Strauss, the Dallas
and Washington lawyer and politico, remembers telling his friends.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. One by one, the big Dallas banks, overextended,
stuck with worthless real estate and energy paper, were forced to
turn to Washington or out-of-state holding companies for rescue.
Finally, not a single locally owned bank was left, only
subsidiaries of the big outfits in New York, and Charlotte, N.C.,
and Columbus, Ohio. A lot of proud old Dallas families watched
fortunes vanish.
</P>
<P>
   There were other shocks. Walker L. Railey, the minister of the
First United Methodist Church, one of the largest in the nation,
was accused of choking his wife, leaving her in a permanent
vegetative state. He had been the golden boy of the religious
community in a city where religion counts for a lot, where a
broadcasting network ornaments its offices at Christmas with red
tinsel letters spelling out the words, ``Happy Birthday, Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   So the downfall of Railey, who tried to commit suicide,
confessed to an affair with the wife of another minister and then
left town with her, staggered the city almost as much as the big
banks' collapse. Even when a jury acquitted him.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the scandal at Southern Methodist University.
Southern Methodist is another of the city's defining institutions,
as pivotal in its way to Dallas as Harvard is to Boston. With its
splendid Meadows Museum of Spanish art, it lies at the heart of the
enclave, north of downtown, known as Park Cities _ Highland Park
and University Park. Conservative, wealthy, snobbish, the Park
Cities are also known as ``the Bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   As its residents see things, scandals belong to the messy world
outside the Bubble, not the orderly one inside, but it emerged in
1987 that Southern Methodist had been illegally paying its football
players. Worse, the board of trustees, led by Gov. William P.
Clements Jr., had known of the payments and had contrived an
elaborate scheme of bribes to cover them up. The National
Collegiate Athletic Association imposed the toughest sanctions in
its history, and Southern Methodist, which had produced gridiron
immortals like Doak Walker and Don Meredith, fielded no football
team at all for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   As John Steinbeck wrote in ``Travels With Charley,'' in 1962,
``Football games have the glory and the despair of war, and when a
Texas team takes the field against a foreign state, it is an army
with banners.'' In war, rules are often bent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of metaphor of how far things can get out of hand
when people are so highly focused on competition, success, being
No. 1,'' Dr. Leroy T. Howe, the president of the university's
faculty senate, commented at the time. ``In Dallas, the people who
aren't winning are losing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
