<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-Y2K-CZAR-$ADV19-HNS &LR;      12-16 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CZAR-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NATION'S Y2K CZAR HOPES FEW WILL REMEMBER HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Dec. 19)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People following the news on New Year's weekend
will likely see a lot about John Koskinen, the White House's Y2K
czar.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Friday, Dec. 31, Koskinen will be telling Americans
how the world is coping as the clock moves past midnight in each of
the world's 24 time zones, gradually ushering in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But once New Year's weekend is over, Koskinen hopes few
Americans will remember his name. If that turns out to be true, he
says he will see it as a signal that the United States experienced
relatively few Y2K-related glitches.
</P>
<P>
   But if Y2K calamities erupt across the nation, he worries that
he would be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I'll) be the person they point fingers at if everything goes
wrong,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen, 60, has spent the last 21 months making sure that
dozens of federal agencies were fixing their computers to properly
read the digits ``00`` as 2000, rather than 1900. Failure to read
the correct date could cause date-based computers to shut down,
potentially creating havoc in such key systems as air traffic
control and electrical power distribution. This is the crux of
concerns about Y2K, a shorthand for year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   During the next two weeks Koskinen will put the finishing
touches on a $50 million federal command center that will act as
the nation's Y2K clearinghouse starting Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 people at the center near the White House will be
responsible for collecting information from other parts of the
federal government as well as private industry about how the world
is faring as it moves into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department will likely be the first agency reporting
into the center shortly after New Zealand becomes the first major
country to enter the New Year at 6 a.m. EST on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen has been spending most of his 15-hour workday
overseeing the design of the nuts-and-bolts operation of the
command center. It involves testing the newly installed computer
system that will connect with other government computers scattered
around the Washington, D.C. area.
</P>
<P>
   He answers more than 100 e-mails a day and continues to have
meetings and conference calls with everyone from Washington, D.C.'s
mayor to federal agency heads to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen says he is confident that there will be relatively few
Y2K-related problems in the United States, although he can't say
the same for some other countries. But when Koskinen began his job
in March 1998, he admits he was ``a little nervous.'' That's
because important government operations such as the air traffic
control system or the agency that manages Medicare and Medicaid and
the Defense Department ``were thought to be lost causes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people suggested that lagging agencies like the Federal
Aviation Administration _ which runs air traffic control _ simply
forgo fixing its computers and draft plans to manually run air
traffic control.
</P>
<P>
   Under Koskinen's leadership, the FAA, the Defense Department and
rest of the federal government did fix their computers and are
expecting normal operations on Jan. 1, 2000. In fact many of those
computers have been properly reading the year 2000 since the
government's new fiscal year began Oct. 1 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   While Koskinen's job description only required him to be
responsible for the federal government, he quickly realized that it
didn't matter if government computers worked if widespread power
outages and food shortages disrupted Americans' lives, as some were
predicting would happen.
</P>
<P>
   He assembled a Y2K task force of key private industry groups
including airlines, banks, electric power, oil and gas and the
pharmaceutical industry to make sure that private industry was
prepared for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   He also became a Y2K czar of sorts for state governments, too.
That's because many federal benefits, such as Medicare and food
stamps, are distributed through the states
</P>
<P>
   And Koskinen also was called on to help oversee the District of
Columbia's Y2K conversion efforts. The district government didn't
start overhauling its computers until this year and isn't expected
to be completely ready by the year's end. However D.C. has
elaborate contingency plans to keep city services like 911
emergency telephone operations functioning smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming the nation's Y2K czar, Koskinen has tried to keep
his dry sense of humor to help him cope with the demands of his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, during a question-and-answer session
after he delivered a speech, an audience member asked whether the
city of Washington, D.C. was ready. Koskinen, a D.C. resident
himself, deadpanned, ``It's important to remember that the basic
infrastructure (the subway, power and phone system) is not run by
the district government.'' The audience erupted in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said he has enjoyed the challenge of helping to ensure
that the United States is ready for Y2K. In less than two weeks he
will find out how well he met the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't spend more than 25 years in the private sector
rebuilding large failed companies or managing two federal shutdowns
if you don't have a slightly masochistic tendency to look for
bigger and bigger challenges,'' he said. ``And they don't come any
bigger than Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen, a Yale-educated lawyer, spent 21 as president of the
Palmieri Co., which specializes in turning around companies with
financial problems. His clients included the Penn Central railroad
and the Mutual Benefit Life Insurance Co., the largest failed
insurance firm in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, President Clinton tapped him to serve as deputy
director of management at the White House's Office of Management
and Budget, a post he held until 1997. While he was at OMB, parts
of the federal government were shutdown in 1995 and 1996 when the
Congress and Clinton failed to reach agreement on a federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said he left his OMB job to travel with his wife,
Patricia. ``I had never taken more than two weeks vacation a
year,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   But his trip was cut short when President Clinton tracked him
down in Amsterdam in January 1998, to ask him to return to
government. Koskinen will likely remain in his post until March.
After that Koskinen plans to resume his travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I won't leave a forwarding address,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
