<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLE'S-DALLAS-ART-2N     12-16 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-DALLAS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DALLAS: are losing.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas is booming again. You see it vividly in the procession of
shiny new buildings marching along the so-called Platinum Corridor,
a 14-mile stretch of the Dallas North Tollway from the L.B.J.
Freeway to Plano. This is now one of many economic nodes of the
Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex, as it is known.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered along the freeways, amid the barbecue joints and the
used-car lots, with their flags the size of basketball courts, are
the headquarters of companies like Frito-Lay and Exxon, J.C. Penney
and American Airlines, Texas Industries and Electronic Data
Systems, and scores of little companies in the computer, software,
Internet and communications businesses. Alcatel, Nortel, Nokia and
Ericsson all have offices on the North Tollway.
</P>
<P>
   But things have changed. Dallas is no longer so closely tied to
one business, as it once was to cotton, and then to oil, and then
to aerospace, and the bankers and developers have learned the value
of caution. They are not quite so eager to make or take loans
secured mostly by thin air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call ourselves `the city without boundaries,' but we're
growing up a little,'' said Gail Thomas, founder of the Dallas
Institute of Humanities and Culture. ``Dallas dreams big dreams; it
always has. You come here with a little idea, and it turns into a
big one. But there's a new realism.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard times produced some new and different leaders. At the low
point, with oil prices at rock bottom and the patriarchy in
retreat, the city turned to a woman, Annette Strauss, wife of
Theodore Strauss, as its mayor. She promptly got dozens of new arts
projects moving. And then Dallas, a little to its own surprise,
elected a black man, Ron Kirk, to succeed her.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Trinity River, the British weekly The Economist said not
long ago, ``bisects the city of Dallas as certainly as an ocean.''
Highland Park's whites enjoy average household incomes of more than
$200,000 a year; in largely black and Hispanic South Dallas, the
figure is a measly $11,350. Poor education takes a toll. Latinos
will make up the majority of the city's work force by 2010, but
today only 1 percent of high-tech employees are Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Dallas is another difficult problem for Kirk.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and law offices _ including Robert Strauss' powerhouse
firm Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld, with more than 900 lawyers
_ bring thousands of workers into the area by day, but by night the
sidewalks are eerily empty. New high-rise apartment blocks are
going up in and around the center of town, and the red Pegasus
sign, a landmark since 1934, is soon to be reinstalled atop the
recently renovated Magnolia Hotel. But Neiman Marcus' store looks
lonely amid shabby neighbors; hoped-for new restaurants and
theaters have not arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a new arts center may be part of the answer, but it
has been a long time a-coming.
</P>
<P>
   The arts center's linchpin is the 2,062-seat Morton H. Meyerson
Symphony Center, named by its principal donor, Perot, for one of
his business colleagues, who sings in the Dallas Symphony Chorus.
Designed by I.M. Pei, it combines the sharp angles of the National
Gallery's East Building in Washington with swelling glass
``blisters'' that allow sunlight to penetrate into restaurants and
lobbies. There are echoes of Garnier's Paris Opera in its
monumental exterior, and touches of Josef Hoffmann in the interior,
which is richly paneled in warmly hued woods.
</P>
<P>
   Both the building and its acoustics have won the affection of
the city, as has Andrew Litton, the Dallas Symphony Orchestra's
40-year-old conductor. New York-born, he reminds me of Leonard
Bernstein both in his athleticism on the podium and his fondness
for dramatic musical effect. He made his reputation with the
Bournemouth Symphony in England, which accounts for the frequent
appearance of Walton and Elgar on his programs.
</P>
<P>
   Only 25 years ago, the orchestra was in such stormy financial
straits that it had to suspend operations for a year. But at a time
when many orchestras face shrinking audiences, Dallas runs a solid
surplus, with subscription sales near 100 percent. It records
regularly, appears every year in Carnegie Hall and tours Europe _
all of the things that the big guys do.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Opera has no splendiferous new home, although the
arts center's master plan calls for one. For the moment, the opera
plays in the barny old Music Hall at Fair Park, a building with all
the charm and acoustical subtlety of an airplane hangar. Still, it
manages accomplished productions like last year's ``Katya
Kabanova'' and this year's ``Walkure,'' which starred James Morris
as Wotan. Next year, it will gain a new leader, Anthony
Whitworth-Jones, who served as the chief executive officer of the
much-admired Glyndebourne Festival Opera in southern England.
</P>
<P>
   A new leader has already arrived at the Dallas Museum of Art:
John R. Lane, who put the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art on the
map. He inherits a collection comprehensive in scope but uneven in
detail, with strong pre-Columbian and decorative arts departments
and several stellar individual paintings, including Mondrians
stretching from the early, representational style to the
neo-plastic masterpiece ``Place de la Concorde''; van Gogh's golden
``Sheaves of Wheat,'' and Hopper's evocative ``Lighthouse Hill.''
The highlight may be Frederic E. Church's immense, chill-inducing
canvas, ``The Icebergs,'' which was rediscovered in England and
bought in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Next door is a real jewel, a small museum of Asian art
established last year by Trammell Crow, one of the world's largest
real estate developers. The jade, the crystal ball (the world's
second-biggest, after one in the Smithsonian) and above all the
18th-century sandstone facade of a Rajasthan palace are don't-miss
attractions. Installations are immaculate. Memories of 1963
</P>
<P>
   Many come to Dallas to see the grassy knoll near which Kennedy
was killed, ``allegedly,'' as an official plaque puts it, by a shot
fired by Lee Harvey Oswald. Dallas still has doubts. In addition to
the city-backed Sixth Floor Museum, which shows
assassination-related articles like the camera used by Abraham
Zapruder to film the shooting, there is also a privately run
Conspiracy Museum nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had a mean streak in the 1960s; Lyndon B. Johnson was
jeered and spat upon in downtown Dallas in 1960, and Adlai E.
Stevenson was hit on the head with a placard by right-wing
demonstrators in 1963. Douglas Kiker, then a reporter for The New
York Herald Tribune, covering President Kennedy's visit, said after
the president was shot: ``If I had the power to, I'd call the
bombers over this place. How could a thing like this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   But of course Dallas did not kill Kennedy, any more than Los
Angeles killed his brother Robert.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
