<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLE'S-DALLAS-3RDTAK     12-16 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-DALLAS-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DALLAS: brother Robert.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven years afterward, a memorial designed by Philip Johnson and
paid for by 50,000 people across the country was opened a few
blocks from the knoll. It consists of four 30-foot-high concrete
walls, with narrow openings on two sides and an unadorned gray
granite cenotaph at its center. Some find it moving; some find it
sterile. Everyone finds it grubby with age, and early next year, a
long-overdue, $70,000 cleanup is scheduled to start.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose Houston buildings helped define that city's sleek
skyline, has designed a number of duds in Dallas, including the
Bank One tower, a weird neo-Palladian effort, and Crescent Court,
which marries lacy New Orleans ironwork to a monstrosity of a
mansard roof. Johnson once said (jokingly?) that he saved all of
his best ideas for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Other well-known architects have misfired here, too, like
Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, with a skyscraper pierced for no
apparent reason by a huge keyhole-shaped opening, and Frank Lloyd
Wright, whose Dallas Theater Center (completed in 1959) is
watered-down Guggenheim-ery. (Which is by no means to denigrate the
quality of the dramatic productions mounted there; the company,
heir to the tradition of Margo Jones, a regional theater pioneer,
is capably run by Richard Hamburger, son of Philip, the New Yorker
writer.)
</P>
<P>
   Pei's glittering, glass-sheathed Fountain Place, surrounded by
water terraces created by Dan Kiley, is the best high-rise in town,
just as Meyerson Hall is the best low-rise. But his Brutalist City
Hall, built in 1978, already looks dated.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable set of buildings in Dallas is the 26
Art Deco structures on the 127-acre Texas State Fairgrounds,
including the Cotton Bowl and the Hall of State, a celebration of
the state's gaudy history. For 24 days each fall, tens of thousands
of country folk, and thousands of others pretending to be, come to
ride the Ferris wheel and see the rodeo. Museums on the Rise
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, pride of place goes to the Kimbell. Kahn's long,
vaulted, refined galleries in oak, travertine, concrete and
stainless steel work as well today as the day they were built
(1972). Miraculously, every single picture in the building is worth
seeing, and almost all of them _ the Duccio, the Mantegna, the two
Georges de la Tours, the Caspar David Friedrich (the only one in an
American museum) and the magisterial ``Cardsharps'' of Caravaggio _
were acquired in the 1970s, '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Fort Worth museums are rebuilding, with the ubiquitous
Johnson doing the honors for the Amon Carter Museum, which focuses
on American art, Western and otherwise, and Tadeo Ando, the
respected Japanese architect, designing a new home for the Museum
of Modern Art. The city, which was once the southern terminus of
the Chisholm Trail, has clearly grown well beyond its colorful old
stockyards and its raucous, gargantuan honky-tonk, Billy Bob's
Texas. Even beyond its longtime slogan, ``Where the West Begins.''
</P>
<P>
   People call Fort Worth ``Bassville.'' The Basses have given it a
new performance hall, named after their father, Perry, with
limestone angels on the facade blowing immense brass trumpets. A
pastiche of Secession, Beaux-Arts and postmodern styles, it is much
loved locally, but I agree with a Dallas critic who termed it a
romance novel of a building.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' latest benefactor is Raymond Nasher, a developer whose
collection of modern sculpture, widely viewed as the world's best,
was courted by major museums from New York to Washington to San
Francisco. Instead, he is building a museum and garden across from
the Dallas Museum of Art to house a rotating selection of his
Matisses and Ernsts, Calders and Miros and Dubuffets, now displayed
in and near his brick-and-glass home in northern Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The architect is Renzo Piano, the Italian who designed the
superb Menil museum in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment,'' Nasher said, ``Dallas has nothing of real
artistic significance, internationally. Perhaps this can be it.
This is a nice city, but it's mostly about money. We're hoping to
change that a little.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
