<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMELESS-PHOTOGRAPHY-     12-16 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-PHOTOGRAPHY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A MUSEUM   DISPLAYS ITS HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, as recently as the 1970s, people did not live
on the street in cardboard boxes with their feet sticking out the
end. Homelessness, always with us but nowhere near as rampant as it
is today, was essentially invisible. Then a combination of
circumstances, including the emptying of mental institutions and
cutbacks in federal funds for housing, drove all sorts of people
onto the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers were on the case almost immediately. Street
photographers and photojournalists hail from a long tradition of
social observation, reporting and reform; and the combination of
real compassion and excitement at finding the picturesque poor
suddenly publicly available lured crowds of students and
professionals to the new haunts of the unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Today, just when you thought that crowds of the homeless in New
York were about to be carted off to jail, along comes the
pronouncement that there are other ways to handle the problem.
Curiously, that message is being delivered not by the press, an ad
or an advocacy group, but by a museum, in this case the Corcoran
Gallery of Art in Washington. Not so curiously, the existence of
despair and the potential for hope are given visual form at the
museum by photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The art museum at the century's end is a mixed institution if
ever there was one, a place where art, most commonly in the guise
of photography, joins social agendas and serves them. Public
museums have almost always had a social agenda, many having been
founded to educate the populace about art and improve the level of
culture and taste. But they did not specifically address the issues
of poverty or mental health or the social ills that beset cities,
nor did they expect their audience to achieve a heightened
awareness of these matters among casts of Greek statues and
paintings by Rembrandt.
</P>
<P>
   Now they do. The Corcoran is presenting ``The Way Home: Ending
Homelessness in America,'' an exhibition of some 150 images by 13
photographers, organized by the gallery in association with the
National Alliance to End Homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   The photographers _ Jodi Cobb, Donna Ferrato, Ben Fernandez,
Betsy Frampton, Annie Leibovitz, Mary Ellen Mark, Eli Reed, Joseph
Rodriguez, Stephen Shames, Callie Shell, Diana Walker and Clarence
Williams, as well as Tipper Gore, who has been active in this cause
_ had their expenses covered but contributed their time.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Brookman, the Corcoran's curator of photography and media
arts, and Jane Slate Siena, the head of institutional relations at
the Getty Conservation Institute in Los Angeles, were co-curators.
The show is accompanied by a book published by Harry N. Abrams,
which is donating proceeds from the sales to the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good show and a worthy one but photographically
uneven. All the work fits respectably within a tradition of
concerned photography, and the roster of photographers is
distinguished, but not all are represented by their best work.
Individual pictures by various photographers, including Ms. Mark,
Reed, Fernandez and Rodriguez, are gripping; Ms. Cobb's color is
startling; Ms. Ferrato's essay is informative. But some of the
photographs are the kind of link pictures that get you from one
place to another in an essay, necessary but not necessarily
arresting.
</P>
<P>
   In a show meant to demonstrate that there are solutions to
homelessness _ some put forward by organizations that provide not
just shelter but also crucial services like medical care,
psychological support and job training _ the entire exhibition may
be more important than individual pictures. At any rate, it has
never been clear how important aesthetics are to persuasion or even
to certain kinds of information. Context is all in such an
undertaking, and the texts add valuable information that the
photographs alone could not supply. Some of the successes achieved
by advocates for the homeless are pictured in the Corcoran show,
which maintains a fragile balance between pictures of homelessness
and of the way home.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to reconcile palaces of high art with the poverty
and distress at the margins of society. The Corcoran has devised an
ingenious setting for ``The Way Home,'' with several open-work
structures within the museum's classical galleries. These are built
of two-by-six boards with sheetrock panels nailed to them, like
frameworks for houses; photographs are displayed on the panels. Yet
disjunctions cannot be helped; one room opens onto the Salon Dore,
a late 18th-century confection of white and gilt and delicious
excess, disporting next to a world of drug abusers living in what
is politely called their outdoor living room.
</P>
<P>
   Until 10 years or so ago, museums thought they knew who their
audience was, and it wasn't a true cross section of the urban
population. After all, inner-city residents seldom even turned up
in appreciable numbers in the collection's images, much less in
person. But museums were put under pressure to serve wider
audiences by the National Endowments, foundations, local
governments and some of their own curators and directors, who had
come of age in the activist 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Precedents for socially conscious shows in museums go back to
the 1960s and even earlier, but raising social consciousness has
recently become part of the museum's function. In its statement of
three-year goals for 1998-2000, the American Association of Museums
pledged to ``continue to promote diversity in museum staff,
programs, governance and audiences'' and to ``work with museums to
explore the changing relationship between museums and the community
at large.''
</P>
<P>
   People who have never been in museums may come for one show _ a
group that aids the homeless is bringing their clients to the
Corcoran _ then may or may not ever come back. But at least those
who feel that society doesn't care gain a sense, however fleeting,
that someone is paying attention, and perhaps the regular museum
audience gets a glimpse of lives they seldom see.
</P>
<P>
   Photography has been the natural entryway into this new
community outreach, which gained impetus after the absorption of
photojournalism into museum programs. The Corcoran, which had a
show about homelessness in 1988, has also had shows on runaway
children and hospice care. The Museum of Photographic Arts in San
Diego has mounted shows on poverty in America and commissioned
photographers from the United States and Mexico to take pictures
along the border, then invited local religious, charitable and
advocacy groups to see the material beforehand and figure out what
use they could make of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts in Houston has an affiliation with a
local high school that includes putting on a yearly show of student
photography. A few students have gone on to college with
photographic scholarships. Other museums are finding their own
innovative ways to address a new mission.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be a brave new world, but it is a new world for
museums. They have to tend to their traditional missions, too. But
for a few short weeks Rembrandt is taking care of himself, and home
is where the art is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
