<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RUSSIANS-Y2K-HNS &LR;      12-16 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. TRUST IN RUSSIAN NUKES IS NOT BASED ON VERIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pentagon officials said Thursday they are confident
Russian nuclear weapons won't be launched accidentally because of
year 2000 computer glitches, but they admitted that they base the
judgment mainly on Moscow's verbal assurances rather than on
independent verification.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our confidence is based on what they tell us,''
Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know in theory how their systems work, and we know a fair
amount about some of the details,'' Hamre said at a news conference
to announce that most all U.S. military weapons and support gear
are Y2K-compliant, meaning they won't fail because of computer
problems on Jan.1.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate Y2K nightmare scenario that both governments say is
unlikely is the launch of Russian intercontinental ballistic
missiles triggered by Russian radars that, during year's rollover
period, mistakenly perceive that Moscow is coming under attack from
U.S. missiles. Russia's nuclear policy, like America's, calls for
launching a retaliatory strike upon determining that an offensive
nuclear attack is under way.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 problem refers to the possibility that computers
programmed to read only the last two digits of a year might
interpret 2000 as 1900 and then crash.
</P>
<P>
   Hamre said that when the Russians ``tell us that there is no
chance that their radar systems are all of the sudden going to plot
trajectories of incoming ICBMs, we believe them. We can't imagine
how that would happen, knowing what we know about them, as well. We
really do not worry about Russia's missiles going off,'' he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pentagon has supplied Russia with $10 million worth
of assistance to help ensure Y2K compliance of nuclear weapons and
a network of early warning radars, Hamre said that Russian
officials ``have been genuinely apprehensive'' about allowing U.S.
officials to enter their classified facilities to double check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have the same reticence to let them come in and look
at our command and control systems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Verga, a deputy under secretary of defense, added that,
``We have 100 percent confidence in our side, and we are as
confident in the Russians. They have given us assurances that
they'll be ready on their side.''
</P>
<P>
   However, despite the assurances, some American experts, perhaps
recalling former President Ronald Reagan's warning to ``trust but
verify,'' worry about the condition of Moscow's nuclear force
because of Russia's years of economic chaos. They recall, for
example, the incident in 1995, when that nation's military
initially interpreted the launch of a Norwegian scientific rocket
as the onset of an U.S. nuclear attack. President Boris Yeltsin
activated his ``nuclear briefcase'' in the first stages of
preparation to launch a retaliatory strike before the Russian armed
forces realized their mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a leading foreign
policy spokesman in the Senate, said the incident underscored the
fact that ``Russian early-warning capabilities continue to
deteriorate, and this deterioration will be compounded by the
transition to the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week a coalition of arms-control experts and 84 members of
Congress charged that Russia's early-warning radars are in such
disrepair and the troops guarding the nuclear-tipped
intercontinental ballistic missiles so demoralized that the weapons
could be accidentally or deliberately launched at the United
States. The coalition said that Y2K computer problems ``will
heighten the risk of a nuclear exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   To reassure a jittery world and further cut the risk of a
Y2K-related accident, the U.S. and Russian governments have set up
a joint command center at Peterson Air Force Base at Colorado
Springs, Colo. Next week joint U.S.-Russian crews there will
conduct around-the-clock vigils over consoles and computer screens
that can would alert them to missile launches around most of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   In its technical aid to Russia, Verga said, the Pentagon has
worked to ensure that the ``hotline'' communications links will
work. It has also provided Moscow with Y2K-compliant alarm systems
to help guard missile silos and other critical facilities. ``That
equipment has actually been delivered, and some of it is still on
the way,'' Verga said.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
