<HEADER>
A1147 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CHRISTMASCDS-1000(2Ta     12-16 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMASCDS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDS OF THE SEASON: WHICH CHRISTMAS CDS TO BUY, WHICH TO BANISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN, 
SHIRLEY JINKINS 
and MALCOLM MAYHEW c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's enough to turn anybody into a Scrooge _ having to face the
tall, unsteady pile of seasonal CDs we've accumulated for review in
the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody and their mom is putting their hand to ``Joy to the
World'' and ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer'' and a dozen or so
endlessly recorded others _ whether their voices suit them or not.
</P>
<P>
   So our hearts were full of cheer and our stockings full of joy
when a wise editor said (read this aloud with deep, grandfatherly
voice): No, don't worry, just pick 12 for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Now this is a man who understands the spirit of giving, as in
giving us time to do other stuff, like graze whenever high-calorie
seasonal food is brought into the office (which these days is
almost every day) and shop with money we don't necessarily have.
'Tis the season, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Gladdened and mirthful, we divvied 'em up, listened to 'em, came
back and sat down in front of our computers, finding out that _ lo
and behold! _ 13 CDs had actually made our list.
</P>
<P>
   And hark! The deadline approaches!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks, ``Garth Brooks &AMP; the Magic of Christmas,''
Capitol: Garth's second seasonal offering is in keeping with his
recent, poorly conceived foray into pop: Country is often
downplayed here, in favor of strings, horns and a choir on several
songs. Brooks often displays little feel for the material, and his
voice isn't always equal to the task at hand, two glaring examples
being ``It's the Most Wonderful Time of the Year'' and ``Let It
Snow.'' The song selection is just the same-old-same-old, and this
CD should appeal to the staunchest of fans and few others.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jewel, ``Joy: A Holiday Collection,'' Atlantic: Um, no. Yodeling
Alaskan folk/rock iconess and bad poet Jewel should avoid seasonal
recordings at all costs, based on this 13-song effort. Simplicity
and directness have always served her well, but they're in short
supply here. The overdone string arrangements (Arif Mardin, you are
due a big chunk of coal) often bury her voice and take away from
what could have been a nice, small-scale, folksy effort. Moreover,
Jewel is just not suited to these songs: Listening to her try to
hit the high notes on ``O Holy Night'' is painful. Let's not do
this again, OK?
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kenny G, ``Faith _ A Holiday Album,'' Arista: The G's spineless,
limp takes on seasonal favorites are, well, neither any better nor
any worse than any of his other material _ drab aural wallpaper,
faux jazz that is, inexplicably, wildly popular. So, then, will
this be _ but that doesn't mean ``you'' have to buy it, unless
you're going for the gag-gift angle for the Miles Davis fan in your
life. And, frankly, this is too expensive for a gag gift.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   George Strait, ``Merry Christmas Wherever You Are,'' MCA
Nashville: A new Christmas album by evergreen George is as welcome
as an old friend on the doorstep. It's been well over a decade
since he first addressed the holidays with ``Merry Christmas Strait
to You.'' That album was a western-swing romp through the holidays,
but ``Merry'' is a more mainstream collection. Don't be frightened
by the overdone standards here: ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer''
and ``Jingle Bell Rock'' get upbeat, jazzy treatments from George.
And his teasing turn on ``All I Want for Christmas (Is My Two Front
Teeth)'' is cute, too. The new material is worthy of more than one
Christmas on the CD player, especially ``Noel Leon,'' a
down-to-earth, conversational tale that will warm hearts all around
with its gentle word play. ``Old Time Christmas'' is bittersweet,
and the title cut of lost love is even sadder. It's a good thing
``I Know What I Want for Christmas'' is playful.
</P>
<P>
   4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ringo Starr, ``I Wanna Be Santa Claus,'' Mercury: Now this is a
Christmas record. Redolent of the late-night recording session and
the wild off-site office party, ``Santa Claus'' is Ringo's first
Christmas record, and it's chock-full of joyous takes on ``The
Little Drummer Boy'' and ``Rudolph,'' PLUS he's written several
originals _ check the Gary Glih stomp of the opener, ``Come
on Christmas, Christmas Come On.'' There's also, yo ho ho, a take
on an obscure Beatles song, ``Christmas Time Is Here Again,'' with
Aerosmith's Joe Perry chipping in a guitar solo. Rock fans looking
to update their cache of seasonal CDs can stop right here.
</P>
<P>
   4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Dan Fogelberg, ``The First Christmas Morning,'' Morning Sky:
Another debut Christmas recording, another resounding success.
Fogelberg's foray into seasonal music has a distinct
olde-tyme/medieval air to it and boasts several pretty original
instrumentals, the most luminous being ``Winterskol'' and ``Feast
of Fools.'' The song selection is also consistently rewarding, with
the English lullaby carol ``This Endris Night'' and ``In the Bleak
Mid-Winter'' getting rare airings. Put this on, light a fire,
cuddle up with your sweetie, and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jimi Hendrix, ``Merry Christmas and Happy New Year,'' Experience
Hendrix: Yes, this is correct _ Jimi does Christmas. Or did,
anyway, 30 years ago this month: Seems that in December 1969 the
Voodoo Chile (with bassist Billy Cox and drummer and current Fort
Worth resident Buddy Miles) taped a medley of ``Little Drummer Boy,
Silent Night'' and ``Auld Lang Syne'' while rehearsing for his
famous New Year's Eve shows at the Fillmore East. The result is
rough, drenched in feedback _ and ultimately well worth a listen or
four. The second, seven-minute take of the same medley (apparently
taped the same day) is even better, with more exploratory guitar.
Also included is the sweet, and actually quite, um, groovy ``Three
Little Bears,'' a Jimi-does-a-children's-tale from May 1968. All in
all, this is an odd, brief little gem that's perfect for the
classic-rock fan on your list.
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Andrae Crouch, ``The Gift of Christmas,'' Qwest Records: This
offering from the Los Angeles-based gospel star is a definite
keeper. Crouch joins with Chaka Khan, Yolanda Adams, Patti Austin,
Kirk Whalum and others to deliver a richly satisfying collection of
favorites and new originals, all hinging on his deft arrangements
and ability to fuse gospel, classical and R&AMP;B. The familiar songs,
such as ``It Came Upon a Midnight Clear,'' are reworked and
invigorated, and the originals, such as ``This Christmas''
(featuring La Chaka) are also well worth hearing.
</P>
<P>
   4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Reba McEntire, ``Secret of Giving: A Christmas Collection,'' MCA
Nashville: Christmas concepts that tie into TV specials seem so
contrived (see ``Garth Brooks &AMP; the Magic of Christmas),'' and Reba
joins the crowd here with an album spawned by her network movie
last week, ``Secret of Giving.'' The title cut is nice enough, as
is the Tony Arata-penned ``This Is My Prayer for You.'' The bulk of
the rest is the most pedestrian of holiday fare: ``I Saw Mommy
Kissing Santa Claus'' and ``Up on the Housetop.'' Two
country-at-heart songs really save the day, however. ``The Angels
Sang'' is a working-mom story that will have commuters pulling over
on the freeway to dab at their eyes, and ``Santa Claus Is Coming
Back to Town'' is, well, less than blissful.
</P>
<P>
   3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   98 Degrees, ``This Christmas,'' Universal: Yet another boy band,
yet another boy-band-sings-a-bunch-of-Christmas-carols record. The
Christmas offering from this momentarily popular foursome differs
little from the one released a year ago by teeny-bop-pop cohorts 'N
Sync: A couple of originals mixed in with predictable traditionals
sung with the syrup turned on, the emotion turned off. Next year
it'll be some other cute-guy-group's turn and 98 Degrees will have
considerably cooled.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Amy Grant, ``A Christmas to Remember,'' Myrrh Records: On her
latest Christmas disc, Amy Grant ... enlists the help of Sonic
Youth guitarist Thurston Moore and plays a feedback-drenched,
13-minute version of ``Silent Night?'' Does a punk-rock version of
``Jingle-Bell Rock?'' Gets Puff Daddy to produce? Not quite, but
the Grammy/Dove-winning pop singer's third Christmas CD does go
beyond the norm _ with mixed results. A symphony provides most of
the music, giving ``Remember'' a somewhat one-dimensional
heavy-handedness; the over-the-top arrangements also frequently
overpower Grant's voice. On the upshot, Grant's selection of
material is interesting: There's plenty of new stuff, a coupla
faves and, this is the weird thing, two nice instrumentals,
including the mournful, bagpipe-driven ``Highland Cathedral.'' Sure
beats ``Let It Snow.''
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Martina McBride, ``White Christmas,'' RCA: Perhaps trying to
inch her way further into the is-it-pop-or-is-it-country territory
of her recent ``Emotion'' CD, Martina McBride has cut this
string-laden, predictable collection of Christmas chestnuts.
Everything here is either slow and sappy or goes way overboard,
like a Celine Dion commercial. McBride's got a rugged, wide-ranging
voice; too bad she wasted it on bland, Sears-intercom glop like
this. Martina, please come back!
</P>
<P>
   2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Bryan White, ``Dreaming of Christmas,'' Asylum Records: This
six-song EP is a stocking stuffer for Bryan White fans and an easy
turn-down for everyone else. Oh, sure, Bryan's fold-out snapshots
from his own Christmases past are so-o-o cute, and ``One Bright
Star (This Christmas Night)'' is ethereal in that high, Bryan White
way. But we can get nice covers of ``I'll Be Home for Christmas''
from so many other sources.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
