<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Dec. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chilliest air mass of the season will glide eastward from
the northern Plains into the upper Great Lakes on Friday. A small
dome of frigid weather over Minnesota, which will produce sub-zero
readings Friday morning, will build into southern Ontario. Its
clockwise circulation will direct gelid air across Lake Superior
and Lake Huron, resulting in several snow squalls. As colder air
surges toward the eastern Great Lakes, more snow showers will
develop.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of polar air will stretch from the Ohio Valley
west into the central Missouri Valley. In spite of the chill,
temperatures will still be near seasonal levels across the Midwest.
Low pressure leading the push of colder air will sponsor a few
patches of light snow from northern Illinois to western
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and cooler weather will dominate the South. A stream of
moisture attendant to a stalled front over Florida will produce
thickening clouds and a few showers over the peninsula. A
disturbance near the Texas Coast should bring more clouds and
perhaps a shower onshore.
</P>
<P>
   A large high pressure system over the central Rockies will
transport milder, dry air from the Pacific into the western Plains.
While the morning will be very cold in the valleys of Utah and
Wyoming, ample sunshine should raise readings close to normal.
Offshore winds across southern California will promote warmer
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and wind will return to the Northwest later on as a potent
storm approaches the Washington Coast. Snow levels will continue to
rise in the Cascades causing more flooding.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: A CHILLING END
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, the mercury hovered near zero degrees
Fahrenheit in Grand Forks, N.D. The remarkably mild autumn weather
of 1999 had come to an end. Between mid-October and mid-December
temperatures averaged 9 degrees a day warmer than normal. On
Tuesday, an inch of snow fell at Grand Forks, ending a period of
253 consecutive snowless days, the second longest since records
began in 1941. While a surge of milder air will reach eastern North
Dakota this weekend, a return to Arctic chill and windswept snow is
expected early next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
