<SLUG> BC-DOLLY-PARTON-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GRASS IS BLUE': DOLLY PARTON SHOWS OFF HER VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER COOPER   
 The (Spartanburg, S.C.) Herald-Journal   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dolly Parton is an enigma. Years ago, she traded what could have
been one of the most artistically important careers in country
music history for a successful shot at Hollywood stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Pabulum like her ``Islands in the Stream'' duet with Kenny
Rogers earned more attention than her earlier, more acoustic-based
songs, and the public was less enthralled with even Parton's
biggest hits than with her immediately obvious physical attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in all the hubbub was a voice for the ages, an instrument
that fluttered, then ached, capable of conveying a childlike
innocence or a hardened wisdom. That voice reappeared at times,
especially on ``Trio,'' Parton's gorgeous collaboration with
Emmylou Harris and Linda Ronstadt. But Parton's best work was at
most a side trip from her career's rickety expressway.
</P>
<P>
   More characteristic were bad movies and National Enquirer
articles about weight fluctuations and plastic surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the music was all but over when Parton bought up
some land in the Tennessee mountains and opened the Dollywood theme
park.
</P>
<P>
   But something happened on the way to musical irrelevance.
</P>
<P>
   Parton had helped the country music industry toward an obsession
with sex appeal and salaciousness. By the mid-1990s, it was clear
that, marvels of cosmetic alterations be damned, a 50-something sex
symbol was about as marketable as a 10-year-old computer. In
essence, Dolly had made the rules that forced her out of the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of commercial appeal freed her from the musical
straightjacket that currently binds all that emanates from Music
Row, though, and Parton realized that she could now be as
successful marketing good music through independent channels as she
could marketing fluff through giant corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's the right reason for doing the right thing is
debatable. But the exercise of singing for the song instead of the
money can be cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be Dolly Parton, it can also be monumentally
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to ``The Grass Is Blue'' (Sugar Hill Records),
an absolutely essential bluegrass album that restores everything
that once was righteous about Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   Take the disc from its case and skip immediately to track three:
Dolly's take on Hazel Dickens' ``A Few Old Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   A band of bluegrass all-stars, including dobro whiz Jerry
Douglas and mandolin hero Sam Bush, back Parton as she sings a
plaintive, waltz-time ballad. She pulls the blue notes, attacks the
long notes, and instills a weary beauty to a classic, lovely song.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Krauss, Patty Loveless, Claire Lynch and others take
guest turns on lovingly arranged harmony vocals, but Parton is the
main attraction throughout ``The Grass Is Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   With this album, Parton allows the listener to peer through the
years, the wig, the whitened teeth and all the rest. In the end,
we're left with what is real. Luckily, that's the best part of all.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal in Spartanburg, S.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
