<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     12-16 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His Life as a Director
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Six years ago, Lasse Hallstrom, the quiet-spoken
director of films including ``My Life as a Dog'' and ``What's
Eating Gilbert Grape,'' was offered the script for John Irving's
adaptation of his novel ``The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom recalled that he had some difficulties with the script
but was too nervous to talk to Irving about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the idea of traveling to Vermont to confront this
literary giant was too daunting for me,'' said Hallstrom, 53. ``I
just couldn't do it. I wouldn't dare. So I turned it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, after a project had fallen apart at the last
moment, Hallstom was looking at a list of films seeking directors.
He saw that ``The Cider House Rules'' was available again after
Irving had made some revisions. ``I got the new script and really
liked it, but there were still some problems,'' he said. ``I
finally had the guts the meet John Irving and convey some thoughts.
And from the first meeting he turned into a wonderful
collaborator.''
</P>
<P>
   His film is a sweet, sprawling, almost Dickensian story about a
young man's journey from an orphanage. The hero (played by Tobey
Maguire) grows up under the tutelage of a good-hearted doctor
(Michael Caine) who delivers babies of unwed mothers and also
performs abortions on request. The film opened last weekend in New
York and Los Angeles, and is expanding around the nation over the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In his review in The New York Times, Stephen Holden called the
movie ``easily the finest adaptation of an Irving novel'' and a
``gentle, beautifully acted fable about a young man's journey into
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At breakfast the other morning at the Four Seasons Hotel in
Beverly Hills, Hallstrom acknowledged that his career in Hollywood
had not been an especially easy one. His most popular films have
been ``My Life as a Dog'' (1985), made in his native Sweden, about
a 12-year-old boy growing up in the 1950s, and ``Gilbert Grape''
(1993), a melancholy drama starring Johnny Depp, Juliette Lewis and
a young Leonardo DiCaprio, whose portrayal of a mentally retarded
boy earned him an Oscar nomination. The two films, while not
especially commercial, still have wide followings.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years several other films have fallen through,
often at the last minute and after months of work. ``I haven't
worked since 1995 and the film `Something to Talk About,''' he
said, referring to the Julia Roberts-Dennis Quaid comedy-drama
about a Southern family. ``I've spent four years developing and
working on different scripts that fell apart for different reasons,
financial and otherwise. I haven't made financially wise decisions
in my career. I maybe put too many eggs in one basket. I've had
some terrible experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom, who is married to the actress Lena Olin and lives in
Bedford, N.Y., in Westchester County, said that Hollywood
executives often viewed him more as an arty director than as a big
commercial filmmaker. ``I'm offered things like `My Life as a
Dog,''' he said with a laugh. ``I'm stuck with children a lot.''
(He has a 23-year-old son studying film in Stockholm, and he and
Ms. Olin have two young children).
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom has struggled to make a film of ``Peter Pan.'' But he
hardly limits his work to films about young people. ``I can do
anything but broad comedy, which I have no interest in,'' he said.
``The story must grip you. The character must grip you. To spend a
year and a half of your life on a film, you've got to be passionate
about the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   He dedicated the current film to his father, Nils Hallstrom, who
died a year ago. He was a dentist and ``frustrated filmmaker,''
Hallstrom said. ``He got me into filmmaking. I'm realizing his
dream.'' Hallstrom's mother, Karin, is a poet and novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom's early career involved work on Swedish television and
directing several music videos for the Swedish band Abba. This led
to him directing ``Abba: The Movie,'' in 1977 and a half-dozen
other Swedish films. He clearly misses Sweden, but his career is
now centered in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Sweden you have a script, you commit to it, it's a
handshake, and you cast it and start it,'' he said. ``In America
it's so much more complicated. I still can't figure it out. The
financial thing is such a mystery to me. It all becomes a Catch-22.
You have to find the actors to get the money. But if you don't have
the money, you often don't get the actors.''
</P>
<P>
   His next film, for Miramax, is ``Chocolat,'' about a mother and
daughter visiting, and transforming, a French village in the 1950s.
But Hallstrom, who visits Sweden each summer with Ms. Olin, clearly
hopes to return one day full time. ``The door has to be open just
for my sanity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fascination Survives
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1974 that Milos Forman saw the comedian Andy Kaufman.
Forman, a director who has received Academy Awards for ``One Flew
Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' and ``Amadeus,'' said his friend Buck
Henry, the writer, took him to the Improv comedy club in Los
Angeles to see the comedian, then unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most exhilarating and puzzling performance I've
ever seen,'' Forman recalled. ``It was fascinating and irritating
all at once. It was just weird. There was lots of embarrassed
laughter. It was just Andy. It was the first and last time I saw
him live. I saw him many times on television after that, and he
always provoked curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of Forman's fascination with Kaufman, who died of
lung cancer in 1984 at 35, is the director's newest film, ``Man on
the Moon.'' The movie, written by the team of Scott Alexander and
Larry Karaszewski (``Ed Wood,'' ``The People vs. Larry Flynt''),
stars Jim Carrey as the enigmatic comedian, who often unsettled
audiences with humor _ including accents, jokes and Elvis
impersonations _ that somehow seemed to blur the line between
reality and fiction. The movie opens on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Forman said the film project began five years ago, when he met
the actor Danny DeVito at a party and the conversation turned to
Kaufman. DeVito recalled Kaufman's portrayal of Latka in the
television series ``Taxi,'' in which DeVito also appeared. At the
same time DeVito talked about Kaufman's unpleasant alter ego, Tony
Clifton, a Vegas lounge singer who seemed to have a life of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `This is fantastic,''' Forman said. At that moment
Forman and DeVito decided to make a film about Kaufman. ( DeVito,
whose company, Jersey Films, produced the movie, plays George
Shapiro, who was Kaufman's manager.)
</P>
<P>
   Forman said he believed the Tony Clifton character was created
and endured as a separate fictional person because of Kaufman's
awareness that he was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``My interpretation of Tony Clifton is that Andy was channeling
his anger and range through him,'' Forman said. ``Andy was seeing
doctors eight years before he died. He knew something was wrong. He
didn't smoke. He didn't take drugs or drink. He watched what he
ate. And yet he was sick. So he created this healthy bull, Tony
Clifton, who drank, who ate meat, who was going to survive. That's
my interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous actors wanted to play Kaufman, including Kevin Spacey,
Edward Norton and John Cusack. But Carrey's tryout videotape _
coupled, of course, with his box office clout _ persuaded Forman
and the producers to hire him. ``I didn't dare cast this part
blind,'' said Forman said. ``I asked whoever was interested to send
me a tape of themselves as Andy Kaufman. I got a lot of tapes. Many
of them were wonderful. They nailed him. But Jim Carrey was Andy.
That's all I can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling Trapped
</P>
<P>
   It was the approach of the millennium that spurred Mike Figgis
to make ``Miss Julie,'' the screen adaptation of the harrowing
August Strindberg drama from the 1890s about the chasm between the
sexes and the interplay of money, sex and power. Figgis, who
directed ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' had intended to make the drama with
Nicolas Cage and Juliette Binoche. They were busy and wanted a
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You develop things at a certain time,'' Ms. Figgis said.
``It's one thing to do this 100 years late, at the end of 20th
century. It's another thing to do it in the 21st century. Somehow,
the time was right this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, released by United Artists, an MGM company, opened
last week in New York and Los Angeles. It will be released around
the country early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Saffron Burrows, Peter Mullan and Maria Doyle Kennedy
and adapted by Helen Cooper, the film depicts the tormented
relationship between Miss Julie, the self-destructive, frustrated
and imperious daughter of a wealthy count, and the virile footman
whom she goads into a sexual liaison.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis used hand-held cameras, little equipment and as few takes
as possible. ``The psychology of the play is very much like a
prison play,'' he said. ``Characters are confined to one location.
The relationship between theater and cinema is not so distant that
we can't take something with visual limitations like this and turn
it into a film. The challenge is, how do you use the camera to best
advantage?''
</P>
<P>
   For Figgis, the drama is contemporary: about two people locked
in a cruel but desirous relationship. ``It's about the feeling of
being trapped,'' he said. ``Because of Strindberg's genius, by the
end of the story we have equal anger and sympathy for the two main
characters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
