<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1156 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CONSERVATIVES-FOREIGN     12-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVES-FOREIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BAUER, BUCHANAN URGE TOUGH U.S. POLICY TOWARD CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN   
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Conservative presidential hopefuls Gary Bauer and
Patrick Buchanan promised Thursday that they would be tougher on
China if they were in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer told reporters he intended to step up criticism of his
rivals for the Republican presidential nomination for being
``unable to do anything (on China) other than repeat the mantra of
`trade, trade, trade.'''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Buchanan criticized China for becoming
``increasingly belligerent'' toward political dissidents and
religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the ability to make China succeed or fail,'' Buchanan
said in a speech devoted to foreign policy. ``If the U.S. closes
its market to China tomorrow, (China's) currency would collapse and
its economy would collapse . We would miss next to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   China ships far more goods to the United States than it
receives. The U.S. trade deficit with China amounted to $23 billion
in the first five months of 1999, the highest of any U.S. trading
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a candidate for the Reform Party nomination, also said
U.S.-imposed sanctions against rogue nations such as Iraq, Iran and
Cuba were ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bauer and Buchanan are long-shot candidates for the
presidency. Bauer is running in the single digits in most polls of
the six Republican contenders, well behind Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a speechwriter for President Richard M. Nixon in the
1970s, abandoned the Republican party in October to seek the Reform
Party nomination. The party, founded by Texas billionaire Ross
Perot, has yet to carry a state in two presidential elections,
although former pro-wrestler Jesse Ventura won election last year
on the Reform ticket as governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bauer and Buchanan represent a barometer of
conservative voters who are a key ingredient of the Republican
electoral base. Many are fundamentalist Christians who have looked
to Bauer and Buchanan on domestic social issues, from outlawing
abortion to reinstituting school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Both reiterated their opposition to abortion, with Bauer saying
``this is going to stick in our throats until we get it right.''
The two men criticized Bush for declining in a debate Monday night
in Des Moines to commit himself, if nominated, to picking an
anti-abortion running mate.
</P>
<P>
   On China, Bauer characterized the world's most populous nation
as more hostile than ever to Taiwan and intent on becoming Asia's
dominant power. The United States can no longer afford to simply
placate China in the name of improved trade relations favored by
American business interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world will be a more dangerous place if we can't come up
with a policy other than the one being dictated in corporate suites
of Fortune 500 companies,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that as president, he would ``re-establish
linkage'' between U.S. trade privileges and such issues as China's
behavior toward Taiwan, China's work on long-range missiles that
could potentially threaten U.S. soil, and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants a war with China,'' Buchanan said. ``But I think
(the Clinton administration) with its embrace of China as a close,
strategic partner was naove in the extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also attempted to close the door on criticism of his
book ``A Republic, Not an Empire,'' in which he argued that German
dictator Adolf Hitler had no strategic interest in taking on the
United States in the early stages of World War II. Buchanan said
the United States had no vital interests at stake in Europe at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have accused Buchanan of insensitivity toward victims of
the Holocaust, of whom over half were Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Buchanan said the criticism was moot because
Holocaust historians said the mass extermination of Jews was not
planned by the Nazis until a 1942 conference outside Berlin. By
that time, the United States had entered the war in the wake of the
bombing of Pearl Harbor in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech at the Washington-based Center for Strategic
and International Studies, Buchanan said he was happy with his
decision to leave the Republican Party. He questioned the sincerity
of Bush and McCain on the abortion issue, saying he believed the
GOP was ``quietly abandoning the pro-life position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain both oppose abortion and its legal foundation in
the 1973 Supreme Court ruling in Roe v. Wade. However, unlike Bauer
and Buchanan, neither is willing to commit to appointing federal
judges who explicitly oppose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that while he shares ``some of Pat's critique'' of
the Republican Party, ``I do not share Pat's pessimism about the
chances of the Republican Party finding its voice again. So I
intend to stay in that fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that if wins the GOP nomination, a Buchanan candidacy
on the Reform ticket would not draw votes away from the Republican
ticket. Without naming Bush directly, Bauer said he believed a
Buchanan could draw votes from the Republican line ``if the party
nominates (someone who) isn't serious about things like the
sanctity of life or a (President) Reagan- type of foreign policy
toward China.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Freedman can be reached at: dan &LR; hearstdc.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
