<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Dec. 17 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ After two days of opening talks,
Israel and Syria agreed Thursday to resume negotiations toward
peace on Jan. 3 in the Washington area, President Clinton
announced. By John M. Broder. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-REPORT (United Nations) _ A strongly worded report issued
Thursday by an international panel of experts holds both U.N.
officials and leading member countries, primarily the United
States, responsible for failing to stop the genocide in Rwanda. The
report says that about 800,000 people were killed in 100 days
between April and July 1994, and it portrays an organization weak
on analysis and slow to respond to accumulating warnings in the
months that preceded the attacks. By Barbara Crossette. (1200
words)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (New York) _ An appellate court ruled Thursday
that the trial of four officers accused of killing Amadou Diallo
last February should be held in Albany County, because a ``tidal
wave of pretrial publicity'' would make it impossible to hold a
fair trial in the Bronx. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK (New York) _ A man was arrested Thursday at
the Brooklyn Museum of Art after he threw white latex paint on the
controversial painting of the Virgin Mary. The suspect got the
paint past metal detectors by concealing it in a plastic container,
then feigned a heart attack to get past a guard and slip under a
plexiglass shield. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MINORITIES (New York) _ A hugely disproportionate number of
minorities represent new AIDS cases, yet blacks and Latinos have
not had front and center positions in AIDS policy making.
Mainstream black groups have shied away from the issue, and
minority groups devoted to it have had trouble getting money. But
slowly, that is all changing, as more minorities find themselves in
powerful positions in the advocacy and policy front, and state and
federal dollars are starting to be newly appropriated in
recognition of where the disease now hits home. By Jennifer
Steinhauer. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BRADLEY (Claremont, N.H.) _ Sen. John McCain and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, both insurgent candidates for president, joined
forces across a partisan and ideological divide to pledge their
support for revamping the nation's campaign finance system and to
take some sharp shots at each other's front-running opponent. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ENGLAND-DRUGS (Montpelier, Vt.) _ In the first such meeting
of its kind, legislative leaders from the four northern New England
states gathered here Thursday to plot possible joint strategies for
lowering the price of prescription drugs, from imposing local price
controls to demanding a regional discount. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
