<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILM-CRITICS-AWARDS-N     12-16 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRITICS-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CRITICS HONOR LEIGH'S `TOPSY-TURVY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The British director Mike Leigh won twin accolades
Thursday when the New York Film Critics Circle voted
``Topsy-Turvy,'' his pageantry-laden tribute to the operetta duo
Gilbert and Sullivan, the best film of 1999. Leigh also won as best
director.
</P>
<P>
   David Lynch was runner-up in the directing category for ``The
Straight Story.'' That film stars Richard Farnsworth, the circle's
choice for best actor, as an old man who drives a lawnmower halfway
across Iowa to visit his ailing brother.
</P>
<P>
   The film earned Freddie Francis the vote for best cinematography
in a very tight race against ``Sleepy Hollow,'' Tim Burton's grim
adaptation of the Washington Irving tale, filmed by Emmanuel
Lubezki.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest was also the setting for the role that earned Hilary
Swank the award for best actress, for ``Boys Don't Cry,'' in which
she plays a young woman who is killed after she was discovered to
be impersonating a man. Directed by Kimberly Peirce, ``Boys Don't
Cry'' was edged out by Spike Jonze's ``Being John Malkovich'' for
best first film.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Plummer, who played the television journalist Mike
Wallace in ``The Insider,'' Michael Mann's film about a
whistle-blower in the tobacco industry, went neck and neck for best
supporting actor with John Malkovich, who ultimately won for
playing a version of himself in Jonze's feature debut. Best
supporting actress went to Catherine Keener for ``Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time the circle voted for a best animated film.
The award went to ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' a
spinoff from the popular Comedy Central series.
</P>
<P>
   Best screenplay honors went to Jim Taylor and Alexander Payne
for ``Election,'' their acerbic satire of the American electoral
process, starring Reese Witherspoon as a tough cookie running for
senior class president.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Wender's ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' about a reunion of
veteran Cuban musicians, earned the award for best documentary,
barely nudging out Errol Morris' ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of
Fred A. Leuchter Jr.,'' a bleak take on a man who builds execution
devices.
</P>
<P>
   The best foreign film award went to Pedro Almodovar's ``All
About My Mother,'' a gender-bending tribute to ``All About Eve''
and ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' and to ``actresses who play
actresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Farber won a special award for his distinguished
contribution to film criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The annual vote, the group's 65th, took place at the Algonquin
Hotel in Manhattan. The awards will be presented at Windows on the
World on Jan. 10. The group's chairman is Owen Gleiberman of
Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
