<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BORGNINE-SCRIPTS-NYTR     12-16 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORGNINE-SCRIPTS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORGNINE SCRIPTS DONATED TO UNIVERSITY OF NORTH ALABAMA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By TERRY PACE   
 TimesDaily, Florence, Ala.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Ala. _ Academy Award winner Ernest Borgnine is
donating a collection of his personal movie scripts to the
University of North Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's giving us leather-bound copies of more than 100 of his
personal movie scripts from throughout his career,'' said fellow
actor George Lindsey, a UNA graduate and Borgnine's longtime
friend.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to presenting his script collection to the library,
Borgnine will be UNA's mid-year commencement speaker Saturday. The
star of ``Marty,'' ``McHale's Navy'' and ``The Wild Bunch'' will
address 380 UNA graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the colleges and universities in this country, we have
the Ernest Borgnine scripts,'' said Lindsey, best known for his
role of Goober on ``The Andy Griffith Show.'' ``I think that makes
us special.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey has established a collection of television and films
scripts at UNA's Collier Library, which includes his own scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Borgnine visited Florence last April, when he was the featured
artist for UNA's second annual George Lindsey Television and Film
Festival. Near the conclusion of that festival, Borgnine announced
his decision to donate his scripts to Lindsey's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``These scripts he's donating include all of his personal notes
and stage directions, and they'll be available for study forever
and forever,'' Lindsey said. ``People will have a chance to study
exactly how Ernie approached each part he played and what all went
into each of his performances.''
</P>
<P>
   The 82-year-old actor is best-known for his tough-guy roles in
``From Here to Eternity,'' ``Bad Day at Black Rock,'' ``The
Vikings'' and ``The Dirty Dozen.'' He earned the best-actor Oscar
in 1955, playing a lovelorn Bronx butcher in the gentle drama
``Marty.''
</P>
<P>
   On television, Borgnine starred as a harried, soft-hearted Navy
commander in the comedy favorite ``McHale's Navy'' (1962-66). In
recent years, he's been active on television in ``Airwolf'' and
``The Single Guy,'' and on the big screen in ``Gattaca,''
``BASE-ketball,'' ``Small Soldiers'' and the movie remake of
``McHale's Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Borgnine, who lives in California, will be the subject of an A&AMP;E
``Biography'' episode Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The TimesDaily in Florence, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
