<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-BRADLEY17-COX     12-16 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BRADLEY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain, Bradley take the pledge on soft money
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, N.H. _ In a rare bipartisan appearance, Democrat Bill
Bradley and Republican John McCain pledged Thursday to ban their
parties from accepting unregulated soft money if they become the
presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and McCain delivered their pledge before 50 New
Hampshire voters in a town hall meeting staged by ABC News's
``Nightline,'' which rebroadcast the event to a national audience
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two men came to this small town nestled in the mountains on
the western edge of New Hampshire because it was the site of a
handshake between President Clinton and then-House Speaker Newt
Gingrich of Georgia. In June 1995, Clinton and Gingrich pledged to
establish a commission to enact campaign finance reform. The
commission never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's joint appearance was the first time candidates in
opposing parties had appeared together since 1980, when Sen. Edward
Kennedy of Massachusetts, running against President Carter,
appeared with Rep. John Anderson, a Republican running as an
independent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley used Thursday's forum as an opportunity to
lay out their platform for campaign finance reform to undercut
their front-running rivals. And each had harsh words for the
front-runner in the other's primary contest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the big scandal of the Clinton-Gore administration
was not Monica Lewinsky but the campaign finance excesses of the
1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   McCain singled out a fund-raising trip the vice president made
to a Buddhist monastery in California during which monks, sworn to
lives of poverty, contributed thousands of dollars to the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain mocked Vice President Al Gore's response to questions
about fund-raising calls made from the White House, when the vice
president insisted there was ``no controlling'' legal authority
governing his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm president, there will be a controlling legal
authority,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also took aim at Republican front-runner George W. Bush,
accusing the Texas governor of ``thumbing his nose'' at the
campaign finance system by refusing to abide by spending limits and
accept federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has flaunted ... the public finance laws,'' Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Bush said he supported a ban on soft
money but that the proposals advanced by Bradley and McCain would
hurt the ``Republican Party and our conservative principles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any plan to reduce the influence of special interest money in
politics must be fair _ and no plan should benefit one political
party over another,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore placed a full-page advertisement in the local paper
Thursday saying he would ban soft money if the Republican nominee
also agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Although both Bradley and McCain pledged to ban soft money if
they are the nominees, only McCain made his pledge unconditional.
McCain said he would not accept soft money regardless of who the
Democratic nominee is, while Bradley reserved the right to make
that decision later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confront different circumstances,'' Bradley said. ``If John
McCain is the nominee and I am the nominee, there will be no soft
money for presidential campaigns. But if it is the governor of
Texas on the Republican side, I then have to deal with somebody who
I think will demonstrate that you can have too much money in
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men also called for broadcast television networks to
provide free television time to presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   They differed, however, on the issue of public financing of
presidential and congressional campaigns. Bradley called for full
public financing of general election campaigns, which he said would
cost $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
