<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BELARUS-SCENE-ART-2TA     12-16 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-SCENE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OPPOSITION LEADERS IN BELARUS FACE PERSECUTION, OTHERS A WORSE
FATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ In the last 32 months, Anatoly Lebedko has been
tried on criminal charges five times, fined four times, imprisoned
twice and seriously beaten once, on the front steps of his
apartment. His office telephone is tapped. His friends are hectored
by the tax police.
</P>
<P>
   The state security police recently ordered his neighbor's
10-year-old son to spy on him, and he recently returned from a trip
to find two subpoenas in his mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the democratic opposition in Belarus is no easy job.
Then again, it could be worse: in September, Lebedko's predecessor
as opposition leader, Viktor Gonchar, went to his local steam bath,
dutifully trailed by his security police collars, and has yet to
come back.
</P>
<P>
   Never exactly a beacon of freedom, Belarus these days is
increasingly the scene of strange and terrible happenings. Lebedko
is persecuted; Gonchar is presumed to be dead.
</P>
<P>
   Gonchar's own predecessor fled to Lithuania in July, fearing for
his life. A fourth opposition leader died in April, ostensibly from
a brain hemorrhage, at age 49. Two top government officials who
turned against Belarus' leadership disappeared in April and May.
</P>
<P>
   Disappearances and death threats are new elements in political
repression in post-Soviet Belarus. They have further winnowed an
already small democracy movement and sent a chill through what
opposition remains.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, they may have forever remade the image of the
country's leader, Aleksander Lukashenko, long regarded as just a
goofy autocrat. Stories abound of his obsession with sports, his
off-color speeches and other quirky behavior, but now he is quickly
earning a reputation as a ruthless dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable foreign analysts say there is no proof that
Lukashenko's government is liquidating opponents. There are
suggestions that in some cases independent death squads or splinter
groups in the nation's large security apparatus may have taken
matters into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no denying that Lukashenko, who became president in
1994 in the country's first free election, has done little to halt
the crimes, or that he has used them to sow disarray among his
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening here in this small country is underestimated
by the U.S.,'' Lebedko said the other day in his office not far
from downtown Minsk. ``This regime is supported by elementary fear.
This is the legacy of the Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Some independent groups say the situation in Belarus has
worsened sharply since last winter, when critics began organizing
surprisingly vigorous protests against Lukashenko's rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government crackdown on independent media, civil society
and political activity has become more systematic and violent,''
said a report issued in April by the East-West Institute, a New
York-based organization promoting democracy in former Soviet-bloc
nations. ``The public mood in Belarus is characterized by an
insidious and deepening fear as well as the widespread belief that
little can be done to change the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The deterioration goes well beyond the disappearances _ of
Gonchar; of Anatoly Krasovsky, a financial backer of government
critics; Yuri Zakharenko, a former interior minister who was
politically organizing police officers when he disappeared; and
Tamara Vinnikova, a former head of the central bank who was under
house arrest when she vanished.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 13, a Belarussian newspaper published what it said was a
statement it had received by telephone from Ms. Vinnikova from an
unidentified country,Reuters reported. She said the Belarussian
authorities had plotted to kill her, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Sannikov, leader of the human rights group Charter 97,
was beaten in February. He later fled to Geneva after a security
police officer delivered a death threat via a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Seymon Sharetsky was speaker of the democratically elected
Parliament that Lukashenko dissolved after a 1996 constitutional
referendum that greatly expanded presidential powers and was widely
judged to be rigged. He fled to Lithuania in July.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Chigir, the prime minister until he resigned in protest
over the referendum, was arrested in March, one day after he
registered to run in a shadow presidential election. He was
released in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Klimov, a member of the disbanded Parliament who signed a
demand for Lukashenko's impeachment, has been in jail since
February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Others suffer without ever seeing the inside of a cell.
</P>
<P>
   Zinaida Gonchar has stopped working since her husband
disappeared. Now she sits in the family's apartment, not really
waiting for news, she says, because even investigators told her
that the truth was probably locked in a secret police file.
</P>
<P>
   Belarussian politics is a closed society, and the Gonchars knew
Lukashenko well _ so well that he often came to their home for
dinner; so well that Gonchar served as deputy prime minister in
Lukashenko's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gonchar said the friendship began to crack in 1994, when
Gonchar remained neutral rather than help Lukashenko campaign for
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, Viktor Gonchar was driving the family car when
``he had an accident _ the wheel just came off,'' his wife said.
``He was pretty badly injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko nevertheless recruited Gonchar into the government.
But Gonchar quit after two months and got a job elsewhere. He was
elected to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the telephone began ringing, with threats and warnings,
mostly against me,'' his wife said. ``They'd say, `We'll come
upstairs and beat you.' Or I'd be walking on the sidewalk and a car
would suddenly jump on the sidewalk in front of me and back out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Someone shot at Viktor Gonchar's car one day, wounding his
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko organized the 1996 constitutional referendum, and
Gonchar became chairman of the government's election watchdog
commission. Then Lukashenko dismissed him and Gonchar became a
member of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Gonchar and other former legislators published a
brochure on constitutional violations by the government. The
security police searched the Gonchar apartment and took him in for
questioning. He took a breather after that, working on a
Belarus-Lithuania tribunal, and the harassment eased.
</P>
<P>
   But in late 1998, democracy advocates decided to hold a shadow
presidential election marking what would have been expiration date
of Lukashenko's term in office had the term not been lengthened by
two years in the referendum. Gonchar was named to run the electoral
commission.
</P>
<P>
   And the troubles resumed. In March the police imprisoned
Gonchar. He went on a hunger strike. After 10 days, he was released
from jail and thrown on a snowbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six months, we were followed constantly _ not only
Viktor, but myself,'' Mrs. Gonchar said. ``We were warned on
several occasions.'' She said the security police were tailing
Gonchar the night he and Krasovsky took their weekly trip to the
baths. ``So I have no doubt,'' she said, ``that the authorities
know exactly who is responsible for this kidnapping.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko pooh-poohs the disappearance, saying Gonchar is
rumored to be in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The president's seemingly casual attitude toward his opponents'
troubles has come at a price. At the recent summit meeting of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, Lukashenko was
ostracized by Western leaders.
</P>
<P>
   An inventive man, though, he found a way around that.
</P>
<P>
   As leaders strolled to a meal one day, Lukashenko ambushed
President Clinton long enough to assert later that they had had a
weighty discussion and that he had even invited Clinton to visit
Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him a joke,'' Lukashenko recalled later. ``If you
cannot'' visit Belarus ``before the end of your term, then all you
will have to do is extend it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
