u w BC-KIDS-BINGE-DRINKING-H     12-16 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BINGE-DRINKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SHOWS PARENTS OUT OF TOUCH WITH TEEN DRINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only 3 percent of parents believe their
high-school-aged children have slugged as many as five alcoholic
drinks in a row over the past month, according to a new survey,
although federal statistics have shown that a third of 9th through
12th graders have done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are not aware and certainly not in touch with what is
happening with their kids and alcohol,'' said pollster Peter D.
Hart, who announced his findings Thursday at a news conference
here.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were part of an extensive nationwide telephone
survey by his polling firm in which he interviewed 574 parents of
10- to 17-year-olds, including 296 parents of high school students.
The margin of error is 4.2 percentage points among the 574 parents
and 5.8 percentage points among the 296.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were part of a report entitled ``Millennium
Hangover: Keeping Score on Alcohol,'' released by Drug Strategies,
a nonprofit Washington research institute funded by philanthropic
groups including the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, which has
played a leading role in the fight to keep tobacco away from
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that a quarter of the parents of high
school students said they would allow their children to go to a
millennium party where they suspected alcohol would be served.
</P>
<P>
   But Hart warned, ``The best way to have a good millennium is to
open your ears and open your eyes to what your children are doing.
They're doing a lot more than you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug Strategies President Mathea Falco said teen drinking has
dramatically increased over the last five years, and that many
youngsters are now talking about drinking to get drunk instead of
going out for a drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``More kids are binge drinking,'' Falco said during the news
conference. ``This is such a national social problem.'' The
solution, she added, lies in ``a massive attitudinal change.''
</P>
<P>
   It would require enforcement of current underage drinking laws,
clamping down on fake identification used by underage youths,
fighting illegal sales of alcohol to minors through the Internet
and launching a massive advertising campaign to change youngsters'
attitudes about heavy drinking, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
found that 33 percent of 9th through 12th graders said they had
consumed five or more drinks in one sitting in the past 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Drug Strategies estimated that the cost of underage drinking is
more than $58 billion a year, including costs from traffic
accidents, violent crime, suicide attempts and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Its report said children who begin drinking at early ages are at
much greater risk for alcoholism later in life. Youngsters who
drink before age 15 are four times more likely to develop alcohol
dependence than those who start drinking after age 21, according to
the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism, a research
arm of the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said after the news conference that advertising campaigns
launched in recent years by Mothers Against Drunk Driving have
helped to make drinking and driving socially unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point is that binge drinking can also become uncool,'' Hart
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1834EST &QL; 
