<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MONSANTO-NORRIS-COLUM     12-16 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONSANTO-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: PUBLIC MISINFORMED ON GENETICALLY MODIFIED FOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the possibilities of a scientific breakthrough that
could allow farmers to grow more food while using less pesticide,
or to produce cholesterol-free soybeans, or to add vitamins to
vegetable oils to prevent malnutrition. Maybe it could let some
plastic products now made from oil instead be produced from plants.
</P>
<P>
   Would the stock prices of companies developing such products
soar to Internet-style heights? Would the scientists be viewed as
potential saviors in a world where hunger and malnutrition are
realities for many millions, and where pollution from oil
refineries remains a problem?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to both questions is ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldom in human history has a technology with such exciting
possibilities seemed less popular than genetic modification of
foods _ a k a ``Frankenstein foods'' in the British tabloids _ is
today. Wall Street is leery, and now class-action lawyers have
leaped in with a double-barreled suit accusing Monsanto, the
leading company in the field, of trying to monopolize a business
the lawyers say relies on foisting possibly dangerous foods on the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The way things are going, Monsanto executives who want to avoid
being harassed at cocktail parties and on airlines may take to
lying about what they do. Perhaps they'd do better if they claimed
to be from Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   How did we get to this point? One answer is that the industry's
lobbyists were too successful. They persuaded the Food and Drug
Administration that genetic modification _ which involves inserting
a gene into a plant _ was not very different from the old way of
breeding plants, and the corn or soybeans were equally nutritious.
So there was no need to call attention to it on labels.
</P>
<P>
   But because there was no need to reassure consumers, there was
also no need to educate them. The marketing efforts focused on
farmers and, as it happened, the early products did more for
farmers, with higher crop yields and resistance to pests, than for
consumers, in terms of improved nutrition. Farmers embraced the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Then the resistance arose, largely in Europe. Who can be
absolutely certain that these products will not have some bad
effect on animals, or plants, or the environment? Ask the question
that way, and the answer is that no one can. Ask whether the
evidently small risks offset the potential gains _ in nutrition and
in reducing pesticide use, among others _ and you might get a
different answer.
</P>
<P>
   Now European fears are being exported to an American public that
knows virtually nothing about the subject _ and is hearing about it
from people warning of dangers. Farmers are getting nervous about
planting the seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wall Street is putting pressure on Monsanto to spin
off its Searle pharmaceuticals business. James Wilbur, an analyst
at Salomon Smith Barney, figures that an independent Searle would
be worth about $38 a share. You can buy Searle, with the rest of
Monsanto thrown in, for less than $41 a share, which gives you some
idea just how happy investors are about agribusiness these days.
Since the end of 1997, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is up 46 percent,
while Monsanto is down 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been better if Monsanto and its competitors had
insisted on _ rather than resisted _ putting labels on genetically
modified products. Perhaps they could have portrayed the labels as
indicating a superior product with environmental benefits. Instead,
they left the public education to the industry's foes. In
persuading regulators that no labels were needed, the lobbyists won
a pyrrhic victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-COLTS-BOS &LR;      12-16 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTS ON THE FAST TRACK TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; moved Dec. 10.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS -- The day in America's heartland is cool, December
dank, and dark. The Colts are leaving the field after a midweek
practice and the members of the media are seated under a giant old
tree, sturdy as the Midwest. Jim Mora walks over and begins talking
about a phenomenon rarely seen in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Time spinning faster than it does on the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   A new rage exploding first in Indiana and only then fanning
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts stomping.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is tanned. There is a glint to his eye. His smile is quick.
That image from New Orleans when he fell apart at a news conference
after his Saints lost their sixth game in eight and Mora resigned
after 11 seasons with the team seems long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is asked by an outsider when he realized his Colts were not
just a team on the upswing, but one of the best in the National
Football League. ``To be honest, I hadn't been asked that question
before,'' he said. ``I don't know if I can say there was any one
moment.'' It's happening so fast. The Colts now have an offense
that draws in neutral fans for a look at how football should be
played. The Colts now have a quarterback, Peyton Manning, and a
running back, Edgerrin James, and a wide receiver, Marvin Harrison,
that seem to have the potential of being more exciting than any of
the last generation.
</P>
<P>
   And it happened so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know in this business,'' said Mora. ``I've been in
this business long enough to know that crazy things happen. No, I
didn't think we'd win this many games.'' Mora exhaled a deep
breath. ``You saw this potential in this team, especially
offensively, and yet you never know what's going to happen next
year. You know you're an injury away, a key injury away, from going
the other way.'' So fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that it's happening,'' said Mora, struggling to put
into words this sudden rise from the ashes of the Colts - and
himself. ``It gives you a nice feeling . . . it's better than not
having it.'' Two games with the Patriots, both in Foxborough, stand
out as benchmarks on the trek upward. The first, early in the 1998
season, was perhaps Manning's worst in his short career, the rookie
quarterback looking confused, lost, bewildered, and inept, throwing
interception after interception. ``That was maybe Peyton's worst
game,'' said Mora, as the Colts struggled to a 3-13 year.
</P>
<P>
   But Manning was not scarred as so many rookie quarterbacks are
by sudden ineptitude when they take that giant step to professional
football. (''That Patriots game was tough,'' said Manning. ``I was
worried that I might be scarred.'') Late last season, said Mora,
``he made it over the hump'' when he went out to San Francisco and
fired three touchdown passes in a 34-31 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The next benchmark, early this season, came when the Colts
scored 28 points in the first half against New England as Manning
checked off at the line of scrimmage on play after play, testing Ty
Law as no other quarterback had tested him, throwing three TD
passes to Harrison over Law. ``That showed how much I'd learned
about defenses since that other game in Foxborough,'' Manning said
of the many audibles.
</P>
<P>
   But the Colts blew that lead, as Mora's teams in New Orleans,
good as they were, so often blew leads and lost games they should
have won. Those experiences often led Mora to go conservative with
a lead, but a hard, hard lesson was learned in Foxborough by these
young Colts. They learned their offense was too good to ever be set
in neutral, that their offense could suck all momentum from
opposing teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mora also learned that he had a quarterback ``who was a
competitor, one who could handle pressure, one who - like a Larry
Bird or Michael Jordan - wants the ball in pressure, critical
situations, one who handles adversity and doesn't let it put him in
the tank.'' Mora has ever been known as a defensive coach, deep in
his core the football truism that defenses win games. But now, as
the Colts' defense is still being built, Mora has a true offensive
power, one that can win games with its sheer explosiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive guru (''Oh, nobody is a guru in this business,''
he countered) was asked to look at his offense from a defensive
coach's eyes. Mora complied, but the essential defensive nature of
his soul told him that no offense, not even the Colts', is unstopp
able. ``Nobody is unstoppable,'' said Mora. ``We fought for our
lives twice against the Jets. We fought for our lives . . . I mean,
we scored 16 points in one game and 13 in the other. Nobody is
unstoppable. I guarantee that. I coached against the 49ers every
year for many years when they had a great offensive machine and
there were times they had trouble scoring points.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody struggles.'' And Mora knows so well the cycle of NFL
football. A team can spring suddenly upon the scene, but as that
team enjoys more and more success, opposing coaches devote more of
their attention, and their schemes, to stopping it. It is the way
of life in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you are doing good in this business, when you
really are doing good on offense, then everybody is really bearing
down to put the clamps on you to stop that offense,'' said Mora.
``It makes it even tougher.'' There is one element to this Colts
team that makes it so different from Mora's New Orleans teams.
Beyond the quarterback, beyond the running back, beyond the wide
receiver, there is Tom Moore. He is 60, has spent 22 years coaching
in the NFL, and, for most of the years, has been the coordinator
for some very good offenses.
</P>
<P>
   From the Steelers of Terry Bradshaw and Lynn Swann in the late
1970s to the Lions of Barry Sanders in the 1990s, the offense that
led the league and was the first to have two receivers (Herman
Moore and Brett Perriman) with more than 1,000 yards receiving,
Moore has been excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Tom Moore more or less called the plays,'' said
Manning. ``As he's gained confidence in me and as I have a better
understanding of what we're doing, it's gotten better. Last year,
I'd just listen to the play. But now I have a pretty good idea of
what he's going to call before he calls it and that's what you want
to have between a quarterback and a coordinator.'' Now, the bond is
total between the wise and savvy Moore and Manning. They think the
same - they think the worst epithet for an offensive game plan
after the last play ``is to be one play away,'' as Manning put it.
``The worst thing is to think, `I just wish we had the post call
when they were in that defense.' `` (For Patriot fans who no longer
remember what a post pattern or quick slant pass play entails, the
receiver cuts diagonally to the inside. Despite the Patriots'
reluctance to use the patterns, they still are most effective
against some blitzes.) ``We want to use that last play,'' Manning
said. ``If they're showing blitz, hey . . . we want the post route
and we know we can get to it. That's kind of a result of how much
confidence I have in Tom and Tom has in me. We never want to leave
the field thinking of that one last play we should have called but
we didn't call.'' These Colts of Mora, unlike those Saints of Mora
who just couldn't take the final step, do not think offense is
merely what happens when the defense is not on the field. Blowing
that 28-7 lead to the Patriots taught them all a lesson - keep
scoring points.
</P>
<P>
   So fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts are among the NFL's best. Unlike last year's Falcons,
who also made a sudden rise, it is clear this team will be very
good for several years.
</P>
<P>
   And if it happened so fast that Mora doesn't realize exactly
when the Colts went from a team on the uptick to a team that must
be feared, his decades in pro football have taught him one lesson:
Seize the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take advantage of the opportunity when you've
got it,'' Mora said. ``All coaches learn that. It's really
important. You've got to . . .
</P>
<P>
   you've got to . . . you never know when it's going to come
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
