<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-BORDEAUX-QUALITY     12-16 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-BORDEAUX-QUALITY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDEAUX TO TASTE WINES FOR QUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KATHLEEN BUCKLEY   
 c. WineToday.com   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bordeaux wines that fail to meet new retail tasting standards
face the threat of being banned from sale as the French wine
industry attempts to counteract increasing competition from the
United States, Australia, Argentina and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The standards, called ``downstream control,'' take effect in
global markets beginning in January. The system is now being tested
in France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are the most famous in the world you receive a lot of
criticism,'' said Eric Dulong, vice president of the Bordeaux wine
bureau and a negociant, the term for a wine wholesaler/exporter.
``If we want to keep our reputation we have to stay the best. This
program is important proof that Bordeaux wants to maintain the
standard of quality for the wine regions of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The new system allows the Bordeaux wine bureau, the Conseil
Interprofessionnel du vin de Bordeaux, to buy 200 samples in any
market _ from retail shelves, distributors or restaurants _ and
subject the lot to a blind tasting by Bordeaux wine experts. Wines
will be graded from A to D. ``D'' is what Dulong said is
``unacceptable for Bordeaux.''
</P>
<P>
   The wines of a producer or negociant with a D rating would be
subject to a comprehensive tasting of all tanks of wine or all
bottles in a negociant's warehouse, not just the wine that fails
the taste test. If the wines do not meet a range of quality
standards, remedial controls will be put into effect.
</P>
<P>
   If, at a second tasting, the wines fail, they will not be
allowed to be sold. The process could take a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux has more than 12,000 producers and 400 negociants
selling more than 170 million gallons of wine worth $1.37 billion a
year, according to 1998 figures. Export sales have slowed in 1999
due to factors including less demand from Asia, skyrocketing prices
for top Bordeaux wines and the gap in quality from one Bordeaux
wine to the next.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important reason, said Dulong and Bordeaux
importers, is the New World competition in the lower price ranges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conscious the competition is very, very strong and that
many other countries are producing fantastic wines today,'' Dulong
said. ``Our wines are not drinkable too young, they are not
mono-varietal. Our aim is to keep our identity and produce
excellent wines.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have come to expect good quality, from the bottom rung
to the top, in Bordeaux wines. But consumers, particularly those
new to wine, are weaned on early-and-easy drinking varietal wines
of the New World and might find Bordeaux hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who are buying wine ``blind'' in the $6 to $12 range
are safer buying wines from other parts of the world, said Alun
Griffiths, a Master of Wine and wine director for Berry Brothers
and Rudd, one of the largest UK importers of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little confidence in that end of the Bordeaux
market. The wines _ from cooperatives and syndicates _ haven't been
quality-driven; the wines have been resting on their laurels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bordeaux wines have gone up so much in price that it is hard
to drink these wines every night,'' said Jeff Zacharia of Zachys,
among New York's benchmark wine retailers. ``Below $20 there's a
crisis in confidence. The issue is price; nobody's going up in
price like Bordeaux, and it is hard to find good quality Bordeaux
to fill in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The French test program began in September. It piggy-backs on
annual appellation tastings that award a winery the right to call
its wines ``Bordeaux.'' Some 98 percent of all wines made in
Bordeaux pass that test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be lower, maybe 85 to 90 percent,'' Dulong said.
</P>
<P>
   The first test grades under the new system will be out in a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When the program expands in January, it will center primarily on
Europe; two of every three bottles of exported Bordeaux wines are
sold within the European Union. It will also be used in the United
States and Japan, Dulong said, beginning in the second half of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Dulong, who is also vice president of the Bordeaux negociant's
association, acknowledged that the program is in response to
criticism such as that of Griffiths and Zacharia, as well as
scathing reports and sour tasting results in the British wine
press.
</P>
<P>
   ``As negociants we travel in other countries, we see the
competition every day, we hear the criticism,'' Dulong said.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffiths and others say the proof is to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud it in principal, but I have reservations about
whether it has real teeth,'' he said. ``If it works and quality
improves, it will make my job easier to sell Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   As the Bordeaux buyer for Zachys, Zacharia said he would welcome
quality control in the United States. ``If the quality of the
lower-end Bordeaux goes up, we could fill more shelves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux has less space on retail shelves and many people are
drinking California and Italian wines instead. In general, wine
sales are up, but not Bordeaux, Zacharia said .
</P>
<P>
   (Winetoday.com is a daily Internet wine publication of the New
York Times Co. The Web address is http://www.winetoday.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
