<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1177 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-Y2K-SOFTWARE-BOS &LR;      12-16 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SOFTWARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAN. 3 COULD BE FIRST TRUE TEST OF Y2K READINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With only 16 days remaining before Jan. 1, 2000, the
conventional wisdom about the pending impact of the Y2K software
bug goes something like this: Party first, fret later.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the message from consumers, who don't seem to be
stocking up on bottled water and canned goods. Not so with
champagne. ``It's a very good year,'' said Gino Pignone, general
manager at Blanchard's Liquors Inc. in Boston, which reports strong
sales of the beverage lately.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's celebrants should have plenty of company, because a
consensus among local utility and bank executives, software
consultants, and federal planners holds that few major disruptions
will strike on New Year's Day in New England and the rest of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest tests may come as business and stock markets
reopen Monday, Jan. 3. Then, minor problems are expected to crop up
at thousands of smaller companies, schools, and other
organizations, ranging from payroll disruptions to manufacturing
problems and lost grades. The cumulative impact of these problems
is hard to forecast but could be significant. Also, the picture is
more confused overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be confident that the basic infrastructure of
the US is going to function,'' said John Koskinen, President
Clinton's chief Y2K adviser, in a recent interview. ``Our concern,
from a global perspective, is that a series of otherwise manageable
problems might tax the systems as they cut across economic
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Most organizations ``will experience only limited damage from
the Y2K bug,'' according to a report issued Monday in Washington by
a United Nations Y2K center. ``The combination of a great deal of
dedicated effort, the limited use of digital controls in most
infrastructures, and society's general resilience mean that,
although there will be many Y2K-caused errors, the combined
negative effect of these errors will be moderate,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasting the impact of Y2K has become a cottage industry
among computer specialists and public officials trying to minimize
the impact of the software flaw. The problem stems from the
convention among many older software programs to represent the year
with only two digits. Left unfixed, the condition could lead to
disruptions everywhere from cash machines to power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have spent billions of dollars on software repairs as
a result and, since the end of June, institutions including New
England's major water and power utilities and banks have said they
met upgrade deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   The progress among smaller companies is much more difficult to
gauge, however. A survey released last week by the National
Federation of Independent Business, which represents firms with
fewer than 100 employees, showed 26 percent have no plans to check
their computers prior to Jan. 1, up from 21 percent last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more worrisome than if they were doing something about
it,'' said spokesman Jim Weidman.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the UN's Y2K center in Washington was to release a report
Thursday warning that upgrade work must continue at nuclear power
plants worldwide, even after New Year's Day, to prevent Y2K-related
problems from reducing safety margins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, forecasts about possible disruptions can have an
impact on decisions by consumers and businesses as to how much
food, fuel, and cash to stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Hoarding itself could prove disruptive. But partly because of
the rosy outlook described by Koskinen and others, it seems, locals
banks including Fleet Boston Financial and Citizens Financial Group
report no increase in cash withdrawals lately.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for Stop &AMP; Shop Supermarket Co. and Shaw's
Supermarkets Inc. say items such as bottled water and canned goods
don't seem to be selling any more than usual. Other retailers
including Hannaford Bros., Poland Spring Water Corp. and BJ's
Wholesale Club Inc. report higher-than-expected sales, but decline
to quantify the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see a buying frenzy,'' said Ann Davin, spokeswoman
for Gillette Co.'s Duracell battery brand.
</P>
<P>
   To some observers, the lack of a clear sales boom suggests
officials have not done enough work to encourage preparations,
beyond suggesting households keep three to seven days' food, water,
and cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that preventing panic was more important than
solving the problem has won out,'' said Leon Kappelman, a professor
at the University of North Texas who has advised government
planners on Y2K. ``I hope that was a good decision; I don't think
it was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen says he sees no basis for greater calls for alarm,
however, and even many skeptics say they don't expect most
Y2K-related problems to strike major cities and corporations on New
Year's Day. In fact, fewer than 10 percent of Y2K-related failures
will occur in the two weeks surrounding Jan. 1, according to a
report by the Gartner Group consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Capers Jones, a computer scientist at Artemis Management Systems
in Burlington, said he is most worried about the impact Y2K might
have on local utilities, water systems, chemical companies, and
smaller municipalities that haven't spent the resources addressing
the problems.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases these problems might not become apparent until
mid-January, he said. By that time, payroll or billing systems
could break down. Plus, there is too little hard data about the
preparations by individual companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of agree with people like Koskinen'' that disruptions
won't be major at first, Jones said. ``But as you drop down into
the medium to small companies, the availability and quality of the
data about what's going to happen to them becomes useless or
dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he notes the Massachusetts Emergency Management
Agency hasn't rated the preparations of municipalities around the
state, making it hard to know which are most vulnerable to
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Judge, a spokesman for the emergency agency, says that's
fine because state officials have met with representatives from
each of the 351 cities and towns in Massachusetts this year to
review their Y2K plans. Often this meant making sure officials had
current phone numbers for local residents with generators to loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gone in and audited the results, so it's easy to
take shots,'' Judge said. ``But local officials will have to speak
to somebody, so there's going to be a lot of accountability if
things go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Val Asbedian, a Massachusetts planning official charged with
leading the Cellucci administration's response to Y2K, says he's
chiefly concerned that water, electricity, and telecommunications
systems function into the new year. And now that he's heard
assurances from Boston Edison parent NStar, Bell Atlantic, and
other providers, he's not so concerned about what else might occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the water pumps, and the lights and phones are working,
most anything else that happens is something that's going to be
manageable,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
