<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BARR17-COX     12-16 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr will pitch $2 million battle for House seat
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr rode to Congress during the 1994
Republican Revolution. Now the Georgia Republican is fighting hard
to avoid becoming one of its casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party is targeting Barr, among others, in a
sweeping effort to wrest control of the House away from the GOP.
With a razor-thin, five-seat voting margin and 19 incumbent
Republicans declining to run again, the Democrats see an
opportunity to win back the chamber they ran for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are three candidates running for the Democratic
nomination in Georgia's 7th Congressional District. And the race is
turning into a high-stakes game between Barr and a leading
Democrat. It is predicted they will need to raise at least $2
million each _ nearly $700,000 more than Barr's arsenal in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the Democrats are after Barr. They've
relished the idea ever since he became the first member of Congress
to call for impeaching President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising is how seriously they are taking a candidate
who comes from a district that is considered comfortably
Republican. Clinton won just 40 percent of the vote in the 7th
District during the 1996 presidential election. By comparison,
Clinton carried the congressional districts of Georgia Republicans
Saxby Chambliss and Charlie Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barr is very vulnerable,'' said Rep. Martin Frost (D-Texas),
the chairman of the House Democratic Caucus and former head of the
congressional campaign committee that doles out campaign dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Barr is in more trouble than he realizes, Frost said, and it's
not just because of his active role during the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Barr had the narrowest margin of victory in the Georgia
delegation in 1998. His challenger that year, Jim F. Williams, won
45 percent of the vote with a shoestring budget of $13,000.
</P>
<P>
   Barr could face much stiffer competition this time. One of the
Democrats, businessman Roger Kahn, has said he would raise $2
million with or without the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a race that we'll look at closely,'' Frost said.
``It will be a very interesting race that bears national
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the upcoming race, Barr is almost sanguine.
After all, he predicted at the close of the impeachment trial that
he would be a victim of what he called the ``revenge factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr knows that he is a ``targeted'' man, but he predicts that
will only help him raise money and convince conservatives to get
out and vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly anticipate that they will throw everything,
including the kitchen sink, at me,'' Barr said. ``That's what
happens when you have a vindictive president and a Democratic
machine running the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr's supporters are just as ferocious as his detractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr will have an enormous amount of help from
conservatives,'' said Matt Glavin, director of the Southeastern
Legal Foundation, a conservative-leaning legal group based in
Georgia. ``He is one of the heroes of the conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is the paradox of Bob Barr, the politician, said Alan
Abramowitz, professor of political science at Emory University.
People either love him or they hate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very polarizing figure,'' Abramowitz said. The 7th
District is not considered a marginal district, he said, but with
Barr in the seat, a Republican victory is not so clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   The national pundits have singled out Chambliss and Norwood as
vulnerable. They've based that on how well Clinton did in their
districts during the last election.
</P>
<P>
   But Abramowitz thinks the hottest race will be in Barr's
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Barr you are going to have a struggle because people are
strongly in favor of him or really negative about him,'' Abramowitz
said. ``There is no question that this will be an extremely intense
race.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll conducted by Alabama-based Anzalone Research on
behalf of Kahn's campaign found that just 40 percent of the
district's voters feel that Barr should be re-elected and 47
percent said that it was time to give ``someone new a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Kahn said he would run a campaign based on
local issues such as making schools safer, saving Social Security,
restoring Medicare cuts and curbing violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that Mr. Barr was working on national issues, but they
weren't issues that would benefit the people of the 7th District,''
Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is again seeking the Democratic nomination,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used his position as a mouthpiece for the radical right of
the Republican Party, instead of for the 7th District,'' he said.
``Barr spent 1 1/2 years of his personal time trying to get Bill
Clinton out of office,'' Williams said. ``That is a waste of time
and money.''
</P>
<P>
   The third candidate, Chip Warren, was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Barr is proud of his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``My record is my record,'' Barr said. ``How could I regret
doing the right thing?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kahn's poll, is Barr worried?
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Kahn's silly little press release,'' Barr said. ``It's
really silly for someone to put out a release saying, `Hey I'm only
behind by `X' number of points.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he knew what he was getting into when he first decided
to focus a spotlight on the president's ethics.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip with his wife, Jeri, he started reading up on
impeachment law.
</P>
<P>
   Jeri asked him if he knew what could happen. ``She said, `Do you
realize what they'll do to you?'''
</P>
<P>
   But Barr thinks he won the impeachment battle. Although Clinton
is still in office, he did become only the second president to be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be his legacy,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   And Barr's legacy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always believed that as long as I'm doing the right
thing, it doesn't matter what they say about me,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   But he does take their challenge seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to,'' he said. ``But I will mount a vigorous
fund-raising campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
