<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKY SPURS ON UPHILL TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The ultimate indignity occurred six days ago,
during a down moment in the only home loss of the season for the
defending NBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   A fan caught David Robinson's ear as the Spurs were inexplicably
falling to the lowly Washington Wizards, 99-89.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Hey, I'm from Oakland,' '' Robinson recounted. `I
could have stayed home and watched the Warriors if I wanted to see
this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Title Defense 101 in the NBA. The Spurs are where
they want to be in the standings _ on top of their division _ but
nowhere else. They host the Celtics Friday night, and it would
surprise no one here if Boston, which last won in San Antonio in
February, 1990, and has lost 11 of 12 to the Spurs, won the game.
We are not making this up.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Spurs rallied in the fourth quarter to beat
Houston, 83-77. It was like a lot of NBA games, where the home
team, the better team, outlasted the exuberant, inexperienced
visitors. Tim Duncan called it an ugly win, said the team still
hadn't found its rhythm or flow, but also said he was satisfied
with the result.
</P>
<P>
   A local television reporter made the mistake of assuming head
coach Gregg Popovich felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be satisfied with the result, no matter how ugly,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be satisfied? I do? Why don't you ask me if I am?''
Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you?'' the reporter asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich went on. ``I thought we played poorly. We looked
confused, discombobulated. We obviously have a helluva lot of work
to do. Right now, we're playing poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   This is from the coach whose team won the game. This is from the
coach whose team is 17-7 while trying to overcome the loss of a
valuable starter from last year's title team, trying to prevent
complacency from settling in, trying to deal with a group of
graybeards in a league designed to help the high and frequent
flyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have won their last two games. Big deal. The loss to
the Wizards _ the Wizards! _ was the fourth in five games.
Statistically, they look pretty strong; Rick Pitino, for instance,
would like to have their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something missing which everyone acknowledges. Many
things, really. It's the (temporary?) loss of Sean Elliott, still
hoping to come back after a summer kidney transplant. It's having a
bull's-eye on the uniform, something which comes with the territory
of being the NBA champion. It's what Popovich likes to call
``residual satisfaction.'' It's age: The Spurs are the oldest team
in the league with a starting backcourt (Avery Johnson, Mario Elie)
whose ages look like a dream round at Carnoustie: 34-36. One of the
top reserves is Terry Porter, 36.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is all about chemistry,'' Robinson said. ``We have to
trust each other and play together; when we do that, we're very
good. But, obviously, when we don't, we're not a great team. We saw
that very clearly last year, and once we made the commitment to
each other, we turned it around. That's what's gotta happen with
this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he went on, ``there's too many mental mistakes.
There's too much garbage. We're not on the same page yet. We can't
fool ourselves. We can't think we're so overwhelming. It's not like
you can come in this locker room, look around, and say, `Wow, we're
going to win every night.' We're not like Portland or LA, with a
lot of physical talent, so that if things break down, you might win
the game just on the basis of that physical talent. We can't do
that. We have to win playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   The record, Popovich feels, is ``fake . . . inflated.'' He's got
a point. The Spurs have yet to play the Lakers, Trail Blazers,
SuperSonics or Kings. They've played Utah once. They have traveled
_ they've played 13 road games _ but they've also fattened up on a
lot of flotsam.
</P>
<P>
   Slow starts, of course, are nothing new here. As Avery Johnson
noted, ``Thank God we're not 9-11 like we usually are.'' Last year,
the Spurs were 6-8 before they made a quick U-turn and won 31 of
their last 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same exact thing as last year. It's just something
that this group does,'' Popovich said. ``I'm wondering if I'm doing
something coaching-wise which starts out with mass confusion, and
then I gotta get it all straight. Because it's certainly not a plan
of mine. I'm not some amazing genius who says, `We're going to
start out really slow, we're going to be really confused, but by
the time we get to the playoffs . . . '
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be perfect now and win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying all this is the uncertain status of Duncan, the
franchise's most prized asset. One has to wonder how he feels
looking around at all these guys who were playing NBA basketball in
short shorts while he was still working at the 400 freestyle on St.
Croix. He can't do anything until next summer, but that restriction
does not prevent him from tipping his hat. He hasn't, and he won't.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan personally saved them last week from even greater
humiliation than a home loss to Washington _ a home loss to
Vancouver _ with a career-high 42 points. He led the way Wednesday
with 20 points, 10 rebounds and 4 blocks. But a quick scan of the
San Antonio roster shows only four players born in the 1970s _
Duncan (23), good pal Antonio Daniels (24), Malik Rose (25) and
Samaki Walker (23.) The next youngest player is Chucky Brown. He's
31.
</P>
<P>
   The status of Duncan may be paramount in the long term, but in
the short term, it's not at the top of Popovich's list. He has said
he supports Duncan's desire to test free agency (read: Orlando),
and the voters of San Antonio last month approved a new arena for
the Spurs. But by the time that building is up and running,
three-fourths of the team could well be retired and Duncan could be
elsewhere, a prospect no one here wants to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term goal is beating the Celtics. Popovich recalled
San Antonio's easy win last month in Boston (121-98) and said,
without equivocation, ``that this will be a lot tougher game for
us. Then again, every game is a danger game for us right now. We're
so inconsistent in excecution. Then we get mad at ourselves for not
doing it. We're going through a real tough time right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
