<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HOME VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of Rediscoveries and Recoveries &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD had a good year, and so did documentaries. Silent films
flourished, and, as always, there was room for odd pursuits and
first-timers on tape. For example, ``Who Is Harry Kellerman and Why
Is He Saying Those Terrible Things About Me?'' (1971), with Dustin
Hoffman as a tortured rock composer, finally appeared in a
cassette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hold it in my hand,'' said Herb Gardner, somewhat
disbelievingly. He wrote the screenplay for the film, adapting it
from his play. Apparently the movie just got lost for a while.
``Nobody knew who owned it,'' he said. Now that has been clarified,
and the video is from Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Monte Hellman's road film ``Two-Lane Blacktop'' (also 1971)
found the path to video blocked by music rights _ not relating to
the film's star, James Taylor, but for songs like ``Moonlight
Ride'' by the Doors and ``Satisfaction'' by the Rolling Stones. The
film was released on cassette and DVD for the first time by Anchor
Bay. ``I'd like a nice copy to show my kids,'' Hellman said.
</P>
<P>
   For unusual activities, there was Abbas Kiarostami's ``Taste of
Cherry'' from Home Vision, in which a dispirited middle-aged man
drives around the Iranian countryside looking to hire someone to
bury his body after he commits suicide. And in Darren Aronofsky's
``Pi,'' from Artisan, a young man labors over the irrational
number, raising, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times,
``age-old questions about the relationships between genius and
insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Silent films gained steadily on tape and DVD. From Kino came
``Strike'' (1924), Sergei Eisenstein's wildly innovative first
feature, in which mounted troops ride right into apartment
buildings after demonstrators. The silent film of the year,
however, was ``The Passion of Joan of Arc,'' Carl Theodor Dreyer's
austere classic of 1928, in a superb DVD special edition from the
Criterion Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the documentaries. On cassette from A&AMP;E was
``The Farm: Angola, U.S.A.,'' a film about prison life in Louisiana
that received an Oscar nomination. The prize-worthy ``Nobody's
Business,'' Alan Berliner's 1996 film about his father, was
released by Milestone.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian documentary released on video in the United States by
Winstar, ``Rock 'n' Roll Invaders'' tells the stories of some major
American disc jockeys. Joseph Dorman's ``Arguing the World,'' from
First Run, covers America's political progression from '30s
socialism to '80s conservatism as viewed by four New York
intellectuals: Irving Kristol, Daniel Bell, Nathan Glazer and
Irving Howe.
</P>
<P>
   Running more than eight hours, Jennifer Fox's acclaimed
``American Love Story,'' from New Video, explores the 30-year
relationship between a black musician and a white businesswoman.
</P>
<P>
   As for DVD's, some nice boxed sets appeared this year, including
seven Stanley Kubrick films from Warner, 10 Francois Truffauts from
Fox Lorber and seven James Bonds from MGM. And the discs look all
right on a shelf (better than cassettes, at any rate).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Pie
</P>
<P>
   With plenty of emphasis on crude exploration and gross-out body
functions, four high school boys labor toward the promised land:
loss of their virginity by graduation day. Only Kevin (Thomas Ian
Nicholas) is virtually in bed with a girl (Tara Reid). The others
have problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jim (Jason Biggs) pins his hopes on a geekish flute player
turned dominatrix. Oz (Chris Klein), the lumbering jock, takes up
singing and flower-arranging to lure Heather (Mena Suvari) while
Finch (Eddie Kaye Thomas) offers $200 to the sexually active
Jessica (Natasha Lyonne) to spread word of his prowess (as yet
untested).
</P>
<P>
   ``Like an upper-middle-class `Porky's,''' Stephen Holden wrote
in The New York Times, `American Pie' is unable to transcend its
own dirty mind.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $26.98. 95 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Run Lola Run
</P>
<P>
   The director Tom Twyker fuses lightning-fast visual tricks,
shifting styles and interactive storytelling into the best case for
a cinematic video game. If Lola (Franka Potente) with the cranberry
hair can't come up with a lot of money in 20 minutes, her boyfriend
(Moritz Bleibtreu) will be killed.
</P>
<P>
   Then the fun is in the details on a dash that leads from her
father's office through assorted encounters. When one sprint is
over, it is erased and the game starts ov the events altered
with ``a vigor and pizazz that offset the essentially empty nature
of the exercise'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $27.95. 81 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Summer of Sam &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's 1977 in Spike Lee's film, the temperature is in the 100s,
the .44-caliber killer is loose, and, caught in a pre-AIDS
libidinous frenzy, New York City absorbs disco, punk, drugs,
screaming headlines and hysterical prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   In an Italian-American neighborhood in the Bronx, a sex machine
named Vinny (John Leguizamo) clashes with Ritchie (Adrien Brody), a
friend who has adopted rebellious affectations. With two tough
actors making their moves, a busy screenplay reaches out for other
lurid characters who may be thinly conceived but keep developments
``furiously enthralling.''(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Touchstone. $104.16; DVD, $39.99. 145 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Very Thought of You &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying for the Julia Roberts effect, Nick Hamm's film sends
Martha (Monica Potter) to London looking for a new life. Along the
way she encounters a pouting record industry mogul (Tom Hollander),
a struggling young actor (Rufus Sewell) and a bridge instructor
(Joseph Fiennes), all of whom are smitten.
</P>
<P>
   In spirit Ms. Potter offers a reasonable facsimile of Ms.
Roberts' all-American princess, but ``if the story is a clever
sitcomy contraption, the dialogue is pedestrian'' (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 88 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HUNLEY. From TNT in Atlanta comes a Civil War television
movie that is unapologetically sympathetic to the Confederate
cause. Ignoring unfavorable test results (two crews killed), Gen.
Pierre G.T. Beauregard (Donald Sutherland) decides to use the craft
to break the Union blockade of Charleston. Needing a victory to
salvage a career beset with blunders, he enlists Lt. George E.
Dixon (Armand Assante), a broken but resilient officer who turns a
ragtag collection of misfits into a unit of heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the submarine couldn't save Charleston, but, Ron
Wertheimer wrote in The New York Times, ``its legacy, generations
of more successful submarines, now includes one more element, a
memorable film.'' 1999. Warner. $72.11. 94 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   UNCLE TOM'S CABIN. Carl Laemmle's sprawling silent adaptation of
Harriet Beecher Stowe's abolitionist novel had more than its share
of epic statistics: 3,531 scenes in 14 reels, 2,400 extras (called
ensemble atmosphere personalities), six hardwood airplane
propellers chewed to bits by fake snow and 50,000 pieces of
clothing for a cast that used up 28,000 sticks of grease paint.
1927. Kino. $24.95; DVD $29.95. (800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   CARESSES. Based on a play by Sergi Belbel, Ventura Pons' film
interlocks 11 stories of urban love (straight, gay, young and old)
in Barcelona, using a minimalist approach to link them in a circle.
1997. Water Bearer. $79.95. 96 minutes. Catalan with English
subtitles. No rating. Release date: Tuesday. (800) 551-8304. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
