<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYPETS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Make Holidays Jolly _ and Safe _ for Pets  
   
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Holidays can be anything except festive to a pet
that plays with decorations or feels neglected while the family
plays. Here are tips for a happier season from the Marin Humane
Society in California, Humane Society of the United States and
American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seasonal greenery _ poinsettias, mistletoe, holly berries _
chocolate and food scraps can poison pets. Turkey bones can cause
choking or intestinal problems, and fatty foods can lead to painful
pancreatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Keep ornaments, lights, electrical cords and burning candles out
of paws' reach.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor a Christmas tree in its stand and let it remain
undecorated for a day while your pet gets used to having a tree in
the room. Avoid using aspirin in the tree water, since aspirin is
toxic to cats.
</P>
<P>
   Recycle or dispose of wrapping, tinsel, ribbons and other
decorations where pets can't find them.
</P>
<P>
   Spend time with your pet; neglected pets are more likely to
become destructive or try to escape.
</P>
<P>
   When you entertain, make sure your pet has a safe haven when it
can retreat from noise and strangers.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning to travel, consider leaving your pet at home
with a pet sitter _ especially if you're traveling by air. More
than 5,000 animals, including pets, are killed, hurt or lost each
year while traveling by air.
</P>
<P>
   If you take your pet, make sure it wears identification. Cats
traveling by car should be in carriers. Dogs should be in carriers
or a pet restraint system.
</P>
<P>
   Don't give a pet as a gift, because the recipient may not want
it. However, some humane societies offer gift certificates for
adopting pets after the holiday season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
