<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   PLANT OF THE WEEK: All-America Cabbage  
   
   
 By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 Plant name:  `Savoy Express' cabbage (Brassica oleracea var.
sabauda).
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Type of plant: &LR;  Annual.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Description: &LR;  One of nine All-America Selections winners for
2000, this is the earliest small savoy cabbage. Plants grow up to a
foot high, though the head is only as large as 8 inches (1 to 13/4
pounds). Heads are slightly pointed and green, with a yellow-green
interior. The cabbage has a sweet flavor, and its crinkly leaves
provide texture in salads and stir-frys.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Microclimate: &LR;  In mild climates of the Bay Area, plant anytime
between January and May; avoid harvesting in August and September.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Special needs: &LR;  To grow from seed, sow indoors six weeks before
transplanting in the garden. Then plant 1 foot apart. Keep soil
moist.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Harvest: &LR;  About 55 days after transplanting.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Comments:  &LR; ``This is the earliest savoy cabbage in the world.
It also has very tender flavor, whereas a lot of the other savoys
can get somewhat bitter. Also, they are small plants, so if you are
a real cabbage nut, you can grow many, many heads of this savoy in
a smaller-space garden.'' _ Nona Koivula, All-America Selections.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Available at: &LR;  Seeds will be available in mail-order catalogs
this month, or send order to Geo. W. Park Seed Co., 1 Parkton Ave.,
Greenwood, SC 29647-0001.
</P>
</TEXT>
