<SLUG> BC-OFFTHEWALL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   OFF THE WALL: A Chip Off the Old Fire Log  
   
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  First came the fake fire log. It required no
sawing, shed no bark on the carpet and transported no hitchhiking
bugs. Now comes a better-than-fake log _ one that crackles as if it
had the knots and ripples of the real thing.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Called Crackleflame, it's a cousin of Duraflame.cq  &LR;  We put a
5-pound Crackleflame, the standard size, to the fire in a typical
San Francisco fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flame was no different from any other log, but there was a
faint crackle sound that sounds like nice dry firewood,'' our
tester, Rebecca Markowitz, said. ``It did not pop or throw sparks
out of the fireplace.''
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't smell like a natural log, since it's made of
sawdust mixed with waxes, but Markowitz said it wasn't unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   The log didn't burn hot but it lasted long _ about three
soothing hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Crackleflame was developed to satisfy consumers who missed
the sounds of a wood fire when using a Duraflame log.
</P>
<P>
   It lights the same way: Touch a match to the lighting strip that
runs down the side, and in about five minutes the single log
flickers like a grate full.
</P>
<P>
   But is the Crackleflame environmentally wise? Compared with
wood, officials at Stockton-based Duraflame Inc. say, it emits 69
percent fewer particulate, 87 percent less visible smoke, 88
percent less carbon monoxide and 66 percent less creosote, the
flammable gunk that can cause chimney fires.
</P>
<P>
   The suggested retail price is $2.49-2.79 a log, which works out
to $700-something a cord. Or pick up a three-pack for $7.49-8.79
and a case of six for $14.99-16.79.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE TO FIND IT
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Crackleflame logs are sold singly in supermarkets, department
stores and hardware stores where Duraflame logs are sold. Find
information, including frequently asked questions, about the logs
at  &LR; www.duraflame.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1855EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
