<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 15 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to include Oakland-Tampa Bay matchup)  
(A graphic of these matchups has been sent electronically to NYT
graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giants (7-6) at St. Louis (11-2)
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are climbing back into the playoff race because of
two things. First, Fassel has the team believing in miracles.
Second, Fassel has worked extensively, sometimes hours a day, with
quarterback Kerry Collins, correcting his faulty mechanics. Collins
is hot and the Giants are hot. The Rams have little to play for
because the team knows it is only a matter of time before they
claim home-field advantage in the playoffs. They may have to wait
until next week.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 20-15
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SATURDAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (5-8) at Kansas City (8-5)
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers are sliding fast, and the Chiefs are peaking.
Kansas City's offensive coordinator, Jimmy Raye, is doing some of
the best play calling in the league, relying heavily on what
coaches like to call ``bully ball.'' The Chiefs line up and ram the
football down a defense's throat, just as they did against
Minnesota on Monday night. In the 1990s when a Chiefs rusher has
over 30 carries, they are 78-5.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs, 20-12
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (4-9) at Carolina (6-7)
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Coach George Seifert is playing his old team, and who
would have thought that when Seifert faced his former employer he
would be fighting for a playoff spot and the 49ers would be dying a
slow death? The Panthers can smell the playoffs. That other stench
is a San Francisco defense that earlier this season allowed
Carolina to score 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers, 28-25
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY 1 P.M. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (3-10) at Tennessee (10-3)
</P>
<P>
   Falcons' coach Dan Reeves keeps flirting with the idea this may
be his last season as head coach of the Falcons. This game may make
his decision a little easier because it will get ugly. The Titans
are not a great team, but they are a solid one. Atlanta will see a
healthy dose of Eddie George, who needs only 85 yards to become the
fourth player in NFL history with at least 1,200 rushing yards in
each of his first four season. Titans quarterback Steve McNair has
been wearing a boot in practice to protect his injured ankle and
should play.
</P>
<P>
   Titans, 30-9
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (8-5) at Chicago (5-8)
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that Lions' quarterback Charlie Batch has a
small fracture in his throwing thumb. The good news is that his
backup, Gus Frerotte, has had a decent season. This game will be
extremely tight. The Bears almost beat Detroit on Thanksgiving Day.
What drives the Lions now are dreams of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 17-14
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (12-1) at Cleveland (2-12)
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville running back James Stewart has a sprained left foot
and may not play. But Jaguars fans need not worry. Fred Taylor, who
had 1,223 yards last year, is as great a reserve as there is in the
league. No land mines for Jacksonville in this game _ they win
convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars, 35-10
</P>
<P>
   New England (7-6) at Philadelphia (3-11)
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ty Law, who will miss the next two to four weeks with
a broken hand, is the latest piece of bad news for the Patriots.
Coach Pete Carroll will likely be fired at the end of the season.
After last week's loss to Indianapolis, quarterback Drew Bledsoe
apologized to owner Robert Kraft for his poor play. When players
start begging for forgiveness from management, that means trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles, 14-13
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (2-11) at Baltimore (6-7)
</P>
<P>
   Running back Ricky Williams likely will not play again this
season beccase of a variety of injuries. He was a good pick and is
a good player, but this season has been a disaster because the
Saints are so pitiful. Meanwhile the Ravens are beginning to show
why they have so much promise. They aim for their third straight
victories for the first time since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 21-3
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (6-7) at Miami (8-5)
</P>
<P>
   There is always trouble when those anonymous quotes from players
start popping up in the newspaper. That's what is happening in
Miami. There are questions on whether this is Jimmy Johnson's last
year, or Marino's. San Diego has a good defense led by end Raylee
Johnson's five sacks, but Marino has enough to get by and stay in
the playoff hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 17-10
</P>
<P>
   Washington (8-5) at Indianapolis (11-2)
</P>
<P>
   There are coaches in the NFL waiting for the Colts to slip. They
will have to keep waiting. Washington has enough offense to stay
with Indianapolis, but the Redskins are much too weak defensively
to stay with the Colts' impressive threesome of Peyton Manning,
Marvin Harrison and Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 35-22
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jets (5-8) at Dallas (7-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are playing the role of spoilers, and they are the most
dangerous spoilers in years. The reason is backup quarterback Ray
Lucas _ he has not only proved he is a capable backup but a starter
in this league. His 85.2 rating, which is better than Troy
Aikman's, is third in the conference. Meanwhile, Dallas running
back Emmitt Smith is questionable with a groin injury. The Jets
will end any realistic hope of Dallas' winning the division.
</P>
<P>
   Jets, 28-21
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (8-5) at Denver (4-9)
</P>
<P>
   Denver has played hard this season, and most of their games have
been close. This one should be as well. The last four meetings
between Seattle and the Broncos have been decided by seven points
or less. Denver has won 13 of the past 14 games at home against the
AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos, 19-16
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (9-4) at Oakland (6-7)
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers can clinch a playoff birth with a victory. What
quarterback Trent Dilfer could not do in years as the starting
quarterback _ just be steady and not mess things up _ rookie Shaun
King is doing in abundance. He is 2-0 in his starts with a 90.6
passer rating. As defensive lineman Warren Sapp is fond of saying,
all the team needs is a quarterback who won't make mistakes. The
defense will take care of the rest. Finally, Sapp has his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers, 17-9
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (8-5) at Arizona (6-7)
</P>
<P>
   A Bills victory means the franchise would be assured of an
eighth winning season in the 1990s. More important, it would keep
them in the playoff race. This is an interesting game to follow.
Both teams are coming off brutal losses, the Bills to the Giants
and the Cardinals to Washington. Arizona's season is pretty much
over. The Bills win because they have more to play for.
</P>
<P>
   Bills, 20-13
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (7-6) at Minnesota (7-6)
</P>
<P>
   This is a position no one expected either team to be in: On the
outside of the playoff race looking in. What is most disappointing
is the Packers' defense. They are giving up 328 yards a game. There
remain rumors that retired Green Bay defensive end Reggie White
wants to bring his cleats back out of the closet. That won't
happen, and if it did, even the future Hall of Famer might not be
able to help this shellshocked bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings, 30-29
</P>
</TEXT>
