<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-DESIGN-EXHIBIT-AR     12-16 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-DESIGN-EXHIBIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL-SCALE EXHIBIT OF 20TH-CENTURY DESIGN AT THE MET MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Austria, Germany, France, Britain, Scotland)  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT1, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Proving once again that it can mount a boutique of a
show with the same panache as a five-alarm blockbuster, the
Metropolitan Museum has unveiled an exquisite sampling of
20th-century design objects from its own collection.
</P>
<P>
   A salute rather than a full survey, ``A Century of Design, Part
1: 1900-1925'' is installed in several intimate galleries in the
20th-century wing. It displays more than 50 examples of furniture,
metalwork, glass, ceramics, textiles, jewelry and drawings, from a
fanciful Pompeian-style dressing table of bronze and basalt by the
French designer Armand-Albert Rateau to a silver claret jug with
sinuous curves and flyaway thumb-piece, the work of the English
craftsman Archibald Knox.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which runs through March 26, is the first in a
four-part series on 20th-century design, organized by J. Stewart
Johnson, consultant for design and architecture in the museum's
department of modern art, that will extend into the year 2001.
``Part 1'' focuses on the three major design currents of the period
1900 to 1925: Arts and Crafts, Art Nouveau and Art Deco. The
star-studded roster includes Charles Rennie Mackintosh, Josef
Hoffmann, Frank Lloyd Wright, Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann, Peter
Behrens, Emile Galle, Rene Jules Lalique, Koloman Moser, Paul
Poiret, Gio Ponti and Eliel Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 19th century, designers were rebelling against
the furbelows of Victorian style with its overblown machine-made
furniture in hodgepodge designs that battened on the past. Fueled
by the utopian ideals of John Ruskin and William Morris _ honesty
of expression, materials and workmanship and the elevation of
applied arts to the level of fine arts _ the revisionist Arts and
Crafts movement was born. To its practitioners, handmade was good,
machine-made unbearable, although from a production standpoint,
they soon came to see the necessity of mechanical help.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great Arts and Crafts proponents was the Austrian
architect Josef Hoffmann (1870-1956), who in 1903, with the painter
and furniture designer Koloman Moser (1868-1918), founded the
influential Wiener Werkstatte (Vienna Workshops). A design
cooperative described by Hoffmann in 1904 as ``a center of gravity
surrounded by the happy noise of handicraft production and welcomed
by everybody who truly believed in Ruskin and Morris,'' it affected
the spirit and substance of European decoration for more than 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the objects by Hoffmann on view is a playfully inventive
1904 table lamp of glass and copper with silvery hammered surfaces.
Made when the shift from gas to electricity challenged designers to
accommodate the new technology, it has electric lights that are
sheltered under a flaring, unshaded top, their shapes and
luminosity echoed by dangling silver spheres.
</P>
<P>
   With Moser, Hoffmann also designed an armchair (1903) that seems
more in keeping with the restrained, geometric architecture for
which he was noted. Essentially a spare, open cube whose top and
sides are supported by elongated diamond slats, it has a cane seat
of painted squares in black and white; the whole is a smart,
elegant triumph of Minimalism.
</P>
<P>
   Parallel with Arts and Crafts ran Art Nouveau, an offshoot of
that movement and of Symbolism, the late 19th-century art and
literary manifestation whose imagery was generated by ideas, moods
and emotions. Art Nouveau's exaggeratedly asymmetrical style, also
a revolt against 19th-century historicism, used a linear vocabulary
based on organic forms: plant shapes, flames, waves, flowing hair
and such. The term comes from the name of a shop, L'Art Nouveau,
opened in Paris in 1895 by Siegfried Bing, which sold original as
opposed to period work.
</P>
<P>
   The movement in its full Continental flower is evident in a
formidable cabinet-vitrine, dated 1899, by the Belgian architect
and decorator Gustave Serrurier-Bovy (1858-1910). A tall structure
of light-reddish wood standing more than eight feet tall, with two
glass-front cabinets and two drawers, it is embellished with
sinuous Art Nouveau relief carvings and bright enameling on the
repousse metal handles and key plates.
</P>
<P>
   A less typical but more important representative of the Art
Nouveau movement was Charles Rennie Mackintosh (1868-1928), the
Scottish architect, designer, decorator and painter, whose
restrained endeavors departed from the more florid effusions of
Continental designers. Using oak painted in black or white,
Mackintosh produced chairs, settees, benches, card tables and
cabinets in a distinctively clean, linear style, often embellished
with small incised decorations and opaque colored glass.
</P>
<P>
   One of the show's knockout pieces is Mackintosh's oak washstand
of 1904, made for the ``blue bedroom''  Cranston; the
Glasgow tearooms he designed for her in 1897 provided his first
commercial success. A sturdy-looking piece in light-colored oak,
the washstand has a counter of tiled blue ceramic and a backsplash
of leaded glass in brilliant shades of blue overlaid by a stylized
floral design abloom with green glass and mirrors. Less exuberant
than the French and Belgian versions of Art Nouveau, it is more
evocative of Jugendstil, the contemporaneous Nouveau mode in
Austria and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Art Deco, the movement or movements that developed out of Art
Nouveau, took its name from the 1925 design fair in Paris,
l'Exposition Internationale des Arts Decoratifs et Industriels
Modernes. But it had begun to establish itself in the years just
before World War I. The best of it was unabashedly elitist;
although it posed as new, it was essentially conservative.
Inspiration came from traditional late 18th- and early 19th-century
furniture models. The French version, for instance, shows
Directoire and Empire influences, bringing seating closer to the
ground with tables lowered to match. (The birth of the cocktail
table is credited to Art Deco.)
</P>
<P>
   The high-fashion breed of Art Deco stressed luxury materials
like exotic woods and Chinese lacquer, with trims in ivory,
shagreen (rawhide patterned like sharkskin) and even
mother-of-pearl. Smooth, shiny surfaces showed off the expensive
materials. Geometric and rounded shapes _ angles, arcs, circles and
lines _ and colors in black, gray, white, silver and red later came
to characterize the style.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important of the French Deco cabinet makers was
Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann (1879-1933), a superb technician whose
craftsmanship equaled that of the finest 18th-century artisans. The
elegant curves of his desk, desk chair and file cabinet (1918-23),
in precious wood with ivory trim, manage to look formal and
discreetly sexy at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable Art Deco pieces in the show include a rosewood
stool (circa 1925) by Pierre Legrain, adapted from a traditional
African form; Edgar Brandt's massive ``Persia'' door of forged iron
with an openwork design of large floral blossoms (circa 1923), and
a suave table (1924) by Clement Rousseau whose top, a sort of ebony
tray, is supported between two high arches of ebony partly wrapped
in sharkskin that serve as legs.
</P>
<P>
   Small and select as it is, the show makes a graceful tribute to
an avant-garde century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1901EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
