<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE DEFICIT SWELLS TO $25.9 BILLION, 7TH RECORD THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's trade deficit swelled again in October, to $25.9
billion, setting a record for the seventh time this year as
prosperous American consumers and businesses kept up their spending
spree. Exports were essentially unchanged, while imports continued
to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Higher prices for imported oil, on which the United States
relies for more than half its needs, more than offset reduced
volume and accounted for one-fourth of the October gap, which was
much larger than expected. Record deficits with China and Japan
accounted for more than half of the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer demand in the U.S. is extremely strong,'' said Bill
Sharp, senior economist at Chase Securities, predicting that
booming sales of foreign cars would contribute to a further
widening of the deficit in the coming months. Weak growth among
various Asian and European trading partners, on the other hand, has
caused demand for American goods to lag.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very rapid growth of our economy vis-a-vis the rest of
the world,'' said William C. Dudley, chief U.S. economist at
Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   The wider trade gap provides some ammunition for those who have
been contending that the United States is being victimized by the
unfair labor practices of other countries and that American workers
need some protection, perhaps by imposing higher labor and
environmental standards on some trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   This was a significant contention at the recent World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle, where efforts to start a new round
of trade liberalization failed amid unexpectedly widespread
protests.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an agreement under which the United States supports
China's bid to join the WTO, in exchange for better access to
Chinese markets, is still subject to approval by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   William Daley, the commerce secretary, cited the far faster rate
of American economic growth as the main reason for the growing
trade imbalance but warned of the political problems it posed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have carried much of the burden,'' he said, referring to
the way the United States has bought large quantities of goods from
economically struggling trading partners, especially in Asia.
``Politically, that gets very difficult over a long period and
other countries have to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise in imports during October was 1.6 percent, to a record
$107.9 billion, with the biggest increases in computer-related and
other capital goods, including semiconductors. Some analysts had
expected imports of semiconductors to decline because of an
earthquake in Taiwan in September. Meanwhile, the nation's bill for
imported oil reached a new peak of $6.4 billion as the average
price rose to $20.74 a barrel from $19.52 even as the number of
imported barrels fell.
</P>
<P>
   Exports edged down 0.1 percent, to $81.9 billion, with
telecommunications equipment one of the biggest drags.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 10 months of the year, exports have climbed
1.9 percent compared with figures in the period a year earlier,
while imports have surged 10.7 percent. This has resulted in a
deficit running at an annual rate of $262 billion, far above last
year's peak of $164.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deficits with Japan and China each climbed to $7.2 billion
for the month, the most ever recorded with any country. The
widening with Japan was 8.1 percent; with China it was 3.6 percent.
Unlike the other figures, those involving individual countries or
other geographic areas are not adjusted for seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit with Mexico narrowed to $1.4 billion as both exports
and imports reached peaks, while the deficit with Canada, the
nation's biggest trading partner, rose to $3.2 billion. Record
imports from Western Europe helped push the American deficit with
the region to $5 billion, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
   While it will probably take the better part of next year before
the deficit starts to narrow, Dudley said, its growth should slow
and the dollar is not likely to weaken by a worrisome amount.
</P>
<P>
   The currency may be piling up in foreign hands, he said, but
American interest rates are already high enough to make investment
in the United States attractive. ``We're offering pretty good
terms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
