<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox cable adds African-American focus
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the battle for subscribers heats up among Internet
service providers, telecom and cable companies, Atlanta-based Cox
Communications has decided to focus some of its marketing efforts
on the African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired Images USA to develop a marketing strategy to
help attract minority subscribers in Cox markets across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Images will develop broadcast, print and outdoor advertising for
Cox cable, broadband and telephone service targeted specifically to
African-Americans. Images will also work with Cox on community
outreach plans, public relations and other grass-roots initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox is developing and delivering a wide range of exciting new
services, and we want to offer those services to as wide a customer
base as possible,'' said Joe Rooney, vice president for marketing,
Cox Communications. Following the close of pending cable system
acquisitions, Cox will serve about 6 million customers nationwide,
making it the nation's fifth-largest cable company.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Communications is a public company controlled by privately
held Cox Enterprises, parent company of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Images says that the technology industry,
although still relatively young, hasn't yet begun seriously
marketing to specific demographics. ``Automobiles and fast-food
restaurants target to specific groups,'' says Images public
relations director Hank Ernest. ``They've targeted, they've tested
and they know it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research senior analyst Dan O'Brien agrees that Cox's
marketing strategy is a good one. ``With all the news about ISPs
and free ISPs and the deals Microsoft has made with Best Buy and
Radio Shack, Internet access has gotten cheaper, and there isn't
that price hurdle to get over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Cox has the local focus and brings in a channel in Spanish
or an African channel, that does make sense, and they can drive
advertising there,'' he said. (Cox Interactive Media produces local
Internet portals in all of its markets, as well as an excellent
stand-alone site. Blackfamilies
</P>
<P>
   .com.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense,'' said O'Brien. ``These lower-priced
ISPs will jump-start the adoption rate for home PCs that much of
the population hasn't really embraced yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen with Cox is they will get a leg up on other
tech-based firms in the African market,'' says Images' Ernest. ``If
you flip though most African-American magazines, you probably won't
see a targeted ad in the technology realm. Our plan is to
absolutely change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
