<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGING-MONK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On leave from monastery, baritone travels to perform
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Giorgio Cebrian, the singing monk, tours
the world, impersonating homicidal fathers (``Rigoletto''), mad
monarchs (``Nabucco''), crowned assassins (``Macbeth'') and, in
West Palm Beach, a slippery, serpentine diplomat in the production
of Andrea Giordano's ``Fedora.''
</P>
<P>
   He worships Verdi when he is not worshiping God. He carries a
photograph of Giuseppe Verdi with him in his travels, along with
his breviary of prayers. He speaks sincerely of leading ``a
consecrated life'' in a little hermitage in Siena, Italy, where he
will return to live in quiet contemplation after his magnificent
baritone voice deserts him, as it must someday. Ashes to ashes,
dust to dust.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he is booked solid through 2005 and is proud of the
fact that he does his own makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know, they invited me to a reception here at your big
Hotel di lusso, what is it called? The Breakers?'' Cebrian said.
``It was a very lovely experience. People have practically cradled
me in their houses. Marvelous hospitality! And at a reception the
other night, they invited me to sing from `Rigoletto' _ I have done
`Rigoletto' 218 times _ Cortigiani, vil razza dannata! (O, you
damned vile race of place-seekers!) And there was a storm of
applause!''
</P>
<P>
   Since he emerged from his little Benedictine monastery in 1990,
with a special extra clausuram (''outside the cloister'')
permission from the Holy See in the Vatican, which must be renewed
every five years, Cebrian has left a worldwide trail of
stage-murders in his wake, each of them elaborately produced,
gorgeously costumed and backed up by some of the most compelling
music on earth.
</P>
<P>
   He will performed Monday in ``Fedora.'' He is not the lead
singer _ that honor, and the showpiece solo, ``Amor ti vieta,''
which launched the great Enrico Caruso's career at the premier of
the opera in 1898, belongs to Mikhail Davidoff, who plays opposite
Oksana Krovytska in the title role. Cebrian plays De Siriex, a
supple and worldly diplomat whose greatest moment in the opera is a
worldly, cynical song about ``La Dama Russa,'' the Russian woman,
her character, her strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   But he takes the role seriously, memorizing the responses as
fervently as an altar-boy learns how to answer at a Catholic Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opera that depends on single words,'' Cebrian says.
``You miss one word, you miss your cue. Yesterday, at the
siesta-hour, I remained awake in my dressing room, going over every
word of the part. It's a role that calls for a brilliancy in the
first act, and then you have to quietly fall apart and become
insufficient, yet maintain your character. That's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the costumes and swelling tides of music, Cebrian has had
a quiet war within himself, between the world and the spirit, a
life in which outward success masks deep loss and difficult
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had what you would call a 'vocation' early on in my life. I
tended toward the consecrated life, but my parents were opposed to
it. They wanted me to get married. And so I launched out on a
musical career and was very successful for a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played `Rigoletto' in 1971 with Alfredo Kraus. I did
`Carmen' in 1975 with Richard Tucker. I have been with conductors
like Claudio Abbado and Georges Pretre. It was a wonderful time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became engaged. She was a brilliant pianist, a beautiful,
wonderful woman. She died very tragically in a car accident just
four months before we were to be married. That outcome made a great
impression on me. It recalled me to my former wish, to become
religious, to lead a consecrated life. I had always felt the call,
you know, the vocation. And so finally I joined the Benedictines
and remained for seven years inside a monastery, dedicating myself
to the spiritual world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one day, my abbot called me aside and said, `It is a pity
you do not display those gifts which God has given you to more
people.' It was a kind of miracle. So I prepared for one year to go
singing again, and I went back onstage with Martinu's `Epic of
Gilgamesh,' the premiere, at the Rome Opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, I've played at La Scala in Milan, the Arena of
Verona, the Greek theater at Siracusa in Sicily. I did `La
Traviata' in Tokyo _ the Japanese are crazy for Verdi _ and now I'm
in Palm Beach with `Fedora.' Amazing, no?''
</P>
<P>
   Cebrian returns to his little monastery several times a year, on
holidays, but lives for the most part outside its walls. More and
more monks, he says, are finding work in the world outside the
cloister, work with the sick, the elderly, with drug addicts. The
motto of the Benedictine order, founded by St. Benedict in the
fifth century A.D., is Ora et Labora, work and pray.
</P>
<P>
   Work. Pray. Sing?
</P>
<P>
   ``My work is my singing,'' Cebrian says cheerfully. His vows
oblige him to fulfill certain religious duties daily, to observe
church rules and, as he puts it, ``to maintain the conduct of an
ordinary Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My monastery is my home. There is where I will go when my
voice gives out. If I die in an accident before then, all my
worldly goods go to my order, the Benedictines,'' he said. ``At the
end of my road, the monastery is always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
