<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    California-based competitor to buy Tradex Technologies
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tradex Technologies is being bought by Ariba, a California-based
competitor, for about $1.9 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Tradex, which recently moved its headquarters to metro Atlanta
from Tampa, develops Internet-based trade networks. The company
employs 185 people, 60 in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba said it will issue 8.3 million shares to cover the
transaction. The deal is expected to close by June 30. Investors
were pleased with the deal, Ariba's second in two months. Ariba's
stock closed Thursday at $232.25, up $8.25, or 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Ariba paid $400 million for Trading Dynamics of
Mountain View, Calif. Ariba and Tradex were partners of Trading
Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba, which went public in June, has a market capitalization of
more than $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Tradex will operate as an Atlanta-based business unit of Ariba,
run by John Baumstock, Tradex's chief operating officer. Daniel
Aegerter, Tradex's 30-year-old founder, will become a senior market
strategist for Ariba. Aegerter moves to Brookhaven this weekend.
The moving van pulled up to his Tampa home soon after the deal
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba is establishing itself as leader among the firms that
connect companies to their suppliers over the Internet. Its
competitors include Suwanee-based Clarus.
</P>
<P>
   Tradex develops tools that let suppliers bid on bulk-buying
contracts. A company such as American Express, a Tradex customer,
would use the technology to solicit bids for office supplies and
other needs.
</P>
<P>
   Tradex is privately held, with employees owning 40 percent of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Aegerter spun off Tradex from Dynabit, a Swiss computer
distributor, in 1996. Aegerter worked in Dynabit's U.S. purchasing
office, based in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Local venture capitalist John Imlay was among the early
investors. Imlay's partner, Sig Mosley, was a Tradex director.
</P>
<P>
   The pair helped steer Tradex from a firm with a software for
bidding on computer parts to a company that helps create Internet
markets between businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet-based marketplaces has boomed lately.
Freemarkets went public last week and now has a market
capitalization of $8.5 billion. Tradex was poised to go public but
felt the price Ariba offered was a fair offer for shareholders,
Aegerter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a bigger mother ship with less volatility for our
shareholders than if we had gone out on our own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
