<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DIA-ARTS-CENTER-ART-2     12-16 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIA-ARTS-CENTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCHARACTERISTIC ADVENTURES IN COMPARATIVE VIEWING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dia Center for the Arts has a certain hauteur. It
tends to favor the minimalist-conceptualist elect, showing their
work in splendid isolation, fastidiously installed, for a year or
even more. Dia's efforts have a distinct intellectual slant that
can sometimes feel slightly medicinal. It is possible to emerge
from a Dia show feeling that good deeds have been done: by Dia, for
organizing it, and by oneself, for seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   But Dia may be unbending ever so slightly. Film, video and
photography, the current juggernauts of contemporary art, have
never been dominant at Dia, so it seems noteworthy that four of the
seven artists it is showing this fall are involved with at least
one of these media. Furthermore, in something of a departure from
Dia's splendidly isolated solo shows, the work of these four
artists is being presented in two two-person shows, which makes
comparisons natural.
</P>
<P>
   One show, ``Double Vision,'' juxtaposes video pieces by Stan
Douglas of Canada and Douglas Gordon of Scotland; both works use
side-by-side projections and are continuously screened in large,
dark rooms. Another two-artist show, ``Time Traced,'' brings
together series of large black-and-white photographs by Rodney
Graham, who is also Canadian, and Vera Lutter, a German artist.
They either use the camera obscura, or pinhole camera, or mimic the
effects of this rudimentary ancestor of photography, which was
invented during the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   All these artists focus rather narrowly on the nature and
mechanics of their chosen media with a self-reflexiveness that
might be called formalist, but only Graham's photographs of
upside-down trees are fully engaging. At once brainy, accessible
and emotionally rich, they avoid this artist's tendency toward
conceptual opacity.
</P>
<P>
   The images, which measure about 8{ by 6 feet, were taken with a
large-format camera turned upside down; they imitate the camera
obscura's inversion, but not its fuzziness. Their precision is
dazzling. The trees are big, old and glorious, shot dead-on from a
distance in a leafless state; even the tiniest, highest twig
registers clearly. They make Joyce Kilmer's shopworn phrase, or
something close to it, spring to mind: if not God, then only nature
can make a tree. They also evoke a royal lineage of trees in art,
from 17th-century Dutch painting to Constable to the photographs of
Atget. Graham matter-of-factly proves the romantic notion that
every tree has a distinct personality, that branches can grow into
full, symmetrical halos or less regular, somewhat crazed ones.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the eye fights to maintain logic. The branches
can read as the underground root systems reaching downward into the
earth. Or they may suggest reflections, lakeside mirrorings of
actual trees that have been cropped out of the picture. But mainly,
the trees' majesty is dramatized and renewed by the oddness of
their inverted state.
</P>
<P>
   While Graham changes up to down, Ms. Lutter's luminous images
might be said to change day to night. Made with large, specially
built pinhole cameras and exposures that can last several days,
they are presented right-side up, but retain the image's natural
negative state. The result is that Ms. Lutter's subjects _ vast
industrial sites that seem abandoned _ are pushed further into a
silvery twilight zone, an eerie past tense that is enhanced by a
resemblance to large daguerrotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the traces of time are visible, most notably in two
images of a zeppelin hangar in Friedrichshafen, Germany, in which a
zeppelin and the machinery around it change position. The show also
includes two images of an empty Nabisco factory in Beacon, N.Y.,
that resembles a prison. Best of all (albeit from a New York bias)
is a close-up of the big Pepsi-Cola sign in Queens, from the Queens
side with the Manhattan skyline visible behind its scaffolding and
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lutter is not the first contemporary photographer to produce
big, well-made images with a pinhole camera, but the combination of
her technical precision and the flat-footed romanticism created by
the reversed image is unusual. Each of her irradiated images seems
to give us a final glimpse of a defunct world just before it went
up in smoke. In the brochure to the exhibition, Lynn Cooke, the Dia
curator who organized it, sums up both Ms. Lutter's and Graham's
images with an unusually romantic quote from Walter Benjamin: ``The
world is beautiful _ that is its watchword.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Double Vision,'' which Ms. Cooke also organized and which
has been up for several months, complex technique supplies a little
too much of the fascination, with the result that the work is
almost more interesting to think about than to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is known for appropriating and manipulating feature films
in ways that frequently stretch time. Previous works include a
24-hour projection of ``Psycho,'' a five-year projection of ``The
Searchers'' and, on opposite walls of the Gagosian Gallery in SoHo
last spring, a double projection of Robert DeNiro's famous
soliloquy as Travis Bickle in ``Taxi Driver'' _ ``Are you talking
to me?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the piece at Dia, which is titled ``Left Is Right and Right
Is Wrong and Left Is Wrong and Right Is Right,'' Gordon has created
another kind of doubleness using the entirety of ``Hypnosis,'' a
little-known 97-minute film noir directed by Otto Preminger. He has
split the film, putting even-numbered frames on one reel,
odd-numbered frames on another and then replacing the excised
frames with black leader. These films are projected side by side on
one wall, with the one on the right reversed (which partly explains
the title).
</P>
<P>
   The result of these manipulations is a hypnotic strobing of
image and sound and an eye-dazzling mirroring that takes full
advantage of the movie's black-and-white film and sharp-edged
stylishness while throwing the camera's every move into high
relief. It is an effect of impressive short-term power, but it is
impossible to spend much time in this gallery (nor is lingering
encouraged, given the absence of benches). Meaning is almost
entirely disrupted; the film becomes a pantomime enacted against
kaleidoscopic patterns and sliding planes.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gordon, Douglas has sometimes worked with existing film,
but in ``Win, Place or Show'' it is the shooting process and the
movie set that he manipulates. The scene, which is projected double
on one wall, is a six-minute exchange of words and then blows
between two men who share a modernistic apartment in a big,
anonymous complex.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument reveals their different backgrounds and
personalities, their shared malaise and their mutual hostility. It
erupts into violence over a discussion of betting on horses,
subsides, and then, seamlessly, the scene begins again. (The whole
effect is rather like a big color photograph by another Canadian
artist, Jeff Wall, come to life.)
</P>
<P>
   The doubling is not at all seamless: the projected images don't
match, but overlap awkwardly; the actors seem to move from one
projection to another. And each repetition of the scene is a little
different. Words and camera angles change; objects come and go; the
fight is sometimes on the floor, sometimes on the bed. Watching it
several times, the viewer becomes increasingly confused, unable to
keep track of the differences and immersed in the film's mechanics,
all the while hoping to catch the cycle beginning again.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is in vain. In fact, the scene has been shot several
times, with different dialogue, props, blocking and multiple camera
angles. The sequence and pairing of the resulting versions are
determined by a computer, and there are about 200,000 possible
combinations. It is virtually impossible to see the same thing
twice, an almost unheard-of situation where film is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The works in ``Double Vision'' offer a variant on the image-text
duality of classic conceptual art: the specific technical feats
involved in making them function as the all-too-necessary
explanation. Still, it is interesting to see the efforts of two
artists in reasonable proximity at Dia; each show is a good match
in which the sum of the parts exceeds the whole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1907EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
