<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YIELD ON 30-YEAR BOND IS HIGHEST SINCE OCTOBER 1997 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-term interest rates jumped to their highest
levels in more than two years Thursday as the persistent strength
of the U.S. economy convinced more and more investors that the
Federal Reserve might have to raise interest rates sharply to rein
in growth.
</P>
<P>
   The view of how hard the nation's central bank will have to push
on the brakes seems to change almost daily. Just a month ago, after
the Fed raised its interest rate target a quarter of a percentage
point, the third increase this year, many analysts thought the Fed
was finished.
</P>
<P>
   But just a few weeks later, the talk was of one more rate
increase, but not until the March meeting of policy-makers. Then
the one rate increase moved up to February. Now the talk is of two
rate increases. And there is even speculation that the Fed might
raise its target for the Federal Funds rate, the overnight loan
rate between banks, by a half-point in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fed policy-makers are going to tighten until they see the
economy slow down,'' said Donald Fine, chief market analyst at
Chase Asset Management. ``And there is no sign the economy is
slowing.''
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 30-year bond jumped to 6.39 percent
Thursday, from 6.32 percent on Wednesday. That is the highest the
yield has been since October 1997, surpassing the recent high of
6.37 percent in October of this year. The price, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell 27/32, to 96 17/32.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the Treasury's two-year note, which is more
sensitive to threats of higher interest rates from the Fed, rose to
6.13 percent from 6.06 on Wednesday. The narrow gap between the
yields of the 30-year bond and the two-year note is also a sign
that investors expect the Fed to move soon.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Slifer, the chief U.S. economist at Lehman Brothers, and
Ethan Harris, the senior economist there, are two of many analysts
who have been forced by strong growth to raise their expectations
of Fed rate increases. A month ago they thought the Fed was
through; now they are predicting two Fed rate increases in the
first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they have increased their forecast of
fourth-quarter growth to 5.5 percent from 4.3 percent. And this
week's economic data seems to confirm that judgment. Retail sales
in November jumped 0.9 percent, well above expectations. Industrial
production rose 0.3 percent, which was strong considering the
revision of October's climb to 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report of a record trade deficit in October was also
a worry because the record imports for the month were another sign
of relentless consumer spending. A decline in initial jobless
claims to a 26-year low also showed how hot the economy is.
</P>
<P>
   The force that seems to be driving the consumer is the continued
strength of the stock market, which increases consumers'
willingness to spend. So until the stock market slows down from its
five-year double-digit pace, it will be hard to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the market strategist at Goldman, Sachs, said
Thursday that the stock market would climb at a more moderate pace
next year, in part because the market is fully valued. Her year-end
target for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index is 1,525, a 7.5
percent move from its close Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But to get this kind of performance, Harris said that the Fed
would probably have ``to take a few more warning shots across the
bow of the stock market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
