<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1217-CO     12-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAEL, SYRIA TALKS END WITH AGREEMENT TO RESUME IN JANUARY
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-PEACE-1217.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli and Syrian officials wound up two days of
preliminary peace talks Thursday with an agreement to meet again
for a more intensive round of negotiations beginning Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who will help mediate the talks somewhere
near Washington, said the agreement put the two blood enemies on a
path, albeit a rocky one, toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   It also set the table, Clinton said, for a year-long diplomatic
full-court press to end half a century of bloodshed in the
fractious Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The journey will be tough. Nothing in the past 48 hours should
lead us to believe otherwise,'' Clinton told White House reporters
during a brief statement outside the West Wing. ``But the parties
are embarked on this path. They have agreed there should be no
looking back, for the sake of our generation and generations yet to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton's announcement itself offered evidence of the
difficulties ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on either side of him were Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, the highest
ranking officials from each country ever to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, though, was permitted to speak, an apparent safeguard
against the sort of unanticipated public criticism Sharaa levied
against Israel and its allies at the outset of the sensitive talks
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two men didn't shake hands, either, eschewing diplomatic
custom. Nor did they shake hands in private, according to Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, who spent most of the past two days
meeting with Barak and Sharaa, separately and jointly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the frosty atmospherics, both men agreed to move forward
on negotiations centered on Israeli return of the strategic Golan
Heights in exchange for an end to hostilities and threats from
Syria and its 400,000-man army to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the core issues that have divided the two neighbors
since Israeli troops seized the Golan territory after Syria
attacked Israel in 1967. The January talks hold out the prospect of
the most concerted effort to date to resolve the 32-year-old
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that the road is not an easy one,'' Albright
told reporters at a White House news conference. ``All I can tell
you of what we came out from this is an incredible willingness for
everybody to put their shoulder to the wheel and really work. And
we will see.''
</P>
<P>
   To help get the wheel rolling, Albright asked each side to take
steps to help build confidence in the peace process among Israeli
and Syrian people, both deeply distrustful of each other and, at
times, of U.S. intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa was told, for instance, to use Syria's extensive
influence over anti-Israeli Hezbollah guerillas, many of whom
operate out of southern Syria, to end attacks against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was told to restrain Israeli-backed militia forces in
southern Lebanon, where one such group lobbed mortar shells into a
school on Thursday, injuring 20 youngsters. The group claimed it
was responding to fire from anti-Israeli guerillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important for there to be a de-escalation and
maximum restraint by all sides,'' Albright said, ``to make sure
that the enemies of peace are not able to disrupt anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Syrian peace efforts are part of a larger puzzle
Clinton hopes to piece together before leaving office that also
entails settling Israel's long standing-conflict with the
Palestinians and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvigorating the Israeli-Syrian talks after nearly four years
of stalemate, Clinton said, was essential to moving the larger
peace train down the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing a new beginning in the effort to achieve a
comprehensive peace in the Middle East,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Syrian-Israeli negotiations off to a good start,
Israeli-Lebanese negotiations expected to begin soon, and the
Palestinian track well underway,'' Clinton said, ``we can truly set
our sights on a new and different Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat have commited to
agreeing, by mid-February, to a framework for hammering out their
remaining differences by October on such contentious issues as the
future of Jerusalem and the question of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   While those talks have bogged down in recent weeks over the
issue of Israeli troop withdrawals from the occupied West Bank,
Albright said Barak reiterated here this week his determination to
stick to the time-frame he and Arafat have agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli-Lebanon talks are not yet scheduled. The issues there,
though, closely mirror the land-for-peace formulation at the heart
of the Israeli-Syrian negotiations. That, combined with Syria's
dominant influence over Lebanon, lead most analysts to expect that
an Israeli-Lebanon accord could quickly fall into place following
the resolution of the much thornier Israeli-Syrian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the Israeli-Syrian negotiations would convene next
month in an ``isolated'' location, yet to be determined, near
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that the talks would follow the model Clinton set
a year ago when he brokered Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations
at the Wye River Plantation in rural Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main kind of needs that we have is that it be close enough
to Washington for the President to be able to come and go, as he
did for Wye,'' Albright said, ``and that the surroundings really be
conducive to hard work, and some informal discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Wye River talks lasted for nine days. Albright said
the administration would set no deadline on the duration of the
Israeli-Syrian round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not putting limits,'' she said. ``We're going to work to
the extent that people are getting serious things done.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
