</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth, Qwest join in deals worth more than $250 million
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth's April alliance with Qwest Communications
has thus far produced contracts worth more than $250 million, the
companies announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 27 contracts, like a big-ticket arrangement with the state
of Tennessee, call for the companies to provide high-speed data and
Internet services, as well as voice communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our alliance with Qwest is paying immediate dividends for our
customers and shareholders,'' said F. Duane Ackerman, BellSouth
chairman and chief executive officer, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for the two companies to provide a broadband
network serving the state government, the Board of Regents and the
University of Tennessee system.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth paid $3.5 billion for 10 percent of Denver-based
Qwest, which offers high-speed and long-distance services. The deal
with Qwest was hailed as a breakthrough for BellSouth. The company
has no long-distance capabilities outside its nine-state region and
is still legally prevented from offering long-distance within its
turf.
</P>
<P>
   While only a fraction of $24 billion-a-year BellSouth's size,
Qwest has assets that BellSouth lacks. The company has been
building an 18,500-mile national high-speed network. Qwest also
owns the nation's fourth-largest long-distance provider, LCI.
</P>
<P>
   Until BellSouth wins federal approval to enter long-distance,
its interest in a long-distance provider is limited to 10 percent.
In the fall, Qwest outmaneuvered Global Crossing to buy U S West, a
merger that has not been completed. When it is, BellSouth's stake
in Qwest will dip to 3.5 percent and BellSouth could again invest
until it reached the 10 percent ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has predicted an entry into long-distance in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the arrangement with Qwest permits BellSouth to
bid for contracts with large companies and organizations that might
otherwise seek a rival provider for all its telecommunication
needs.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and Qwest have bid on more than 250 other contracts,
the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The score card on the Qwest alliance comes one week after
BellSouth announced a complex arrangement that will boost its
European holdings. The widely praised deal calls for BellSouth to
eventually trade its interest in a German wireless company for a
much more valuable stake in Dutch-based KPN Telecom. Qwest has a
European joint venture with KPN.
</P>
