<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-EGYPTAIR-BOS &LR;      12-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPT ENVOY SEES ACCORD WITH US ON FLIGHT 990 PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The United States and Egyptian governments are not at
odds but have worked with ``absolutely amazing cooperation'' to
determine what caused the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990, the
Egyptian ambassador to the United States, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Nabil Fahmy would not discuss possible causes of the
Oct. 31 crash off Nantucket, including media speculation that an
Egyptian pilot sent the jetliner into its dive into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Globe reporters and editors, Fahmy said he is
hopeful that a cause can be determined, but cautioned it could take
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   He implied that much more work is needed to determine if a
mechanical problem or weather brought down the Cairo-bound Boeing
767, which took off from New York's John F. Kennedy International
Airport and went into the steep controlled dive 30 minutes later.
All 217 people aboard were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board has said investigators
have uncovered no sign of mechanical, weather or air traffic
control related problem that could have caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, salvage work is continuing with the Smit Pioneer,
a privately contracted ship, using a crane to haul up human remains
and aircraft parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can reach the point where it is not weather and not
mechanical, at that point we will still not be able to say if there
is evidence of a criminal act or not,'' said Fahmy, who became
ambassador to the US in October and was the individual who
requested the NTSB conduct an investigation into the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Fahmy, who has listened to the cockpit voice recorder tape, said
he was disappointed by leaks that resulted in incorrect and
incomplete information fueling faulty analyses of the crash.
Because of that, he said he would not comment on the tape or any
details of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was been good cooperation between the two
governments. ``This is not an Egyptian-American issue, it is a
human tragedy. . .there has been absolutely amazing cooperation and
no one has seen that or reported it. What we have seen is the
negative implications from leaks by officials.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has reported that officials familiar with the
investigation believe that co-pilot Gamil El Batouty may have
intentionally disconnected the plane's autopilot, and sent the
plane into its death dive when he was alone in the cockpit. When
Captain Ahmed El Habashi returned to the cockpit there is an
indication the two struggled over control of the plane, before the
engines were turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators want to recover the section below the cockpit to
determine if the metal rod connecting the control columns of the
pilot and co-pilot was sheared off, which would bolster the theory
that the two men battled for the lives of everyone on board. It
takes 50 pounds of pressure to shear the connecting rod.
</P>
<P>
   Fahmy said it will take ``evidence to convince both sides'' and
finding critical parts of the plane could provide ``evidence to
make an objective determination'' of the likely cause. Fahmy said
he did not have the technical knowledge to discuss how much of the
plane, if any, should be reconstructed as part of the investigative
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it was an Egyptian plane, we have a vested interest in
knowing the truth. Because there were Americans on board, the US
has a vested interest,'' he said. ``No one will hide the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
