<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-U.S.-2TAKES-NY     12-16 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-U.S.-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM FOR HYPER-SENSITIVE AMERICA FROM A GOOD FRIEND, CHIRAC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Britain)  (See also FRANCE-IRAQ) 
(DW) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Among allies, France has had for 50 years a unique
capacity to annoy Americans who may love French fries, French wine
_ and sometimes even the French themselves, at least in those rare
moments when they stop their constant hammering.
</P>
<P>
   Irritation at the French is running high now in Washington, so
President Jacques Chirac and other French officials are putting out
the word that it is time to apply a little Gallic charm to their
sensitive American friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not feel in any way irritated or annoyed at the United
States,'' Chirac said in a relaxed interview in French in the
Elysee Palace, a stone's throw from where the American ambassador
lives.
</P>
<P>
   But Chirac, 67 and in his fifth year as president, spoke out
critically on subjects ranging from the Senate's recent rejection
of a comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty, to the failure of
global trade talks in Seattle early this month, to plans for a new
European armed force early in the new century, which in his view
will by no means be an American century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes read that France wants a multipolar world so as to
take the United States down a notch, or create rivalries to
American power,'' he said. ``I talk about a multipolar world
because I think it's inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   China, India, Europe (as Chirac believes) and Russia (according
to Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine) will all be great powers in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   French criticism of American ebullience may seem as relentless
as Cartesian logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are moments when Americans get exasperated and think all
we're trying to do is create difficulties for them,'' Vedrine told
a group of American journalists here the other day, and those
moments have sometimes stretched on endlessly since the days of de
Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing irritates the French more than being dismissed as cranks
rather than accepted as helpful critics. Chirac in particular bends
over backward to assure Americans of his friendly predisposition,
proudly telling visitors that he has credentials as a soda jerk
from Howard Johnson from a student summer in Cambridge, Mass., and
has scores of American friends he considers family. So he feels
entitled to offer a little constructive criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been, of course, an observer of Congress for quite some
time,'' he said. ``To be perfectly frank, there used to be
prominent people you could telephone, ask about things, discuss,
consult, have a dialog with. Today it's more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, he observed, Congress did not seem as open to the
world as it once was _ ``Not the best attitude, given the
responsibilities the United States has in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly critical of this fall's Senate rejection of
the test ban treaty, a vote that threatens, in his words, ``to set
a bad example and start the arms proliferation race again.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision next year by the Clinton administration to build a
limited anti-missile defense against intercontinental rockets
launched by small states like North Korea, Iran or Iraq would
create more global strategic instability than it would eliminate,
Chirac believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at world history,'' he said, ``ever since men
began waging war, you will see that there's a permanent race
between sword and shield. The sword always wins. The more
improvements that are made to the shield, the more improvements are
made to the sword. We think that with these systems,'' he said,
referring to the possible United States anti-missile shield, ``we
are just going to spur swordmakers to intensify their efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China, which was already working harder than we realized on
both nuclear weapons and delivery vehicles for them, would of
course be encouraged to intensify those efforts, and it has the
resources to do so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``India would be encouraged to do the same thing, and it, too,
has the resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it would also increase tensions within NATO, which would
be too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat from North Korean missiles is sometimes mentioned
as well,'' Chirac said. ``Quite honestly, it isn't persuasive, but
I'm ready to talk about it. I could be wrong, but I'm not the only
one who thinks this way. But these are such important subjects that
they ought to be discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   American criticisms of the rapid deployment force Europe plans
to build for itself by 2003 as an attempt to torpedo the NATO
alliance, Chirac said, just about caused him to fall off his chair.
``The Americans kept saying Europe had to do more for its own
defense, so we finally said, all right, we will,'' he said. ``Now
you shouldn't criticize us for doing what you wanted us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   American ambassadors in European capitals made coordinated
approaches before the Europeans agreed on the details in Helsinki
earlier this month, asking in no uncertain terms for close
coordination with NATO and assurances that the European force would
strengthen the alliance and not weaken it, according to French and
American officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has to make a choice,'' Vedrine said. ``They
have always been for sharing the burden. They've never been much
for sharing the decision-making. Obviously, there are some real
questions we have to answer, such as how are we going to organize
this so as not to interfere with the Alliance. We are well aware
that it's complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac was even more reassuring. ``Very soon the Americans will
understand that this is not going to cause them any problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, it was not the French but Tony Blair, the
British prime minister, who at a European summit in Austria in late
October, 1998 first suggested a European armed force that could
intervene in crisis situations where the United States did not want
to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Britain and France, followed by other European allies,
formally proposed one, and all 15 European Union leaders endorsed a
60,000-strong force in Helsinki last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any feeling that President Clinton was upset by
it,'' Chirac said. ``If there was going to be a real problem, Tony
Blair would never have suggested it in the first place,'' Chirac
added. ``All this strengthens NATO, it doesn't in the least mean
any diminution of our commitment to the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac said he would not use Vedrine's word, ``hyperpower,'' to
describe the unique economic, military, and technological power of
the United States, perhaps because he knew it sent American
officials into overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chirac, a Gaullist conservative whose current term runs
out in 2002, said he understood the foreign minister, a Socialist
who came into office in 1997 when Chirac called a parliamentary
election he mistakenly thought the conservatives were going to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``In French, `hyper' is a word kids like to use,'' like
``super,'' Chirac explained. ``When Vedrine said that America was a
hyperpower there was nothing pejorative about it.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that the awkward power-sharing arrangement of
the past two years between his Gaullists and Vedrine's Socialists
had actually given France an advantage in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really do speak with one voice,'' he said. ``At
international gatherings I'm probably the only one who can truly
say that he speaks in the name of all of his country's people.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac and the Socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin, along
with the rest of the European Union, have said ``no'' to imports of
American beef treated with hormones, despite American assurances
that it was safe. The World Trade Organization authorized the
United States earlier this year to retaliate by imposing high
tariffs on European delicacies and luxury goods to retaliate
against the beef ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been through some big traumas in France, in particular
with blood contaminated with the AIDS virus,'' Chirac said, ``so
you have to understand that these things are highly sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people died in France after contracting AIDS in the
mid-1980s from transfusions of blood. Some French health officials
were later convicted of allowing the blood to be used even though
they knew it might not be free of the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five or six hormones in hormone-treated beef, and of
those, one is officially recognized by the highest scientific
authorities as being carcinogenic,'' Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have disputed such assertions, but, Chirac
said, ``You can't make us eat something we don't want to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for British beef, which France is refusing to
import any even though the European Union recently decided that it
was now free of ``mad cow disease,'' a neurological disorder in
cattle that may be communicable to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac has called for an international world scientific body to
resolve such disputes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac and other officials say they are not trying to cause
trouble for their powerful ally across the sea. Both Chirac and
Vedrine, for example, both charitably refrained from describing the
collapse of the trade talks in Seattle early this month as an
American failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an American failure, not a European failure, not a
failure of the developing countries,'' Chirac said. ``It will work
out next time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0276 </DOCNO>
