<HEADER>
A1228 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-INTEL-PLANT-BOS &LR;      12-16 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL TO INVEST $800 MILLION IN BAY STATE CHIP PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp. said Thursday it will spend $800 million over the
next two years to overhaul its chip plant in Hudson, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade will mean an additional 450 jobs at the factory,
which already employs about 1,200 workers. The move also indicates
that the world's largest chip maker is making a long-term
commitment to manufacturing processors at a Bay State plant once
owned by a bitter rival.
</P>
<P>
   Intel acquired the Hudson chip plant, or ``fab,'' as part of a
deal with Digital Equipment Corp. to settle a legal dispute between
the two firms. Digital was later acquired by Houston-based Compaq
Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Digital had built the Hudson plant to manufacture its advanced
Alpha microprocessor chips. As part of the settlement, Intel
continues to make Alpha chips at the fab under contract to Compaq,
which now owns the Alpha design. Another part of the settlement
gave Intel ownership of StrongARM, a Digital chip designed for use
in lightweight, low-powered devices such as palm-sized computers
and cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Digital had never used the Hudson fab to its full capacity, and
neither has Intel, up to now. And by today's standards, the chip
making processes at the Hudson plant are nearly obsolete. ``It's
still running basically the same . . . process technology that it
was when they got it from Digital,'' said Linley Gwennap, editorial
director of Microprocessor Report, a leading industry journal.
``It's way old.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's commitment to upgrade the plant is related to the
company's new plan to become a leading maker of chips for computer
networking devices. Earlier this year, Intel acquired Level One, a
California firm that uses StrongARM-based processors designed to
control networking devices, such as routers that direct information
to various points of the Internet. Intel will now offer such a
processor, and build it at the Hudson fab, along with other
StrongARM processors and a variety of networking chips.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Intel will add new chip making technologies to
the Hudson plant, to make it consistent with the company's other
chip factories. ``The fab will essentially be 100 percent an Intel
process,'' said Ann Hurd, a spokeswoman for the Santa Clara, Calif.
company.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the cost of the overhaul will be defrayed by tax breaks
from the Massachusetts Office of Business Development and the city
of Hudson. The town agreed to a tax-increment financing deal that
will limit increases in Intel's property tax assessment. For its
part, the state is providing a 5 percent investment tax credit over
the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It signals that Massachusetts welcomes these large
investments,'' said state business development director Dean Serpa.
``It dispels the perception that Massachusetts is a high-tax state
for developers.''
</P>
<P>
   Work on the fab will begin next month and should be completed in
2002. Little construction on the building will be needed. Indeed,
much of the project will involve the purchase and installation of
the complex machines used to make microchips. These machines cost
between $1 million and $3 million each, must be ordered months in
advance, and must undergo a complex cleaning process before being
installed in the ultraclean rooms where the chips are made.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's stock rose 1 5/16, to 80 1/4, in trading on the Nasdaq
Stock Market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TEXACO-OPERA-ART-3TAK     12-16 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXACO-OPERA-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXACO'S SATURDAY AFTERNOONS AT THE MET: 60 YEARS AND COUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, the 3rdtake is a listing of operas through April.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Opera has long been saddled with the perception that
it is a pricey art form for elitist audiences. This is not quite
fair. After all, decent seats for a Knicks game at Madison Square
Garden are comparably expensive, and more difficult to obtain than
decent seats for the opera.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to make the elitism charge stick when for 60 years
the Saturday matinees of the Metropolitan Opera have been broadcast
live across the United States and Canada, sponsored by Texaco.
``The Texaco-Metropolitan Opera International Radio Broadcasts,''
as the series is officially called, represents the longest
continuous commercial sponsorship in broadcast history. (Met
performances were first heard on radio nine years earlier.) The
broadcasts have also been carried live in Europe since 1990.
Australia, New Zealand and Hong Kong were added later, and this
year the network was extended to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's broadcast, beginning at 12:30 p.m., offers the new
Met production of Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde'' with the latest
contenders to the daunting title roles, the tenor Ben Heppner and
the soprano Jane Eaglen. James Levine conducts. As usual, the
performance will be carried complete (meaning, in this case, more
than five hours) and without commercial interruption, although the
Texaco name is repeatedly tucked into the commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The first intermission feature offers a Singers' Roundtable with
two sopranos, Birgit Nilsson, a great Met Isolde of the past, and
the beloved Eileen Farrell, in conversation with the conductor and
critic Will Crutchfield. The second intermission will be, of
course, the Texaco Opera Quiz, a popular component of the
broadcasts since it first appeared in 1940 as Opera Question Forum.
Thousands of listeners send in questions every year, hoping to
stump the panel and, especially, to provoke some informative and
amusing banter, which is the real purpose of the quiz.
</P>
<P>
   When the current radio season ends on April 22 with Wagner's
``Gotterdammerung,'' Texaco will have sponsored the broadcasts of
1,192 live performances of 142 operas. It is estimated that 10
million listeners tune in each season. What other art form has been
made so available to so many people for so long?
</P>
<P>
   Betty Allen, a former mezzo-soprano who is now president emerita
of the Harlem School of the Arts, first listened to the broadcasts
as a girl in Campbell, Ohio, a suburb of Youngstown. Hers was one
of the few black families in the working-class neighborhood. ``The
families on my street were mostly Sicilian and Greek,'' she said.
``On Saturday, walking down the street, you could hear the Met
broadcasts coming from the windows of everybody's house. No one
told them that opera and the arts were not for them, not for poor
people, just for rich snobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The composer John Harbison, whose opera ``The Great Gatsby''
will receive its world premiere at the Met on Monday night, was
reared in a cultured household: His father was a history professor
at Princeton University and an amateur musician. Harbison needed
little encouragement to listen to the Met broadcasts, which he
started doing faithfully when he was 8.
</P>
<P>
   He even subscribed to Opera News, the magazine of the
Metropolitan Opera Guild, which offers guides to the broadcasts. He
was mortified when one day during intermission the announcer cited
``Little Johnny Harbison,'' then 9, as ``the youngest official
member of the guild.'' Now, more than 50 years later, Harbison's
new opera will be broadcast on the afternoon of Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Countless other musicians, singers and opera buffs, especially
those who grew up in regions of the country not convenient to
professional opera companies, have emphasized the importance of
listening to the broadcasts as youngsters. In a new biography of
the tenor Jon Vickers, Jeannie Williams reports that young Jon and
his siblings usually spent Saturday afternoons at home in Prince
Albert, Ontario, scrubbing and polishing the floors under the
watchful eye of their mother, a fastidious housekeeper. As they
worked, they listened to the Met broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   This was in the late 1930s, before Texaco's sponsorship began.
One broadcast in particular was unforgettable to Vickers: On Feb.
26, 1938, the tenor Giovanni Martinelli, who was singing Radames in
Verdi's ``Aida,'' collapsed halfway through the ``Celeste Aida''
aria and had to be replaced with Frederick Jagel. As he mopped the
floors that season, Ms. Williams relates, Vickers would have heard
Lauritz Melchior as Siegmund and Parsifal and Martinelli as Otello,
roles that would become central to his own career.
</P>
<P>
   My childhood experience with the broadcasts was fairly typical
for an American baby-boomer. My parents, though not at all musical,
encouraged me to study piano and gave me spending money for
classical records. I found my own way to the Met broadcasts.
Sometimes, in a sort of role reversal, I would listen on the
crackly kitchen radio and try to interest my mother. More often
than not I took my portable radio into the hallway, where the
reception was best, and listened alone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I loved hearing the plot summaries read by the avuncular Milton
Cross, the announcer for more than 40 years, until his death in
1975, when Peter Allen took over. The stories were too convoluted
to follow, and I essentially had no idea what the operas were
about. I didn't care. The singing hooked me. Hearing the ovations
and bravos of the audience was almost my favorite part. It made me
want to understand why everyone got so excited.
</P>
<P>
   The first Met broadcast was of Humperdinck's ``Hansel and
Gretel'' on Christmas Day 1931. It was instigated not by the opera
company's desire to spread the gospel but by its financial
troubles. The Depression had brought the Met's first budget
deficits, the company archivist Robert Tuggle reports. So when NBC
offered $120,000 for the right to broadcast the season in 1931, the
Met jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hansel'' was the only complete opera on the air that season.
The other broadcasts offered excerpts from the performances. But
the listeners' response was so enthusiastic that complete opera
broadcasts began the next season. At first there was a changing
roster of sponsors. During the 1938-39 and 1939-40 seasons, there
were no sponsors at all. Extinction seemed imminent.
</P>
<P>
   James Kinnear, formerly the president and chief executive of
Texaco and now the Met's board chairman, said the oil company was
well positioned to come to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texaco was the only company that since 1928 was doing business
in all 48 states,'' he said recently. ``So when this opportunity
was brought to the chairman at the time, W.S.S. Rodgers, he felt
that as a truly national marketer, Texaco was the ideal sponsor for
these nationwide broadcasts.''
</P>
<P>
   That first Texaco broadcast came on Dec. 7, 1940, a performance
of Mozart's ``Nozze di Figaro'' with Licia Albanese, Elisabeth
Rethberg, Ezio Pinza, Salvatore Baccaloni and other great singers,
conducted by Ettore Panizza.
</P>
<P>
   Given the shifts of direction and changes of leadership that
routinely occur in major corporations, the longevity of Texaco's
commitment is striking. Kinnear said that in his 45 years with the
company he never once heard serious discussion of eliminating the
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about hard-sell product advertising,'' he said.
``This does much good for the company's corporate image and much
good for listeners. I can't remember a single annual meeting with
shareholders, who often show up ready to give you a hard time, when
somebody didn't say, `Thank you for the Texaco opera,' and then
everyone would stand and applaud.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bijur, Texaco's current chairman and chief executive, said
the company's total support of the Met over the years was
approaching $200 million, which includes, in addition to the
Saturday radio broadcasts, the lead sponsorship of about 80
television broadcasts on PBS since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sponsoring the Met has become part of our corporate DNA,'' he
said. ``It creates tremendous goodwill for us. You should see the
letters we get thanking us.'' Thousands arrive each year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Various stations in the network have not been so steadfast in
their commitment. Some managers grumble about having to set aside
some 20 Saturday afternoons each season for opera. The most recent
dropout was WCRB-FM in the Boston suburb of Waltham, the largest
commercial classical music station in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Campbell, the chief executive of Charles River
Broadcasting, the station's parent company, decided to drop the
broadcasts, citing the rigidity of the format (he wanted to use his
own announcers, for example) and the loss in potential revenue from
commercials. Texaco negotiates a fee it pays to each station for
broadcasting the series.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell received ``hate mail and threatening letters'' from
devoted opera fans, he said recently. WHRB, the scrappy, committed
student station at Harvard University, stepped into the void,
although its lower wattage will leave some patches of the region
unserved. The Met's network of 325 commercial and noncommercial
stations reaches about 95 percent of the population in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell revealed his hand when he was quoted as saying in a
recent article in The New York Times that opera was a hard sell for
many radio listeners. ``The popular operas are fine,'' he said,
``like `La Traviata' and `La Boheme.''' But ``then along comes a
five-hour Wagner feature, and I've got to tell you, that is an
acquired taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, listeners will never acquire the taste if they don't
get a chance to hear those five-hour Wagner operas, like the one
scheduled for Saturday. The radio legacy of ``Tristan und Isolde''
alone is illustrious. From 1932 to 1950, Melchior sang 20 radio
performances as Tristan, the most by one singer in a single role.
</P>
<P>
   The Met has long planned its schedule so that radio audiences
can hear as much of a season's offerings as possible. The staples
have come regularly. But so have unusual works like Verdi's
``Stiffelio,'' Poulenc's ``Mamelles des Tiresias,'' Schoenberg's
``Erwartung'' and ``Moses und Aron,'' and Barber's ``Vanessa.''
</P>
<P>
   Audience surveys as well as mail suggest that listeners love the
intermission features. Everyone has a favorite recollection. I
remember _ I must have been about 12 _ being entranced as the
conductor and opera expert Boris Goldovsky traced the use of the
``Scarpia chords'' in Puccini's ``Tosca'' in one of his inimitable
lectures from the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the legendary Singers' Roundtable in 1970 with
Dame Joan Sutherland, Marilyn Horne and Martina Arroyo. At one
point the question posed was: Are there any roles that would have
suited you vocally but that you chose not to sing for other
reasons? Ms. Arroyo, who was not a small woman, answered, in one of
the great Freudian slips of all time, ``Yes, Madama Butterball.''
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable almost came to a complete halt because Ms. Horne
could not stop laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The actor Tony Randall, an informed opera buff, made his debut
as a panelist on the Opera Quiz in 1967. Appearing shortly
afterward on the ``Tonight'' show, he told Johnny Carson that he
was used to being stopped on the street in New York now and then by
well-wishers, but that such encounters had increased after his
debut on the Met broadcasts. Everywhere he went, it seemed, people
were shouting at him, ``You were great on the Opera Quiz!''
</P>
<P>
   Carson, seeming a bit nonplussed, admitted that he had never
heard of it. So the Met broadcasts may not be reaching everyone.
But they are hardly elitist.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
