<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-LEBANON-ART-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 15 CHILDREN WOUNDED BY SHELLING IN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-TALKS ,  MIDEAST-ASSESS, MIDEAST-WESTBANK) 
(ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ At least 15 Lebanese schoolchildren were reported
wounded Thursday, some seriously, when Israeli-allied militia
forces fired rockets at a village Israel says is a base for
Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   In an indirect acknowledgement of responsibility, the Israel
Defense Forces called the attack ``a mistake'' and said it
``expresses regret at the injuries to civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the children were wounded while playing in the
schoolyard in the village of Arab Salim, while others were hit
inside the school building, according to teachers and other
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting in the classroom, and all of a sudden a shell
landed,'' said one young girl interviewed in a television report
from the southern Lebanese village Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's talks with Syrian peace negotiators in
Washington, Israeli state television reported, Israeli officials
voiced distress at what they said was the accidental shelling of
the primary school by militia fighters of the South Lebanon Army.
Though nominally autonomous, the Israeli-equipped South Lebanon
Army fights in tandem with Israeli troops in the southern Lebanese
border zone that Israel has occupied since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   David Levy, Israel's foreign minister, told an Israeli
television interviewer in Washington that the Syrians were
concerned about an escalation of the southern Lebanon conflict.
``It is clear to them that if the fighting continues in Lebanon, it
will damage everything that we are doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, Lebanon's president, Emile Lahoud, issued a statement
saying he ``condemns the crime and places the responsibility for it
on Israel and those who are collaborating with Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The village of Arab Salim is north of the Israeli-controlled
border zone in an area partly controlled by the insurgent
Hezbollah, or Party of God, which has been backed in the past by
both Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Ephraim Sneh, Israel's deputy defense minister, put the blame
for Thursday's incident on Hezbollah, which he said has been
staging artillery attacks from residential areas. ``When we react,
something like this is likely to occur, sad though it may be,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army said in its brief official statement that the
South Lebanon Army had returned artillery fire ``toward the source
of terrorist fire'' near the village of Arab Selim, and had
unintentionally hit populated areas. ``Firing from populated areas
endangers residents, as it requires a response against the source
of the fire,'' the statement said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The army did not provide its own information about the
casualties and made no specific mention of the schoolchildren. Its
statement did say, however, that three local Lebanese women had
been wounded recently by Hezbollah artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing retaliation for the school shelling, residents of
Israeli border areas prepared Thursday for a possible evacuation to
bomb shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and South Lebanon Army forces have had intensive
firefights with Hezbollah units for the last two days, an
escalation that some commentators here interpreted as a signal that
Hezbollah is no longer beholden to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said it plans to withdraw from southern Lebanon next
year, either unilaterally or through a negotiated agreement with
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, who is concluding
his first round of peace talks with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel in Washington Thursday, plans to stop in Beirut on his way
back to Damascus to discuss the negotiations with Lebanese
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
