<SLUG> BC-TIMBER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific's Timber Co. completes sale of California tracts
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The timber unit of Georgia-Pacific Corp. has finished
selling off land that doesn't fit the company's focus.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. said Thursday it completed the previously announced
sale of 194,000 acres in California to Hawthorne Timber Co. for
$397 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1998, Atlanta-based Timber Co. has been selling
forests in Maine, West Virginia and New Brunswick, Canada, to
streamline its business and boost profit.
</P>
<P>
   Trees in Maine and New Brunswick, for example, were
slow-growing. The California timberlands included redwood trees
that were too specialized, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has sold 1 million acres, or about 20 percent of its
land base, as part of the repositioning. Timber Co.'s remaining 4.8
million acres, mostly fast-growing Southern pine trees, represent
some of the most productive forest land in the world, said Don
Glass, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we're positioned now, we'll double our harvest over
the next 30 years in the South,'' Glass said. Through increased use
of farming techniques and technology, foresters can map and manage
trees down to 10-acre plots _ making them substantially more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trees we put in the ground today are twice as productive
as trees 30 years ago,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. harvested 14.6 million tons of timber in 1998, of
which 11.9 million tons were sold to Georgia-Pacific Group. Timber
Co. is the largest independent seller of logs in the country, Glass
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it has finished its major land sales, Timber Co.
will continue to buy, sell and trade small land parcels, Glass
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company plans to step up its ongoing share repurchase
program. Timber Co. has repurchased nearly 11 million shares, or 12
percent of outstanding shares, since Georgia-Pacific made the
company a separate stock in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. closed Thursday at $24.06 1/4, down 81 1/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
