<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TESTIFIES SHE DIDN'T CONSENT TO TAPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. _ Monica S. Lewinsky exacted some payback
Thursday as she provided damaging testimony against her former
friend, Linda R. Tripp, in a wiretapping case stemming from Tripp's
betrayal of Lewinsky's secret affair with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, testifying publicly for the first time since the
scandal, told a packed courtroom she reacted with horror when she
discovered last January that Tripp had circulated secret recordings
of Lewinsky confiding her sexual affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As a Maryland prosecutor showed her a copy of a Newsweek
magazine containing transcripts of the Tripp tapes, Lewinsky said,
``It terrified me because I was concerned about the privacy of my
relationship being revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   The former White House intern added, ``I was pretty upset. That
was frightening to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, who has made no secret of her disdain for Tripp,
interrupted her current pursuit _ an entrepreneurial foray into the
handbag industry _ to help prosecutors press two counts of illegal
wiretapping against her former confidante.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing dark glasses and a black pants suit, Lewinsky
sidestepped a swarm of journalists as she rushed in and out of the
Howard County Circuit Court through a rear door, guarding what
little remains of the private life she once led as a White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who did not attend the hearing, faces up to 10 years in
prison and $20,000 in fines if she is convicted on the two charges.
Tripp has described the case against her as ``unfair and
vindictive,'' the work of Clinton allies who want to ``destroy''
her.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's tapes, which she also gave to former independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr, became the key evidence in the impeachment saga.
The case ended with Clinton's acquittal in the first Senate trial
of a president in 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky appeared generally unflustered in 90 minutes on the
witness stand as she provided a linchpin for the prosecution's case
by repeatedly testifying that she did not give Tripp consent to
tape her conversations. Maryland law prohibits taping a
conversation without the permission of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Seated beneath crystal chandeliers in the court, in suburban
Baltimore, Lewinsky insisted under cross-examination, ``I had not
consented'' to the taping.
</P>
<P>
   She addressed another pivotal point for the prosecution by
testifying that she relied only on her memory to identify the date
that the tapes in question were recorded: Dec. 22, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors must prove in the pretrial hearing that they did not
use any information that was protected under Tripp's immunity
agreement with Starr in building their case, including Tripp's
grand jury testimony about the date the tape was recorded.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewinsky was Challenged by Tripp's lawyer, Joseph Murtha,
about her recollection of the date, she said, ``It was etched in my
mind because it was a pretty frightening time for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was not asked about her relationship with Clinton or
her feelings toward Tripp, though Murtha indicated he will try to
portray Lewinsky as a biased witness when the full trial begins
next month.
</P>
<P>
   After Lewinsky's testimony, Murtha cited a passage from the
book, ``Monica's Story,'' written by Andrew Morton with Lewinsky's
cooperation. The book describes Lewinsky and her family
experiencing ``unalloyed pleasure'' when they learned Tripp was
under investigation in the taping episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in our family wants Linda Tripp to lie awake at night
worrying about going to jail,'' the book quotes Lewinsky as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her apparent hostility toward Tripp, Lewinsky
occasionally joked with Tripp's lawyers. At one point, she
playfully scolded Murtha for misstating her birth date, saying,
``Nope, nope, nope.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor, Stephen Montanarelli, said he was ``very
pleased'' with Lewinsky's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha told reporters Lewinsky was in an ``unenviable
situation,'' having to endure the latest twist in the scandal.
``But at the same time,'' Murtha said, ``this situation is of her
own making and I am here to defend my client.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Diane O. Leasure, is expected to rule as early as
Friday on which evidence can be used in the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
