<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1243 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-NBC-COVERAGE-COX     12-16 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NBC-COVERAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBC puts Games on cable networks
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC-TV will break new ground at the 2000 Sydney Olympics by
offering 172 hours of original coverage on its cable networks CNBC
and MSNBC, it was announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the Summer Games will be shown on basic
cable, starting a trend that will continue through the 2008
Olympics. All coverage will be taped.
</P>
<P>
   Pat O'Brien of ``Access Hollywood'' and HBO's Jim Lampley will
host the Sydney coverage on CNBC and MSNBC, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leaped at the chance to be a part of history. This is an
unbelievable project,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entire soccer and basketball games will be shown,'' Lampley
said. ``People can choose to see certain events that might not have
been readily available.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable coverage will begin on MSNBC, two days before the
opening ceremony, with men's soccer on Sept. 13, followed the next
day by the opener of the U.S. women's soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC will air the Sydney Games from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. (Eastern)
on weekdays, repeating each telecast at midnight for an additional
101 hours of coverage. Its weekend hours were not released.
</P>
<P>
   The CNBC telecasts will be 5-9 p.m. on weekdays and 4-9 p.m. on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 finals will be shown on cable, including boxing,
soccer, tennis, equestrian, water polo, baseball and weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC did a great job in Atlanta, but the criticism was not what
we did, but what was left out,'' said NBC Olympics co-chairman
Dennis Swanson. ``There is some overlap with the network coverage,
but the important thing is that the American public will be able to
see more of the Olympics than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time the Summer Games have been televised beyond ``free
TV'' was at Barcelona in 1992, when NBC tried a disastrous
experiment with pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not anything like that,'' said Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC is available in 71 million homes, including nearly all of
metro Atlanta. MSNBC, limited in metro Atlanta, is available in 51
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
