<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-PARODY-1STLD-WRI     12-16 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PARODY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS OPEN 'GORE STORE,' 'BRADLEY BOUTIQUE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 5thgraf, Al Gore, to add dropped word in quote. Pickup:
Copies of.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Poking fun at Democratic presidential hopefuls Al
Gore and Bill Bradley, the Republican Party on Thursday opened the
``Gore Store'' and ``Bradley Boutique'' for holiday shoppers with a
taste for political sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   The stores offered such items as the ``I Invented the Internet''
mousepad for $15, which mocked Gore's retracted claim than he
invented the World Wide Web, and $15 ``Alpha Male'' baseball caps
that allude to the hiring of a feminist writer by the Gore campaign
to help the vice president appear more masculine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is your chance to grab that last-minute stocking stuffer
or gift for those hard-to-buy-for friends and relatives,'' said Jim
Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee. The party
said proceeds from the one-day sale, which was held at the
committee's headquarters near the U.S. Capitol, will be donated to
the United Way.
</P>
<P>
   Other items for sale at the so-called ``Gore Store'' were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Al Gore business cards at $5 for a pack of 50. The cards make
fun of what Republicans say is the Gore penchant for inflating his
resume. Among the jobs listed on the cards, which bear the quote,
``You name it, I've done it,'' were tobacco farmer, homebuilder,
inspirer of the book ``Love Story,'' and Internet inventor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Copies of Gore's book on the environment, ``Earth in the
Balance'' for $10. The book _ which many Republicans consider
alarmist _ comes with a candle, which would be used to read the
book and to save electricity.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $20 computer from the 1980s, before the Internet was broadly
available for use.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Bradley Boutique'' offered only one product: A Bill
Bradley Speech Survival Kit. Making fun of what even Bradley admits
are his less than scintillating speaking skills, the $10 kit
includes a coffee mug with a picture of the candidate on it, along
with a bag of high-caffeine coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're listening to a Bradley stump speech, this gift could
be the difference between you and an hour-long nap,'' said
Nicholson, who wore a red Santa hat.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the rush of Republican holiday shoppers at the
store, the most popular item was the mousepad, which has a picture
of Gore next to a computer saying, ``I invented the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just such a ridiculous statement,'' said Mike Newman, a
political consultant in Washington. ``I laugh every time I think of
him saying that, so now I have it next to my computer, which I
think Gore invented as well.''
</P>
<P>
   With about half of the merchandise sold, Nicholson announced
that the RNC had achieved its goal of raising $353, the amount Gore
reported giving to charity on his 1997 tax return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit it wasn't the hardest goal to reach, but it took Al
Gore a whole year to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the Gore campaign could be reached for comment on the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   A Bradley campaign official called the Republican event
``silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a perfect contrast between the Republicans and
Bill Bradley,'' said Bradley spokesman Tony Wyche. ``While they're
selling gimmicks, Bill was talking how to get special interests out
of the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
