<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1251 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-ANALYSIS-BOS     12-16 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW VOTERS FACED WITH GRIM MESSAGE FROM CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The grim reports of more than 100 dead Russian soldiers
sprawled on the streets of Chechnya's capital Grozny have cast a
dark shadow over what has until now been portrayed by Moscow as a
relatively easy military campaign against separatist fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel ambush of a Russian armored column late Wednesday _
just days before Sunday's national election _ sent the message that
if Moscow is going to achieve its stated goal of wiping out the
Chechen insurgents, it will have to pay a heavy price in the lives
of its soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a message the Kremlin does not want voters to hear on
the eve of the vote _ especially now that the pro-government Unity
bloc has ridden the apparent success of the war to second place in
most popularity polls.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, most Russian voters did not hear it. Senior
officials dismissed first-hand accounts of the massacre by
correspondents working for Western news agencies in Grozny.
Official Russian media carried denials the battle took place,
denials of the high casualties, and statements blaming the reports
of the ambush on a conspiracy of foreign powers to try to discredit
the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction underscored the importance of Moscow's
``anti-terrorist operation'' in Chechnya to the Kremlin's domestic
political strategy, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you analyze the Chechen war as an anti-terrorist operation,
it makes no sense,'' said Alexander Zhilin, military analyst for
the weekly Moscow News. ``But if you analyze it from the point of
view of domestic politics, it makes perfect sense. The point is to
get Kremlin allies elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhilin and other military experts questioned the rationale
behind sending Russian troops into Grozny, where up to 7,000 rebel
fighters, hardened by their experience in fighting Moscow to a
humiliating stalemate in a 1994-1996 war, are dug in and waiting
for a battle.
</P>
<P>
   Zhilin said it would be more logical for the larger, more
powerful Russian force, which surrounded Grozny last month, to keep
up pressure on the rebels by just maintaining its seige of the
capital. But he said that the generals had been under pressure to
take Grozny in time to give a victory for the war's architect anKremlin's presidential hopeful, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin,
that could be parlayed into votes for the Unity coalition he has
actively backed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was done to take Grozny on the eve of elections,''
Zhilin said. ``But this could mean that the army will suffer great
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   General Valery Manilov, deputy chief of Russia's general staff,
denied that the army had tried to capture Grozny, and dismissed the
reports of fighting as ``planned disinformation.'' The military
said only two soldiers had died in Wednesday's fighting in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Federal Security Service, post-Communist
successor to the KGB, went further. Reflecting Russian anger over
Western criticism about Chechnya, the spokesman suggested that the
whole ambush story was an anti-Russian plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``With just a couple of days to go to the election, it is very
important, considering the position some Western countries have
taken with regard to Russia ... to present our military as being
incapable of effective action,'' said the spokesman, Alexander
Zdanovich.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, an Associated Press reporter described counting the
bodies of at least 115 Russian soldiers as they lay next to the
burned-out hulks of seven Russian tanks and other armored vehicles
in a Grozny square. On Wednesday night, Reuters reporter Maria
Eismont, a veteran Russian war correspondent, described nearly the
same scene and said she counted more than 100 Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Both reports described hundreds of Chechen fighters firing
rocket-propelled grenades and machine guns at a column of about 15
armored vehicles that had somehow wandered from the eastern
outskirts Russian troops control to the vast Minutka square, just
south of the city center.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts conjured grim images of the disastrous attempts to
storm Grozny at the beginning of the 1994-1996 war, when poorly
trained draftees sent into the city in an ill-conceived tank
assault were cut down by rebels firing hand-held anti-tank weapons.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Russian officials have worked hard to prevent
people from making parallels to the last conflict. Now, Moscow
severely restricts access to the combat zone. Instead, a government
press center presents journalists with daily briefings that detail
the successes of the Russian tactics. Few journalists have been
able to get into Grozny. No footage of Wednesday's attack was
available.
</P>
<P>
   While controlling information about the fighting, Kremlin allies
have made little secret of the political backdrop of the war in
Chechnya. Ostensibly started in response to attacks by Chechen-led
Islamic rebels on neighboring Dagestan and a wave of deadly
apartment bombings last summer Moscow blames on the rebels, the war
has been portrayed by some politicians as a rallying cry for a
nation that has suffered nothing but setbacks and humilitation
since the 1991 Soviet breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not Chechnya,'' said Anatoly Chubais, a leader of
a bloc of economic liberals which has formed a coalition with the
pro-Kremlin Unity bloc. ``What is being decided in Chechya is a far
more important issue _ the revival of the Russian army.''
</P>
<P>
   This euphoria has carried over to much of the Russian press,
which was highly critical of the last war. The Russian military's
march across Chechnya so far has faced limited resistance from the
outgunned militants, who have repeatedly retreated rather than wage
full-scale ground battles.
</P>
<P>
   Even though some analysts say the Russian advance through
Chechnya has gone slowly, and at a high cost _ Moscow admits losing
over 400 soldiers in the fighting _ the Russian media have given
the army its backing.
</P>
<P>
   Few Russian journalists actually make it to Chechnya, partly in
response to a wave of kidnappings in the region that targeted
correspondents. Many of the reports from Chechnya depict
competent-looking and motivated troops and their successes. There
have certainly been some of those, but the reports ignore the
setbacks, and the grimy, scrawny draftees who are once again
involved in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, wounded soldiers in a military hospital pleaded with
two American reporters to tell the truth about their units, which
they described as poorly equipped and poorly led. Last week,
soldiers on the outskirts of Grozny described a costly ambush of
Russian troops in the suburbs of the capital that went unreported
in the Russian press.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no willingness of the main news media to get this info
to the people,'' said Alan Rousso, director of the Carnegie Moscow
Center. ``This reflects an unwilingness of the people to hear the
real story. People like the story their getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who criticizes the military has been branded an enemy of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Moscow's Mayor Yury Luzhkov, leader of a centrist bloc
competing with Unity for votes in Sunday's election, raised
concerns about the Russian tactics in Chechnya, particularly
heaving bombing of areas populated by civilians. When Luzhkov's
ally, former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, repeated these
concerns, Kremlin-controlled television stations accused the two of
being in the employ of foreign powers which are plotting to weaken
Russia's influence in the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in Chechnya, Russian forces shelled Grozny through the
night and into this morning, even though many of the estimated
10,000 to 45,000 civilians in the city remained trapped in their
makeshift basement bunkers, unable to reach safe corridors set up
with much fanfare by Unity's leading candidate, Emergency Minister
Sergei Shoigu.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe the tanks that were trapped in Grozny were
part of a reconaissance mission gone badly awry, and not an attempt
to storm the city. Alexander Golts of the news magazine Itogi said
that the unit probably was scouting out Chechen defenses in
preparation for an all-out attack and, encountering no resistance,
kept going until it reached the city center.
</P>
<P>
   Few analysts believe that the rebels, despite their success
Wednesday, can hold Grozny. But the Russian mission, as originally
defined, was not intended to include an assault on the capital.
</P>
<P>
   When Russian forces entered Chechya, officials said they
intended to set up a security zone around the region and destroy
terrorist bases. Then they changed that to a security zone that cut
half-way through Chechnya. Now, with elections approaching, the
goal has changed to occupying as much of the region as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is for the ruling party to stay in power, and the
strategy has been to show successs, success, success,'' Zhilin
said. ``This false victory, when the Russian troops raise flags
over every Chechen town, is near. But then we will see the
beginning of the real war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NICOTINE-VACCINE-BOS &LR;      12-16 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICOTINE-VACCINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENTAL VACCINE SAID TO BLOCK CRAVING FOR NICOTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists say they have devised a vaccine that blocks nicotine
from entering the brain, raising the prospect of a novel way to
help smokers quit.
</P>
<P>
   The experimental vaccine has been tested so far only in
laboratory rats, but a government-sponsored study shows it reduced
the amount of nicotine entering the animals' brains by almost
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant, scientists say, the vaccine blocked nicotine's
effect in raising blood pressure and it prevented hyperactive
behavior that researchers see when they inject the animals with
nicotine, the addictive ingredient in tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that ``vaccinated persons would not be able to get
a `kick' from the nicotine in tobacco smoke or chewing tobacco,''
Dr. Alan I. Leshner, director of the National Institute on Drug
Abuse, which funded the research, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Human trials of the vaccine are planned within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials hope nicotine immunization will be
among the first of several vaccines against addiction. Also in
early stages are vaccines against cocaine, methamphetamine, and
PCP, an anesthetic drug called phencycladine that is often abused.
Leshner said the cocaine vaccine is closest to human trials.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of an anti-nicotine vaccine, Leshner said, is
``tremendous'' because smoking remains ``one of the biggest public
health problems in this country, and we need to have as many
treatment approaches as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Although overall smoking rates have declined, an estimated 60
million Americans still smoke cigarettes, according to the drug
abuse institute. Among adults between the ages of 18 and 25, the
smoking rate has steadily crept upward in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional vaccines are designed to stimulate the production of
antibodies against infectious organisms, such as polio or hepatitis
virus. The idea of immunizing against addictive substances
represents ``a very new and different use for a vaccine,'' said Dr.
Paul Pentel of Hennepin County Medical Center in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Pentel is a coauthor of the new study on a nicotine vaccine,
which appears in the journal Pharmacology, Biochemistry and
Behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Although nicotine, like a virus, is foreign to the body, it is
too small a molecule to be recognized by the immune system, Pentel
said. To make a vaccine, researchers at a Florida-based company
called Nabi Pharmaceuticals attached nicotine to a protein derived
from the outer coat of a bacterium. That enabled the immune system
to make antibodies to the nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers later injected regular nicotine into the lab
rats, the vaccine-induced antibodies attached to it and prevented
it from passing into the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine has so far produced no obvious harmful effects in
laboratory animals. Because antibodies are generally not able to
pass through a natural barrier that shields the brain from large
molecules, the vaccine-induced antibodies bind to nicotine outside
the brain and ``presumably would not disrupt other behaviors and
brain functions,'' Pentel said.
</P>
<P>
   Most existing treatments for drug abuse act on brain receptors
or neurotransmitters, the chemicals that allow brain cells to
communicate with each other. This can create side effects that
presumably a vaccine may avoid.
</P>
<P>
   A nicotine vaccine would most likely be used to help smokers
quit the habit, although Pentel said it might be used to immunize
people at high risk of nicotine addiction, such as teenagers who
have just started to smoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
