<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With 3 weekends to go, 3 hot division races
 &HT;    Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NFL starts playing games on Saturday this weekend, so you
know things are getting serious.
</P>
<P>
   With only three weeks left in the regular season, three
divisions are still up for grabs _ the AFC West and the NFC Central
and East.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC West, the St. Louis Rams already have won the
division. The Colts and Jaguars soon could follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts, riding a franchise-record nine consecutive victories,
are one away from tying the 1929 Giants and 1963 Raiders for the
biggest single-season turnaround in history. The Colts can claim
the AFC East on Sunday by beating or tying the Redskins, or with a
loss or tie by the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars have won 10 games in a row and are the first AFC
Central team since the 1975 Steelers to have a 12-1 record.
Jacksonville can win the division by beating the lowly Browns, or
with a loss or tie by the Titans, who play the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win a division, trying to win a Super Bowl,''
Jags offensive tackle Tony Boselli said. ``It doesn't matter how we
get there, or what we look like, as long as we get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the league is battling for position.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins need to upset the Colts in Indianapolis to stay at
least one game ahead of the Cowboys and Giants in the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC Central, Detroit must beat Chicago to stay within one
game of the Buccaneers, who travel to Oakland. The Packers and
Vikings meet on Monday night, and the loser could fall out of the
playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The reeling Seahawks, who have lost three in a row to fall into
a first-place tie with the Chiefs in the AFC West, must beat
Denver, which has lost only once in its past 14 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Divisional match: Unlike the Falcons, the two-time defending
Super Bowl champion Broncos are still playing inspired football.
They nearly upset Jacksonville on the road last week. With a
victory at home Sunday, Denver could knock the Seahawks one game
behind the Chiefs, who should beat reeling Pittsburgh on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Grudge match: Carolina coach George Seifert gets another shot at
the 49ers, who forced him out of San Francisco after the 1996
season. The Panthers won 31-29 at San Francisco on Oct. 17. It
could be much worse in Charlotte on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Upset opportunity: Tampa Bay rookie Shaun King won his first two
starts, giving the Bucs a one-game lead in the NFC Central. But
King starts his first NFL road game Sunday at Oakland, which isn't
a friendly place to play.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy play: Titans running back Eddie George had 199 rushing
yards vs. Oakland last week. The Falcons rank 29th in the league
against the run, so George could post more gaudy numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Individual match: With Falcons right tackle Ephraim Salaam
sidelined with a hip injury, second-year pro Jose Portilla could
make his first start at Tennessee. Portilla's assignment will be
stopping Titans rookie Jevon Kearse, who leads the AFC with 11 1/2
sacks. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
