<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ANNA&AMP;KING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A royal bore: Storytelling flat, views gorgeous in new `Anna'
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Anna and the King'' _ the fourth
cinematic account of the adventures of schoolmarm Anna Leonowens in
Siam, circa 1862 _ is a visual feast. The movie itself is a mess,
but it looks gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   You probably know the story by now, from either the 1946 version
that pitted Irene Dunne against Rex Harrison as the Siamese
monarch, or from the 1956 musical adaptation with Deborah Kerr and
Yul Brynner. Or the least of the options, the 1999 animated musical
hodgepodge.
</P>
<P>
   Such familiarity breeds a yen for something new, but for the
first hour or so, ``Anna and the King'' plods earnestly along
telling its too-well-known West-meets-East tale of the British
widow who goes to Siam to teach the many offspring of King Mongkut
about the world. It covers the usual ground with only minor tweaks
for historical accuracy or political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into Mrs. Leonowens' Victorian hoop skirts this time is
the estimable, intelligent Jodie Foster, who invariably gives each
role her complete commitment. Here, however, that amounts to lots
of forehead furrowing and such a resolutely stern, clenched jaw
that the actress has little ability to register any expression.
</P>
<P>
   Chow Yun-Fat (yup, the action figure from ``The Replacement
Killers'') fares somewhat better, sporting a full head of hair in
an attempt to avoid comparison with Brynner. He makes the king more
erudite, less of a barbarian, but no less perplexed by his
adversarial female employee. Alas, he is gypped out of a
scenery-chewing death scene like his predecessors had.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not, as you might imagine, the lack of Rodgers
and Hammerstein songs, even though you might miss the strains of
``Shall We Dance?'' when Mongkut takes Anna in his arms for one of
several ballroom spins. Rather it is the feeling that neither
director Andy Tennant (``Ever After'') nor screenwriters Steve
Meerson and Peter Krikes (``Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home'') has
any new ideas for the story, beyond luxuriating in the surroundings
found in Mayalsia, the film's shooting site.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about two-thirds of the way through the overlong movie,
someone must have looked at the daily rushes and realized how bland
a film they were making. Suddenly, we are thrown into a
full-blooded, buckle-swashing war between the Siamese and the
Burmese, as abruptly as when the animated version decided to make
the king an action-adventure hero. As if that weren't enough to
satisfy all those with no interest in pretty scenery and a
near-romance story, Mongkut's new concubine Tuptim (the delicately
beautiful Bai Ling) and her clandestine lover are given a
slow-motion ritual beheading.
</P>
<P>
   Better concentrate instead on the lovely scenery, the
sumptuously recreated palace, the pageantry of the exotic
livestock, the teeming marketplace, the decadent banquets, and on
and on, concocted by production designer Luciana Arrighi and
captured with fairy-tale high gloss by cinematographer Caleb
Deschanel. There is something about this story that brings out the
best in technicians. Both earlier live-action versions won Oscars
for art direction and were nominated and/or won for cinematography.
``Anna and the King'' could easily join that group.
</P>
<P>
   But as for a truly involving, novel take on the tale, it is
unlikely that audiences will be whistling a happy tune. They may,
however, leave the theater whistling the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
