A1257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-DEVIL17-COX     12-16 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DEVIL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Ride With Devil' gives Civil War human face
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Where you think we are, we ain't,'' says a guerrilla
leader on the Missouri-Kansas frontier during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar might be said about Ang Lee, the
Taiwanese-born director of the handsome ``Ride With the Devil.''
Look for him where he was _ and he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Eat Drink Man Woman,'' Lee made a meal out of his Chinese
roots. But he then chose an item from Column B _ namely, the
Regency England period in ``Sense and Sensibility.'' Would he stick
with the classics? Nope, he motored off to suburban Connecticut
with ``The Ice Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   So don't look for him in modern America. His new movie is a
horse opera about love, freedom and coming-of-age amid a bloody
sideshow of the Civil War. The film flirts with the epic. But its
real strength resides in small scenes featuring acutely observed
characters. Contemplative moments and sly jokes flourish amid the
carnage.
</P>
<P>
   By design, this is a measured action movie. But it's also a tad
too long _ largely because about midway the narrative focus shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Be patient. This gear-grinding turns a sleek shoot-'em-up into a
thoughtful study of human and social transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Devil'' features a cast of promising young actors. Tobey
Maguire (``The Ice Storm'') and Skeet Ulrich (``Scream'') play
teen-age pals who join a guerrilla band fighting the Yankee
``invaders'' of their native Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich is Jack Bull Chiles, the smoldering son of a plantation
owner. Maguire is Jake Roedel, the son of German immigrants. He's
never allowed to forget that Missouri's Germans are Union
sympathizers. Despite his proven courage, Jake remains a watchful
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   The friends' comrades include the bemused Cavalier, George Clyde
(Simon Baker), and his friend and former slave, Daniel Holt
(Jeffrey Wright).
</P>
<P>
   Like Jake, Holt is an outsider fighting under the Confederate
banner. He's loyal to the man who bought his ``freedom.'' As the
film unfolds, Jake and Holt form a silent bond transcending war and
race.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is full of bloody ambushes, breakneck horsemanship and
one showy set battle. Lee captures the fierce hatreds that animated
the ``border wars.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``Devil'' takes an inward turn when the friends
encounter Sue Lee, played effectively enough by the singer Jewel,
who owns a 19th-century face. Recently widowed, she encourages
their awkward attentions. The result is pregnant with possibilities
in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The sloe-eyed Maguire conveys innocence, wariness and a stubborn
streak. At first, he can kill without a cringe. We watch him
develop a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire's deliberate speech also suits the formal syntax of the
era, making innocuous remarks sound like eloquent prose. (This may
charm some viewers; grate on others.)
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich is more flamboyant, a commanding presence in a more
obvious way, although at times he seems to be trying on attitudes
rather than acting. As the sensitive former slave, Wright
(``Basquiat'') is an occasional scene-stealer.
</P>
<P>
   Although filled with violence, ``Ride With the Devil'' is a
sentimental film. As in any good Western, the war's survivors ride
into the sunset to embrace the future.
</P>
<P>
   Lee lets it be known that their future will be ruled by the new,
overarching principle of American life firmly set in motion by the
Union victory _ equality, or the right of the individual to
personal fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
