A1263 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE     12-16 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield's pastor ordered to give deposition Tuesday
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield's preacher, Creflo Dollar, has been
ordered to give a deposition next week in the boxer's high-stakes
divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Holyfield's lawyers are tracing the ex-champion's
finances and say he may have given up to $7 million to Dollar's
church, World Changers Ministries in College Park. Fayette County
Superior Court Judge Ben Miller said Thursday that he's tired of
Dollar's efforts to evade the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears Pastor Dollar has placed himself above the law,''
Miller said Thursday. ``No citizen of this country is above the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller ordered that Dollar and his lawyers show up at 10:30 a.m.
Tuesday to answer questions from Janice Holyfield's lawyers. A
deposition is the testimony of a witness taken under oath in
preparation of a trial. Most depositions are taken in lawyers'
offices, but Miller said this one will be held inside the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar did not appear Thursday at the hearing in Fayetteville.
His lawyer, Lecora Bowen, argued that Dollar should not be deposed
because of the separation of church and state, pastor-parishioner
privilege, several state laws and the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (a deposition) would require him to violate God's law,''
Bowen said, quoting 1 Corinthians 6:1.
</P>
<P>
   She said Dollar was in a touchy situation because he'd counseled
both Evander and Janice Holyfield. Bowen said John Mayoue, Janice
Holyfield's lawyer, has the information about donations to the
church from Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that some information about the Holyfields is indeed
privileged. For instance, conversations intended as confessional or
confidential can stay off the record, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoue has said Evander Holyfield may have given up to $7
million to the church. Mayoue said he's determined that Holyfield
gave $403,000 to the church in 1998, yet donated $3.9 million to
the church in the 60 days before the ex-champ filed for divorce
last March 26. Mayoue said $3 million of that came in one check
five days before the divorce filing.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield also wrote checks for $150,000 to Dollar personally,
Mayoue said.
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield's lawyer, Barry McGrough, said he didn't have
any problems with Dollar giving a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he probably would find the minister in contempt
if he didn't show up Tuesday. ``I don't know if he thinks he is an
irresistible force,'' Miller said. ``If a conflict comes, I know
who will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Dollar is a leader in the ``prosperity gospel'' movement, which
teaches that God promises wealth and health to the faithful.
Holyfield is one of 20,000 members of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Miller also denied Bowen's motion that he recuse himself from
the Holyfield case. Miller has scheduled the divorce trial for
April 3.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
