A1267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-TUMBLEWEEDS17-     12-16 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-TUMBLEWEEDS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mother-daughter coming-of-age film showcases relative unknowns
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It happens too often to be pure chance,
two movies arriving with startlingly similar subjects and plots.
Maybe industrial espionage can explain the repetition of such
high-concept notions as volcano disaster pictures or animated bugs.
But what could be behind two nearly identical films about an
irresponsible, flirtatious mother and a level-headed daughter who
leave home, drive across country, move to California and muddle
through mom's bad choices for male companionship and daughter's
coming of age?
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for answers to the riddle, just accept serendipity
and enjoy. Maybe you can still find the Susan Sarandon-Natalie
Portman match-up of ``Anywhere But Here'' somewhere around, but
also seek out the touching bonding-though-tough-times tale,
``Tumbleweeds,'' featuring the also first-rate, though lesser box
office magnets Janet McTeer and Kimberly J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Who? Theater fans already know about McTeer, whose Tony
Award-winning Nora in ``A Doll's House'' stunned Broadway in 1997.
Brown also has impressive theater credits, especially considering
that she is 13. Regardless, they are actresses likely to establish
themselves in the public consciousness if their performances in
``Tumbleweeds'' is any indication.
</P>
<P>
   McTeer is magnetic as Mary Jo Walker, an attractive Southern
woman who is no longer young, who has a knack for attracting men,
but never the right kind. Her daughter Ava (named for Ava Gardner)
knows the pattern of flirtation to delusions of love to flaring
annoyance to stormy walkout so well she can predict the onset of
the next stage.
</P>
<P>
   When they have car trouble on the road west and Mary Jo begins
primping in the mirror when a truck driver named Jack stops to
offer help, Ava sees what is ahead and wearily admonishes her mom,
``Don't even think about it.'' But Mary Jo encounters Jack (played
by director/co-writer Gavin O'Connor) again in a bar in the
Southern California beach town where the two Walkers alight. She
beds him that night, they move in together soon after and find a
measure of happiness together. Briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Also brief is Mary Jo's office career, working for a crotchety
lecher (``Bonnie and Clyde'''s Michael J. Pollard, of all people).
Before she gets fed up there, Mary Jo and Ava are befriended by
co-worker Dan (Jay O. Sanders), a Shakespeare-spouter who is so
clearly Mr. Right he might as well wear a halo. Ava, you see, is
trying out for a role in a school production of ``Romeo and
Juliet'' and, with Dan's coaching, she wins a leading role _ Romeo.
When Ava also wins the attentions of a prospective boyfriend, Mary
Jo coaches her in the art of kissing, her own area of expertise.
</P>
<P>
   McTeer has a most expressive face and is not yet such a star
that she feels the need to protect how it is seen. As Mary Jo, she
gets an emotional workout, fast-forwarding through anger,
determination, exhaustion, coquettishness, passion, despair and
back again. One minute she is alluring, the next she is haggard and
plain. If ``Tumbleweeds'' were a studio picture, there would be
plenty of deserved Oscar talk about McTeer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Tumbleweeds'' is that other movie that's like
``Anywhere But Here'' and McTeer is that actress who plays a role
so similar to Sarandon's. Still, she and the film can stand on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
