<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-WESTBANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS WORRY THAT THEY MAY BE ECLIPSED BY ISRAELI-SYRIAN
TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-TALKS)  
(js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ After nearly four years of being the sole
Arab partner in peace talks with Israel, Palestinians are concerned
that they may be left in the dust as Prime Minister Ehud Barak goes
off in pursuit of Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see how the Americans deal with us in the coming
weeks,'' said Nabil Amr, a member of the Palestinian cabinet.
``Because they consider the Syrian track now as the most important
breakthrough in the peace process, they'll concentrate on reaching
a real achievement on the Syrian track. They'll send us messages
from time to time, but I'm not sure that they'll push as hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to allay those concerns, President Clinton made a point
of mentioning the Palestinian-Israeli talks as he stood between
Barak and the Syrian Foreign Minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, when they
began their meetings in the White House on Wednesday. Clinton
referred to the Palestinian talks again when the meetings ended
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also invited Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
to meet in Washington next month as Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators race to meet a Feb. 13 target date for a framework
agreement on a permanent peace.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Washington, Barak contacted Arafat to
reassure him that he would not pursue talks with Syria at the
expense of the Palestinians, promising to meet the Palestinian
leader when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Palestinians remain wary that the Israeli prime
minister might use the talks with Syria as a pretext to slow
progress and to squeeze more concessions from the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Tayeb Abdel Rahim, a senior aide to Arafat, warned in a speech
on Wednesday against ``attempts to play one track off the other''
and urged a concerted stance with Syria that would ``plug all the
gaps in the Arab position through which attempts could be made to
avoid carrying out commitments on the Palestinian track.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some Palestinian officials said they sawages in the resumption of the Israeli-Syrian talks. They said
an Israeli agreement to withdraw entirely from the Golan Heights
and to remove Israeli settlements there could strengthen
Palestinian demands that the same apply to the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a precedent for us,'' said Ahmad Abdel Rahman,
secretary of the Palestinian cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Abu Rudeineh, a spokesman for Arafat, said that Syria's
entrance into peace talks would also help the Palestinian leader by
neutralizing opposition to his policies by militant Palestinian
factions based in Damascus and long backed by Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erakat, a senior Palestinian negotiator with the Israelis,
said that neither side could afford to put their talks on the back
burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the same street corner, in the same shop,'' he said.
``There is no comparison between the Palestinian track and the
other tracks. We are the core of the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEAT-ECOLI-1212-COX     12-16 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-ECOLI-1212-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DANGEROUS NEW STRAINS OF BACTERIA EMERGING IN AMERICA'S FOOD
SUPPLY
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Dec. 12
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY and ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dangerous and sometimes deadly new strains of the
E.coli bacteria have emerged and are moving through America's food
supply undetected because no one is testing for them.
</P>
<P>
   Public attention and food safety efforts have focused on a
single strain, known by the scientific name O157:H7, since it
killed two children in the Jack-In-The-Box fast-food hamburger
outbreak in 1993. But the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta recently issued a report estimating that
O157:H7 may cause only half of the approximately 110,000 E. coli
illnesses in the United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   The rest are caused by an estimated half dozen similar, though
not identical, toxin-secreting E. coli bacteria. Researchers don't
know how prevalent these dangerous forms of E. coli are. They also
do not know how many people in the United States may have died from
the new strains.
</P>
<P>
   But most agree that the toxin itself cannd in about 25
percent of the nation's ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists disagree over whether citizens should be alarmed by
that percentage. Some emphasize that many toxin-producing E. coli
bacteria have not been found to cause illness and the only way to
be truly safe is to cook meat thoroughly. But at least one
prominent E.coli expert argues that putting the toxin at the center
of health efforts is the wisest course.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, food safety experts in America have spotted
many of the virulent new strains of E.coli overseas. But they seem
to have been caught off guard when they spread here.
</P>
<P>
   That was illustrated last June when a little-noticed outbreak of
E. coli O111, a new strain, swept through a gathering of high
school drill team members in Denton, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At final count at least 132 people were infected, several were
hospitalized, and two had appendectomies at hospitals where doctors
groped for solutions to the riddle of why they couldn't find
O157:H7 in patients who so clearly had the symptoms of severe E.
coli poisoning. No one was killed in that outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Texas case represents the first confirmed major
outbreak of O111 in the United States, the presence of the bacteria
hardly comes as news to Nancy Rehker of Cleveland. In October 1998,
she spent seven horrifying days watching E. coli O111 consume her
7-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She died one week to the day after she got sick,'' said
Rehker, 41, who still is angry that health officials couldn't
figure out what had infected Lauren. ``Do you want to see her
autopsy? Do you want to see what it did to her? It ate her alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the CDC three weeks, long after Lauren had died, to
identify the bacteria that killed her. Doctors in Cleveland knew
they had a case of hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS), the devastating
side effect of E. coli infections that causes kidney failure. But
their tests found no trace of O157:H7.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the fatal illness listed on Lauren Rehker's death
certificate still reflects the erroneous guesswork on the cause:
Hemolytic uremic syndrome, but ``Not E. coli.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren's death and the Texas outbreak occurred despite warnings
to both the CDC and the U.S. Agriculture Department in 1996 that
the country was facing a greater E. coli threat than just O157:H7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been screaming about the non-O157 (strains) for years and
nobody listens,'' said Dr. David W.K. Acheson, who heads a
nationally-recognized research project on E. coli in Boston.
``There's not a lot of logic, that I can see, in looking for
O157.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department officials didn't return repeated phone
calls, made over several days, seeking comment for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Acheson was among a small group of doctors who began studying E.
coli in the 1980s when the normally harmless intestinal bacteria
began turning up as a common thread in illness in several
countries. Soon, the researchers realized that some strains of the
microscopic E. coli bacteria carried a gene that allowed them to
secrete a potentially lethal poison known as the Shiga toxin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical factor is the toxin, and it's the toxin that
makes people sick... the E. coli are not as critical as the toxin
itself,'' Acheson explained.
</P>
<P>
   Since those early days, scientists have identified approximately
50 different E. coli strains that produce the toxin, but ohandful appear to be as dangerous as O157:H7 and some seem not to
be a threat at all.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of the 1993 Jack-In-The-Box outbreak, the U.S.
Department of Agriculutre decided to declare the O157:H7 strain an
adulterant. That made it illegal for anyone to sell meat that had
tested positive for the pathogen. Acheson, who says the E. coli
bacteria evolve so rapidly it's foolish to think any of the Shiga
toxin-makers will remain harmless to humans, said he didn't think
that decision made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it was screamingly obvious that any bug that was making
toxin had the potential of causing human disease,'' Acheson said.
``I started to make calls to people at USDA and saying 'Well, wait
a minute, why are you singling out O157?'''
</P>
<P>
   And even without the evolution of harmless strains, doctors
already knew about O111, which had caused outbreaks of severe
illness in Australia and Europe. Scientists in Canada had confirmed
that E. coli O26, yet another strain, was dangerous to people, too.
Acheson said the Agriculture Department told him it deferred to CDC
on issues of human disease, and that the CDC said it didn't have
enough evidence of a problem in the United States to cast a wider
net over E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, oh boy, you know we know they are causing disease
in Canada, Australia, Europe, (and) South America but not in the
United States,'' Acheson said, recalling his frustration. ``And
it's like 'Do these bugs need passports to come into the country
and we won't issue them?'''
</P>
<P>
   Acheson's attempts to get the attention of federal policy makers
failed in part because he could not prove that any of the other
strains of the bacteria were causing sickness in the U.S. But he
doesn't believe the lack of evidence is proof of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line was the reason we weren't finding them in the
United States was not because they weren't here,'' Acheson said.
``It's because nobody was looking. And it was as simple as that.
The emphasis was on O157.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the CDC was at the time tracking other forms of
toxin-carrying E. coli both in the U.S. and overseas. But Dr. Paul
Mead, who heads the CDC's infectious disease unit, is not sure
there was enough information in 1996 to say non-O157:H7 posed a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said his agency now is developing a clearer sense of the
dangers of non-O157 E. coli, and Acheson agrees that CDC appears
more willing to recognize that potential. In 1997, Mead and a group
of colleagues questioned whether the decision to make O157 an
illegal substance in meat adequately addressed the potential for
other forms of E. coli poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have prevention measures decreased risk?'' Mead asked in a
scholarly journal. ``How much illness is due to (strains) other
than O157?''
</P>
<P>
   Then this year CDC used Acheson's data to make its ``best
guess'' that the 0157:H7 strain only is causing half the E. coli
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mead is not as convinced as Acheson that the mere
presence of the E. coli toxin is cause for alarm because not all
toxin-producing bacteria are dangerous to humans.
</P>
<P>
   This view is echoed by Dr. Michael Doyle, who is the director of
the Center for Food Quality Enhancement at the University of
Georgia in Athens. Doyle's research is funded largely by government
money, but corporations also contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said testing all beef for the toxin, which is Acheson's
preferred remedy, isn't a workable solution to catching dangerous
E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds good when you say it fast,'' he said. ``But if a
quarter of the ground beef supply is condemned, I'm not sure we
could afford to eat out. It's a matter of teasing out the strains
that are the pathogens.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said tests must be developed to sort through the
toxin-producing E. coli bacteria, and find only those strains that
also have the characteristics needed to colonize in the human gut
and cause sickness. He also advocates an ``across the board'' look
at farming and slaughtering procedures to find ways to control the
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   For Nancy Rehker, the relative dangers of different types of E.
coli hold no interest. She has become focused on learning all she
can about the strain that killed her daughter, and she has been
trying to spread the word to others. She still doesn't know exactly
where the bacteria came from, though it seems clear Lauren was
infected while traveling in Virginia and Maryland days before she
became sick.
</P>
<P>
   The diarrhea began shortly after they got home on Aug. 4. Before
very long it turned to blood. And then it wouldn't stop. That
night, Lauren drifted in and out of sleep with her head in her
mother's lap while sitting on the toilet. In the morning she was in
the hospital, and by the end of her life she was delirious, sucking
on the metal bed post.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren was in the grip of HUS. There is no cure, though it isn't
always fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in the world that will ever be able to erase
the memory of rocking Lauren, dead, and staring into the faces of
my family,'' she said in a letter.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rehker wants to know what's going to be done about the E.
coli nobody talks about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a government agency to protect our food, don't we?''
she said. ``They can't cure it, so they just have to stop it before
people get sick.''
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Montgomery can be reached at: scottm(at)coxnews.com.
Elliot Jaspin can be reached at: elliotj(at)coxnews.com )
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
