<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TEXAS-AIR-COX     12-16 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-AIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough air-quality standards may conflict with Texas tastes
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush says Texans should consider
following California's lead in reducing air pollution from motor
vehicles, but automakers say the idea could put a crimp in Texas'
love affair with pickups and SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, under federal mandate to reduce air pollution by 2007, is
looking at various options to comply. Bush has suggested possibly
adopting California's limits on vehicle emissions that contribute
to smog.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the auto industry says that could limit
Texans' access to new trucks and sport-utility vehicles. That's
because the popular vehicles emit more pollutants than mid-sized
and small cars. California has a ceiling on the total emissions
that can be produced by vehicles in the state. If Texas adopted a
similar program, that could force automakers to reduce sales of
pickups and SUVs, which make up a greater share of the new car
market in Texas than California, the industry says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the California program has the real
potential of limiting model choices,'' said Alan Weverstad of the
Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers. He made his remarks to the
Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission, which is
considering the idea as part of a sweeping set of proposals to make
Texas' air cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental and consumer activist Tom Smith accused automakers
of trying to avoid tough anti-pollution standards by scaring Texas
truck and SUV enthusiasts. Smith, who heads Public Citizen in
Texas, supports the California program for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said automakers haven't cut their
truck and SUV sales in California, and Texas officials doubt that
will happen here.
</P>
<P>
   But Weverstad said trucks and SUVs are far more popular in Texas
than they are in California or New York and Massachusetts, which
also have adopted California's emissions standards. He couldn't say
how many of Texas' more than 16.4 million vehicles are trucks and
SUVs, but added that it historically has been in the range of 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at the parking lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, has been criticized by state and national environmental
groups as having a poor record on pollution issues. In a letter
this week, Bush encouraged the environmental agency to consider
adopting California's vehicle emission standards. He said it would
``encourage the development of a new generation of cleaner vehicles
and fuels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked that the TNRCC consider adopting California's vehicle
emissions standard because the governor believes that the
California standard has a great deal of merit and we should give it
a great deal of consideration,'' Edwards said. ``He also encourages
people to comment on these proposals in the coming months.''
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC approved a proposal Thursday to do just that,
scheduling public hearings on the issue for coming months. The
proposal is part of a package of ideas meant to get nearly all of
Texas in line with federal ozone pollution standards by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   That package includes changes to vehicle emission testing in the
12 counties around Dallas and around Houston; tighter restrictions
on pollution from cement and power plants; limits on the use of
commercial and industrial machinery and statewide restrictions on
pollution from water heaters. The commission scheduled public
hearings on these matters, including one in Austin on Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also adopted final rules governing pollution from
so-called grandfathered plants. Those power and industrial plants
weren't required to follow air quality standards adopted in the
1970s because they already were built or were in the middle of
construction. Owners of those plants now will be encouraged to
register with the state and reduce pollution. If they don't, they
will face substantial fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is to be allowed to opt out of participating (in
pollution reduction efforts).'' TNRCC Chairman Robert Huston said.
</P>
<P>
   Four areas in Texas _ Dallas-Fort Worth, Houston-Galveston,
Beaumont-Port Arthur and El Paso exceed federal standards for ozone
pollution. Other areas are considered near ``nonattainment,''
including the Austin area, which includes Travis, Williamson, Hays,
Bastrop and Caldwell counties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
