<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Pervomaiskoye, Russia) _ Desperate civilians
fleeing the blistering Russian bombardment of Grozny say they had
to run a gantlet of gunfire in the ``humanitarian corridor'' set up
by the Russian army. Refugees interviewed at a checkpoint six miles
from the outskirts of Grozny said a bus full of refugees was
riddled with machine-gun fire. Mortars exploded as elderly
civilians, women and children huddled in a ditch for hours before
making the long, chilly walk to Russian-controlled Chechnya. By
Michael R. Gordon. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MINORITIES (New York) _ A hugely disproportionate number of
minorities represent new AIDS cases, yet blacks and Latinos have
not had front and center positions in AIDS policy making.
Mainstream black groups have shied away from the issue, and
minority groups devoted to it have had trouble getting money. But
slowly, that is all changing, as more minorities find themselves in
powerful positions in the advocacy and policy front, and state and
federal dollars are starting to be newly appropriated in
recognition of where the disease now hits home. By Jennifer
Steinhauer. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,600 words.
</P>
