<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CHILD-MURDER-     12-16 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CHILD-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN COURT SAYS BOYS CONVICTED OF MURDER DID NOT GET FAIR
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The European Court of Human Rights ruled Thursday that
two 10-year-old boys who kidnapped and killed 2-year-old James
Bulger in a suburban Liverpool shopping center in 1993 had not
received a fair trial in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The judges said that the two boys, Jon Venables and Robert
Thompson, had been too young to take part effectively in a
procedure meant for adults and that the home secretary at the time,
Michael Howard, had erred in increasing their eight-year jail
sentence to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The boys have already served six years, and while the European
decision does not affect their convictions, it could be the basis
for lawyers to seek their release in British courts.
</P>
<P>
   The crime, committed on Feb. 12, 1993, generated horror and
revulsion among people around the world when still photos from
security camera videotapes were made public. Photos from the
shopping center showed an older boy calmly leading the toddler away
by the hand; stills from a construction company camera not far away
showed two youths beating him.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping occurred while the child's mother was momentarily
distracted as she stood in line at a butcher shop in the commercial
arcade. The boy's mutilated body was found two days later by
children playing on a railroad embankment two miles from the
shopping center. He had been thrown onto the tracks from a bridge
and hit by a passing train.
</P>
<P>
   The age of James' tormentors, the methodical manner in which
they made off with him and the brutality of his killing provoked a
national debate in Britain over whether social neglect was making
both victims and victimizers of the country's young.
</P>
<P>
   In the House of Commons on Thursday afternoon, Jack Straw, the
current home secretary, said, ``This terrible case _ and not least
the image of that 2-year-old being led away to his death _
traumatized a generation of parents more than any other single
event of this decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The original minimum sentence of eight years set by the trial
judge was increased to 10 years by the lord chief justice at the
time and later to 15 by Howard. The law lords of the House of
Lords, England's highest court, threw out Howard's decision in
1997, and the government has since said that it would await the
European court's ruling before deciding what action to take in the
boys' continuing imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Straw told Parliament on Thursday that he needed time to
consider the 120-page ruling before acting in the case but that
overall reforms would now have to be made in the way juvenile
offenders are tried and sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the European Court of Human Rights, which is based
in Strasbourg, France, and operates entirely separately from the
European Union, is to ensure that countries that have signed the
international human rights convention live up to its terms. The
British government is in the process of incorporating the
convention into the law of the United Kingdom, meaning that future
complaints of violations can be taken up in British courts.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling Thursday, judges said that a home secretary's
involvement in fixing terms for young offenders violated the
convention's guarantee of the right to ``a fair hearing before an
independent and impartial tribunal.'' As a member of the
government, a home secretary is not independent of the executive,
it said.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, both 11 by the time of the 17-day trial, were the
youngest children in Britain to be tried for murder this century.
The European court said that the proceedings had breached their
rights because the bewildering atmosphere of an adult court
prevented them from taking a proper part in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, with its judicial formality and lawyers in robes and
wigs, must have seemed ``incomprehensible and intimidating'' to the
boys, the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   Practical modifications to take account of their youth _ like
raising the floor level of the criminal dock to allow them to see
the courtroom, and limiting the length of sessions to accommodate
their attention spans _ did not go far enough, the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the boys had skilled and experienced lawyers ``within
whispering distance,'' they would have been too cowed and shy to
talk to them freely, according to the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Proceedings against children must take into account ``age, level
of maturity and intellectual and emotional capacities.'' It might
be necessary, the judges added, to conduct such trials in private
to reduce the inhibiting effect of the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   However, they ruled that the ``blaze'' of publicity connected to
the trial did not have such an impact on the boys as to constitute
``inhuman or degrading'' treatment, as the youths' lawyers argued.
</P>
<P>
   James' mother, Denise Fergus, was said by her lawyer, Sean
Sexton, to be ``devastated'' by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She feared the worst and always thought there was a danger of
this happening and that they were trying for the minimum
sentence,'' he said. ``She fears if they are let out, they might do
something similar again, and she will do anything she legitimately
can to stop this happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
