<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-SOLDIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN SOLDIER KILLED IN KOSOVO BY LAND MINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An American soldier in Kosovo died early Thursday
after his vehicle struck a land mine that may have been planted in
a recent act of sabotage, Pentagon officials said Thursday. His was
the first American death in NATO's peacekeeping operation in the
Serbian province not caused by an accident or suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is littered with mines, but officials said they suspected
that the mine that killed the soldier might have been placed
recently, because his vehicle was traveling on a road that had been
used regularly and was thus believed to be free of mines.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier, Staff Sgt. Joseph E. Suponcic, 26, was riding in an
Army Humvee when the mine detonated beneath it on Wednesday night
near Kosovska Kamenica in southeastern Kosovo. The village lies in
the part of the American zone that is regularly patrolled by
Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter flew Suponcic to a hospital at the main American
base in Kosovo, not far from Urosevac, but he died from his wounds
nearly five hours later, according to a statement by the
headquarters of the Army's European Command in Heidelberg, Germany.
The driver was slightly wounded.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear who might have laid the mine, the
officials said. Both Serbian forces and Kosovo Albanian rebels used
mines extensively during the civil war that ended with the
occupation of Kosovo by more than 40,000 NATO-led troops in June.
Since then, Kosovo has been riven by violent acts of retribution by
Albanians against Serbs and, less often, against the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The area around Kamenica saw little fighting during the war
between Serbian forces and Albanians fighting for the province's
independence. It is one of the few parts of Kosovo that still has a
significant population of Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Both the remaining Serbs in Kosovo and Russian peacekeepers, who
are viewed as historical and cultural allies of Serbia, have been
the targets of attacks by Kosovar Albanians, possibly those
associated with the officially disbanded Kosovo Liberation Army,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said a mine planted in that area would
presumably be intended to harm Serbian civilians or Russian troops,
raising the possibility that it may have been laid by Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Suponcic, a member of the Third Battalion of the 10th Special
Forces (Airborne), based at Fort Carson, Colo., was assigned to the
American unit that serves as a liaison with the Russian
peacekeepers. He was one of few Americans working in that part of
the American sector.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, said it was also
possible that a long-dormant mine could have been exposed by rain.
But he added that ``the circumstances are still under review.''
Bacon said that while other mines were believed to be on both sides
of the road, the mine that killed Suponcic was on the road itself.
</P>
<P>
   American commanders in Kosovo have begun an investigation to
determine who might have planted the mine.
</P>
<P>
   In the six months since the peacekeeping operation began, there
have been six other Americans killed in Kosovo and another in
Macedonia, but this was the first death caused by a hostile act,
the officials said. The others are believed to have been caused by
accidents or possible suicides.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and NATO suffered no combat casualties during
the 78-day air war over Serbia last spring. But two Army soldiers
died in a helicopter crash during a training mission in Albania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 1956EST &QL; 
