<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT &LR;      12-16 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE OF PEACE BETWEEN ISRAEL AND SYRIA COULD RUN INTO BILLIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-TALKS, MIDEAST-ASSESS) 
(DW) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Peace is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Any agreement reached in the Israel-Syria talks is certain to
entail huge costs _ to monitor security arrangements, to relocate
Israeli settlers and to bolster the Syrian economy. If the past is
any guide, the United States will bear the lion's share of the
burden.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's immediate challenge is to continue serving
as midwife in negotiations between Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel and Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria, scheduled to
resume on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the negotiations succeed _ and that is by no means
certain _ the president will have to present a multibillion-dollar
bill for peace to a bitterly riven Congress that lately has been
reluctant to grant Clinton political or budgetary victories. That
is likely to get worse in a presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   The president's position is complicated by Syria's record as a
haven for terrorists, its presence on Washington's list of nations
that tolerate large-scale narcotics traffic, and Clinton's
dwindling term in office. Clinton has criticized Congress for what
he calls growing isolationist sentiment, another factor that will
undercut his appeal for billions of dollars more in foreign aid to
bankroll reconciliation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The president, in a preview of arguments he would make for new
money to support an Israeli-Syrian accord, said that continuing
conflict in the Middle East is more expensive than peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``For we have learned from experience that tensions in the
region can escalate,'' Clinton said in a Rose Garden appearance
with Barak and al-Sharaa at the start of the negotiations on
Wednesday. ``And the escalations can lead into diplomatic,
financial and, ultimately, military involvement, far more costly
than even the costliest peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials refuse to discuss the potential level
of American financial support for a possible agreement between
Israel and Syria, saying such questions are speculative and
premature.
</P>
<P>
   The cost would probably far exceed the $1.8 billion price tag of
implementing the Wye River accords reached by Israel and the
Palestinians last November. Even that relatively modest sum was
hung up in Congress for weeks this fall in a battle over unrelated
issues in the appropriations bill for foreign aid and State
Department operations.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials and Middle East analysts estimated that the
immediate costs of a deal under which the Golan Heights would be
returned to Syria would be at least $15 billion _ and perhaps
several times that.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has provided $100 billion since 1979 to
support the peace deal between Anwar el-Sadat of Egypt and Menachem
Begin of Israel, worked out at Camp David under the auspices of
President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between Syria and Israel would entail different costs,
some higher and some lower. Part of the American commitment at Camp
David was an assurance that Israel's military would always maintain
a technological superiority over neighboring armies. The billions
in American aid and Israel's own technological prowess have given
Jerusalem a significant qualitative edge over any Arab state _ and
over virtually any combination of Arab states.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, American military aid following an accord with
Syria would focus more narrowly on creating a security buffer
between northern Israel and Syria, including sophisticated
monitoring systems. While these would be expensive, they would not
require the same level of spending as the 20-year effort to upgrade
Israel's land and air forces.
</P>
<P>
   Still, an Israel-Syria agreement would be a costly proposition,
and Congress would have to sign the checks. The bad blood between
the administration and the Republican-led Congress could make it a
tough fight for a lame-duck president.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of Middle East peace say that Clinton must involve
Congressional leaders early in the process if he wants to win their
support for large new appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a deal _ assuming there is a deal _ the only way
this is going to succeed is if both the administration and Congress
get behind this historic opportunity,'' said Howard Kohr, executive
director of the American Israel Public Affairs Committee.
``Congress has to have some ownership of this issue. The
administration cannot go it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of ignoring Congress until late in the process was
dramatized for Clinton this fall when Congress rejected a global
treaty to ban nuclear testing. The White House and treaty
supporters did not consult with Republican leaders on the treaty
and had no idea of the depth of opposition until it was too late.
Clinton tried to delay a vote on the nuclear treaty but was dealt a
humiliating defeat by a well-organized Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has traditionally given bipartisan support for aid to
Israel, but Syria presents a different case. President Hafez
al-Assad has long been a leader of Arab hostility to Israel, and
many in Congress may be reluctant to reward him for an 11th-hour
conversion to the cause of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Any direct economic reward to Syria, therefore, would probably
have to come from Europe, Japan or the Arab world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
