<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TALKS (Washington) _ After two days of discussions in
Washington, Israel and Syria announce that they will resume peace
talks on Jan. 3. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-Y2K (Washington) _ Pentagon officials say they are
confident that Russian nuclear weapons won't be launched
accidentally because of Y2K glitches. But they base that judgment
mainly on Moscow's verbal assurances rather than independent
verification. ``A lot of our confidence is based on what they tell
us,'' Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre admits. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BINGE-DRINKING (Washington) _ Only 3 percent of parents
believe their high-school-aged children have slugged as many as
five alcoholic drinks in a row over the past month, according to a
new survey, although federal statistics have shown that a third of
9th through 12th graders have done so. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Manchester, N.H.) _ Democratic presidential
candidate Bill Bradley and Republican John McCain hold a town hall
meeting on campaign finances and pledge that if they become the
nominees of their parties, they will not accept the ``soft money''
contributions that flow into political parties. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-FOREIGN (Washington) _ Conservative presidential
candidates Gary Bauer and Patrick Buchanan attack President Clinton
and some moderate Republicans, saying they should stop putting
trade above human rights and national security in dealing with
China. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PARODY (Washington) _ Poking fun at Democratic presidential
hopefuls Al Gore and Bill Bradley, the Republican Party opens a
``Gore Store and Bradley Boutique'' here with gifts for harried
shoppers. The store offers such items as ``I invented the
Internet'' mouse pads, ``alpha male'' baseball caps and coffee mugs
for those who want to stay awake during Bill Bradley speeches. By
MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-DELAY (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ The launch of the
Discovery on a much-delayed mission to repair the Hubble telescope
is postponed until Friday at the earliest so engineers can widen a
search for improperly welded components in the shuttle's fuel
lines. NASA has said it will postpone all efforts to launch the
mission until January if Discovery is not off the ground by
Saturday night. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS-CENTRAL (Houston) _ While several of the Astros' main
competitors in the NL Central have strengthened themselves, the
Houston Astros have done nothing except subtract a key player. We
look at how the off-season race in the Central is shaping up and
where the Astros stand after the winter meetings. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FBN-KEARSE (Undated) _ A look at Tennessee Titans rookie Jevon
Kearse, who has emerged as one of the best defensive linemen in
football. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA (Undated) _ Overview on the NBA season thus far, and the
wild trade rumors that are flying with the league's new trade
rules. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-WATKINS-A&AMP;M (College Station, Texas) _ Basketball coach
Melvin Watkt build not only a team but interest in
basketball at Texas A&AMP;M. By NEIL HOHLFELD.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-A&AMP;M-FOOTBALL (College Station, Texas) _ Texas A&AMP;M returns to
practice in preparation for the Alamo Bowl. By NEIL HOHLFELD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Everyone knew six years ago that the
don't-ask-don't-tell rule for gays in the military was a temporary
cop-out because President Clinton couldn't get the change in policy
he wanted. Now the rule is back as a campaign issue, and nobody is
surprised. It was never going to work. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CZAR (Washington) _ People following the news on New Year's
weekend will likely see a lot of John Koskinen, the White House's
Y2K czar. But Koskinen hopes that once the weekend is over, few
Americans will remember his name. To him that would mean the United
States experienced relatively few Y2K-related problems. By JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
