<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-HISPANICS17-COX     12-16 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HISPANICS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush taps media outlets for access to Latino votes
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, hoping to win over
Latinos in his quest for the White House, is exporting the formula
that helped him capture 40 percent of their vote in Texas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He's starting in Iowa, where the Jan. 24 caucus marks the formal
kick-off of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The state may have just 56,000 Latinos, but it provides a
relatively safe lab to test advertising and other strategies
designed to reach out to Latino voters. It's all part of a plan to
reach beyond the Latino CEOs that the Bush campaign has spent
months courting and appeal to the grass-roots in New York, Florida
and, most importantly for those counting electoral votes, in
California, where there are 2.3 million Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the Latino population rose more than 35 percent in
the 1990s, according to census data. Hispanic voters are
concentrated in the five states packed with electoral votes: Texas,
California, Florida, New York and Illinois, reason enough for
politicians from both major parties to court them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials say they're looking to win every Latino
vote. They're searching for media outlets aimed at Latinos in
lily-white New Hampshire, home to the first primary on Feb. 1. (So
far, they haven't found any). And they're planning an advertising
strategy designed to reach Latinos in California, where voters go
the polls March 7.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, Texas, ad man Lionel Sosa, media director of Bush's
1998 effort, is working on the current campaign. He said the
campaign is buying, ``all available Spanish media everywhere we
go.'' In Iowa, ads are running in one bilingual newspaper and two
Spanish-language newspapers, both weeklies, and a Spanish-language
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find a part-time Spanish-language radio station
somewhere in Iowa, we're going to buy it,'' Sosa said. ``If we find
a bilingual or Spanish-language newspaper that's 12 pages and
publishes once a month, we're going to buy it. It's a front burner
priority and it'll be that way as we go through the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   California organizers are planning a major push in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get those messages out there in forms, radio,
TV. I think what you're going to start seeing is a lot more
outreach to many, many different types of people and types of
groups ...'' said Hector Barreto Jr., until recently chairman of
the influential Latin Business Association. ``There will be high
profile events, just like the one we did in September. We'll be
doing some fund-raising. We'll be getting some high-profile
endorsements ... We'll be kicking this off in January and just
continue to turn up the volume until the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has assiduously courted Latino CEOs with the help of Raul
Romero, a University of Texas Regent and Bush appointee heading the
campaign's effort to win support from the well-heeled executives.
Helping in California is Barreto and, in New York, Jose Fourquet, a
33-year-old Bush cash contributor who works at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   In southern California alone, some 440,000 small business are
owned by Latinos, Barreto said. That's a statistic Bush quotes on
the campaign trail and one that tells Barreto there are votes and
money out there from untapped sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is calculated that three out of five new businesses being
started in Los Angeles are Latino-owned,'' Barreto said. ``Those
businesses are doing $50 billion in annual revenues. The
demographers think those numbers are going to double in the next
five years. It's an explosion. It's not this quaint new trend. A
lot of those companies are not on anybody's radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials say they don't categorize donors by
ethnicity so they can't say how much of the $60 million to $70
million they've raised comes from Latino contributors. But they
know that six of the 156 pioneers _ people who have raised at least
$100,000 for Bush _ are Latino. Another group of Latino supporters
is working on raising between $10,000 and $100,000, said Sonia
Colin-Martinez, a campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bush met with about 40 of his ``American
Dreamers,'' first generation immigrants who gathered at the
governor's mansion for a private luncheon held to thank them for
their work on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to raise money,'' Romero said. ``Basically,
American Dreamers, the concept, the governor is very, very upbeat
about it. He feels that's the reason why a lot of us are here, to
fulfill the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush extends the unrelenting optimism he
aims at Anglos to Hispanic voters. He touts free trade and NAFTA,
saying that, ``family values don't stop at the Rio Grande.'' He
calls for higher educational standards for all students, regardless
of race, and talks about, ``the soft bigotry of low expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   He speaks Spanish (albeit limited, even some supporters say),
and visits inner-city neighborhoods usually left untraversed by
Republicans. This week, Bush's campaign sent out a press release
announcing the unveiling of the mansion's holiday decorations,
``comprised of colorful, Hispanic ornaments made by local Texas
artists.''
</P>
<P>
   But such ornamental outreach won't quell the challenges Bush
faces or criticism that his Latino outreach is only skin deep. This
week, the chairs of the House Census Task Force called on Bush to
provide a population count derived from statistical sampling should
he be elected president. Sampling is intended to remedy the chronic
undercounting of minorities. It is controversial because Democrats
expect that a more accurate count of black and Latino people will
help them when Congressional and legislative districts are redrawn,
while Republicans fear it will hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you stand with those who would deny minorities, children
and the poor fair representation and economic benefits for purely
partisan political reasons?'' asked the chairs, including Rep.
Charles Gonzalez, a San Antonio Democrat and member of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush must first clear hurdles in California, where former
Republican Gov. Pete Wilson alienated Latinos with his
anti-immigration stances. Houston radio station owner Tom Castro, a
Democrat and Los Angeles native, said Latinos were, ``the pinata of
California politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro chairs the New America Alliance, a nonpartisan group
working to increase Latino political clout. Board members include
former San Antonio Mayor Henry Cisneros, a Democrat, and A.R.
``Tony'' Sanchez, a Laredo oil man and Bush supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush is successful and becomes president, I think there's a
fair chance the Republicans can fracture the Latino allegiance to
the Democratic party,'' Castro said. ``It could turn that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hopes so. The Bush ads run in Spanish and English, he said,
because 60 percent of Latinos use both languages. And the message _
focused strongly on family, god, work, opportunity and
inclusiveness _ doesn't differ in substance from much from the,
``compassionate conservatism'' Bush touts before Anglo audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying, 'We're sending out engraved invitations through
the media because we want you at our party,' `` he said. ``You
know, Latinos don't crash parties, but if we're invited we go every
time. We bring the whole family and we stay a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
