<HEADER>
A1291 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-OLIVE-SPI &LR;      12-16 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLIVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUN THE VCR: `OLIVE' SURE TO BECOME HOLIDAY CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of the Fox network and you don't necessarily think of
charming and endearing. Risque, yes. Irreverent, certainly.
Subversive, probably. Coarse, most likely.
</P>
<P>
   So, to find nary a crude moment in Friday night's Christmas
special, ``Olive, the Other Reindeer,'' is, well, stunning.
Executive producer Matt Groening, creator of ``The Simpsons'' and
``Futurama,'' calls it ``a Christmas show that adults and kids will
actually be able to stand to watch together.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. And you really don't have to stand. It's cute. It's
funny. And, in the grand tradition of ``Rocky and Bullwinkle,''
it's sly enough on one level to keep parents amused while the kids
are enjoying the basic cartoon. (There's even a quick tribute to
Frostbite Falls.)
</P>
<P>
   In a role designed for her timbre, Drew Barrymore gives
beautiful voice to Olive, the well-meaning dog who swings into
action when Santa tells the media he'll have to make do with ``all
of the other reindeer'' or maybe cancel deliveries altogether after
Blitzen is injured during a practice run. You might think Rudolph
could fill in, but we soon learn the whole Rudolph saga is just one
of those urban legends, like alligators in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   So Olive, the dog, decides she's Olive, the other reindeer, and
sets out for the North Pole on a Mauvehound bus. Make sure the VCR
is running. There are plenty more sight gags like that, a la ``The
Simpsons,'' to keep you rewinding till Christmas Eve, such as the
``churn o' the century'' sale at Butters of the World.
</P>
<P>
   The special, based on the book by J. Otto Seibold and Vivian
Walsh, is essentially the Rudolph tale updated for the '90s, with
the key changes being the empowered-female character and the
enormous merchandising tie-in at Nordstrom stores across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Olive's nemesis is a disgruntled postman (voiced by Homer
Simpson himself, Dan Castellaneta), who hopes to keep Santa
grounded forever. Her biggest ally is a streetwise penguin (Joe
Pantoliano), who sells bogus Rolexes but has the savvy to get past
North Pole security. Olive meets other characters along the way,
including Blitzen's flight-challenged cousin, Schnitzel, and the
misunderstood Round John Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Parents looking for a gentle lesson in doing the right thing,
helping others and standing by one's friends might check out
``Olive.'' Most Christmas specials are easy to dismiss as seasonal
fluff, but good music, good writing and a good heart make ``Olive''
a good bet to become a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Olive, the Other Reindeer. One-hour animated Christmas special
about a dog who fills in for an injured reindeer on Christmas Eve.
Voices by Drew Barrymore, Dan Castellaneta and Joe Pantoliano.
Friday night on Fox. Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
