<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1297 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NICOTINE-VACCINE-SUB-     12-16 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICOTINE-VACCINE-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENTAL VACCINE SAID TO BLOCK CRAVING FOR NICOTINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (In 4th graf, clarifies NIDA is in Bethesda, Md.; in 10th graf,
added sentence details researchers who did study.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists say they have devised a vaccine that blocks nicotine
from entering the brain, raising the prospect of a novel way to
help smokers quit.
</P>
<P>
   The experimental vaccine has been tested so far only in
laboratory rats, but a government-sponsored study shows it reduced
the amount of nicotine entering the animals' brains by almost
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant, scientists say, the vaccine blocked nicotine's
effect in raising blood pressure and it prevented hyperactive
behavior that researchers see when they inject the animals with
nicotine, the addictive ingredient in tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that ``vaccinated persons would not be able to get
a `kick' from the nicotine in tobacco smoke or chewing tobacco,''
Dr. Alan I. Leshner, director of the National Institute on Drug
Abuse in Bethesda, Md., which funded the research, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Human trials of the vaccine are planned within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials hope nicotine immunization will be
among the first of several vaccines against addiction. Also in
early stages are vaccines against cocaine, methamphetamine, and
PCP, an anesthetic drug called phencycladine that is often abused.
Leshner said the cocaine vaccine is closest to human trials.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of an anti-nicotine vaccine, Leshner said, is
``tremendous'' because smoking remains ``one of the biggest public
health problems in this country, and we need to have as many
treatment approaches as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Although overall smoking rates have declined, an estimated 60
million Americans still smoke cigarettes, according to the drug
abuse institute. Among adults between the ages of 18 and 25, the
smoking rate has steadily crept upward in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional vaccines are designed to stimulate the production of
antibodies against infectious organisms, such as polio or hepatitis
virus. The idea of immunizing against addictive substances
represents ``a very new and different use for a vaccine,'' said Dr.
Paul Pentel of Hennepin County Medical Center in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Pentel is a coauthor of the new study on a nicotine vaccine,
which appears in the journal Pharmacology, Biochemistry and
Behavior. &UR;  &LR; The researchers who conducted the study are associated
with the Minneapolis Medical Research Foundation and Hennepin
County Medical Center; the University of Houston-Clear Lake; and
Nabi, a pharmaceutical firm based in Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Although nicotine, like a virus, is foreign to the body, it is
too small a molecule to be recognized by the immune system, Pentel
said. To make a vaccine, researchers at a Florida-based company
called Nabi Pharmaceuticals attached nicotine to a protein derived
from the outer coat of a bacterium. That enabled the immune system
to make antibodies to the nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers later injected regular nicotine into the lab
rats, the vaccine-induced antibodies attached to it and prevented
it from passing into the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine has so far produced no obvious harmful effects in
laboratory animals. Because antibodies are generally not able to
pass through a natural barrier that shields the brain from large
molecules, the vaccine-induced antibodies bind to nicotine outside
the brain and ``presumably would not disrupt other behaviors and
brain functions,'' Pentel said.
</P>
<P>
   Most existing treatments for drug abuse act on brain receptors
or neurotransmitters, the chemicals that allow brain cells to
communicate with each other. This can create side effects that
presumably a vaccine may avoid.
</P>
<P>
   A nicotine vaccine would most likely be used to help smokers
quit the habit, although Pentel said it might be used to immunize
people at high risk of nicotine addiction, such as teenagers who
have just started to smoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
