<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON VOWS HIKE IN HIRING OF MINORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. has pledged to increase minority hiring following
meetings with the Rev. Jesse Jackson throughout this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a onetime presidential candidate, has also recently
begun discussions with executives at State Street Corp. as part of
an effort to promote minority employment and improve access to
capital for minority-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson calls his effort the Wall Street Project, and its
director, Cheechee Williams, said Thursday she doesn't have
specific complaints about the treatment of women and minorities at
Raytheon, the country's third-largest defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``Traditionally the (aerospace) industry and the
company have been pretty much a white-male bastion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happened that once we started talking to them, they
started looking at what more they could do,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings with Raytheon began last winter, she said, and
since then Raytheon named William Spivey of Lucent Technologies to
its 14-member board of directors, its first African-American
member.
</P>
<P>
   That appointment was ``already in the works'' before the talks
with Jackson began, said Raytheon spokesman David Polk. But
Raytheon agreed to hire more minorities, and to steer more work
managing its pension funds to minority-owned firms, ``as an
extension of our diversity efforts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, it is critical for a high-performing
work force to be inclusive,'' Polk said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a civil arbitrator ruled that a Virginia-based
Raytheon unit discriminated against a group of women involved in
work to dismantle old Soviet weapons _ a charge Raytheon, based in
Lexington, Mass., denies.
</P>
<P>
   But Raytheon has also undergone management shuffles lately,
particularly in the past year, under new chief executive Daniel
Burnham. BankBoston's representative on Raytheon's board is now
Henrique de Campos Meirelles, from Brazil. The Raytheon board's
only female member, Barbara Barrett, was also named this year.
</P>
<P>
   Polk wasn't able to provide the exact percentage of blacks and
other minorities in the company's work force, but he noted the
company was also bound to meet certain targets for hiring and for
contract assignments under the terms of its many federal contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are ongoing between Jackson's group and Raytheon, and the
two say they expect to announce specifics at a conference set for
next month in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That conference will be organized with the help of State Street
Corp., which Williams said was approached because of its large
pension management business.
</P>
<P>
   State Street in recent years has talked up its cooperation with
minority-owned brokerage firms, and last year helped organize a
Federal Reserve conference on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   In ongoing talks with Jackson and his deputies, State Street is
reviewing the capital requirements it sets to do business with such
firms. ``The question was, are we looking at the right levels?
That's what's under review,'' said Marshall Carter, State Street's
chief executive and chairman. State Street has also been the
subject of discrimination complaints by several women in recent
years, but the firm's employment practices are not at issue, both
Carter and Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
