<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-RWANDA-BOS &LR;      12-16 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-RWANDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN LACKED `POLITICAL WILL' TO STOP MASSACRE, PANEL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The United Nations ignored repeated warnings of an
impending massacre in Rwanda in 1994, paving the way for an orgy of
ethnic killing that left 800,000 Tutsi and moderate Hutu dead in
less than 100 days, an independent panel reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community did not prevent the genocide, nor
did it stop the killing once the genocide had begun,'' said the
report. This stemmed from a ``lack of resources and political
will'' before and after the massacre of Tutsis by the minority
Hutus began on April 6, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, who was then head of UN
peacekeeping forces, the United States, and Belgium all bear some
responsibility for failing to stop the genocide, the investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggested that the United States put controlling the
cost of peacekeeping operations above saving lives and accused
Belgium of pulling its peacekeeping troops out too quickly _ at one
point abandoning 2,000 people in a technical school and leaving
many of them to be murdered.
</P>
<P>
   The findings marked the second time in two months that the UN
has acknowledged failing to stop mass killings that could have been
prevented. In an internal report in October, the UN accepted blame
for the massacre of thousands of Bosnian Moslem men in 1995 in
Srebrenica, Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both reports _ my own on Srebrenica, and that of the
independent inquiry on Rwanda _ reflect a profound determination to
present the truth about these calamities,'' Annan said Thursday in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Annan requested the inquiry into the Rwanda massacre last March.
The panel, which began work in June, was headed by former Swedish
Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson, former South Korean Foreign
Minister Han Sung-Joo, and Nigerian Major General Rufus Kuolati.
</P>
<P>
   Their 58-page report said the mandate the Security Council gave
the UN peacekeeping force in Rwanda was inadequate and its rules of
engagement unclear. It said UN officials, including Annan, failed
to act after receiving direct evidence of a carefully planned
genocide, and former UN chief Boutros Boutros-Ghali did not inform
the Security Council of the information.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Annan admitted that the UN stood by
during a genocide the ``purest and most evil form.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us must bitterly regret that we did not do more to
prevent it. There was a United Nations force in the country at the
time, but it was neither mandated nor equipped for the kind of
forceful action which would have been needed to prevent or halt the
genocide. On behalf of the United Nations, I acknowledge this
failure and express my deep remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's statement was criticized by some diplomats and human
rights officials as falling short of the ``clear apology'' to the
Rwandan people that the report demanded.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan's spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said, ``The word `remorse'
is stronger than sorry.'' Annan has not considered resigning or
disciplining any UN officials involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report singled out Annan for failing to act on numerous
cables sent to New York by Canadian Brig. Gen. Romeo Dallaire, head
of the UN peacekeeping mission in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   As early as November 1993, Dallaire asked that the rules of
engagement be broadened to allow UN peacekeepers to use force to
stop ethnically motivated crimes. ``Headquarters never responded
formally to the force commander's request for approval,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, 1994, Dallaire sent a cable citing an informant who
had brought the UN details of a trained militia of 1,700 Hutus who
were prepared to kill up to 1,000 Tutsi in 20 minutes in the
capital, Kigali. Annan did not alert Boutros-Ghali to the cable,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Later the same day, Annan overruled a request by Dallaire to use
``overwhelming force'' to prevent the planned attacks, saying such
a step was beyond the Security Council's mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Annan shares the blame with other UN officials,
the Security Council, and the US government. During a trip to
Rwanda last year, President Clinton apologized for Washington's
failure to act. He has cited the Rwandan bloodbath as one reason he
backed NATO's intervention on behalf of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   One European diplomat criticized the report, however, saying it
``does not take into account is the context of the times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of public reaction to the fiasco in Somalia,''
added the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 US servicemen were killed and one dragged through the
dusty roads of Mogadishu in 1993, the American public and Congress
soured on UN peacekeeping efforts. In May 1994, a month after the
Rwanda massacres began, President Clinton issued a directive
putting strict conditions on US support for UN peacekeeping, with
an emphasis on keeping down the costs.
</P>
<P>
   This led to a reduction in the size of the UN force as the
killings got under &UR;  &LR; way. ``It will always be difficult to explain
why the United Nations decided to reduce the troops from 2,500 to a
minimum force once the genocide started, and increase the numbers
to 5,500 when the genocide was over,'' said Carlsson, who headed
the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommended that the secretary-general develop a plan
to prevent future genocide by giving all peacekeeping operations
authorization to use force to ``prevent acts of genocide or gross
violations of human rights wherever they may occur.'' Annan is
planning a new set of initiatives on humanitarian intervention,
Eckhard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
