<HEADER>
A1301 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LATIN-XMASDINNER     12-16 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-XMASDINNER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traditional Christmas Eve meal overflows with food
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _In Latin homes across South Florida,
there's no waiting for the big Christmas dinner _ it's on Christmas
Eve, or Nochebuena.
</P>
<P>
   With many variations, Cubans, Spaniards, Puerto Ricans and
Mexicans celebrate the birth of Christ on Dec. 24 with a lavish
feast of symbolic and traditional regional dishes, games and music,
and Midnight Mass _ Misa del Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Isasi, owner of Casa Gabriel in West Palm Beach, will
celebrate Nochebuena as he did in Jovellanos, Cuba, as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year the feast moved _ from friends' to families'
houses. We'd always have a big crowd, 20 to 50 people or more,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The meal begins Dec. 23, with the men cooking the pig, usually
outside on a spit or in the ground. It roasts almost all night, and
must be watched during the cooking. ``It's a great excuse to play
dominoes and drink beer,'' Isasi said, laughing. The women,
meanwhile, are preparing the rest of the food in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then about 7 o'clock on Christmas Eve, the families and
friends gather and we put all the foods out and everybody eats.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the roast pig, ``there's a turkey _ even in Cuba.
That's because some of the old people can't eat the pig, so we have
a turkey. There's boiled yuca with mojo (garlic and citrus sauce).
Two kinds of black beans _ the moros, which is the black beans
mixed with rice, and then plain black beans served with plain rice.
Cuban tamales are different from Mexican tamales. Ours are made
with fresh corn, not the dried masa harina. They're filled always
with pork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salads have avocado and lettuce and onion, and have radishes _
that's a tradition. We also serve membrillo, (a fruit paste
traditionally made of quince) and cheeses. And preserved orange
rind and grapefruit and papayas in heavy syrup with cream cheese,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bunuelos, a fried pastry made with sweet potatoes and squash, is
drizzled with a sugar syrup flavored with a cinnamon stick. The
dough is twisted into a figure eight or pretzel shape; a
traditional Christian symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my favorite, the turron _ almond candied nougat and pastes
imported from Spain. These are always served at Christmas time. We
have them year round now, but when I was a child, only at
Christmas. They are imported _ we don't grow almonds in Cuba,''
Isasi said.
</P>
<P>
   Some families, he said, serve plantains and flan and maybe a
fish dish; the menu can vary according to family preference and the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we eat all night long, the feast goes on and on. The
musicians come and play, with guitars, and they go singing from
house to house. You give them some money.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meal, the men retire with their cafe Cubano (Cuban
coffees), often spiked with anisette or brandy, and puros _ Havana
cigars; women clean up. There are no gifts exchanged; that takes
place on Three Kings Day _ January 6, he said. ``And it's just for
the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholic families may wait to eat until after Midnight Mass, for
which some fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's mostly a feast day, the biggest feast of the year,''
Isasi said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Latin countries celebrate the same way, with huge meals
and perhaps the largest family gathering of the year, but with
slightly different foods.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans serve a turkey with mole sauce, green chili and instead
of the buneulos, they serve sopaipillas _ a variation of the fried
dough that forms a crispy pillow into which honey is poured.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish include baked red cabbage with apples, almond soup,
red snapper and fried turnovers called bollinas. Their meal is
served in several courses and typically begins with nuts and
cheese, then soup and roast chicken. The dessert is a brazo gitano,
a cream-filled sponge cake covered with a sherry syrup and topped
with meringue.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans include vianda, assorted boiled roots and arroz
con gandules (rice with pigeon peas) in their Nochebuena meal. A
paranda, a pick-up musical band of serenaders, travels from house
to house, sometimes into the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
