<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACE-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL, SYRIA AGREE TO ANOTHER ROUND OF HISTORIC PEACE TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa agreed Thursday to continue their
peace talks in the Virginia countryside Jan. 3 as they wrapped up
two days of White House discussions mediated by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement before the two men left Washington, Clinton
sounded a hopeful note that the next round of talks may finally
yield the framework for a long-sought comprehensive Middle East
peace settlement, which has been so illusive over the 51 years
since the state of Israel was created, setting off a series of
Arab-Israeli conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 48 hours Israel and Syria have taken a critical
step in the journey toward peace. With courage and perseverance on
both sides, the result will be deeply rewarding to the people of
Israel and to the people of Syria,'' Clinton said at the conclusion
of the first ever high-level talks between the two long-time
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   He called their discussions, which took place at Blair House
across Pennsylvania Avenue from the presidential mansion, ``a new
beginning.'' But he acknowledged that ``the journey will be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Barak nor al-Sharaa spoke after Clinton's brief remarks,
nor did they shake hands when encouraged to by photographers and
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined to provide any details about the talks that
began Wednesday or what the outline for negotiations would be when
they continue at as yet undetermined location in northern Virginia
just outside Washington. But he said the two men agreed ``to take
steps to ensure that these negotiations will be conducted in a
productive and positive atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters a short time later, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said both sides had agreed to do what they can
to rein in terrorist activities that might disrupt negotiations.
White House National Security Adviser Sandy Berger also indicated
that al-Sharaa had promised that Syria would ``use its influence''
in helping to control the activities in Lebanon of the militant
Arab group Hezbollah, which engages Israeli forces almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ... spoke about the necessity of reining in those forces
that create terrorist activities,'' Albright said, adding that
Barak and al-Sharaa understand ``the importance of doing everything
possible not to let terrorism disrupt what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the commitments an important part of the
``confidence-building measures'' needed to reinforce the decision
by Israel and Syria to revive the peace negotiations that broke off
between them four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no handshake between Barak and al-Sharaa,
Albright said ``the bottom line'' in their two days of talks was
that both men demonstrated ``real movement'' toward establishing
more friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spoke about each other as partners and neighbors. And so
that leads me to believe that despite the difficulties, which we
all know will exist, it does make me believe that this can be
done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Syrian officials characterized the talks as
constructive, adding that both men were satisfied with the progress
made and had agreed to do what they can to help sell a peace
agreement to their people.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, said one Israeli official, also asked al-Sharaa for
``some signs'' from Syria as the negotiations move forward that
Israel's security concerns will be adequately addressed in any
final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Knesset, Israel's parliament, signaled its support
for the talks in a vote last week, Barak is still under pressure
not to sign on to any deal that will return all of the Golan
Heights territory captured from Syria during the 1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is demanding the return of the Golan Heights to its
pre-1967 boundaries, which would mean that some 18,000 Israeli
settlers would be forced to leave the territory now controlled by
the Israeli military.
</P>
<P>
   In her briefing for reporters, Albright said that ``all the
issues'' between the nations would be ``on the table,'' including
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights, mutual security
concerns, a timetable for fulfilling all the terms of an agreement,
and anything else necessary to normalize relations and establish a
peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
   She said Barak and al-Sharaa had demonstrated ``a very clear
determination'' to reach an agreement sometime next year before
Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's characterization of the talks as ``friendly'' at
times seemed to belie the rocky start Wednesday when al-Sharaa
surprised and angered Clinton and Barak by criticizing at length
the Israeli occupation of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton did not mention the remarks specifically in his
brief statement Thursday, he noted rather pointedly that the two
sides had ``agreed that there should be no looking back'' as
negotiations proceed.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official said Clinton secured a promise from
both sides to refrain from making ``inflammatory'' statements that
could disrupt the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The White House talks were not expected to yield a breakthrough
leading to an immediate deal ending more than 50 years of
Arab-Israeli hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did get what he had hoped for, which was a general
framework for continuing negotiations early next year that could
lead to an agreement ending the last remaining dispute between
Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis, beginning with the Camp David Accords in 1978
spearheaded by then-President Carter, have settled their
differences with Egypt and Jordan, and is now engaged in working
out the final details of a peace arrangement with the Palestinians
in the West Bank and Gaza. A deal with Syria would finally yield
the comprehensive peace between the Arabs and Israel that has so
elusive since the creation of the Jewish state in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   If such an agreement emerges, Clinton would deserve a large
share of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart denied, however, that
Clinton is pushing for an agreement before he leaves office Jan.
20, 2001. He bristled at a reporter's suggestion that Clinton's
motives may be driven by his desire to enhance his legacy, which
may be noted more for the Monica Lewinsky affair than anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president believes we're at a historic moment
right now. That's what the president's focus is,'' Lockhart said.
``There's pressure to take advantage of this opportunity now and
not to squander it, and (it has) nothing to do with the president's
own time or tenure in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also emphasized the importance of seizing the moment,
insisting that the isolation and news blackout of negotiations next
month will increase the odds for success.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia meetings will be modeled after the Wye River
sessions that produced an agreement between Israel and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat. There were few public briefings and no access
for reporters during the course of those talks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
