<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1304 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-920     12-16 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND SYRIA TO BEGIN INTENSIVE TALKS NEXT MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT 7-11 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of Syria and Israel agreed to begin
intensive and accelerated talks early next month intended to end
the state of war that has existed between them for 50 years,
President Clinton announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned that ``the journey will be tough'' when the talks
start near Washington, and he pointedly did not predict success.
But he emphasized the determination of the Israelis and the Syrians
to negotiate in good faith and promised American aid at every step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 48 hours,'' Clinton said, ``Israel and Syria
have taken critical steps in the journey toward peace. That journey
will be a difficult one. But with courage and perseverance on both
sides, the result will be deeply rewarding to the people of Israel
and to the people of Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   The president announced the talks in a five-minute statement on
the White House driveway Thursday afternoon. Prime Minister Ehud
Barak of Israel stood tight-lipped and mute to his right; Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria stood in impassive silence to
his left.
</P>
<P>
   The three men returned to the West Wing of the White House after
the president's remarks without answering reporters' shouted
questions. Clinton guided them with a hand on each of their backs,
but the Israeli and the Syrian did not speak or shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the moment was heavy with promise and symbolism, coming
after nearly four years of cold silence between the two nations.
President Hafez Assad of Syria, who is thought to be in ill health,
did not attend the talks, but it is clear that al-Sharaa carries
his proxy.
</P>
<P>
   This week's talks about talks, which began on Wednesday morning
in the Oval Office, had a narrow goal: to set a time and ground
rules for more formal negotiations on the issues that divide Israel
and Syria. Those include borders _particularly the status of the
strategic Golan Heights _ security, terrorism, water rights and
diplomatic and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Those substantive matters were not on the table and were dealt
with only obliquely. Thus, all three parties could claim that the
two days of talks were an unqualified success.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations will resume on Jan. 3 at a location that has
not yet been chosen. State Department officials are searching for a
location near Washington that is secure and secluded but also close
enough for Clinton to reach on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   No deadline has been set for securing an agreement and White
House aides said the talks would continue as long as they are
making progress. Barak and al-Sharaa agreed to stay in the United
States for an extended period, or to break off for a time and
return, if the prospect of success remains, a senior White House
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But an Israeli official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said that Barak was not willing to conduct open-ended
negotiations without the promise of a comprehensive settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton briefed several world leaders by telephone after the
discussions concluded on Thursday, according to a White House
spokesman. He called Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader; Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain, President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt,
Crown Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia, King Abdullah of Jordan and
King Muhammad VI of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, Syrians and Israelis agreed not to discuss the
substance of the talks conducted over the past two days, and for
the most part kept the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and al-Sharaa decided not to speak on the White House
driveway on Thursday afternoon, in part because al-Sharaa's bitter
harangue on Wednesday morning about Israeli occupation of Syrian
territory morning was poorly received by Israeli and American
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told an Israeli reporter as he was entering his limousine
to leave the White House on Thursday afternoon that the talks were
``hard, but we're on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadi Baltiansky, Barak's spokesman, said: ``Overall, the
atmosphere was quite positive. It was the first step in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa made no comments as he left the White House, nor did
any other member of the Syrian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   American officials were more expansive, but offered few details
of the substance or the tenor of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, a sense of relief that the initial round had
borne fruit, and a guarded optimism that next month's more pointed
negotiations could lead to a peace treaty that would forever change
the psychological and physical map of the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is significant is that the two sides at the very highest
level met together for first time in 50 years and decided to launch
serious negotiations to reach a peace agreement,'' Sandy Berger,
the national security adviser, said on Thursday night in an
interview. ``I think that's a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``They opened a gate. They now have to walk down a
very bumpy road and I can't say for sure whether they will succeed.
But I can say they are embarking on this with a serious intent to
reach an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger described the atmosphere of the talks as proper and
cordial, but not warm. He said the Israeli prime minister and the
Syrian foreign minister spoke informally during negotiating
sessions but did not appear to establish anything approaching
camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa, for example, refused to shake Barak's hand in public.
He told American officials that he would reserve that gesture for a
more significant moment.
</P>
<P>
   If a warmer personal relationship is to develop, Berger said, it
will grow from the more intensive discussions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A senior State Department official who handles Middle East
matters said Barak and al-Sharaa refuse to follow any script, even
one written by the chief sponsor of the talks, the United States.
And while there will be an element of theatrics to the negotiations
_ the withheld handshake, for instance _ there will also be
substance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meat is that both sides have their own reasons for wanting
to come to a deal and they're not going to let theatrics get in the
way of that,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks on Thursday afternoon, Clinton said Israel has
embarked on serious negotiations with the Palestinians and the
Syrians and talks on Lebanon are expected soon. He said the world
could hope to see a ``new and different'' Middle East in the coming
months and pledged American assistance ``every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on the Syrian track, American participation is crucial.
Hostility and distrust are so deep that neither side is yet willing
to speak without an interlocutor present. At no time during the
past two days did al-Sharaa and Barak meet alone.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is thus destined to be mediator, guarantor and
ultimately underwriter of any peace between Israel and Syria. The
costs will be large, but the administration is prepared to ask
Congress for a multi-billion-dollar package to implement an
agreement, should one be reached next year.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said that the two days of
discussions had been ``inspiring'' because of the apparent depth of
commitment to peace by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a sense of great movement forward and a
sense of hope, but also a very realistic view of the fact that
we've got a lot to do,'' Albright said at a briefing after the
leaders left the White House. ``And so these two days were filled
with hope and also frank realism about the amount of work that
needed to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
