<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL, SYRIA AGREE TO SECOND ROUND OF TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Signaling their determination to intensify a
historic push for peace, Israeli and Syrian leaders have agreed,
after two days of face-to-face, talks to return to Washington in a
little over two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called the first round of talks and the
leaders' commitment to resume negotiations a ``good start'' toward
a land-for-peace deal _ giving all or most of the Golan Heights
back to Syria in exchange for peaceful relations and security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   The talks between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa were described by US officials as
professional, businesslike and interspersed with a few informal and
friendly moments of inquiry about each other's family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the US officials said Thursday, they kept their physical
distance. There was no private handshake.
</P>
<P>
   The two men will meet again on Jan. 3 at an as yet undetermined
location close enough to Washington that will allow President
Clinton to participate as needed.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who spoke of hopes for a wider Mideast peace,
also said negotiations would be difficult. US officials said no
substantive agreements were reached in the two days of talks.
</P>
<P>
   As the State Department hunts for a secluded site, there was no
early word on the little-noticed but critical decision on the
comfort level of the surroundings, whether it should be as spartan
and severe as the Dayton Talks in 1995 that encouraged Balkan
leaders to stay at the table or as pleasing outdoors as the Camp
David presidential retreat nearly two decades ago that encouraged
informal walks.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty was that neither Camp David, site of the
historic Israel-Egypt talks, nor the Wye Plantation, site of the
difficult Israel-Palestinian negotiations last year, would be
chosen. Syria and Israel have vetoed both places because of the
connotations each site would raise.
</P>
<P>
   The content of the Israeli-Syria talks for the last two days
remained a closely held secret, although Israeli officials said
they discussed their security need for Syria to control Hezbollah
guerrillas in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Sharaa sat across a table from each other at a room at
the Blair House, a presidential guest house across from the White
House, and had a ``very good personal interaction that I think
helped'' the talks, said Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright,
who sat at one end of the table.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that both leaders talked not just about their
issues, but about a wider peace that could result from an
Israeli-Syria deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found interesting, really, from both sides is the fact
that they see what they're doing as historic and opening up the
possibility for an entirely different relationship, not only
between Israel and Syria, but for the Middle East as a whole,''
Albright told reporters. ``We are talking about something that is a
qualitative difference in the relationship within the region.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli-Syria deal is likely to encompass four major
components: withdrawal of Israeli settlements from the Golan
Heights, the timetable for withdrawal, mutual security and the
diplomatic, economic and cultural nature of relations.
</P>
<P>
   But tied into the deal is Lebanon, which Syria essentially
controls. Alongside an Israeli-Syrian deal, US officials expect a
companion Israeli-Lebanese arrangement in which Israel would
withdraw its troops from southern Lebanon and the Lebanese army
would control Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Syrian and Israeli negotiations off to a good start,
Israeli-Lebanese negotiations expected to begin soon and the
Palestinian track well under way, we can truly set our sights on a
new and different Middle East,'' Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But both Clinton and Albright Thursday sounded cautionary notes
about first securing an Israeli-Syrian deal.
</P>
<P>
   Said the president: ``The journey will be tough. Nothing in the
past 48 hours should lead us to believe otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was specifically referring to the talks between
Barak and Sharaa, the past two days also included fresh violence in
southern Lebanon, last active Arab-Israeli warfront.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-supported Southern Lebanese Army fired mortar rounds
at the Arab Selim village in south Lebanon Thursday, hitting near a
school and wounding 20 Lebanese children. The attack was a response
to Hezbollah guerrilla attack on a village inside
Israeli-controlled South Lebanon that wounded a children.
</P>
<P>
   Even as television pictures Thursday showed chairs scattered in
the school, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy, at the end of the
Washington talks, told Israel's Channel One television:
</P>
<P>
   ``If there will be a hostile situation there (in southern
Lebanon), everything we are doing will blow up,'' Levy said in
Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the talks, the highest level discussions ever between
Israel and Syria in their 51 years of enmity, the White House had
strategically attempted to lower expectations from the Barak-Sharaa
meeting. The goal was simply to set another round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set our expectations at the bottom of the barrel,'' one US
official said on condition of anonymity. The official called the
talks ``good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication on how long either leader would stay.
There also was little indication about the lasting impact of
Sharaa's strong words Wednesday at the opening of the talks in
which he said that the world has failed to recognize that Syria was
the wronged party in Israel's capture of the Golan Heights in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Said one Israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity:
``We know he was talking to a Syria-Arab audience. But it didn't
help us. It just ignited the opposition back home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
