u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-900(T     12-16 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-900(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIANS DODGE GUNFIRE TO FLEE INTENSE RUSSIAN BOMBING OF GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERVOMAISKAYA, Russia _ Desperate civilians fleeing the
blistering Russian bombardment of Grozny said Thursday that they
had to run a gantlet of gunfire in the humanitarian corridor set up
by the Russian army.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees interviewed at this checkpoint six miles from the
outskirts of Grozny said a bus full of refugees was riddled with
machine gun fire, leaving four wounded, and at least one car burst
into flames. Mortars exploded as elderly civilians, women and
children huddled in a ditch for hours before making the long,
chilly walk to Russian-controlled Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the refugees said the terrifying Russian bombardment had
persuaded them to take their chances on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to leave today because I could be dead tomorrow if I
stayed,'' said Abdrazak Dovletmirzayev, 64. ``The Russians are
really bombarding us very heavily now. There are artillery strikes
every night. It is really horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   As the battle for Grozny has begun, residents say the city is
being pounded relentlessly. Russian commanders do not plan a
frontal assault on the capital but plan to move cautiously to take
Grozny neighborhood by neighborhood. As they prepare to mount
reconnaissance raids into the city, they are depending heavily on
their advantage in firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters reported from Grozny on Wednesday that more than 100
Russian soldiers were killed and 15 armored vehicles destroyed on a
doomed expedition into the center of the city. The Russian military
reacted angrily to the story, denying that any fighting had taken
place within the city limits. Military spokesmen said that two
soldiers were killed, but they did not say where.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian plan calls for evacuating as many of Grozny's
civilians as possible before the fighting comes to a head. But only
4,500 have used the two humanitarian corridors so far, Sergei
Shoigu, Russia's minister for emergency situations, said at the
Russian military base at Mozdok Thursday. Shoigu said that between
7,000 and 45,000 civilians are still living in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The question for them is what is safer: to stay and risk dying
from Russian bombs and starvation or to risk being fired at in the
safety corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They open a corridor for us and when we try to leave we are
turned into kasha,'' said Lyubov Shakhtemirova, 48, using the
Russian word for porridge.
</P>
<P>
   In the turmoil around the capital, it was difficult to determine
who was doing the shooting. Gen. Ivan I. Babichev, the senior
military commandant of the Russian-controlled zone in Chechnya,
blamed the Islamic militants, saying that they were trying to
discourage the civilians from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shoot at the entrance of the corridor from the city,''
Babichev said. ``They are trying to preserve their human shields.''
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees, however, blamed the Russian forces, though
shell-shocked civilians who passed through the checkpoint here
Thursday said they did not get a good look at their attackers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Grozny was established in the 19th century as a Russian
fortress. The very name of the city means ``menacing.'' And it
certainly lived up to its name Thursday _ for the civilians, for
the Islamic rebels and for the Russians troops.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny has also become a symbol of the West's inability to
influence Russians or the militants they are fighting. Knut
Vollebaek, the chairman of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe and Norway's foreign minister, completed a
three-day trip to the Caucasus Thursday by visiting the
Russian-controlled part of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek has talked in very general terms about the need for
negotiations and has repeatedly urged a cease-fire. The Russians
have listened to his proposals but without any apparent interest.
And at Pervomaiskaya Thursday, the European diplomat was little
more than a bystander.
</P>
<P>
   ``The counter-terrorism operation is underway and nobody is
going to stop it,'' Shoigu said. ``We do not need any mediators
involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, in fact, the fate of Grozny's civilians was not the
main story. Rather, it was the news reports that the Russian
reconnaissance force in Grozny had been wiped out by Islamic
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russian spokesmen disputed the report, Russian
commanders have said in recent days that numerous raids and
reconnaissance probes will be carried out to reclaim the city. The
operations within the city, they said, are to be conducted by
Interior Ministry forces with the support of a small number of
Chechen militia, which is supporting the Russian side.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Babichev predicted in his interview that the city would be
firmly under Russian control within a month and invited a reporter
to visit him in January in his new office in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   At the checkpoint near Pervomaiskaya, it was clear that the
battle for Grozny was entering a decisive phase. The civilians who
trudged through Checkpoint North, located in the hills overlooking
the city, were passed by a column of Russian armor and trucks
heading toward the capital as artillery and rocket fire rumbled in
the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing is increasing,'' said Dzhamlat Abuyev, 20, who
staggered through the checkpoint, exhausted by a long and
treacherous hike from Grozny. ``That's why I left. But we were shot
at and had to abandon the car we left in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shakhtemirova had a particularly harrowing tale of her
flight through the humanitarian corridor. She had taken refuge in a
basement with her child. Last month, she joined a small group of
civilians that tried to escape to the south but turned back after
they were raked by fire, dragging their dead with them. Her knees
are still scrapped from crawling along the ground to avoid the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But as her food _ mostly pickled vegetables _ began to run out,
she decided to make another run for it. There is some food for sale
in Grozny, she said, but noodles, rice and vegetable oil are being
sold for more than twice the amount charged in pricey Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were starving,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And with Russian troops tightening their stranglehold on the
city, it was also clear that the time to try an escape was running
short. Rumors have swept Grozny that the corridor will only be open
until December 28, with stepped-up Russian assaults on the rebel
positions in Grozny to follow.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Shakhtemirova joined a group of 50 civilians packed into
a bus that moved out of Grozny Thursday morning. Suddenly, she
said, the vehicle was riddled with machine gun fire and its tires
were shot out. Mortars exploded around it. Two cars behind the bus
caught on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The civilians _ many elderly, as well as women and children _
climbed out of the bus and took refuge in a roadside ditch for two
hours. Finally, they ventured out of the trench and made the long,
cold trek to Checkpoint North at the end of the corridor. Four
civilians were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out of the bus with our white flags, but they kept
shooting,'' she said. ``We don't know exactly where the shooting
was coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Dovletmirzayev trudged through Checkpoint North a little while
later. He had tried to ride out the war in Grozny so he could keep
an eye on his small apartment even though that meant surviving
entirely on tea and a ration of bread, which he baked himself. The
intensifying bombardment finally persuaded him to leave, but he
also reported that the safety corridor was anything but safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a shooting on the road,'' he said. ``A car with a
trailer was hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Dovletmirzayev said his trek to the checkpoint had taken six
hours. He moved slowly though the checkpoint, pulling a small wagon
with his belongings: soap, several cans of food, a razor and an
extra pair of trousers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all that I have at 64 years,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
