<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND LAWMAKERS BRAINSTORM ON BEST WAYS TO LOWER PRICES
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND-DRUGS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT   (rk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. _ Legislative leaders from the four northern New
England states gathered here Thursday to plot joint strategies for
lowering the price of prescription drugs, from imposing local price
controls to pooling their residents to demand a regional mass
discount.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, the first of its kind, was largely a brainstorming
session, but participants said it could grow into a movement among
states to forge ahead where Congress had balked, and pass laws
forcing the pharmaceutical industry to cut prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress could solve this problem in four hours,'' said Peter
Shumlin, president pro tem of the Vermont Senate, ``but they're
choosing not to because pharmaceutical companies give them gobs of
money for their election campaigns. So we have a responsibility as
states to see what we can do while Congress is sitting on its
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The envoys from Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Vermont
agreed to explore several avenues. They included price controls on
drugs at the state level _ bills to impose such controls are in the
works in Maine and Vermont _ and pooling residents into a sort of
big buying club to negotiate the kind of discount that, say, Canada
has. They also said they planned to invite Connecticut, New York,
Rhode Island and Quebec into the process.
</P>
<P>
   Many details _ in fact, virtually all the details _ remain to be
worked out about how the states can collaborate in challenging the
drug industry. But New England legislatures are known for
undertaking bold social experiments, and by meeting's end, there
was a consensus that the initiative was worth pursuing. The
attendees agreed to an interstate conference call next week and a
second, larger meeting soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Drug company representatives were not invited to the conference.
But the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, the
industry's trade association, issued a statement saying that the
solution to the financial crunch that many Americans, especially
the elderly, face in paying for their medications lies not with
government controls but with Medicare reform and broadened
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Price controls ``tell private investors all around the world
that they can earn a higher return on their money if it's invested
in other industries,'' Judith H. Bello, the trade association's
executive vice president, said in a phone interview. Such controls
are bad for the momentum of pharmaceutical research, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for bulk-buying or pooling arrangements, Ms. Bello said, a
Maine commission had recently decided against bulk buying as too
cumbersome and costly, and a bulk-buying plan in the works in
Massachusetts is raising heated debate.
</P>
<P>
   The association also expressed skepticism about the possibility
that the New England states could create a ``pharmaceutical
compact'' much like the regional dairy compact that sets milk
prices. Such a compact, its statement said, ``could take years to
design and implement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, though speakers at the meeting raised the idea of a
compact, no one appeared to have the patience at this point to
focus on such a politically complex solution: A compact would
require agreement among the states and congressional approval as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they shared some of the shorter-term measures that they
have been trying in their individual states. They heard about the
Massachusetts effort to create one big buyer pool out of 1.6
million residents, among them the uninsured and the poor, and
negotiate a mass discount. And about Maine's expansion of its
insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   From New Hampshire came descriptions of a new discount drug
program for senior citizens. And from Vermont, members of a special
legislative committee on drug prices described how they were
pinning many of their hopes on their proximity to Canada, even
considering state-run, medication-buying bus trips across the
border.
</P>
<P>
   It was largely out of that committee's frustration that
Thursday's effort at forging a regional bloc to circumvent Congress
grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to be as creative as we could,'' said Jan Backus, the
state senator who headed the panel, ``but everything we came up
with, there was a block put in place by the drug industry lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   They found they were not allowed by law to re-import drugs from
Canada, where they are much cheaper, Ms. Backus said; they were
also barred from joining the steep group discount the federal
government gets, and could not buy through Indian tribes who share
that discount. They also could not, under the Constitution, impose
price controls on out-of-state manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere we looked, we found a dead end,'' she said. ``It was
very frustrating and very clear we had to come together to make a
political case to get change in Washington, as well as coming
together to bulk buy.''
</P>
<P>
   To these state lawmakers, Congress has succumbed to
pharmaceutical companies and left the state legislatures to find
ways to help citizens pay for drugs. Several bills meant to ease
the pain of high drug prices are in the works in Congress, but the
New England envoys appeared to hold out little hope of a federal
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Obuchowski, the speaker of the Vermont House of
Representatives, said baldly that ``Congress has been bought off by
the pharmaceutical industry.'' In contrast, he said, Thursday's
meeting, in a purple-curtained chamber of the venerable State
House, was ``almost like a clean room environment,'' like those
used in chip manufacturing or space science.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also emphasized that they did not equate drug
companies with tobacco makers, whose products harm people. They
simply did not think Americans should pay significantly more than
people in other countries, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the meeting took home a draft resolution
proclaiming that they would work together as a coalition to
coordinate the passage of model laws to cut drug prices, to enter
joint purchasing agreements and more.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting pleased Anthony Pollina, a senior policy adviser for
the Vermont Public Interest Research Group, which has been pushing
for price-control laws for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that this has happened, that leaders of
any group of states have come together to talk about prescription
drugs,'' Pollina said, ``and I think it shows how serious the
problem is, and how serious state policy leaders are about
providing the leadership Congress won't and taking on the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others predicted that other states would begin to band
together to lower drug prices. First, however, the New Englanders
must show that such a group approach is effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a long battle,'' Obuchowski of Vermont
said. ``It's going to be a hard battle, depending on what approach
is taken, and I hope we bring to that battle the resolve to see it
through to the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
