<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1328 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RWANDA-REPORT-890(2TA     12-16 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-REPORT-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICIZES U.N. AND U.S. FOR FAILING TO PREVENT GENOCIDE IN
RWANDA
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(sw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A strongly worded report issued on Thursday by
an international panel of experts holds both the United Nations and
leading member countries, primarily the United States, responsible
for failing to prevent or stop the genocide in Rwanda in 1994,
which cost hundreds of thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   The report, commissioned by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who
was then head of the peacekeeping department, spares no one, naming
those in the highest reaches of the United Nations who were running
the operation in Rwanda, including Annan and his predecessor,
Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
   Annan and others in his department made weak and equivocal
decisions in the face of mounting disaster, the panel found. At the
same time the Clinton administration _ represented at the United
Nations by Madeleine Albright _ persistently played down the
problem, setting the tone for a Security Council generally lacking
the political will for a tougher response.
</P>
<P>
   Both the United Nations and the United States sent the wrong
message to militias bent on genocide, the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Annan called the report ``thorough and objective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of the United Nations, I acknowledge this failure
and express my deep remorse,'' he said, calling the events in
Rwanda ``genocide in its purest and most evil form.'' In Rwanda,
government officials said the secretary general should visit and
apologize in person.
</P>
<P>
   But the leader of the investigation, Ingvar Carlsson, a former
Swedish prime minister, did not place all the blame on the United
Nations. At a news conference on Thursday, he said it would
``always be difficult to explain'' why the Security Council _
managed by the world's major powers and not the U.N. bureaucracy _
decimated the peacekeeping force in Rwanda, reducing it to a few
hundred from 2,500 troops when the genocide began, and then
increasing the force to 5,500 when the weeks of massacres were
over.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which provided Carlsson's investigators with
minimal help and no documents during their six-month study,
effectively blocked the Security Council in 1993 and 1994 from
authorizing any significant action in Rwanda. No high-ranking
American officials involved in policy making at the time agreed to
meet the panel.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department said on Thursday that it had cooperated
fully with the investigation, adding that the United States has a
policy of not releasing classified documents to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with their assessment,'' said James B. Foley, a
State Department spokesman. ``We provided senior officials who
extensively briefed the panel and answered all their questions
satisfactorily.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley said those officials included William Woods, deputy
assistant secretary of state for international organizations, and
Richard Bogosian, one of the department's top Africa specialists.
Both men had studied all the records of the period and discussed
them with the panel, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Carlsson repeated the Clinton administration's
explanation that the loss of 18 American Rangers in Somalia in
October 1993 had scared the United States off peacekeeping for
domestic political reasons, particularly peacekeeping in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Carlsson said blame rested with ``those who didn't care at all,
who said Rwanda is a distant African country.'' On a trip to Rwanda
last year, President Clinton apologized for Washington's inaction.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations opened its archives and made all its former
officials available to the panel on Annan's orders. A U.N. official
said this led to an ``asymmetry'' in the damning details by which
U.N. actions could be judged compared with those of pivotal
governments. Belgium and France, whose peacekeepers were in the
field in Rwanda before and after the genocide, have conducted their
own investigations. The United States has not.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that about 800,000 people were killed in 100
days from April to July 1994, in a Hutu-led campaign of genocide
against Tutsi and moderate Hutu who often defended their neighbors
with their own lives. The killings in Rwanda set off a chain
reaction that led to the current war in Congo, the former Zaire,
involving more than half a dozen African nations.
</P>
<P>
   Annan appointed the three-member panel in May to conduct an
independent investigation into the U.N. role in the critical months
in Rwanda. Besides Carlsson, the members were Han Sung-joo of South
Korea, a former foreign minister and leading international affairs
scholar, and Rufus M. Kupolati of Nigeria, a retired lieutenant
general familiar with U.N. peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwanda report follows by several weeks the release of an
internal U.N. inquiry into problems in the Bosnia peacekeeping
operation that led to thousands of deaths in Serbian attacks on
Bosnian Muslims in Srebrenica and other towns. That report also
found fault with both the organization and Security Council
members.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
