<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teammates ready to play in Heritage, not watch it
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roy Johnson, Warren Broughton and Ronnie Jones have
watched the Heritage Bowl from the stands the past two years.
Saturday, the trio of Hampton University players will be competing
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   As former standouts together in high school, the three were home
during the holidays and were easily able to attend the annual event
at the Georgia Dome. This year they're playing in the game, and
Johnson is one of the primary reasons why.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 180-pound Johnson threw for 1,940 yards and 10
touchdowns in leading the Pirates to a 7-4 record. Last season,
Johnson completed 53.6 percent for 1,892 yards in leading the
Pirates to a 9-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   One of the team's losses this year came against Southern, 21-6
in October. Johnson, who has already earned an undergraduate degree
and is enrolled in grad school, will enter Saturday's game
motivated by that loss and what he perceives as unkind words from
the opposition's camp leading up to this rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been preparing for Southern, hoping to have an
opportunity to play them again,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I don't know if it was as much Roy as it was his
receivers in that game. We literally dropped 10 balls,'' said
Pirates coach Joe Taylor, whose team won back-to-back MEAC titles
and represented the league in the Division I-AA playoffs in 1997
and '98. ``Our receiver corps, to me, may be our biggest
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot for the Hampton receivers has been Broughton,
who leads the team with 504 receiving yards on 31 receptions. The
other former Redan player, the 6-5, 325-pound Jones, anchors the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Other Georgians expected to play a big role for Hampton include
cornerback Rashad Muhyee and defensive linemen Damon and Ira Dawson
from Westlake High in College Park and offensive guard Jason Thomas
of Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pirates hope to gain a measure of revenge against
Southern, they will need a big game from Johnson, who will finally
get a chance to play in the game he has watched from the stands the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy has provided a lot of great moments for the Hampton
family, on and off the field,'' Taylor said. ``We've won two
conference championships, and he's helped our program move to the
level where we've received some national attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
