<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-INDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING AIDS IN INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Renee Loth  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUMBAI, India _ Rabiya is a prostitute in Kamathipura, the
red-light district in South Bombay. It is not an easy life. With a
going rate of 20 to 250 rupees per sex act (50 cents to $6.25), it
is almost impossible for her to work herself out of the job, and
now she and 15,000 other sex workers in Bombay have added AIDS to
their list of dangers and degradations. ``Some men offer us more
money not to use a condom,'' she said through a translator. ``We
try to make them understand that the illness is here.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago Rabiya's life took on a new purpose. She was
recruited by Population Services International, a nongovernmental
organization, to join a sort of AIDS brigade. She was trained to
explain sexually transmitted diseases and the importance of using
condoms to her peers. Fresh-scrubbed and wearing uniform saris and
ID badges, Rabiya and about a dozen other streetwalkers look almost
like girl scouts. The impression is deepened when they greet a
group of foreign journalists with a chirpy, much-rehearsed chorus
of the spiritual ``This little light of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the work Rabiya and the others do is dead serious. Because
of India's 1 billion population, even a small percentage increase
in AIDS involves huge numbers of individuals. According to the UN
Program on AIDS, at least 4 million Indians are infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The red-light district project is an example of what is called
``social marketing'' _ the distribution of condoms, mosquito nets,
medicines, and other health aids vital to Third World countries.
When it comes to AIDS, social marketing targets people at high risk
_ prostitutes, long-distance truckers, prisoners _ and distributes
condoms and educational messages using everything from street
theater to mobile vans to key chains.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say social marketing is more effective than
government giveaways, which are often rejected as coercive, low in
quality, and ``unhip.'' Let's hope so for Rabiya's sake, India's,
and the world's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
