<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      12-16 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BEHIND HARD-LINE TALK, A WILLINGNESS TO CONCEDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-TALKS, MIDEAST-U.S., MIDEAST-WESTBANK,
MIDEAST-LEBANON.) 
(th) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing the cameras during a ceremony on Wednesday
meant to herald the resumption of Israeli-Syrian peace talks,
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria sounded every bit the
unreconstructed foe of the Jewish homeland.
</P>
<P>
   True to his genuinely hard-line persona, he did not make any
overtly conciliatory gesture, not even eye contact with Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel. This completely unnerved many
Israelis glued to their television sets for the historic moment,
although it reportedly heartened al-Sharaa's intended audience back
home.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, however, al-Sharaa did not display the same muscular
posture privately. Before the Israeli and Syrian leaders emerged
into the Rose Garden, they did shake hands, a senior Israeli
official said. Afterward, ensconced in the Blair House on Wednesday
and Thursday, the negotiations were ``not friendly, not hostile,
just businesslike,'' the Israeli said.
</P>
<P>
   Each side did indeed mean business, or the two would not have
bothered to break a 45-month freeze in talks. The proof lay in
Thursday's pledge: a genuine renewal of negotiations at an
accelerated pace.
</P>
<P>
   Although there may seem to be a puzzling inconsistency in
al-Sharaa's behavior, it fits a pattern in Israeli-Arab peace
negotiations. On every track, there is a private and public face to
the relationship. For both Israeli and Arab leaders, making peace
involves juggling two campaigns: one at the negotiating table, the
other on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations, concessions are inevitable. But publicly, some
leaders choose to present an implacable facade as defenders of
their own people's needs and rights.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this split posture serves the ultimate purpose of real
peace is debatable. It may help the parties reach a deal while
avoiding domestic discontent. But those who take this approach may
also be failing to educate their people, to prepare them for peace
by helping them move beyond deeply ingrained hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``By acting tough in public, you buy yourself some space to
negotiate in private,'' said Richard N. Haass, vice president of
the Brookings Institution, who was a staff member of the National
Security Council under President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the short run,'' he said. ``In the long run, you risk
emerging from negotiations with an agreement your population isn't
ready to buy. Or you limit yourself to a very spartan agreement so
people in the street don't see the signs of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question of whether a final peace achieved under
such conditions will be shallow or deep. Will it be nonbelligerence
or the genuine dawn of a new dynamic? Will it be a cool peace like
Israel has with Egypt 20 years after Camp David?
</P>
<P>
   The emotionally complicated relationship between the Israelis
and the Palestinians cannot be equated with the clearer-cut
conflict between the Israelis and the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Palestinian front, too, the officials' rhetoric can
often be belligerent at the same time that closed-door negotiations
with the Israelis are quite cordial. On the surface, judging from
the words, it can seem like a crisis. Behind the scenes, though,
progress is often being made.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, both
sincerely and with an eye on his conservative constituency, adopted
a hostile public personality toward the Palestinians and the Arab
world in general. Meanwhile, he was talking through a private
intermediary to the Syrians and negotiating peace deals with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, the contradiction caught up with him. His
government fell last winter partly because of the discordance
between his actions and his words.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the people are readier to change than their leaders
think or want. Some experts, for instance, believe that Syria's
president, Hafez Assad, and his emissary, al-Sharaa, are trapped
inside decades of their own dogma, while the Syrian people, eager
for the changes that peace could bring an insular, stagnant
society, are more moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned diplomats say they do not have faith in a peacemaking
style in which leaders combine private pragmatism with a public
dialogue that is coarse or inflamed. Many think that peacemaking
should be accompanied by public diplomacy by the leaders _ each
side speaking both to its own people and to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are catering to your home gallery, like al-Sharaa
did, you are undermining the other leader's support at home,'' said
Itamar Rabinovich, president of Tel Aviv University, a former
ambassador to the United States and a lead negotiator in previous
rounds of Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
   As president of Egypt, Anwar Sadat understood that he personally
had to campaign for Menachem Begin, the former Israeli prime
minister and his peace partner at Camp David. He went so far as to
journey to Jerusalem and address the Israeli Parliament. It helped
in Israel, but one Palestinian official recently said that he
believed Sadat, who was assassinated, to some extent paid for that
with his life.
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Rabin, the Israeli prime minister who was assassinated
in 1995, made a point of telling his people how hard it was for him
to cross the threshold from enemy to peace partner with Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader. He made clear his discomfort with
their handshake, in a way that helped nudge Israelis along the path
he had traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has made a point of using his public engagements in Israel
to reach out to Syrian and Palestinian leaders. In speeches to
Parliament, he has praised both Assad and Arafat. Telling
Palestinians that he is trying to see things through their eyes, he
has legitimized their suffering, which sends a strong message to
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Without such messages, people can be confused when their leaders
finally close a peace deal, and the peace itself can be fragile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
