<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SEEKS TO BLOCK RUSSIAN LOAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-CHECHNYA) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House officials called Thursday on the
independent Export-Import Bank of the United States to delay or
cancel a pending $500 million loan package to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the aid, in the form of loan guarantees to a
Russian oil company for the purchase of U.S. equipment, should be
blocked because of allegations that the Russian company had
defrauded foreign investors in another deal.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said their position was not related to Russia's
war in Chechnya, but there has been a growing debate at the White
House and at the State Department about whether approval of the
transaction would send the wrong signal as the Russian army wages
an increasingly bloody conflict in the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund, in which the United States is
the largest shareholder, is also continuing to withhold a $640
million loan to Russia because Russia has failed to meet the
necessary economic and financial conditions, though this
explanation has been greeted with skepticism by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Export-Import Bank is an independent agency whose charter
precludes it from making decisions based on political
considerations. It had scheduled a board meeting for Friday to vote
on the loan guarantees, but postponed the meeting until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bank makes its decisions independently of the
administration, the State Department can halt loans if it
determines that the recipient violates human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The guarantees are to go to Tyumen Oil Co., which has been
embroiled in a dispute with BP Amoco, one of the world's largest
oil producers, and investors including George Soros. The fight is
over Tyumen's acquisition _ at a bargain price through a bankruptcy
proceeding _ of an oilfield in which BP Amoco and Soros were part
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Another investor in the oilfield, the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, denounced the bankruptcy deal as a
``sham'' that raised questions about the Russian government's
commitment to attracting foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the issue by reporters Thursday, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said, ``I have my people looking into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House took a harder line, clearly intending to
send a public signal to the bank even as White House officials said
the administration was not lobbying the bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   White House aides said that Gene Sperling, the director of the
National Economic Council at the White House, had concluded that
there was enough merit to the allegations that Tyumen had acquired
the oilfield in an unscrupulous manner that the bank should at
least delay its decision while the legal fight over the acquisition
goes forward.
</P>
<P>
   They said Sperling was concerned that going ahead with the loans
now could be perceived as a reward for a Russian company that had
undermined the country's halting efforts to develop laws and rules
for the conduct of business.
</P>
<P>
   The loans are tricky for the administration not just because of
the Russian assault on Chechnya. Vice President Al Gore's rivals in
the presidential race have intermittently raised questions about
whether he failed to act aggressively enough in demanding that
Russia clamp down on corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
