<SLUG> BC-ART-SFMOMA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO CURATOR TAKES JOB AT MOMA 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH BAKER  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gary Garrels, chief curator at the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art, has been appointed chief curator of drawings
and curator of painting and sculpture at the Museum of Modern Art
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the hardest decision of my life, bar none,''
Garrels said. ``SFMOMA has extraordinary staff and one of the great
boards of any museum in the world. I'm always going to keep a close
relationship with the Bay Area. And I think MOMA in New York sees
SFMOMA as one of its key colleague institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   As New York MOMA's curator of drawings, Garrels will head a
nine-member department. ``As a curator within painting and
sculpture,'' he said, `n task will be to think about
acquisition strategies and collection presentation in tandem with
drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrels formally assumes his new position in May but will be
actively involved in several SFMOMA projects already under way.
</P>
<P>
   They include retrospectives of American artists Sol LeWitt and
Robert Gober and a survey of the outstanding private collection of
Harry and Mary Margaret Anderson of Atherton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have some cushion for learning MOMA's huge drawing
collection,'' Garrels said, as MOMA will gradually gear down its
programs at the end of 2000 to permit expansion into an adjacent
53rd Street lot long occupied by the Hotel Dorset, a project to be
finished by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting activity will not be affected'' by MOMA's gearing
down, Garrels said. ``If anything, it will intensify.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrels, 48, came to SFMOMA in 1993 from the Walker Art Center
in Minneapolis. He is already well known in New York for having
been director of programs at Dia Center for the Arts, Manhattan's
leading private, nonprofit art institution, before his stint in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
