<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-LANDROVER-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST LOOK AT YOU: HAVE YOU BEEN PLAYING IN THE MUD AGAIN?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROGER W. STRONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODBURY, Conn. _ ``Are we going up there?'' I asked the young
woman with the clipboard and a name tag that said Rachel. I was
referring to what, in another season, would be a ski slope.
``Sure,'' she said. ``It's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel checked me in, painted a big ``3'' on my windshield,
demonstrated how to put my Land Rover in low range with the center
differential locked, and directed me to park near a sign that said
Borneo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It had started to rain, so the weather was perfect for an
off-roading event of Land Rover owners. A year ago, I had leased a
Discovery and was told that I would be invited to an outing the
dealership sponsors each fall. (I have since learned that this is
done by all Land Rover dealers. Some have events as often as four
times a year.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five events were set for the morning session _ an afternoon
session was planned, too _ including a cross-country trek in the
woods and a descent on a ski slope. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The morning group had 13 cars divided into four teams. I was on
the Borneo team with two other Discoverys and a Range Rover. Borneo
was first to take on the cross-country course, through the woods,
across a stream and into the mud. As it kept raining steadily, the
mud got slicker and deeper. We soon found out what Land Rovers can,
and more important, cannot, do.
</P>
<P>
   My car led the Borneo team and got through most of the course
pretty easily. It was not so easy, however, for my teammates, one
of whom had just spent a couple of hundred dollars getting her car
detailed. We learned how to push, pull tow and employ other
techniques for helping one another get unstuck.
</P>
<P>
   Team Borneo got almost all the way through the mud. All that
remained was a fairly short uphill section, then it would be all
downhill. I made a run at the hill, got almost to the top and lost
traction. I backed down, got up a head of steam and tried again.
This time, I got a little farther up, but lost traction and went
into a wheel-spinning slide sideways to the right, stopping so that
a tree wound up behind me. That was it. The rain had turned the
hill to something resembling grease and I couldn't go up or down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three vehicles behind me turned around and headed back out
the way they came, through the mud. I waited _ stuck _ where I was.
A tractor materialized on the hill above and pulled me out up the
hill. From there, I was able to complete the course, the only
driver to finish.
</P>
<P>
   My teammates were still in the woods, working their way out
through the mud. Getting them out required cutting some new paths
around the mud bogs. It had taken all morning to get through one
event. The rest of the day's adventures were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   I was wet and muddy and didn't get to go up or down the ski
slope. My Discovery was coated with mud, inside and out, but I had
had more fun with a car than I have had in a long time. And I
learned a lot more than I would have without the rain. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
