<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INDICTS MONEY MANAGER ON FRAUD AND KICKBACK CHARGES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J.)   By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street money manager Alan B. Bond was indicted
Thursday on charges he took $6.9 million in kickbacks from
commissions paid to brokers to whom he steered his clients'
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Bond runs his own investment company and is also a regular guest
on the PBS's television program, ``Wall Street Week with Louis
Rukeyser.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11-count indictment returned in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan charged Bond with conspiracy, investment advisory fraud,
commercial bribery, and making false statements to the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends Bond, who is 38, had used three
brokerage firms to carry out his scheme from 1993 to 1998, having
them execute Nasdaq stock trades on behalf of his clients, then
taking kickbacks of 57 percent to 80 percent from commissions.
</P>
<P>
   A second man, Robert I. Spruill, a broker who worked at all
three brokerage firms, was charged Thursday with conspiracy and
fraud charges for his role in the scheme. The government contended
that he had set up a dummy corporation, called Satchmo Inc., which
was used to funnel commission kickbacks to Bond.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Bond could face five years in prison on each
count, said the office of Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in
Manhattan. The SEC, in a separate action, sued Bond, seeking
repayment of his gains and other civil penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The government contended Bond had concealed the scheme from the
clients he victimized, which included the National Basketball
Association, the City University of New York Investment Pool, and
several city pension and retirement funds, including the Washington
Metropolitan Transit Authority Retirement Plan Local 689, his
largest client. In all, his firm managed about $600 million for 25
clients, the authorities said. His firm's strategy focused on
growth securities.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment contended Bond had used the proceeds of his
crimes to ``maintain a lavish lifestyle.'' The authorities said
this included the refurbishing and decorating of his home, the
purchase of two vacation properties in Florida _ including a house
with a pool in Sarasota _ the purchase of 75 luxury and classic
automobiles, tickets to Broadway, and his Harvard Club dues.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, who lives in Montclair, N.J., has not yet been arraigned,
and he could not be reached by phone Thursday. His lawyer, John S.
Siffert, said his client would be entering a not guilty plea and
will be contesting the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that he will be vindicated,'' Siffert added.
</P>
<P>
   Spruill was released on his own recognizance Thursday by U.S.
Magistrate Judge Frank Mass after entering a not guilty plea. His
lawyer, Frederick P. Schaffer, had no comment.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An SEC spokesman, Clifford C. Hyatt, said the investigation of
Bond began when the agency's examiners discovered irregularities in
the books of Lintz Glover White &AMP; Co., a small broker-dealer in
Sherman Oaks, Calif. The firm, one of the three Bond ultimately
used in his scheme, was ``running a high volume of trades for a New
York money manager,'' Hyatt said, and was receiving high
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The trail led to an employee there, Spruill, and his use of the
dummy company to funnel money back to Bond. Bond was then president
and chief investment officer of Bond, Procope Capital Management in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Spruill, 52, of Newark, ultimately worked at each of the three
firms used in the scheme and ``played a critical role in
implementing Bond's advisory fraud,'' the SEC's lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond also instructed the brokerage firms not to report the
commissions or mark-ups he established on the confirmation and
account statements sent to his clients, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Caproni, Pacific regional director of the SEC, said in a
statement: ``By choosing to direct trades to these firms, Bond was
not only deciding when he received a kickback, he was also deciding
how much the kickbacks would be, while at the same time, preventing
his clients from detecting the scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Bond's clients were mostly pension funds, the victims
are human,'' Caproni added, ``People who believed that their
pension fund adviser was investing for their benefit not his.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond was also accused of taking kickbacks by misappropriating
hundreds of thousands of dollars in ``soft dollar'' credits, which
belonged to his clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft dollar'' credits are partial rebates of broker
commissions that may be paid back to investment advisers if they
are used on behalf of the client, such as for the purchase of
research reports or computer software. But Bond used this kickback
to pay his credit card bills and other personal expenses, the
government contended.
</P>
<P>
   The two other firms used by Bond were the Brenner Securities
Corp., a now defunct brokerage firm in New York, and Value
Investing Partners, of Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a 1987 graduate of Harvard Business School, was an
associate with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. from 1987 to 1989, and a
portfolio manager for W.R. Lazard &AMP; Co. from 1989 to 1991, the SEC
suit said.
</P>
<P>
   He was president and chief executive of Bond, Procope from 1991
until late last year, when he bought out his partners, and
reconstituted the firm, now called Albriond Capital Management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
