<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-ALCOHOL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonfire 1998 crew caught drinking, records reveal
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ A year before the Texas A&AMP;M Bonfire
collapse, university police found dozens of bonfire workers with a
beer keg at the building site, documents released Thursday show.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 students, including 20 minors, were inside a storage
shed with a 15.5-gallon keg, and police believed they were
drinking, according to an offense report written Nov. 5, 1998. A&AMP;M
police called an ambulance for an 18-year-old student they found
passed out and vomiting on a sofa inside the shed, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The documents raised further questions about supervision ofAggie
Bonfire, where a log-stack collapse Nov. 18 killed 12 people and
injured 27. One, John Comstock, remained in critical condition
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials investigating the collapse have said they were not
aware of evidence showing alcohol was a factor in the accident, but
documents released by the university since the collapse show that
drinking during the preparation and burning of the bonfire has been
a concern for years.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology reports found that two of those killed had
blood-alcohol levels well above the legal limit to drive a motor
vehicle in Texas. Evidence from the accident site shows several
beer cans were discovered either inside a truck or in a
construction shack.
</P>
<P>
   In March, A&AMP;M Vice President for Student Affairs J. Malon
Southerland wrote in a memo to other university officials, ``I
think we are dangerously close to having a serious incident that
connects alcohol, residence halls and Bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   The following month, Ron Sasse, the university's director of
residence life, recommended ``a training effort to assist student
leaders ... to motivate others without using alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   A November 1998 memo and a copy of the police report were
addressed to Ben Welch, the university's director of student
affairs, from Brent Paterson, A&AMP;M director of student life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the information in the police report, I am forwarding
it to you for consideration of disciplinary charges against the
(Student Bonfire) organization. Since specific individuals were not
identified as `owners' of the keg, Student Life does not have any
plans for disciplinary charges against individuals related to
possession of the keg. However, we will pursue charges against
individuals cited for minor in possession and public
intoxication,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The document's second page contains what appear to be the
signatures of Bill Kibler, associate vice president for student
affairs, and Southerland. Under the signatures is a hand-written
note: ``This was handled by Blaine and Rusty,'' possibly referring
to Bonfire faculty adviser Rusty Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the students involved were likely disciplined for having
alcohol at the bonfire site, but it is unclear whether they were
allowed to continue working on the bonfire, said Cynthia Lawson, a
university spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   She said that when asked about it Thursday, Thompson could not
remember the 1998 incident or what kind of action was taken against
the students involved. Lawson said she does not know the identity
of ``Blaine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure what they did is they followed the university's
discipline procedures,'' Lawson said. ``Those procedures are pretty
strict. If it says, `Do A,' they do A.''
</P>
<P>
   Another document released Thursday shows that in April, Thompson
requested and received permission to hire a part-time graduate
student to provide hazing and alcohol awareness education programs
for the bonfire workers, as well as perform other administrative
duties. In the spring, Lawson said, Thompson hired a former bonfire
red pot _ construction leaders so named for the color of the
helmets they wear.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
