<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holiday Celebrations With an Extra Kick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flush with cash from the booming economy, some companies are
going all-out to celebrate the holidays, and not just with parties.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent online survey of 531 employers, Vault.com, a company
that studies workplace issues, found that 32 percent said they were
planning more lavish events this holiday season than last.
</P>
<P>
   One company said it planned a millennium party in January at a
local restaurant, rather than in the company cafeteria, the usual
spot for gatherings. ``We've got more money to spend,'' a company
representative said.
</P>
<P>
   Another company said it was sponsoring a cruise to the Bahamas
for employees, while a third said it provided a cocktail
party-dinner-dance at a hotel for each employee and a guest, and
paid for those who wanted to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half the respondents said parties would be about the
same as last year's; 16 percent said they would be less
extravagant. ``We don't do a party,'' a representative of one
company commented. ``We just have a lunch catered that we eat at
our desks between noon and 1 p.m.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
