<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE WILL SEEK TO CHANGE WAY `DON'T TELL' POLICY IS
USED 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARC LACEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Addressing a sympathetic audience of gay and
lesbian backers of the Democratic Party, President Clinton said
Thursday that the way the military was implementing the ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy toward homosexuals in uniform could turn
soldier against soldier and that he intended to push for changes in
how the services put the policy into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us what he's been telling us privately for two years _
that he doesn't like the policy but that it was the best he could
get politically,'' said Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the
Human Rights Campaign, a gay political group. ``The president
called it institutionalized hypocrisy and said it creates an
atmosphere of secrecy that turns soldier upon soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to about 50 gay men and lesbians at a
$10,000-a-plate luncheon sponsored by the Democratic National
Committee. In his speech, he ignored the ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy altogether, but after reporters were ushered out of the
room, the policy and how the services were carrying it out came up
in the closed question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to take a very close look at this and make sure it's
implemented right,'' said Julian Potter, the White House liaison to
the gay and lesbian groups.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis M. Dougherty, a gay Vietnam veteran who served in the
Army and is seeking to overturn the current policy, said he asked
Clinton whether he would sign an executive order lifting the ban on
gays in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty said Clinton then recounted the legislative standoff
that led to the compromise in which the military may not inquire
into a soldier's sex life unless there is clear evidence of
homosexual conduct. Clinton did not commit himself to a change in
policy, and Dougherty said that when he tried to press the issue,
he was cut off by the Democratic committee treasurer, Andrew
Tobias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect an answer at the luncheon,'' said Dougherty, a
former Republican who switched parties after Clinton's election.
``But I do think he's looking at this issue. After all, it's his
legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Potter, the White House adviser, said Clinton was looking
for ways to improve the situation before leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if he could issue an executive order overriding
the law,'' Ms. Potter said. ``The White House counsel's office is
looking at that. My gut reaction is I don't think that can work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first criticized the implementation of the policy in a
radio interview last week after his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
said in New York that she believed that gays should be allowed to
serve openly. Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley
of New Jersey have called for the elimination of the
administration's policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon this week ordered a 90-day review to determine if
gay service members were being harassed, a step that some advocates
for homosexuals criticized because Defense Department officials had
failed to promise confidentiality to those who reported harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton urged gays to continue their support of
Democratic and administration efforts to pass hate-crimes
legislation next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you to stay with me and to make a good effort,'' Clinton
said. ``I think we've got a much better chance to pass it in 2000,
and I hope you will help me with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged the audience to work for the election of
Democrats in next year's congressional and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said many times I wish we could have done more,''
Clinton said, ``but I'm glad we did what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the luncheon in the Mayflower Hotel said Clinton
brought up the murder in July of Pfc. Barry Winchell at Fort
Campbell, Ky., as an indication of the current climate in the
military. Last week, Pvt. Calvin Glover was found guilty of
bludgeoning Winchell in their barracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes tragedy brings a greater spotlight,'' said Winnie
Stachelberg, the political director for the Human Rights Campaign.
``There are action-forcing events that happen in this country all
the time. If there is a silver lining in the tragedy of Barry
Winchell, we may be able to improve the lives of gay people who are
willing to die for their country but cannot openly serve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2122EST &QL; 
