<HEADER>
A1357 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV19-N     12-16 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GENERATION GAP IN YEAR 2000 PLANS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as the Book of Proverbs says, the prudent see danger and
take refuge, but the simple keep going and suffer for it, then I
must be among the simple.
</P>
<P>
   I have given the Year 2000 computer issue approximately 8.2
minutes of thought _ and that was only to gauge the danger involved
in airline travel on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I'm unconcerned about a digital meltdown. I just
don't think there is much I can do about it. Besides, what's the
worst that can happen? If the electricity goes out, I'll buy
candles (scented, of course). If the banks crash, then I don't have
to pay bills. As for water, well, I prefer Diet Coke. A friend
looks at it this way: ``If the world ends, then I don't have to
worry about dating again.'' There's a silver lining to everything.
</P>
<P>
   Many young people, especially those in high-technology
industries, see Y2K as only a minor annoyance, if that. ``Sure,
I'll grab a few extra bucks from the ATM,'' they may say, or
``Yeah, I'll throw some extra soup in my food cart.'' But they see
no cause for panic: ``Hey, if the pilot's willing to get into the
cockpit, who am I to say no?''
</P>
<P>
   But many of our parents _ the same people who consider
programming a VCR a technological feat _ are piling their basements
with canned food and bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Van Couvering, 30, a senior strategist in the London
office of Organic, a San Francisco-based company that helps build
Web sites, said her mother ``wants to be on the safe side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She lives in a log cabin in New Mexico, on the Colorado
border, and as far as I know she's stockpiling food and getting
wood ready,'' Ms. Van Couvering said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Wolf, 27, president and founder of zUniversity.com, based in
Manhattan, which builds branded portals and online communities for
universities, is in a similar situation. ``I invited my mother,
who's a big football fan, to go to one of the college bowl games
with me on New Year's Day, and she refused, despite the fact that
we have box seats with the head of a university,'' he said. ``She's
been offered an amazing trip to New Orleans with her son and she
says no. I think she's been reading too many articles about Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   A person's Y2K fear may reflect a broader attitude toward
computer technology. To many older people, who think JavaScript has
something to do with coffee and cursive, high technology is
interesting but not quite relevant to daily life. To their
offspring, life without megabytes and RAM is inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother's really worried about her computer, while I have a
better sense about what's going to be affected by a Y2K bug, what's
not and what the consequences will be,'' Ms. Van Couvering said.
``Even if my PC is completely messed up, the most I'm going to have
to do is set the clock and download a patch,'' a program that fixes
software bugs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just technology that has widened the gulf between young
and old; it's also life experience. Unlike our parents, my
generation didn't grow up with much sense of doom. They had the Bay
of Pigs; we have ``Baywatch.'' They had air-raid drills; we've got
air-fare wars. They lived through World War II and Vietnam; we
watched the Persian Gulf war, the mini-series. To us, much Y2K fear
has the feel of a made-for-TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   So who needs the worry? Not Natalie Faciane, an account
executive for the Portland, Ore., edition of the Employment Guide,
a free, help-wanted publication. ``Six months ago, my dad said
`We're not leaving the house on New Year's Eve, absolutely not,'''
she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few months, she said, her father, who is familiar
with potential Year 2000 glitches through his work at a
high-technology marketing firm, has been stuffing his California
home with water, food, batteries, a gas-powered generator, candles
and a hand-crank radio. Ms. Faciane said she believes he's
overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's some truth to Y2K _ I've bought some food and
a hurricane lamp, which is always nice to have around _ but if we
constantly lived in fear we wouldn't be able to do anything,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   I agree. Still, you never know. Maybe there will be worldwide
blackout. As it happens, I'll be celebrating the millennium at a
chateau in the Loire Valley. If things go awry, I guess I'll be
stuck there. Perhaps the simple don't have to suffer after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
