<HEADER>
A1361 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$AD     12-16 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE NEW PARADIGM CAN'T BEGIN TO EXPLAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of average annual growth in sales, operating
income, net profits is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Little can be said to change the minds of investors who believe
in the so-called new paradigm, the idea that today's stocks, for a
variety of reasons, should not be judged by historical valuation
standards. The believers generally ignore the skeptics, who gamely
point out that ignorance of such valuations in the past has almost
always been cause for regret.
</P>
<P>
   But the believers' reaction is hardly surprising. Indeed, a
historical argument is hardly relevant to people who think that
history itself is no longer relevant. ``This time is different,''
they often say.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone aiming to convert the paradigmistas, then, must do so
without referring to the historical norms of market valuation. Nor
should the argument be based on stocks' recent performance. After
all, it is impossible to know whether the recent gains in the
overall market are a result of the new paradigm or of extreme
overvaluation.
</P>
<P>
   But some assumptions underlying the new paradigm can be tested _
at least in how they should affect the relative operating
performance of small-capitalization value stocks and large-cap
growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s notwithstanding, small-cap stocks have historically
outperformed the large caps, and value stocks have outperformed
growth. But adherents of the new paradigm contend that the market's
leadership has changed permanently. Because of technological
advances and the economies of scale of a global marketplace, the
reasoning goes, small-cap value stocks should no longer be expected
to lead the market; only the very largest companies with the
biggest investments in technology will survive and thrive in the
new millennium _ the very growth companies that, indeed, have led
the market higher over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   But if the theory is correct, one would expect that large-cap
growth companies would have enjoyed extraordinary gains in
operating performance in recent years, both in absolute terms and
relative to small-cap value stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas were tested recently by three finance professors _
Louis K.C. Chan and Josef Lakonishok of the University of Illinois
at Urbana-Champaign, and Jason Karceski of the University of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   They focused particularly on the period since the end of 1995,
when stocks became grossly overvalued by almost all historical
valuation measures. They found that the new paradigm was an almost
complete failure in describing the recent operating performances of
public American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Sales growth is but one example. From the end of 1995 through
1998, sales of large-cap growth companies grew just 6 percent a
year, on average. That is not only lower than their historical rate
of 10.3 percent a year _ from 1970 through 1998 _ but also lower
than the 12.7 percent rate for small-cap value companies over the
same three years.
</P>
<P>
   A similar story emerges for operating income before
depreciation. For large-cap growth companies, this line item grew
9.6 percent, annualized, over that period, lower than their
historical rate of 10.6 percent and far below the 16.6 percent
annual rate for small-cap value companies over the same three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The data on net income is only slightly more encouraging for
new-paradigm believers. Before extraordinary items, profits at
large growth companies grew 11 percent, annualized, over the test
period _ higher than the historical growth rate of 9.6 percent. Yet
the growth was much slower than the 22 percent annual rate for
small-cap value companies.
</P>
<P>
   So if you are looking for evidence of a new paradigm at work,
the professors' study furnishes none. The conclusion is
inescapable: This time is not different.
</P>
<P>
   While advocates of the new paradigm come in varying degrees of
orthodoxy, that should give all of them reason to pause. Rather
than representing a brand-new world, the recent outsized gains of
large-cap growth stocks simply reflect overvaluation _ which the
market will correct in due course. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Annandale, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
