 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Friday, December 17, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PAGE ONE SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PUC  &LR; _ Bay Area telephone customers scored a major victory
yesterday against a controversial plan that would have required
them to dial 11 digits for a local call. In a 3-to-2 decision, the
California Public Utilities Commission permanently halted several
``overlay'' plans scheduled statewide, including those in the 415,
408, 650 and 510 area codes, plus the 714 area code in Anaheim. By
Kelly Zito
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FOR SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE BUSINESS: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; GENENTECH _ &LR;  Genentech Inc. said yesterday that it plans to proceed
with the third and final stage of clinical trials aimed at
developing a new class of drugs that would fight cancer by cutting
off the flow of blood to tumors. Company officials and Wall Street
analysts said it could be years, if ever, before these experiments
prove successful against lung, colon and rectal tumors. But
yesterday's announcement means Genentech is still in the race to
develop a new class of drugs, called anti-angiogenesis agents, that
have been hyped as possible cancer cures. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ALZA _  &LR; Palo Alto's Alza Corp. yesterday called off its troubled
merger with Abbott Laboratories, sending Alza's stock price down 30
percent in after-hours trading yesterday. In an announcement after
the close of trading, Alza chief executive Ernest Mario said the
deal was scuttled because Federal Trade Commission investigators
had concerns about the antitrust implications of the merger. By Tom
Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLL  &LR; _ The Bay Area dwarfs the rest of the nation when it comes to
using computers and the Internet, according to a poll of the
nine-county region conducted by an organization of local employers.
Nearly 8 in 10 people surveyed said they use computers regularly,
and 62 percent have e-mail addresses. By contrast, only one-third
of people nationwide have Internet access. By Carrie Kirby
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ADOBE  &LR; _ Adobe Systems, which has lately been making a habit of
beating analysts' expectations, did it again yesterday, reporting
surprisingly strong results for its fourth fiscal quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The news pushed the company's shares up almost 10 percent in
after-hours trading _ even though Adobe also announced that its
president and co-founder, Chuck Geschke, will soon retire. By Henry
Norr
</P>
</TEXT>
