<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-16 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Everett deal sends disturbing signals
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   There are those of us who become frustrated even when we lose
mere pocket change between the cushions of the living room couch.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we certainly feel Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr.'s pain
over losing a reported $120 million over the past seven years of
being a Major League Baseball owner.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that $120 million figure came about only after a
veritable olympiad of accounting gymnastics, we realize the man no
doubt has lost money and he should hope to recoup it.
</P>
<P>
   But the question today is one McLane has uttered hundreds of
times over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   What have you done today to become a champion?
</P>
<P>
   You have traded your best outfielder, Carl Everett, who arguably
also was your best overall player in 1999, for a Class AA shortstop
and a pitching prospect.
</P>
<P>
   You have hinted a trade of your best pitcher also might be
imminent, given Mike Hampton's decision to pass on a contract
extension in order to play out his free-agent options next season.
</P>
<P>
   Only months after talking openly about the World Series, you
have begun talking about the team being, ``in transition.'' You
have begun saying things like, ``building blocks'' and discussed
building bridges to where you want to be in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to today?
</P>
<P>
   You've taken a big chunk of your city's money and its citizens'
confidence in you and built a fancy new playpen. You've capitalized
on all the enthusiasm and Astros successes of the past three years
to market a hot new team logo and uniform design, just in time for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   And now you've done this _ sent out a most interesting and
disturbing message to the citizens who helped give you the stadium
and money-making mechanism you now own.
</P>
<P>
   What have the Astros done today to become a champion? They have
taken a step backward.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, McLane has every right to begin recouping some of his
losses. For the sake of the future of baseball in this city, we
should all hope he eventually does.
</P>
<P>
   But we all also should ask, why such a desperate move and why
right now?
</P>
<P>
   Everett is a pivotal player and this is a pivotal time in the
history of the organization. It's not every season that a team
faces an opportunity to make it to the World Series, it's been 38
seasons and Astros fans still are waiting.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that not only has the players and general manager
in place to make a run to its first World Series, but definitely is
on the way toward putting a dent in McLane's fiscal shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   With the opening of Enron Field next spring, the club should for
the first time surpass the 3 million mark in attendance. Ticket
prices also will be higher, corporate suites will be filled and
McLane again will earn a sizable portion of concession and parking
revenue, not to mention a certain increase in marketing income
based on the new team logo.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there were a time McLane could have made one last sprint
for the ring, one last year of bullet-biting with the hope of it
paying off with the most illustrious of world championships, this
was it.
</P>
<P>
   He might still be in an overall fiscal hole given his previous
losses, but he does not figure to take a big hit in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The message we received with Tuesday night's trade of Everett
was a disturbing one and fans have every right to begin wondering
if they have been hoodwinked. It was a day when the Astros did
nothing to become a champion, instead likely took a step toward
mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a good Astros team in 2000, but it will not be a
better one. Should Hampton also be lost, it will be a stretch to
even consider the Astros favorites in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Everett, the gifted shortstop acquired in the deal, will do
nothing to help this team become a champion in 2000. The outfield,
with the embattled Derek Bell, the talented but still unproven
Daryle Ward and Lance Berkman, and Moises Alou and Richard Hidalgo
coming off injuries, will dearly miss the reliable and gritty Carl
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff could be decimated if it loses Hampton and it
is wondering about the viability of Scott Elarton, who's coming off
rotator cuff surgery.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the club could have been doing everything
possible toward christening The Gashouse with another division flag
or maybe even a National League pennant in 2000, it has us
wondering if it is on the way toward joining the likes of the San
Diego Padres and Florida Marlins by raising a white flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
