<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-ADOBE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Adobe Systems' Net Income Soars 94%, President to Retire  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Adobe Systems, which has lately been making a habit of beating
analysts' expectations, did it again yesterday, reporting
surprisingly strong results for its fourth fiscal quarter.
<P>
   The news pushed the company's shares up almost 10 percent in
after-hours trading _ even though Adobe also announced that its
president and co-founder, Chuck Geschke, will soon retire.
</P>
<P>
   Net income for the quarter, which ended December 3, jumped 94
percent to $97.4 million (76 cents per share) from $50.3 million
(39 cents) in the same period last year. Excluding investment gains
of $61.7 million and other nonrecurring charges, earnings for the
quarter were 46 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The average prediction among analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial was 42 cents. The ``whisper numbers'' _
estimates provided by some analysts to major clients and posted on
investor Web sites _ were as high as 45 cents, according to
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fifth consecutive quarter in which Adobe's results
exceeded analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the quarter reached a record $281.8 million, up 14
percent, from $246.7 million in the last three months of last year.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, revenues were $1.015 billion _ the first time in
the San Jose company's history that they'd topped $1 billion. Net
income for the year was $237.8 million, a 126 percent jump from
$105.1 million in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously a great quarter,'' said analyst Jennifer
Smith of Dain Rauscher Wessels in San Francisco, ``but we weren't
really surprised because they'd been doing such a great job over
the last three quarters. They've been doing really well in
executing their new-product initiatives as well as in containing
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Geschke, 60, will retire as president of the company at the end
of March but will continue to serve as co-chairman of the board,
alongside CEO John Warnock. Warnock will add the title of
president. The two men founded the company in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Geschke achieved celebrity, of sorts, in 1992, when he was
kidnapped from an Adobe parking lot and held bound and blindfolded
for four days. He was freed after one of the kidnappers was caught
by the FBI and confessed.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement yesterday, Warnock attributed Adobe's growth to
``increased demand for Web content creation and delivery.'' In the
past year the company has released new versions of Photoshop, its
industry-leading image-editing program, and Acrobat, a series of
utilities used to publish electronic documents with graphics,
layout and typographical features intact.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in September Adobe delivered a new program called
InDesign, which is used for laying out newspapers and magazines.
That market is currently dominated by Quark Inc. of Denver, but
Adobe's new entry has received good reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for them in the next year will be to break out
of their traditional base in publishing,'' said analyst Smith.
``One thing we're looking for is more endorsement for their
Web-site development tools from the Web-building community.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Web development market, Adobe faces competition from a
number of companies, including San Francisco's Macromedia. But
another longtime rival, Metacreations Corp., earlier this week
announced plans to abandon the graphics-application market. The
Carpinteria company, which has not recorded a profitable year since
1993, will sell off most of its programs to concentrate its
resources on technology for streaming video from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe reported its results after the close of regular trading,
during which its shares had risen $1.88, to $63.75. After the
announcement, prices on after-hours exchanges exceeded $70 at
times, before settling back to $69.69.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
