<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-POLL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Bay Area Leads the Way in Use of Computers, Internet  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The Bay Area dwarfs the rest of the nation when it comes to using
computers and the Internet, according to a poll of the nine-county
region conducted by an organization of local employers.
<P>
   Nearly 8 in 10 people surveyed said they use computers
regularly, and 62 percent have e-mail addresses. By contrast, only
one-third of people nationwide have Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The survey asked about 600 people about their overall
perceptions of the quality of life in the area, and specifically
examined use of the Internet and attitudes about the housing
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Sunne Wright McPeak, president and CEO of the Bay Area Council,
which conducted the survey, noted that the high Internet use is
spread evenly through almost all counties in the region. ``It's not
just Multimedia Gulch or Silicon Valley,'' she said. Alameda lagged
slightly behind other counties in the number of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   The results show that although the Bay Area is the nation's most
wired region, it's not immune to the Digital Divide _ the gap in
Internet use between lower and upper income groups. More than 80
percent of Bay Area residents making more than $80,000 thousand  &LR; a
year use the Internet, while only 46 percent of those whose annual
income is less than $40,000 regularly log on. The survey did not
divide respondents by ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of Internet use in the Bay Area actually makes
the Digital Divide here more acute, said David Geilhufe, director
of Oakland's Eastmont Computing Center/OCCUR, a program that helps
at-risk youth and other disadvantaged people learn about computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there are so many people in the Bay Area using
computers, public services are using the Internet. The people who
can use computers are getting the full benefits of these services,
and the people who can't are blocked from jobs and other benefits
of economic development,'' Geilhufe said.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area residents feel good about the economy, with 52 percent
saying their families are financially better off now than they were
in 1998. Despite that optimism, respondents recognize that the
area's housing shortage and transportation woes threaten future
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-six percent agree that increasing affordable housing is
important to the economy's health, and in almost all counties,
people identify transportation as the region's No.1 problem. San
Francisco residents call another issue equally important as
transportation: homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   But while more than half say new housing should be encouraged in
the Bay Area, the survey revealed what McPeak called ``deep
ambivalence'' when it comes to developing housing in peoples' own
neighborhoods. Only 47 percent throughout the region say new
housing should be encouraged in their communities. North Bay
respondents are even less enthusiastic, with 58 percent against new
housing.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area Council is an organization of area employers. Its
annual poll questions people over the age of 18 living in six Bay
Area regions: Alameda, Contra Costa, San Francisco, San Mateo and
Santa Clara counties, and the North Bay, which lumps together the
counties of Marin, Napa, Solano and Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
