<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ETHICS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ETHICS, IT'S THE THOUGHT THAT COUNTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JEFFREY L. SEGLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the holidays approaching, and after a grueling season
setting up fund-raising campaigns, Kathleen E. Pavelka, chief
executive of Telecomp in Rochester, decided to do something special
for her clients. She sent each of them a $50 American Express gift
check with a note: ``For all the evenings spent at work, please
enjoy an evening out on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, 2 of the 20-odd recipients returned the
checks, saying that accepting them would violate their
organizations' policies. ``It was embarrassing,'' Ms. Pavelka said.
``I only realized in hindsight that several of the clients had a
policy of accepting no more than $25 value gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   But set aside the etiquette aspect for a moment. Gift policies
are ostensibly about ethical behavior. Were the two returners
hewing to a higher ethical standard?
</P>
<P>
   Gifts given and received stir up a witches' brew of conflicting
impulses and desires, in business no less than in personal
relationships. Imperatives of manners, obligations, reciprocity and
appropriateness converge on the giving of a business gift (here
defined as gifts to people at other organizations _ clients,
suppliers, potential customers, and so on _ and not gifts to
co-workers).
</P>
<P>
   Most people say it feels nice to get a present, or to give one.
That is a big reason they are given at all, though far from the
only one. Setting any limits on such a pleasant practice feels
Grinch-like. So it helps to remember that it isn't the gift that
presents the ethical problem; it is what is implicitly expected in
return.
</P>
<P>
   And something is always expected, whether it is getting to
deliver a pitch ahead of a stingier _ oops, make that ``less
thoughtful'' _ rival, or being ``taken care of'' when a vital
component is in short supply, or getting calls returned the same
day.
</P>
<P>
   On the receiving side, many companies want to send a message
that their favor cannot be curried this way. But they don't want to
seem mean and puritanical. A usual result is a compromise: a dollar
ceiling like the one Kathleen Pavelkas fell afoul of.
</P>
<P>
   Executives who develop such policies, like Patrick J. Gnazzo,
vice president for business practices at United Technologies, in
Hartford, acknowledge that there is nothing magic about the
amounts. (In his company's case, gifts worth $50 or more and meals
worth $100 or more must be reported to a supervisor.) ``But you
have to set a number,'' he said, ``and it's what we considered to
be a reasonable number.''
</P>
<P>
   But do ceilings, however practical, get to the root of ethics
issues? To borrow the old punchline, once you are willing to accept
a gift meant to alter your commercial behavior, everything else is
just quibbling over price.
</P>
<P>
   Gnazzo's company has a major exception to its policy: Employees
in procurement cannot accept gifts at all. But it is a ban rooted
as much in cool business calculus as in ethics. ``We would rather
have the product be a product that is priced fair,'' Gnazzo said of
the company's relationships with suppliers. ``We don't need them to
entertain us and buy us gifts, because that all goes into the cost
of the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people argue that businesses cannot afford to buck the
culture. Gnazzo is not alone in observing that if a company
chairman were to visit a country where ``gifts are being given and
are customary, we're going to bring a gift and we're going to
receive a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the gift is passed on to charity after the chairman
flies home, the fact that gifts are expected in the course of
business suggests that the practice is more than social nicety.
</P>
<P>
   A telltale sign of ethical trouble is a policy that is harsher
on receiving gifts than on giving them. In a 1996 survey, two out
of five executives at large public companies said their companies
had such double standards.
</P>
<P>
   Strict no-gifts policies _ bans on giving or receiving _ may
seem impractical, though Wal-Mart Stores seems to manage. It has
banned gifts and gratuities of any value since its founding in
1962, to no obvious ill effect. ``Our relationships with our
suppliers are very strong, very healthy and mutually respectful,''
said John Bisio, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There may indeed be little real harm in accepting, say, a $40
bottle of wine from a supplier or sending a $60 ham to a client.
Maybe you can remain impartial afterward; who, after all, can be
bought so cheap? But why not stop pretending that there is a bright
line between safe and unsafe business gifts, and acknowledge that
they all come with strings attached? Then, at least, you are being
honest about it _ as long as you declare them to the IRS. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey L. Seglin teaches at Emerson College in Boston. His
column on business ethics appears the third Sunday of each month.
E-mail may be sent to: righthng(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH_S     12-16 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Genentech Plans Final Tests on Cancer Drug  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Genentech Inc. said yesterday that it plans to proceed with the
third and final stage of clinical trials aimed at developing a new
class of drugs that would fight cancer by cutting off the flow of
blood to tumors.
<P>
   Company officials and Wall Street analysts said it could be
years, if ever, before these experiments prove successful against
lung, colon and rectal tumors. But yesterday's announcement means
Genentech is still in the race to develop a new class of drugs,
called anti-angiogenesis agents, that have been hyped as possible
cancer cures.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long known that tumors can't grow larger than a
pinhead without forming new blood vessels to nourish them. Many
scientists, notably Harvard University's Dr. Judah Folkman, have
sought drugs to interrupt this process of blood vessel formation,
called angiogenesis.
</P>
<P>
   Although Folkman received widespread publicity last year for
some promising results in animal experiments of an
anti-angiogenesis drug called endostatin, other efforts, sponsored
by biotech firms like Genentech, are were  &LR; actually much further
along in testing anti-angiogenic drugs on humans.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in this approach is intense. The National Cancer
Institute (www.nci.nih.gov) lists 19 clinical trials for  &LR; underway
to test  &LR; anti-angiogenesis drugs on human cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Pluda, a senior investigator with the National Cancer
Institute, said these 19 experiments represent three broadly
different strategies for inhibiting blood vessel formation.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy that is furthest along in clinical trials is one
that attempts to prevent tumors from drilling tiny holes in the
matrix of flesh around the cancer site _ a prerequisite to
blood-vessel growth.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies working on this strategy are Agouron
Pharmaceuticals of La Jolla (San Diego County) and Aeterna
Laboratories of Quebec. They are already in phase III trials of
matrix inhibitors in lung and colorectal cancers, according to the
cancer institute.
</P>
<P>
   A second strategy, and the one Genentech employs, attempts to
interrupt the signals that cancer cells send out to call for new
blood vessels to reach them.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech, which plans to ask the Food and Drug Administration
for permission to begin phase III trials on this approach next
year, will face stiff competition from its South San Francisco
neighbor, Sugen Inc., which is a couple of months further along in
testing a similar strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The third broad anti-angiogenic strategy seeks to stop
endothelial cells from building small blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman's endostatin drug, which recently began first-stage
human tests, falls into this category. Another contender in this
third approach is Thalidomide, once reviled for causing birth
defects, but now being explored as a possible tumor-suppressor.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of these experiments has received FDA approval,
cancer fighters are hopeful that at least some of them will pan
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're cautiously optimistic anti-angiogenesis may yield
positive results and become a useful weapon in our war on cancer,''
Pluda said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Genentech is expected to announce,
perhaps as early as today, that based upon positive phase III
trials, it plans to ask for FDA approval for an asthma-fighting
drug.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech investors cheered the anti-angiogenesis news, lifting
the company's shares $5.63, to $113.69. Genentech's stock has more
than doubled since July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
