<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1372 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      12-16 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 11-Digit Bay Area Calls Voted Down  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bay Area telephone customers scored a major victory yesterday
against a controversial plan that would have required them to dial
11 digits for a local call.
<P>
   In a 3-to-2 decision, the California Public Utilities Commission
permanently halted several ``overlay'' plans scheduled statewide,
including those in the 415, 408, 650 and 510 area codes, plus the
714 area code in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in those locales had been scheduled to begin 11-digit
dialing over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a great move,'' said Natalie Billingsley, an
analyst with the PUC's Office of Ratepayer Advocates. ``The
commission has made a very consumer-friendly decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Overlays are designed to deal with a growing shortage of phone
numbers caused by the proliferation of cell phones, pagers and
other communications devices.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to a ``split'' _ dividing a region geographically
and giving customers in one half a new area code _ an overlay lets
existing customers keep their area code and assigns a new area code
to new phone lines. The downside is that everyone in the overlay
area must dial 11 digits _ 1 plus the area code and seven-digit
phone number _ on every call, even when making calls within their
own area code.
</P>
<P>
   As a remedy, the commission instituted ``number conservation
measures,'' such as allocating numbers to phone companies in
smaller blocks and requiring phone companies to give back unused
numbers to slow down the depletion of numbers within the affected
codes.
</P>
<P>
   Although phone companies favor overlays _ saying they are
simpler than forcing consumers to switch to a new area code _ the
public has come out staunchly against them.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pink, a San Francisco resident who lived through an area
code change from 408 to 831 in Santa Cruz, said both splits and
overlays ``create a lot of confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing commissioner Joel Hyatt said yesterday's action
essentially does away with the possibility of overlays statewide
for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy of the commission is now clear,'' Hyatt said in an
interview after the vote. ``We now have a policy in California to
take whatever conservation measures are possible to prevent the
rapid exhaustion of numbers, so people aren't going to continue to
be inconvenienced by dialing 11 digits when making a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt, PUC president Richard Bilas and Carl Wood approved the
measure. Commissioners Josiah Neeper and Henry Duque voted against
it.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement before the vote Duque said, ``conservation
measures, however helpful, cannot solve the number problem in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Duque said he doesn't know the solution to the state's number
crisis but believes barring overlays is futile, particularly in
area codes like Los Angeles' 310 where numbers are severely
depleted.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, yesterday's vote doesn't preclude area code splits in
the future. In a separate action, the commission approved a
three-way area code split for the 707 area code (Sonoma, Napa and
Solano counties) beginning in December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there will be a need in some areas for a new area
code,'' said Regina Costa, a telecommunications analyst with the
Utility Reform Network. But yesterday's vote ``means that the
commission prefers to do splits where it's feasible, eliminating
the need for overlays.''
</P>
<P>
   Costa said the decision, while expected, signals a change in the
regulatory body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of focusing on dealing with these situations on a
crisis-by-crisis basis, they're coming up with a strategic plan for
dealing with numbers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several rulings this fall set the stage for yesterday's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   In early November, PUC administrative law judge Thomas Pulsifer,
recommended ending the overlays, saying they cause confusion and
disruption among customers.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal followed PUC's decision to end the state's first
overlay in the 310 area code. The overlay, which began in April in
the West Los Angeles region, caused severe problems and prompted a
huge consumer outcry. After it went into effect, customers were
unable to get through to some phone numbers and some security
systems did not work with 11-digit dialing.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsifer said that experience, combined with a recent decision
by the Federal Communications Commission that gives California more
flexibility in how it assigns phone numbers, should preclude the
need for overlays across the state.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the FCC gave California the right to hand out new
numbers to phone companies in blocks of 1,000 instead of 10,000.
The FCC also told the state it could require phone companies to
return any unused phone numbers back to a pool so they could be
reassigned to other phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is when ``pooling'' will begin in the Bay Area.
The 310 area code is scheduled to begin the practice in March.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how that trial goes, pooling in the 408 area code
could begin as early as late next year, followed by 415 and 650 and
finally, 510, according to Billingsley. Pooling only affects phone
companies. For consumers, it wouldn't make any difference in their
service.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
