<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abbott Labs Is Abandoning $7.3 Billion Deal for Alza
</P>
<P>
   Abbott Laboratories, the nation's largest maker of medical
diagnostic devices, said that it was abandoning its $7.3 billion
acquisition of Alza, a developer of drug delivery technologies,
because of antitrust opposition from the Federal Trade Commission.
The development is the latest in a string of trouble for Abbott,
including a record $100 million fine levied in October by the Food
and Drug Administration connected to the manufacture of medical
test kits.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Giants Star Awarded $10 Million
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Newark, N.J., awarded more than $10 million to Philip
J. McConkey, the former New York Giants football player, after
finding that Frank G. Zarb, the chairman of the group that runs the
Nasdaq stock market, deceived McConkey into working for him at
Alexander &AMP; Alexander, the insurance brokerage firm that Zarb
formerly ran. The six-person jury unanimously found that Zarb
fraudulently misled McConkey about the status of takeover talks
between the firm and the Aon Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann Seen Receptive to Bid
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann of Germany may be willing to consider a friendly
takeover deal from Vodafone AirTouch of Britain if it adds a cash
sweetener to its hostile all-stock offer, executives close to
Mannesmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Deficit Set Record in October
</P>
<P>
   The nation's trade deficit swelled again in October, to $25.9
billion, setting a record for the seventh time this year as
prosperous consumers and businesses kept up their spending spree.
Exports were essentially unchanged, while imports continued to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   Yields Increase Sharply on Bonds
</P>
<P>
   Long-term interest rates jumped to their highest levels in more
than two years as the persistent strength of the nation's economy
convinced more and more investors that the Federal Reserve might
have to raise interest rates. The yield on the 30-year issue jumped
to 6.39 percent from 6.32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index set its 53rd record this year,
surging 93.11 points, or 2.57 percent, to 3,715.06. The Dow Jones
industrial average climbed 19.57 points, to 11,244.89, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index closed up 5.45 points, to
1,418.78.
</P>
<P>
   Nike Earnings Beat Expectations
</P>
<P>
   Nike said that its profit in the most recent quarter rose 50
percent as sales outside the United States helped the athletic
footwear and apparel company exceed expectations. The results were
released after the close of trading on the New York Stock Exchange,
where Nike's shares closed at $43.6875, up $1.9375. In after-hours
trading, shares rose to $44.25.
</P>
<P>
   Supercomputer Chip Is Resurrected
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard and STMicroelectronics, Europe's largest
computer chip maker, plan to announce on Monday that they are
forming an alliance to adapt a chip that failed commercially when
it was introduced for supercomputers in the 1980s for home
entertainment and other consumer devices.
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 to Cost U.S. $8.38 Billion
</P>
<P>
   While federal agencies have pronounced themselves ready for the
Year 2000, they say the preparations have been costly. The Office
of Management and Budget estimated that federal expenses relating
to the Year 2000 problem would total $8.38 billion over five years,
ending next September.
</P>
<P>
   Merger to Create Japan Phone Giant
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, three companies _ KDD, IDO and DDI _ said they would
merge, creating a telephone and data transmission business that
would be No. 2 domestically to Nippon Telegraph and Telephone.
</P>
</TEXT>
