<HEADLINE>
PLAYER ACCUSED IN GIRLFRIEND'S MURDER AGREES TO EXTRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Rae Carruth, the former wide receiver for the
Carolina Panthers, was brought shackled and in prison clothes into
a courtroom in Jackson, Tenn., on Thursday and agreed to return to
North Carolina to face charges that he engineered the murder of his
pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth had disappeared after his girlfriend, Cherica L. Adams,
died on Tuesday of gunshot wounds she suffered in a drive-by
shooting last month; it became apparent that Carruth, who had been
charged with attempted murder and released on $3 million bail,
would be charged with murder instead.
</P>
<P>
   But his flight did not last long. Acting on a tip given to the
Charlotte police, federal agents captured him Wednesday night in
the parking lot of a motel in Wildersville, Tenn., hiding in the
trunk of a car. He was traveling with an unidentified woman who has
not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief hearing before U.S. District Judge James Todd,
Carruth said he would not fight attempts to extradite him to
Charlotte to stand trial. ``I'm going to voluntarily go back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth, 25, was turned over to federal marshals after the
hearing, but it was unclear when he would be transported to North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth is the first active National Football League player to
be charged with murder, according to the Football Hall of Fame. If
convicted, he faces either life in prison or the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers cut Carruth from the team Thursday, Coach George
Seifert announced, because he had fled the state. As a condition of
his bail, Carruth had been ordered by the court to turn himself in
if either Adams or her baby died. The Panthers had suspended
Carruth without pay after his arrest, under NFL rules, but he was
still a team member. Thursday the NFL suspended him indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a court order that was broken,'' Seifert said.
``This thing is beyond football.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Adams was only six and a half months pregnant when she
was shot on Nov. 16, doctors delivered her son by Caesarean
section, and the infant has survived. He was listed in fair
condition Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The three other men charged with conspiring with Carruth to kill
Adams were arraigned on murder charges in Charlotte on Thursday. A
judge revoked bail for all three: Michael Eugene Kennedy, 24;
Stanley Drew Abraham, 19, and William Edward Watkins, 44.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry Caudill, the lead prosecutor, said the district
attorney's office is considering asking for the death penalty for
all four defendants in the case, but had not made a final decision.
In North Carolina, a judge must hold a special hearing to determine
whether a murder is heinous enough to warrant capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Police and prosecutors have remained tight-lipped about the
evidence linking Carruth to the killing, but a picture is beginning
to emerge, from preliminary hearings and police accounts, of a
premeditated and carefully orchestrated attack on Adams.
</P>
<P>
   After a night out with Carruth, Adams was driving her black BMW
at 12:30 a.m. on Nov. 16 when a rented car pulled up alongside it
and a man fired several shots from a handgun, striking her four
times in the neck and face, police said. She drove her car up on a
lawn and called police from a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   It was that initial conversation with a police dispatcher, along
with statements she made to detectives later that day at the
hospital, that led the police to suspect Carruth's involvement.
Carruth's cellular telephone records led detectives to the other
three defendants, some of whom have since made statements
implicating the football player, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' mother, Saundra Adams, told The Associated Press on
Thursday that Carruth had broached the topic of abortion with her
daughter early in the pregnancy, but did not pressure her. The two
had been dating for a year, but did not live together. Later,
Saundra Adams said, Carruth seemed to be excited about the prospect
of a child and even went with the future mother to several prenatal
checkups.
</P>
<P>
   His attitude changed, however, when he sprained his ankle about
two months ago and was taken out of the Panthers' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed more pressured after his injury,'' Saundra Adams
told The Associated Press. ``More pressured about money and how
much the baby was going to cost him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
