<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SURPRISE, REFORMISTS IN RUSSIA LOOK STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If you think it's easy being a pro-Western, pro-market
politician in Russia these days, get an earful of the first
question asked Anatoly M. Chubais during a radio interview this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a widespread attitude,'' the interviewer said, ``that
you have brought the country to the point of collapse _ taken the
economy to an extreme, `done animal experiments,' that you are
`laboratory scientists who do not know what life is,' that you have
`with the cruelty of vivisectors' pushed millions of people beyond
the poverty line. Why should people vote for you?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad question.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, the former deputy prime minister who drew Russia's
capitalistic cold bath in the early 1990s, embodies policies that
spawned a handful of super-rich tycoons and a boundless indigent
class before the economy collapsed in a speculative heap in 1998.
In a competition for the most reviled man in Russia, he would be a
triple threat.
</P>
<P>
   So it is worth asking why Chubais' latest creation, the Union of
Right Forces, seems poised to achieve what has been denied the vast
majority of Russia's political factions: winning its own bloc of
parliamentary seats in this Sunday's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems to be that the free-market theorists behind the
Union of Right Forces are proving considerably more adept at
playing power politics than they were at running an economy.
</P>
<P>
   Russian political parties can only win representation in the
lower house of parliament if they can collect at least 5 percent of
Sunday's vote. In the final pre-election polls conducted last
weekend and released Thursday, the Union of Right Forces registered
7 percent, and was gaining.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem unlikely for a political faction that did not even
exist before late this summer and whose headliners _ Chubais,
former deputy prime minister Boris Nemtsov and former prime
minister Sergei Kiriyenko _ were all forced out by President Boris
N. Yeltsin for their roles in last year's economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But Chubais, a central strategist in Yeltsin's come-from-behind
re-election victory in 1996, has prospered by making strengths out
of weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   If the West is widely blamed here for hastening Russia's
economic collapse and suspected of profiting from its decline, a
quarter of all Russians still aspire to European and American
lifestyles. And at least 10 percent still want to adopt immediately
Western economic and political models, says Sergei Markov, director
of the Moscow-based Institute of Politics.
</P>
<P>
   That group of voters, who retain some fondness for the pre-crash
policies of the Yeltsin government, is the Union's target. To reach
them, the faction has combined splinter parties established by
Nemtsov and Kiriyenko with a third faction set up by a liberal
parliament member, Irina Khakamada.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an I.D.,'' Markov said. ``And now, when they've
decided to build one coalition, they have a very important message
for those people: One, we want to live as all people live in Europe
and the United States. And the second message is that we are
united. You don't have to waste your vote.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Union's leaders have visibly de-emphasized
the pro-Western half of their pro-Western, free-market philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Union's formation this summer, its leaders were
among Russian politicians who denounced NATO's air attacks on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, who has been on a first-name basis with the West's
finance ministers for much of this decade, has regularly denounced
Western criticism of Russia's war in Chechnya as hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   And party leaders have embraced Prime Minister Vladimir Putin,
the man in charge of that war, as the sort of no-nonsense leader
Russia needs to restore its global image and shake up the domestic
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Masha Lipman, the deputy editor of the weekly newsmagazine Itogi
and a longtime political analyst, says the notion that Russia needs
to stand up to its enemies, internal and external, is an important
part of the faction's appeal. ``Chubais is clearly capitalizing on
this sentiment,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   It has not hurt the Union that the Kremlin and Putin have
returned the compliment. Putin, now the most popular man in Russian
politics, publicly praised the Union platform this week as a plan
that could be carried out in large part without much change.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has its own party of incumbency, Medved, which Putin
already has said he supports. But more than a few experts believe
Yeltsin and his government are working to boost the Union faction
as well, hoping to build a coalition in the parliament that can
break the grip on legislation that the communists and their allies
currently enjoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
