<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Dec. 17 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CIDERHOUSE (Undated) _ In this adaptation of John Irving's
best-selling novel, ``The Cider House Rules,'' director Lasse
Hallstrom finds nobility with two abortionists and an incestuous
father. It's quite a feat, and quite a movie. Many will find the
subject matter disturbing (and worth more than a PG-13 rating), but
it's clearly one of the holiday season's richest and most daring
movie entries.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STUART (Undated) _ It may not be the unqualified
crowd-pleaser that the already phenomenally successful ``Toy Story
2'' has turned out to be, but ``Stuart Little'' _ the second of the
holiday movie season's ``family'' affairs _ makes a more than
worthy companion piece.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BICENTENNIAL (Undated) _ ``Bicentennial Man'' represents
one of Hollywood's rare excursions into the realm of ``classic''
science fiction. It's far from completely successful, and is sure
to disappoint much of its audience _ including sci-fi purists who
will object to Robin Williams' shtick. But it has an interesting
and rather outrageous premise, which it follows faithfully to a
logical end.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ANNA (Undated) _ This latest _ and at 140 minutes, longest
_ version of ``Anna and the King'' definitely has its moments, and
looks so stunning that it works on the level of an historical epic.
In most other ways, however, it pales in comparison to its classic
predecessors, and also just generally feels like one too many trips
to the well.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BREAKFAST (Undated) ``Breakfast of Champions,'' bankrolled
by and starring Bruce Willis, is a glorious, totally outrageous,
off-the-wall mess of a movie that's likely to confound, confuse and
irritate audiences like no film of the year. I personally enjoyed
its daring unpredictability and sheer abandon, though be warned I
seem to be in a distinct minority.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RIDE (Undated) _ In ``Ride With the Devil,'' Ang Lee's
Civil War drama, he's mixed zen with a Larry McMurtry sensibility,
utilizing a cross-cultural troupe of characters with a cause. In
this case, men of the South are mobilized to form a guerrilla
warfare unit of Bushwhackers wreaking havoc on the invading Union
army and its sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WARZONE (Undated) _ In ``The War Zone,''
actor-turned-director Tim Roth succeeds in bringing the horrific
truth of the impact of illicit incest on a family in a very real,
almost too real, way. And he's not just exploiting the act itself
but responsibly showing the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-OLIVE (Undated) _ Parents looking for a gentle lesson in
doing the right thing, helping others and standing by one's friends
might check out Friday night's ``Olive, the Other Reindeer'' on
Fox. Most Christmas specials are easy to dismiss as seasonal fluff,
but good music, good writing and a good heart make ``Olive'' a good
bet to become a classic.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Seattle) _ Seattle SuperSonics host the Portland
Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
