<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     12-16 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPSULE REVIEWS OF MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. (star) denotes a highly recommended film or series. Ratings
and running times are in parentheses.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER,'' starring Cecilia Roth, Marisa
Paredes, Antonia San Juan and Penelope Cruz. Directed by Pedro
Almodovar (R, 101 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A whole new order of Almodovar extravaganza. The antic fizz and
theatrical exaggeration of this filmmaker's earlier work have
blossomed into a newly sophisticated style, one that is far more
wise and deeply felt. Lovingly dedicated to actresses who have
played actresses, this film weaves its own soap opera around ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' and tells of splendidly resilient women;
Almodovar has aptly described his material as ``screwball drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich and entertaining, this story celebrates the power of
artifice and impersonation to transcend ordinary truth. The
irrepressible Ms. San Juan, a Spanish nightclub performer, plays a
transsexual named Agrado and is the film's biggest treat (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``BOYS DON'T CRY,'' starring Hilary Swank and Chloe
Sevigny. Directed by Kimberly Peirce (R, 114 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This stunning debut feature tells the strange and resonant story
of Brandon Teena, who despite being born Teena Brandon went on to
create a charismatic identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately
wrenching tale may sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into
Theodore Dreiser's idea of American tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The film makes it hauntingly real and even tenderly romantic,
with the astonishing acting needed to make it work. One of the
year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE CIDER HOUSE RULES,'' starring Tobey Maguire,
Charlize Theron and Delroy Lindo. Directed by Lasse Halstrom
(PG-13, 125 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Radically downsized in scope, and its examination of the issue
of abortion greatly softened, John Irving's sixth novel (with a
Dickensian screenplay by the author) has been turned into a lovely
World War II-era fable about a young man venturing out into the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire is Homer Wells, a doleful innocent raised in an
orphanage by Dr. Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), who performs
abortions. Fleeing the institution with a golden young couple (Ms.
Theron and Paul Rudd), he becomes an apple picker. Sentimental but
smart, the movie has the sweetness and narrative drive of a 40s
``David Copperfield'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``CRADLE WILL ROCK,'' starring Emily Watson, John Turturro,
Ruben Blades, John Cusack, Joan Cusack, Bill Murray and Vanessa
Redgrave. Written and directed by Tim Robbins (R, 132 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This huge Depression-era story features well-known figures from
Orson Welles to Nelson Rockefeller to Diego Rivera, and it works
them into an ambitious ``Ragtime''-like tableau. Though too many
figures in this landscape are reduced to naive caricature, Robbins
and his impressive cast bring strong passions to bear upon this
(mostly) true story of a legendary event: the trouble-fraught
production by Welles and John Houseman of the banner-waving 1936
agitprop musical ``The Cradle Will Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins and his cast play out all sides of this event with the
certitude that its importance lives on (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE END OF THE AFFAIR,'' starring Ralph Fiennes,
Julianne Moore, Stephen Rea and Ian Hart. Directed by Neil Jordan
(R, 105 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's intoxicating version of Graham Greene's 1951 novel, in
which an illicit affair becomes a far greater gamble than either
lover could have imagined. For this fearlessly eclectic filmmaker,
this is one more intelligent, brooding love story with a secret
twist.
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes and Ms. Moore breathe life into this story with a
dreamy, erotic intensity that in no way trivializes the film's
underlying ideas about religious faith. Period detail (the setting
is London in the mid-1940s) is sumptuously heightened by the
inspired costume designer Sandy Powell (``Shakespeare in Love'')
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``END OF DAYS,'' starring Arnold Schwarzenegger, Robin Tunney,
Gabriel Byrne and Kevin Pollak. Directed by Peter Hyams (R, 118
minutes). The star modestly tackles the role of a new savior who
may just keep mankind free of Satan for the next thousand years.
And that's not even the worst thing about this pointlessly nasty
would-be thriller.
</P>
<P>
   The material is so derivative that it amounts to a tag sale of
used parts from better apocalyptic films, with special credit owed
to ``The Exorcist'' for grisly sacrilegious tricks. Hyams favors a
jack-in-the-box approach to delivering shock value. The star
dutifully protects a nice young woman from demonic forces. But
Byrne plays the swaggering embodiment of pure evil and has the
better role (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GREEN MILE,'' starring Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan,
David Morse, Doug Hutchison, Sam Rockwell and Bonnie Hunt. Written
and directed by Frank Darabont (R, 180 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In adapting the death row drama that Stephen King wrote in
multiple installments, the director of ``The Shawshank Redemption''
could have managed more economy and fewer talky bits of business
around the cellblock. Still, this lengthy film is vivid and well
played.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth ensemble acting builds up to the discovery that a
gigantic condemned man (Duncan) is a prisoner with very special
abilities, which gives the film its mixture of religious overtones
and mild horror. Hanks, as a wry Southern prison guard, is so
unaffectedly good that it's redundant to say so (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``LIBERTY HEIGHTS,'' starring Adrien Brody, Joe Mantegna
and Ben Foster. Directed and written by Barry Levinson (R, 134
minutes). This semi-autobiographical comedy-drama remembering
teenage life, anti-Semitism and racism in mid-1950s Baltimore is
the fourth movie by Levinson to be set in his native city.
</P>
<P>
   A deeply felt nostalgia trip, the movie adroitly captures the
look and social attitudes of the city 45 years ago. But the
screenplay and performances are too muted for the movie to come to
terms with growing pains cushioned in the nostalgic haze (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``MANSFIELD PARK,'' starring Frances O'Connor and Jonny
Lee Miller. Written and directed by Patricia Rozema (PG-13, 105
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Rozema's skillful screen adaptation of Jane Austen's
third novel, the protagonist Fanny Price (Ms. O'Connor) has been
sharpened into a proto-feminist heroine who triumphs over the
materialist, patriarchal values of her wealthy relatives through a
combination of wit, beauty and daring.
</P>
<P>
   Without bearing down too heavily, the screenplay (which
incorporates fragments of Austen's letters and diaries) equates
early 19th-century slave trading with the oppression of women. The
message is leavened with smart humor and warm three-dimensional
performances (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``MISS JULIE,'' starring Saffron Burrows and Peter Mullan.
Directed by Mike Figgis (R, 100 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Figgis, whose previous films ``Internal Affairs''
and ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' dwelled obsessively on the
darker aspects of sex, August Strindberg's late-19th-century drama
becomes a bleak study of the sexual disgust shared by a rebellious
aristocrat (Ms. Burrows) and the upwardly mobile footman (Mullan)
she taunts into having sex.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie's contemporary cinema-verite style is at odds with
the story and its setting. And Ms. Burrows' coldly haughty title
character is far less compelling than Mullan's earthy, cunning
footman (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``SLEEPY HOLLOW,'' starring Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci,
Miranda Richardson, Michael Gambon, Jeffrey Jones, Michael Gough
and Christopher Walken. Written by Andrew Kevin Walker and directed
by Tim Burton (R, 110 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This ornate visual fantasy, artfully concocted using a palette
that suggests nuclear winter, has little to do with Washington
Irving's story and everything to do with Burton's macabre vision.
</P>
<P>
   Depp makes a dashing hero as the film's shy detective, but the
story (by the writer of ``Seven'' and ``Fight Club'') is determined
to put the ick into Ichabod Crane.
</P>
<P>
   A first-rate cast and extraordinary technical talents are
attention-getting here, but so is the film's penchant for sardonic
beheadings. It's possible to admire Burton immensely for the secret
tenderness and rich imagination of his work without wanting to peer
at the exposed brain stems of his characters (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``SWEET AND LOWDOWN,'' starring Sean Penn, Samantha Morton and
Uma Thurman. Directed by Woody Allen (PG-13, 95 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In homage to the kind of jaunty 1930's jazz that has been heard
on many of his other films' soundtracks, Allen imagines a
consummate jazz character: Emmet Ray (played with gusto by Penn),
who can play the guitar as gorgeously as Django Reinhardt but lacks
certain interpersonal skills when it comes to his private life.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing attributes of various real musicians, the film turns
Emmet into another one of Allen's cad-geniuses and gives him a
long-suffering mute laundress as a sweetheart. (Ms. Morton works
miracles in her wordless role.)
</P>
<P>
   But on the storytelling level, the film remains flimsy. It's the
musical interludes, frequent and lovingly presented, that keep it
alive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``TOY STORY 2,'' with the voices of Tom Hanks and Tim
Allen. Directed by John Lasseter; a Pixar Animated Studios film (G,
98 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A wonderfully playful sequel, sustaining the first film's wit
and novelty while bringing new sophistication to computer-generated
animation. And here is welcome proof that Hollywood can still make
movies to please audiences of any age or persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   From its opening (a perfectly adorable ``Star Wars'' parody) to
its Capraesque conclusion, this is seamless work with more
metaphorical cleverness than that usually found in the toy bin.
Colorful new characters and more adventurous action enhance the
story of how Woody falls into the clutches of a sleazy toy dealer,
experiences newfound celebrity and needs to be rescued by his old
friends (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``TUMBLEWEEDS,'' starring Janet McTeer and Kimberly J.
Brown. Directed by Gavin O'Connor (PG-13, 100 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   An astoundingly vital performance by the British actress Janet
McTeer makes all, beautifully acted slice of contemporary
Americana a must-see film. Ms. McTeer is Mary Jo Walker, a sexy,
free-spirited woman with four marriages behind her who travels
across the country with her 12-year-old daughter, Ava (Ms. Brown).
</P>
<P>
   Like few other films, this one captures an intimately loving
(though not conflict-free) relationship between a parent and child
without becoming saccharine. The director plays Mary Jo's trucker
boyfriend, who is only the latest in a series of romantic disasters
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE WAR ZONE,'' starring Freddie Cunliffe, Ray
Winstone, Tilda Swinton and Lara Belmont. Directed by Tim Roth (not
rated, 99 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Roth is an actor known for roles in tough films, but never for
anything quite as raw as this. In this searing first feature, the
title battlefield is a rural English home where a teenage boy looks
upon his own family with helpless rage and astonishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the incestuous relationship between his father and older
sister, the film's wordless, baleful young hero struggles to come
to terms with this household horror. Understated but extremely
graphic at times, and shot with mournfully expressive simplicity by
Seamus McGarvey (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH,'' starring Pierce Brosnan, Sophie
Marceau, Dame Judi Dench, Robert Carlyle and Denise Richards.
Directed by Michael Apted (PG-13, 128 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This director is much admired for his ``Up'' series chronicling
the lives of former schoolchildren as they mature. And he has
managed to make James Bond grow up a little, too. Brosnan has grown
much more comfortable with the role of Bond, and most of the other
characters are also more interesting than might have been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marceau slinks memorably through the role of a treacherous
oil heiress. Ms. Richards seemed a lot smarter playing high school
vixens than she does as a brilliant scientist here. The itinerary
roams from Scotland to Central Asia. And Apted handles the action
as well as he does the talk (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   BOGART RETROSPECTIVE. He was a gangster. He was a private eye.
He skippered a fishing boat and ran a cafe in Casablanca. He was,
of course, Humphrey Bogart (1899-1957), the son of a Manhattan
surgeon and a magazine illustrator who achieved stardom in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the occasion of the centennial of his birth, he is the
subject of a retrospective in BAMcinematek, the Brooklyn Academy of
Music's Rose Cinemas' repertory program. This weekend offers two of
his best: Saturday, Raoul Walsh's ``They Drive by Night,'' about
two truckers framed for murder; and on Sunday, John Huston's
``Maltese Falcon,'' with Bogart as the private detective Sam Spade,
drawn into the intrigue surrounding a murder and a priceless
statuette.
</P>
<P>
   Each film is to be shown at 3, 6 and 9 p.m. Screening times are
subject to change. Admission to ``Bogie at BAM,'' through Jan. 30,
is $8.50 for adults and $5 for people over 62, children under 12
and students with valid identification. Information: (718) 623-2770
(Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1388 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK-A     12-16 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ATTACKS PAINTING IN DISPUTED BROOKLYN EXHIBIT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The painting of a black Madonna whose elephant dung
and pornographic touches have incurred the wrath of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and stirred a religious, cultural and political furor in
the city, was attacked at the Brooklyn Museum of Art Thursday by a
man who smeared paint on it but did no permanent damage, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Feigning illness to lull a security guard, the man, identified
as 72-year-old Dennis Heiner, of Manhattan, leaned against a wall,
darted behind a plexiglass shield, took out a plastic bottle and
squeezed white paint in a broad stroke across the face and body of
the Madonna, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   As the stunned guard and several museum visitors watched in
horror and shouted, ``Don't!'' and ``Stop!'' the man used his hands
to smear the paint over about a quarter of the surface of the
8-by-6-foot painting, ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' by Chris Ofili, a
British artist of Nigerian descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He covered the head and face down to the shoulders and then
down to the breast line,'' said David Eigenberg, who witnessed the
incident at 2:33 p.m. in a small, fifth-floor gallery of the museum
on Eastern Parkway. He said he made a move to stop the man, but was
told by the guard to stay back.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, while the guard radioed for help, the man emerged
from behind the plexiglass, his paint-smeared hands shaking
nervously, but made no effort to get away. As other security
officials raced up, the guard, whose name was not disclosed, asked:
``Why did you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's blasphemous,'' the man replied quietly.
</P>
<P>
   James G. Kelly, the museum's security manager, said the guard
had not halted the attack because he had been surprised, and he
called the reaction correct under the circumstances. ``They're here
to truly observe and report,'' he said of the guards. ``If they can
come between someone in an act of aggression, they can stop it. But
they're not peace officers and have no arrest powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the police arrived, handcuffed Heiner and led
him away. He was charged with criminal mischief in the second
degree, a class D felony. A woman who said she was Heiner's wife,
Helena, said he was a devout Roman Catholic who believed the
painting, adorned with elephant dung on one breast and cutouts from
pornographic magazines, was sacrilegious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The painting was offensive, he's absolutely right about
that,'' the woman said in a telephone interview. ``This painting is
your mother, the painting of the blessed mother, the mother of
Christ. So he said, `I will go there today and try to clean it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the attack, museum conservators removed the
painting and within an hour had cleaned it before the white paint
was dry, leaving the artwork apparently undamaged. ``It's like a
stain _ the sooner you get at it the better your chances of
removing it,'' said Sally Williams, a spokeswoman for the museum,
who noted that the painting would be back on display Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, in a statement, said that the trustees and staff
were ``shocked and extremely saddened by this incomprehensible
act.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ofili painting is part of an exhibit, ``Sensation: Young
British Artists from the Saatchi Collection,'' that has been one of
the most successful, and controversial, in the 177-year history of
the Brooklyn Museum. Charles Saatchi, the British advertising
magnate, owns the paintings and sculptures and is the show's
largest financial backer.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, a week before the exhibit's opening, Giuliani
led a chorus of protests by various groups, including the Catholic
league, objecting to the Ofili painting, a collage of paper, oil
paint, glitter and resin on linen. It depicts a black Madonna in
flowing blue robes, with a shellacked clump of dung on one breast
and cutouts of female genitalia from pornographic magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ``sick stuff,'' repulsive and offensive to Roman
Catholicism, Giuliani denounced the museum for mounting the
exhibit, vowed to cut off its $7.2 million annual city subsidy,
then withheld the city's monthly subsidy payment and began
proceedings to evict the museum.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court battle ensued. The museum, backed by cultural
organizations, noted that Ofili often used elephant dung and other
unusual materials in his work as a cultural reference to his
African heritage, and contended that the mayor was violating the
free-speech rights of the artist and the museum in attempting to
suppress of exhibit. Judge Nina Gershon sided with the museum and
ordered the city to resume its subsidies and end its eviction
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Since the show's opening on Oct. 2, nearly 130,000 visitors have
flocked to see the ``Sensation'' show, making it the most
successful exhibit of contemporary art ever put on by the museum,
Ms. Williams said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because of the controversy surrounding the painting, the museum
had wanted to post 21 guards for the exhibition, which features
more than 90 items on the museum's fourth and fifth floors. But
requests by Saatchi, who put up $160,000, increased costs, and the
museum had to pare down the security staff to 10 guards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one museum official said, Saatchi had objected to a
piece of plexiglass that would have completely enclosed Ofili's
painting. Instead, a piece slightly larger than the painting was
hung from the ceiling, leaving gaps of several feet on either side
and a four-foot separation from the surface of the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Heiner, who the police said was arrested in 1990 on a charge of
obstructing government administration in a protest, bought his
$9.75 ticket to the exhibition at the museum entrance Thursday and
took an elevator to the fifth floor, where Ofili's painting is
hung, along with only one other item _ Ron Meuck's ``Mask'' _ in a
small, 12-foot-wide gallery between two larger rooms.
</P>
<P>
   After walking through several galleries, Heiner approached a
guard and said he was feeling dizzy and ill, said Kelly. The guard
advised him to sit down. He then approached the guard near the
Ofili painting and again said he was dizzy and ill.
</P>
<P>
   He was clad in a herringbone sport coat and dark trousers and
did not seem suspicious. ``He was very dapper,'' Kelly said. ``He
looked like a typical museum visitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Heiner then leaned up against the wall beside the painting, and,
choosing his moment, suddenly darted behind the plexiglass,
witnesses said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
