u p BC-GORE-EDUC-NYT &LR;      12-16 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH `DEBATE' EDUCATION AT A DISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE and FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas stood on Gore's home turf on Thursday and sparred
over their education plans, acting for all the world as if they
were their party's nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who Thursday pledged a $115 billion federal commitment to
education that drew positive reviews from teachers unions, accused
Bush, a Republican, of wanting to drain money from public schools
to provide vouchers to students for private school.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused Gore, a Democrat, of advocating a big-spending
liberal education program that invited the federal government to
intrude into local decision making. The problem with the Gore plan,
Bush said, is that it assumed that Washington was the source ``of
all wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither man has captured his party's nomination, but each held
his party's fundamental principles aloft Thursday in a preview of a
classic fall election matchup. Their messages, delivered hours
apart from the libraries of two Nashville schools on Thursday, were
noteworthy for the underlying assumption that each man would become
his party's standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   And their broadsides were delivered at the same time that their
two maverick challengers _ former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
on the Democratic side and Sen. John McCain of Arizona on the
Republican side _ sought to capture the hearts of independents by
making a joint appearance in New Hampshire on campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   With McCain and Bradley garnering much of the attention
Thursday, Gore and Bush both seemed eager to get on with their own
show.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was asked whether he wished he were involved in the session
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm involved in a debate here in Nashville,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush clearly relished the idea of engagement on Gore's home
court. He said he looked forward to debating Gore about education
because Gore was focused on ``bricks and mortar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president talks about buildings,'' Bush said
dismissively. ``I'm talking about children. The vice president
talks about bricks and mortars; I'm talking about hearts and souls.
I'll be glad to make that debate all day long across America.''
</P>
<P>
   The two also collected money at the same saloon here, the
Wildhorse, with Gore staging a fund-raiser Wednesday night and Bush
following Thursday night, in his first fund-raising foray into
Tennessee. Gore's wife, Tipper, introduced him by saying, ``He's
good enough, he's smart enough,'' an allusion to the idea that Bush
lacks the intellectual heft to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared with the state's top Republican officials,
including Gov. Don Sundquist, Sen. Bill Frist and former Gov. Lamar
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Gore drew more than $1.6 million, and Bush took in about
$750.000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore set the tone for the day by filling in the numbers of the
education plan he outlined in May. He said he would spend $115
billion over 10 years, $50 billion of it to provide universal
access to preschool for 3- and 4-year-olds. He would use federal
money to help increase teacher salaries, a novel proposal in a
presidential campaign, and to provide incentives to failing schools
to reverse course.
</P>
<P>
   The plan engendered much support from the teachers unions, which
have endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Feldman, president of the one-million member American
Federation of Teachers, liked the plan's comprehensive approach
toward recruiting teachers and retaining them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately we have to have higher teacher salaries along with
higher standards as we go forward because otherwise we aren't going
to be able to attract teachers into districts that have the
greatest needs,'' Ms. Feldman said in a telephone interview from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the National Education Association, the
largest union in the United States with 2.2 million teachers, also
hailed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole preschool program is particularly important,'' Chase
said in a telephone interview from Washington. ``All research shows
us those early years are vital to the ongoing success of the child,
and when you couple that with smaller class size, and standards for
students and teachers, tying that into questions of salary is
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   More skeptical was Abigail Thernstrom, a senior fellow at the
Manhattan Institute and a conservative education analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is not class size, it's that we don't have a
sufficient number of top college graduates going into teaching,''
Ms. Thernstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government doesn't have a track record of doing
this kind of thing well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had a similar response when asked his reaction to Gore's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the amount of money, which is fairly typical of
somebody who runs around the country saying I'm going to spend
money and solve your problems,'' Bush said. ``We have a fundamental
disagreement on the role of the central government. I believe the
role of the central government is to do a few things and do them
well. And when we have money left over, to pass it back to the
working people.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Bush would do with his proposal for a $483 billion
tax cut over five years, which Gore referred to Thursday as his
``risky tax scheme'' that would throw the nation back into deficits
and back into a recession.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference in the two candidates' education plans is how
they deal with failing schools. Bush would take back federal money
from nonperforming schools and give it to students to use as
vouchers toward private schools. Gore said he would require the
school districts to adopt an aggressive plan to turn around the
school and provide pay incentives for teachers in districts that
managed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that Bush's plan, in draining money from the public
schools, would give new meaning to the three R's: ``Reckless and
retrograde, reactionary, radical _ that's four R's. I sincerely
believe that it's an ideologically driven mistake,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
