<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1392 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WORLD-RUSSIA-$ADV     12-16 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-RUSSIA-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORED BY VODKA, RUSSIANS FIND MORE STYLE IN BEER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN VAROLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ To some Russians, it is nothing short
of heresy. Consumers, especially young people, are discovering
something they'd rather drink than vodka.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joy of beer is you can savor it for a long time and not
get drunk quickly, unlike vodka, which you must down in one shot,''
said one young businessman, as he finished a beer at a St.
Petersburg cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Vodka is still czar here, but consumption of beer is rising
sharply _ and the biggest Russian brewers, owned mainly by Western
European brewers, are investing heavily to step up production and
meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are drinking more beer now,'' said Viktor Tikhomirov, a
local artist and observer of popular culture. ``First, because it
is available, while in Soviet times it was hard to get. And second,
beer is now better made than before, when it was often sour and God
knows what substance collected at the bottom of your cup. Vodka is
more for holidays, birthdays and other festive occasions, and
getting warm on a cold day.''
</P>
<P>
   Russians drank almost 25 percent more beer in 1998 than in 1995,
according to Andrei Sterlin of Business Analytica, a Russian market
research firm. Consumption reached 910 million gallons, or 6.2
gallons per capita in 1998, Sterlin said, up from 730 million
gallons, or 5 gallons a person, in 1995. He expects output to reach
980 million gallons this year, with virtually all of it sold and
consumed domestically.
</P>
<P>
   The per-capita figures are still well below those in Western
Europe, where the average is 21 gallons of beer a year. ``There is
still a long way to go for the beer industry in Russia, and lot of
growth potential,'' said Hans Christian Jacobsen, director of the
agribusiness team at the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, which has invested $150 million in Russian breweries.
``The beer market is the last big underdeveloped market in Russia,
and it is potentially lucrative.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucrative, that is, for domestic brewers, whose costs are
counted mainly in rubles. The weakness of the Russian currency has
all but priced imports out of the market: at retail prices of 6 to
10 rubles (25 to 40 cents) for a half-liter bottle, more expensive
Western brands cannot hope to compete profitably for the mass
market.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, imports, which commanded 14 percent of the Russian
market as recently as 1995, have shrunk to 4.5 percent now,
according to Business Analytica. Heineken, once popular here, has
all but vanished from stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are especially aiming to win over those drinkers who used
to drink imported brands,'' said Andrei German, director of
marketing of Vena, the St. Petersburg brewery that makes Nevskoye,
a brand that has won international awards for quality.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to the trend than import substitution. Beer
has become a consumer rage, especially among younger and
better-educated Russians. Beer festivals in Moscow and St.
Petersburg last summer attracted crowds estimated in the millions.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg is Russia's Milwaukee, its unofficial beer
capital. The city is home both to the industry leader, Baltika
Breweries, and to its first Western-style microbrewery restaurant,
Tinkov's, a fashionable spot popular with affluent young Russians
since it opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important tasks of the beer-making industry in
Russia is to get our citizens to change their habit for drinking
hard alcohol to drinking beer,'' said Timur Bolloyev, general
director of Baltika. To help create a ``culture of beer drinking,''
the company sponsors the St. Petersburg Beer Festival, now two
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, a shift to greater beer consumption here may be
welcome on health grounds. In a country that taxes vodka heavily,
25,000 Russians a year die of alcohol poisoning from impure bootleg
vodka; beer is too cheap to be worth bootlegging in any quantity.
</P>
<P>
   The growing demand for low-priced, high-quality beer has not
gone unnoticed by foreign investors. They have poured almost $700
million into the industry since 1990, half of it in the last two
years, and bought major stakes in the most important companies as
they were privatized.
</P>
<P>
   Vena, founded in 1872 by Austrian and German entrepreneurs, is
now two-thirds owned by the Finnish brewer Sinebrychoff, with the
remainder owned by the development bank. A joint venture of two
Scandinavian brewers, Pripps Ringnes and Hartwall, owns 70 percent
of Baltika, plus stakes in smaller breweries.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Interbrew was created by a merger of the Russian operations
of Interbrew, the Belgian company whose North American brands
include Labatt's and Rolling Rock, with Sun Brewing, founded in
Russia in 1993 by Indian entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   A fierce rivalry is developing between the two market leaders.
Sun Interbrew has been aggressively buying breweries in an effort
to vault its market share, now 14 percent, past that of Baltika and
its siblings, which together have 19 percent, according to Business
Analytica. And Efes of Turkey and South African Breweries have been
buying Russian breweries as well.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate profits are not the lure, since the same slide in the
ruble that priced imports out of the market also stretches the
payback period for these investments farther into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic that sector will grow in a volume basis, but
it is very hard to make decent money selling beer in Russia now,
because the current sale price has made it one of the cheapest
drinks on the market,'' said Jacobsen of the development bank.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the manufacturers want the volume now, even if profits
must come later. Vena is quadrupling its output to 32 million
gallons a year at a cost of $70 million. Baltika, which opened a
$50 million malt factory here last year in a joint venture with
Groupe Soufflet of France, has embarked on a $114 million capital
project to more than triple its beer output by 2002, partly
financed with a loan from the development bank.
</P>
<P>
   Bolloyev said Baltika wants to make 320 million gallons of beer
a year by 2002; it has started modest efforts to export its beer to
the West. Baltika's domestic sales are concentrated in St.
Petersburg and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Interbrew has tried a more dispersed strategy, expanding in
regional centers and buying two breweries in Ukraine. In Moscow, it
is in the final stages of buying the Klinsky Brewery, one of the
largest in the region, a deal that the company said would help it
match Baltika's planned size.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that beer is worth making'' in Russia,
said Shiv Vikram Kemka, a director of Sun Interbrew and a founder
of its predecessor, Sun Brewery. ``We're here for the long term,
and despite all volatility in the past few years, the business has
grown with varying degrees of profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is attractive because it is untapped,'' he added, ``and
you can build up a brand from scratch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
