Clinton escorts Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa back to the White House after a
brief statement, Thursday. Israel and Syria ended two days of
inconclusive peace talks Thursday which they agreed to resume early
in the new year. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON - Dec. 16, 1999 -- SUB-MIDEAST-TALKS-2 --
President Clinton escorts Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, left,
and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, back into the West
Wing of the White House following a brief statement on Thursday.
Israel and Syria ended two days of inconclusive peace talks
Thursday which they agreed to resume early in the new year.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON - Dec. 16, 1999 -- MIDEAST-TALKS -- President
Clinton escorts Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, left, and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa back into the West Wing of the
White House following a brief statement on Thursday. Israel and
Syria ended two days of inconclusive peace talks Thursday which
they agreed to resume early in the new year. (Paul Hosefros/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- FOOD-COOKBOOKS-BOS-- A new
crop of cookbooks has hit the bookstores just in time for the
holiday buying season. This year's crop of experts' advice to
amateurs tells us a lot about the cuisine of some of today's finest
restaurants. (Pam Berry/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WATERVILLE, Maine -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- CHRISTIAN-MEDIA-BOS
-- Taki Pilitsis, 12, kneels to the left of Pastor Bill Cripe,
while his brother Alexander, 9, is at the Pastor's right. Allison
Pilitsis, Taki and Alexander's mother, became a born-again
Christian eight years ago. She decided to remove her children from
the influence of most popular culture without making them feel cut
off. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS -- Under
the basket in a recent game at the Fleet Center, the Boston
Celtics' Tony Battie sails over Utah Jazz center, Karl Malone. ``I
intend to keep playing this way my whole career,'' Malone says
about his all-out nature of play. ``And when I do retire, I'll know
I left it all out there, on the floor. I think I can do it, as long
as I keep preparing to play the way I know how.'' (Jim Davis/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES -- The
independent film actress Parker Posey is headed for Broadway in the
spring. The twinkly gamine will make her New York theater debut in
``Taller Than a Dwarf,'' the Elaine May play that opens at the
Longacre Theater in April. ``I'm thankful,'' says Ms. Posey, 31,
who has been highly praised for her work in movies like ``Party
Girl'' and ``Dazed and Confused.'' ``It's pretty hard to get plays
unless you're well known.'' (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- WINGS-THEATER-REVIEW --
Lauren Bacall, left, and Rosemary Harris in Noel Coward's ``Waiting
in the Wings,'' at the Kerr. There are few sights more warming on
Broadway at the moment than that of Ms. Harris being chilly. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED - Dec. 16, 1999 -- MET-DESIGN-EXHIBIT --
``Washstand'' 1904 by Charles Rennie Mackintosh (Scottish,
1868-1928). Oak, ceramic tile, leaded colored glass, and mirror
glass. At right, ``Armchair'' by Francis Jourdain (French,
1876-1958). Mahogany; split cane. Proving once again that it can
mount a boutique of a show with the same panache as a five-alarm
blockbuster, the Metropolitan Museum has unveiled an exquisite
sampling of 20th-century design objects from its own collection. A
salute rather than a full survey, ``A Century of Design, Part I:
1900-1925'' is installed in several intimate galleries in the
20th-century wing. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
