Nancy Rehker, mother of the late Lauren Rehker, sits in ``Lauren's
Corner'' in the library at Roadoan Elementary in Ohio. The school
has set up two memorials in remembrance of Lauren, who was a first
grader here. She died in October of 1998 from E. Coli poisoning.
(Gary W. Green/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- MEAT-ECOLI-1-COX -- Lauren
Rehker, 7, of Cleveland died in October 1998 after being infected
with E. coli 0111, a strain of the bacteria that scientists say is
more prevalent in the United States than previously thought. Health
experts never found the source of the infection, though they
believe she came in contact with the bacteria while traveling in
Virginia or Maryland. (Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) ARLINGTON, Va. - Dec. 16, 1999 - NEW-AMERICANS -- With
1999 drawing to a close, more than a hundred immigrants could look
forward to the new year as new Americans. In a naturalization
ceremony on Thursday, on the law school campus of George Mason
University, Judge Wayne Iskra, left, led the new citizens in a
pledge of allegiance to the United States flag. (Shana Raab/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) MEGIDDO, Israel -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT., DEC.
18 -- MIDEAST-TRAVEL-2-COX -- Ron Cathers, an evangelical pastor
from near Lexington, Ky., has come to Megiddo four times. The plain
behind him is where the New Testament predicts the final battle
before Judgment Day will occur. (Larry Kaplow/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- MIDEAST-TRAVEL-1-COX --
Crowds in Jerusalem's Old City making way for a procession of monks
leaving the Church of the Holy Sepulchre. For more than a year,
Israeli officials have wanted to install an emergency exit in the
church - which most Christians believe is the site of Christ's
crucifixion - but the six denominations that control parts of the
cavernous church cannot agree on a location. (Larry Kaplow/Cox
Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED - Dec. 16, 1999 -- NY-DIALLO-TRIAL - The cover
of the March 8, 1999 New Yorker Magazine. Citing a ``tidal wave of
pretrial publicity'', an appellate court ruled on Thursday that the
trial of four officers accused of killing Amadou Diallo last
February should be held in Albany County. The change of venue order
by the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court was an extraordinary
remedy that is reserved for the rarest of cases. But it said that
the shooting of Diallo is that rare case. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
COSMETICS-3-COX -- Linda Mom models the Stila makeup line. The eye
shadow colors are trendy and great for evening. But the foundation
needs to be boosted with a dual powder/foundation to provide better
coverage for someone with flawed skin or discolorations. (William
Berry/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
COSMETICS-2-COX -- Dorscheiia Jackson models the Versace makeup
line. This is a high-quality brand that contains everything a
professional makeup artist looks for in a cosmetic. Great for
people who want a polished look with a rich color and lightweight
texture, but might be a bit pricey for someone who doesn't wear
makeup often. (William Berry/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
COSMETICS-1-COX -- Jessica Hanna models the Sonia Kashuk makeup
line made exclusively for Target. The line offers good quality for
the price, but the foundation and concealer don't provide enough
coverage for flawed skin. A good set of brushes is a must to apply
and blend this makeup properly. (William Berry/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) BOSTON -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- RACISM-CHALLENGE-BOS -- At
left, Horace Seldon, 76, and Ian White Maher, 27, have bridged the
generational gap to devise a plan to fight institutional racism,
which is defined by them as a system where policy decisions of
institutions negatively affect minorities. The two are using their
whiteness to challenge other white people to see the privileges
that come with being white. (Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- WOM-COACHES-BOS --
Jennifer Rizzotti, the head coach for the University of Hartford's
womens basketball team, makes some adjustments during time out in a
game against La Salle University. At 25, the former starting point
guard for the New England Blizzard, is the youngest of any Division
1 coach. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- HOMELESS-PHOTOGRAPHY-B&AMP;W
-- A 1990 photograph by Mary Ellen Mark, at the Corcoran Gallery of
Art in Washington. The existence of despair and the potential for
hope are given visual form by the photographers on display at the
museum. (Corcoran Gallery of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- DIA-ARTS-CENTER-2-B&AMP;W --
Rodney Graham turns his camera upside down to give a new
perspective of trees at the Dia Center. Dia's efforts have a
distinct intellectual slant that can sometimes feel slightly
medicinal. It is possible to emerge from a Dia show feeling that
good deeds have been done: by Dia, for organizing it, and by
oneself, for seeing it. (Dia Center for the Arts/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- DIA-ARTS-CENTER-1-B&AMP;W --
Douglas Gordon uses double images from ``Hypnosis,'' a little-known
Otto Preminger film, in his current work at the Dia Center. Film,
video and photography, the current juggernauts of contemporary art,
have never been dominant at Dia, so it seems noteworthy that four
of the seven artists it is showing this fall are involved with at
least one of these media. (Dia Center for the Arts/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ART-NOTES-B&AMP;W -- Rembrandt's
drawing of the Bulwark de Rose in Amsterdam will be offered next
month at Christie's. The work is one of two Rembrandt drawings from
the estate of Michael S. Currier, a rancher and philanthropist who
was a great-grandson of Andrew W. Mellon, the financier who was a
founder of the National Gallery of Art in Washington. (Christie's
New York/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- TEXACO-OPERA-B&AMP;W -- Milton
Cross, the announcer on the Met Opera radio broadcasts for more
than 40 years, in 1937. ``The Texaco-Metropolitan Opera
International Radio Broadcasts,'' as the series is officially
called, represents the longest continuous commercial sponsorship in
broadcast history. (Metropolitan Opera/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
CANBY-THEATER -- ``Minnelli on Minnelli'' is the self-explanatory
title of the show now at the Palace: Liza Minnelli's irresistible
tribute to her father, Vincente, who, beginning with ``Cabin in the
Sky'' in 1943, directed some of MGM's greatest musicals. Ms.
Minnelli may be somewhat rounder than when she won her Oscar for
the 1972 film ``Cabaret,'' but the need to please is real and the
talent unstoppable. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
TRUMP-ARCHITECTURE-1 -- The Trump International Hotel and Tower, at
1 Central Park West. Trump has become a point of orientation in an
environment where cultural bearings are easily lost. (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- CIVIL-RIGHTS-COX -- From
left, Attorney General Janet Reno, Florida Attorney General Bob
Butterworth and Acting Assistant Attorney General for Civil Rights
Bill Lann Lee at a news conference Thursday in Washington. The
Justice Department and the state of Florida announced a federal
lawsuit Thursday against Adam's Mark Hotels and Resorts for
discrimination in its 21 hotels located across the country. ``This
kind of behavior is simply unacceptable,'' says Reno. (Rick
McKay/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
TRUMP-ARCHITECTURE-2 -- Donald Trump in his limousine in Manhattan.
Some have singled out Trump as a supreme example of Bad Taste,
whatever that might be. The shiny marble, bronze and brass, the
gilded building crowns, the gaudy Atlantic City casinos, the
spangled showgirls: it all adds up in their eyes to vulgar excess,
an unsophisticate's delight in meretricious baubles. (Jeffery A.
Salter/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK - Dec. 16, 1999 -- AIDS-MINORITIES -- Sylvia
Witts-Vitale, leads a class that teaches students to become peer
educators at the Harlem Directors Group. Prominent black
organizations and traditionally black churches have overcome their
reticence to take on the issue of AIDS, recognizing that the
illness in the last decade has claimed more and more of their own
and is no longer contained primarily to gay white men. (Ruby
Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK - Dec. 16, 1999 -- BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK 09-27 --
Chris Ofili's ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' his 1996 painting of a
black Madonna made in part with elephant dung and cut-outs of
genitalia from pornographic magazines, being filmed just before the
``Sensation'' exhibit, at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, opened to the
public in September. The painting was placed behind protective
glass to prevent vandalism. A man, who apparently wanted ``to
clean'' the controversial work, defaced the painting on Thursday.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) JAFFERY, N.H. -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- BINDING-GIFTS-2-BOS --
Peter Sawyer carries wood that will be used in the rebuilding of
his barn. A fire in August claimed the barn at his dairy farm and
killed 120 cows. Sawyer's neighbors and friends rebuilt his barn,
as they did when a silo fell on it in 1983. That's why the new silo
bears a ``thank you'' sign. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) JAFFERY, N.H. -- Dec. 16, 1999 -- BINDING-GIFTS-1-BOS --
David Coll with his wife, Kelly, and their two children, in front
