<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1398 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-LANDROVER-     12-16 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-LANDROVER-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAND ROVER DISCOVERY SERIES II: OFF-ROAD APPLICATIONS FOR MOBILE
COMPUTING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LABELLE, Quebec _ A camel is said to be excellent for traveling
through the desert, but you'd never guess as much if you took it on
a test drive through New York. Though it comes with standard
leather and can be fitted with Asian carpets, the thing lurches,
belches and is hard to park, and the fact that it goes a long way
on a gallon of water is neither here nor there.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with sport utility vehicles. Most are bought these days
as ersatz minivans, and are therefore rated on how carlike they
ride, how much stuff you can pack in, how many cupholders, how
teeth-rattling the stereo.
</P>
<P>
   True, many have made stunning strides in coddling passengers,
slathering the interior with supple hides, filtering out the moan
of those big tires, taming the ride. But the fact remains that SUVs
are beasts best appreciated in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, after a white Land Rover Discovery Series II test car
arrived in Manhattan, off we drove to the great north woods, aka
the Papineau-Labelle Provincial Park in the Laurentian Mountains of
Quebec. A large and lovely stretch of hilly wilderness rich in deep
lakes, wildlife and mosquitoes, Palineau-Labelle goes farther off
the beaten path each year as its trails succumb to benign neglect.
</P>
<P>
   I like to go fishing there, and used to do so in whatever old
car I had, most memorably an '81 Honda Civic wagon. The previous
summer we cracked the oil pan of a (rented) Nissan Altima; last
summer, the park banned low-slung sedans and urged visitors to use
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   This is entry-level off-roading, requiring a few inches of extra
clearance and some basic smarts about fallen branches, washed-out
roads and scampering bear cubs. On the latter: as soon as I saw the
cubs, I stopped and cut the engine. After a few moments, my
partner, abruptly recalling legends of how fiercely maternal bears
feel toward their progeny, whispered, ``Can you raise the windows
with the engine off?''
</P>
<P>
   This is where sport utilities come into their own _ and where
the Disco's proud pedigree starts to show. The silhouette of a
jerrycan on wheels, for example, begins to make sense when you go
airborne over an unexpected heave in the road.
</P>
<P>
   Front-seat passengers return to their seats with L.L. Bean caps
intact, while those in the rear are rewarded with brief glimpses of
the trees through windows thoughtfully punched into the high roof.
Sunroofs front and aft expand the possibilities of free flight even
further, and during one particularly dramatic launch I fantasized
about being catapulted into the great outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The Disco not only takes punishment, it seems to enjoy it (which
is something you wouldn't say about a camel, even in the desert).
We took it up abandoned logging trails, weaving around boulders and
logs; we took it on a road drowned under a breached beaver dam; we
took it up vertical hills and through raspberry patches; we raced a
Jeep Grand Cherokee around an old quarry, tying to see which would
get stuck first. (Neither did.)
</P>
<P>
   The thing bobs, weaves, digs in and keeps going. This is what
driving an SUV should be all about: fun.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, a rumpled baby boomer in search of fine bass is
unlikely to do anything that requires extraordinary skill or poses
serious danger, and most SUVs can handle the backwoods. But I'm not
sure that throwing a Lincoln Navigator or Cadillac Escalade around
the woods qualifies as ``fun.'' They're too big, too plush, too
suburban.
</P>
<P>
   For fun you need attitude, and Land Rover has a heritage it
nurtures even in the literature with the car. In the owner's
manual, instructions for fording streams include a haughty warning
that the CD changer under the seat might get soaked.
</P>
<P>
   Attitude is good. But if I was looking to plop down
$34,000-plus, and I was not planning to spend the rest of my life
in Papineau-Labelle Park, I'd make sure that the attitude was
tempered by serious creature comforts _ if only because every other
vehicle in this price range has them. That, in effect, is the
challenge Land Rover faced with the Series II Discovery _ a
challenge created by its own Range Rover stablemates, which
effectively pioneered the upscale sport utility and still wallow
comfortably in the $60,000-plus class.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The problem with updating the Disco was that so much of its
charm lay in the very anomalies that made it clumsy on the highway.
Its signature silhouette comes from the greatest height (76.4
inches without roof rails) and shortest wheelbase (100 inches) of
any mainstream sport utility, but these attributes also cause the
truck to sway to every crosswind and induce carsickness in children
and other domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover says the Series II is very different from Disco I _
that it is 6 inches longer, 3.5 inches wider, has a broader stance
and 13,500 new parts. It certainly has all the mainstream luxury
cues, like 10-way power seats, speakers everywhere, six cup holders
and the aforementioned dual power sunroofs.
</P>
<P>
   But the equipment that makes the biggest difference is an option
called Active Cornering Enhancement. It senses when the body starts
to tilt during cornering and automatically pumps special sway bars.
The effect is to keep this box tall and upright through normal
cornering.
</P>
<P>
   Lest the driver get carried away, body lean is progressively
returned at higher speeds. Though I did not have a Disco without
ACE to compare, I've driven enough sport utilities to appreciate
the relative absence of sway.
</P>
<P>
   We also had fun with another feature: Hill Descent Control,
which is activated by a button on the dash. Shift into low range,
point the Disco down a muddy hill, push the button and let go. A
computer manipulates the brakes to keep the Disco crawling down at
3.5 to 7.5 miles an hour, or faster if you apply the gas.
</P>
<P>
   We played with this and the equally sophisticated four-wheel
electronic traction control in the sand pits, using them on
progressively steeper and sandier hills, and the Disco kept clawing
away, up or down, like a determined ant.
</P>
<P>
   There are who think this is almost too much, that something in
off-roading is lost when computers take over. That may be true on
the odd stint into the woods, when working the pedals is part of
the fun, but if I had to traverse the Gobi Desert for a living, I
wouldn't mind sharing the chores.
</P>
<P>
   My main complaint was with its reluctant power. The Disco uses a
vintage 4-liter, aluminum, pushrod V8 _ designed by Buick in the
early 1960s _ that produces 188 horsepower and 250 foot-pounds of
torque at 2,600 rpm. It is undoubtedly capable of towing the 5,500
pounds the vehicle is rated for, certainly ample for cruising the
turnpike at 80, where legal, and awfully good at slurping fossil
fuel. But it does nothing to dispel the feeling that this is a
heavy vehicle _ at more than 4,800 pounds, it is _ pushing a wall
of air, a feeling enhanced by the accelerator's long travel. My
Cherokee Sport with its in-line 6 feels perkier, not to mention a
Grand Cherokee with a 4.7-liter V8.
</P>
<P>
   But power is not the name of this game. Image is, and
competence, and you're not likely to get more of either in anything
short of a Hummer _ or a camel.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A look that speaks of mountains to conquer, a
computer to get you up there and bring you down and keep you
vertical in the process. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
