<HEADER>
A1403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ONLINE-SERVICE-ART-2T     12-16 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SERVICE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SALES ARE UP AND SO ARE CUSTOMER COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.J., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thrill of shopping online is that it replaces the shopping
cart with a vehicle that has the power and responsiveness of a
fighter plane. Shoppers can rapidly scan the horizon for available
products, dive to examine individual items, and then track them
with radar-like precision as they are shipped from a warehouse to
their front doors.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more this holiday season, Internet users are
finding that the sophisticated online shopping machinery can
malfunction under actual field conditions.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, some shoppers experience a particularly
aggravating form of helplessness: Companies that have spent tens of
millions of dollars on advertising to attract shoppers often become
distressingly mute when customers complain.
</P>
<P>
   Online stores face all the pitfalls of any Internet service _
sites that can be slow and hard to use and crash at the moment
people want to use them most. They are subject to all the flaws of
any mail-order company _ shipments that may have the wrong items or
damaged goods, or arrive late, or are inexplicably lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say mistakes never will happen is unrealistic, especially
given the scale of what is happening in this industry,'' said John
Barbour, the chief executive of Toysrus.com. That site was nearly
crushed by a tenfold increase in visitors in November that was
prompted by a sale promoted in 62 million catalogs mailed by its
parent, Toys ``R '' Us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a bricks-and-mortar business where things grow 5
percent a year,'' Barbour said. ``We are tripling and quadrupling
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties of online retailers reflect, in large part,
their very success. Traffic at online stores is up 45 percent this
month from last December, according to Media Metrix, a New York
research firm. Analysts expect online sales to triple from last
year, the first big holiday season on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   What is exasperating for many customers is the way some online
stores are dealing with the inevitable problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk away feeling this is so ducky that I didn't leave my
house and got all my shopping done at 10 o'clock at night,'' said
Terri Ann Sullivan of Manhattan Beach, Calif., who bought her twin
daughters two hot Nintendo Game Boy units as well as electronic
cameras and printers available on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the box arrives, and there is only one stupid Game Boy,
without all the pieces you need, and you say this is no good,'' Ms.
Sullivan said. When she logged back on to Amazon, the site would
say only that her other Game Boy had been delayed, along with the
cameras and printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just freaked,'' she said. ``They didn't contact me to say
it's possible you won't ever get these. And they never said they
were sorry.'' Ms. Sullivan eventually canceled the order and found
some items in a local Best Buy store and others on Etoys.com.
</P>
<P>
   More people receive their orders as promised than have
experiences like this, of course. But BizRate, a company that
surveys 30,000 online shoppers each day, is finding that customer
satisfaction, especially with the speed of delivery, is falling.
</P>
<P>
   Customers' rating of on-time delivery, on a 10-point scale, fell
from 8.16 in October and the first half of November to 7.91 in the
three weeks ended Dec. 5. Overall satisfaction was down by a
similar amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much buzz about the ease of shopping online that
expectations are going up,'' said Farhad Mohit, the chairman of
BizRate. ``If thing's don't go flawlessly, it's much more likely
for Web sites to disappoint people.''
</P>
<P>
   The current timeliness rating of 7.91 is well below the 8.11
that BizRate measured for the corresponding period last year. As
the online stores became swamped at the end of the holiday season
last year, BizRate's score fell to 7.39 by the end of December
1998, from 8.17 at the end of November.
</P>
<P>
   One area in which BizRate finds online customers more satisfied
this year is pricing, reflecting the big discounts some sites are
offering as they put growth above profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen such crazy deals on the Net as there are
now,'' said Jack Yedvobnick, a book salesman in Mahomet, Ill., who
says he scours the Web for bargains using sites like Cybergold.com
and Coolsavings.com that offer the online equivalent of coupons.
Mercata.com, he boasts, offered him $50 off on a $100 video
recorder. So far, he has received all the items he ordered,
although he concedes that many sites with the lowest prices are
hard to use.
</P>
<P>
   This year, online stores are hoping that they can prevent the
sort of meltdowns that occurred a year ago. Fingerhut, the
mail-order unit of Federated Stores that handles the shipping for
Etoys and Wal-Mart.com, has ordered all its employees, from its
chief executive down, to help out in its warehouse, a tactic used
by Amazon last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Toysrus.com declared this week that it would no
longer promise to deliver new orders in time for Christmas so it
could devote its attention to a backlog of existing orders.
</P>
<P>
   That is of no help for Nancy Olson, who ordered a video game
from Toysrus.com at the end of November for her nephew's birthday
on Dec. 8. The Web site assured her that the item was in stock and
would be delivered before her deadline. But after a week of
waiting, two unanswered e-mails and 10 minutes on hold on the
telephone, Ms. Olson was told by a phone representative that the
game would not be available until Dec. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think four weeks is a bit much for an order,'' said Ms.
Olson, who runs a small graphics business in Chatham, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of mistake should not have happened, because the Toys
``R'' Us computer is programmed to remove any product from the Web
site as soon as the last item in the warehouse is sold. But when it
comes to keeping track of hundreds of thousands of objects, the
system is not perfect. ``If somebody picks the wrong product and
puts it in a box, suddenly your inventory goes out of kilter,''
Barbour, the chief executive, said.
</P>
<P>
   Web store operators say that keeping up with questions from
customers is like the sorcerer's apprentice trying to keep back the
flood with a bucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do the orders go up dramatically over holidays; calls
and e-mail go up even faster,'' said David Lord, the chief
executive of Toysmart.com, which this week was trying to work
through a backlog of 1,500 e-mails. ``Whether we like it or not,
customers don't trust the Web. So they will place an order now and
call us 10 minutes later to say `Are you sure you will get the
order out?'''
</P>
<P>
   Research analysts for FAC/Equities, a brokerage firm, tested the
customer service capacity of 89 top online retailers, sending an
e-mail question to them. About half answered within a day, a
quarter took two to six days to respond, and a quarter did not
reply.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
