<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SERVICE </SLUG>
 -ART -2NDTAKE-NYT 
UNDATED: not reply.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Often, even if an e-mail or a phone call is answered, the
response leaves aggrieved shoppers cold.
</P>
<P>
   Robb Sansone, an executive with a liquor wholesale firm in
Lebanon Township, N.J., said he was shocked that an Amazing Ally
doll from Amazon.com was delivered in its original manufacturer's
box, allowing anyone to see what he had ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two young daughters who still believe in Santa,'' he
said, ``and I don't want to compromise this.'' Sansone called
Amazon to complain and was told that the company's policy is to
ship certain large items in their manufacturers' boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong answer,'' he wrote in a followup e-mail to Jeff Bezos,
Amazon's chief executive. That note prompted a response from an
Amazon executive who said the policy would be changed. An
Amazon.com spokesman said such large toys are now wrapped in paper
before they are shipped.
</P>
<P>
   As for the problems with out-of-stock items that Ms. Sullivan
had, the Amazon spokesman said the company was largely shipping
products as advertised but had run into delays, especially with
some popular products.
</P>
<P>
   Some complaints about Internet shopping have been more
psychological. Michael Melcher, for example, a New York lawyer,
said he had received all his online orders as promised but still
was not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much as I enjoyed avoiding surly clerks and pushy shoppers, I
felt unexpectedly empty after purchasing gifts for six nieces and
nephews,'' he said. ``I missed the physical exploration of
shopping. Ordering online was faster, but it felt like work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
