<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LE-CORSAIRE-DANCE-2TA     12-16 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LE-CORSAIRE-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BETTER TV WHEN THE DANCE DOES THE TALKING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Harris Green, a former editor editor at Dance magazine, writes
about the performing arts.  
 By HARRIS GREEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Dance in America'' broadcast of American Ballet Theater in
``Le Corsaire,'' which Channel 13 will broadcast Monday night at 9
in New York, finds the dancers in splendid form when they are
allowed to do what they do best _ dance. They're less successful
when required to do what's increasingly demanded on television
today _ talk, talk, talk.
</P>
<P>
   It's another example of the medium's forgetting that actions not
only speak louder than words but also make livelier viewing.
</P>
<P>
   The company, taped live last February at the Orange County
Performing Arts Center in Costa Mesa, Calif., is certainly at its
best in this Byronic romp, in which pirates, slaves and a jolly
pasha dance in harems and grottoes and on storm-tossed ships.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally the director Matthew Diamond and the editor Girish
Bhargava will jerk the viewer from a good center seat downstairs to
a perch in the top balcony to savor a floor pattern (even though
the corps may look like a flea circus performing it).
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, they avoid the hazards inherent in televised
ballet by using a minimum of close-ups to concentrate on steps and
phrases, line and mass. Although far from a great ballet,
``Corsaire'' emerges as great fun.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the producer, Channel 13, has added some
contrived showmanship. Kevin McKenzie, Ballet Theater's artistic
director, introduces the program, gracefully speaking a jaunty text
by Wendy Wasserstein about the difficulty of summarizing the
ballet's plot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the plot of ``Corsaire'' is not complex; it's merely
overpopulated. There are two villains and two ballerinas, plus a
Pirate Woman who struts on whenever a partner is needed by the
leader of those impromptu ensembles that may come merrily, merrily
from out of nowhere. A brief synopsis would have oriented the most
innocent of viewers within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, considerable time is spent having the dancers describe
what their characters will do in the coming act. Nothing could have
been better devised to befuddle the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Stiefel at least gives a charmingly casual account of his
derring-do as Conrad, the lead corsaire. Vladimir Malakhov,
however, discusses his role of the slave trader, Lankendem, in a
heavy Russian accent that is difficult to follow. Angel Corella,
caught in close-up on a bad-hair day, is only a bit more
intelligible about his part, Ali, the slave boy. ( Corella's
sensational dancing in Act II will bring down the house.)
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kent as the heroine, Medora, actually forgets what comes
next at one point, but this lapse is occasioned more by the
nebulousness of the plot than by its intricacy. The case for
complexity is hardly proved when some unfortunate child is cornered
at intermission for a pop quiz on Act I. (He flunks.)
</P>
<P>
   Viewed during this festive season and consumed along with cups
of sufficiently potent eggnog, such genial gimmickery would seem
harmless enough if Ballet Theater and PBS hadn't collaborated on
what was presented as a special performance, with Natalia Makarova
as host, two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   The show was actually assembled from two performances taped
before an audience invited to provide ``live'' reactions. Now,
anything that gets more ballet on television is welcome, but what's
unsettling about this ruse was how time that could have been
devoted to dance was given over to several vapid interviews with
the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   This fascination with chitchat over performance had already
reached epidemic proportions on telecasts of the Olympics. The
world's top athletes competing among themselves was apparently
considered such a poor ratings draw by NBC that its coverage of the
1996 Atlanta games completely ignored some sports to make room for
mini-biographies (usually of Americans and often of eventual
losers) and the deeper thoughts of John Tesh. Wasn't PBS created to
avoid programming by polls and focus groups?
</P>
<P>
   PBS was also reluctant to let well enough alone when presenting
some works of Paul Taylor. ``Company B,'' danced to the galvanizing
recordings of the Andrews Sisters, was utterly deconstructed when
Diamond, Bhargava and the producer Judy Kinberg set it in a
realistic dance hall as part of a program aptly titled ``The
Wrecker's Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Taylor drew a picture of American innocence on the eve of World
War II in ``Company B'' and regularly undercut its high spirits
with dark portents of the looming conflict. In the abstract space
of an empty stage, a man crumpling to the floor during ``Bei mir
bist du schon'' is deeply moving.
</P>
<P>
   In PBS's concrete setting of a real ballroom, he's just another
drunk. ( Taylor is said to have loved the result, I should add.)
</P>
<P>
   If the best of Fred Astaire's classic RKO film routines haven't
demonstrated it, the movie ``George Balanchine's The Nutcracker,''
also edited by Bhargava, inadvertently showed how filmed dance
makes its strongest impact simply by occurring right before your
eyes. Bhargava's inventive cutting of the Act I children's party
and the battle with the mice made these ``Nutcracker'' scenes
unusually exciting. (Has anyone pointed out that the designer
Rouben Ter-Arutunian's mice are caricatures of Balanchine?)
</P>
<P>
   But when it came time for the Christmas tree to grow five
stories high and for the snow-laden forest to materialize, the
director, Emile Ardolino, replaced this genuinely awesome stage
spectacle with some not-so-special effects. Although New York City
Ballet dancers looked great in Act II, the special ``Nutcracker''
buzz created by those transformation scenes was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a place for truly informed commentary as a
complement to televised dance. ( McKenzie could have been amusing
as well as instructive by explaining how ``Corsaire'' arrived, via
Boston Ballet, with a brace of choreographers and five composers in
its credits.) What's not needed is more of the taped blandness that
occupied the intermission of last summer's live telecast of Peter
Martins's ``Swan Lake'' at City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Sills, who can always be counted on to keep a
conversation bubbling along, chatted up Martins and the rather wary
looking scheduled stars of the performance, Darci Kistler and
Damian Woetzel.
</P>
<P>
   Martins's instantly controversial production had already raised
many questions _ Why was Rotbart shown hexing the Prince in Act I?
Why use a pestiferous Soviet-style Jester? Just exactly what did
the designer, Per Kirkeby, think he was up to? _ but Ms. Sills
genially skirted most of them.
</P>
<P>
   The segment had already been overtaken by events anyway. An
aggravated injury had forced Ms. Kistler to cancel, and Miranda
Weese replaced her on exceedingly short notice; an interview with
Ms. Weese at intermission would certainly have proved newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Intermission interviews, once a fixture of live PBS telecasts,
also inject a note of extra risk. Who can forget Dick Cavett's
breathlessly assuring Ms. Makarova that Act III of ``Swan Lake,''
which she had just performed, was the best act of any ballet he had
ever seen, and her turning a hooded glance upon him and saying,
``So what was wrong with Act II?'' Live dance on television doesn't
get any livelier than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
