u f BC-JAPAN-PHONE-NYT &LR;      12-16 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3-WAY MERGER WILL CHALLENGE JAPANESE PHONE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MANNESMANN-VODAFONE) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's dominant telecommunications company confronted a
new competitive challenge at home Thursday with the announcement
that three smaller rivals would soon be merging.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of KDD Corp., IDO Corp. and DDI Corp., to be
completed by next October, would create a new telephone and data
transmission business that would be No. 2 domestically to Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Such a merger had been rumored for weeks. Although it would
remain smaller in size than NTT, it would effectively present
Japanese customers with a full-service alternative to Japan's
telephone giant, a former government monopoly that had been largely
unchallenged at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``NTT is further strengthening its grip on the market, and we
felt a need to create a group that can compete with NTT,'' Yusai
Okuyama, president of DDI and designated president of the new
company, also to be known as DDI, said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Since its reorganization in July, NTT has tightened its grasp on
the local phone market, carved its business into highly focused
pieces under a holding company structure, and begun to take aim at
providing international phone services. It is the parent of two
highly successful subsidiaries, NTT Mobile Communications Network
Corp., better known as NTT DoCoMo, and NTT Communications, which
specializes in data transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Part of NTT's strength, however, lay in the fragmented nature of
the telecom industry here, and the merger announced Thursday marks
the beginning of the end of that advantage.
</P>
<P>
   DDI will be able to offer its customers everything that NTT
offers them except local telephone service, which is increasingly
under pressure anyway from the proliferation of mobile telephones
and the services available on them. DDI is Japan's second-largest
cellular phone service company after NTT DoCoMo, which controls 57
percent of the market, and IDO is a privately held mobile phone
company in which Toyota Motor Corp. has a 63 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company does have some competitive drawbacks. In a
business where size and geographic reach can make a difference, DDI
will be only one-third the size of NTT, with projected revenue of
2.69 trillion yen in the fiscal year that will end March 31, 2001,
or roughly $26 billion at current exchange rates. NTT estimates
that its revenue for the year that will end March 31 will be 10.7
trillion yen, or almost $104 billion.
</P>
<P>
   DDI also will be saddled with debts of 1.9 trillion yen, or
roughly $18.4 billion. That debt load might crimp its ability to
invest in new so-called third-generation mobile telephone
technology that can trasmit voice, data and video signals, the
starting point for the discussions between the three merger
partners. All wanted an opportunity to win one of the three
licenses to offer the third-generation phone services that the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications will hand out next year,
but alone, none of them was a likely candidate.
</P>
<P>
   DDI, which is bringing most of the debt to the new company,
lacked the investment capital needed. KDD has no cellular phone
service and its international phone services are under severe
pricing pressure. And while IDO has wealthy Toyota as a financial
backer, it is tiny compared with the other players in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, none of the three was able to attract an international
partner, which many analysts see as critical to success as the
telecom business becomes increasingly global.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Telecom, which will be the third-largest
telecommunications company after the merger, has linked up with
British Telecom, Vodafone AirTouch and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The new DDI might make a more attractive partner, and KDD has
said it has had talks with France Telecom and Deutsche Telecom, as
well as with the Internet-related telecom companies Global Crossing
and Qwest Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
