<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      12-16 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED CELTICS FACING TWO AWAY GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Celtics are staggering, weakened by injuries. They
have lost three straight, and they are about to hit the road, where
they have won just once this season.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Rick Pitino remains optimistic as the Celtics prepare
to play in San Antonio and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can win both games,'' Pitino said Thursday. ``But it will
take a great night from more people offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker carried the Celtics in their 96-86 loss to Utah
Wednesday night. Walker took charge from the power forward spot and
had 36 points and 12 rebounds. But without Paul Pierce (ankle) or
Vitaly Potapenko (calf) available, no other Celtic frontcourt
player presented a threat.
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino is also being realistic. He plans to shift Walker to
the small forward position for at least part of Friday night's
game, relying on Tony Battie and Pervis Ellison, and preparing for
the return of power forward Danny Fortson in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics entered the week above .500, but losses at Cleveland
(115-88) and to Utah within 24 hours dropped their record to 10-11.
Now, they must prepare for the Spurs' Tim Duncan and David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard, but we didn't play intelligently against
Cleveland,'' Pitino said. ``And we played hard, and we played well
against Utah. But playing hard is not enough against some of these
great teams. You've also got to make shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics weren't making their shots against Utah, which left
them unable to press. The Jazz took control with an effective
transition game and a masterful half-court attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking reserves who are by nature not scorers and
putting them in scoring roles, and it's difficult for them,'' said
Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan scored 31 points as the Spurs defeated the Celtics,
121-98, Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll be able to make adjustments against San
Antonio the second time around,'' Pitino said. ``If you concentrate
on (Duncan and Robinson), they have spot-up shooters who can kill
you. Plus, they are unselfish and play good defense. They have the
size to keep you off the backboards. We are going to have to hit
our perimeter shots because they don't give you too much inside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about Tim Duncan, but (the Spurs) can be
stopped,'' guard Adrian Griffin said. ``It will take a team effort,
and a lot of weak-side help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do what we try to do in every game: play our style.
Once you let the other team play to their style, it's to their
advantage. We've played well against these teams before. We just
have to go out and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Battie will be a central figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we played them, we did a decent job with their
big men,'' Battie said. ``But we didn't do as well with our
defensive rotation, and they killed us down the stretch from the
outside. If me or Pervis gets in foul trouble, we are in trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
