<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1418 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RWANDA-REPORT-1STLD-W     12-16 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICIZES U.N. AND U.S. FOR FAILING TO PREVENT GENOCIDE IN
RWANDA
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for new 3rd and 4th grafs summarizing Rwanda conflict; subs
17th graf to eliminate duplicated material; inserts new 19th graf
about impact of report; adds 890-word addatend) 
(sw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A strongly worded report issued on Thursday by
an international panel of experts holds both the United Nations and
leading member countries, primarily the United States, responsible
for failing to prevent or stop the genocide in Rwanda in 1994,
which cost hundreds of thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   The report, commissioned by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who
was then head of the peacekeeping department, spares no one, naming
those in the highest reaches of the United Nations who were running
the operation in Rwanda, including Annan and his predecessor,
Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
   The genocide in Rwanda, which took place in 1994 when Hutu began
to massacre Tutsi and moderate Hutu, set off a chain reaction that
led to the current war in Congo, the former Zaire, involving more
than half a dozen African nations.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations sent a small peacekeeping force to the area
in 1993 after repeated warnings about the growing ethnic conflict
in the civil war between the Hutu-led government of Rwanda and the
Tutsi-led armed opposition. But the presence of the peacekeeping
force was not enough to prevent the killing of an estimated 800,000
people from April to July 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The panel found that Annan and others in his department made
weak and equivocal decisions in the face of mounting disaster. At
the same time the Clinton administration _ represented at the
United Nations by Madeleine Albright _ persistently played down the
problem, setting the tone for a Security Council generally lacking
the political will for a tougher response.
</P>
<P>
   Both the United Nations and the United States sent the wrong
message to militias bent on genocide, the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Annan called the report ``thorough and objective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of the United Nations, I acknowledge this failure
and express my deep remorse,'' he said, calling the events in
Rwanda ``genocide in its purest and most evil form.'' In Rwanda,
government officials said the secretary-general should visit and
apologize in person.
</P>
<P>
   But the leader of the investigation, Ingvar Carlsson, a former
Swedish prime minister, did not place all the blame on the United
Nations. At a news conference on Thursday, he said it would
``always be difficult to explain'' why the Security Council _
managed by the world's major powers and not the U.N. bureaucracy _
decimated the peacekeeping force in Rwanda, reducing it to a few
hundred from 2,500 troops when the genocide began, and then
increasing the force to 5,500 when the weeks of massacres were
over.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which provided Carlsson's investigators with
minimal help and no documents during their six-month study,
effectively blocked the Security Council in 1993 and 1994 from
authorizing any significant action in Rwanda. No high-ranking
American officials involved in policy making at the time agreed to
meet the panel.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department said on Thursday that it had cooperated
fully with the investigation, adding that the United States has a
policy of not releasing classified documents to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with their assessment,'' said James B. Foley, a
State Department spokesman. ``We provided senior officials who
extensively briefed the panel and answered all their questions
satisfactorily.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley said those officials included William Woods, deputy
assistant secretary of state for international organizations, and
Richard Bogosian, one of the department's top Africa specialists.
Both men had studied all the records of the period and discussed
them with the panel, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Carlsson repeated the Clinton administration's
explanation that the loss of 18 American Rangers in Somalia in
October 1993 had scared the United States off peacekeeping for
domestic political reasons, particularly peacekeeping in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Carlsson said blame rested with ``those who didn't care at all,
who said Rwanda is a distant African country.'' On a trip to Rwanda
last year, President Clinton apologized for Washington's inaction.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations opened its archives and made all its former
officials available to the panel on Annan's orders. A U.N. official
said this led to an ``asymmetry'' in the damning details by which
U.N. actions could be judged compared with those of pivotal
governments. Belgium and France, whose peacekeepers were in the
field in Rwanda before and after the genocide, have conducted their
own investigations. The United States has not.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that about 800,000 people were killed in 100
days from April to July 1994, in a Hutu-led campaign of genocide
against Tutsi and moderate Hutu who often defended their neighbors
with their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Annan appointed the three-member panel in May to conduct an
independent investigation into the U.N. role in the critical months
in Rwanda. Besides Carlsson, the members were Han Sung-joo of South
Korea, a former foreign minister and leading international affairs
scholar, and Rufus M. Kupolati of Nigeria, a retired lieutenant
general familiar with U.N. peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
   The report carries no force but highlights the difficulties that
the United Nations has in gaining support for increasingly complex
and dangerous peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
   It follows by several weeks the release of an internal U.N.
inquiry into problems in the Bosnia peacekeeping operation that led
to thousands of deaths in Serbian attacks on Bosnian Muslims in
Srebrenica and other towns. That report also found fault with both
the organization and Security Council members.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The report issued on Thursday shows a pattern of ignored
warnings and missed signs of the genocide to come in Rwanda.
Reports from the commander in the field, Gen. Romeo A. Dallaire of
Canada, of plans for ethnic attacks and accumulating arms caches
were not taken seriously enough or passed high enough up in the
organization for immediate attention, the panel found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information received by a United Nations mission that plans
are being made to exterminate any group of people requires and
immediate and determined response,'' the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   It also said U.N. headquarters in New York should have given
more weight to reports from Rwanda peacekeepers that arms caches
were being assembled by the Hutu militia. Instead it was decided
that confiscating arms was not in the mandate of the force. The
Security Council had made that clear, Kupolati said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that ``instructions from New York not to
seize weapons'' gave the signal to the Hutu militia that the
peacekeepers were not likely to ``take assertive action to deal
with such caches.''
</P>
<P>
   The report does not support accusations that Boutros-Ghali was
personally responsible for ignoring warnings of genocide, though it
does say he prevented officials in day-to-day contact with Rwanda
from briefing the Security Council. The panel found that a cable
from Dallaire in January 1994 warning of Hutu plans for massacres
of Tutsi was not immediately shown to Boutros-Ghali, whom some
politicians and others in Europe have tried to charge with
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The information was shared with the embassies of Belgium, France
and the United States in Rwanda, which were asked soon after the
cable was received to warn the Hutu-led government of President
Juvenal Habyarimana not to allow any such attacks. Diplomats
relayed the information to their capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the report, ``Independent Inquiry into the Actions of
the United Nations During the 1994 Genocide in Rwanda,'' is a
painstaking chronological reconstruction of the crisis beginning
the year before the killings. The panel noted that various reports
during that time had provided early warning of the increasingly
dangerous ethnic dimensions of the ongoing civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Among the signals was a report by the United Nations Human
Rights Commission expert on extrajudicial, summary or arbitrary
executions, Waly Bacre Ndiaye, which suggested that genocide was
possible. The report seemed to have been largely ignored at the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after a peace agreement was signed between the Hutu-led
government of Rwanda and the Tutsi-led armed opposition, the Rwanda
Patriotic Front, in August 1993, a joint delegation came to New
York to sound an alarm that the agreement could fall apart and to
plead for more than 4,000 U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later Boutros-Ghali recommended a force about half that
size, but that was cut back further by the Security Council.
Dallaire was appointed commander. Aware of the ethnic volatility in
Rwanda, he proposed rules of engagement for his forces _ which the
investigation found were often ill trained and ill equipped _ to
let them intervene in crimes against humanity. U.N. headquarters
never responded to his request for approval.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, Dallaire sent his cable warning of major trouble,
which has become the center of accusations that the United Nations
could have predicted genocide and did nothing. The cable was sent
to Maj. Gen. Maurice Baril, a Canadian who was a military adviser
to Boutros-Ghali. In it, Dallaire said that in addition to
information about arms caches and a campaign to list all Tutsi and
others apparently being selected for death, there were plans to
assassinate opposition members of parliament and provoke Belgian
peacekeepers into using force, which would prompt Hutu to kill a
few of them and force their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, then head of peacekeeping in New York, sent Dallaire and
the United Nations' special envoy in Rwanda, Jacques-Roger Booh
Booh, to talk to Habyarimana, who denied that his officers or Hutu
militias were planning attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Fears continued to mount in Kigali, the capital of Rwanda, until
April 6, 1994, when a plane carrying Habyarimana and President
Cyprien Ntaryamira of Burundi was apparently shot down while
approaching Kigali airport. Hutu radicals seized the moment and
unleashed the genocidal campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the bloody melee that followed, groups of U.N. peacekeepers
were rounded up by Rwandan Hutu troops and 10 Belgians were
executed. The remaining Belgians, the best-qualified soldiers among
the peacekeepers, were then abruptly withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Belgium was criticized for this and for
abandoning 2,000 civilians hiding in a technical school after
telling them they would be protected. They were savagely attacked.
The Belgian withdrawal prompted others to pull out, an action
supported by the United States, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other Rwandans died when they fled to churches,
assuming that houses of worship would be places of refuge and
safety. Carlsson, who remembers as a boy of 10 seeing survivors of
the Nazi Holocaust being trucked out of Germany in white buses,
said his most searing memory of Rwanda was one pair of tiny shoes
still lying in a churchyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pair of small shoes from, evidently, a 3-year-old
girl,'' he said, ``her crime being that she was a Tutsi or belonged
to a moderate Hutu family. She probably didn't know about the world
yet. I can assure you I will never forget, I will never forget
those two shoes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
