<SLUG> BC-Y2K-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000 PREPARATIONS WERE COSTLY, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation will be warm and secure on Jan. 1, the
federal government predicted Thursday, but the Year 2000 computer
problem has made it a little poorer.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said Thursday that it was ready for the Year 2000,
but that it had spent $3.6 billion, enough to buy an aircraft
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department said that all the electric utilities in
the United States are ready for Jan. 1, but industry
representatives said the utilities had spent $2.5 billion, the
price of several power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Management and Budget estimated on Wednesday that
federal expenses relating to the Year 2000 problem would total
$8.38 billion over five years, ending next September.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the General Accounting Office found that 24 agencies it
surveyed expected to spend $7.5 billion, which was up sharply from
earlier estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The expenditures were intended to root out computer coding that
stored the date as a two-digit number and could read the year after
1999 as 1900 instead of 2000, and then malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The spending had some side benefits. The Federal Aviation
Administration said Thursday that it, too, was ready, after
spending $368 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a very up-to-date, accurate inventory of all our
systems,'' said Mary Powers-King, who is in charge of the Year 2000
transition at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, she said, the air traffic control system probably
would have run about the same if nothing had been done because it
does not use the year in handing minute-to-minute tasks. But
various administrative systems would not have run without
renovation, Ms. Powers-King said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on Thursday concentrated on progress, not cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate absolutely no problems in the Department of
Defense,'' said John Hamre, the deputy secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   He said all but two of the 2,101 systems crucial to the Pentagon
are ready. Those two are internal data management systems in the
National Imagery and Mapping Agency. There are 5,500 other systems,
only 10 of which have not been cleared, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating to say that we had to spend $3.6
billion,'' Hamre said. But, ``We could not stand the consequence if
we had not spent the $3.6 billion. In the process, we have much,
much better positive control over our information systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The energy secretary, Bill Richardson, said the last seven of
the more than 3,000 companies that supply electricity in the United
States have now reported that they are ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``With just 16 days until the year 2000, all American customers
will be serviced by Y2K-ready power companies by the new year,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that oil supplies could be disrupted if other countries
have problems, but that Mexico, Venezuela, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia
have agreed to step up production if that happens.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman of another agency, the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission, warned that while all fuel distribution
systems should be able to cope with normal demand, gasoline
supplies could run out if consumers hoarded gasoline in
anticipation of a shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, James Hoecker, who coordinated the preparedness of
natural gas companies for the year 2000, said that his agency was
ready.
</P>
<P>
   But he urged consumers ``to be prudent, to be prepared, but not
to make energy-purchasing decisions they would not normally make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to hoard or store dangerous fuels, for
example,'' Hoecker said. ``There are important reasons not to do
that. Nor do we want unexpected demands placed on distribution
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and Hoecker, along with executives from the electric
and natural gas industries, delivered a ``final report card'' on
the energy industries Thursday at a Potomac Electric Power Co.
control center in suburban Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of that utility, John Derrick, said that half of
his company's employees would be ``on shift or on call'' on New
Year's Eve and the early hours of New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also said Thursday that the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve, a half-billion-barrel stockpile maintained by the federal
government, might be used in case of a supply interruption.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had already taken the legal step of advising the
president to open the reserve, which must be done two weeks in
advance of using the oil. But he added that his recommendation was
just a precaution. ``I don't want to move markets,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
