<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL INQUIRY BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   Parliament began an investigation into allegations that former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's party accepted bribes. Kohl has admitted
he used secret accounts to pay for campaign activities of his
Christian Democratic Party, a violation of finance laws. The
inquiry will also examine allegations that Kohl's party received a
$1.6 million donation in exchange for the sale of a group of
state-owned apartments, which went for well below a rival bid.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: JAILED AS SPY
</P>
<P>
   A former top official of the foreign ministry's Asian
department, Valentin Moiseyev, was sentenced to 12 years in prison
after being convicted of spying for South Korea. Moiseyev was
accused in a 1998 espionage case in which a South Korean diplomat
was expelled and Seoul's foreign minister resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: POLITICAL MANEUVERING
</P>
<P>
   Political uncertainty deepened after a member of Parliament had
a heart attack and other deputies accused Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema's government of seeking to buy votes to firm up his fraying
center-left coalition. But the lower house passed a budget,
clearing the way for Senate approval by the weekend. D'Alema has
said he will quit if he cannot form a new coalition once the budget
is passed.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: IRA LEADER FREED
</P>
<P>
   Padraic Wilson, 42, commander of Irish Republican Army prisoners
inside the Maze Prison and a supporter of the Northern Ireland
peace pact, left jail after serving a third of a 24-year sentence
for possessing explosives. He is reportedly key to IRA plans to
begin discussing disarmament with an international panel.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: 35-HOUR WORKWEEK NEARS
</P>
<P>
   The government moved a step closer to giving French workers one
of the world's shortest workweeks. Seventeen months after adopting
a law calling for a 35-hour workweek, it has adopted a second piece
of legislation detailing how and when businesses are to make the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: OPTIMISM ON GREECE
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said he hopes to resolve disputes
with Greece before a new deadline of 2004. The European Union
recently said it may recommend arbitration if the two countries are
not able to come to settlements of their own by then. They disagree
on issues related to Cyprus and Aegean Sea islands.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PROVINCIAL TAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando de la Rua has begun a 180-day federal
takeover of the bankrupt provincial government of Corrientes in an
effort to end months of protests by state employees. The workers,
who have not been paid for up to six months, are blocking several
bridges and threaten to take over a bridge connecting Argentina
with Uruguay that is vital to trade.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BUDGET FAILS TO PASS
</P>
<P>
   In a raucous session, the Congress failed to approve the federal
budget for next year and scheduled a special session for the vote
next Tuesday and Wednesday. The lower house did pass the revenue
law for 2000, which raised the expected average price of petroleum
to $16 a barrel from the $15.50 proposed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SINGER REAPPEARS
</P>
<P>
   Karina Yapor, a 17-year-old backup singer for Gloria Trevi,
Mexico's best-known rock star, reappeared for the first time in a
year. In a televised interview, Ms. Yapor denied that Ms. Trevi's
manager, Sergio Andrade, had sired her son, whom Ms. Yapor bore
when she was 15 and living with Andrade. Ms. Yapor's parents have
filed kidnapping and other charges against Andrade, brother of a
ruling party senator. He and Ms. Trevi are fugitives.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: HELD 37 YEARS WITHOUT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A panel of Supreme Court judges ordered an inquiry into how and
why Ajay Ghosh was jailed for 37 years apparently without a trial
on charges of murdering his brother. Ghosh was supposed to be tried
in 1963, but the trial was postponed after he was found to be of
unsound mind. His case came to light as part of a public interest
lawsuit filed on behalf of people jailed for long periods while
awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: AID BAN LIFTED
</P>
<P>
   The United States lifted a hold on a shipment of medicine to
Afghanistan that the relief group Doctors Without Borders has been
trying to send to Kabul. A State Department spokesman said the
delay was caused by ``technical'' concerns about what else may have
been on the Afghan plane.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: VICTORY DECLARED
</P>
<P>
   On the first anniversary of the start of four days of punitive
air strikes, Iraq declared ``a great victory'' in its military and
diplomatic confrontation with the United States and Britain. An
Iraqi military spokesman said U.S. and British jets had flown
16,848 missions since last December's attacks and killed 156
people.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA: HOPES OF ENDING WAR
</P>
<P>
   During a daylong visit, the United States under secretary of
state, Thomas L. Pickering, expressed optimism about the prospects
for an end to the Angolan civil war. Pickering, who met with
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, told the local news media that
peace would come only through a political settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
