<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN:  GRIFFEY NEEDS TO DO WHAT HE DOES BEST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. needs to play in a game somewhere, anywhere,
soon. Even if it were one of those silly, celebrity softball games
on MTV, Junior needs to show us that sweet swing, that majestic
arm, the climbing-up-the-outfield-fence catches and that
once-ubiquitous smile.
</P>
<P>
   Remind us why he is the best player in baseball, and why we love
to watch him. Give us some evidence to return our murky minds to
baseball and the reasons we stare at him in awe. Even watching
Griffey wave a stickball bat would be much more preferable to
digesting these soap opera details about where he will permit the
Seattle Mariners to trade him on this day or that day.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Griffey's wonderful talents as a future Hall of
Famer have been temporarily nudged aside by this saga over the last
six weeks. It has been tedious to digest the evolving decisions
that Griffey has made since telling the Mariners that an
unprecedented $135 million contract could not coax him to stay with
them beyond next season, and that he instead wanted to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   That is his prerogative. The Mariners might not even still call
Seattle home and Safeco Field might not exist if it were not for
Griffey. As a 10-year veteran who has played 5 years with his
current team, Griffey has sacrificed and starred for the Mariners
and has earned the valuable right to determine his future by being
able to veto trades.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey squashed a potential trade to the Mets late Monday
night, a deal that would have inserted him in front of Mike Piazza
in the lineup on a stellar team that crawled to within two
victories of the World Series last season. How could a hungry
player who watched the Mets soar, stagger and soar again during an
incredible dash, not be intrigued enough to give New York a
one-year tryout?
</P>
<P>
   The two-time World Series champion Yankees are a borough away
and Griffey could have elevated the Mets to the Yankees' lofty
status. If Griffey wanted to exceed his two postseason experiences
with Seattle, he should have pondered how rewarding it could be in
New York in October. But Griffey, the biggest star in the sport,
had no interest in this enticing notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' said Piazza, ``you don't know what a guy is
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   What is Griffey thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Probably that everything will eventually unfold the way he wants
and he would be correct. Griffey has serious leverage over the
Mariners and envisions himself pursuing Hank Aaron's career home
run record in Cincinnati, the city where his father could be the
next manager and where Junior grew up. Eventually, this will be a
homey image. Getting there has been, and will continue to be,
unsightly.
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence that the Mariners called a news conference
as soon as Griffey asked for a trade. As amazing a player as
Griffey is, one Mariners official said he used the word ``control''
too often, sounding more like a cranky new owner than a confident
All-Century player. The Mariners could finish first in the ordinary
American League West with Griffey, but it is improbable that he
will still be with them at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   There was bogus talk about Griffey's wanting to play closer to
his home in Orlando, Fla., which no sane person believed. Griffey
then gave the Mariners a list of four teams (Reds, Mets, Atlanta
and Houston) that he would agree to be dealt to, but the list was
also unreliable because Griffey erased it after the Mariners
mentioned trade scenarios with teams other than the final four. So
Griffey, who is more insecure than a superstar should be, declared
that it had to be the Reds or he would remain in Seattle for
another year before becoming a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pursued Griffey aggressively and were left feeling a
bit empty, but they must forget about Griffey and concentrate on
adding a starting pitcher and a power-hitting outfielder. Let the
thoughts about Griffey in center field at Shea Stadium vanish.
</P>
<P>
   One supermarket with an advertising marquee zipper along the
Henry Hudson Parkway in Manhattan already feels that way. The store
advertised some items on the zipper while also giving a message to
Griffey: ``We have enough obnoxious and overpaid players in New
York. And I hope you enjoy the night life in Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Griffey's right to veto potential trades and say he will
only go to Cincinnati. But it is everyone else's right to stop
caring until Griffey returns to playing baseball and restores the
appeal of the player who first entranced us a decade ago. See you
in April, Junior. Somewhere.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
