<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, DEC. 17
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 14,
about a delay in the Security Council's vote on a resolution
renewing arms inspections of Iraq misstated the degree to which the
country is said to have enriched a supply of uranium. According to
David Kyd, a spokesman for the International Atomic Energy Agency,
it is 2.6 percent, not 2.3 or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also because of an editing error, the article referred
incorrectly to a comment by Paul L. Leventhal, president of the
Nuclear Control Institute, an independent organization in
Washington. He said that uranium enriched to 3 percent from 2.3
could be used to create bomb-grade uranium. He did not say that an
Iraqi supply of 1.8 tons of uranium had been enriched to 2.3 or 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The headline on the article misstated France's action. France
did not halt debate on the resolution; it delayed a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Because of another editing error, an article yesterday about
Iraq's refusal to admit inspectors from the International Atomic
Energy Agency misstated the year the United Nations imposed
economic sanctions on the country. It was 1990, after Iraq invaded
Kuwait _ not 1991, the year of the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 13 and Tuesday,
Dec. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 13
and Tuesday, Dec. 14, about the conflict in Chechnya misstated the
given name of the chairman of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, who is seeking an end to the fighting. He is
Knut Vollebaek, not Kurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
