<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1448 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-BRADLEY-1STLD-     12-16 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, BRADLEY TEAM UP ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS that event was a taped town hall meeting for ``Nightline''in
7th graf; EDITS to conform in 3rd graf of 2nd take) 
 (rk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, N.H. _ Sen. John McCain and former Sen. Bill Bradley
joined forces across a partisan and ideological divide Thursday to
pledge support for revamping the nation's campaign finance system
and to take some sharp shots at each other's front-running
opponents for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to underscore Washington's inability to change itself,
McCain, a Republican, and Bradley, a Democrat, re-created on
national television the bipartisan handshake between President
Clinton and former House Speaker Newt Gingrich at the same location
in 1995. At the time, the president and speaker called for a
commission to study changing campaign finance laws. But nothing
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I most of all want to give the government back to the people
of this country,'' McCain said, agreeing with Bradley that
big-money interests have caused gridlock on Capitol Hill. ``I don't
believe we can do that unless we reform the finance system.''
</P>
<P>
   During their event, Bradley and McCain signed a pledge stating
that if both won their parties' nominations, they would not allow
their parties to spend soft money on their general election
campaigns. Both also support legislation to ban soft money
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is used by the parties for activities like voter
registration and printing signs. Soft money cannot be used to help
specific candidates. But in 1996, soft money was used by both major
parties to finance so-called issue advertising that essentially
promoted the presidential candidates, violating the spirit, if not
the letter of the law.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing to ban soft money, McCain and Bradley would try to
close that loophole. But only McCain has pledged to give up soft
money unilaterally. Bradley says he'll forgo soft money as long as
the Republican nominee does, too. Neither McCain nor Bradley could
stop state parties from spending soft money, expenditures that can
also benefit presidential candidates. So they would leave a
loophole even as they attempted to close one.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's event was unusual not only because the two men are
from different parties and hold conflicting positions on issues
ranging from taxes to gun control to abortion, but also because
their personalities and campaign styles are so different. The event
was a town hall meeting taped for broadcast on the ABC News program
``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   Those disparate styles were on view from the moment they
appeared in a tent outside the Earl Bourden Senior Center here. In
his opening statement, McCain, the more combative of the two,
launched a caustic attack on Clinton and Vice President Gore,
Bradley's lone rival for the Democratic nomination, asserting that
they had debased ``every institution of government'' with their
aggressive fund raising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scandal of the last two years was not Monica Lewinsky,''
McCain said. ``The president took the Lincoln bedroom and treated
it like a Motel 6 and he was the bell hop. And the vice president
of the United States asked monks and nuns to violate their vow of
poverty in order to pay thousands of dollars so that they could
spiritually commune with him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to a 1996 campaign event that Gore attended at
a Buddhist Temple in Los Angeles. Gore later said he did not know
the event was a fund-raiser, a statement McCain ridiculed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the more cerebral and cautious of the two, opened with
a call for ``a bipartisanship that puts nation above party'' and
described the influence of money on politics as ``a plague'' on
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Republican and Democrat who differ on any number of
other issues, have come together because we believe that money is
eating away at the core of our government the way acid eats away at
cloth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, McCain and Bradley differ in their approach to
campaign finance reform legislation. Bradley supports public
financing of congressional elections while McCain opposes full
taxpayer financing of congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, who barely mentioned Gore during the two-hour
event, later criticized the leading Republican contender, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, who has far outpaced the other candidates
in fund raising. Bush is not participating in the federal campaign
finance system which provides matching funds to presidential
candidates who limit their spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think that the governor of Texas will demonstrate
that you can raise too much money in politics,'' Bradley said. ``I
see that he has essentially thumbed his nose at the public
financing of presidential campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men said they had not consulted each other about their
remarks beforehand, and their aides denied coordinating their
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have built their surprisingly strong outsider campaigns
around courting independent voters, a growing segment of the
electorate, particularly in New Hampshire and Iowa, the first
states to vote in next year's primary season. Aides to both men
assert that independents care more about campaign finance than the
general electorate.
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville Thursday, Gore told reporters that he would also
eschew soft money in the general election if the Republican nominee
did the same. And he said that he would make campaign finance
reform a priority as president, asserting that Bradley was a
Johnny-come-lately to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I have supported and introduced and sponsored
and co-sponsored more than a dozen measures for more than 20 years
I think does serve as evidence that this is not just a new
political issue, this is a commitment for me of long standing,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He also took a swipe at McCain, noting that he had been one of
five senators who took large campaign contributions from Charles
Keating, a savings and loan operator who was later convicted of
fraud. The Senate Ethics Committee found that McCain had done
nothing improper.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush asserts that banning soft money would hurt
the Republican Party by strengthening the hand of labor unions,
which typically support Democrats. Though unions would be
prohibited from giving soft money under the McCain-Bradley
proposal, they could continue to support candidates with their well
financed get-out-the-vote operations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Thursday that he would support a ban on soft money
only if labor unions were also prohibited from using union dues to
support a candidate, unless each individual worker agrees to it.
``I'm for taking away corporate soft money, money where
shareholders have no say in how the money is spent,'' he said at a
news conference in Nashville. ``I'm also for taking away labor
union soft money so long as the working people have a right to
decide how their money is spent.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 election, the two political parties raised more than
$250 million in soft money, and various campaign finance experts
predict that the figure could more than double by election day
2000. Most of the soft money raised by the political parties has
been spent in recent elections to help elect presidential
candidates, although millions have also been spent by the national
parties to aid state and local candidates.
</P>
<P>
   While pledging to curb soft money spent on the top of the
ticket, it would be nearly impossible, even if Bradley and McCain
are nominated by their respective parties, to eliminate so-called
coordinated soft money spending, which helps elect an entire ticket
of candidates, from local office-holders to president.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer session moderated by Ted Koppel ,
McCain showed off his feistiness in a tart retort to a man who
claimed that his soft-money ban would abridge free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you sir, that's a very clever misrepresentation of my
position,'' McCain said. By comparison, Bradley handled his first
critical question by agreeing with his interlocutor's premise.
</P>
<P>
   The two men also had very different answers to a question about
whether they had ever been influenced by campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that there have been times when I have probably been
influenced because the big donor had access to my office and we
know that access is influence,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley asserted he had never been influenced by donations.
``But it's impossible in the current system to prove that because
there is always suspicion,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In several ways, Thursday's event was symbiotically useful to
each candidate. In Bradley's case, McCain was willing to blast Gore
in ways the more courtly Bradley would not. And McCain may have
benefited from Bradley's larger campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   When, for instance, Bradley pulled up outside the senior center,
a group of his supporters stood by with blue-and-white ``Bill
Bradley for President'' signs. But when McCain rolled up in his
bus, there were no supporters with banners. So Bradley's volunteers
simply turned their cardboard posters around to show another slogan
that served McCain's purposes just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Soft Money,'' they read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
