<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLLINS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collins' arrest may seal fate in football career
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The day he became an NFL player, Cecil Collins
declared that his past problems _ two arrests for breaking into
women's apartments, two dismissals from college football teams and
27 days in prison _ had changed him.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked ``the Lord and Jimmy Johnson'' for giving him another
chance. And he pledged to make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is my last chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At about 5:30 a.m. Thursday _ less than eight months after the
Miami Dolphins made Collins a fifth-round draft pick and gave him a
three-year, $860,000 contract _ the 23-year-old running back may
have blown that chance in an all-too-familiar manner.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was arrested and charged with burglary of an occupied
dwelling after neighbors said he broke into their apartment as they
slept. Collins, free on $10,000 bond, was suspended by the
Dolphins. In addition, the new charges could lead authorities in
Louisiana to revoke his probation and force him to serve a
five-year suspended sentence on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald and Tina Nolte, a couple living in Collins' apartment
complex, told Davie police that Collins had been stalking Tina
Nolte for two months. They said early Thursday that Collins forced
open a window in a spare bedroom of their apartment, then opened
the door to their master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:38 a.m., as her husband chased Collins, Tina Nolte called
police. At 6:30 a.m., Collins was arrested in his own apartment. As
police continue to investigate what happened, Lt. Gary Killam said
there is the possibility Collins could face more charges, perhaps
including stalking.
</P>
<P>
   After Collins was interviewed by detectives, transferred to the
Broward County Jail and released on bond, he hopped in a Cadillac
sport utility vehicle driven by his pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just made a mistake; that's all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate repercussions: Johnson, the Dolphins' coach,
indefinitely suspended Collins, but hasn't decided if it's with or
without pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know all the details yet, and I hope these
allegations aren't true,'' Johnson said in a statement. ``However,
he will be suspended until we find out more information about it. I
want to make it clear that the Miami Dolphin organization does not
condone the behavior that was reported to us, but since we are
still in the process of gathering additional information, it would
be premature to speculate on what further action might be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one day earlier, when asked about his reputation for
signing players with troubled pasts, Johnson had said: ``Yes, we do
give players second chances, but once they are with us, if they get
out of line in the least little way we're going to go ahead and ...
go a different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision of where Collins goes from here could be out of the
hands of Johnson and the NFL. Not only do Thursday's charges carry
a potential 15-year jail penalty, but even if he were to plea
bargain to lesser charges, he would be in violation of his
probation in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he was kicked off the Louisiana State team after being
arrested and charged with breaking into an apartment and fondling a
17-year-old woman. Less than a month later, he was arrested again,
this time charged with breaking into an apartment and touching an
18-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a plea bargain, he pleaded guilty to two misdemeanor
counts of simple battery and two felony counts of unauthorized
entry of an inhabited dwelling. He was put on four-year probation
and ordered to perform 300 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Bernie, the prosecuting attorney in the case in Baton Rouge,
said Thursday that if Collins is involved in ``any criminal
activity'' whatsoever _ the severity doesn't matter _ he is subject
to serving his suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm terribly disappointed that he was not able to stay out of
trouble,'' Bernie said. ``He had an opportunity to put his criminal
activity behind him and apparently he was unable to. And now he has
hurt a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest victims, according to police, live near Collins, his
girlfriend and 3-year-old daughter in the gated apartment complex a
few miles northeast of the Dolphins' training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lewis, an attorney and friend of the Noltes, said Thursday
that a couple of months ago, Collins became infatuated with Tina
Nolte, who turns 28 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept asking her out,'' Lewis said. ``He saw her in the gym
and kept hitting on her. He followed her home on one occasion. She
had expressed concern to her husband and they had toyed with the
idea of getting a restraining order.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the Noltes hoped Collins would stop harassing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then this happened,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Noltes told police happened Thursday: They
awoke to the sound of someone opening the door to their master
bedroom. Ronald Nolte jumped out of bed and chased Collins. Collins
ran through the apartment and dove out the same window in a spare
bedroom that he had entered, landed on wet grass and fled.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Nolte told police he ran out of the apartment and chased
down Collins on the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to what I was told, the victim basically said, `Hey,
what are you doing in my house?''' Killam said. ``And (Collins)
said, `It wasn't me, man. I wasn't in your house.'''
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived, the Noltes identified Collins by name and
described his clothing. Police took fingerprints from near the
window and sent them to the crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   No weapons were involved. Collins was not tested for alcohol or
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is still under investigation,'' Killam said.
``This is going to take some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
