u f BC-BROKERAGE-LAWSUIT-NYT     12-16 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKERAGE-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 JURY SIDES WITH FORMER N.Y. GIANT IN JOB LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A jury in Newark, N.J., awarded more than $10 million Thursday
to Philip McConkey, the former New York Giants football player,
after finding that Frank Zarb, the chairman of the group that runs
the Nasdaq stock market, deceived McConkey into working for him at
a previous concern.
</P>
<P>
   McConkey had sued Zarb and Alexander &AMP; Alexander Services Inc.,
the insurance brokerage firm that Zarb formerly ran, contending
that he would not have gone to work for the firm in May 1996 if
Zarb had not assured him that it was not for sale. Seven months
after meeting with McConkey, Zarb announced plans to sell Alexander
&AMP; Alexander to Aon Corp. for $1.23 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The six-person jury, in the Superior Court of New Jersey,
unanimously found that Zarb fraudulently misled McConkey about the
status of talks between the companies. The jury awarded slightly
more than $5 million to McConkey to compensate him for his losses,
including $2 million for emotional distress, and $5 million in
punitive damages. If that award stands up to challenges and
appeals, Aon will be liable for all of it. Some of the award might
have come out of Zarb's pocket, but, in an unusual move, McConkey
quietly dropped Zarb as a defendant at the beginning of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb could not be reached for comment. A spokesman for the
National Association of Securities Dealers said: ``We're
disappointed. At no time was McConkey misled.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Carr, an Aon lawyer who also represented Zarb while he was
a defendant, said he had asked Judge Kenneth Stein to throw out the
jury's decision because it did not fit with the facts. If he does
not, Carr said, Aon will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Although McConkey may not receive the award for a long time, if
at all, he said after the trial, ``I'm very much relieved and
pleased that the jury was able to look at the evidence and focus
through the haze and come up with the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes at a bad time for Zarb, who is trying to
convert the Nasdaq market into a private company. He has been
traveling around to meet with the brokerage firms he represents to
persuade them to allow him to sell stakes in Nasdaq to a select
group of corporations and brokerage firms. Some smaller members of
the association have complained that Zarb does not plan to let them
vote on his plan.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-week trial, McConkey's lawyer, Neil Mullin,
repeatedly pointed to a document signed by Zarb and filed with the
federal government that appeared to contradict what Zarb had told
McConkey. A proxy statement that Alexander &AMP; Alexander filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission said that ``from January to
May of 1996'' Zarb and Patrick Ryan, the chairman of Aon, discussed
``a possible business combination,'' including an outright purchase
by Aon. But Zarb testified that he thought those talks ``were
dead'' when he met with McConkey in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   McConkey testified that, before he joined Alexander &AMP; Alexander
from another insurance brokerage, he had asked Zarb about rumors
that Aon might buy the firm. In a brief meeting in Zarb's office,
McConkey said, Zarb told him that Alexander &AMP; Alexander was ``the
predator, not the prey.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the acquisition, Aon laid off McConkey, who has not
worked in the insurance business since then. Zarb testified that he
received $23 million in severance when he resigned as chairman and
chief executive of Alexander &AMP; Alexander in early 1997. He left to
become president of the NASD and is now its chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
