<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ABBOTT-ALZA-NYT &LR;      12-16 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBOTT-ALZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT LABS ABANDONS PURCHASE OF ALZA CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing its string of recent public misfortunes, Abbott
Laboratories Inc. said Thursday that it was abandoning its $7.3
billion acquisition of Alza Corp. because of antitrust opposition
from the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, the nation's largest maker of medical diagnostic
devices, had announced in June that it would buy Alza, a leading
developer of drug delivery technologies, but soon encountered a
series of troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts became convinced that the acquisition was imperiled
when the companies said in September that they would sell Viadur,
one of Alza's experimental treatments for prostate cancer, to
satisfy antitrust concerns from the FTC. Abbott sells Lupron, a
leading prostate cancer drug.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a month later, Abbott agreed to pay a $100 million fine _
the largest penalty ever levied by the Food and Drug Administration
_ to settle complaints that the company had failed to meet quality
standards in manufacturing some of its medical test kits.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ernest Mario, Alza's chief executive, said Thursday that he
was concerned about the fine, but insisted that the deal had fallen
apart over the two companies' disagreement with the FTC, not the
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, the FTC was concerned about what they
called the monopoly Abbott had in prostate cancer treatments,''
Mario said. ``We thought we had done enough by offering to sell
Viadur, but we could never come to terms with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that the deal had been scrapped came after the
market closed, and investors reacted aggressively in after-hours
trading. Shares of Abbott, which had risen $1.125, to $36.3125,
climbed as high as $39.50. Alza, which closed at $36.4375, down
$3.1875, plunged an additional 23.8 percent after hours, to $27.75.
Mario attributed the drop to arbitragers, who, he estimated, held
about 40 million of Alza's 102 million outstanding shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
