<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1466 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-WILSON-COL-AZR &LR;      12-16 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE GROWTH PLAN NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time for a new slogan:
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix _ the city you can't wait to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Or:
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to the Valley and discover why bigger isn't better.''
</P>
<P>
   Or:
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow your dreams to Phoenix, then wake up and get out.''
</P>
<P>
   A case could be made for any of those lines in light of the
response to this survey question: ``If you were able to move out of
the greater Phoenix area tomorrow, would you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' replied 45 percent of the 1,020 residents. It was the
finest display of community loyalty since the Colts fled Baltimore
in the middle of the night in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Even though The Arizona Republic survey was taken in September,
when the infernal heat has worn us down, the result is noteworthy.
So is the fact that the No. 1 reason given for wanting to move away
was ``too many people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a demonstration of discontent with growth, and it holds
up across all the demographics of age, gender, income, race and
ethnicity,'' said Ryan Johnson of the Morrison Institute for Public
Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Woods, the former attorney general and leader of the
Sierra Club-sponsored initiative to slow growth, put it more
bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 45 percent of the people say they're ready to move,
something's seriously wrong. That survey shows that people here
have finally hit the wall and want significant change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I don't disagree, but the poll may not reflect quite as
negatively on the Phoenix area's growth as Woods suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has more than its share of restless souls with roots
elsewhere. They're not unhappy here, but they're also not deeply
committed.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie and Stephanie Schmitgen are examples. They grew up in
rural Minnesota and moved to Tempe in 1992. He earned a master's
degree at Arizona State University and has a good job with the city
of Phoenix. They like it here but are moving next month to
Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly to be closer to our families,'' he said. ``We have
a 13-month-old daughter, and both sets of grandparents will be
nearby. We miss the seasons a little bit, too. The Valley's growth
really isn't the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said the Citizens Growth Management Initiative already has
about 90,000 of the 101,762 signatures needed by July to put it on
the ballot next November. One provision would require cities, towns
and counties to impose growth boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says voters will approve the initiative if
they aren't satisfied with a milder plan called Growing Smarter,
supported by Gov. Jane Hull and most of the business community.
That plan awaits legislative action this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pfister, head of the Growing Smarter Commission, calls the
Sierra Club plan too extreme and filled with ``booby traps'' meant
to subvert growth. He said it would also lead to a welter of
lawsuits by activists, create much higher densities and risk
throwing the local economy into recession.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise may be in the works. Supporters of the two plans
have been meeting privately to see if they can reach agreement on
what could be a third alternative.
</P>
<P>
   One person trying to bridge the differences is Eddie Basha, the
grocery store owner and 1994 Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   He said Chandler, where he lives and his company is based, ``has
sold out to developers and landowners.'' He regards Growing Smarter
as too weak a remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an expansion-minded capitalist who believes in growth, but
it has to be balanced,'' he said. ``I think Grant Woods is being
reasonable and wants to find a compromise. If a decent one can't be
forged, I'll join his side.''
</P>
<P>
   Basha's on the right track. A hybrid growth control plan should
be developed. If the quality-of-life survey isn't the last word,
it's clear enough. People want to put the brakes on growth, and
they want to hit them hard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
