<HEADER>
A1468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     12-16 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY ADDRESSES FOR `SQUONK,' `COPENHAGEN,' PARKER POSEY, `DAME
EDNA' AND OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT3, is being sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Could it be? Could Broadway, an industry that is
practically synonymous with safe, staid entertainment, where
revivals rule and new plays founder, actually be getting a little
quirky?
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of offbeat theatrical thinking was everywhere this
week, from the casting of a queen of independent film to the
arrival of the so-called squonkers. While it's hardly time to label
it a renaissance, all of it may make the spring more interesting
than the current schedule suggests.
</P>
<P>
   First off is word of one of the most unlikely leaps to Broadway
in recent memory. Beginning on Feb. 8 at the Helen Hayes Theater
are performances of ``Squonk,'' the eccentric downtown hit
developed by a quintet from Pittsburgh. ``Epic Proportions,'' the
Hayes' current tenant, closes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A Broadway address for ``Squonk'' comes as a major surprise.
After completing a successful if brief run last August at Public
School 122 (that would be Off Off Broadway) the show initially
seemed headed for a run at the Salon, a 250-seat space in NoHo. But
that deal fell through, and just around the time the Hayes was
looking for new tenants. ``It was the luck of fate,'' said William
Repicci, the lead producer.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, subtitled ``BigSmorgasbordWunderWerk,'' is not easily
defined. Roughly put, ``Squonk'' is a 80-minute musical melange
incorporating bits of everything from German Expressionism to
Japanese Noh theater. There's dance, and big props. And it's
apparently funny. And slightly trippy. Reviewing the show in The
New York Times, Ben Brantley called ``Squonk'' a ``charmingly
thought-free diversion'' whose overall effect he likened to ``a
hallucinatory game.''
</P>
<P>
   How this will play uptown is an open question. Off Broadway has
supported a variety of plotless but intriguing entertainments,
including ``Stomp,'' ``Blue Man Group,'' and ``De La Guarda,'' all
of which have benefited from sizable tourist and
non-English-speaking audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Cult status downtown, of course, does not guarantee success on
Broadway, where the current idea of bold experimentation seems to
be casting Susan Lucci as Annie Oakley. Still, Repicci says he
feels that this is the moment. ``I just thought maybe it was time
for this genre of show to break into Broadway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING EGGHEADS IN `COPENHAGEN'
</P>
<P>
   In other quarters, there were details about another
unconventional play heading to Broadway. It is ``Copenhagen,''
Michael Frayn's complex meditation on physics, memory and bodies in
motion, in this case two geniuses: the German physicist Werner
Heisenberg and the Danish physicist Niels Bohr.
</P>
<P>
   The play, directed by Michael Blakemore, is to open on April 11
at a Shubert theater yet to be named. Philip Bosco has been cast as
Bohr, Michael Cumpsty as Heisenberg, and Blair Brown, currently in
``The Dead,'' as Margrethe, Bohr's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copenhagen'' was a surprise hit in London, where it won the
Evening Standard Award for best play in 1998. Still, Blakemore
said, it is a risky thing to do on Broadway. ``It's a very unusual
play,'' he said. ``Copenhagen'' seems likely to be a strong Tony
contender in a season of few standout new plays. Blakemore is also
enjoying the status of the hottest director on Broadway, with his
hit revival of ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' and his productions of
``Copenhagen'' on the West End and in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   How does he think the American production will play?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a little juicier, Blakemore said: American actors ``are
emotionally a little more accessible than British ones.''
</P>
<P>
   INDIE STAR SIGNS ON
</P>
<P>
   Titles seem to stick to Parker Posey. She has been variously
described as ``the queen of Sundance Film Festival,'' the ``high
mistress of independent film'' and the ``doyenne of downtown
comediennes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now add Broadway babe to the list. The twinkly gamine from
Laurel, Miss., will make her New York theater debut in ``Taller
Than a Dwarf,'' the Elaine May play that opens at the Longacre
Theater in April.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Posey has signed on to play Selma, an unhappy typist,
opposite Matthew Broderick in the comedy, about a modern couple at
war in a ramshackle Manhattan apartment. She said her decision was
part art, part fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading the script on the plane, and in the play, Selma
is having bathroom trouble,'' Ms. Posey said, with just a hint of
Southern drawl. ``So I come home to my apartment, and water comes
out of my medicine cabinet. It was a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Posey, 31, is best known for her memorable turns in
low-budget, highly praised movies like ``Party Girl,'' ``The
Daytrippers'' and ``Dazed and Confused.'' But her career has also
included a run in John Patrick Shanley's play ``Four Dogs and a
Bone'' at the Geffen Playhouse in Los Angeles and conservatory
training at the State University of New York at Purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having earned herself a name _ or two _ she's back to the
stage. ``I'm thankful,'' she said. ``It's pretty hard to get plays
unless you're well known.'' SISTER ACT
</P>
<P>
   Auditions were under way this week for a musical adaptation of
``Little Women,'' which producers say is Broadway-bound. Like its
many film predecessors, the musical is based on Louisa May Alcott's
novel about good girls' coming of age in wartime New England (the
Civil War, that is). The project is led by Randall Wreghitt and the
first-time producers Dani Davis, a former actress, and Jason
Howland, a musical supervisor for the composer Frank Wildhorn. Ms.
Davis said the production would have a workshop in the spring, a
summer tour and an autumn opening on Broadway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   The cast is set for ``Arms and the Man,'' to be presented by the
Roundabout Theater Co. in February. Katie Finneran, Henry Czerny
and Paul Michael Valley will star.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Broadway may be taking New Year's Eve off, but not
Dame Edna. In her third month at the Booth Theater, she will be the
host of the BBC's New Year's television broadcast. Let's hope the
Queen is asleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
