NYT-12-16-99 2311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-CHIPS-NYT &LR;      12-16 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED SUPERCOMPUTER CHIPS RETURN IN CONSUMER GUISES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mass.)   (rk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A microprocessor that failed commercially when
it was introduced for supercomputers in the 1980s is about to find
new life in home entertainment and other consumer devices of the
next decade, many of which will require more raw computing power
than the most powerful machines from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard and STMicroelectronics, Europe's second-largest
maker of computer chips, plan to announce on Monday that they are
forming a research and development partnership to adapt the old
design to a new generation of home products.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, known as VLIW, for ``very long instruction
word,'' was pioneered by computer designers at Yale University in
the early 1980s. It was commercialized in the mid-80s by Multiflow,
a Connecticut company that made supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   Like a scheme to increase traffic flow by packing cars
bumper-to-bumper in high-speed freeway lanes, VLIW uses a special
``compiler'' that packs the computer's instructions densely so that
processing takes place more efficiently. Compilers are the software
that translates a programmer's written code into the binary
language of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently some VLIW concepts found their way into the IA64
microprocessor being jointly developed by Hewlett and Intel. Intel
is planning to begin producing the first IA64 chip, named Itanium,
in the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Both Intel and Hewlett-Packard were silent investors in
Multiflow. Joseph A. Fisher, a former Yale computer scientist who
co-founded Multiflow, joined Hewlett-Packard in 1990, establishing
a small research group in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer makers, including Sun Microsystems and Texas
Instruments, have also recently turned to VLIW designs in
microprocessors and microcontrollers found in thousands of consumer
products, ranging from automobiles to washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, consumer video and audio entertainment products
require processing speeds once found only in supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   In such applications, where the processing tasks are relatively
repetitive, compared with the work performed by general purpose
computers, VLIW frequently has huge cost and power advantages.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it fits well with the kinds of computing power
demanded by modern printers, which must scale or transform the
colors of an image that consists of millions of pixels.
</P>
<P>
   Still to be proven, however, is whether VLIW designs will become
the dominant technology for general-purpose applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of debate about whether the IA64 is
really the right technology,'' said Linley Gwennap, editorial
director of Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter. But he
also acknowledged that in some applications, like printers, VLIW
``makes a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Hewlett-Packard, a leading maker of computer
printers, and STMicroelectronics say the VLIW approach has broad
applications in low-power devices like wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will open up new portable applications that have not been
possible before,'' said Loic Lietar, corporate strategic marketing
manager at an STMicroelectronics manufacturing plant in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   STMicroelectronics, formerly SGS-Thomson Microelectronics, is
the second largest European semiconductor maker behind Philips, and
is the 9th-largest in the world. The company is a leading maker of
components for the cellular phone industry and analog
semiconductors. STMicroelectronics already makes components for
print heads for Hewlett-Packard's ink-jet printers.
</P>
<P>
   The research deal, which is expected to lead to products next
year, is a measure of vindication for Fisher, who has quietly
continued to work with VLIW technology in his small Cambridge
laboratory since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview Thursday that at times he had felt
depressed about the prospects of VLIW while waiting for hardware
technology to grow in sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he said, ``There are many uses for embedded processors
that require powerful computing capabilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DIALLO-LEGAL-NYT &LR;      12-16 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-LEGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE OF TRIAL'S LOCALE CAN MAKE DIFFERENCE IN VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-DIALLO-TRIAL, NY-DIALLO-REACT) 
(mk) 
 By JANE FRITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For police officers facing brutality charges, moving
a trial to a new location can mean the difference between
conviction and acquittal, legal experts say. There is no more
powerful example than the case of the Los Angeles police officers
who beat Rodney King, a black man, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Although the incident occurred in Los Angeles, lawyers for the
four officers, citing pretrial publicity, persuaded a judge to move
the trial to Simi Valley, a largely white area in neighboring
Ventura County. The officers were acquitted in 1992 by a jury that
had no black members, leading to rioting that roiled Los Angeles
for days. In 1993, the officers were tried on federal civil rights
charges. Two were convicted and two were acquitted by a 12-person
Los Angeles jury that included two African-Americans and one
Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Pretrial publicity was the main reason cited Thursday by a New
York appeals court for moving the trial of four New York City
police officers to upstate Albany. The four officers are accused of
killing Amadou Diallo on Feb. 4 as he stood near the entrance of
his apartment building in the Bronx. Comparisons between Simi
Valley and Albany seem unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Requests by defense lawyers to move cases are not unusual, but
courts rarely grant them; on Thursday, the appeals court called the
move ``an extraordinary remedy reserved for the rarest of cases.''
Lawyers usually argue that the move is necessary because pretrial
publicity has tainted the local jury pool, but judges often rule
that such fears are exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for John Wayne Gacy, who was convicted of murdering 33
boys and young men in the Chicago area two decades ago, argued for
moving the trial, known legally as a change of venue, because of
publicity, but Judge Louis Garippo of the Cook County Circuit Court
rejected that argument. He did, however, order that a jury be
selected in another county and brought to Chicago, because of the
large number of victims and the possibility that potential jurors
in Chicago would have known them or their families.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of high-profile cases in the New York area have been
moved in recent years because of concerns over pretrial publicity,
including the 1986 federal trial of Stanley Friedman, the Bronx
Democratic leader, which involved charges of corruption in the New
York City Parking Violations Bureau. That trial was moved to New
Haven, Conn., after an agreement between defense lawyers and
Rudolph Giuliani, then a U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Giuliani, now the mayor, said, ``You should
basically resolve these things in favor of the defendant's getting
every opportunity to have a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, trials for a number of defendants accused in
an armored car robbery in Rockland County that left three dead were
moved to Orange County and to White Plains, in Westchester County,
because of publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Only in rare instances, like the case in Los Angeles, is there
perceived to be a deeply felt public sentiment against the
defendants. And some legal experts believe that public sentiment
about a defendant or a particular crime should not necessarily
disqualify a community from meting out justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defendants are using these venue motions as a way of avoiding
the evaluation of their conduct by the community where the crime
was committed,'' said Drew Kershen, a law professor at the
University of Oklahoma. The trial of Timothy McVeigh on murder
charges stemming from the bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City was a case in point, Kershen said. It was moved to
Denver largely because of the presumed prejudice of the people of
Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence that people in the districts
affected can make these decisions, and they're the ones who ought
to,'' he said. The Simi Valley jurors, he said, had no stake in
what happened in Los Angeles. ``The defendant should not have to
face a howling mob, but until you prove that to me, I don't think
you ought to let defendants get away from facing possible
condemnation. It's not about letting defendants pick a place where
they can win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The moving of trials far from the location of a crime surfaced
as an issue in American law during colonial times, when people
accused of crimes were often transported to England for trials.
Colonists objected, saying local juries were in a better position
to evaluate their actions than juries in London. That sentiment was
written as a defendant's right into the Sixth Amendment to the
Constitution, which guarantees ``a public trial by an impartial
jury of the state and district wherein the crime shall have been
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, the New York officers are likely to find a more
sympathetic jury pool. ``I don't think I could pick a better spot
than Albany to present a case like that,'' said Terence Klindon, a
trial lawyer in Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
