<HEADLINE>
TRIBAL BUDGET SOARS TO $68 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with an uproar among tribal members who say they aren't
getting their fair share, the Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Com
munity unveiled its annual budget, $68 million, a $25 million
increase since the tribe opened its two casinos 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal leaders handed out copies of tribal finances for the
first time during a volatile debate &UR; over a proposal to give members
a cut of the profit from the tribe's two casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hasn't happened in the past, and we want to make it an
annual presentation,'' Tribal Presi dent Ivan Makil told an
overflow crowd of more than 600 at a council meeting that ran five
hours Wednes day night.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Indian tribes aren't re quired to and have
traditionally not released tribal financial information.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was made public as a strategy to convince community
members that revenue from tribal business and the Casino Arizona
gambling halls is needed to improve an array of services on the
55,000-acre reservation, which borders Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past several months, about 1,000 tribal members have
signed petitions demanding that the tribe's 6,200 members split a
25 per cent share of the profits. The casinos opened in October
1998 and last March.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Ray, a tribal member, agreed with others that the budget
presentation lacked details because it is not clear how the tribe
arrived at the $68 million figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just picking those numbers out of the air,'' he said
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Garnet Gates, a former Tribal Council member who directed the
petition drive, called the budget presentation a ``dog and pony
show'' because it did not divulge casino profits.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, a member of a committee considering whether the profits
should be shared, said unless his panel gets the profit
information, it won't know how to divide the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Makil told the sometimes jeering crowd Wednesday that the
council will not divulge casino profits because the information
could be used by competing Indian casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also point to Indian gaming to justify reducing govern
ment aid to gaming tribes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make those profits public, I guarantee you they would
be in the newspaper the next day and you would be negatively im
pacted,'' Makil told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Makil struggled to keep order as the audience cheered a demand
that each tribal council member take a stand on the payout plan.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the nine council mem bers, including Makil, said the 25
percent payout formula would take too much of the money needed for
community improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe predicts it will need $425 million over the next
decade for public safety, a new detention center, fire protection,
recreation, education and housing. None of those projects has been
funded, and tribal officials want to keep the money for those
needs.
</P>
<P>
   But he said per capita payments haven't been ruled out.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
