<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      12-16 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: THE McCAIN-BRADLEY SHOW  
(sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Dec. 17:
</P>
<P>
   The air and even some of the questions in New Hampshire were
frosty on Thursday at the unusual joint appearance of Sen. John
McCain of Arizona and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey. But
these two presidential candidates were making a significant
contribution with their attempt to give the issue of campaign
finance reform a more prominent place on the agenda for 2000. This
marked the first time that two serious contenders from opposing
parties have come together to challenge the Washington
establishment on so fundamental a problem as the two parties' joint
dependence on special-interest money.
</P>
<P>
   It was especially fitting that McCain and Bradley made their
appearance, broadcast on ABC's ``Nightline'' on Thursday night, at
the exact spot where President Clinton and former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich promised to bring about a bipartisan campaign cleanup
in 1995. Nothing came of that meeting except for mounting popular
disenchantment as detail after detail of the corrupt election of
1996 came to light. It is still fashionable in Washington to think
that campaign finance reform is a low priority among voters, as Ted
Koppel said repeatedly. But in fact, the issue has propelled both
McCain and Bradley in New Hampshire, where they are surging ahead
because they have made it a centerpiece of their respective
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, McCain and Bradley exchanged promises to bar their
parties from spending the unlimited contributions by corporations,
unions and rich individuals known as ``soft money'' should they
face one another in the general election. These donations to the
party circumvent longtime limits on campaign donations to the
candidates enacted by Congress over many decades, and McCain said
he would forgo soft money no matter whom he faces. Vice President
Al Gore has also pledged to forgo soft money in a general election
if his opponent does. But McCain and Bradley have been most
aggressive in promoting a move that would cut off an expected $500
million in party donations from the nation's most powerful special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, Thursday's joint appearance by McCain and Bradley
drew an irate response from George W. Bush. Early in the campaign
the Texas governor said he would favor a ban on soft-money
donations to political parties by corporations and unions. Lately
he has retreated, saying that such a ban would be effective only if
it were attached to a harshly anti-labor provision making it
difficult for unions to raise campaign money from their members.
His position is a dodge, since corporations already give more to
campaigns than unions do, by a ratio of more than 10 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   It took some nerve for McCain to attack his party's front-runner
on this issue. Bush has rejected fund-raising limits and is rapidly
becoming the champion money harvester of all time, even compared
with Bill Clinton. By defending soft money, Bush, a self-styled
outsider, has truly become the advocate of the Washington
fund-raising establishment in this election.
</P>
<P>
   In hard political terms, Bradley and McCain were competing on
Thursday for the independents and crossover voters that both of
them need in New Hampshire's open primary. But their meeting has
the potential of expanding the base of voters who understand the
corrupting influence of special-interest money. They should take
their show on the road and invite other candidates to join them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991216.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-STADIUM-AZR &LR;      12-16 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA BOWL OFFERS FUNDS FOR STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tostitos Fiesta Bowl is will ing to help finance a new
Phoenix areafootball stadium, but the amount it commits depends on
the kind of deal assembled in the coming months, the bowl's
executive director said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   John Junker told Gov. Jane Hull's stadium task force that his
organiza tion ``has a major stake in this issue, as does the state
of Arizona,'' because a new stadium could deter mine whether the
Fiesta Bowl remains in the rotation for the national college
football champion ship game.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the task force accepted proposals on proposed
stadium sites in Tempe and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Mayor Neil Giuliano and Mesa Mayor Wayne Brown offered
four sites for consideration in north Tempe and along the
Tempe-Mesa line. The Downtown Phoenix Part nership and Phoenix City
Council man Cody Williams proposed one site apiece in central
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Ferris, Hull's deputy chief of staff, said it is possible
the task force could recommend more than one site to Hull and the
Legislature if there are several feasible alterna tives.
</P>
<P>
   The task force is studying how and where to build a new stadium
that could house the Arizona Cardi nals, the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl
and other sports events. Cardinals offi cials say the NFL team
needs a more modern, air-conditioned facil ity to increase
attendance, earn more money and remain competi tive.
</P>
<P>
   The team has not disclosed how much it would spend to finance
the stadium. The task force has been told some public money would
be needed, but Hull has ruled out a general tax increase as an
alterna tive. The cost of the proposed stadium is pegged at $329
million, but that doesn't include land pur chase, parking
facilities or site development.
</P>
<P>
   None of the sites proposed Thurs day was accompanied by offers
of free land, infrastructure development or other financial
incentives. But Giuliano said Tempe was prepared to work with the
task force to determine how it could contribute to stadium
development in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are anxious to have those discussions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Junker said negotiations begin next year on membership renewal
in the Bowl Championship Series, un der which the Fiesta, Sugar,
Orange and Rose bowls rotate as hosts of a national championship
game. The current rotation doesn't end for several more years, but
Junker is concerned about the Fiesta's long-term prospects because
of competition from new stadiums cropping up in other parts of the
country. Bigger, more modern stadi ums produce more money, which
appeals to the Bowl Championship Series and college football confer
ences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like every other business _ we need to grow,'' Junker
said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fiesta is allowed to keep ticket, concession and
advertising revenues from its event each year, a larger, more
luxurious stadium would guarantee both the attendance and revenues
needed to keep the Fiesta Bowl competitive for years.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``we're not here looking for a free pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Junker said the Fiesta Bowl would discuss putting up part of the
construction money when it was clear that a deal could be
structured to satisfy the bowl. So far, he said, he's encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Using temporary seating, the sta dium design being discussed
would fit 80,000 fans and have a partially retractable dome and
natural turf, all of which appeal to Fiesta Bowl officials. The
bowl could earmark certain revenues _ ticket sur charges, for
instance _ to fund a portion of construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sites proposed Thursday included one southeast of Bank One
Ballpark in downtown Phoenix, between Sev enth and 11th streets,
south of Jackson Street and north of Sher man Street. The property
is all private, owned primarily by the railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kearney of the Downtown Phoenix Alliance said the site
would not need to be rezoned and would ``allow significant spinoff
develop ment.'' Its proximity to other sports facilities would
allow it to take advantage of surrounding restau rants, bars,
hotels and shops. More than 22,000 parking spaces are available
within a three-quarter-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the councilman, pro moted a 450-acre site, partly on
an old Phoenix landfill, that would provide easy access to
Interstate 17. The site includes 240 acres owned by the city just
north of the Salt River between Seventh and 19th avenues. Private
land farther north also would be used. It would need significant
work to prepare the site for development.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe proposed four sites:
</P>
<P>
   Papago Park Center, a parcel owned by Salt River Project. Seated
between the Salt River and Wash ington Street just east of Priest
Drive, it's near Tempe's Town Lake and along a proposed light-rail
route. About 7,000 parking spaces are available in the area, but
12,000 more would have to be built nearby.
</P>
<P>
   A larger site south of the river and east of McClintock Drive
that has various private owners, one of whom controls 50 acres.
It's on the proposed light-rail route but would need cleanup before
use. Part of the site now is a junkyard.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Rio Salado Crossing, a site east of the Pima Freeway and
south of the Red Mountain Freeway. The land, held by Arizona State
University, Maricopa County and a few private landowners, offers
quick access to two freeways.
</P>
<P>
   A joint Mesa-Tempe site that straddles the city limits to take
in land owned by Mesa north of the Tempe Rio Salado Crossing. It
offers quick freeway access and room to develop parking lots, and
would permit joint development by both cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
