<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-THEFT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attempt to steal balloons, tires goes bust
 &HT;    By John Lynch
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ How do you get rid of a 140-foot tall,
800-pound internationally known corporate icon that resembles the
Pillsbury Dough Boy?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently that question stumped some thieves Thursday morning
because they abandoned a trailer containing a hot-air balloon
shaped like Bib the Michelin Man south of Longview, said Gregg
County Sheriff Bobby Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a first for me,'' he said about recovering a stolen
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   A deputy on patrol found a brightly colored blue and yellow
trailer emblazoned with the 101-year-old trademark of the
international tire-maker shortly after 7 a.m., Weaver said. The
trailer hadn't been reported stolen, he said, but investigators
became suspicious when they noticed the trailer wasn't locked.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said he contacted several members of Longview's
ballooning community, trying to determine who owned the trailer and
its contents. His fifth call reached Guy Gauthier, owner of Balloon
Repairs of East Texas, who was surprised to learn it was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Guy, who has the Michelin Man,' and he said, `I do,'
'' Weaver said. ``It was as much a surprise to me as it was to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The trailer contained about $250,000 worth of ballooning
equipment, including a second traditional balloon and a Bib costume
for personal appearances, Gauthier said. The trailer and equipment
belongs to a Florida advertising company, he said, and the balloons
had been at Gauthier's shop for routine maintenance since October
after appearing at the Albuquerque International Hot Air Balloon
Fiesta in New Mexico. Gauthier said the trailer had been locked up
in the back of his shop, and thieves cut through two padlocks
sometime Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The balloon's pilot will be in Longview today to inventory the
trailer, but Gauthier was able to determine two fans used to
inflate the balloons were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Gauthier say they don't think the thieves intended to
steal hot-air balloons, but thought they were getting a trailer
full of Michelin tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure when they saw the trailer, they thought they had a
load of tires _ these (balloons) are a little harder to get rid
of,'' Gauthier said.
</P>
<P>
   The thieves would have a hard time disposing of the balloons, he
said, estimating the entire American ballooning community could be
notified within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's investigators checked the trailer and equipment for
fingerprints and continue to investigate the theft.
</P>
<P>
   The Michelin Man balloon has made several appearances at
Longview's Great Texas Balloon Race, Gauthier said. He said the
balloon is about twice the height and four times the weight of a
traditional 75-foot, 200-pound balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The Michelin Man, a white stack of animated tires, has
represented the France-based company since 1898 and takes his name
from the French word meaning ``to drink,'' according to the
company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
