<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RWANDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LOOKING BACK AT RWANDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Dec. 17:
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the slaughter of as many as 800,000 Tutsi in
Rwanda, the world is still grappling with its failure to prevent
the killing. The United Nations published a sobering, self-critical
report on Thursday that catalogd in painful detail how it ignored
abundant warnings of impending carnage and withdrew most of its
peacekeeping force as the massacres began. In Tanzania, meanwhile,
the United Nations' war crimes tribunal charged with prosecuting
those responsible for the genocide in Rwanda faces questions about
its very survival after an appeals court ordered the release of a
suspect because he had been held for nearly two years without being
formally charged.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. report is noteworthy less for its sadly familiar
account than for the fact of its existence and its timing. It comes
a month after a comparably critical internal report that showed how
the United Nations allowed the Bosnian Muslim ``safe area'' of
Srebrenica to be overrun in July 1995 by Bosnian Serbs, who then
killed thousands of the town's men and boys. Together these
inquiries establish an admirable new standard of candor at the
United Nations under Secretary General Kofi Annan. They can point
the way to more effective international action if similar cases
arise in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwanda report does not spare Annan, who was in charge of the
United Nations' peacekeeping operations during the killings. But it
properly decries the ``lack of political will'' among member
nations, not least the United States, which set Annan's agenda.
Washington, shaken by the killing of American peacekeepers in
Somalia in 1993, blocked effective U.N. action in Rwanda. President
Clinton acknowledged last year that he ``did not do as much as we
could have and should have.''
</P>
<P>
   The report underscores the importance of the United Nations'
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda, which was established
in September 1994 in part to make amends for the United Nations'
earlier failure. In five years the tribunal has made fitful but
undeniable progress, reinforced last week by the conviction and
life sentence handed down against Georges Rutaganda, vice president
of the Interahamwe, the machete-wielding gangs that hacked their
Tutsi neighbors to death in three months of concentrated slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   But the tribunal's legitimacy has been cast in doubt by an
appeals court ruling that another suspect should be released, in
part because of the tribunal staff's own negligence. Last month the
Appeals Chamber in The Hague, which oversees both the Rwanda
tribunal and its better known counterpart, the war crimes tribunal
for the former Yugoslavia, ordered the release of Jean-Bosco
Barayagwiza, who had been charged with genocide and crimes against
humanity. The appeals court said his due process rights had been
denied because he was held for 19 months in Cameroon before being
handed over to the tribunal and formally charged.
</P>
<P>
   The court has agreed to reconsider, but not before an outraged
Rwandan government, now dominated by Tutsi survivors of the
genocide, suspended its cooperation with the tribunal. The response
is understandable, but it is in Rwanda's own interest to resume
cooperation. Rwanda lacks the resources to try top suspects itself.
The procedural integrity of the tribunal is critically important.
Those who have backed the tribunal thus far, including the Clinton
administration, should provide the resources and oversight to
ensure that similar mistakes are not made in the months ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
