<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIAL REVEALS PLAN TO AVERT WEST NILE ILLNESS IN NEW YORK
REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York state's health commissioner said on Thursday
that the state's residents should ``not be concerned'' about a
possible return of the West Nile virus that killed seven people and
sickened dozens of others in the region last summer, because the
state has organized a full-scale campaign to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   But some regional health commissioners said that they were
concerned about how they were going to pay for local mosquito
control and related services. Other officials, including those in
New York City, said that they already had a program in place to
deal with mosquito control and did not need guidance from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from around the state and from the federal Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention met on Monday to discuss a plan to
prepare for next spring, when mosquito larvae hatch and could
potentially reintroduce West Nile to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans, outlined by the health commissioner, Dr. Antonia C.
Novello, during a news conference in Manhattan on Thursday, include
strengthening the state's thinly staffed mosquito surveillance
unit, which traps the insects and tests them for dangerous
diseases, hiring more staff for the state laboratory where samples
from both infected birds and humans are tested in an effort to
detect any outbreak early and stop it, and mounting a large public
health advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, officials said they had just started to meet this
week to form a plan for the spring. In Connecticut, where dead
birds were found to have carried the disease, experts said that
they would be adjusting their existing program to take West Nile
into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in very good shape,'' said Jane Stahl, the deputy
commissioner for Connecticut's environmental protection agency.
``Our spray program has always included preventive programs'' and a
program for municipalities to make sure there are no areas of
standing water.
</P>
<P>
   Novello said that 35 new full-time employees have been added to
the department to take on the threat of West Nile, including
scientists who test mosquitoes and birds for diseases. Most experts
on insects and infectious diseases agree that careful surveillance
is the best method of controlling diseases that are introduced into
new environments; spraying for mosquitoes after a disease has shown
up in humans is costly and largely ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   But the ability of regional health departments to strengthen
their programs is hindered by a lack of money, commissioners said.
``There was no discussion at that meeting about revising how state
aid is provided,'' said Dr. Kathy Gaffney, the health commissioner
of Nassau County on Long Island. ``We spend $1 million in that area
and get $55,000 in state aid. We are supposed to be in public
health, but we don't get funding until it is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has said it would pick up half of any city's expenses
for dealing with the West Nile virus, but only if that city had an
outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus, which until last summer had not been found
in the Western Hemisphere, killed six New Yorkers and one Canadian
tourist between July and September. The virus is carried by birds,
which can be bitten by mosquitoes that then transmit the illness to
humans. The virus is usually mild, although in severe cases, it can
develop into an encephalitis that can be fatal. Those who are most
vulnerable to life-threatening cases are the elderly, children
under 5 and people with weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   While human cases of West Nile were believed to have been
limited to the New York region this summer, birds infected with the
virus were found as far south at Baltimore, and federal agencies
continue to test birds along the eastern seaboard.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Novello also said that the state would work closely with
veterinarians to identify cases of West Nile in horses and other
domestic animals, to improve information systems so counties and
the state can quickly share information about a potential disease
as it moves across the region, and to encourage residents to reduce
the number of mosquitoes by keeping pools of stagnant water to a
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where most of the West Nile cases were found
last summer, plans for mosquito surveillance are already well
underway, said the city's health commissioner, Dr. Neal Cohen, who
added that the city would also test chickens and other birds for
traces of the illness, ideally before there are any human cases.
The city will not spray for mosquitoes unless it is sure that
infected bugs or animals are in the area. ``We don't see pesticide
spraying as a first line of control,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-99 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
