<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LANCOME WILL SHOW MODELS WITH FRECKLES AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a saying that beauty is not a pretty
business. If there isn't, maybe there should be, because
competition in the cosmetics field, particularly at the
higher-priced end, is getting almost, well, ugly.
</P>
<P>
   The giants that dominate the upper tier of the industry are
intensifying their fractious battling as they increase advertising
budgets for premium makeup, skin care and fragrance brands; bring
out additional products, and rework long-running campaigns. For
instance, for the new year L'Oreal, the U.S.. subsidiary of
Cosmair, will significantly revamp the marketing efforts for its
popular Lancome line.
</P>
<P>
   Lancome ranks third in sales in American department stores,
according to Mottus &AMP; Associates in New York, behind only two
brands belonging to the Estee Lauder &UR;  &LR; Cos., Estee Lauder and
Clinique. Other competitors include products sold by Chanel, LVMH
Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton and Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to reinforce our brand territory,'' said Marc
Menesguen, president of Lancome International in Paris, ``we want
to enter the new millennium with a new brand expression: more
contemporary, more relevant, more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women were telling us Lancome is a fantastic brand,'' he
added, summarizing the results of what he described as a year's
research among 5,000 consumers in eight countries, ``but they
wanted us to say it with more conviction, maybe with a little bit
more courage.''
</P>
<P>
   What could constitute courage when it comes to peddling products
like lotions, lipsticks and wrinkle creams? Perhaps running a
photograph of a model in a print ad that is not heavily retouched,
leaving some of her freckles visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this category, that's a breakthrough,'' said Tony
DeGregorio, president and chief creative officer at the New York
office of Publicis, the Lancome agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's less technique to the way the women are
photographed,'' he added, ``so it's less artful.''
</P>
<P>
   According to DeGregorio, that offers consumers ``a much more
human, approachable, intimate interpretation of beauty,'' which
``is a bold, confident way of saying, `Get in touch with your inner
beauty.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another step on the road to approachability is an apparent
renaming of at least one product: in a print ad, Rouge Magnetic
lipstick seems to have lost its accent mark.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, created by offices of Publicis, part of Publicis
SA, in Canada, France and the United States, introduces as a theme
the phrase ``Believe in beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to help every woman find her own beauty,'' said Luc
Nadeau, senior vice president and general manager at Lancome USA in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tested this new campaign carefully,'' he added, ``and found
it spoke not only to reason but to the heart, letting each woman
have the freedom to interpret as she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The print, television and radio campaign, which also includes
materials for retailers, makes over a series of ads running since
September 1996 that have been centered on images of roses, the
Lancome brand icon, standing tall, as if blooming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rose is a symbol of femininity, elegance, unique to
Lancome,'' Menesguen said. ``It's a strong actor in the new
campaign, but less rigid than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there's a complete rose,'' he added, ``and sometimes
there's a petal.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, as in a print ad for Primordiale Intense skin
lotion, the rose gets the star treatment, appearing by itself
rather than accompanied by a model's face.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's turn, as Stephen Sondheim might call it.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is starting with ads in January issues of more than
two dozen magazines, some already being sent to subscribers and
sold on newsstands. They include Allure, Cosmopolitan, Elle,
Harper's Bazaar, In Style, Interview, Jane, Mademoiselle, Marie
Claire, Mode, More, People, Self, Texas Monthly, Vogue and W.
</P>
<P>
   The first TV commercial, for a new product named Re-Surface
Retinol Concentrate Intense Wrinkle Corrector, is scheduled to
begin running the week after Christmas on local stations in large
markets like Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles, San Francisco and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lancome executives declined to specify spending for
the campaign around the world, Menesguen said: ``This year, our
media expenditures increased at a double-digit rate. And we're
definitely planning to keep that rate of growth next year.''
</P>
<P>
   In this country, Lancome and retailers will spend an estimated
$35 million in 2000 on television, radio and print advertising.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
